<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEECEE-TAX-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REBELLION IS BREWING IN U.S. CAPITAL OVER STATUS
</HEADLINE>
  By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attitude, the gritty urban ingredient that seemed
to go missing with the fall of Mayor Marion Barry Jr., is
threatening to return to the capital city's profile in the form of
a rebellious new license plate motto decrying the city's status of
``Taxation Without Representation.''
</P>
<P>
   A proposal to proclaim that motto on District of Columbia
license plates has been unanimously co-sponsored by city council
members to protest the fact that residents pay $2 billion in annual
federal taxes but have failed repeatedly to gain a voting
representative in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have much chutzpah lately in this city, so why not
make this an in-your-face issue?'' said Mark Plotkin, a local
political broadcaster who was delighted to see the license plate
proposal begin with an angry taxpayer's e-mail message and quickly
spread through the city council.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning it even drew the endorsement of Mayor Anthony
Williams, the gentler, nonconfrontational executive whose image is
no match for the rapscallion style of Barry, who made a spectacle
of this city's political plight.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Williams had wanted new license plate mottoes with
optional pro-environment or pro-children themes. But he decided to
join the protest movement, describing the motto as ``a creative and
effective way to raise nationwide awareness about the lack of full
democracy in the nation's capital.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters, led by the council's chairwoman, Linda Cropp, are
delighted that a city that must routinely police endless
visitations by protest groups might finally rise up on its own and
put a dash of contumely before the eyes of the 25 million tourists
who visit each year. President Clinton's limousine, like all other
cars registered here, bears D.C. plates now proclaiming the tepid,
noncontroversial plea to ``Celebrate &AMP; Discover'' the nation's
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Well worth discovering, Cropp emphasized, is the fact that the
district maintains its own statelike level of services and finances
80 percent of local government needs, roughly $3.5 billion, through
its 700,000 residents. The patriotic contribution in lives spent in
the nation's wars, she said, makes the case even more compelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, this mirrors the frustration the colonials felt in
padding the coffers of England and having no say,'' Cropp said,
aiming to put the proposal on a fast track for approval.
</P>
<P>
   Under current House rules, the district has no representation in
the Senate, while in the House its taxpayers have Eleanor Holmes
Norton serving as their elected delegate, not representative. She
has only limited power to vote in committee but never on the floor
where laws are enacted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Americans don't even know the district lacks voting power
even though it pays the third highest per capita federal taxes in
the nation,'' Norton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to happen,'' she said of the license plate
protest, predicting that Congress, which has review power over new
laws passed by the council, would shy from interfering with such a
basic expression of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   The delegate drew strong agreement from David Marin, the
Republican spokesman for the House subcommittee on the district.
``I see absolutely no reason why this Congress will not support the
district's decision to highlight this inequity,'' said Marin, press
secretary for the committee chairman, Rep. Thomas Davis III, R-Va.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Shapiro, a district native and angry taxpayer who proposed
the license plate to Plotkin in an e-mail message, first suggested
the edited version of the colonial rebels' cry of ``No taxation
without representation!''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one out there knows how benighted we are,'' said Shapiro,
who made the proposal after a friend she considered well educated
``floored'' her by casually saying he thought district residents
paid no federal taxes and so did not deserve the right to vote in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, we went to Yale together,'' Shapiro declared. ``This
guy is not some shrub from Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are clueless.'' she said, of such basic facts as
district residents not gaining the right to vote in the
presidential election until 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-five percent of the nation's college graduates do not know
that district residents do not have equal voting rights in
Congress, according to a recent poll by Bisconto Research Inc.,
cited by Norton. When properly informed, 72 percent of those polled
supported voting rights.
</P>
<P>
   This provides evidence for the stand of Plotkin, the political
broadcast polemicist who helped stir up the license plate proposal.
He says the district badly needs to emblazon its plight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been so appropriate lately,'' Plotkin complained. ``Now
maybe we'll actually roil some people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
