<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA SCHEDULE SOON WILL BE BACK TO NORMAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   American sports fans should know by now the TV networks will do
whatever it wants when it comes to the scheduling of sports events,
so no one should be too cranky that it's taken almost a fortnight
to finish the best-of-five first round of the NBA playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Both NBC and Turner Sports wanted the first round extended so it
could maximize its inventory and get around the fact that Nielsen
ratings have declined, and with them the sales price for commercial
time.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has averaged a 4.4 rating thus far for 12 telecasts, a 19
percent drop from a 5.4 a year ago for 11 telecasts over the same
calendar period. The overall ratings for Saturday's tripleheader
was down 26 percent, and down 29 percent for Sunday's tripleheader.
The late Sunday game, Game 3 of the Lakers-Kings series, did a 6.3,
down 26 percent from the late game a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Nielsens for Turner's games on TNT and TBS have at least
stayed steady with last year at 2.3.
</P>
<P>
   In the litany of complaints about schedules, going to slo-mo for
the playoffs ranks far below transgressions like a 9:07 p.m. ET
first pitch for World Series games and college football bowl games
that kick off before lunch.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule from here on should be more normal, with no more
than two days off between games. Should the Lakers beat Sacramento
in Game 5 tonight (7:30 p.m., Fox Sports Net), they'll open up the
next series against Phoenix Sunday at home, time to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   THE NEW CHICK: The Lakers have made as many appearances on NBC
this season as the TV series ``Freaks and Geeks,'' meaning Bob
Costas is as familiar with them as Chick Hearn and Jack Nicholson.
He'll be there again Sunday if the Lakers advance to the next
round.
</P>
<P>
   He's as surprised as anyone that the Lakers have been forced to
a fifth game by the Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't that surprised the Kings hit them with an energy
burst on Sunday,'' said Costas. ``Anyone can have an off day. But I
was very surprised at the way Tuesday's game went. I thought they
would take command and end things, and it turned out they were
never in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you reduce any series to one game, with this much at
stake, you can't be 100 percent of the outcome. You sure would
expect the Lakers to win, but you can't be as sure of it as you
might have been a week ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' future is of great importance to NBC, which
televised many Laker games outside of the west coast with the
thought they were the team most likely to play in the finals.
Eliminate the major market team with the best record in the league
and the playoffs immediately become a lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Lakers were to fall, that makes it wide open,'' said
Costas. ``I would still favor whoever comes out of the west over
anyone in the east, but we still have to see if Utah will be
around, too.''
</P>
<P>
   NO SKIPPING OUT: Say what you want about the parochial attitude
of the Atlanta Braves broadcast team, but no one on the broadcast
team has flinched when it comes to talking about the Mouth from the
South, John Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   Both Skip Caray and Pete Van Wieren have been critical of his
actions since returning from suspension, which has included trading
barbs with fans in the stands, verbally assaulting media members
and blowing off security personnel placed near the Braves bullpen
in San Diego last week and Los Angeles this week.
</P>
<P>
   Caray took him to task for his comments to a photographer in San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, KXTA's (1150 am) always-amusing Vic Jacobs said
he had an interview with Rocker set up, only to have the reliever
blow by him and slightly push him out of the way as he was running
into the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Rocker was just scared off by Jacobs' always intriguing
headwear.
</P>
<P>
   AND NOW THE NEWS: HBO airs tape of the Lennox Lewis-Michael
Grant fight tonight at 10 p.m. It also debuts its new boxing
series, KO Nation,'' Saturday at 5 p.m. A pair of fights will be
featured on each broadcast, set for the moment at one telecast per
month ... ABC's lame duck coverage of the Kentucky Derby Saturday
begins at 1:30 p.m., with Al Michaels, Jim McKay and Lesley Visser
among t he cast. The Derby and other parts of the Triple Crown move
to NBC next years ... ABC will only televise a NHL Stanley Cup game
Sunday if Colorado and Detroit go to a Game 6 ... ESPN Classic airs
the 1970 Stanley Cup game that featured Bobby Orr's airborne goal
Wednesday evening ... In a move that has everyone confused, the
Senior PGA has signed a multiyear deal to air its events on
all-news CNBC after several years on ESPN. It sure seems like a bad
fit for all parties ... DirecTV is offering the 31-game, 16-team
Euro 2000 tournament to subscribers as a pay add-on package at a
cost of $149 for the series. The tourney begins June 10 ... Tracy
Dolgin has been promoted to President of Fox Sports Net. he
previously was COO ... Congratulations go out to veteran local
radio sportscaster Eric Tracy and wife Kathleen on the birth of a
daughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
