<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SIERRA-LEONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE LESSONS OF SIERRA LEONE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, May 5:
</P>
<P>
   With one U.N. peacekeeping force under violent attack in Sierra
Leone, the international organization moved ahead on Thursday with
plans to dispatch another to Congo. The juxtaposition clearly
suggests a need to improve the planning and execution of such U.N.
missions to ensure that peacekeeping forces do not become
casualties in the conflicts they are supposed to help end.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leone demonstrates the danger of sending a weak and
inadequately trained peacekeeping force into a country where there
is not yet a peace to keep. Rebels killed four Kenyan peacekeepers
this week and took hostage at least 92 U.N. troops and civilians.
The United Nations must quickly reinforce the 8,500 peacekeepers
already there and regain control of an unraveling mission.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago the Revolutionary United Front, the group that
terrorized Sierra Leone throughout an eight-year civil war by
severing the limbs of thousands of civilians, signed a peace accord
with an elected government. But the rebels have flouted it ever
since. In February the Security Council authorized an increase in
the mission from 6,000 to 11,000 troops, but has not fully carried
out the plan because of lagging troop contributions from member
states. Washington can help by providing cargo aircraft to fly
Jordanian, Bangladeshi and Indian troops into Sierra Leone as soon
as they are ready.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. troops have responded to the recent rebel attacks by
surrounding the home of the rebel leader Foday Sankoh in Sierra
Leone's capital, Freetown. They should continue to do so. Sankoh
may be induced to arrange release of the hostages, but he has
failed to honor his pledge to disarm his forces and allow U.N.
troops to move into rebel territory, where they might interfere
with his lucrative diamond-smuggling operation. The peace agreement
gave Sankoh immunity from prosecution for crimes committed during
the war. It is now clear that Sierra Leone is unlikely to enjoy
real peace until he and his confederates are held accountable for
their crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations' mistakes in Sierra Leone should not be
repeated in Congo, which agreed on Thursday to accept a U.N. force
of 5,500 troops to monitor a tenuous cease-fire there. Richard
Holbrooke, the chief American representative to the United Nations,
rightly noted this week that the United Nations ``can't turn away
from crises like these.'' But an outside force should be called
upon to maintain peace, not to make it. A mission of this kind is
appropriate only when a realistic peace deal is respected by all
sides and a cease-fire has been established. An international force
must then be given the financial resources, manpower and
disciplined command needed to protect itself and effectively carry
out its mandate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
