<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-LEHTINEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS HOPING TO HAVE LEHTINEN BACK FOR GAME 4
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ The Stars could get two-time reigning Selke
Trophy winner Jere Lehtinen back for Game 4 tonight against San
Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, stop rolling your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   This is a big deal. Really, it is. Sharks players compare it to
the boost they got when captain Owen Nolan returned Tuesday after
missing one game. Lehtinen, honored as the NHL's top defensive
forward the past two seasons, hasn't played in the playoffs, and
the Stars know they'll be a better team when he returns.
</P>
<P>
   Which they're pretty sure _ well, might be, if nothing goes
wrong _ will be tonight. He's ``really, really'' close, and skated
on the checking line with Mike Keane and Guy Carbonneau yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, so you've heard this before, have you?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Lehtinen admitted. ``I've been here before.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here'' is one step away from returning to a lineup that has
included him only 17 times in 90 games this season. He has had a
little trouble getting from ``here'' to ``there,'' which is in the
lineup. Yes, one or two of Lehtinen's comebacks from a fractured
right ankle he suffered Oct. 16 turned out to be false alarms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on four,'' Stars trainer Dave Surprenant said.
</P>
<P>
   This will be Lehtinen's fourth comeback if he is indeed in the
lineup tonight, which won't be a definite until his ankle passes
inspection this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how he is in the morning. If there is no soreness
and he feels fine, then he'll play'' tonight, Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said before adding the ``but'' that usually comes along
with Lehtinen updates. ``There is no lock that this is going to
work. ... He's going to be a bonus if he comes in.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's the big deal? Why should anybody care?
</P>
<P>
   The big deal is two-fold. One, Lehtinen isn't just another
player. Two, yesterday's practice was only the second time all
season the Stars have had the entire team on the ice. The other was
the team photo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot of bodies out there. It was kind of nice. You
don't do the drills as often,'' Stars center Mike Modano joked.
``It's probably been since October since we've had everybody out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Mike. Try June.
</P>
<P>
   Stars defenseman Richard Matvichuk hadn't signed in time for
Game 1, and by Game 2, Modano and Darryl Sydor were hurt. Every
time it looked as if the Stars were close to getting their entire
team back, somebody else got injured. (Technically, Brian Skrudland
and Shawn Chambers are still injured, but the Stars have replaced
them, knowing they won't return this season.) The injury carousel
continued all season.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's season spun more out of control than Lehtinen's.
</P>
<P>
   By now, the tale of his ankle has been well-chronicled. He
fractured his right ankle Oct. 16 against Nashville. He was
supposed to miss six weeks, blah, blah, blah. He tired to return
around Thanksgiving but couldn't. He returned on New Year's Eve but
was sidelined again in January. He returned for the regular-season
finale but reinjured his ankle that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a tough season that way,'' Lehtinen said. ``A lot of
guys out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have managed without all of them. They survived
without captain Derian Hatcher, playoff MVP Joe Nieuwendyk, goalie
Ed Belfour, et al. They've survived without Lehtinen for so long
that it's easy to forget what a loss he really is.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the best two-way players in the league,'' Sharks
winger Niklas Sundstrom said. ``He's like Nolan for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Sharks defenseman Jeff Norton: ``He brings what Mike Ricci
brings for us. He's the type of guy who maybe his name isn't in the
score sheet every night or something like that, but he shuts down a
top line.''
</P>
<P>
   These were only two players. Everybody said the same things.
</P>
<P>
   If Lehtinen isn't one of the best two-way players in the league,
it's because he is the best. He can shut down almost anybody, from
Peter Forsberg to Jaromir Jagr. He doesn't look to score big goals,
but he can. He kills penalties. He plays on the power play. He
makes teammates better.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can get Jere, I think that makes the third line a lot
better,'' Carbonneau said.
</P>
<P>
   There is another if, of course, the if that comes when a guy
misses 65 regular-season games and hasn't played a second in the
playoffs. He'll provide a big boost if he can play his gritty,
tenacious, two-way game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not something that a player, even though he's missed a
few games, forgets or loses,'' Sharks coach Darryl Sutter said.
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen says the biggest challenge will be mental. Physically,
he says, he's ready. Beyond ready. He has been swimming and
rehabbing and weathering the frustration, all because as he says:
``I think I can play still. Someday I'll be back.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll see if today is someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Lehtinen said. ``I think so. We'll see how it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   So don't roll your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   If he isn't back tonight, it won't be too long in coming.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, the difference will be noticeable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, you've been out you get hunger, and you have a lot
of energy,'' Lehtinen said. ``A lot.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
