<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER RISING STEADILY, PRODUCTIVITY SLOWS IN FIRST QUARTER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Ill.)  By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After rising spectacularly for six months, the productivity of
U.S. workers climbed more slowly in the first quarter, the Bureau
of Labor Statistics reported Thursday. Once again, most of the
improvement came in the manufacture of computers, machinery, autos,
appliances and other durable goods _ particularly computers and the
chips that go into them.
</P>
<P>
   Labor productivity rose at a 2.4 percent annual rate. That was
less than half the improvement in the two previous quarters and,
indeed, one of the poorer quarterly performances in the last two
years. But over the last four quarters, productivity is still
rising at a very strong 3.7 percent, unchanged from December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Underlying productivity is still very strong,'' said James
Glassman, senior domestic economist at Chase Manhattan Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The labor productivity growth rate published by the bureau is
the chief measure of the efficiency of the average U.S. worker.
When the growth rate rises at a 2.4 percent annual rate, that means
in effect that a steelworker, for example, has improved his
efficiency sufficiently to produce $102.40 worth of steel each
hour, up from $100. Or an auto mechanic, given better tools, or
simply working faster, has increased the garage's revenue from
repairing cars by a similar amount.
</P>
<P>
   Higher productivity means that companies collect more revenue
without employing more labor. The additional money can then go into
raising profits or raising wages, or both, without having to raise
prices. ``There is not a lot of inflation pressure coming from
labor costs yet,'' said Ken Matheny, senior economist at
Macroeconomic Advisers in St. Louis, ``but that situation could
quickly reverse.''
</P>
<P>
   Unit labor costs, the outlay in wages and benefits to labor for
making a fixed amount of steel or repairing a car, did rise at a
1.8 percent annual rate in the first quarter, after having fallen
in the two previous quarters. But over the last 12 months, from
April 1999 through March of this year, unit labor costs were up
only 0.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The strong productivity growth _ averaging 2.8 percent annually
since the end of 1995, up from 1.8 percent in the first half of the
decade and even slower rates in most of the 1980s and 1970s _ helps
to explain why inflation has remained mild.
</P>
<P>
   Another measure of labor costs, however, is not as promising.
Hourly compensation _ covering every outlay for labor, including
bonuses and stock options, when they are cashed in _ rose at a 4.2
percent annual rate in the first quarter, up from 3.8 percent in
the fourth, the bureau reported Thursday. Although 4.2 percent
represents one of the smallest quarterly increases in the last two
years, many economists on Wall Street nevertheless expressed the
worry that inflationary pressures were developing.
</P>
<P>
   They note that the rise in compensation is now clearly
outstripping the rise in productivity, a trend not as clear in the
third and fourth quarters of 1999, when productivity grew at annual
rates of 5 percent and 6.9 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   If productivity growth is slowing, and it may be, Matheny said,
that would create inflationary wage pressures.
</P>
<P>
   For many economists, the most interesting issue is whether the
surge in productivity since 1995 reflects rising productivity
throughout the economy or is narrowly focused. And the answer
appears to be narrowly focused, on durable manufactured goods:
machinery, steel, appliances, vehicles, computers, semiconductors,
communications equipment and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Those goods account for 12 percent of the nation's nonfarm
business output, and if they are subtracted, then the productivity
growth rate for the remaining 88 percent is only 1.8 percent, said
Robert Gordon, a Northwestern University economist.
</P>
<P>
   Other experts gave similar credit to the efficiencies achieved
in manufacturing durable goods, particularly computers,
semiconductors and communications equipment. Part of the strong
productivity growth in computers represents improvement in quality.
Workers, in effect, get credit for manufacturing ever more powerful
and more valuable computers.
</P>
<P>
   A drag on productivity in the first quarter came in the service
sector, in such things as legal and educational services and auto
repair. The number of hours worked rose more quickly in the first
quarter than output, contributing to the slower productivity growth
rate.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department also contributed _ by making payments in
the fourth quarter for goods and services produced in the first.
The payments were added to fourth-quarter output, but the hours
worked to produce the prepaid goods and services were registered in
the first.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
