<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WEBSTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAYARD WEBSTER, 82, SCIENCE EDITOR AND WRITER 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bayard Webster, a former editor on the science desk of The New
York Times and former Times science writer, died on Sunday at the
Heron Point Retirement Community in Chestertown, Md. He was 82.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was congestive heart failure, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Webster worked for The Times from 1957 until he retired in 1985;
during that period he was an editor on the metropolitan desk as
well as on the science desk, and a writer specializing in nature,
wildlife and animal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   His versatility in science writing was shown by such headlines
on his articles as ``Alligators in Love,'' ``Elephants Have
Language Inaudible to Humans'' and ``Prehistoric Man's Killing of
90 Giant Baboons Suggests Early Ritual.''
</P>
<P>
   Webster was born in East Orange, N.J., attended Wesleyan
University in the 1930s, became an account executive at a New York
advertising agency and was a Navy pilot with the rank of lieutenant
in the Pacific theater during World War II. He received the
Distinguished Flying Cross and Air Medal with Silver Star. After
the war he was an editor at The Baltimore Evening Sun before
working for The Times.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, the former Martha Millspaugh, whom
he married in 1951; two sons, Kirk and Anthony; a daughter,
Jacqueline Webster Harwood; and two grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
