<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTPHAL, SONICS MAKE POWERFUL STATEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ It happened moments after an embarrassing Game
2 loss.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics were in an 0-2 hole, and their best-of-five series
against the Utah Jazz seemed hopeless. Even Gary Payton and Vin
Baker admit they never saw the writing on the locker room wall.
</P>
<P>
   Both stars had already bolted by the time Paul Westphal, armed
with a magic marker, marched over to a board. The Sonics coach
calmly scribbled ``We are coming back to Utah'' amid stark silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't look for a reaction,'' Westphal said. `` ... It was
just a statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Seattle has written its ticket in this series,
winning two home games to draw even and force a decisive Game 5
Friday at 5 p.m. against Utah in the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   With their trapping defense, the Sonics reconfigured Utah's
predictable offense and molded the series into Westphal's prophecy.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, ``we are coming back to Utah'' means the animosity
between both teams is a notch higher. The pressure is greater on
the Jazz to avoid blowing what appeared to be an insurmountable
series lead.
</P>
<P>
   And now, the seventh-seeded Sonics are confident they deserve to
move on in place of the second-seeded Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Westphal made a good prediction,'' Payton said. ``We're
going back, and we just have to make it stick, and try to move on
in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised (it's come to this). Anything can happen in
basketball. They won two on their floor and we won two on our
floor. That's the way it's supposed to happen in the playoffs.
You're supposed to protect your home. Now we're going back there to
try and reverse it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Sonics are into script, they can also rewrite a few
records.
</P>
<P>
   They can become the sixth team in NBA history to overcome an 0-2
deficit and win a five-game series. The Sonics also are in position
to become the fifth seventh seed to upset a No. 2 seed in the first
round since this format was adopted.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an element of doubt has crept into the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 2-2, and you never like a deciding game, but that's what
we've got right now,'' Jazz forward Karl Malone said. ``And I don't
think we need any motivation (for Game 5). I don't think we need
any speech. I don't think we need to read about it or talk about it
because these are the kind of games you should be ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics expect a physical, no-holds-barred contest. Verbal
jousting between Malone and Payton at the end of Game 4, which
included seven technical fouls and two ejections, set the tone for
Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to back down to anybody. We're going to play
hard,'' forward Vin Baker said. ``I think (the end of Game 4) was
jockeying, getting ready for Game 5. It's going to be a war and if
you're not ready for a war, you might as well stay home because
it's going to be dirty.''
</P>
<P>
   It is safe to assume that the game will go in the favor of the
team that executes best.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team has changed strategy the past two games. Even
though the Sonics' defense has effectively taken Utah out of its
sets, the Jazz will run the same plays. Utah, which shot 41 percent
in Games 3 and 4, will dare the Sonics to be as good defensively a
third time.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the last time the Jazz lost three consecutive games
was the last week in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's (Utah coach) Jerry Sloan,'' Payton said. ``I played for
him in the 1996 Olympics. He's not going to change anything. That's
why he's still coaching. That's why he wins games. He's not going
to change his lineup (or game plan) to adjust to us. He's been
winning with it all this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``So they're going to be more aggressive. They're going to try
to get more calls. They're going to get the fans in the game.
They're going to try to get the referees on their side. We're just
going to have to try and defuse it and stay focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Composure will be a key.
</P>
<P>
   Next to Sacramento's ARCO Arena, the Delta Center is considered
the most rowdy arena in the NBA. It is also a place where the Jazz
seem to always get the benefit of the doubt with officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be the aggressor in this series,'' Westphal said.
``The officials know the Jazz like to flop and get calls. This game
will be determined by how aggressive we are, hopefully, not by
their flops.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal said the Sonics' 21-20 road record verifies their
mental toughness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have guys that like to shut up the crowd,'' he
said. ``If they beat us, it won't be because the crowd intimidated
us. It will be because the Jazz played a better game than we did.
That's why we've had a good road record this year. We go into a
place and play the game and don't worry about whether people are
yelling for us or against us.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the Sonics have already won regardless of the outcome.
They were the underdogs left for dead after starting the series
with a revamped lineup and some internal discord.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics, though, have proven a point by beating the Jazz
twice _ a feat that made this old-versus-new-blood series
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still contend we have everything to gain by winning this
series, getting into the second round and coming together and
proving to ourselves that we're capable of winning,'' guard Brent
Barry said. ``I don't think that there is so much of that on the
line for them. But there's still pressure on both of us. We both
know if we lose we go home.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
