<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS STRONGER AFTER ETERNITY ON THE EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ This morning begins the 11th day on the
precipice.
</P>
<P>
   Not even Columbus spent that much time at the edge of the earth.
</P>
<P>
   Famous, or infamous, for their play in do-or-die moments during
the term of former coach George Karl, the Sonics under coach Paul
Westphal _ and under an NBA that no longer has a scheduling
conscience _ have stretched brinksmanship to new frontiers.
</P>
<P>
   While five teams in NBA history have come back from 0-2 deficits
to win a best-of-five playoff series, none spent 11 days attempting
to do so. Whatever happens Friday in Game 5 at the Delta Center,
the Sonics will enter the Guinness chronicles in the category of
``Cliffs, Hanging From'' as having the world's toughest
fingernails.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the lone gratifying development in spending much of the
spring dangling over the abyss is that for the last couple of days,
the Sonics have had company.
</P>
<P>
   The Utah Jazz are with them, handholds crumbling to dust, too.
</P>
<P>
   But as recent newcomers, the Jazz, in a rare twist, are the
lesser experienced unit. The Sonics have been here so long the
cable-TV installer has found them.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly for Sonics fans, the Jazz have fewer ways up
and away.
</P>
<P>
   The most surprising aspect of the Sonics' riveting 105-94
triumph in Game 4 Wednesday at KeyArena that evened the series was
how little adapted Utah was to the changes in the Sonics defense
that debuted in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   For two games, the Sonics have blunted the best plays the Jazz
offer. Utah is groping for solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're the favorite, you have something that's been
working and then it stops,'' said Westphal Thursday. ``Suddenly
they say, `Do we change? Do we stick with it?' You start doubting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at (the opponent) and say the line from `Butch
Cassidy and the Sundance Kid': Who ARE these guys?''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the Sonics this season qualify as a mysterious band of
desperados, as likely to shoot themselves as anyone else. But in
these 11 days, they have finally settled on a starting lineup and
an eight-man rotation, as well as attending school on what the Jazz
do best.
</P>
<P>
   ``You keep trying to find something that works, and when you do,
it's like enlightenment,'' said Westphal. ``Then you come together
and believe it. Then you tend to be able to play through the ups
and downs.''
</P>
<P>
   Rarely does such enlightenment strike so belatedly in a season.
But when it does, a fair number of these almost inexplicable
postseason reversals have involved current and former Sonics
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   If the Sonics win Friday, Westphal will be the only coach in NBA
history to have come back twice from 0-2. In 1993, his Phoenix Suns
rang up three straight on the Los Angeles Lakers after losing the
first two at home.
</P>
<P>
   The second team to have pulled the feat (after Fort Wayne in
1956) was the 1987 Golden State Warriors, coached by none other
than George Karl and against the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Sonics assistant coach Nate McMillan has experienced both ends
of the whipsaw as a player. He was a rookie in 1987 when the
seventh-seeded Sonics lost the opening game 151-129 to the
second-seeded Dallas Mavericks, then won three straight, including
two at UW's Hec Edmundson Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, he was a part of the Sonics' collapse to the Denver
Nuggets, the first time a No. 1 seed lost to a No. 8.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan recalled vividly the '94 nightmare, from which only
Gary Payton remains on the active roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're the favorite, at home, and you have to win the last
game,'' he said. ``It's pressure _ a lot of pressure. You wonder:
`What can we do? Coaches, come up with something!' There's nothing
you can do except go out there and try to make plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against Denver, we started making excuses. We started
believing that these guys matched up well with us _ which they did.
That's similar to what Utah is facing. We've defended their best
plays very well, and stopped what adjustments they can make.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real confidence for them is they're going home. But they
are nervous about the fact that we have their number on the
floor.''
</P>
<P>
   A year before the Sonics' crash, Westphal had his big reversal,
although it was not an upset. The Suns were top-seeded in the West,
but the eighth-seeded Lakers took the first two games in Phoenix,
mostly because of an injury hampering Suns All-Star guard Kevin
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Westphal boldly predicted after Game 2 that the Suns
would win the series _ no equivocations or asterisks. The
spontaneous maneuver worked when the Suns, with Johnson back in
form, took three straight, eventually advancing to the Finals
against the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had to,'' he said of becoming the lightning rod
for media and fans. ``If I didn't believe in them, who would? The
last thing we wanted was finger-pointing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took pressure off them and made them feel better that the
coach wasn't kicking them while they were down like everybody
else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns also had then what the Sonics have now _ a ruthless top
gun willing to eat gravel and spit it at the bad guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each team had a crazy superstar who could rise to the occasion
in any circumstance,'' he said. ``For all that swirled around
Charles Barkley and swirled around Gary, the other players have
been able to understand that in a big game, both guys can do
amazing things.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have somebody like that on your team, you have a
chance to win a big game.''
</P>
<P>
   Having returned from the cliff's edge once, doing the deed again
does not seem so preposterous to Westphal. And after this visit of
11 days, it would be a shame to let go now, just when it's become
familiar and comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
