<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6114 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-DEVIL-RAY     05-05 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-DEVIL-RAYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS LOSE IN 11TH AS VAUGHN HOMERS FOR DEVIL RAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The Rangers came close last night to
having a wonderful flight back to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   They could have sat back, relaxed, popped a cold one at 30,000
feet and toasted many things: a winning road trip, an exhilarating
comeback, Mike Lamb's first career home run and maybe, if
everything had fallen right, John Wetteland's 300th career save.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't quite work out that way. After a wild ride over
the final six innings, the Rangers' gritty effort came to an abrupt
end when Greg Vaughn hit a one-out home run off Jeff Zimmerman in
the bottom of the 11th to give the Tampa Bay Devil Rays an 8-7
victory at Tropicana Field.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn almost single-handedly destroyed the Rangers' potential
late-night celebration somewhere over the Gulf of Mexico. He had a
broken-bat double off Tim Crabtree in the seventh that led to a
three-run rally and another run-scoring double off Francisco
Cordero in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't make a much better pitch than that,'' Crabtree said.
``He flares it out to right field. The story of my season ... our
season.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been that bad lately, but instead of enjoying
themselves last night, the Rangers were left to wonder about
Vaughn's late-inning marvels and the continued vulnerability of
their once-dominate right-handed setup relievers.
</P>
<P>
   There is probably nothing more on the minds of Oates and
pitching coach Dick Bosman than Crabtree and Zimmerman.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was our strength,'' Oates said. ``I told Bos during the
game, we've got to get things worked out. We depend on them. It's
been a rough month for Crabby, it's been a rough month for Zim. But
we have a long way to go. They'll get it back because we need
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Both admit to being frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not as consistent as I want to be,'' said Zimmerman, now
0-4 with a 7.36 earned-run average. ``Definitely a lot more of my
mistakes are being punished than last year, but I don't have to
same level of execution either.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to hold the game at 7-7, Zimmerman executed enough to
strike out Dave Martinez to start the 11th. He then threw one good
slider to Vaughn and one bad one. The bad one ended in the seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's his bread-and-butter pitch,'' Vaughn said. ``He made a
mistake. The first one was good. The second one was up a little
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Crabtree, with the Rangers up 4-3 on home runs by Lamb and Ruben
Mateo, entered the game for Esteban Loaiza with one out in the
seventh and a runner on second base. But Vaughn doubled down the
right field line to tie the game and, after Fred McGriff was
intentionally walked and Vinny Castilla popped out, John Flaherty
grounded a run-scoring single through the left side.
</P>
<P>
   A wild pitch brought home another run, and the Devil Rays added
an unearned run off Cordero in the eighth to take a 7-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, yeah, I'm frustrated,'' said Crabtree, whose ERA is
9.22. ``It seems like it's been on one good outing, one bad outing.
I can't get on a roll.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened to Zimmerman and Crabtree was nothing compared
with what the Rangers did to their old nemesis, Roberto Hernandez,
in the ninth. Down three runs, the Rangers hammered him for five
consecutive _ including clutch singles from injured infielders Luis
Alicea and Rafael Palmeiro _ to tie it at 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez left with no out outs, runners at first and second,
and the sparse remaining crowd booing loudly. But the Rangers
couldn't finish the rally against Devil Rays reliever Albie Lopez.
After Chad Curtis bunted the runners to second and third and Ivan
Rodriguez was walked intentionally, Lopez induced David Segui to
hit into an inning-ending double play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
