<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 STRAIGHT SKINNY ON A WEIGHTY ISSUE  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The city is throwing its weight behind people of
width.
</P>
<P>
   I would say ``fat people,'' but only fat people can say ``fat
people.''
</P>
<P>
   I can't say overweight, because that begs the question, ``Over
 &UR; what? &LR; ''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the largeness lobby is prevailing upon the S.F. Board of
Supervisors to add height and weight language to city's
anti-discrimination codes.
</P>
<P>
   This is good, but I am hoping the language doesn't leave skinny
people falling between the cracks.
</P>
<P>
   I am a recovering thinny. Long ago I was thin. That's no longer
a problem, but I remember the pain, society's constant hurtful
reminders that thin ain't in.
</P>
<P>
   Who controls the world? Fat cats. Thin cats control nothing.
</P>
<P>
   If you are way overly sensitive, you are thin-skinned. When the
outlook is desperately bleak, your chances are slim and none. If
there's almost nothing left to choose from, it's slim pickings.
</P>
<P>
   If some weasel is looking for dirt or gossip, he asks, ``What's
the skinny?'' Lousy movie or book? Yeah, the plot was thin.
</P>
<P>
   If someone's fat, they are jolly, or prosperous. Someone's
skinny, they are lean and mean.
</P>
<P>
   The economy is in the Dumpster? Lean times, man, I don't have
one thin dime.
</P>
<P>
   Not much of substance in this column? Yes, the material is thin.
Other columnists write heavy stuff; I'm a lightweight. This is a
buncha crap, thinly disguised as journalism. Maybe I can beef it up
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   NORMAN ROCKWELL moment:
</P>
<P>
   Isadora Alman was motoring on Geary, came to a red light and
stopped behind a red sports car and an SUV.
</P>
<P>
   Sports car had top down and speakers blaring rap at bone-vibrate
level, the F-word echoing off buildings. The SUV driver was glaring
at the sports-car driver while chatting on a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between the two of them a helmeted biker glided to a stop. He
lifted both hands from his handlebars and simultaneously gave the
rigid digit to both drivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Eloquent.
</P>
<P>
   IN CARMEL, they take their junk seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The Church of the Wayfarer is having its annual Upscale Rummage
Sale on Saturday, and a special $10 ticket admits you to the
two-hour ``pre-sale'' tonight. After that: Slim pickings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be there,'' says Daryl Glen. ``Don't want to miss out on
those castoff Monets.''
</P>
<P>
   WE GOT CARMEL covered here, folks.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Montague read an item about a crime-log note in the Carmel
Pine Cone, a report of a dead bear cub that turned out to be a live
cat.
</P>
<P>
   ``While this was amusing,'' sniffs Ernie, ``Carmel does have
serious crime. Two years ago, high school kids on a drunken rampage
whacked my mom's mailbox with a baseball bat, causing a dent. It's
sad that you portray Carmel as a crime-free paradise.''
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute, Ernie. I thought Carmel didn't have mailboxes.
It's a felony to defraud a columnist, you know.
</P>
<P>
   MORE LARGE NEWS: People of width have erotic poetry, too.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight: ``Big Love: An Evening of Plus-Sized Poetry,'' 7:30,
848 Divisadero (at Fulton).
</P>
<P>
   They don't say if snacks will be served, but I'm guessing yes.
</P>
<P>
   And once again, the skinnies are left out in the cold. There are
no erotic poetry readings for the emaciated.
</P>
<P>
   RATS VS. LIZARDS: No, this isn't about politics.
</P>
<P>
   The Conservatory of Flowers is wiping out a cockroach
infestation by unleashing hungry gecko lizards. But someone told me
rats will feast on the lizards.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong, says Sherri Ferris, apparently an expert on rats and
geckos. She says the lizards are too elusive for the rats, who
can't get into the building anyway.
</P>
<P>
   And: here's a handy tip offered by Tom Pettyjohn. He remembers
reading in Mother Earth magazine that rats cannot burp. So if you
have a rat problem, put out a saucer of cola. The little pests will
drink up and since the fizz has to go somewhere, they'll internally
belch their little brains out, thus failing the Pepsi Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   No word on whether geckos or cockroaches can burp.
</P>
<P>
   FUSCHIA. That's the color of the window overhangs at the new San
Leandro Boy Scout office.
</P>
<P>
   Gary William Molitor wonders, ``Has the official Boy Scout
position on homosexuality softened?''
</P>
<P>
   REVISIONIST HISTORY: The Kent State shootings were 30 years ago,
and memories fade. But the moment was memorialized by Crosby,
Stills, Nash and Young in the song ``Ohio.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Signer heard a local radio DJ comment that ``Ohio'' was
about an event that occurred at Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   Right, and it was Woody Hayes doing the shooting.
</P>
</TEXT>
