<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OYSTER-FOSSILS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLIEST `OYSTER BAR' FOUND IN AFRICA
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists have discovered the earliest well-dated example of an
oyster bar _ a fossil reef on Africa's Red Sea coast where
ancestral humans must have waded out to collect oysters, clams,
scallops and crabs some 125,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery shows that early humans had taken up coastal life
at least 10,000 years earlier than previously believed, and it
suggests that waves of those humans could have migrated out of
Africa and into Europe and Asia along the Red Sea coast, in
addition to other routes.
</P>
<P>
   An international team of geologists and anthropologists
unearthed a trove of stone tools from the fossil reef along the Red
Sea coast of Eritrea. The researchers like to call their discovery
``the world's first oyster bar.''
</P>
<P>
   But they also propose a far more significant meaning to their
find: It could help resolve long-standing debates about the origin
and evolution of modern humans and their migration routes out of
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   A report in the current issue of the journal Nature describes
the scientists' discovery of two-sided stone hand axes and flaked
obsidian blades in the same fossil reef terrace as the fossil
remains of shelled bivalves and crabs.
</P>
<P>
   The site where the stone tools were found is near the Red Sea
coastal village of Abdur in Eritrea's Gulf of Zula. In the same
area, the team also discovered fossil bones of large land animals,
including elephants, antelopes, rhinoceros and hippopotamus.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that the humans who lived at the site may have driven
some of those animals toward the sea and killed them there to
supplement their seafood diet, the team suggested.
</P>
<P>
   The expedition was led by Robert C. Walter, a geologist with
Mexico's Center for Scientific Investigations and Higher Education
in Ensenada, Mexico, and included scientists from Mexico, Canada,
the United States, the Netherlands, France and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
   According to Walter, the site offers the oldest evidence of
modern humans' adaptation to seashore living _ at least 10,000
years older than similar evidence from recent finds along the
shores of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear, Walter said, that the people of 125,000 years ago
were living during a relatively warm ``interglacial'' period that
succeeded an earlier cold epoch when inland humans might have been
driven toward the east African coast as lakes and rivers froze or
dried up.
</P>
<P>
   No one doubts that Africa was the original home of humanity.
Recent studies of the genes of today's humans strongly imply that
modern Homo sapiens arose from more primitive species of Homo
between 200,000 and 150,000 years ago. Those studies also suggest
that humanity began spreading into Europe, the Near East, and Asia
well before 100,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, those modern humans eventually must have displaced
the evolutionary dead-end Neanderthal peoples, while other
migration waves eastward reached India about 60,000 years ago and
Australia by 40,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fossil bones of long-ago peoples discovered in Israel and Jordan
seem to confirm that pattern of northward and eastward migration,
and the discovery by Walter's team provides a significant clue to
at least one of the migration routes out of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our discovery opens up a whole new way of looking at early
man, his origins and immigration routes all along that coast _ and
probably during many more waves of migration,'' said Richard
Buffler, a geologist at the University of Texas at Austin who first
explored the site with Walter and his team three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The bones of the larger animals, Buffler said, were found close
to the ``oyster bar,'' and must have offered the early humans who
lived there the world's first opportunity for ``surf and turf
dining.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the expedition hope to return to the site soon to
search for other coastal dwelling places by humans. But that hope
may prove difficult to realize right now, Buffler said, because of
the uncertainties raised by the border war between Eritrea and
Ethiopia.
</P>
</TEXT>
