<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP CANDIDATE REVEALS MORE CANDID _ AND PLAYFUL _ SIDE ON 
 CALIFORNIA SWING
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  PALM SPRINGS, Calif. _ George W. Bush, on a campaign swing
through California, heads to the back of the plane where the press
is hunkered down and flashes a mischievous grin.
<P>
   He holds up a newspaper bearing the major endorsement that most
of them missed: The Weekly World News, a tabloid that scooped the
world this week by announcing ``Alien Endorses Bush for
President.''
</P>
<P>
   ``New faces, new voices,'' Bush mugged. ``It goes to show I'm
willing to reach across certain demographic lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it a ploy, a practicality or simply good campaign strategy,
but the presumptive GOP nominee is definitely on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor, once pegged as a candidate too scared to
deal with the sharks of the Fourth Estate, has not only begun
swimming with them, but seems playfully at home doing it.
</P>
<P>
   As he makes his second campaign trip in California since the
state's March 7 primary _ and vows to return in two weeks _ a Wall
Street Journal and NBC News poll released this week shows he has
seized the lead from Vice President Al Gore, 46 to 41 percent, with
his biggest gains in the crucial Midwest and among women and
Catholics. In a March poll, Bush trailed by three percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   And the polls numbers  &LR; aren't the only place where the campaign
has been pumped up. With the tough primary campaign behind him,
Bush has become noticeably more confident and comfortable, both in
public and in private.
</P>
<P>
   In Santa Ana Thursday, he walked the Fourth Street Mall in the
heart of the city's Latino business district, hearing cries of
 &UR; ``Tejano!''  &LR; (Texan) and  &UR; ``Viva Bush, &LR; '' as he practiced his
Spanish on just about anyone who would listen. In the same week a
Field Poll suggested that Republicans have little hope of winning
them over, Bush visited the heart of Democratic Rep. Loretta
Sanchez's district, underscoring his push for new Latino voters.
</P>
<P>
   In the Fiesta Market and Taqueria, the GOP candidate slid behind
a Formica table and ordered a  &UR; ``taco de carne asada ... &LR; 
 &UR; con todo, &LR; '' then plunged into the plate of meat, guacamole, salsa
and onions _ with gusto.
</P>
<P>
   His style contrasts markedly with that of Gore, the presumptive
Democratic nominee, who stumbled badly with his comments on the
Elian Gonzalez case and whose press availability Thursday made news
because he so rarely meets reporters these days. Journalists
covering Gore's recent visits to California have been kept at bay
behind rope line _ keeping the candidate out of earshot of
reporters yelling questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore has been so unavailable ... and you have an opponent
who is making love to the press, and the press responds,'' said
state political analyst Sherry Bebitch Jeffe.
</P>
<P>
   Garry South, who advises Democratic Gov. Gray Davis, said Bush
cannot win California because of his stands on key issues like
abortion, gun control and the environment. South claims the GOP
candidate's California outreach is ``designed more to placate the
Republican leadership than it is to influence any voters. It's all
a show.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bebitch Jeffe says Bush's success may reflect voters' desire
for more authenticity from their candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters are at a place where they're looking for someone who's
at least in their own skin,'' she said. ``Bush has gotten into that
mode, and Gore has gotten away from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bush, once distant from the media and sheltered in the
front compartment of his campaign plane, now joshes with reporters,
delivering self-deprecating lines and seizing their cell phones to
chat with their surprised families back home.
</P>
<P>
   But the Texas governor gets serious when it counts.
</P>
<P>
   In a press conference Thursday, he ramped up criticism of Gore,
saying the vice president has been a candidate more interested in
``tearing people down'' than offering ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like talking about me and my ideas,'' Bush said. ``I'm glad
he's talking about me and my ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also appears more frank and confident answering questions
about his father's administration, telling an ABC News crew
Thursday that President Bush made a mistake when he reneged on his
``read my lips'' promise not to raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Political insiders say the changes have come because Bush, after
months on the campaign trail, has clearly absorbed some tough
lessons _ many of them from Arizona Sen. John McCain, a onetime
rival for the Republican nomination, whom he will meet with
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of what he knows and what he articulates, yes, he's
begun to study,'' said Bebitch Jeffe. ``His people have begun to
program him, and I don't mean that in the negative sense ... he's
going through what he needs to in a presidential campaign, and he's
become more focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Goodman, a longtime Bush friend and GOP consultant, said
``the more personable, comfortable, authentic, in-your-own-skin
side of Bush is starting to penetrate and permeate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bebitch Jeffe said Bush's strategy is ``brilliant: neutralize
Gore on the issues and make this all about character.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, California Democrats fairly fume when they discuss the
campaign these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush could be here on vacation for all the good it's going to
do him,'' said South, the political adviser to Gov. Davis. South
predicted that when the going gets tough in the fall, Bush won't be
as accessible to California media _ and won't be here much at all.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush was quick to counter. ``It's wishful thinking,'' he
said Thursday, ``for Al Gore and his supporters to think I'm going
to write California off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
