r a BC-CHRONICLE-SALE-SFCHRO     05-05 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRONICLE-SALE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 3 NATIONAL FIRMS SOUGHT CHRONICLE BESIDES HEARST  &HT;     By REYNOLDS HOLDING 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Three of the nation's largest newspaper
companies competed aggressively to buy The San Francisco Chronicle
last year, but the Hearst Corp. trumped their efforts with a bid at
least $100 million more than the others were willing to pay, a
financial adviser to The Chronicle testified Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of the Los Angeles Times, the San Jose Mercury News
and USA Today said they would pay between about $400 million and
$550 million for The Chronicle, far below Hearst's winning offer of
$660 million in cash, said Jill Greenthal, a managing director at
investment bank Donaldson Lufkin and Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believed it was the highest price they (The Chronicle
owners) were going to see,'' testified Greenthal, who was called as
a witness by attorneys for Chronicle Publishing Co.
</P>
<P>
   Her testimony came during the fourth day of trial in former
mayoral candidate Clint Reilly's antitrust lawsuit to stop Hearst's
purchase of The Chronicle. Chronicle attorney Gregory Lindstrom
used Greenthal's statements to undermine Reilly's contention that
other newspapers would have been willing to pay more for The
Chronicle if Hearst had not pre-empted the bidding with an offer
submitted before the August 10 deadline. The Chronicle announced
its sale to Hearst on August 6.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly argues in his suit that Hearst intends to create an
illegal newspaper monopoly in San Francisco by purchasing The
Chronicle and giving the Examiner to the Fang family, publishers of
the San Francisco Independent.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle and the Examiner currently operate under a joint
operating agreement that allows the two papers to share printing
and other business operations while maintaining editorial
independence.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly claims that Hearst's proposed transfer of the Examiner _
with a subsidy of up to $66 million over three years _ to the Fang
family is a ``sham'' sale that will ensure the newspaper's demise
in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's testimony, though, offered the first public glimpse
into how The Chronicle solicited buyers and which potential
purchasers were most interested.
</P>
<P>
   According to Greenthal, The Chronicle's owners hired her firm in
February 1999 to evaluate their financial options. By May,
Greenthal had concluded that their best option was to sell The
Chronicle and Chronicle Publishing Company's other holdings,
including television station KRON, Chronicle Books and newspapers
in Massachusetts and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Greenthal valued The Chronicle at between $400 million and $610
million and the entire company at between $2 billion and $2.4
billion, she testified Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   One hurdle to a sale of The Chronicle, she said, was Hearst's
right to match any offer for the paper. To skirt the problem, she
recommended bundling The Chronicle with Chronicle Publishing's two
other newspapers so that any sale would include all three papers
rather than just The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Before any offers had been solicited, Hearst said it would offer
$565 million for The Chronicle alone, but the bid was rejected,
said Greenthal.
</P>
<P>
   Three other companies quickly expressed interest in The
Chronicle and said they would be willing to take the other two
papers just to get it. The companies were Gannett Co., owner of USA
Today and the Marin Independent-Journal; Knight Ridder, Inc., owner
of the San Jose Mercury News and the Contra Costa Times; and Times
Mirror Co., then-owner of the Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   Knight Ridder, Greenthal testified, ``really wanted to buy'' The
Chronicle. ``They pursued it aggressively.'' Tony Ridder, president
of the company, indicated to Greenthal that it would be willing to
pay ``in the low to mid-400s for the Chronicle alone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Times Mirror said it would be willing to pay up to ``the low
500s,'' Greenthal testified, about the same as Gannett was willing
to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst, meanwhile, asked Greenthal what it would take to buy The
Chronicle, and she suggested that the owners wanted at least $700
million. Hearst then offered $660 million, and a deal was struck,
she testified.
</P>
<P>
   On cross-examination by Reilly's attorney, Joseph M. Alioto,
Greenthal was forced to explain some of the scenarios presented to
The Chronicle owners in a confidential report. Two of the scenarios
dealt with what might happen after the joint operating agreement
expired in 2005: the first with one surviving newspaper and the
second with a ``newspaper war'' between The Chronicle and the
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   With one newspaper, the report projected that advertising rates
would rise about 20 percent. With two competing newspapers, though,
the report said ad rates would drop between 10 percent and 15
percent and that newsstand prices would also drop for The
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Greenthal responded that this was ``a worst-case scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   But Alioto argued that the report proved consumers and
advertisers would benefit if both newspapers stayed in business
past 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ``You call competition `war' and `pessimistic,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenthal pointed out that the report also projected that the
Examiner would lose $160 million if it stayed in business for three
years after the joint operating agreement expired in 2005 and that
Hearst would then shut the paper down.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, The Chronicle announced Thursday that the paper would
drop its newsstand price from 50 cents to 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto pounced on the announcement, saying that the drop
``appears to be as a result of (Reilly's) lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   But Steven Falk, president of the San Francisco Newspaper
Agency, which runs the two newspapers' business operations, called
Alioto's charge ``absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   The price drop was announced to Chronicle staff last week, and
new coin boxes for the news racks were ordered months ago, Falk
said.
</P>
<P>
   The paper also announced Thursday that it would expand its
business section and publish a special section for San Francisco
readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these initiatives are part of our strategic marketing
plan for the year 2000. They are all designed to better serve
readers and advertisers and have been in the planning stages for
several months.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 0035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
