<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6122 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NETWORTH-COLUMN-SFCHR     05-05 1657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET WORTH: TOP-PERFORMING SMALL-CAP VALUE FUNDS ARE
WORTH  INVESTIGATING
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By KATHLEEN PENDER 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A sentence buried in the next-to-last page of
Wednesday's Wall Street Journal caught my attention. It said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the 1,596 stock mutual funds that have a rating of four or
five stars (from Morningstar), 342 are large-cap growth funds and
just five are small-cap value funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the market's disdain for small, cheap companies, I was
surprised that any small-cap value fund had earned four or five
stars. Naturally I was curious to see who these 5-foot-10-inch
players in the NBA were. The story didn't say, so I went to
 &LR; www.morningstar.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that no small-cap value funds rate five stars, and
only four get four stars. Although Morningstar's rating system is
based solely on past performance _ a criticism at the heart of the
Journal article _ I still figured these funds were worth a look.
</P>
<P>
   But first a bit of background. For the past few years,
investors, like car buyers, have been infatuated with anything big,
fast and expensive (think SUVs). Last year, they also lusted after
small, fast and expensive (think Porsches). That left anything
small and cheap sitting on the lot.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 and 1999, small-cap value funds trailed growth funds of
all sizes and large-cap value funds. But things may be changing.
With an average return of 2.1 percent this year, small-cap value
funds are at the top of a very small heap.
</P>
<P>
   These funds typically buy stocks that are cheap by traditional
yardsticks such as price-to-earnings or price-to-book value. This
kept most of them out of high-flying technology and Internet
stocks, which hurt their performance in 1998 and 1999 but helped
them this year.
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar categorizes funds not by how they say they will
invest, but by how they actually invest. Funds in the
small-cap-value category own stocks with an average P/E ratio of
19.6 and a median market value of $586 million.
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar analyst Christopher Traulsen sees three reasons to
reconsider small-cap value. First, growth funds have done so well
that investors may need to ``rebalance'' their portfolios by adding
value funds.
</P>
<P>
   Second is the takeover potential of small caps. ``When companies
get this cheap, it may escape Wall Street's notice, but it doesn't
escape the notice of big companies,'' Traulsen says.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, small-cap value ``has a lot of upside potential, and a
lot less price risk'' than growth, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Before jumping into any fund, it's important to find out how it
achieved its returns. If a fund invested in stocks like Cisco
Systems, it may not be a good choice if what you really want is
small-cap value. That said, let's take a look at the four
small-value funds that earned four stars.
</P>
<P>
   Royce Funds
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that two of the four were from the Royce family
of funds.
</P>
<P>
   All nine Royce funds specialize in small-cap value, which makes
these guys total experts, but also makes it a tad confusing if all
you want is one small-cap fund.
</P>
<P>
   The two that made the list are Royce Trust and GiftShares,
managed by Chuck Royce, and Royce Opportunity, managed by Buzz
Zaino.
</P>
<P>
   The Trust and GiftShares fund is an ``off-the-shelf trust'' that
requires investors to put money into an account for someone else _
usually a child _ for at least 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Both Royce funds are managed similarly, but GiftShares holds
fewer stocks than most funds. That makes it more volatile on the
upside _ and helped account for its good performance _ as well as
the downside. If you're holding for 10 years, volatility shouldn't
be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   In the Opportunity fund, Zaino says his ``eclectic approach''
looks first for undervalued assets on the balance sheet and then
for growth prospects on the income statement.
</P>
<P>
   He generally invests for 12 to 18 months. After that time, he
sells his winners ``and moves on to the next thing.''
</P>
<P>
   A former technology analyst, Zaino says he's ``not afraid'' of
tech stocks. During the Asian economic crisis of 1998, the sector
got very cheap and Zaino loaded up on chip-equipment-makers,
distributors and other tech stocks.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, his big hits included Photon Dynamics and California
Micro Devices. ``This year, we've had Precision Castparts,
Benchmark Electronics and Coorstek.'' The last is a ceramics
company spun out of the Coors brewing empire.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Zaino is finding value in defense and retailing. He
thinks the military budget has been so depleted that defense
spending will grow no matter who becomes president. He especially
likes EDO and DRS Technologies and a couple others he's still
buying and won't name.
</P>
<P>
   He's also bullish on low-end retailers like Burlington Coat
Factory and Fred's, which should benefit from a probable increase
in the minimum wage and a possible tax cut. ``That (money) goes to
people with a high propensity to spend. You'll see it in those
stores fairly quickly,'' Zaino says.
</P>
<P>
   Bigger retailers like Kohl's, Kmart and Wal-Mart also will
benefit, but those companies are trading at 40 to 50 times
earnings. The companies Zaino likes are trading at eight to 10
times earnings, which gives them less risk and greater upside
potential. ``If something goes from six to seven times earnings,
you just made 16 percent. You get that statistical bias,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Royce also likes retailers such as Ross Stores, Claire's and
Urban Outfitters, the last of which ``is in a class by itself. It's
very eclectic and fashion forward _ not the kind of thing you're
ever going to buy on the Internet. The stock fell by 60 percent
when the company missed earnings estimates, and Royce expects at
least two more bad quarters. ``We're not afraid to buy into
short-term disappointments,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Third Avenue Value
</P>
<P>
   Anybody who thinks small-cap value investing is dull has never
talked with Marty Whitman, the long-tenured manager of the Third
Avenue Value fund.
</P>
<P>
   Calling from the Bahamas, the 75-year-old ``vulture investor''
says he'll continue managing the fund ``as long as I'm  &LR; compos
mentis &LR;  (sane). What else am I going to do? If I could qualify to
be a tennis pro, I'd quit tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Third Avenue doesn't bill itself as a small-cap fund. In fact,
it can buy a wide range of big, small, foreign and domestic
equities.
</P>
<P>
   But its median market capitalization of $1.4 billion _ meaning
half of the stocks in the fund are worth more than $1.4 billion and
half are worth less _ still places it in Morningstar's small-cap
value category. (The category ranges from a median market cap of
$325 million to $1.7 billion.)
</P>
<P>
   The fund's larger market cap is partly a result of its success
and its emphasis on minimizing taxes. Compared with the Royce
funds, Whitman is more reluctant to sell his big winners because a
sale triggers capital gains taxes.
</P>
<P>
   And Whitman has his share of winners. Like Royce, he made a big
bet on technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1997 and 1998, when the semiconductor equipment industry
was going through its worst depression, we loaded up and it got to
be almost 40 percent of our assets,'' Whitman says. ``We've
lightened up on some of the more glamorous ones,'' such as Applied
Materials and KLA Tencor. His fund remains the largest shareholder
of San Jose, Calif.'s Silicon Valley Group.
</P>
<P>
   The fund is expanding its positions in real estate, health care,
agricultural equipment and financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're steady buyers of Catellus,'' the big San Francisco real
estate developer, Whitman says. ``Nothing is easier for us to
analyze than well-managed real estate selling at a discount from
appraised value.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Whitman will turn his attention to beat-up Internet
stocks. ``I met recently with my research staff. I said we're going
to have a reprise of the semiconductor equipment (sell-off) 10
times over in dot-coms, but the goddamn problem is it's much harder
to analyze. At least 80 percent of the dot-coms are phony
baloney.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; State Street Aurora
</P>
<P>
   The State Street Research Aurora fund is managed by the
self-effacing Rudy Kluiber. He attributes his recent success to
painstaking research and luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of our companies got taken over. That helped,'' he says.
But acquisitions are mixed blessings. ``You get a short-term pop,
but then you have to go back to the drawing board.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his big takeovers last year was Wyman-Gordon, which is in
the glamorous business of forging aerospace parts such as a landing
gear. It was acquired by Precision Castparts.
</P>
<P>
   Among his non-takeover winners is Coherent, a Santa Clara,
Calif., maker of medical and industrial lasers. ``My average cost
is probably $17. It's at $54 now.'' he says. The stock represents
about 5 percent of his fund, but ``it's not necessarily one I'd buy
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Kluiber says Coherent is ``a leader in its field, it's
profitable and its growth is accelerating. The sizzle is their deep
UV lasers for the semiconductor business. They also have a budding
optical components business.''
</P>
<P>
   Sectors he finds inexpensive include auto parts, rail supply,
casinos and financial institutions. Tech stocks make up 15 percent
of his fund _ matching Morningstar's small-cap-value category
average.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest challenges facing small-cap managers is a
belief that as technology forces prices down and markets become
more global, companies will have to achieve economies of scale to
compete. In other words, bigger is better.
</P>
<P>
   Kluiber says, ``That very well could be true. That's why we try
to make sure our small companies are leaders in what they do. It's
just that their markets are small. A small company that tries to
compete against Microsoft in the operating systems market is not
going to survive. A large company in a small niche can do well.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at  &LR; kpender(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
