<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-PRICEWAR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PRICE WAR IS GOOD NEWS FOR BAY AREA READERS  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's a good time to be a news junkie.
</P>
<P>
   An old-fashioned newspaper war is breaking out in the Bay Area,
with several major dailies announcing plans to cut newsstand prices
to a quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle joined the fray Thursday by saying it will cut its
newsstand price in half, to 25 cents from 50 cents, beginning
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The move follows word from the San Jose Mercury News that it,
too, plans to lower the newsstand price of its paper in San
Francisco, to 25 cents from 35 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, the Contra Costa Times said yesterday that it
will also cut its newsstand price, to 25 cents from 50 cents, also
beginning Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that increases newspaper competition is a good
thing,'' said Steve Barnett, a University of California at Berkeley
law professor specializing in the publishing industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had far too little economic competition,'' he said.
``It's very welcome that a newspaper war is breaking out again.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most observers, Barnett cited the pending acquisition of
The Chronicle by Hearst Corp. and its pending sale of the San
Francisco Examiner as being behind all the changes in the local
media market.
</P>
<P>
   ``One has to assume it's a reaction to Hearst's move,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, Bay Area newspapers are wasting no time in
trying to steal away readers from rival dailies, not to mention
hang on to existing readers.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury News, with a daily circulation of about 300,000, was
the first to announce plans to drop the price of its papers in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Along with a price cut, Mercury News Executive Editor David
Yarnold was quoted last month as saying his paper would beef up its
San Francisco bureau and begin publishing a San Francisco section
by early summer.
</P>
<P>
   Yarnold was unavailable for comment yesterday. But Patty Wise,
Mercury News public relations manager, had this to say from a
prepared statement: ``We are in a competitive environment and we do
not discuss our business plans.''
</P>
<P>
   While insisting that she was not contradicting Yarnold's earlier
statements, Wise stressed that the Mercury News' plans for San
Francisco are ``a liquid situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Falk, the president and chief executive of the San
Francisco Newspaper Agency, which is responsible for all
noneditorial aspects of The Chronicle and Examiner, admitted that a
perceived threat from the Mercury News played a role in The
Chronicle's price cut.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle has a daily circulation of about 457,000. The
Examiner, with a daily circulation of about 107,000, already sells
for 25 cents during the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to sell more copies,'' Falk said. ``The Mercury News,
combined with our March publishing numbers that showed circulation
to be down, motivated us to get serious about turning around
newspaper trends.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he said the lower prices would not extend to The
Chronicle's subscription sales, which will remain at 50 cents a
copy. Falk said this wouldn't change even if the Mercury News
slashed its delivery charges as well.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Falk did say the lower newsstand price will
probably last for quite some time.
</P>
<P>
   George Riggs, publisher of the Contra Costa Times, had no
illusions about why his paper, with a daily circulation of about
173,000, was jumping on the price-cut bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're following your lead,'' he said. ``If you're moving to a
quarter, we're moving to a quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Fang, publisher of the Independent and publisher-in-waiting
of the Examiner, could not be reached for comment on how he would
price the Examiner if, as planned, he were to move it to morning
publication.
</P>
<P>
   For now, in terms of a price war, he has all other Bay Area
newspapers beat. He gives the Independent away, three times a week.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; davidlaz(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
