<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETRADE-SURVEY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 E-TRADE GAINS ON SCHWAB, SURVEY SAYS  &HT;     By SAM ZUCKERMAN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The sound you hear in the online brokerage
market could be E-Trade breathing down Charles Schwab Corp.'s neck.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of industry market share released Thursday by the
brokerage firm U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray shows the No. 2 Internet
broker narrowing the gap with San Francisco's Schwab by a full
percentage point in the first three months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   During a quarter in which the online brokerage industry's total
trades per day catapulted an astonishing 69 percent from the fourth
quarter of 1999, TD Waterhouse, Fidelity Investments and Ameritrade
also gained on the market leader.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade would be poised to overtake its rival in about a year
were it not for Schwab's recent purchase of CyBerCorp, No. 9 in
trading market share and the fastest-growing firm among the top 10,
said Piper Jaffray analyst Stephen Franco, the report's author.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you fold CyBerCorp in, E-Trade might not catch them,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The breathtaking growth in online trading early this year
reflected the continuing move of investors to the Internet plus a
cresting of the mania for technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, brokers stirred the pot by spending a record $600
million on advertising, up from $400 million in the previous
quarter, Piper Jaffray estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Menlo Park, Calif.'s E-Trade spent $154 million, while
Ameritrade shelled out $55 million. They were rewarded with the two
largest trading-volume gains among major brokers, 74.1 percent and
82 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   With many stock prices down, trading has subsided in the current
quarter, Franco said. He predicted a 15 percent fall in overall
volume from first-quarter levels.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab registered an average of 293,318 trades per day during
the latest period, equaling 21.4 percent of the total market.
Buoyed by heavy ad spending, E-Trade posted 214,573 trades per day,
raising its share to 15.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Those figures compared with a 22 percent market share for Schwab
and 15.3 percent for E-Trade in the fourth quarter of last year.
And the gap was much wider the year before that. At the end of
1998, Schwab had a 27.6 percent share, while E-Trade was third
behind Waterhouse, with 11.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While Schwab lost market share, its trading volume still jumped
65.3 percent, Piper Jaffray calculated. ``The firm should be
extremely pleased,'' Franco said.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Schwab said it looks at other market share
measures. ``Trades are important. So are assets and so are
accounts,'' said spokesman Dan Hubbard. ``You've got to look at all
three.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwab continued to have a substantial lead in online customer
assets, with $417.7 billion compared with No. 2 Fidelity's $328.3
billion. E-Trade was a distant fourth by that measure behind
Waterhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity, which operates under the Powerstreet name, took the
top spot in the number of online accounts, with 4.2 million
compared with Schwab's 3.7 million. E-Trade was third with 2.4
million.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 0038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6127 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKL-COMETS-RIZZOTTI-H     05-05 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-COMETS-RIZZOTTI-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
Whenever someone hollers ``coach'' during the Comets' training
camp, Van Chancellor or one of his assistants is likely to turn an
ear in the direction of the caller.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jennifer Rizzotti might do so as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no. Not now. I'm a player now, not a coach,'' Rizzotti
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Now in her second season as a guard for the Comets, Rizzotti,
25, has just completed her first year as the women's basketball
coach at the University of Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   One might think the rigors of coaching at the NCAA Division I
level and being one of the youngest coaches in the college game
would tax a person's physical and emotional mettle enough to want
to take it easy during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   But for someone who has played in the now-defunct American
Basketball League and been part of the second NCAA team to go
undefeated and win a national title (Connecticut Huskies in 1995),
squelching the competitive fires can be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in the fact that Rizzotti comes from an athletic,
competitive family, and the reason she is back fighting for her
place among the three-time defending WNBA champions becomes
apparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``My love of the game, both playing and coaching, is too strong
now,'' she said. ``I feel like I'm young. I feel like I have a
passion to get out on the floor. The closer the season comes, I'm
itching to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I couldn't pass up the opportunity. Very few women get the
chance to play professional basketball. I've got to take that
chance while I have it. The coaching just falling in my lap was a
very fortunate thing. And I'm going to take that chance while I
have it, too. I'm young and have energy. I'd rather be busy doing
two things I love rather than not be busy at all.''
</P>
<P>
   After winning a WNBA championship ring with the Comets last
summer, Rizzotti didn't actively go in search of the coaching
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``The female athletic director at the university called me and
offered the job to me,'' Rizzotti said.
</P>
<P>
   So Rizzotti took her competitive nature to Hartford, grabbed the
reins of a young team and guided the Eagles to a 14-14 record.
</P>
<P>
   That might appear mediocre compared to the 36-1 mark and second
NCAA championship in five years won by UConn. But in recent years,
the women's basketball program at Hartford had struggled.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had an 8-19 record the year before I came. That's all I
know about,'' Rizzotti said. ``I didn't check into what it was
before. That didn't really matter to me.''
</P>
<P>
   There were times during the past season that Rizzotti wondered
when the Eagles would grasp her concepts and begin to turn the
program around.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-1 start served as inspiration. But when the Eagles
approached mid-December and the usual rash of tournaments, their
plight had worsened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went up to a tournament, we had a really bad week of
practice, and I felt like I was wanting too much from them right
away,'' Rizzotti said. ``I felt I was expecting them to make all
these changes overnight. And I was frustrated when I'd come back to
practice (the following day) and they hadn't made the changes I
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I told them in a pre-game speech (during the tournament)
that my expectations were too high, and I just wanted them to go
out there and have fun. It kind of (angered) them a little bit that
I'd said I had set my expectations a little too high. They went out
and played their best game of the season to that point. And it just
kind of grew from that. They learned from each experience.''
</P>
<P>
   But it pained Rizzotti to reach that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times I went to the office in the morning and
wondered what I was going to do,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rizzotti said she never second-guessed her decision to
accept the coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   The root of her frustrations, Rizzotti said, could be traced to
the team's youth. There were only two seniors on the roster, and
the Eagles' starting five included two freshmen, two sophomores and
a junior.
</P>
<P>
   They began to jell as a team in December, Rizzotti said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just got better and better. Some of the frustrations were
still there (later in the season),'' she said. ``We still had our
ups and downs. But when the season was over, I think the important
thing was they gained confidence, they did have pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how you build a program, with kids who want to get out
there and they believe in themselves. And that's what I think we
had.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
