<HEADER>
A6128 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SATELLITE-TV-NYT &LR;      05-05 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SATELLITE-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME WARNER-DISNEY FIGHT IS A BOON FOR SATELLITE TV
</HEADLINE>
  By JIM RUTENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dispute between Time Warner and the Walt Disney Co. that led
to ABC's being blocked from 3.5 million homes earlier this week is
proving to be a boon for the satellite television industry.
</P>
<P>
   About 25,000 Time Warner subscribers have asked for the coupons
that entitle them to receive free equipment from DirecTV, a unit of
the Hughes Electronics Corp., which is a division of General
Motors, and thousands more have subscribed to the Dish Network of
EchoStar Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Since the dispute began, DirecTV executives said, 20,000 Time
Warner subscribers in Houston and another 5,000 in New York and Los
Angeles have requested full rebate coupons, but it is unclear
exactly how many of them have bought the systems.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, EchoStar told retailers to start giving away its
Dish Network equipment to Time Warner customers in those cities and
Philadelphia if they agree to buy its service for one year.
Executives from the company were unable to say Thursday how many
people had responded, but they said it was in the thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Executives from both companies said they began planning to
capitalize on the dispute months ago after Disney, which owns ABC,
and Time Warner began to hit an impasse. The executives said they
saw the situation as a perfect national advertisement for their
services. Their marketing campaigns describe their services as
superior to the cable services and describe the cable companies as
arrogant and inattentive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an opportunity to say `Look, there is an alternative
and we're going to make it easier for you to switch to Dish
Network,''' said Charles Ergen, the chief executive of EchoStar.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at DirecTV said they were also making plans to step
into the fray, but their plans accelerated in February, when they
were approached by ABC on a joint agreement to give away dishes for
two weeks in Houston as a way to put pressure on Time Warner there.
The two companies are splitting the cost of the rebates, though
neither would disclose terms of their agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The DirecTV offer was revived in Houston and expanded to include
New York and Los Angeles on Wednesday, after Time Warner had
already agreed to return the ABC signal to its systems, at least
until a new July 15 negotiating deadline passes. The deal, which
includes a $99 rebate and free installation, is expected to stay in
place for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first priority was uninterrupted service for all of our
viewers,'' said Julie Hoover, an ABC spokeswoman. ``In light of the
recent threat, we thought it was important for viewers to have the
security of an alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner executives said they considered Disney's partnership
with DirecTV an act of bad faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, it is something that we think they should suspend as
a way of demonstrating good faith,'' said Mike Luftman, a Time
Warner Cable spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Time Warner began offering refunds and a free
one-month subscription to one of its premium movie services to the
customers who were affected.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Time Warner's chairman, Gerald M. Levin, called
for a cooling of the heated exchanges; ABC executives said that
Robert Iger, the president of Disney, spoke by telephone with Time
Warner's president, Richard Parsons, about resuming talks.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner executives said it was impossible to tell exactly
how much damage the satellite offers from DirecTV and EchoStar had
done to its bottom line. Neither satellite company can say how many
of the people who requested rebates actually installed the service
and disconnected their cable.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Gerbrandt, a media analyst for Paul Kagan Associates, said
each subscriber represented $4,000 to $6,000 of potential revenue
over the life of a contract.
</P>
<P>
   While the loss may hurt, Gerbrandt said, there are much bigger
things at stake in the negotiations _ like how much power Time
Warner is going to have after it is merged with America Online.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are big boys playing for large stakes,'' he said. ``It's
not about 25,000 subscribers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
