<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6130 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-CUBS-HNS &LR;      05-05 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CUBS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
CHICAGO _ There are some days when the manager of a big-league club
can simply walk the lineup card out to the home-plate umpire, take
a seat in the dugout and enjoy the game.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Astros manager Larry Dierker doesn't figure to have many of
those this season.
</P>
<P>
   Managing the 2000 Astros will offer little margin for error, and
Dierker had more than a few decisions to make Thursday in the
Astros' 6-2 victory over the Chicago Cubs at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   Starting pitcher Scott Elarton turned in six strong innings and
Dierker used three relievers to get through the final three frames
as the Astros avoided being swept in the three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   The solid performance by the pitching staff was supported by a
collection of clutch hits. Five of the Astros' six runs scored
after two were out, including the three that came on Jeff Bagwell's
game-breaking double in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   It was timely in more ways than one for Bagwell, who had only
five hits in his last 25 at-bats prior to Thursday's big hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was good to see,'' Dierker said. ``Baggy has been in a
little minislump, but he doesn't stay in one for long.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' slump has meant few save opportunities for closer
Billy Wagner, who finally picked up No. 4 Thursday. It was his
first since April 12 against the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Although Dierker tries to guard against using Wagner for more
than one inning, the fourth-year manager wisely called on his
hard-throwing lefthander to bail Jose Cabrera out of a two-out,
bases-loaded jam in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner retired the Cubs in order in the ninth to seal the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't rest easy until we got the final out,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker had another tough call to make earlier, after Elarton
had completed his sixth inning having thrown just 73 pitches.
Understandably, Elarton wanted to remain in the game, but Dierker
had other plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elarton was outstanding,'' Dierker said. ``I practically had
to hold him down to keep him from going back out there. His pitch
count wasn't high, but (pitching coach) Vern (Ruhle) and I wanted
to lock in a good performance, get him a win and get his confidence
going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to leave him out there and have him give up a
cheap home run or two and maybe not get the win.''
</P>
<P>
   For that theory to pay dividends, the bullpen had to do its job,
which has been anything but a given this season. However, the
relievers have been more consistent of late.
</P>
<P>
   Righthanders Mike Maddux and Cabrera weren't airtight Thursday,
combining to allow five hits and a run in 1 innings. But they
didn't surrender the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a tough day to pitch,'' Bagwell said. ``To hold the
Cubs to just two runs on a day when pop-ups were going out of the
park, our pitchers did a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Elarton and Cubs starter Ismael Valdes, a couple of pitchers
battling back from injuries, matched up pretty evenly through the
first four innings, but that was as long as Valdes could keep it
up.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, making his first start of the season, turned the game
over to the Cubs' bullpen after just 4 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had great, quality pitches,'' Valdes said. ``Overall, I
think it was a great outing for me. It's good to not feel pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Elarton allowed just four hits and a run in the best of his
three starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really relaxed out there,'' Elarton said. ``In the first
two starts, I probably had a little doubt in my mind. But I felt
really good out there. I felt like I had better velocity, and my
curveball was better. The sixth inning was my best as far as
command. I wanted to go back out there in the worst way, but I'm
not one to argue.''
</P>
<P>
   The starting right fielders provided the early scoring, with the
Astros' Richard Hidalgo hitting a solo homer in the second and
Chicago's Sammy Sosa matching him in the bottom of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Girardi's seventh-inning homer off Maddux accounted for the
Cubs' other run.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo's home run was his second in as many days and his eighth
of the season, tying Bagwell for the club lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just looking for a pitch to drive,'' Hidalgo said. ``I
don't really consider myself a home-run hitter. I'm just trying to
make good contact and hit line drives. I'm seeing the ball pretty
well right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell broke the game open in the fifth when Cubs manager Don
Baylor resorted to an interesting bit of strategy, lifting the
righthanded Valdes, against whom Bagwell is 3-for-22, in favor of
lefthander Mark Guthrie with the bases loaded and two outs.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell foiled the move with a three-run double to put the
Astros on top for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to throw a sinker away, and I made a bad
pitch,'' Guthrie said. ``It wasn't the pitch. It was the execution
of the pitch that was bad. It was a horrible pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor's bullpen was populated mostly by lefthanders, and he
said he was saving righthanders Kyle Farnsworth and Rick Aguilera
for later in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not many people bring in a lefty to face me unless it's their
closer,'' said Bagwell, whose career average is about 30 points
higher against lefthanders. ``But (former Dodgers manager) Tommy
Lasorda used to bring him (Guthrie) in to face me because Guthrie's
got that good forkball, and I've been known to swing at pitches in
the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to come through in that situation because I've had
some opportunities lately to drive in some runs and I haven't been
doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros padded their lead with Tim Bogar's sacrifice fly in
the eighth and an RBI double by Ken Caminiti in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
