<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOLDSTEIN-SENTENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APOLOGY FOR SUBWAY KILLING, THEN THE MAXIMUM SENTENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Andrew Goldstein, the schizophrenic man convicted of
pushing a young woman to her death in front of a speeding subway
train, stood in a Manhattan courtroom on Thursday, blamed a
``psychotic incident'' for the attack and apologized to the
victim's parents for the nightmare he created. He was then
sentenced to 25 years to life in prison for the murder, the maximum
possible sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein made his brief statement to the family of the victim,
Kendra Webdale, shortly after her mother, Patricia Webdale, said in
a tearful speech that Goldstein had learned over the years that
because he was mentally ill, he was never held accountable for 13
past assaults on doctors, medical staff and strangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my contention,'' Webdale, speaking before Justice Carol
Berkman of State Supreme Court in Manhattan, said, ``that if Andrew
Goldstein had been held responsible many incidents ago, there would
not have been 13 assaults and one homicide committed by him. His
ongoing aggression was tolerated and deemed acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   During the sentencing hearing, Berkman and the prosecutor joined
Webdale in saying that the attack stemmed from the state mental
health system's failure to punish Goldstein for past assaults.
</P>
<P>
   That view stood in sharp contrast to the long-running contention
of defense lawyers and mental health advocates that Goldstein's
attack on Webdale in January 1999 happened because Goldstein had
received shoddy care from the state's underfinanced mental health
system. Goldstein's attack on Kendra Webdale focused intense
scrutiny on the state mental health system, which had repeatedly
sent him back to the streets despite his history of violence and
mental illness and his requests for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein admitted pushing Webdale to her death on Jan. 3, 1999,
but blamed his schizophrenia for his actions and pleaded not guilty
by reason of insanity. After his first trial ended in a hung jury
last November, a second jury convicted him of second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement to the court on Thursday, Goldstein seemingly
dismissed the symbolism and political debate surrounding his case.
He said that it did not matter to him whether he served his
sentence in a mental institution or state prison, which is where he
will be sent because of his guilty conviction. ``Granted, you kill
somebody, you deserve punishment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But moments later, Goldstein, 30, seemed to attribute the
killing to his failure to take his anti-psychotic medication. If he
had taken it the morning he killed Webdale, ``this thing would have
never happened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor in the case, William Greenbaum, argued that the
meaning of the case had been twisted by defense lawyers. ``What a
slur on the mentally ill to have this individual made a poster
child for mental illness,'' Greenbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenbaum repeated his argument that Goldstein was a
manipulative, high-functioning schizophrenic who used his mental
illness as a crutch.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein's lawyer, Kevin Canfield, scoffed at that account. He
said Goldstein was clinically insane and asked Berkman to sentence
him to the minimum sentence of 15 years to life in prison. ``He's
not a monster, judge, he never was,'' Canfield said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
