<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For FRIDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, May 5.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-ASSESS (Kinshasa, Congo) _ A news analysis on U.N.
efforts to bring peace to Africa as the mission in Sierra Leone
turns into a battle against rebels at the same time Security
Council members are in Congo trying to set up a peacekeeping
operation. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   SAO-PAULO-MAYOR (SAO PAULO, Brazil) _ The drama that has been
unfolding here in recent weeks has all the ingredients of the
convoluted soap operas that Brazilians love to watch: a power
struggle, betrayal, sexual intrigue, jealousy, revenge. But most of
all it is money, lots and lots of money, that has brought about the
downfall of Celso Pitta, mayor of Sao Paulo, South America's
largest and richest city. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OCONNOR-CATHOLICS (Undated) _ The impact of Cardinal John
O'Conner's death on Catholicism in America. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TB-SCREENING (Undated) _ The National Academy of Medicine,
in a wide-ranging report, recommends that prospective immigrants
from countries with lots of tuberculosis get a skin test for latent
TB before they enter the country. Currently those immigrants must
only get a chest X-ray to check for active cases and get treated
before they come. The academy says that although the number of TB
cases is dropping in this country, action is needed because a
global epidemic remains a potential source of new infections and
the country has entered a ``dangerous'' phase in trying to keep the
disease at bay. The scientists also recommend that inmates be given
skin tests and that this country give money to countries with lots
of TB to help them get rid of it. By Kenneth Chang.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GORE-STRATEGY (Washington) _ Analysis: It has become the daily
call-and-response of the presidential contest. Vice President Al
Gore brands Gov. George W. Bush as, take your pick: reckless,
irresponsible, profligate or arrogant. And Bush calmly replies that
the vice president is like an addict when it comes to distorting
the truth. If this acidic minuet seems vaguely familiar, it is.
Gore's aggressive strategy worked just fine in the primaries, but
he is now engaged in a very different race against a very different
opponent, and the question is, can it work again? By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-DAUGHTERS (Austin, Texas) _ The Bush family has been
remarkably successful in protecting the privacy of his two
18-year-old daughters, so much so that while Bush could become the
next president and while his extended family is beginning to look
an awful lot like a political dynasty, his two daughters are almost
invisible, their faces unknown to 99.9 percent of voters outside
Texas. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DEECEE-TAX-PROTEST _ Attitude, the gritty urban ingredient that
seemed to go missing with the fall of Mayor Marion Barry, is
threatening to return to the capital city's profile in the form of
a rebellious new license plate motto decrying the city's state of
``Taxation Without Representation.'' A proposal to proclaim that on
District of Columbia license tags plates has been unanimously
co-sponsored by the city council to protest the fact that city
residents pay $2 billion in annual federal taxes yet have failed in
repeated attempts to win voting rights in Congress. By Francis X.
Clines.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-AIR-BAGS _ The Transportation Department is scheduled to
announce new standards for automobile air bags Friday, and people
involved in the decision say that the government will set the rules
to allow less-powerful bags, to reduce the risk to children and
small-statured adults, possibly at the expense of large men who
drive unbelted. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LOVE-VIRUS (Undated) _ A rogue software program, borne by an
e-mail message proclaiming ``I love you,'' wreaked havoc around the
world, jamming and crashing e-mail systems and destroying data on
hundreds of thousands of computers. To defend themselves, thousands
of corporations unhooked their computer systems from the Internet
and began the laborious process of purging the program internally.
By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   UNILEVER-STRATEGY (London) _ This week, Niall FitzGerald and
Anthony Burgmans, FitzGerald's co-chairman at the Anglo-Dutch
Unilever, offered $18.4 billion for Bestfoods, of Englewood
Cliffs., N.J., which owns top-selling brands like Knorr soups,
Hellman's mayonnaise and Skippy peanut butter. Bestfoods said no.
But FitzGerald hopes that a no can turn to yes. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-TECH-JOBS (Paris) _ Eric Perbos-Brinck gave up a
promising management career last year at Promodes, the big French
retailer, to start an Internet company called Bravonestor.com. He
began in November with just two people, but already has 10
employees, with plans to hire five more in the next few weeks. To
fill the jobs, Perbos-Brinck, 31, casts his net wide. One of his
programmers is Moroccan. The designer of search engines is
Senegalese. Perbos-Brinck's polyglot staff would not draw a second
glance in the United States, where the technology industry's
ravenous demand for skilled workers has created a multinational,
multicultural work force that includes many foreign nationals. But
in Europe, his effort to find qualified help has collided with one
of Europe's most divisive issues: immigration. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
