   &UR; WEEKEND (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ACTING-COMPANY (Undated) _ It sounds like the setup for some
bizarre avant-garde reality show: take a dozen or so actors, put
them on a bus for five months and see what happens. This isn't
``The Real World,'' however. This is theater, Acting Company style.
For 27 years the company has followed a deceptively simple
strategy: find good young actors, put them in good old plays and
take them to small towns from coast to coast. For those involved,
it is a mission that requires not just a deep love for the stage
but a boundless appreciation for fast-food, sleep deprivation and
hotels where the pillows haven't seen a mint since Eisenhower. By
Jesse McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   CONTEMPORARY-INDIANS (New York) _ ``Reservation X: The Power of
Place'' at the National Museum of the America Indian in Lower
Manhattan, is a lean, clean contemporary take on the tangled
subject of what it means to be Indian in America today. By Holland
Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   ALBERTINA-DRAWINGS (New York) _ Few art acquisitors of the 18th
_ or any _ century had the drive, determination and buying power of
Albert, duke of Saxe-Teschen (1738-1822), for whom the Albertina in
Vienna is named. A small but choice sampling of holdings from the
Albertina can be seen at the Frick Collection, in a show organized
by the Art Gallery of Ontario and the Albertina in conjunction with
the Frick. By Grace Glueck.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-YORKER-ANNIVERSARY (New York) _ The New Yorker's 75th
anniversary festival is this weekend, and all the proper nouns will
be there: Julian Barnes, Edna O'Brien, Richard Ford, Alice Munro,
Cynthia Ozick, Stephen King, Frances FitzGerald, Calvin Trillin,
Joe Klein, John Lahr, V.S. Naipaul, Roger Angell, Roz Chast. But
what about the most prolific writer in New Yorker history, the
author of countless Talk of the Town pieces, the loyal, royal
``we''? Why wasn't ``we'' invited? By Sarah Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   NY-GALLERIES (New York) _ Maybe credit should go to the revived
art market, the arrival of spring or some kind of harmonic
convergence, but Madison Avenue from 69th to 79th Street is rife
with art. It's hard to recall a time in the last 20 years when so
many galleries on, or just off, the avenue offered such a diverse
range of high-quality viewing opportunities. On a recent Monday _ a
six-day week frequently prevails in these parts _ one resident art
dealer cheerfully described the neighborhood as ``the Chelsea you
can get to.'' By Roberta Smith.
