<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENNEY-RETIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
J.C. PENNEY CHIEF TO STEP DOWN EARLIER THAN ANTICIPATED
</HEADLINE>
  By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly a year after James E. Oesterreicher vowed to turn around
the troubled department store giant J &UR; . &LR; C. Penney, he announced
Thursday that he would retire as chairman and chief executive
earlier than expected and without fulfilling his promise.
</P>
<P>
   Oesterreicher, 58, who has been with the company since 1964,
said Penney had started a search for his replacement and that he
would stay until a successor was named.
</P>
<P>
   He said that his decision to step down almost a year before
Penney required was in part based on the fact that several
high-profile chief executive searches are under way in the retail
sector _ including one for a chief executive to replace Arthur
Martinez at Sears, Roebuck. In this brutally competitive
environment, he said he did not want Penney to miss out on top
talent.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Oesterreicher has also felt pressure from investors
to move along because Penney's has continued to post dismal sales,
as customers desert its stores for more hip and better-priced
competitors like Kohl's and Old Navy. Since he took the helm in
1997, Penney's stock has lost 66 percent of its market value. Last
May at the annual shareholders' meeting, he predicted that sales
would pick up; they have not. Sales at stores open at least a year
have fallen for all but six of the last 23 months, according to
Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street cheered the news of his departure. The stock rose 8
percent, up $1.5625, to $17.4375, on a day when the Dow Jones
industrials fell 67.64 points. ``The company has clearly
underperformed expectations in recent years and an infusion of new
blood is likely to be regarded as positive by the Street,'' said
George Strachan, a Goldman, Sachs analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also expressed optimism because they said
Oesterreicher's eventual retirement was one of a series of changes
that indicated the company was serious about righting its course.
Since last year, Oesterreicher has made many moves to bolster the
share price and to refocus Penney on its core retailing business.
Last fall, he sold Penney's credit card business, and just recently
the company announced it would consider selling its direct
marketing arm as well. A year ago, the company created a tracking
stock for its fast-growing Eckerd's Drug Store division.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Oesterreicher broke with Penney's tradition of
promoting people to top jobs solely from within. He hired Vanessa
Castagna, executive vice president for merchandising and chief
operating officer, from Wal-Mart Stores six months ago. Castagna is
credited with having helped Wal-Mart turn its women's apparel
business from a poorly assorted afterthought to a powerful market
force. Although new in her job, Castagna is thought to be among the
contenders to replace Oesterreicher.
</P>
<P>
   ``The announcement today is continued evidence of change at
Penney, and therefore is being seen from a positive standpoint,''
said Jeff Feiner, a Lehman Brothers analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Penney said it would consider candidates from outside the
company as well as within. ``This would be the first time that our
company has considered external candidates,'' Oesterreicher said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
