<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE COULD BE OUT FOR SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Devon White's diving attempt has possibly cost the
Dodgers center fielder the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   An MRI revealed White has a partial tear of the rotator cuff in
his left shoulder. He's slated to be placed on the 15-day disabled
list today. The plan is for White to rehab the shoulder and try to
become healthy so he can play the bulk of the season. But if
rehabilitating the shoulder doesn't work, surgery is the next
option.
</P>
<P>
   And surgery could knock White out for a minimum of a few months,
and potentially, the remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Also, shortstop Kevin Elster had a cortisone shot in his pulled
right groin. He also is scheduled to go on the 15-day disabled list
before today's series opener against the Houston Astros. Alex Cora
is expected to be activated and become the starting shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hollandsworth, whom the Dodgers elected not to trade for
this very reason when teams inquired about him during spring
training, moves into the starting center-field spot and will bat
leadoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Alex comes up, I'm going to play him,'' Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson said. ``We couldn't (survive these injuries) last
year. The way things were, I couldn't explain it last year but now
I can. We have better depth.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone did not make himself
available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a two-pronged type of depth. Not only do Hollandsworth
and Cora fit in to replace the injured White and Elster on the
field, but they won't force Johnson to restructure the lineup.
Hollandsworth will bat first and Cora will hit eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Osuna, who's pitched well during his rehab stints in
Single-A San Bernardino and Triple-A Albuquerque, is expected to
join the Dodgers this weekend to take up the other roster spot. The
right-hander is coming off elbow surgery but has thrown in the
mid-90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I'll say is I want to see where Osuna's at,'' Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   White, in the second year of a three-year, 12.4 million
contract, hurt the shoulder in the ninth inning Tuesday when he
dived for a ball hit by Atlanta's Brian Jordan. Johnson said he
thought a contributing factor to White diving was his desire to
show Los Angeles fans he's willing to do so. He was roundly booed
last season for not doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Though White isn't the prototypical leadoff hitter, he was off
to a solid start. He walked four times in 87 plate appearances, and
his .326 on-base percentage was 10th among National League leadoff
hitters. But Johnson likes White's power and defense. White has
three homers and nine RBI, he's hitting .289 and playing a solid
center field.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth went 3 for 4 with a homer and three runs scored in
White's place Wednesday, and the Dodgers are hoping he brings
enthusiasm and energy to the top of the lineup, which is averaging
5.8 runs per game. Hollandsworth, a former NL Rookie of the Year,
has been slowed by injuries the past three seasons. He's hitting
.260 and has a .327 on-base percentage. He had his first two steals
of the season Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It will be White's fourth stint on the disabled list, and first
since he pulled his left calf muscle in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to try and rehab (the shoulder),'' Johnson said.
``If that doesn't work, they'll cut on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Elster was injured while running to first on a sixth-inning
groundout Wednesday. He provided the offense Johnson wanted at the
bottom of the order. His six homers 17 RBI and 15 runs scored
topped all No. 8 hitters in the NL, and there's little chance Cora
can match that.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was Elster's offense that won him the starting
shortstop job ahead of Cora in spring training. But Elster also had
the knack for extending innings so pitchers didn't lead off the
following inning. He has 14 walks and a .378 on-base percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Cora was batting .394 with Albuquerque, but he didn't have any
homers. In two stints with the Dodgers in 1998 and 1999, the
24-year-old Cora hit .143 with three RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``My leg, I'm kind of like dragging it around,'' Elster said.
``I'm a little frustrated, but I'm not going to sit and dwell on
it. The way my career has been, at least it's not a broken wrist.''
</P>
<P>
   The hope in the organization is that Osuna or right-hander Alan
Mills pitch well enough to increase their trade value before
right-hander Gregg Olson comes off the disabled list, a club
official said. Olson, on the disabled list with a pinched nerve in
his right forearm, is supposed to begin a rehab assignment today in
San Bernardino. He could be ready to come off the disabled list in
a week.
</P>
<P>
   DODGERS vs. HOUSTON
</P>
<P>
   Time: 7:10 p.m., at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: Fox Sports Net 2; 1150-AM, KWKW-AM (1330 Spanish).
</P>
<P>
   Matchup: With Thursday's day off, the Dodgers staggered their
rotation to make sure right-hander Kevin Brown (2-1, 2.88 ERA)
remains on four days rest whenever possible. So he gets the start
in the opener of a three-game series against Houston righty Shane
Reynolds (4-0, 3.35). Since returning from his broken pinkie,
Brown's allowed one earned run in seven innings in both of his
starts. Last season Brown was 2-0 with a 1.06 ERA in two games
against Houston, and he's 3-2 with a 1.50 ERA in seven career
starts against the Astros. Reynolds beat the Dodgers 10-3 April 19
at Dodger Stadium. He allowed one run on four hits in six innings.
Saturday - Dodgers RH Darren Dreifort (1-1, 2.67) vs. Astros RH
Octavio Dotel (1-2, 4.20); Sunday - Dodgers RH Eric Gagne (0-2,
3.22) vs. Astros RH Jose Lima (1-5, 9.59).
</P>
<P>
   -Brian Dohn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
