<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIBBY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIBBY'S CONTRACT TALKS STALLED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Contract talks between USC and basketball coach
Henry Bibby have stalled, and there are serious doubts whether he
will sign an extension before the start of next season.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby's current five-year contract expires after the 2001-2002
season, but he has sought a new deal that would offer more
security. During the past season, Bibby and USC verbally agreed on
a three-year extension, with salary details to be worked out later.
</P>
<P>
   But the negotiations have broken down in the past month, making
it less likely Bibby will sign a new deal this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said I would get a new deal, but I can't really comment
on it,'' Bibby said. ``I have no comment on it. But their word has
been good.''
</P>
<P>
   USC associate athletic Daryl Gross, who has been negotiating an
extension with Bibby, remained optimistic that a new contract could
be signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say we feel Henry's doing a great job building this
program up,'' Gross said. ``We saw where we could go before the
injuries last season. With that in mind, we expect Henry to be at
USC for many years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   According to sources, Bibby is expected to earn about $375,000
in base salary next season. He would like a new deal to place him
in the upper echelon of Pacific-10 coaches, which would mean a
salary of at least $650,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby has also worried that without a contract extension,
recruiting would be harmed.
</P>
<P>
   But there was virtually no negotiating between the two sides in
April, when talks began to deteriorate, and neither side is sure
when talks could resume.
</P>
<P>
   This week, there have been no negotiations. The last time the
pair discussed contract matters was during the Final Four in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Even if negotiations begin again, there has also been some
question whether Bibby would actually sign a new contract. He might
wait to see if his stock goes up if the Trojans have a successful
season next year.
</P>
<P>
   USC returns all five starters from last year's 16-14 team, and
seven of their top eight players. USC also signed prep All-American
shooting guard Desmon Farmer of Flint, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Trojans signed point guard Robert Hutchinson
and shooting guard Gennaro Busterna, and 7-foot-3 freshman center
Luke Minor will be eligible after redshirting last season.
</P>
<P>
   It's conceivable USC could be chosen to finish among the top
three teams in the Pac-10 next year. A top-three finish would raise
Bibby's value considerably, and it would hardly shock anyone if his
name came up regarding another position.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, Bibby discussed the then-vacant Memphis opening
with school officials.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, there has also been speculation that he might be
a candidate for the Clippers job if the team fires Jim Todd. Bibby
was seen at the Clippers' final home game with team owner Donald
Sterling, but it is not believed the coaching position was
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Sam Williams, USC's director of basketball operations,
and a former NBA player with the Golden State Warriors and
Philadelphia 76ers, has resigned to pursue his degree at Arizona
State.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that will probably raise some eyebrows, Williams will
be replaced by Tim Farmer, the older brother of incoming freshman
guard Desmon Farmer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 0146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
