<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENA: GALAXY DOESN'T NEED ANY HELP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ Any time Galaxy defender Danny Pena talks, it's good
to have a tape recorder rolling, especially when he needs to clear
his head.
</P>
<P>
   With the Galaxy (5-0-2) playing host to Major League Soccer's
only other unbeaten team, Kansas City (6-0-1) on Saturday at the
Rose Bowl, Pena was asked about the lingering rumors that Mexican
standout Luis Hernandez will be allocated to the Galaxy for as many
as two quality players.
</P>
<P>
   Before the question was finished, the frustration on Pena's face
suggested what was coming next: Why does the Galaxy need to change
anything?
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need anybody right now, we're happy with where we
are,'' Pena said. ``How can you ask a team that is undefeated to
make any changes? If were below .500, we could use a change but for
the league to tell us we need to give up two of our starting
players to get a player whose only going to be here a third of the
season is ludicrous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating, I have no respect for the way this league is
run and the people on top of it. What they're trying to do is
unacceptable. All we can do is battle under the circumstances
because at the end of the day, the league is going to do what they
want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   MLS executive vice president Ivan Gazidis has issued a weekly
``no comment,'' response during MLS conference calls concerning
negotiations with Mexican players. With the speculation that
Hernandez is coming to the MLS from several publications, Gazidis
felt compelled to comment this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name Luis Hernandez has never been mentioned by me,'' he
said. ``A lot of comments, rumors are about him and Tigres, but
that's not coming from the league office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at a number of different options for a Mexican
player in L.A. Any deal for Mexican players is difficult to do
financially. It involves a lot of different pieces and some
scheduling problems.''
</P>
<P>
   -Wizards goalkeeper Tony Meola was a featured player on the 1994
U.S. World Cup team. Despite many soccer experts having high
expectations for him after the '94 tournament, Meola left soccer
for a tryout with the New York Jets as a placekicker.
</P>
<P>
   Meola also tried acting and other things before returning to
soccer to join the New York/New Jersey MetroStars in 1996, MLS'
inaugural season. Meola struggled, and his reputation diminished.
He was traded to the Wizards last season and struggled again. But
now he's having his best MLS season, allowing a league-low four
goals.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, U.S. national team coach Bruce Arena has
noticed Meola's improved play, recalling him to the national team
on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid, an assistant on the U.S. team in '94,
said Meola is playing as well as he ever has.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the ups and downs that Tony has had, with the
changing of the careers and the return to soccer, what it has done
is made Tony stronger,'' said Schmid. ``It's made him more
dedicated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 0203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0036 </DOCNO>
