<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-HADDOCK-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERTA CLINGS TO INDY HOPES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM HADDOCK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Racing in the Indianapolis 500 might be a tailpipe dream for
Bryan Herta, but the Valencia driver says returning to the
Brickyard is not out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   Herta, who finished his two-race deal with Derrick Walker with a
20th-place showing in the CART Fed/Ex Series Rio 200 on Sunday in
Brazil, said it's possible he will continue his relationship with
Walker Racing in the Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   Walker has two entries for the 500, an Indy Racing League event,
and only one driver, Sarah Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has no plans for the second car,'' Herta said. ``That's
mainly because there is no sponsor for it. But we've discussed it.
It's something I'd like to do, but there's less than two weeks to
prepare for it, so the chances are not good.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker also said the possibility exists that Herta could run his
second car in the Indy 500, but it's not likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had some drivers and some sponsors interested,'' Walker
said. ``I am keeping the possibility open. The option is still
there and we have definitely talked about it. He's told me he'd
like to do it. The easy part is finding a driver. The hard part is
getting the rest of your ducks in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   Herta, who finished fifth at Long Beach for Walker Racing, was
subbing in for Shinji Nakano, who injured his head during a
practice session in March. Now that his deal is up with Walker,
Herta, who was signed to drive for CART team owner Gerald Forsythe
at the start of the season, is back in limbo as he waits for CART
officials to decide the fate of Forsythe's request for a third
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Forsythe already has two CART teams, with Alex Tagliani and
Patrick Carpintier as drivers for the Player's/Forsythe Racing
team.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Herta said he plans to go to Motegi, Japan, for
the Firestone Firehawk 500 on May 13, but not as a driver. He will
serve as a representative for Honda.
</P>
<P>
   But if Nakano is unable to drive in Japan, Herta is ready to sub
in for the Japanese-born driver again. Nakano underwent medical
tests this week to gain clearance to compete. CART has also allowed
an extra practice session for Nakano to insure that he is medically
and physically ready to return. Walker said if Nakano suffers any
setbacks, Herta will be the replacement driver in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Runaway win: Greg Pursley of Sun Valley practically ran away
with the NASCAR Featherlite Southwest Series Home Depot 100 at
Irwindale Speedway on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Pursley, a Canyon High graduate, started from the eighth spot
but quickly moved up to take the lead on lap 16. Aside from a late
charge by Granada Hills native M.K. Kanke, Pursley had few
challengers en route to his first win of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt my car was really good, but Kanke was real strong,
too,'' Pursley said. ``Kanke was trying to catch me underneath, and
he kept trying, but he couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pursley said because Kanke continued to try to pass him low on
the race track, Kanke was wearing down his tires more quickly.
Pursley was able to conserve his tires and maintain the lead, which
was the winning combination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Southwest tour has the best drivers around,'' Pursley
said. ``For me to be able to beat them is awesome. The top 10
drivers on the series - anybody can win. And you could have thrown
a blanket over the top three drivers on Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   The Southwest Series continues at Tucson Raceway Park on
Saturday. Pursley, who hasn't competed in Tucson since winter heats
there in 1996, said he remembers the track being similar to the
half-mile oval at Irwindale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty close to Irwindale, just smaller,'' said Pursley,
who tested his Crown Motorsports Chevy Monte Carlo at Tucson in
January.
</P>
<P>
   In other action at Irwindale Speedway, Brandon Miller of Rancho
Santa Fe became the fifth different winner in as many events in the
NASCAR Super Late Model division. Vince Little of Clovis won the
Ultra Wheel Spec Trucks feature.
</P>
<P>
   Benson fined: NASCAR officials penalized Johnny Benson more than
$10,000 Tuesday for rules violations in the NASCAR Winston West
race at California Speedway on Saturday. Benson's car had an
illegal restrictor plate on the manifold.
</P>
<P>
   Benson was fined $10,440 and lost his 108 Winston West points he
scored in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Sedgwick of Acton finished 15th in the Winston West race.
Jerry Cain of Canyon Country was 26th.
</P>
<P>
   Sedgwick is also 13th in points after four series races. Cain is
19th. The next race on the Winston West series will be the Salinas
250 at Laguna Seca Raceway on May 21.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia bound: NASCAR Busch Grand National Series driver Ron
Hornaday Jr. finished 19th in the Auto Club 300 on Saturday at
California Speedway in Fontana. So, it's no wonder the Palmdale
driver of the NAPA Auto Parts Chevy Monte Carlo can't wait to get
to Virginia for tonight's Hardee's 250 at Richmond International
Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   Hornaday has had success in Richmond over the last few years. He
won a pole on the NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series in 1997 and
finished second in a Truck race there in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   He even has fond memories of his only Winston Cup experience at
Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran the Winston Cup race at Richmond in the fall last year
and had a blast,'' he said. ``I got spun by one of my Truck buddies
on lap 242 and tore up my car a little, but I was still able to
keep up with the leaders as far as lap times were with a torn up
car. I think I just have a natural feel for this track.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with his 19th at Fontana, Hornaday leads the Busch rookie
points standings and is fifth overall in the series standings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
