<HEADLINE>
BODINE HASN'T LOST DESIRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nobody would blame Geoffrey Bodine if he never climbed into a
race car again.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody except for Bodine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have a burning desire to get behind the steering wheel
and go out there and compete,'' said Bodine, who resumes his NASCAR
Winston Cup career at this weekend's Pontiac Excitement 400 in
Richmond, Va. His comeback comes nearly three months after being
involved in a horrific crash at Daytona in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be stronger now then it was before. I love a
challenge. And this is one of the biggest challenges of my life to
deal with this accident and the injuries. I'm very anxious to get
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodine escaped serious injury after being involved in a 10-truck
crash during the Daytona 250 Craftsman Truck series race. He
suffered broken bones in his right cheek, wrist, elbow and big tow.
His truck rolled over 11 times and flipped three down the front
straightaway before coming apart and bursting into flames.
</P>
<P>
   The driver's compartment and roll cage remained intact. The
crash, which delayed the conclusion of the first truck race at
Daytona for more then two hours, was started when three trucks
collided into each other in the tri-oval, setting off a chain
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bodine is ready to return, his outlook on racing, and
life has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get back and do the best I've ever done,'' Bodine
said. ``I want to come back 110 percent. All those things are still
important, but through this accident, I've learned they are not the
most important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm not going to be a racer 10 more years. That's not
the end of the world. This wreck has put a lot of things in
perspective. Cars, houses, possessions don't mean anything when you
are laying in bed and can't move. When you are in the hospital and
don't know if you are going to survive, those things become
unimportant. Your health becomes very important, your family. Those
things are more important. That's what this experience has done for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Bodine has had to comeback from a
major crash.
</P>
<P>
   He was nearly killed during a single-car incident at Watkins
Glen, N.Y. in the late 1980s and responded by taking the pole at
Michigan the next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``That day, I really thought I was going to kill myself,''
Bodine said. ``I had a few seconds to think about that. I didn't
kill myself. I got hurt and I survived. The following week we went
to Michigan. I had to tell myself that day, 'Depending what you do
today, is going to tell yourself that you have it, that you still
have your nerve and be able to continue driving.'
</P>
<P>
   ``This coming off a serious crash at Watkins Glen thinking I was
going to kill myself. Well, I went out and got the pole (at
Michigan). I proved to myself that I still had the nerve. I proved
that going through a bad accident didn't slow me down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel that even though this accident(at Daytona) was
much more severe, I never had that feeling that I was going to get
hurt, or killed. I can see it, and how close I came to (being
dead). So when I get behind the wheel, I don't think I'm going to
have any problems going out there and going fast.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bodine is also not expecting any help from his Winston Cup
competitors when he rolls out his Chevrolet Monte Carlo on to the
Richmond three-quarter mile oval this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone's going to cut me any slack,'' Bodine
said. ``They never have. I don't expect them to just because I was
in that horrific wreck in Daytona and haven't been racing for a few
months. And I'm not going to ask them to. I don't want them to. . .
. If I feel there's any problem out there, I'll get someone else to
drive. But I don't expect that -- especially after (testing at
Richmond two weeks ago).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
