<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHRA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIXON EYES CHAMPIONSHIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ask most National Hot Rod Association enthusiasts before the
season who might win the Top Fuel championship, and you would get
the list of usual suspects - Joe Amato, Gary Scelzi and defending
champion Tony Schumacher.
</P>
<P>
   You can add Larry Dixon's name to that list.
</P>
<P>
   The 1995 NHRA Rookie of the Year, who has struggled with
consistency since, has won the past two national events and is
second in points through six of 23 races. Dixon will get attempt to
add to that streak at this weekend's Southern Nationals near
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have won poles, won Indy (the U.S. Nationals), and set
national records,'' said Dixon, who won last weekend's Moto1.Net
Nationals near Richmond, Va. after defeating rival Kenny Bernstein
in the final. ``The one thing I haven't done is win the Winston
Championship and I would love to do that for Snake (NHRA legend Don
Prudhomme).''
</P>
<P>
   And Dixon, who has won three of the past eight national events
dating back to last season, appears to have a legitimate shot in
2000. New crew chief Dick LaHaie, who tuned Scott Kalitta to
back-to-back titles in the mid-1990s, is a big reason for his
sudden turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep thanking Dick LaHaie, but you don't know how important
he is and how much of a great job all the crew guys (have done),''
Dixon said. ``LaHaie is everything to this team. He is a very sharp
guy and if I am lucky I will end my career with him as my crew
chief. I haven't been in a car this strong since 1995 (his rookie
of the year season).''
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with John Force?
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, if you judge the nine-time Funny Car champion by his
performance at last weekend's Moto1.Net Nationals.
</P>
<P>
   The Bell Gardens won for the 83rd time in his career and had the
quickest run of the season with a 4.823-second pass during
qualifying. It's quickest run since the NHRA adopted rules limiting
the nitromethane fuel mixture to 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a long way from being dead and the season's a long way
from being over,'' said Force, who moved within 69 points of
first-place Jerry Toliver after winning a tire-smoking battle over
Ron Capps on Sunday. ``We may not dominate like we did last year,
but we're not going to just roll over the first time somebody
challenges us, either. This team has a lot of pride.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory moved Force to within two victories of Bob Glidden's
career record of 85 wins.
</P>
<P>
   -Is anybody going to stop Jeg Coughlin Jr.?
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't appear so after the three-year Pro Stock driver won
for the fifth time in six nationals events last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin, who moved 211 points ahead of second-place Warren
Johnson, is the first driver to win five of the first six national
events since the late Lee Shepherd pulled the trick in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you're held up to guys like Lee Shepherd you know
that's about as good as it gets,'' said Coughlin, who finished a
career-best second in points last season. ``Hopefully, we can win
championships like (Shepherd) did.''
</P>
<P>
   -Scotty Cannon, who is in his second season in Funny Car, is on
the verge of putting together a second-car for his Oakley-sponsored
operation. The second car will be piloted by Scotty Cannon Jr. and
is expected to debut in early July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
