<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 05:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6195 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-`BOSS'-GRAY-DAVIS-CA-     05-05 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`BOSS'-GRAY-DAVIS-CA-ECONOMIST-425&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOV. GRAY DAVIS: CALIFORNIA'S MILD-MANNERED MEGLOMANIAC  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: California Editors...NOTE 100-word trim at 425; 1,075
uncut)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 1,075-word (untrimmed) material from
The New York Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The
Economist. Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special
arrangement. For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or
Debra Weydert at 732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   If you are looking for a demonstration of raw political power,
forget about the elder Daley's Chicago, Tammany Hall or any of
those strange shenanigans they get up to in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, consider Gray Davis's California.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom might say that party machines are a thing of
the past. But on the face of things, the mild-mannered governor has
amassed the sort of political clout that his more brutal
predecessors only dreamed about.
</P>
<P>
   The intriguing question is why he uses it so sparingly. Davis
won election in 1998 by a stunning 20 percentage points. He will
probably be reelected in 2002, unless Al Gore makes him his vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Davis's troops hold 25 of the 40 seats in the state Senate; 47
of the 80 seats in the state Assembly; both federal Senate seats;
and 28 of the 52 seats held by the California delegation to the
House of Representatives. All but two of the statewide elected
officials are Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In the primary in March, Al Gore beat George W. Bush by seven
percentage points, and in the latest polls the vice president looks
likely to carry California just as Bill Clinton did in the last two
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   More telling, perhaps, is the complete shambles that the
Republicans find themselves in. Even the two state officers who
managed to win in the teeth of the Davis Democratic landslide are
in poor shape today.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Jones, the state secretary, backed John McCain rather than
Bush in the primary in March this year, putting him out of favor
with the mass of his party.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Charles Quackenbush, the centrist insurance
commissioner who briefly seemed the Republicans' last best hope, is
going down in flames.
</P>
<P>
   Were Davis a more Machiavellian type, it would be tempting to
imagine him plotting the hearing Quackenbush recently had to endure
in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the insurance commissioner admitted, it had not been wise
to forgive the large fines owed by insurance firms that had failed
to pay victims of the Northridge earthquake in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it had been a bad idea to let them make rather smaller
contributions to foundations he had set up.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was not good that the foundations had given none of this
money to the earthquake victims but, instead _ among other things _
to a football camp that Quackenbush's sons attended.
</P>
<P>
   All that stands between California's Republicans and utter
collapse is the hope that Bush, at the top of the ticket in
November, will pull them through the election without losing any
more seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (100-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 425) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The only apparent constitutional brake on Democratic ambitions
is the requirement that the state budget pass by a two-thirds
majority; this ensures that as long as the Republicans retain their
seats in the state Senate, their views cannot be altogether
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are now praying that Bush does not follow his
father's example and in effect abandon California, giving the
Democrats a chance to increase their majority.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, Davis's battalions will probably control the
redistricting process next year, giving them another chance to lock
in the party's advantages for the future. Big Business certainly
seems to have reached that conclusion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,075) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Davis has raised a record $1.2 million a month since taking
office at the beginning of 1999. Not only have habitual Democratic
supporters such as the unions and lawyers showered money on him,
but also the oil industry, agriculture, and such stalwart
Republican paymasters as Gallo, Fox and GTE.
</P>
<P>
   These defections are extremely pleasing for Democrats. But they
also reflect Davis's pitch to his corporate backers. He portrays
himself as a regulatory and fiscal conservative who offers
insurance against the wilder instincts of the left wing of his
party.
</P>
<P>
   The last two Democrats elected governor _ both members of the
Brown dynasty _ built up the state institutions California
Democrats cherish: Pat introduced grand educational and
infrastructure programs, while son Jerry expanded the state's green
laws.
</P>
<P>
   Liberals who had hoped for more of the same from Davis have
watched in dismay as he has vetoed all but a small set of measures
creating performance indices for schools (and some would argue that
this is a Republican idea).
</P>
<P>
   A cautious soul who has devoted most of his life to crawling
slowly up the ladder of California Democratic Party politics (and
who has endured endless taunts about the aptness of his first
name), Davis seems convinced that the lesson of his own landslide
is that drawing away from the center in pursuit of a radical agenda
is to court disaster.
</P>
<P>
   His predecessor, Pete Wilson, was a moderate Republican, but he
listened to the extremist wing of his party by endorsing an
anti-immigrant program. That helped secure Wilson's own reelection
in 1994, but it also stirred up a backlash among California's many
Latinos and Asians that wiped out Davis's Republican opponent.
</P>
<P>
   A policy of clinging to the center is not without risks. A
warning shot, showing how the Democrats might be sunk, was fired in
March last year.
</P>
<P>
   A pocket of California that did appear truly one-party, where
the question was not ``Which party do you like?'' but ``Which
faction within the party do you like?'' _ a perpetually Democratic
assembly seat in Oakland where no Republican had even bothered to
run _ elected the first Green representative in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader, a Californian, has promised a Green run at the
presidency this year, and could carve support away from the
Democrats' left flank.
</P>
<P>
   There is even the chance of Seattle-hardened rowdies disrupting
Davis's showpiece _ the Democratic Convention to be held in Los
Angeles in August.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the odds are that Davis has got it right. The truth is that
California is not a one-party state but a no-party state. Its
policies are increasingly dictated by ballot propositions voted on
directly by the people.
</P>
<P>
   Term limits have winnowed away the professional politicians and
knocked holes in the boilers of the party machines.
</P>
<P>
   Davis's paralysis is the fear of a politician who has lived
through tax revolts and has seen the punishment that voters mete
out to mainstream parties.
</P>
<P>
   He has achieved party dominance at precisely the time that the
country's fastest-evolving state is reaching beyond the party lines
that have defined American politics in the 20th century. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 0533EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
