<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Summer tomatoes in the spring? It
can be done
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ A gaggle of good ol' boys had gathered for an
evening near Lake Sam Rayburn.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the main dish was smoked brisket. The main topic
of conversation was tomatoes. The main talker was Murphy George.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, who has a hand in most everything that works for a good
purpose hereabouts, knows tomatoes, his main business being William
George Co., a food distribution operation that helps feed folks
halfway across Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy had provided the fresh tomatoes for that evening's
cookout. He didn't have to tell us what they'd taste like. They'd
taste like next to nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Ol' Roy Blount Jr., the Southern writer, said it well, that
somewhere along the way tomatoes and fudgcicles got to tasting
about the same.
</P>
<P>
   These were hothouse tomatoes. They're not so hot.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody knows you can't get a good, vine-ripened Texas tomato
until the middle of summer. That's the way it is, always has been.
</P>
<P>
   But it may not be that way for much longer. Murphy was telling
us something about tomatoes none of the rest of us knew.
</P>
<P>
   He's planning on having good tomatoes as early as the end of
May. He planted early _ way early _ and in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   This is an experimental operation he has under way with a couple
of partners, trying to bring big-time produce production back to
this part of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It involves plastic sheeting to protect the young plants, drip
irrigation to keep them from drying up, the good red dirt of the
pineywoods, plenty of sun and, for good measure, Styrofoam cups and
old car tires.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Murphy was telling us, how he, personally, saved
this year's young crop of tomatoes from late freezes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know I'm a gambler,'' Murphy likes to say. He was betting
that they could plant tomatoes earlier than ag experts say you
ought to. He had 4,000 tomato plants riding on his wager.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy likes to gamble. He doesn't like to lose.
</P>
<P>
   He got a call one day with the bad news. Freezing weather was
expected that night. The young tomato plants, just peeking up,
wouldn't survive. What could they do?
</P>
<P>
   Murphy told them to hold on, that he was coming.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't come alone. He brought 4,000 Styrofoam cups with him.
</P>
<P>
   He and his crew covered every tomato plant with a cup, each
topped with a clump of dirt to hold it in place against the north
wind.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy grins when he tells you that they didn't lose one plant
that night. So far, so good.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later he got the same call. Another freeze was on
the way.
</P>
<P>
   The plants were too big for cups. What could they do?
</P>
<P>
   Murphy told them to hold on. Here he comes again, this time
rounding up loads of old car tires.
</P>
<P>
   He and his crew lined the perimeter of the tomato beds with
tires, and then they waited. They waited until 2 a.m., just before
the thermometer was about to drop below freezing. That's when they
set fire to the tires.
</P>
<P>
   The temperature fell to 30 degrees overnight, but they didn't
lost a single plant.
</P>
<P>
   By the last week of April, they already had full green tomatoes
drooping on the vine. By the end of the month, they'll have
vine-ripened tomatoes on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a cash crop. What will folks pay for a good tomato
way early in the year? What won't they pay?
</P>
<P>
   Smart man, Murphy George. He knows tomatoes, and most anything
he puts his mind to. Maybe one of these days he'll give some
thought to fudgcicles.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(AT)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
