<HEADLINE>
ABC HAS A BIG PLAN FOR ITS DERBY FINALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABC survived its scare with Time Warner and plans to air the
Kentucky Derby for the 26th consecutive year, in time for the May
sweeps period.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over transmission rights left an estimated 3.5
million cable viewers, including those in Houston, Los Angeles, and
New York, without ABC for 39 hours until Disney and Time Warner
agreed to a six-month truce. Regardless of the outcome, ABC
spokesman Mark Mandel said his network was planning to proceed
``full speed ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   This is marks the last time ABC will have the television rights
to the Kentucky Derby. NBC has acquired the rights to all Triple
Crown events and will show the Derby next year. ``We have just as
much passion and excitement as ever before,'' said ABC producer
Curt Gowdy Jr. ``It's been a wonderful ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Veterans Jim McKay and Al Michaels are ABC's co-anchors and Dave
Johnson will call the race. There will be a feature on the
favorite, Fusaichi Pegasus, a $4 million yearling trained by
Hall-of-Famer Neil Drysdale and ridden by Kent Desormeaux, who won
the Derby on Real Quiet in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ABC also will employ ``On-Track,'' a three-dimensional virtual
animation graphic that details how the race will be run from start
to finish, and the network has placed 37 cameras around the track
and wireless microphones on jockeys.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Playoff winners
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Turner Sports commentator Mike Fratello has heard nothing but
good reactions to the NBA playoff schedule. The former NBA coach
said the two- and three-day rest periods have helped teams with
banged-up players recover and enabled coaches to fine tune game
strategies. ``I have not received a single negative reaction from
any of the coaches or players,'' Fratello said. ``With the
exception of Miami, which won its round early and had a long
stretch of practice time, the days off have been great not only for
the teams but also for the fans. The fans now know when the games
are going to be on, and it's helped eliminate the confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   NBA commissioner David Stern said the schedule was designed, in
part, to increase television ratings, a decision that has generated
criticism from columnists throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   The ratings have slipped but are expected to improve with the
remaining two Game 5 series between the surprising Sacramento Kings
and Los Angeles Lakers and the Indiana Pacers and the Milwaukee
Bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Fratello said the playoffs have proven disappointing for young
stars Kevin Garnett and Vince Carter. ``It's a learning
experience,'' said Fratello. ``When Michael Jordan was in his first
playoff games, he didn't win either. He didn't have enough weapons
to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Fratello has been the subject of several rumors that he would
soon leave the broadcast booth for another head coaching job. ``I
don't know,'' Fratello said. ``We have to wait and see if anyone
wants me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cleaning the plate
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ozzie Smith, CNN/SI's baseball analyst, said that he agreed with
Pedro Martinez when the Red Sox pitcher told reporters he was only
doing his job when he hit Cleveland's Roberto Alomar Sunday.
``Pitchers are going to have to regain their dominance of the
plate,'' Smith said. ``Right now batters own the plate _ the
inside, outside, everywhere. And it shows, because baseballs are
flying out of the park at record speeds this year. If I'm a pitcher
standing on that mound, I don't want that batter digging in and
owning the plate. You've got to throw inside and shave the inside
plate. If not, the batters will continue their slugfest.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reporting live
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fox Sports New England launches its ``Regional Sports Report''
July 31. The 30-minute live show will start with one presentation
at 11 p.m. and eventually air another at 6:30 p.m. . . . HBO's ``KO
Nation'' debuts Saturday at 5:30 p.m. with a light heavyweight
fight between Paul Spadafora and Mike Griffith followed by the
heavyweight bout between Lamon Brewster and Clifford Etienne. ``KO
Nation'' is HBO's attempt to deliver a program with a hip-hop
flavor. Ed Lover is host, while New York sports anchor Fran Charles
will do the blow-by-blow . . . Tracy Dolgin has been named Fox
Sports Net president. Dolgin had worked as chief operating officer
at Fox Sports Net since 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
