<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6289 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-RAC-DERBY-SAHADI-2TAK     05-05 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-SAHADI-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FIRST IN WINNER'S CIRCLE? 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ No horse trained by a woman has ever won the
Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Jenine Sahadi knows this, just as she knows the times. Gender
politics is an issue, ``and I knew that it was going to be a big
issue even before I stepped off the plane in Louisville. It was an
issue when I was up at Woodbine (racetrack in Toronto) and when I
was at Belmont (Park in New York) for the Breeders' Cups there.
I've always said, until I win these races, it's always going to be
an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   She won those Breeders' Cup races. Twice. The first woman to win
a Breeders' Cup race on the dirt. (A French woman, Cricket Head,
has trained a Breeders' Cup grass champion.) So Sahadi's expertise
is beyond dispute.
</P>
<P>
   But Sahadi, a 37-year-old woman who knew as a little girl she
always wanted to be around horses, also says ``I'm no Gloria
Steinem'' and ``I'm not going to burn my bra if I win the Derby.''
Seemingly, a more personal passion burns within her.
</P>
<P>
   Namely: no horse trained by Jenine Sahadi has ever won the
Kentucky Derby. And Saturday her colt, The Deputy, most likely will
be the second choice to win the 126th Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women have not had the opportunity to play (in racing's major
races),'' said Sahadi, matter-of-factly. ``If you want to play
you've got to have the stock. Luckily, for me, I've had the stock
and I've been in situations where I've been the first (woman to
win). But wherever I go, I see it's still going to be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1875, 712 trainers have entered horses in the Kentucky
Derby. Only nine have been women. The closest a woman came to
winning was in 1992, when Shelley Riley's Casual Lies finished
second. Horse racing is a male-dominated business, especially at
the top.
</P>
<P>
   If scores and scores of exercise riders, those near the bottom,
are women, very, very few women are either jockeys or trainers at
the top levels of racing. Horse racing keeps no gender statistics
on its trainers, but 5 percent might seem a plausible estimate of
women trainers at the top tracks, even if women trainers might
number as many as 10 or 20 percent at smaller tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know women who work very, very hard and do a fantastic job
and just are never given a chance,'' said Sahadi. ``A trainer is
only as good as his or her stock. Some women I know are training
low-level claiming horses, and maiden claimers, and that sort of
thing. It's really difficult to make a living at that level.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the issue is that until recently it has been men
who have had the millions and millions of dollars to play with, to
throw at horses, to buy a baby horse for $400,000 or $4 million.
These men with money are likely to choose men as trainers.
</P>
<P>
   It is not until women become independently wealthy, said Sahadi,
and want to enter the racing game that women trainers will be
trusted with the care of the best racehorses. Society is changing
in that regard, as more and more women become wealthy, but horse
racing still entices many more men than women at all levels, from
fans to gamblers to trainers and jockeys; the road to hoe is very
long.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of a break-even situation (for trainers who train
average horses) and you never do really well until you compete in
the big races and participate in the big pots,'' said Sahadi. ``But
you know, there are not even a lot of female assistant trainers. I
know Todd Fletcher (who has four horses entered in the Derby) has
his gal and April Mayberry (an assistant to Sahadi-nemesis Bob
Baffert) is an assistant, but there aren't that many.''
</P>
<P>
   Sahadi said one of her best friends is Summer Mayberry, April's
sister, ``and here's a gal who absolutely loves horses and her last
name is Mayberry so I don't know how much more I need to say about
how she was involved in the barn (of Brian Mayberry, a California
trainer and father of April and Summer). Here's a girl who gets on
all her horses every day and she . . . she . . . she just
struggles.''
</P>
<P>
   But the personal and the political are so difficult to separate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, the personal and the political clashed and crashed
and exploded for Sahadi. During a press conference prior to the
Santa Anita Derby, Sahadi stormed off the dais when the
wise-cracking Baffert asked jockey Chris McCarron, who'll ride The
Deputy for Sahadi in the Kentucky Derby, ``Are you training the
horse or is Jenine?''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert later would say he was only joking. Sahadi later would
say this was the latest in a long list of slights and barbs she has
heard ever since she left the Hollywood Park publicity office 10
years ago and began training horses.
</P>
<P>
   Typical: Sahadi's boyfriend at the time she began training was
Julio Canani, a California trainer, and she'd hear barbs that asked
whether it was she or Canani who was training the horses. More
recently, Sahadi married Ben Cecil, another California trainer, and
again the whispers whether it was she or her husband doing the work
that has paid off so well.
</P>
<P>
   (Gender politics can slide into sexual politics; the first
``Who's training the horses?'' whispers reportedly came from
Canani's ex-wife, and Baffert is best friends with Canani, the man
Sahadi did not marry. Baffert, for his part, said his
``relationship with Sahadi is the same as ever; we're still not
speaking.'' Baffert's barbs, of course, have hit men as well and
women; Baffert and top trainer D. Wayne Lukas are bitter enemies
and seldom speak.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I'd read something about myself, it was like a
historical registry of who I dated and who I slept with,'' she said
with a laugh. ``You do that with Lukas and his four wives, and I
told him that the other day, and you'd never write about a horse of
his. He's been married four times and I love the guy to death, but
you'd never hear about his horses if you did that with him. You'd
run out of column space.''
</P>
<P>
   Even worse for Sahadi than the barbs was what happened to her
after she won her two Breeders' Cup races, the pinnacle of success.
``I thought my phone'd be ringing off the hook (with new
business),'' she said, ``but instead the opposite happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Her main owners, Evergreen Farms, dropped out of the business
and Sahadi was left to scramble. Things went so poorly a year ago
that she thought of quitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I interviewed with TVG (the new horse racing cable network)
and I talked to Amy Zimmerman at the Santa Anita publicity office
about doing some stuff there,'' said Sahadi. ``I'd gone the whole
year without winning a graded stakes (race) . . . whatever we try
to forget, you guys always remember to bring up.''
</P>
<P>
   Precisely. Sahadi had majored in communications at the
University of Southern California, and started out in publicity,
handing out media credentials and typing up press releases at
Hollywood Park. With Marje Everett running Hollywood Park, Sahadi
seemed to have a future there. But Hollywood Park was sold, Sahadi
saw little future with the new owners and decided to follow her
first love, first engendered by her father _ horses.
</P>
<P>
   But when life on the track looked bleakest, Barry Irwin and the
Team Valor thoroughbred consotium gave Sahadi ``some stock'' as she
puts it; namely, some good horses to train. And the best may be The
Deputy, an obscurely-bred horse from Ireland that Team Valor bought
for $400,000 six months ago and sent to Sahadi. The horse's future
seemed to be with grass racing, but Sahadi switched him to the dirt
and The Deputy has been spectacular since.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
