<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6290 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-RAC-DERBY-SAHADI-2ND &LR;      05-05 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-SAHADI-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 LOUISVILLE, Ky.: ... spectacular since.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I had known Barry since my press box days and we had claimed a
filly together, Barry and I, and I've actually had a great
relationship with him,'' said Sahadi. ``He has great knowledge of
horses and has a great eye for them. I'm a person who's brutally
honest with my clients and I want to be able to call them and say,
`Hey, this is the deal with this horse,' and good, bad or
indifferent I want to be able to cut to the chase. And Barry
appreciates that.''
</P>
<P>
   While Irwin (``Jenine is an oustanding trainer'') may appreciate
that bluntness, many other horse owners do not. Owners may spend
millions on horses for millions of reasons but, for many, one of
the primary reasons is to seen at the race track at the big race
and (hopefully) to be seen in the winner's circle. Many owners do
not like to hear from their trainers that their horse is not ready
for the big race. Yet, Sahadi has retained her bluntness.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, also another side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clothes and jewelry,'' said Sahadi of her loves for diamonds
and garb, not mentioning a third, her ever-present sunglasses.
``When my husband went to get my ring, I told him, 'I'm a big girl
. . . I'm 5-10 . . . so get me a big ring.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This was inside the dimly-lit Kentucky Derby Museum Wednesday
evening, just after the post-position draw for the Kentucky Derby.
Jenine Sahadi, making the rarest of public appearances without her
sunglasses, was pronouncing herself pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly didn't want to be inside,'' said Sahadi,
ever-cooperative as always with the media; her job once was to
serve the media's needs and the old training persists. ``I always
wanted to be further out (in the starting gate) than further in.
I'm happy.''
</P>
<P>
   More and more questions.
</P>
<P>
   Was she surprised that fellow-California trainer Neil Drysdale
chose to place his tempermental Fusaichi Pegasus, the Derby
favorite and petulance horsified, out in stall 16 when he could
have been more inside, such as Post 11, where Sahadi had been able
to place her colt, The Deputy?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ahhhhhhhhh . . . '' replied Sahadi, thinking out loud, ``Not
really. You know, with his horse's running style, the idea was to
get a very clean trip. And then he wouldn't be in the gate that
much from out there. And, you know, (Drysdale's) concerns with his
horse are a lot different from mine. Having said that, my horse may
lose it on Saturday, too. I mean, I don't think he will, but you
never know.''
</P>
<P>
   You never do. Not on the first Saturday in May at Churchill
Downs. Never.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kentucky Derby,'' John Steinbeck wrote back in 1956,
``whatever it is _ a race, an emotion, an explosion _ is one of the
most beautiful and violent and satisfying things I have ever
experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Saturday afternoon experience. Ah, but this was
Wednesday evening, Jenine Sahadi had been alone, away from her
California home for three weeks, away from her husband, away from
her 14 other horses, bored silly here in faraway Kentucky with
pressure building and building and building, her months of
preparation now only hours away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fellas,'' Sahadi said, ``will you please apologize (to Derby
officials) for me?'' She was tired, could not do more interviews
with the other Derby trainers in a formal press conference, just
had to leave. ``I've got a big day tomorrow . . . I've tried to be
as helpful as possible. I'm exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   Her horse is absolutely ready. Her twin battles are near their
final moments. One battle for her gender, the woman who has endured
slight after slight despite her successes. The other for herself,
for the Jenine Sahadi who fell in love with horses as a little girl
as she hung around with Charlie Whittingham, the legendary
California trainer who cared so deeply about each of his horses;
for the Jenine Sahadi who came close to quitting a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes, it would be a step forward for a woman trainer to win
the Derby. But that would be political. So much more personal,
though, it would be if Jenine Sahadi is that first woman trainer to
step into a Derby winner's circle. No whispers could be heard amid
the tumult.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
