<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-MCCARRON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOGGED `DEPUTY' EXCITES MCCARRON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Chris McCarron has ridden in the Kentucky
Derby 16 times and won twice, with Alysheba in 1987 and Go For Gin
in 1994. The 45-year-old Dorchester native was elected to the Hall
of Fame in 1989 and remains one of the best money riders in the
game. McCarron has a legitimate chance to complete a personal Derby
trifecta Saturday aboard The Deputy, the second choice in the
morning line for the Rose Run at 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   McCarron flew in from California last Monday night, worked The
Deputy (five furlongs in a minute) Tuesday morning, and stayed in
the Louisville area to socialize and ride some mounts to get a feel
for Churchill Downs strip.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Deputy gets over the ground here beautifully,'' said
McCarron. ``He's very competitive. He's definitely talented, and
he's very generous with that talent. He's a very professional
horse.''
</P>
<P>
   The Deputy, owned by the Team Valor Stable and Gary Barber, who
heads a film production company, began his career in Europe in
modest fashion. The son of Petardia, who was bred in Great Britain
out of Manfaith, who was bred in Ireland, The Deputy ran five times
on grass as a 2-year-old in England, winning only once. He did not
race past seven furlongs. Purchased by Barry Irwin, president of
Team Valor, and turned over to trainer Jenine Sahadi, The Deputy
won his first race in America in his 3-year-old debut, taking the
Hill Rise Stakes on the Santa Anita turf Jan. 2. Sahadi then
switched him to dirt because he trained well on it, and The Deputy
won the Santa Catalina, finished second in the San Felipe to Derby
favorite Fusaichi Pegasus, and proved he could cover the distance
when he captured the $1 million Santa Anita Derby at a mile and
one-eighth April 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's by a sprinter, out of a sprinter,'' said McCarron, who
has ridden The Deputy in every US race. ``But I think he'll hold
his own at a mile and one-quarter (for the Derby). He's already
proven he can run up to a mile and one-eighth. His style is very
adaptable. In Europe, he came from way back. Here, he closed in his
first race. In the next race, he went to the lead. It just depends
on the way he gets away from the starting gate. He's got natural
speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus is regarded as the second coming of Secretariat
by some, but he beat The Deputy by only three-quarters of a length
in the San Felipe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave him a little scare, but The Deputy hung in the
stretch'' said McCarron. ``He was very game, he was just in need of
a race. He had't run in seven weeks (from the Jan. 30 Santa
Catalina to the March 19 San Felipe). Also, we gave Fusaichi
Pegasus six pounds (122-116). The Deputy has every right to move
forward the next time he meets Fusaichi Pegasus. The Deputy is just
a good competitor. He's going to be tough to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Sahadi will become just the 10th woman to saddle a Derby starter
in 126 races. The Run for the Roses has never been won by a female
trainer or jockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jenine is one of the most conscientious horsemen I've ever
dealt with,'' said McCarron. ``She cares about her horses, she
treats them like you'd treat kids. She puts in lots and lots of
hours at the barn. A rider can't ask for more than that from a
trainer. She cares, and puts in the time and effort. I know when I
get on one of her horses, I'm going to get on one that's ready, and
likely to do well. That's a good feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you can do something special (helping Sahadi become
the first woman to win the race), it's good. And this is the Derby,
so it's automatically special.''
</P>
</TEXT>
