u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     05-05 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CEOS GOT MORE, EVEN IF THEY DIDN'T EARN IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We develop a case of CEO envy this time every year.
</P>
<P>
   By now, most of the state's largest public companies have filed
their annual proxies detailing how much chief executives were paid
in 1999. That means salary, bonus and selected perks, but more
importantly it includes restricted stock awards and options.
</P>
<P>
   The results of our informal survey: more, more, more, and not
necessarily in proportion with the joy or pain distributed to
stockholders last year.
</P>
<P>
   That is consistent with national surveys, in direction if not
details. There's enough methodology in a real compensation study to
spin a wonk's head.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of chief executives at the 350 largest US companies by
consultants William M. Mercer Inc. found that short- and long-term
direct compensation rose 24.5 percent to an average $4.9 million
last year. Another national survey in the current issue of Forbes,
measuring compensation at 800 companies, concluded CEO pay was up a
more modest 12.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, almost every Massachusetts CEO was better off in
1999, at least when it came to the compensation basics. Divining
the real value of stock and option kickers and comparing them is a
much tougher call. (We declined to look at past restricted stock or
option awards granted in past years that took effect in 1999.)
</P>
<P>
   FleetBoston Financial Corp. chief Terry Murray was the state's
king of cash compensation by our list of public big-company execs.
His combined salary and bonus rose a relatively tame 11 percent to
$5 million, surely a balance sufficient for no-fee banking.
</P>
<P>
   There's more: Murray was awarded restricted stock worth another
$14.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, FleetBoston's stock was slumping 19.9 percent, though
that can be a misleading statistic. All financial stocks were
clobbered last year and Murray did manage to pull off the
BankBoston megamerger in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Only one chief executive in our crowd received less cash
compensation in 1999. Before you cry for Raytheon Co. chief Daniel
Burnham, whose bonus got cut 40 percent to $900,000 last year,
recall that shareholders took a 51 percent haircut on their
investment in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham also was awarded 300,000 stock options, which have a
potential value of roughly $6.5 million over time. In the corporate
world, that's called alignment of interests of management with
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Buck, a consultant with Mercer in Boston, points out that
long-term incentives, which were 49 percent of a CEO's pay package
in 1995, now amount to 63 percent of their compensation. ``That
highlights a significant trend,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly signifies something. The option trend is generating
long-term compensation that has the potential of becoming worth
five to 10 times a CEO's cash compensation in the year of the
award.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette chief executive Michael Hawley earned $1.5 million in
cash last year, while the company's stock was slipping 12 percent.
But Hawley was also awarded 750,000 options that could eventually
be worth nearly $11 million, using a common option pricing model
that Gillette included in its proxy.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing generated options like James Tobin's career moves of
1999. Tobin, who had been chief execuitve of Biogen Inc. of
Cambridge, quit and resurfaced as the new CEO of Boston Scientific
Inc. in Natick.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin won the mother of all golden handshakes when he walked in
the door at Boston Scientific, a million stock options that could
be worth $54.2 million if you assume 10 percent compounded stock
value increases over the 10-year life of the option agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Back at Biogen, chairman James Vincent stepped into the void
left by Tobin's exit and served as a temporary chief executive in
1999. The payoff: a $1.5 million cash bonus and 740,000 options
with a potential value of $63.3 million using the same 10 percent,
10-year calcualtion.
</P>
<P>
   With all this cash and stock flying in the executive offices of
Greater Boston, is there a shareholder-friendly compensation story
out there? We found at least one.
</P>
<P>
   Our Bang For the Buck CEO award of 1999 goes to George
Chamillard of Teradyne.
</P>
<P>
   Chamillard was paid about $1.3 million in cash last year and
received 105,000 Teradyne options potentially worth about $2.1
million in the future.
</P>
<P>
   We liked his option deal for two reasons: it didn't seem
excessive by the standards of other CEOs and his share of all
company options granted last year appeared fairer than most.
</P>
<P>
   Chamillard was awarded 1.86 percent of all Teradyne options last
year and four other company executives each received at least half
as many as his. Most CEOs in our group got 5 percent or more of the
option pie and several examples were much worse (Vincent took
nearly 25 percent of the 1999 Biogen options).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, earnigns per share at Teradyne increased 55 percent
last year. The stock, which more than tripled in 1999, is up
another 52 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Teradyne is enjoying a rising tide benefitting all
semiconductor companiens. But shareholders have seen their
investment rise 515 percent since Chamillard became Teradyne's
chief executive three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That's getting value for your money.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre (929-2918) and Charles Stein (929-2922) can also be
reached by e-mail at boscap(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
