<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-LUEDTKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARBARA E. LUEDTKE, 51; AUTHORITY ON NATIVE SETTLEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Calif.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barbara E. Luedtke, an authority on Native American settlements
who was a professor of anthropology at the University of
Massachusetts at Boston, died of cancer Tuesday in Beth Israel
Deaconess Medical Center. She was 51.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Luedtke was born in Milwaukee and raised in the San Diego
area. Her interest in archeology began as a junior high school
student, when she took a ferry from her family's home on Coronado
Island each weekend to participate in local digs. A semester in
Australia as an undergraduate at Pomona College sparked her
interest in aboriginal populations.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Pomona, she earned a doctorate at the
University of Michigan, where her research focused on the stone
working technology and prehistoric communities in the Eastern
woodlands. Her later research focused on Native American
settlements in the Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   In a story published in the Globe on Nov. 7, 1986, she said,
``We have great descriptions from the Pilgrims of what the Indian
villages were like, but we can't find them archeologically.''
</P>
<P>
   She said sites dating from early periods are very common, but
those dating from just before the Europeans arrived are very rare.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Luedtke conducted an archeological survey of Boston Harbor,
ferrying groups of students each summer to excavations at Thompson,
Long, and Calf islands.
</P>
<P>
   She lectured widely on her findings and often opened her digs to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992 she conducted a week-long open dig at the Wampanoag
Indian homesite at Plimoth Plantation. While the dig was in
progress, she and her students interpreted their findings to
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   She was associate director of the Center for Materials Research
in Archaeology and Ethnology at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, where she taught lithic analysis to graduate students.
She was also a member of the Massachusetts Archaeological Society
and editor of its bulletin.
</P>
<P>
   She leaves her parents, Charles and Margaret Luedtke, and a
brother, Tom, all of Coronado Island, Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
