<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6300 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-LATHAM-COLUMN06-COX     05-05 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What you think often depends on just which house you live in
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ The guy on the other end of the line said:
``I'm so-and-so at the white house,'' and, right away, I figured
there was trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Yep. I was just sure that my dogs had found freedom again and
been practicing their evil ways on the lawn of the white house down
the street. It wouldn't have been the first time and the squatty
one likes to dig for oil.
</P>
<P>
   I was worried about what the damage might be when the guy starts
talking about China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hold on, buddy, I know that dog can dig deep, but don't you
think you're exaggerating just a bit?''
</P>
<P>
   Then I figured it all out. This guy wasn't from the white house
down the street but The White House. That's the problem with
telephones, you don't see capitalization.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, I wanted to ask him exactly where he was in The White
House: The Oval Office? The Lincoln Bedroom? The Rose Garden? My
guess is this guy was probably closer to The Utility Room, which is
one of those that isn't on the tour. But, hey, every room in The
White House is important, isn't it? Even if he was just calling
from a hallway, I suppose I should have been impressed.
</P>
<P>
   He was trying to talk to me about some matter which he insisted
was important, but I wasn't really listening. No, I wanted to know
if there was any funny business going on. You know what I mean, any
Chief Executive telling an intern to sit on his knee so he could
take a deposition?
</P>
<P>
   But apparently this guy wasn't close enough to the action which,
I suppose, is really a good thing for him. Seeing no evil may be
difficult at The White House (as opposed to the white house down
the street), but it sure keeps you out of testifying before a
congressional committee.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I decided that he wasn't going to shut up until I
listened to him (I'll happily hang up on most telemarketers, but
not one from The White House. I have a patriotic streak.).
</P>
<P>
   It became clear that he was, indeed, talking about China, home
of billions of future customers for the United States and most
likely home of future campaign contributions for presidential
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that someone very important in the administration
had written a column about just how important it was for the United
States to Permanant Normal Trade Relations and it was absolutely
vital to the survival of the Republic that this be printed in the
Marshall News Messenger. I guess my patriotism isn't all it should
be because it isn't going to run.
</P>
<P>
   Then White House guy said a piercing bit of truth, though he
didn't catch it (otherwise, he probably wouldn't have said it). He
said:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about Marshall, Texas, but this subject is what
everyone is talking about. It is the most important topic right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The bit of truth he told was, ``I don't know about Marshall,
Texas....''
</P>
<P>
   Because not only do most people in Washington not know about
Marshall, Texas, they don't know much about anywhere outside the
District of Columbia. Things there aren't like anywhere else on
earth.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to tell him that China wasn't the first thing on our
minds here in Marshall, that we were more consumed with cleaning up
after a tornado, and protests over the police chief, and, for that
matter, how the youth baseball leagues were going or how tomato
plants were growing.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't that trade status for China isn't important, but I
can't help but wonder what America would be like if most
politicians in Washington really did think the people in the white
house instead of the people in The White House.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (TX) News
Messenger. His email address is platham(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
