<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6301 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN06-COX     05-05 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baby Sophie arrives with ready-made honors
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Jena Roytman still doesn't know what came over
her, that day in the hospital last summer when she told her
grandmother she was pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   She had taken the home pregnancy test only the night before, and
wasn't scheduled to see her obstetrician until the following week.
``Normally, I wouldn't tell anyone that early,'' Roytman said.
</P>
<P>
   But when she walked into Sophia Litvak's room at Good Samaritan
Hospital, Roytman did the last thing she had expected to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you're just glowing today,'' her grandmother said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pregnant, grandma,'' Roytman blurted.
</P>
<P>
   Then Sophia Litvak asked something she had never before asked of
her granddaughter _ a favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the baby is a girl, would you name her after me?''
</P>
<P>
   As Russian Jews, it was not traditional for the family to name a
baby after a living person. ``Oh, Grandma, don't talk like that,''
Roytman protested. ``You're going to live another 100 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Litvak was, in fact, recovering nicely from a bout with
pneumonia, and scheduled to be released over the weekend. But she
extracted her promise anyway: ``Just in case I don't live another
100 years, will you name the baby after me?''
</P>
<P>
   Roytman promised.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, July 24, Sophia Litvak died of a heart attack. She
was 87.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, Roytman learned the baby was a girl _ a
little sister for son Eric, 3 _ due on her grandmother's birthday,
March 27.
</P>
<P>
   Roytman was devastated by the loss of a woman who was ``the
backbone of the family.'' Her grandmother, who worked as a
pediatrician in Russia for more than 30 years, had retired to take
care of her first granddaughter, a sickly child. Litvak became an
``extra mom'' for the only child, who already had an exceptionally
close relationship with her parents, Bella and Vladimir
Futoryansky.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was there for me when I came home from school,'' Roytman
recalled. ``She was there to share school stuff, grades. She was
there when I was upset or happy. She knew what my life was about
and what I dreamed of.''
</P>
<P>
   At 18, Jena married high school sweetheart Mikhail Roytman.
Shortly afterward, her new husband and his family attained
political refugee status and emigrated to the United States, where
they were sponsored by the Dayton Jewish Community Center. A year
later, in 1991, Jena emigrated with her parents and grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Life was good in Dayton. The Roytmans established their own
computer consulting and recruiting business, Roytman Information
Services. And Sophia Litvak achieved a lifelong goal: Living in her
own home.
</P>
<P>
   Litvak continued to be an inspiration, as she studied, at 83, to
become an American citizen along with the rest of her family. ``She
had never known English before coming here, yet she took the exam,
passed it _ and did it in English.''
</P>
<P>
   After her grandmother's death, there was no question, for Jena,
that she would honor the only request her grandmother had ever made
of her. Mikhail initially had misgivings, as the couple had always
dreamed of having a little boy named Eric and a little girl named
Emily.
</P>
<P>
   For their 10th anniversary in November, Mikhail presented Jena
with an enormous Pier 1 gift bag with boxes stacked inside boxes
like Russian nesting dolls. Inside the smallest box she found an
envelope containing a slip of paper with a single word: ``Sophie.''
</P>
<P>
   Roytman doesn't think he could have given their daughter, born
March 18, a better gift.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to be half the person my grandmother was, to have
the common sense that she had, to have the ability to hold the
whole family together,'' Roytman said. ``And that is what I wish
for Sophie.''
</P>
<P>
   She understands, too, why her grandmother wanted a namesake.
``She didn't do it in a selfish sense. It was because she didn't
want me to be sad for her being gone. She wanted still to be part
of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   And when Jena holds baby Sophie, she has no doubt that Sophia
Litvak is still a part of all of them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
