<SLUG> BC-MINISTER0506-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Singing to the congregation
 &HT;    By Khalid Moss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Before gospel and Christian music became the
burgeoning industries that they are, standard procedure in most
churches was that ministers preached and choirs sang.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   As the line between singing gospels and preaching the gospel
becomes less defined, a new breed of musical ministers _ Kirk
Franklin, Shirley Murdoch, Michael W. Smith and Andre Crouch to
name a few _ intermingle their spoken messages with elaborate
musical praises.
</P>
<P>
   Pop crooner-turned-minister and ex-Daytonian Derek Floyd is a
disciple of this trend.
</P>
<P>
   While living in the Gem City, Floyd fronted his own group, Derek
and Cyndy, and was lead singer for the popular R&AMP;B band Cliche. His
national work includes sessions with vocalist Bobby Womack and
Philadelphia International's Gamble and Huff. After the death of
his first wife, television personality Audrey Moore, Floyd
abandoned secular music, moved to North Carolina and channeled his
energies into the church. In 1982 he was invited to join the
Inspirational Network as featured vocalist. Since then, Floyd has
been nominated for two Dove Awards and his song, ``Hero For
Today,'' was heard on Bob Hope's 1991 NBC special ``A Salute to
America.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993 Floyd graduated from East Coast Bible College and soon
after, launched his musical ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
