<HEADER>
A6303 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD06-COX     05-05 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Novice woodworker's shoes on well-trodden path
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Here, from the Internet, is probably the most common
dilemma that any untrained, novice woodworker faces:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a planer, jointer, or even any planes yet, so
now's the time to start fresh. I'm also on a low budget. I've been
building small projects such as stepstool, two-shelf bookracks,
etc. and they never quite come out right. My table saw is aligned
just right and ... people tell me it's probably because the boards
I'm working with aren't perfectly true. (flat on all sides) I've
done all my projects with S4S red oak and they've come out pretty
well, considering. But they always have annoying little gaps and
never stand on all four legs until I sand them.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I think the time has come to buy some flattening equipment.
One other complication: If the choice is hand planes (good for the
budget) how do I fasten the wood down? I have a Workmate and an
aluminum workbench with no provisions for dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The planer and jointer wouldn't be a bad idea, but it would
take a while to afford them. As I see it, here are my options:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1. ``Buy a portable planer (that's what I have room for) on my
Mastercard and a jointer plane.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  2. ``Buy a few planes (jointer, jack, and block) and try to
rig something up to hold the board steady.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  3. ``Try to find room and build a real workbench with dogs and
use planes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  4. ``Don't build anything else really precise until I can
afford a planer and jointer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are there any options I'm missing? Anyone else been in my
shoes? What would you do?''
</P>
<P>
   Lots of people have been in your shoes, my friend. You have
narrowed your options wisely, except for No. 4, which is not good
at all.
</P>
<P>
   Your first option isn't going to work out well either, because a
planer only removes wood and cannot be depended on to flatten a
bowed board, and you still have to have a means of holding the wood
for the jointer plane.
</P>
<P>
   What you want to do is combine options 3 and 4. Build yourself a
good workbench. It doesn't have to be fancy, and it doesn't have to
use expensive wood. It only has to have a very flat top and be very
heavy and rock-steady. As for dogs, it doesn't have to have those
either, although they're useful and if you're going to build a
bench you might as well put in a couple of holes for dogs. Make
your dogs of wood, though. Don't buy those metal ones. Then buy
good planes and learn to tune them and use them properly.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, keep your projects small. It's a lot easier
to flatten a two-foot board than a four-foot one.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if you limited yourself to things like jewelry boxes,
and picked your stock carefully, you probably wouldn't have to
exert yourself too much at all. And you'll save a lot of money if
you can stay away from the S4S stock.
</P>
<P>
   These are compromises, certainly, but they'll keep you working,
and learning, while you save money for the big investments.
Investment in a workbench and hand planes will never be wasted,
either. You'll always need them.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
