<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PEPPER-SPRAY (San Francisco) _ Nine anti-logging protesters
whose eyes were swabbed with pepper spray by Humboldt County
sheriff's deputies to break up demonstrations are entitled to a
second jury trial to attempt to prove that they were subjected to
excessive force, the U.S. Court of Appeals has ruled. By ERIC
BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-GLADIATOR (Undated) _ Just one word will do in
describing ``Gladiator,'' an epic of such emotive power and raw,
thrashy action that it may go down in history as the world's first
bona-fide bloodbath-tearjerker. That word is: Wow. By AMY
BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-AFRICA (Undated) _ ``I Dreamed of Africa'' never
gets much beyond a photogenic travelogue. Nonetheless, the film
offers bursts of beauty and emotion: Sections of it are actually
quite touching, not to say lachrymose, and Bernard Lutic's
exquisite cinematography provides visual drama on its own. By AMY
BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-BASKET (Undated) _ With its mild
anti-war/anti-discrimination message and upbeat David-and-Goliath
climax, ``The Basket'' scores a few points as a well-intentioned,
nicely shot family film. As a history lesson about rural America
during World War I, it's earnest and kid-friendly _ also simplistic
and dramatically creaky. By WALTER ADDIEGO.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-COTTON (Undated) _ ``Cotton Mary,'' the scary new
Ismail Merchant movie, has a pristine veneer for a few of its 123
minutes. An Indian nurse (Madhur Jaffrey) ingratiates herself into
the home of a visiting British family and cares for their newborn.
When mommy can't bring herself to feed her infant, the nanny's
handicapped sister secretly (Neena Gupta) plays wet nurse. By
WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-CENSORSHIP (Undated) _ The current debate in the U.S. Senate
about censoring TV was started by the Parents Television Council,
an extremely conservative group with former funnyman and current
censorship goon Steve Allen as their poster boy. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXAMINER-SALE (San Francisco) _ A Hearst Corp. executive
testified that the Fang family's offer to wield their political
clout to help Hearst buy the San Francisco Chronicle was ``a
consideration'' in Hearst's decision to give the Fangs its San
Francisco Examiner along with a $66 million publishing subsidy. By
SETH ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   LEVI-EARNINGS (San Francisco) _ Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. revealed its
1999 earnings decreased a stunning 94.8 percent from a year earlier
in documents the San Francisco jeans maker filed with the
Securities and Exchange Commission. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SF-HOUSING (San Francisco) _ San Francisco is the least
affordable county in California in which to buy a home, according
to a real estate association survey. By RICHARD PAOLI.
</P>
<P>
   FARMERS-MUSEUM (Cooperstown, N.Y.) _ High-speed computers and
electronics can bring the world to your fingertips. But a visit to
the Farmers' Museum in Cooperstown can take you back in time to
rural 19th-century America, where life was a hands-on experience.
Here you can discover the tradespeople who practice crafts of the
1800s. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS. (For release Sunday, May 7.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RAC-WOMAN-TRAINER (Louisville, Ky.) _ A year ago, Jenine Sahadi
was considering a new line of work. Only an unwavering loyalty to
her co-workers and an unflappable passion for the game kept her
marching toward a possible rendezvous with racing history. No woman
trainer ever has won the Kentucky Derby, but in The Deputy, Sahadi
arguably has the best chance ever to bridge the largest gender gap
associated with America's premier horse race. By MATT GRAVES.
</P>
<P>
   RAC-COMEDIAN-TRAINER (Louisville, Ky.) _ The $4 million monster
known as Fusaichi Pegasus swaggered down the track, causing
trainer/comedian Bob Baffert to cock his head. ``I wonder how he's
going to feel,'' Baffert said, ``when my little ol' $70,000 horse
runs right past him on Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Just when people start telling me
I'm losing weight, I find out I also may lose my protected status.
San Francisco is banning discrimination against fat people, and I
don't know if I'm one of them. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
