<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6310 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-DEFENDING-TAIWAN-1STL     05-05 1712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEFENDING-TAIWAN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-$ADV07-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     U.S. WOULD HAVE TOUGH TIME DEFENDING TAIWAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, May 7)   &HT;     (EDS: SUBS grafs 9-12 to clarify U.S. commitment to  
 Taiwan)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL and ERIC ROSENBERG   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ China's saber-rattling to quell Taiwan's talk of
independence spotlights one of Washington's best-kept secrets: The
United States would be hard-pressed to protect the island against
any Chinese attack.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials are hopeful that their warnings
to Beijing will prompt China to halt threatening rhetoric and
military movements before Taiwan's inauguration of a
pro-independence president on May 20.
</P>
<P>
   China's psychological warfare stems from concern that
President-elect Chen Shui-bian is the first leader in 51 years to
urge independence for Taiwan rather than eventual reunification
with mainland China.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. officials, keenly aware of the limits of U.S. power in
the distant region, are appealing to Taiwan as well to avoid
needless provocations of China, such as the declaration of
independence that China vows to crush by force.
</P>
<P>
   CIA Director George J. Tenet warned Congress even before
Taiwan's March 18 presidential election that Chen's
pro-independence agenda would prompt China to stage ``a show of
force'' that would create a ``high potential for another military
flare-up across the Taiwan Strait this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The People's Liberation Daily, China's official military
newspaper, has raised the specter of nuclear war if the United
States stands in the way of China's reunification with Taiwan,
reminding Washington that Beijing has ``certain long-distance
strike capabilities'' capable of delivering nuclear-armed missiles
against U.S. cities.
</P>
<P>
   With talk like that, Harvey Sicherman, a foreign policy analyst
with the Foreign Policy Research Institute in Philadelphia, says
U.S. war planners are focusing anew on threatened conflict with
China.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big problem _ bigger than it has been before,'' says
Sicherman.
</P>
<P>
   Yet any Chinese aggression against Taiwan would pose a tough
political decision for a U.S. president. The United States has an
ambiguous defense commitment to Taiwan, stemming from 1979 when
Washington broke diplomatic relations with Taiwan, switched
diplomatic recognition to China and adopting Beijing's policy that
Taiwan is part of China.
</P>
<P>
   The United States ended its mutual defense treaty with Taiwan
and Congress substituted domestic legislation known as the Taiwan
Relations Act to govern unofficial U.S. ties with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   The law falls far short of security guarantees once provided
Taiwan by treaty, merely obligating the United States to provide
``arms of a defensive character'' to Taiwan and to ``maintain the
(U.S.) capacity'' to ``resist any resort to force'' by China.
</P>
<P>
   The law leaves wide leeway for any U.S. response to a Chinese
attack on Taiwan, only stipulating ``that any effort to determine
the future of Taiwan by other than peaceful means _ including by
boycotts or embargoes _ is considered a threat to the peace and
security of the western Pacific area and of grave concern to the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Independent experts and U.S. war planners caution that the
United States would face immense difficulties defeating a
determined effort by China's 2.9 million-member armed forces to
terrorize, dominate or seize control of Taiwan, an island of 22.1
million that is one-third the size of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Every aspect of Taiwan's defense poses problems for the United
States, which relies on 300,000 U.S. military personnel to protect
U.S. Pacific interests, including nearly $600 billion in annual
two-way trade with three dozen countries. Much of the U.S. effort
in the Pacific is devoted to protecting South Korea and Japan,
rather than positioning for a possible defense of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Any likely combat scenario for China to dominate Taiwan _
whether a naval blockade, a missile attack, domination from the air
or an outright invasion _ would pose a huge challenge the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Fisher, a senior fellow and China expert with the
Jamestown Foundation, a conservative think tank, says China would
``move too quickly for the U.S. to respond,'' crushing Taiwan's air
force and navy within a day and seizing air superiority and control
the sea lanes within two to three days.''
</P>
<P>
   War planners are weighing the consequences of U.S. responses to
at least four possible scenarios for a Chinese military move
against Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chinese naval blockade of Taiwan:
</P>
<P>
   The far-flung U.S. Pacific Fleet would be forced to operate
warships from its 190-ship armada more than 1,000 miles from ports
in Japan and 2,000 miles from facilities in Singapore, where the
Navy signed an agreement on April 20 to enable U.S. warships to
resupply at state-of-the-art pier facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Long-range U.S. air operations staged from U.S. bases in Japan
or South Korea would face marauding forays by China's air corps of
4,970 combat aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chinese missile attack:
</P>
<P>
   The United States would face difficulties thwarting a Chinese
campaign to inflict terror and destruction with nuclear-capable
surface-to-surface missiles fired from coastal batteries.
</P>
<P>
   China's arsenal of 200 missiles is expected to swell to 800 by
2005, posing a challenge for U.S. anti-missile weapons such as the
Army's mobile Patriot anti-aircraft system that had difficulty
knocking down supersonic Iraqi warheads during the Persian Gulf
War.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kagan, of the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace,
says a Chinese missile onslaught could effectively ``force Taiwan's
capitulation without an invasion.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Seizing Taiwan airspace:
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon admits the difficulties of combating the Chinese
air force if Beijing launched an all-out bid to seize air
superiority over Taiwan. The sheer numerical advantage of China's
4,970 combat aircraft over Taiwan's paltry fleet of 392 combat
warplanes would enable China to wear down Taiwan's air defenses,
the Pentagon told Congress in a report last year.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has six aircraft carriers assigned to the
Pacific region capable of carrying almost 500 combat aircraft.
There are nearly 400 Air Force combat aircraft in Japan, South
Korea, Alaska, Guam and Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   _ Normandy-style amphibious invasion:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials take comfort that China currently lacks the
amphibious capability to carry out a successful amphibious landing
on Taiwan against opposing forces. But China's planned acquisition
of aircraft carriers and modernization of naval amphibious forces,
in addition to the acquisition of two modern Russian-built
destroyers this year, would Beijing the ability to carry out such
an operation by 2005, the Pentagon told Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the challenges posed by each scenario, the United States
faces the wider frustration of being unable to rely on Taiwan as an
equal partner in a joint defense. The island's 376,000-member armed
forces lack high-tech weaponry and extensive military-to-military
integration with U.S. forces, according to a secret 40-page
Pentagon report.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Taiwan have nothing like the close
military relationships, joint exercises and compatible weapons that
enabled U.S. forces to mobilize with allies to defend Persian Gulf
oil fields and expel Iraqi occupation forces from Kuwait in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan _ technically a province of China _ is not permitted to
take part in U.S. exercises, such as a six-week allied naval
exercise off the coast of Hawaii beginning May 30 that involves 50
ships, 200 aircraft, and 22,000 personnel drawn from seven nations.
</P>
<P>
   Political impediments also imperil the U.S. commitment to sell
defensive weapons to Taiwan. In April, the White House deferred
Taiwan's request to buy four sophisticated $1.1 billion Aegis-radar
equipped destroyers capable of tracking 100 airborne targets nearly
300 miles over the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Americans' staunch, Cold War-era support for the
defense of Taiwan has gradually ebbed in favor of broadening U.S.
commercial ties with China, a promising, fast-growing market of 1.2
billion people that does almost $100 billion a year in two-way
trade with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup Poll released March 22 showed Americans regarded China
and Taiwan in roughly the same terms: 26 percent called Taiwan
friendly but not an ally and 24 percent ranked China that way.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. appetite for increased trade with China has tempered
Americans' once ardent anti-communism and stalwart support for
non-communist Chinese Nationalists on Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate under Republican leadership since 1994 have
been every bit as supportive of expanding trade ties with China as
the Democratic-led House and Senate in earlier years. The GOP
Senate leadership is shelving action on House-passed legislation to
require the United States to forge military-to-military ties with
Taiwan. ``I just don't see the need for it,'' Sen. Frank Murkowski,
R-Alaska, said after returning from a visit to Taiwan in late
April.
</P>
<P>
   The ambiguous U.S. defense commitment to Taiwan _ far short of
the mutual defense treaty obligations that the United States has
undertaken with six nearby Asian nations _ leaves Washington plenty
of wiggle room when it comes to aiding Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   James Lilley, a former U.S. ambassador to China, says the
provision of U.S. law requiring defense aid to Taiwan ``gives you
the language to move in _ and it gives you the language to stay
out.''
</P>
<P>
   The ambiguity fosters flexibility _ and uncertainty about what
the United States would do if China carried out its threats against
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Eric McVadon, a retired Navy rear admiral who served as U.S.
naval attache at the U.S. embassy in Beijing in the early 1990s,
says an American president would face ``a really tough call'' about
whether to intervene to protect Taiwan against Chinese aggression,
adding: ``Even the question of whether we respond is one we don't
have great assurance on.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell and Eric Rosenberg can be reached at
202-298-6920 or at the e-mail addresses stewart &LR; hearstdc.com or
eric &LR; hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
