<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6316 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-POLL-SUCCESS-CENTERPI     05-05 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLL-SUCCESS-CENTERPIECE-ART-ADV07-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV07 
 ON THE ROAD TO SUCCESS, EVERYTHING CHANGES MONEY
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Sunday, May 7, or thereafter.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following article from The New York Times
Magazine is for use by clients of the ``Centerpiece'' package.
Nonsubscribers can use these articles only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 (ART ADV: A graphic of four poll questions and answers is available
by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.)  
 By ORLANDO PATTERSON 
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Of the many contradictions that make American life so endlessly
fascinating, few are more curious than those pertaining to money
and success.
 &HT;    The zeal to make money drives America's globally dominant
economy. It has long been observed that in the absence of an
aristocracy and the other insidious obfuscations of too much
history, money has been the chief maker and marker of status and
power. And if my profession is certain of one thing, it is the fact
that a family's income matters greatly for the welfare and
development of its children.
 &HT;    It is odd, then, that so many Americans have always held money
in suspicion. The Puritans were certain that it was the root of all
evil, even as they flagellated themselves for making more and more
of it. Leaders from Benjamin Franklin to Martin Luther King Jr.
have warned of the dangers of materialism.
 &HT;    Today, a substantial majority of Americans insist that they do
not overvalue money as a measure of their success. What's more,
they also deny the influence of money in the way they or their
children turn out. The puzzle deepens when we observe that even
African-Americans, as well as poorer and older people, are among
those most inclined to deny such influences.
 &HT;    What's going on? Are these people simply in denial? Or are they
just misinformed? Perhaps it's a little of both. But I think
something more complex is at play, having to do with the need to
reconcile our deeply held beliefs about equality with the realities
of inequality in America.
 &HT;    America justified its declaration of independence with the
startling principle that all people are self-evidently equal.
Nonetheless, in the more than two centuries since this declaration,
income inequality has grown, except for the period that began with
the mid-1930s and ended with the late 1960s.
 &HT;    This growth in inequality has been accompanied by an extension
of democracy far beyond what prevailed in Jefferson's day. And yet,
contrary to the fears of postrevolutionary leaders that a tyrannous
majority would inevitably soak the rich, for most periods of
American history, including our own, political power has rarely
been used to reduce inequality. Why is that?
 &HT;    There is little support for the cynical view that Americans
don't really take their egalitarian ideal seriously. They do, and
what's more, nearly half consider present economic inequalities
morally wrong.
 &HT;    As someone who has known or lived with the invidious injuries of
the British class system, the ostentatious iniquities of Caribbean
color-class hierarchies with their ``one people'' cant, not to
mention Brazilian apartheid with its Orwellian double-speak of
``racial democracy,'' I'll take the dilemmas of American
egalitarianism any day, racist warts and all.
 &HT;    Nonetheless, while most Americans genuinely endorse equality in
principle, they seem unable to embrace the political means
necessary to achieve it. Jennifer Hochschild, a political
scientist, thinks that Americans are highly egalitarian in the
domains of home, school and community, but that they reject
egalitarianism in the workplace. They are uncomfortable using
politics to redistribute wealth because they feel it mixes up
domains.
 &HT;    I doubt it. Working people do not use politics to repair income
inequality because they believe that the democratic process has
been corrupted and that politicians are beholden to vested
interests. Working- and middle-class Americans certainly desire
more money. But having long given up on politicians to do anything
about inequality, they have by necessity developed attitudes toward
money that enable them to live with it.
 &HT;    Religion is one buttress. In this most religious of
industrialized nations, it is religious Americans, among whom
African-Americans are disproportionately numbered, who are among
the most inclined to deny money's impact or its role as a measure
of success.
 &HT;    But a majority of the less devout among us also disclaim the
influence of money. They imagine that anyone can make it if they
really want to. Becoming rich is a matter of choice, and if there
is any virtue left, it lies in the road not taken. Many still share
Emerson's view that ``money often costs too much,'' added to which
are recent developments indicating that it buys less and less
status.
 &HT;    One effect of the vast growth of wealth in contemporary America
is that the rich are no longer exalted: too many millionaires have
socially degraded wealth. This is all the more true in the strange
roller-coaster world of the new economy, where millionaires are
daily made from market ether and traditional economic values are
upended. The rich can no longer claim to earn their status the
old-fashioned way. Like lottery winners, it could happen to anyone.
 &HT;    It may be, too, that people invest money with different symbolic
meanings. Viviana Zelizer, a sociologist, has argued that money has
cultural significance beyond its wholly instrumental uses. People
earmark and valorize money differently, depending on how it is
acquired.
 &HT;    The same person who scrupulously saves a portion of her income
for the down payment on a home will blow $1,000 won from the
lottery on a fancy dress or a party. In this cultural recoinage,
money ceases to be fungible. There is earned money and welfare
money; clean, laundered and dirty money; breadwinner's money and
pin money. And, one surmises, there is the funny money of the rich,
and the real, honest money of working people.
 &HT;    In fact, I would contend that the willingness of many Americans
to accept the widening income gap, despite their moral reservations
about it, grows out of a deep and abiding national conviction:
whatever differences fortune may have dictated between people,
where it really matters all of us are of truly equal worth.
 &HT;    
 c.2000 Orlando Patterson 
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Orlando Patterson, professor of sociology at Harvard, is the
author of ``Rituals of Blood,'' the second volume of a trilogy on
race relations.) &QL;
<P>
