<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 11:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6317 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-POLL-MORALITY-CENTERP     05-05 1384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLL-MORALITY-CENTERPIECE-ADV07-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV07 
 AMERICAN MORALITY: THE GOOD LIE
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Sunday, May 7, or thereafter.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following article from The New York Times
Magazine is for use by clients of the ``Centerpiece'' package.
Nonsubscribers can use these articles only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 By JANE SMILEY 
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    After reading the results of this poll, you'd have to say that
lying to protect someone's feelings is as American as enriching
your life by having children, almost as American as not ever having
done yoga, and more American than thinking you are too fat or
feeling guilty about a thing or two you did when you were younger.
 &HT;    On the other hand, lying to protect someone's feelings is not
nearly as American as thinking that being American is a big part of
who you are.
 &HT;    Myself, I would have to say that lying is not nearly as big a
part of who I am as writing fiction, and in fact, I almost never
lie, even to avoid hurting someone's feelings. What I do to avoid
hurting someone's feelings is just keep my opinion to myself.
 &HT;    Even so, my occasional forays into lying have made me something
of a theorist of lying. (Here are the lies I told: 1. I sold a car
knowing it needed new valve rings, but I really did not know that
it needed a new transmission until the buyer told me about it five
days after the sale. 2. I told one of my husbands that I still
loved him even though I didn't know whether I did or not.)
 &HT;    There are several forms of what you might call lying. One is
misrepresenting the truth. Another is keeping a secret. A third is
presenting as true what you wish were true, or perhaps hope is
true, but don't know for sure is true. A fourth form of lying is
shorthand _ the truth is changing so quickly that to detail every
shift would in fact present something as true that could very
quickly become false. A fifth is being mistaken, which sometimes
looks like a lie.
 &HT;    Let's begin with being mistaken. Everyone is mistaken almost all
the time, and so almost everything that everyone says will
eventually be proved wrong, and so almost everything that everyone
says is untrue.
 &HT;    The best answer to any question is, ``I don't know,'' even to so
simple a question as ``How do you like these shoes I bought?'' ``I
don't know'' is a real commitment to the larger truth, because it
recognizes that the passage of time makes every judgment
provisional.
 &HT;    However, people who always say ``I don't know'' find themselves
in a double bind _ either they are considered too bland to have
opinions or, if they explain why they don't know, they are told
that they think too much, and thinking too much is not very
American at all. So, logically, there is no truth telling, but
people persuade themselves that they more or less tell the truth
anyway.
 &HT;    A recognition of complexity makes truth telling that much more
difficult. Government officials or unfaithful spouses involved in
some quickly developing crisis, for example, are often subsequently
accused of either withholding information or misrepresenting the
partial information already available.
 &HT;    But the supposition that the truth is known almost always leads
to action, and most actions, of course, turn out to be unreasoned,
wrongheaded ones. Best to put off action as long as possible, and
lying to achieve this goal is a perfectly wise decision.
 &HT;    If the truth is almost always misrepresented, then the real
moral distinctions with regard to lying have to do with motive.
Most of those polled seem to feel that lying to save someone else
pain is moral. I suspect, though, that they would have had a
different response to the statement ``Lying is sometimes necessary
to protect oneself.'' Let us say that 60 percent might have
disagreed with this statement, and yet we all know that lying is
sometimes necessary to protect oneself, even when we choose not to,
and fail to protect ourselves.
 &HT;    In fact, one of the main tasks of raising children is to
convince them that telling a lie does not protect them; that it in
fact endangers them even more than the misbehavior that gave rise
to the lie. Children understand that to tell the truth is sometimes
counterintuitive, which is why teaching them to tell the truth
depends very much on how much power they think Mom and Dad really
possess. In my experience, oldest children hardly ever lie, but
second children, well aware of the disparity between what parents
think is going on and what is really going on, lie rather easily.
 &HT;    What constitutes self-protection? I wish the pollsters had asked
a final question: ``Although this is an anonymous questionnaire, I
have misrepresented the truth, exaggerated things and held
information back on one or more questions. Do you agree or
disagree?'' (See question No. 8, ``Have you ever cheated just a
little on your taxes or an office expense account, or haven't
you?'')
 &HT;    Obviously, of the 84 percent who say they have never exaggerated
their business mileage, never failed to report even a penny of cash
income, never filled in the wrong amount on a blank taxi receipt,
at least some are protecting their own opinion of themselves.
 &HT;    And how about if the pollsters had asked the question, ``Lying
is sometimes necessary for personal gain?'' How American would it
be to agree with that one? In what area of our booming economy do
the sellers of goods advertise them truthfully? In what area do the
buyers expect them to? In what political arena do the candidates
come clean? In what political arena do the voters expect them to,
or even want them to?
 &HT;    I remember when President Carter's attempt to rescue the
hostages in Iran failed. He spoke to the American people of his
sense that the hostage taking posed something of a dilemma, not
easily solved. As a result of his honesty and understanding of
complexity, he was widely perceived as weak and summarily replaced
in office by a simple man who seems never to have found himself in
a dilemma.
 &HT;    Is it more American to keep a secret or to tell it? The person
doing the choosing often has to consider the motives of the person
seeking the information. Almost all Americans, for example, would
have considered it extremely un-American for those hiding Jews
during World War II to divulge their whereabouts. In fact, many
Americans would consider it highly American for those living under
tyrannical regimes in faraway places to keep and bear arms, even
unlawful, secret arms.
 &HT;    My own feeling is that even in America, there are some to whom
it is obligatory to lie. When you are going through a serious
crisis, and a casual acquaintance or your mother asks how you are,
it is a very bad idea to actually tell them. ``Fine'' is fine.
 &HT;    It is also OK to lie to unsolicited telephone callers, guys who
make passes and friends who like to retail gossip or offer
unasked-for advice.
 &HT;    In this category I would have to include the press too: there is
never any moral opprobrium to be suffered by those who lie to the
press. Reporters are in the business of selling secrets for money.
They do not, therefore, have your best interests at heart. I have
always admired the efforts of every single celebrity or politician
who lied to the press. Just as the role of the press is to be a
watchdog upon the government, the role of celebrities and
politicians is to frustrate the all-seeing eye of the press and
remind everyone that there are questions that should never be asked
if a civil society is to be maintained.
 &HT;    
 c.2000 Jane Smiley 
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Jane Smiley is the author, most recently, of ``Horse Heaven,'' a
novel.) &QL;
<P>
   -----
</P>
