<HEADLINE>
$ADV07 
 THE WAY WE LIVE NOW
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Sunday, May 7, or thereafter.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following article from The New York Times
Magazine is for use by clients of the ``Centerpiece'' package.
Nonsubscribers can use these articles only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 By ALAN WOLFE 
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    America, no longer a nation of sheep, has entered the age of
autonomy. People are pretty much on their own when it comes to
finding a mate, rearing children, choosing a career or planning
retirement.
 &HT;    Deep inside, Americans are exploring a new frontier. Though they
still believe in God, uphold the family and love their country,
they increasingly decide which God best suits their temperament,
which family structure works for them and whether their country's
government is worthy of their trust.
 &HT;    In March, The New York Times Magazine conducted a poll that
asked Americans not about their party affiliations but about their
beliefs, fears, anxieties, fantasies and opinions. The results of
the poll demonstrate the degree to which Americans find themselves
falling back on their own resources when it comes to thinking about
the conditions for a good and meaningful life.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The Inner God
 &HT;    No one should ever underestimate Americans' faith in faith.
Despite a widely perceived trend toward secularization, 49 percent
of the respondents to the Times survey said they were about as
religious as their parents; 21 percent said they were more
religious.
 &HT;    But doctrinal disputes leave most people cold. Americans want a
capacious God who smiles on everyone, not a jealous God protective
of one particular version of his teachings.
 &HT;    Paradoxically, Americans have a specific distaste for the
theological doctrine that has informed our national morality from
the beginning: Puritanism. The Puritans believed in an inherent
human depravity that could be countered only by God's willingness
to extend, even arbitrarily, his grace.
 &HT;    Americans, though, are inveterate optimists; 75 percent believe
in the intrinsic goodness of people, which suggests, whether they
fully realize it or not, that they no longer subscribe to the
Judeo-Christian notion of original sin. Americans are simply too
nice to see Satan everywhere around them.
 &HT;    The niceness of Americans can drive thoughtful people to
distraction. Allan Bloom, the political philosopher whose life is
more or less at the center of Saul Bellow's new novel,
``Ravelstein,'' believed that the willingness of his students to
see good in everyone rendered them ``spiritually unclad,
unconnected, isolated, with no inherited or unconditional
connection with anything or anyone.''
 &HT;    Bloom was right to see a connection between a sunny temperament
and rootlessness. When people are responsible for shaping their
world, they learn that, since no one can credibly claim to have all
life's answers, it pays to treat everyone with respect.
 &HT;    But Bloom's observation also brings up the question: Would
America really be better off if its citizens were meaner? After
all, when we were more tightly connected by region, race and
religion, our conflicts were bloodier, our words harsher, our
politics more vituperative. Greater autonomy has not produced a war
of all against all. If niceness is the price we have to pay for
autonomy, we should consider ourselves doubly blessed.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Right and Wrong
 &HT;    Those who believe that we need a strong God fear that a people
unwilling to abide by his Commandments will live in a state of
moral relativism. If religious Commandments are understood to be
absolutes, their concerns would be justified. Fully 60 percent of
the survey's respondents said that lying is sometimes necessary to
protect another person's feelings, thereby contravening the
complete prohibition against lying laid down by the great Christian
theologian St. Augustine and the equally great Enlightenment
philosopher Immanuel Kant.
 &HT;    Just because Americans are suspicious of moral absolutes,
however, does not mean that they find no difference between right
and wrong. Ninety percent of those surveyed say they believe that
adults have a moral responsibility to care for their parents, and
84 percent claim that they have never cheated on their taxes.
 &HT;    That government collects enough money to function _ and that
elderly people are not sent out into the cold _ is because most
Americans believe in moral principles like paying one's fair share
or assuming the obligation to help those who once helped you.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Their Bodies, Themselves
 &HT;    There is a moral majority in America; it just happens to be
unwilling to follow anyone's party line about what morality ought
to be. Attitudes about sex confirm this. The efforts of novelists,
filmmakers and pharmaceutical companies notwithstanding, the poll's
respondents seem clear on this point: sex is not all that
interesting.
 &HT;    Ever since the 1960s, cultural radicals have argued that
political freedom leads to sexual freedom. At some level they are
correct, for autonomy will be taken by many to mean that their
bodies really are their own. Yet if America has become freer with
its sexuality, it also remains stubbornly conventional. In America,
the joys of family life outweigh the joys of sex; 63 percent of
those surveyed say they believe that people who have children lead
richer lives than those who do not.
 &HT;    In their own way, conservative attitudes toward sex and marriage
underscore, rather than undermine, the emergence of the age of
autonomy. An autonomous people unwilling to accept God's
Commandments as absolute is just as unwilling to accept the
libidinous definitions of sexuality offered on television.
 &HT;    Imagination seemed to be the domain of sexual freedom; 46
percent of the poll's respondents believe that it is OK to
fantasize about having sex with someone other than one's partner.
Infidelity of the mind compared with infidelity of the flesh, is
the kind of pragmatic compromise that makes sense to people who
respect autonomy while fearing unregulated sexuality.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The Place of Work
 &HT;    For all the talk of dot-com millionaires, Americans do not
understand themselves as workaholics. If they were suddenly given
three extra hours a day, most of them would spend it with their
families and friends rather than at work.
 &HT;    Money, to no one's surprise, does matter. Still, people do not
attribute their achievements to the money their parents had; they
also do not think that their money will be a significant
determinant of who their children will turn out to be.
 &HT;    The Times survey gives little support to the argument that
Americans, frustrated by the demands of family life, have turned to
the world of work for satisfaction. Time, career and financial
pressures cause far more stress than one's love life or family
demands.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Public and Private
 &HT;    Americans tend to be cynical about politicians, distrustful of
institutions and civically disengaged. Yet they trust their
spouses, love their children and feel good about themselves.
 &HT;    The public and the private constitute two entirely different
realms of life, one driven by suspicion, the other informed by
love. The same Americans who give to charity are more likely to
support welfare reform. People who disapprove of homosexuality will
respond with compassion when someone they know becomes
HIV-positive.
 &HT;    Let an issue be defined as a cause, and Americans, wary of the
impersonal and abstract, will turn their backs. Let it be defined
as a matter of friendship, family or faith, and they will act
generously.
 &HT;    What matters is whether the issue is viewed as public or
private. The public is what you have to do; the private is what you
want to do. To make the personal the political is to sacrifice the
very autonomy that makes personal life the refuge Americans believe
it has become.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Inner Differences
 &HT;    Autonomy means different things to different people. Black
Americans, the survey demonstrates, show less confidence that they
can be anything they want to be; are more likely than whites to
conclude that those who get to the top of American society are less
moral than others; and are more inclined than whites to believe
that race played a big role in making them who they are.
 &HT;    The wealthiest and most educated of the respondents find less
fault with unequal income distribution than the poorer and least
educated.
 &HT;    Women are more likely than men to think that cheating on taxes
is wrong, that taking care of elderly parents is right and that
there is something morally problematic about income inequality.
Thus, to the degree that there is a moral gap in America, it can
also be described as a gender gap.
 &HT;    On matters related to sex, America has a genuine two-party
system: one group of Americans thinks it is wrong to fantasize
about having sex with someone besides your partner, while another
group does not. What differentiates these groups is not religion
but religiosity.
 &HT;    On nearly all the questions asked by the Times survey, no
appreciable differences existed between Catholics and Protestants.
Yet major differences did exist between people who described
themselves as frequent church attendees and those who did not. It
is whether you believe, not what you believe, that counts. Though
both agree that people are inherently good.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The Risks of Autonomy
 &HT;    America is a harder country to govern in an age of autonomy. Its
inhabitants are increasingly unwilling to do things just because
someone in authority tells them they should. Everyone seems to have
an opinion on truths that were once considered self-evident. The
resulting turbulence is often too much for those who worry that
Americans, preoccupied with their own selfish concerns, do not
worry enough.
 &HT;    They fear that, especially during this golden age of prosperity,
people are paying too little attention to the poverty around them
or to the responsibilities the country must exercise toward the
world. Only when we face such catastrophes as depression and war,
the argument goes, do we seem capable of keeping our narcissistic
inclinations in check, as if worthy public lives were dependent on
tragic private ones.
 &HT;    Of those surveyed, 90 percent say that being an American is a
big part of who they are. That may well be because being an
American enables them to discover who they are.
 &HT;    People in Puritan America or Victorian England were instructed
in the proper way to live, often by those who could not live by the
rules they designed for others. Compared with those eras, the age
of autonomy is worth celebrating for the sense of freedom it
offers.
 &HT;    The age of autonomy should be embraced for another reason: its
optimistic theory of human nature makes more sense than the one it
replaced. Earlier worldviews in America argued that a strong God,
like a strong state, was necessary to keep weak people in line. But
Americans see themselves as capable of making their way in the
world without firm guidance from their moral superiors.
 &HT;    If the results of the Times survey are any indication, the age
of autonomy is not an age of anarchy. Americans are not out to
destroy the institutions and practices that make it possible for
them to live together in relative peace. Rather, they are engaged
in a process of rethinking what properly ought to be the concern of
others and what properly belongs to themselves.
 &HT;    In the mid-1800s, America was an overwhelmingly Christian
society in which morality was public while work and family were
private. Today, people choose their religions and shape their
moralities even as they can no longer shield their incomes, family
sizes or consumer preferences from inquisitive eyes. The less
privacy we have over the things that matter relatively little, the
more privacy we crave over the things that matter most.
 &HT;    Americans seem to recognize that the things that matter most
ought to matter to us all; 61 percent think that America was a
better place when people had stronger attachments and did not move
around so much. But they do seem to have gotten used to living less
confined lives.
 &HT;    Autonomy does raise the prospect of people too preoccupied with
their private selves to care much about the common good. But it
also challenges those who emphasize the importance of the common
good to take heed of what Americans find valuable about their way
of life.
 &HT;    The question is whether Americans can learn to use the autonomy
they have gained to strengthen the institutions that make civil
society possible. If they do not, this new age promises to be
unstable. But if they do, it will produce institutions from which
people will feel less need to escape _ in large measure because
institutions will not escape from them.
 &HT;    
 c.2000 Alan Wolfe 
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Alan Wolfe is the author of ``One Nation, After All,'' a watershed
in American public-opinion research.) &QL;
