<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6329 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN07-COX     05-05 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Never trust anything that doesn't have shoulders
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ Snakes alive. That's the problem.
</P>
<P>
   One of my long-gone predecessors at the newspaper often referred
to himself in his column as the ``Dead Snake Editor,'' because so
many readers would bring by snakes they had killed and ask to have
their photo made holding the dead snake. I have occasionally been
asked to do the same, especially while working at small weekly
newspapers. Some good ol' boy would bring a 7-foot rattlesnake to
the office and request his photo be made holding up the dead
creature as if he had bagged a trophy deer. Being as how most of
these men were built like brick outhouses, I would dutifully take
the photo and stick it in the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Then I started following editor Sam Malone's way of handling
this whole snake scenario. He told readers he was the ``Live Snake
Editor,'' and if you wanted your picture made with a snake, it had
to be brought in alive. This drastically cut the number of photo
requests. There aren't many people besides zookeepers and the
occasional member of one of those serpent-handling churches who are
willing to hold a live snake long enough for a photographer to get
the camera focused and the picture made.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not really scared of snakes, but I don't like them. I don't
trust any creature that doesn't have shoulders. I have had close
encounters with poisonous snakes: nearly stepping on a rattlesnake
once, having a water moccasin fall in a boat from a branch above as
we floated down a river, and finding a coral snake curled up on the
back porch. In all three cases, the snake lived and so did I.
</P>
<P>
   The rattlesnake slipped away, the water moccasin was pitched
into the water with the barrel of a shotgun, and the coral snake
was captured and set loose far in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   I don't like killing stuff. It's messy. That's why I don't hunt.
It's not a moral issue. I just like my meat pre-wrapped in
cellophane, and I am willing to pay someone else to do the dirty
work.
</P>
<P>
   But I will commit violence if I have to, and the other day a
snake left me no choice. My step-daughter and I were returning from
softball practice about dark. I pulled into the garage. As she
walked ahead, I grabbed her shoulder about two steps before she
would have stepped on a 6-foot-long snake curled up at the door
into the house.
</P>
<P>
   Next thing I know, the stepdaughter is perched on the roof of
the car, and I'm trying to herd the snake out of the garage and
head it in the direction of the woods.The snake did not appreciate
my prodding it with the handle of garden hoe and kept striking at
it and returning to the doormat. The kid had escaped out the garage
and through the front door, and now the entire family was gathered
on the safe side of the door into the house, listening to my
progress.
</P>
<P>
   I'm fairly certain this wasn't a poisonous snake, though the
light was bad and I couldn't remember the rhyme: Was it ``black and
yellow, kill a fellow?'' Or ``flat head, you're dead?'' The snake's
head seemed flat to me, and its coloring was brown and black, near
as I could tell in the dim light of the garage.
</P>
<P>
   Every time I tried to scoot the snake out the garage door, it
would hiss, strike at the hoe handle and get back in the corner. I
realized a hard truth. This snake was claiming the garage as its
new home, and even if he finally slithered out, he'd be back. (All
snakes are male, at least in print.) If I didn't kill him, I would
have to worry about stepping on a snake every time I walked out in
the garage. Worse, I would have to put up with paranoid children
and womenfolk worried about the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   So I dispatched the snake quickly with a machete. I'll spare the
gory details. Suffice it to say there was clean-up involved, which
further confirmed for me why I have no desire to kill things as a
pastime. Everyone is treading a bit cautiously outside, including
me.This snake may have a buddy who could return to the scene of the
crime. I'm wearing shoes outside all the time, just in case.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The (Nacogdoches, Texas)
Daily Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
