<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6347 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-AFRICA-HN     05-05 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-AFRICA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EXQUISITE CINEMATOGRAPHY SAVES THIS DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like many films based on autobiography, ``I Dreamed of Africa''
leans hard on circumstance. This happens. That happens. She gets in
a car crash. He gets hurt in a hunting accident. They get tracked
by lions. People die. People weep. Life goes on. And on. And on.
</P>
<P>
   Which isn't all bad: The folks in Hugh Hudson's beautiful,
stilted film lead an existence full of wild animals and wilder
vistas, and the fact that their travails are based in fact lends a
measure of dignity to their lives.
</P>
<P>
   That Kuki Gallmann's memoir of making it in the highlands of
Kenya never gets much beyond a photogenic travelogue isn't her
fault; life is episodic, and most of us don't find closure until we
croak. Gallmann didn't. Her story doesn't. It just ... winds ...
down.
</P>
<P>
   All the same, ``I Dreamed of Africa'' offers bursts of beauty
and emotion: Sections of it are actually quite touching, not to say
lachrymose, and Bernard Lutic's exquisite cinematography provides
visual drama on its own. At the very least, movies set in Africa
don't need bad guys: Any film in which pythons rank as harmless
pets has zoological menace to spare. Snakes are the least of their
worries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I Dreamed of Africa'' stars Kim Basinger in her first role
since winning the Oscar for ``L.A. Confidential,'' and she returns
to the screen with a stripped-down, tough-mother assurance. She
plays Kuki, the divorced Italian mom of 7-year-old Emanuele who
remarries following a horrific car accident.
</P>
<P>
   Her new husband, Paolo (Vincent Perez, ``Queen Margot''), is a
restless sort who longs to live in Africa. So off they go in their
bouncing Land Rover, navigating dirt tracks and herds of wildlife
(zebras, giraffes, et al) on the road to a dilapidated ranch amid
the soaring views of the jagged Kenyan landscape.
</P>
<P>
   After that, you can guess the plot. Kuki adjusts. Kuki gets
spooked by animals. Kuki learns that life ``has a different
rhythm'' here in Africa. Paolo, that restless guy, goes off on too
many hunting trips. Emanuele (played by two actors, Liam Aiken and
Garrett Strommen) collects snakes and gambols around the grounds
and grows up. Kuki speaks Swahili with a nearby chief. Stuff
happens.
</P>
<P>
   Basinger carries the film as well as she can, giving Kuki plenty
of smarts and pluck. Perez, the Swiss-born heartthrob best known
for his work in French films, adds his runway-chic brand of
virility; their scenes together are believably warm.
</P>
<P>
   The enduring Eva Marie Saint materializes now and then as Kuki's
mom, though her role never gets beyond the standard-issue
Perpetually Worried Mother. Her presence is one of many omens that
some characters are doomed to die. And we know which characters.
And we know how.
</P>
<P>
   Too much is telegraphed; too much of the film follows a
pedestrian course. Yet Hudson, whose small, pearl-like output began
with the radiant ``Chariots of Fire'' and yielded (most recently)
the compassionate and quirky ``My Life So Far,'' isn't a director
to play with narrative structure. His tales unfold with regularity
and emotion, captured in comely mise-en-scenes. None is comelier,
or more stubbornly incidental, than ``I Dreamed of Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 1244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6348 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-GLADIATOR     05-05 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-GLADIATOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WOW: ROCK `EM, SOCK `EM `GLADIATOR' WOOS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a word, wow.
</P>
<P>
   One word, one syllable, one slightly numb expression of
amazement mixed with awe. Wow. I could say more: I could (and will)
go on about the artistic vision, the grand scope, the spectacular
war scenes, the gut-churning gladiatorial combat, the molten star
turn by Russell Crowe, the computer-generated vistas of ancient
Rome and the moving, intelligent script.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, just one word will do in describing ``Gladiator,''
an epic of such emotive power and raw, thrashy action that it may
go down in history as the world's first bona-fide
bloodbath-tearjerker. ``Braveheart,'' another raucous war film,
offered up the hero as avenging husband; in ``Gladiator,'' the
avenging husband breaks down and sobs (snot, drool, saline, sweat,
the works) on the naked feet of his murdered son. Then he goes on
to slay one heavily armored behemoth after another.
</P>
<P>
   Wow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gladiator'' was directed by Ridley Scott, a renowned visual
stylist who knows how to make a movie look slick. His great films
(``Blade Runner''), his good films (``Thelma and Louise''), even
his lousy ones (``1492: Conquest of Paradise'') all bear the vivid
detail and composition of a trained painter's eye.
</P>
<P>
   Less often do his stories live up to his visuals, as though
Scott were more comfortable with the frou-frou of setting than he
is with character and plot. There are exceptions, ``Alien''
included. Count ``Gladiator'' among them.
</P>
<P>
   The action opens in 180 A.D., upon the final Germanic campaign
of the Emperor Marcus Aurelius (played by Richard Harris, who has
the same wispy mien as Alec Guinness' Marcus Aurelius in 1964's
``The Fall of the Roman Empire''). Leading the charge against the
Barbarians is General Maximus (Crowe), a stout-hearted soldier who
longs to rejoin his wife and son after three long years waging war.
</P>
<P>
   The gory opening battle sequence smacks of ``Braveheart'' _ big
bloody men with broadswords _ and establishes up front both Scott's
artistry and the breakneck pacing of the movie's action setpieces.
Much as Steven Spielberg did in ``Saving Private Ryan,'' Scott
plays with exposure and film speed to exaggerate the crashing mania
of men in mortal combat. The result wracks nerves and limbs in
equal measure.
</P>
<P>
   Maximus, played by Crowe with the brooding resolve (but not the
beer belly) he brought to ``The Insider,'' is a hero forged from
tragedy. When the ailing Marcus Aurelius tells Maximus he has
decided to appoint the general heir to the throne, Maximus freezes
_ Marcus Aurelius already has a son, the spooky, conniving Commodus
(Joaquin Phoenix). But the emperor persists: He wants Maximus to
use the powers of Caesar to dissolve the dictatorship and return
Rome to the Senate. Of Commodus, Marcus Aurelius says, ``He cannot
rule. He must not rule. You are the son I should have had.''
</P>
<P>
   Commodus himself isn't pleased with the arrangement, and after a
painful confrontation with dad _ one of the film's most
extraordinary and touching scenes _ he ensures that the transfer of
power to Maximus will never occur. Commodus' first acts as Emperor
are an order to kill the general, which fails miserably, and
another to kill the general's family, which doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Maximus, clawing his way home after a dramatic escape from the
woods of Germania, discovers his dead wife and boy. He collapses.
He's caught and chained as a slave. He's sold to Proximo (the late
Oliver Reed), a gladiator trainer. And so begins his new life in
the human cockfights of ancient Rome, a literal and figurative
arena in which Maximus hopes to enact his revenge upon the Emperor
Commodus.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, not much of this is new _ Roman-epic territory has been
covered often and well in ``Spartacus'' (1960), ``Ben-Hur'' (1959)
and sundry others, including the previously mentioned ``Fall of the
Roman Empire.'' Nor is Crowe's taciturn warrior much of a novelty:
the Man With No Name meets Mad Max in an iron breastplate. But the
brilliance of Scott's film is its epic ambition, its desire to go
beyond the big wows of spectacle and swordplay into much trickier
human ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gladiator'' never pretends to be history (the real Commodus
ruled for 12 years and wasn't quite the same ogre), but it does use
history to powerful effect. It's easy to imagine gladiators as
desperate and proud as these. It's easy to imagine an emperor as
scheming and starved for love.
</P>
<P>
   Crowe will probably get kicked straight to the A-list for his
work here, as well he should: Few actors can handle unironic
heroism with such gravity and slow-burn fire. But the rest of the
cast impresses as well, from Phoenix's shifty, immature, deeply
wounded Commodus to Connie Nielsen as Commodus' terrified sister,
Lucilla. Djimon Hounsou, unforgettable as the rebellious slave in
``Amistad,'' has a small part as a wise gladiator. And Derek Jacobi
pops up in full robes as a senator. (Rumor has it that DreamWorks
``grafted'' Reed's head onto a stand-in's body after the actor died
mid-shoot. If so, I saw no obvious evidence of it, but I will say
this: Oliver Reed's head delivers a terrific performance.)
</P>
<P>
   Beyond its first-rank thespians, perhaps the film's most welcome
element is its script, one of those rare committee screenplays (by
David ``Amistad'' Franzoni, John ``Any Given Sunday'' Logan and
William ``Shadowlands'' Nicholson) that doesn't wind up as a muddle
of bonehead-action cliches. When Commodus tells his father, ``I
would butcher the whole world if thou wouldst love me,'' you have
to admire his poetic urge. But worry thou not: Olde Englishe doth
not dominateth the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Visually, of course, ``Gladiator'' is a banquet. Anyone who can
stomach the gore ought to keep their eyes open (but their ears
shut: Hans Zimmer's blowhard score is the movie's only irritant),
and not only to best admire the gladiatorial pas-de-deux.
</P>
<P>
   Say what you will about artistic limitations in
computer-generated imagery, the film's sweeping shots of the great,
walled city and its thrumming inhabitants are cause enough for
slack-jaw. As Hounsou says upon seeing the Colosseum, ``I didn't
know men could build such things.'' Frankly, neither did we.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 1245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
