<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6361 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-CENSORSHIP-HNS &LR;      05-05 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CENSORSHIP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DEAR SENATOR: NO MORE RERUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TIM GOODMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   While you are quietly wondering how you'll live without
``Beverly Hills 90210'' or secretly hoping that ``Who Wants To Be a
Millionaire'' will go to seven days a week, there's been some
serious squabbling about television among lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   This happens quite a bit, actually. People get upset about
television in one way or another and they go cry to Congress.
Because it's not politically wise to be pro-choice when it comes to
letting people watch what they want _ this country has always been
about censoring television and movies, no matter what those famous
declarations say _ most politicians take these complaints
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. It's a win-win situation for either party:
``Violence on TV is bad! Racy TV shows are bad! Kids are killing
kids because of TV!'' On and on. Won't pass a handgun bill to save
their lives, but TV? That's a no-brainer for a crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   The current series of dust-ups in the Senate were started by the
Parents Television Council, an extremely conservative group with
former funnyman and current censorship goon Steve Allen as their
poster boy. They released a report last month that said sex,
violence and profanity have tripled on television in the last 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   And they want it stopped. Wah!
</P>
<P>
   What they have conveniently ignored is that their efforts _ and
those of religious and conservative groups before _ have already
resulted in the creation of the V-chip and ratings for TV shows.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently that's not good enough. It seems that parents aren't
really taking the time or showing an interest in checking out what
ratings shows get, then using the guidelines (as intended) to
shield the shows from their children (or themselves, who knows).
And the V-chip, mandatory in all new televisions and capable of
blocking out shows, is either too complicated to learn how to use
or the fight to get them installed took all their energy and now
they're simply too tired to screen anything, and that damned ``WWF
Smackdown!'' is ruining their family.
</P>
<P>
   Let's not forget that modern cable boxes are also capable of
channel-blocking. And then there's that foolproof innovation for
stopping unwanted programming: the off button on the remote. Or,
more extreme measures are available, like unplugging the TV set,
not putting a TV in a child's room or simply not owning one.
</P>
<P>
   That's a fairly exhaustive and effective list of ways to stop TV
from tainting families and rotting them to the core. But apparently
it's not enough. According to groups such as the Parents Television
Council, the government has way too much time on its hands and
needs to set up even more laws, more governmental controls, to keep
``smut'' from entering our living rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Thank God for the government. With any luck, one day you'll be
able to actually send your kid to them at age 2, and Uncle Sam and
all the congressional godmothers and fathers will watch over and
protect Little Billy until he's ready to come back home, at 18,
completely free of all that blue language on ``The Sopranos'' or
the sleazy content of Ricki Lake and her ilk.
</P>
<P>
   Until that program _ Raise Our Kids For Us _ is implemented,
apparently there will be much squawking from people who blame
television for everything. Frankly, this is exhausting for anyone
with a brain or good parenting skills. Here we are trying to figure
out those tricky tech stocks, working to improve local schools and
wondering how we'll get through gridlock traffic in time for that
lovely 9 p.m. dinner, and now there's an added worry that masses of
freedom-squelching fearmongers have invited a Big Brother mentality
to prevail upon us and ruin next season's ``Sex and the City''
episodes.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, these censorship flare-ups seem to happen more and more
frequently, necessitating a return rant that ultimately stops at
the same place, with the same argument: If you don't want your kids
watching ``bad'' television, then be a better parent. Vote with the
remote. Don't expect the government to raise your offspring. Use
the multitude of blocking techniques to censor your own family, not
your neighbor's family. Throw your TV out the window if you must,
but let us decide for ourselves what to watch.
</P>
<P>
   What's even more annoying than the utterly unsurprising,
repetitive nature of these calls for censorship, is the fact that
anyone in Congress even listens anymore. Why should the Parents
Television Council and other conservative pot-bangers get all the
attention and force all the stupid, ineffectual laws that now
control TV?
</P>
<P>
   Why can't ordinary people who love television make some changes
of their own?
</P>
<P>
   Why can't we bend the ears of people like Sen. Joseph I.
Lieberman, the Democrat from Connecticut who is always ranting
about TV content, or even Sen. John McCain, the Arizona Republican
who spent much of his time battling the TV industry before running
for president?
</P>
<P>
   Let's go to them with the same kind of moral outrage as the
conservative watchdogs who want to tell us what we can or can't see
on TV. Let's work up some anger and demand action on a number of
things that we think stink about TV.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a short list:
</P>
<P>
   _ No more wacky neighbors! That's such a hackneyed premise,
let's mandate it out of existence.
</P>
<P>
   _ We want 22 or 24 straight episodes _ no reruns!
</P>
<P>
   _ We've seen a dramatic increase in the last 10 years of
smart-ass kids and we've had enough. We want laws that say children
on television can't have all the answers, can't be smarmy and can't
act like they're 35.
</P>
<P>
   _ Commercials are too loud! We want a mandatory device in all
televisions that automatically lowers the grating voice of TV
announcers when hawking products.
</P>
<P>
   _ We will go to advertisers and demand that they pull
advertising from networks that don't send us free popcorn!
</P>
<P>
   Righteous indignation shouldn't be reserved for those people
with closed minds and petty First Amendment objections. Maybe this
is the answer. Fight stupidity with equal, but more amusing,
stupidity. And perhaps politicians used to knee-jerk reactions
meant to mollify the very loud will feel abused, as they should,
and tell everyone to go home and get a life.
</P>
<P>
   And once there, watch TV if they so desire.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
