<HEADER>
A6369 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-05 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FAT IS ONLY IN THE EYE OF THE BEHOLDER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Just when people start telling me I'm losing
weight, I find out I also may lose my protected status. San
Francisco is banning discrimination against fat people, and I don't
know if I'm one of them.
</P>
<P>
   According to my wife, I'm fat. Maybe I'll hire that Sock
Puppet's lawyer and sue her skinny butt.
</P>
<P>
   According to my mirror, I'm average, middle-sized and not all
that bad looking in the right light. I can't sue anybody looking
like this, so there's only one thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   I'm forming the California Association of the Not So Bad,
Average and Mediocre (CANSBAM), and we're putting on our Hush
Puppies and tassel loafers and marching on the San Francisco Board
of Supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   We demand our right to remain the way we are, and we're not just
talking about our weight _ which isn't all that much with our shoes
off.
</P>
<P>
   The average rule. Mediocrity is a way of fitting in. Ordinary is
underrated. The median is the message.
</P>
<P>
   As Sen. Roman Hruska said when Nixon wanted to appoint Harold
Carswell to the Supreme Court, ``The mediocre deserve
representation too.''
</P>
<P>
   They sure get it on the San Francisco Board of Supervisors, but
somehow the board hasn't voted to protect its own interests.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean to trivialize the problems of fat people, because
they're my problems too, at least according to the one nearest and
dearest to my cholesterol-speckled heart.
</P>
<P>
   But what do you expect? As an average San Francisco scribbler
feeling a little below average this week, the Board of Supervisors
presented me with a topic too hard to resist.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the supervisors have voted to protect tropical
hardwoods, the Burmese people and San Francisco's two daily
newspapers, and look at all the good that's done.
</P>
<P>
   Now the supervisors want to protect the fat, but if I were fat
(and my wife thinks I am) I wouldn't expect much.
</P>
<P>
   You'll still be treated poorly at work, if you can get a job.
But nobody will tell you that you're overweight, just that you're
underqualified.
</P>
<P>
   You'll still get lousy tables in restaurants. You'll still be
jammed into airline seats that are too small for you.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, we average people are jammed into airline seats that
are too small for us, so we know what you're up against. When you
sit next to us, we really know what you're up against. Us. And it
isn't your fault.
</P>
<P>
   My larger friends and relatives have told me about the reproving
or disgusted looks they get from the thin. I know thin people even
say rude things about heavy people's weight.
</P>
<P>
   I know a little about how that hurts, because I get those
comments from a thin person who lives in my own home, and I'm not
even chunkily challenged, when I suck it in.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you'll still be ridiculed, and with fake politically
correct phrases like ``the big and proud'' or ``the
other-metabolismed.'' Language reform hasn't led to thought reform,
just more ways to insult people.
</P>
<P>
   Stick with ``fat,'' and don't worry about the idiots who stare
or call you names. Just worry about your health.
</P>
<P>
   Being average and ignored has its down sides, too, although
nobody listens when you protest about it.
</P>
<P>
   Stigma has a way of sticking around, and human resources
departments find new ways to tell you they're sorry, but you're not
the right fit for the job. What liberation movements do first is
change the attitudes of those being liberated, and that eventually
starts changing others' attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   No, wait. What happens first is that the Board of Supervisors
passes a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The time will come when making jokes about fat people will be
just as unacceptable as making jokes about women, gays, people of
other races, blondes, priests and rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't all that encouraging a thought, is it? The
supervisors aren't making as much headway against intolerance as
they'd like.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco already bans discrimination in housing, employment
and accommodations on the basis of race, religion, age, gender
identity, disability and place of birth.
</P>
<P>
   That's a good thing, but most of those are readily defined
categories. If the city ends up banning discrimination against the
fat, someone is going to have to pull out those depressing ideal
height and weight charts you always see in magazines.
</P>
<P>
   They're always so different, and they always tell me that at my
weight I'm 7 feet tall. So maybe it's good that height also is
being added to the list of protected characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   But I know what I am, average, ordinary and not so bad. In San
Francisco, people like that are often treated as if they are
subhuman, or from Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   We need protection from discrimination, too, even if we are an
unspecial interest group.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
