<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKET ATTACKS CONTINUE ALONG ISRAEL-LEBANON BORDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By DANIEL J. WAKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lebanese guerrillas and the Israeli military traded rocket fire
and air strikes Friday in their worst fighting in nearly a year,
prompting immediate concern and calls for calm from Britain, France
and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides sounded defiant. But later in the day, the Israeli
Cabinet decided against further retaliatory strikes because no one
had died or been seriously injured in Friday's attacks, Israeli
television reported.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks, which have escalated since Wednesday, have jarred
the region as Israel's July 7 deadline for a withdrawal from its
self-declared buffer zone in south Lebanon approaches.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting was the worst since June, when Israeli strikes
caused severe damage in Lebanon and killed eight civilians.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest attack, the Shiite Muslim guerrillas of Hezbollah
fired a barrage of rockets at the northern Israeli border town of
Kiryat Shemona. Residents had just begun emerging from shelters
after another barrage on Thursday, and the streets were crowded
with shoppers for the Jewish Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   One Israeli soldier was wounded by shrapnel, Israel Radio said,
raising the toll in the two days of rocket attacks to one soldier
killed and five people wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The Hezbollah, or Party of God, which is trying to dislodge
Israeli troops and their allies from southern Lebanon, launched its
hour-long attack on Kiryat Shemona and another settlement in
response to Israeli air strikes on Lebanon early Friday morning.
Those Israeli strikes, in turn, were retaliation for a guerrilla
attack on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli warplanes bombarded two power stations and a guerrilla
arms depot. Large areas were plunged into darkness, and power was
cut to Tripoli, Lebanon's second-largest city. The blasts rattled a
northern suburb of Beirut, where a major power substation is
located. A strike also blew open a crater in the Beirut-Damascus
highway.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, after visiting Kiryat Shemona
Friday, justified the attack, telling reporters, ``No country can
accept its residents being targeted by bombs and make no
response.'' Barak has been under pressure from right-wing leaders
and some northern Israeli community leaders to order an immediate,
large-scale bombardment of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement about its attacks released in Beirut, Hezbollah
said: ``We are firm today to defend our people, our country and the
infrastructure. So we fired barrages on Kiryat Shemona and Shlomi
settlements. We warn the Zionist enemy against continuing in the
rape of Lebanon, because we are going to respond and confront it.''
</P>
<P>
   A special envoy of the U.N. secretary-general, Terje
Roed-Larsen, was in Lebanon to discuss Israel's promised pull-out
after 22 years in southern Lebanon. ``Any attacks against any
civilians are unacceptable,'' he said. ``Such actions are
particularly unhelpful at the present time.''
</P>
<P>
   France called for an early meeting of an international
monitoring committee for south Lebanon, which it and the United
States chair. The British foreign office appealed for restraint on
both sides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
