<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-HOUSING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     REPORTS SAYS HOMES LESS AFFORDABLE IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RICHARD PAOLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco is the least affordable county in
California for homebuyers, according to a real estate association
survey.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterly affordability index, released by the California
Association of Realtors, compares median household income with
median home prices. Its percentile results show what portion of
wage earners at the median income level can afford to buy a home in
various counties.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, where the median income is $72,400 and the
median home price is $420,000, the affordability index is 12
percent, according to the survey. A year ago, it was 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The statewide level of 31 percent is the lowest in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time housing affordability was this low was in June
1992, when it was 30 percent,'' said Richard F. Gaylord,
association president. ``The median price of a home, which rose to
an all-time high of $238,870 in March, coupled with rising mortgage
interest rates, is putting home ownership out of reach for many
families in California.''
</P>
<P>
   Also at the bottom of the affordability index are two other Bay
Area counties _ Contra Costa and San Mateo _ both ranked at 13
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Southern California, San Diego County was the least
affordable, at 25 percent, followed by Orange County at 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles County, affordability was 37 percent. Ventura
County had an affordability index of 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The best chance of affording a house is in the state's high
desert region, northeast of Los Angeles, where the affordability
index was 72 percent.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Supervisor Mabel Teng, who heads the Board of
Supervisors' housing and social policy committee, said creating
more ways for first-time buyers to be able to afford mortgages and
finding ways to build moderate-rent apartments, are vital to
maintaining housing stock in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got to preserve housing and rental stock because we
can't stop the increase in real estate prices. At the same time, we
have to expand the opportunities for affordable housing for the
first time buyer.''
</P>
<P>
   What Teng proposes is using a $100 million bond measure ``to
leverage even more money'' from the city and banks for first-time
buyers to tap for mortgages and to finance construction or
rehabilitation of buildings for rentals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
