</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARMERS-MUSEUM-$ADV07-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HANDS-ON FARMERS' MUSEUM OFFERS ESCAPE FROM THE WIRED WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, May 7)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ High-speed computers and electronics can
bring the world to your fingertips. But a visit to the Farmers'
Museum in Cooperstown can take you back in time to rural
19th-century America, where life was a hands-on experience. Here
you can discover the tradespeople who practice crafts of the 1800s.
</P>
<P>
   At the American Paper-Staining Manufactory, master wallpaper
printer Wendy Weeks makes wallpaper by hand on the only working
press of its kind in North America, dating to the 1830s.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the Farmers' Museum became the first
manufacturer of documented reproduction early 19th-century
wallpaper.
</P>
<P>
   The wallpapers, featuring patterns borrowed from the collections
of American museums and historic sites, are thoroughly researched
and are made using authentic distemper paint formulated by hand at
the manufactory from chalk, pigment, water and historic tools.
</P>
<P>
   Color variations are made only for documented colors, Weeks
said.
</P>
<P>
   The toughest part of the job is the research, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Records were not often kept back then, like they are today,''
Weeks said. ``Also, a lot of craftsmen keep what they did a trade
secret, keeping it all in their heads and never writing any of it
down. This is a constant process of trial-and-error and dedicated
research.''
</P>
<P>
   Weeks went to France for much of the research. She said Chris
Ohrstrom, a paint and wallpaper researcher, and Don Carpentier, a
craftsman and architectural historian, were the driving forces
behind the Farmers' Museum program.
</P>
<P>
   A pagoda pattern found at the Marblehead Historical Society in
Massachusetts that came from the Jeremiah Lee mansion in Marblehead
was reproduced by Weeks for an upstairs bedroom in the Payton
Randolph House at Colonial Williamsburg. Weeks has also made
wallpaper for the Carlyle House Historical Park in Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``Commissions take about 18 months to complete,'' Weeks said
during a recent demonstration. ``Although we don't have the ability
to mass-produce historic wallpapers for sale, we will do our best
to replicate a damaged pattern or for a specific historic
commission. In this way, we also learn about the printing process
for yet another historic pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   The 23-inch-wide wallpapers made at the manufactory are made in
18-foot lengths of handmade cotton fiber paper, half the length of
the standard English papers. The room in a converted creamery on
the museum property where the paper is made is only 20 feet long,
so the length of the rolls is limited.
</P>
<P>
   A two-color roll costs $160 and will cover 34.5 square feet.
Weeks said the price is based on the printing design block, which
costs about $1,000 to make, plus materials and labor.
</P>
<P>
   In the labor-intensive process, the lengths of the handmade
cotton rag paper are first joined by animal hide glue and polished
with a smooth stone to seal the seams, to form a roll of wallpaper,
standard practice in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   The roll of paper is then placed on a long table to be painted
with a base color of distemper. For health and safety reasons, the
museum uses substitutions for highly toxic compounds used in early
American pigments, while maintaining accurate color.
</P>
<P>
   Base color is applied in a traditional manner using a two-knot
natural bristle brush, which looks like two mid-size brushes
clamped together side-by-side in one grip. This creates the same
hand-rendered irregularity characteristic of the work of early
paper.
</P>
<P>
   After the base color is dry, the papers are imprinted with
hand-held pattern blocks on a facsimile press and water-box inking
sieve that are accurate scale copies of the originals.
</P>
<P>
   An artist draws the patterns for the blocks from the original
paper design, Weeks said. ``We use end grain for delicate work,
because when the design is carved that way, it doesn't chip as
easily,'' she said. The face of the block is then soaked in water
so that the paint isn't absorbed and will release onto the paper
easily.
</P>
<P>
   Every engraved pattern block is made from two to three layers of
hardwood, that are glued in a crisscrossed fashion, to prevent
warping and to hold up under the pressure of the printing process.
When printing the design repeat, the block is precisely placed on
the paper, matching it up to registration marks. A large, long
wooden lever is lowered on the block to ensure an even transfer of
paint from the block's surface.
</P>
<P>
   This process is repeated along the length and width of the paper
for as many colors and design elements as required, with a drying
time in between each new color.
</P>
<P>
   Because the distemper paint is water-based, the papers cannot be
washed. Sealer can be used over the paper once it is installed.
</P>
<P>
   The most difficult reproduction to date for the Farmers' Museum
was a French pattern featuring 10 colors and 27 blocks. Weeks and
her assistants made 65 rolls for a private historic home in
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Historic reproduction handmade papers dating from 1790 to 1835
are also used to cover handmade one-of-a-kind bandboxes, which are
sold in the museum's General Store.
</P>
<P>
   The bandboxes, which are made in the manufactory, come in five
different patterns (using four-block patterns and four-block border
patterns) and five oval sizes ranging in price from $25 to $50.
</P>
<P>
   Bandboxes were very popular in the United States between 1820
and 1845, when travelers used them to carry accessories such as
hats, trinkets and shirt collars.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the days prior to cardboard boxes and plastic containers,
these decorative boxes were also used to store items at home,''
said Weeks. ``These colorful containers were produced in a variety
of shapes and sizes and were often sold in `nests' of three or
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Early bandboxes were made by individual craftsmen and women, as
well as wallpaper manufacturers and hangers, to use up wallpaper
remnants.
</P>
<P>
   Historic bandboxes were covered with trimmed repeating sidewall
or wide border papers, Weeks explained. Single, repeating scenes
were developed specifically for use on bandboxes by 1830. Popular
themes included mythology, patriotism and national or natural
history.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the stacking set of five bandboxes, the
manufactory has begun a Special Series Collector's Box, featuring a
single repeat scene. The Squirrel Box, a scene pattern set on a
blue or yellow background, is from the collection of the New York
State Historical Association dating from 1830.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, the museum will launch the second bandbox in the
series,
</P>
<P>
   ``Clayton's Ascent.'' The scene commemorates the record-breaking
350-mile hot-air balloon ride, from Cincinnati to western Virginia,
made by Richard Clayton on April 8, 1835. It has been reproduced in
its original colors. Clayton's balloon was elaborately decorated by
Jean-Baptiste Reveillon, an unrivaled French paper-stainer.
</P>
<P>
   Each bandbox begins with a wooden template, which is used for
cutting pieces of acid-free rag board. The acid-free boxboard
ensures that the handmade wallpaper will not discolor or be
degraded by wood fiber acid. The pre-cut sections of rag board are
hand sewn into their oval shape with linen thread, then precisely
fitted with a finished wallpaper, which is glued in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boxes are lined with newspaper hand-printed on foolscap (a
forerunner of today's newsprint) on an early 19th-century
letterpress in the print shop building here on the grounds of the
Farmers' Museum,'' Weeks said. The newspaper lining is a
reproduction of broadsheets from Cooperstown's local weekly
newspaper, The Freeman's Journal. Each box is finished with an
American Paper-Staining Manufactory label.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
