A6464 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-BASKET-HN     05-05 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-BASKET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `BASKET' LACKS A FULL-COURT PRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WALTER ADDIEGO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With its mild anti-war/anti-discrimination message and upbeat
David-and-Goliath climax, ``The Basket'' scores a few points as a
well-intentioned, nicely shot family film. As a history lesson
about rural America during World War I, it's earnest and
kid-friendly _ also simplistic and dramatically creaky.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers were likely inspired by Michael Anspaugh's
``Hoosiers,'' with its theme of an outsider using basketball to
bring needed change to a close-knit and troubled community. In
``The Basket,'' the setting is the wheat-farming town of
Waterville, Wash., in 1918. The outsider is teacher Martin Conlon
(Peter Coyote), a Bostonian with cosmopolitan views and a working
knowledge of the then-young game of basketball, which he learned
directly from its inventor, James Naismith.
</P>
<P>
   Also newly arrived are two young German orphans (Robert Karl
Burke and Amber Willenborg). It's a scary time for them: America is
at war with their homeland, and a local boy has returned badly
wounded from the conflict. Tensions are also high because the town
is struggling economically. The Germans become targets for bullying
and general ill will.
</P>
<P>
   The town is clearly in need of spiritual doctoring, so the
teacher begins punctuating classroom lessons with opera excerpts
that pique the interest of all but the most biased _ it's a German
opera (created for the film, by the way). Director Rich Cowan
offers a running joke in which the townspeople catch each other up
on plot developments of this elaborate work, which has violence and
sexual intrigue but also an unsubtle message. ``It's a story about
what war does to all of us,'' Conlon says.
</P>
<P>
   He also tries to build esprit de corps by introducing his
students to basketball. The game is new enough that players are
called ``goal-tossers'' and the hoop is a fruit basket. His methods
earn the hostility of the wounded boy's father (Jock MacDonald), an
angry, rigid farmer, but win sympathy from the farmer's wife (Karen
Allen, a welcome presence who deserves a more complex role).
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Conlon wins everyone's support by offering to coach
the local hoopsters in a match against an experienced team from
Spokane, in hopes of winning funds for a new harvester to be shared
by the hard-pressed farmers. Late in the day, a few surprises are
tossed in about Conlon's background, but they finally feel like
heavy-handed attempts to flesh out the character.
</P>
<P>
   The story is worked out schematically in the style of television
movies and Saturday-afternoon specials, but the sincerity of the
filmmakers, the generosity of their message and the overall decent
performances make partial amends for the hokiness and shortcomings
in the plot and characterizations.
</P>
<P>
   Cinematographer Dan Heigh does a creditable job of capturing the
isolation and stark beauty of the wheat fields, creating images of
hard-times farm life that are haunting enough to give the picture
some illusion of depth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
