<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6467 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-ETIQUETTE-SCHOOLS-ART     05-05 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETIQUETTE-SCHOOLS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 ETIQUETTE CLASSES SEEK TO INSTILL OLD-TIME VALUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUINCY, Mass. _ It is time for Judi Vankevich's manners class,
and the students file in and take their seats. Vankevich, who
believes in setting a good example, is making eye contact with
every student and saying thank you to everyone for coming.
</P>
<P>
   On today's schedule is how to behave at your own birthday party.
Vankevich poses a hypothetical question. What if you open a present
and discover you have the exact same toy already?
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you say, `This is dumb, I have one?' '' she asks the 11
students, ages 3 to 11, in mock horror.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you don't. ``You say, `This is soooo great, I love
it.' '' Next lesson: How to clap your hands the right way and
return things after you've borrowed them.
</P>
<P>
   A generation ago, a class like this would have been
unimaginable. But that was before the concept of dignified behavior
became hopelessly retro, before the days of children neglecting to
thank their grandparents for Christmas gifts and showing up in
school in belly shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in response to a growing sense of horror among parents and
educators over the pervasive boorishness of young people in public
settings, classes like Vankevich's are springing up around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The curriculum goes far beyond table settings and thank-yous and
takes a page out of the old schools of decorum and comportment,
extending even into the self-esteem movement. The classes stress
such values as respect, empathy, and self-confidence. They
emphasize life skills not measurable by any MCAS tests, but vital,
the instructors maintain, if America isn't going to unravel in the
next generation into a sort of social anarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Vankevich's four-week class in her living room, are
no-frills grass-roots efforts aimed, she says, at redressing the
fact that ``social IQ is very low today.'' A vivacious mother of
three and a former Paris fashion model, Vankevich, 38, teaches what
she thinks of as ``survival skills'' to children and teens because
of her concern about proper character development of American
children.
</P>
<P>
   At its most mundane manifestation, she says, poor manners mean
not bothering to take a phone message for Mom and Dad. At its most
troublesome, it's the trend toward violence in public schools. But
the common denominator is the decline in ``honesty and respect''
among youth today.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the keyword in her class _ repeated in Vankevich-written
rap songs and printed on handwritten laminated posters _ is
``honor,'' which she always enunciates as ``awe-ner,'' ``so they
feel a sense of awe in the word.''
</P>
<P>
   Honor your parents by coming when they call you. Honor your
friends by looking them in the eye when you thank them for the
birthday gift. Honor your table companions by not eating mashed
potatoes with your fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the more subtle, finer points. Never shake hands
like a ``dead fish.'' Look the person in the eye and shake hands
firmly. When you are thanking a relative for a gift of money,
``never say how much she sent you, because it's not important.
What's important is that she gave it to you with lots of love.''
There is a right way and a wrong way to interrupt your mother when
she's talking to someone else. (The right way is to put your hand
in her lap or on her arm to get her attention, and wait until she's
done.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I want this to be like an old-fashioned finishing school,''
Vankevich says.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Jojin, an elementary school principal in Connecticut,
emphasizes etiquette and manners because she wants it to be more
like an old-fashioned classical school.
</P>
<P>
   Jojin, who oversees the Norfeldt Classical Magnet School in West
Hartford, brings in guest speakers who discuss civility, lectures
students and staff on the importance of basic etiquette, and
sponsors a monthly musical ``classical cafe,'' where she stands at
the door in white gloves, greeting students in a receiving line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect good eye focus and a good handshake,'' she says. ``It
sounds so mundane, but it is really forgotten in so many homes. I
think these are life skills, and we need to bring them back. This
is so important for children's development. It directly reflects
back on their self-esteem and gives them the feedback that we are a
civilized world. When you read in magazines that there are
high-level executives who have to learn how to eat properly and the
art of conversation, it is scary to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sue Fox, author of ``Etiquette for Dummies'' (IDG Books
Worldwide, 1999) and president of the California-based Etiquette
Survival Inc., oversees consultants who run social etiquette
workshops in schools and other venues. Etiquette expert Dana May
Casperson of Santa Rosa, Calif., author of ``Power Etiquette: What
You Don't Know Can Kill Your Career,'' (Amacom, 1999) has developed
a program for Brownies troops culminating in a manners badge for
graduates.
</P>
<P>
   She has also taught manners courses in public schools and has
had ``teachers pay me out of their own salaries'' because they are
so desperate to have children improve their manners. ``They see
these kids every day,'' she says. ``Things have deteriorated
terribly. We have parents who don't know the rules either. They
were the '60s `me' generation that rebelled against tradition. Now
they're trying to establish authority with their children.''
</P>
<P>
   The big question is: Is it too late for things to change,
especially in a world where human contact is minimized by answering
machines and computers, where social decorum is considered alien,
if not out-and-out geeky, or where children address grown-ups by
their first names and using ``Mr.'' and ``Mrs.'' seems like a
peculiar anachronism?
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is optimistic, including James B. Twitchell, author
of ``For Shame: The Loss of Common Decency in America'' (St.
Martin's Press, 1997) and a professor of English at the University
of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any redressing of it,'' he says. ``Look at what
adults are inflicting on each other, such as using the cellphone
while we are on the train sitting next to someone. That's as
egregious a violation as when junior refuses to acknowledge an
elder.''
</P>
<P>
   But many parents are hopeful, including the ones bringing their
children to Judi Vankevich's class. ``I'm so excited about the
concept,'' says Debbie Toomey, a nurse whose 6-year-old son,
Phillip, comes to manners class. ``My husband and I feel it's
important for our boys to be healthy and into academics and sports,
but it is also important for them to have manners because, these
days, it is those people who stand out in a crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Her son ``loves the class,'' she says. ``He practices at home
and corrects me, at times.''
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Murphy, 11, loves it, too. She thinks her manners are
pretty good, in general, but the class ``reinforced'' some of the
basics, such as how to set a table.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to go home, but she hasn't forgotten her manners.
``Thank you for interviewing me,'' Jessica says politely, extending
a hand and shaking it firmly. ``It was nice to meet you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
