<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SHORTAGE OF GOSSIP AT YALE REUNION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The World's Second Greatest University is much on my mind as I
prepare for my 25th Yale reunion later this month. I wonder if true
Blue Henry Becton, top dog at WGBH, will be with his class? I'd
like to congratulate him on surviving Monicagate. I refer to Boston
Herald writer Monica Collins' revelations of trumpery and fraud in
'GBH's wildly successful ``Antiques Roadshow'' program. This is the
third time in two years Henry has weathered a major public
relations debacle _ good show! But I digress.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, all is not well at W2GU. President Richard Levin has
announced the first convocation of the University Tribunal for the
purpose of stripping a faculty member's tenure. The teacher in
question is Antonio Lasaga, a geochemist and the former master of
Saybrook College. Lasaga will be sentenced later this month on
federal child pornography charges, and is also facing trial for
sexual assault in state court. He has been on leave _ Yale won't
say if he's being paid _ ever since his arrest in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, it's a big deal when a major university moves
to strip a faculty member of tenure. Lasaga has the right to choose
a Yale Law School professor to mount a defense before the tribunal,
and I'm told that he will do so. But losing his livelihood is less
important than losing his freedom, which will probably happen on
May 22. Sentencing guidelines for his crime call for a minimum 11
years in jail.
</P>
<P>
   In a less somber case, Yale students have been rallying to
protest the firing of popular history professor Lee Blackwood,
whose contract was not renewed. The reasons given, according to the
Yale Daily News, were faculty ``concern over his dissertation's
lack of promise as a book and over his professional service to the
department and the University.'' But even Blackwood allows that his
irreverent, occasionally bizarre behavior contributed to his
downfall.
</P>
<P>
   At the peak of hostilities between himself and the history
department graybeards, he delivered a lecture on decolonization as
``Leeanne Blackwood,'' while wearing lipstick and a dress. ``Some
of my colleagues insist in calling me a wacko,'' he told his
students. ``I think that this will give them something more
substantive to address.'' ``People had started to question my
sanity in a very vicious way,'' is how Blackwood explained his
action to me. While he is pursuing an appeal of his contract
termination, he is also considering alternative employment. ``This
whole affair has made me reconsider whether I want to be an
academic,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Traveler Reports
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hilarious but unreliable Taki Theodoracopulos contributes an
amusing account of his recent visit to Boston in the April 22
London Spectator. (An issue also distinguished by scientific proof
of Jesus' ascension into heaven, attributed to unusual combinations
of thermal updrafts in the Middle East 2000 years ago.) Taki was a
guest of Boston University's Claudio Veliz, who organizes the
unintentionially comic ``Conversazioni,'' ponderous group
discussions peopled by self-styled illuminati, like _ gasp _
Supreme Court justice Stephen Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   No trip to Veliz-land is complete without an homage to the Great
Dictator, Augusto Pinochet, whom the courtly Chilean expat has
saluted at previous meetings. (TGIF, Dec. 4, 1998) So Taki was
treated to ``a video of the Chilean armed forces parading on 19
September, the national day, and saluting the greatest of them all,
General Augusto Pinochet.'' What fun! Taki then heaps praise on the
BU wine cellars and his hosts: ``The chancellor, John Silber, and
the president, Jon Westling, were delightful fellows, and they've
done a hell of a job recruiting some very good people.'' The only
example Taki comes up with is right-wing crackpot Joachim Maitre,
whose name the peripatetic hack misspells, a mistake perhaps
attributable to weekly deadline pressure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Surf's Up!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even though he went to Yale _ and played football, no less _ I
love Elisha Cooper's watercolor travel books. He's an old-fashioned
writer/painter/explorer who sketches and comments on the
new-fashioned world. He did ``A Year in New York,'' moved to
Berkeley, and has now produced ``California.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent a year driving around the state and went to some
pretty cool places,'' Cooper reports on his Web site,
elishacooper.com, including ``Yahoo, the Castro, Chez Panisse, a
Fresno cattle ranch, a Silicon Valley startup, the big wave spot
Mavericks.'' He looks in on the West's Greatest University _ ``At
first I mistake Stanford for a corporate headquarters . . . you can
almost smell the endowment'' _ and even attends a Jerry Brown
morning clergy breakfast. Oakland mayor Brown on the subject of
change: ``It's no time to cool off. It's no time for `the
intoxicating drug of gradualism.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
