<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-VILLA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`UP AT THE VILLA' EVOKES '30S ITALY WITH STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
UP AT THE VILLA 
Directed by: Philip Haas 
Screenplay by: Belinda Haas (novella: W. Somerset Maugham) 
Starring: Kristin Scott Thomas, Sean Penn, Anne Bancroft, James
Fox, Jeremy Davies, Derek Jacobi, Massimo Ghini 
Running time: 115 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (thematic elements) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Up at the Villa,'' which traverses the same shaky upper-crust
ground as ``Tea with Mussolini,'' has a rueful worldliness that the
earlier film, entertaining as it was, lacked. Which is another way
of saying that the husband-and-wife filmmaking team of Philip and
Belinda Haas has succeeded in transferring to the screen the
brittle, acerbic tone of W. Somerset Maugham. More important, they
also nail the more elusive romanticism beneath Maugham's world
view, heavy-laden with experience, more familiar than it wanted to
be about betrayals.
</P>
<P>
   As a genteel but impoverished British widow residing at a
borrowed villa on the outskirts of Florence in 1938, Kristin Scott
Thomas rights herself nicely after the faltering ``Random Hearts.''
Which is to say she projects an almost gallant poise as a woman
betwixt and between. Hers is a life up for grabs, as, indeed, she
herself is. The question is whether she'll do the sensible thing
and opt for security by marrying James Fox's career diplomat, who
has known her for many years, or take a flyer with Sean Penn's idle
but appealingly dangerous ne'er-do-well.
</P>
<P>
   While Scott Thomas delivers the kind of idiomatic performance we
expect of her, and Anne Bancroft has a field day with the role of
an imperious American principessa by marriage, sending wave after
wave of charm and shrewdness curling over the film like surf, it's
Penn who proves the bonus here. Although he remains the best actor
of his generation, and nothing he encompasses is surprising, it's
just that we've never seen him do one of these between-the-wars
dinner-jacket roles. Projecting savvy and a confidence that always
stays controlled, his disreputable American here is Bogart-worthy _
cynical yet capable of generosity.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thomas convinces us she feels an inner turmoil at doing
the sensible thing. It's almost as if we can hear heavy iron gates
clang shut in her mind at the thought of marrying the kindly but
dull diplomat. Maugham had a way of keeping the possibility of
romance alive even though he also made clear that he was convinced
it usually would lead to disaster. It's a conflict kept very much
alive here, nudged in the direction of romance, intensified by
collective uneasiness arising from the political storm about to
break.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst here is a desperate Austrian refugee (Jeremy
Davies) who mistakes a night of charity sex with Scott Thomas as
something more and commits suicide in her bedroom after returning
the next night and being told he has no future with her. Since she
can't call on any of her respectable friends for help, she calls
upon Penn's suave lounge lizard, who she turned down the night
before in the film's best scene. The offhandedness with which he
implicates himself by becoming an accessory impresses her as none
of his smooth moves did.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the romantic in Maugham assumes that getting rid of a
corpse is the sort of thing that brings people closer, especially
as the fascist blackshirts are beginning to crack down on hitherto
cossetted foreigners. Massimo Ghini is the fascist heavy here,
leaning ever more crudely on all of them. And Derek Jacobi's
remittance man, known _ and ostracized _ by all, neatly personifies
the effeteness of the English who were about to find out just how
powerless they were.
</P>
<P>
   There's no tea here, but plenty of Mussolini, at least as an
ominous presence in Rome. ``Up at the Villa'' is a chamber romance,
in that there's nothing grand or sweeping about it, but it's got
all the style it needs to go with those glorious Tuscan settings.
The latter, incidentally, are more than backdrops. Between the
imposing classical structures and the steamrolling designs of the
fascist buildings, you can almost see why the Axis powers thought
they couldn't lose World War II. How could they? They had the
architecture, didn't they?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
