<HEADER>
A6486 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-05 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THROWN FOR A LOSS AT FENWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It is a moment both simple and glorious. Rob Barry
cocks his legendary right arm. He makes his throw. The bag of
peanuts soars purposefully through the perfumed air of Fenway Park,
the plastic wrapper glinting in the stadium lights above.
</P>
<P>
   Thoughts, conversations, indeed, all of life, seem suspended
during this splendid flight. Fans, their mouths agape, stare upward
in shock. Grown men point toward the heavens. Children in Red Sox
jerseys shriek in unabashed delight.
</P>
<P>
   And as suddenly as it begins, it ends. The bag nestles into the
hands of a wanting spectator. The murmur of the ballpark resumes _
the crack of the bat, the strains of the organ, Barry's voice
barking out, ``Peanuts. Grab your peanuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Barry, in the very best sense, is Nuts, which is his
nickname as well as anything else. If you've been over to Fenway in
the last decade, if you've scored some good seats, you've seen him
ply his trade on a route he calls ``dugout to dugout'' as arguably
the best peanut hawker in these United States.
</P>
<P>
   But his glory days are at risk of coming to a premature end, and
not by his choosing. It's a predicament, in short, that should
shell shock (sorry) his legion of fans.
</P>
<P>
   Some people have a gift. I have a cousin who can wiggle his ears
without moving another muscle in his face, and a college roommate
who could fit more than 40 grapes in his mouth at once.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Barry can throw peanuts. Good God, can he throw peanuts. He
can take a 7-ounce bag of those salted, dry-roasted beauties, fully
in the shell, and toss them 20, 30, even 40 rows up, hitting a
14-year-old fan square in the hands.
</P>
<P>
   He can stand below and toss a bag of nuts up into the roof
boxes, then catch the payment in his hat. He can hit a spectator
two sections away. Once, on July 10, 1994, he threw a bag across
the field, from the stands near one on-deck circle to the stands
near the other, in a bomb that caused an umpire's timeout and was
captured in a signed photograph that to this day adorns a wall of
the Baseball Tavern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll throw them as far as they want them,'' he says without
even a hint of cumbersome modesty. ``I make 200 to 250 throws a
night, and I'm in the lineup every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, almost. On Tuesday night, Rob Barry was pulled from the
game in the fifth inning. A boss who had shadowed his every pivot
and toss yanked him aside and sent him to the showers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy stalks me,'' Barry, 33, says. ``He'll be hiding in
the stands. He'll say, `I don't want you throwing this stuff.' I
say to him, `Talk to me when I hit someone.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It ends up, Aramark, the company that provides you remarkably
mediocre hot dogs and $4.50 cups of beer, has a rule, and that rule
prohibits vendors from throwing food around the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no throwing of food products,'' says Deborah Albert,
an Aramark spokeswoman at the Philadelphia headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to cups of Coke or boxes of Crackerjack, it's not
a bad idea, but some nitwit supervisor has decided it should extend
to Barry and his pillowy bags of peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Lyons, Aramark's general manager at Fenway, is one of the
good guys in a city that doesn't have nearly enough of them and, in
that light, offered precisely no comment when asked why one of his
minions was trying to push Barry off his game.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons privately fears if he lets it continue, all his vendors
will mimic Barry, and soon enough you'll have a cotton candy spear
sticking through some young fan's eye and a cash settlement that
could cost the Red Sox Nomar Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he knows Barry's accuracy, knows what the fans
want, and knows there are no recorded cases of catastrophic injury
caused by a bag of peanuts. With Barry, he wants to look the other
way, but some of his overeager underlings won't.
</P>
<P>
   So Barry will continue making his tosses, glancing over his
shoulder, prepared at any minute to be jerked from the game. If it
happens much more, he says he'll retire.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen years he's been a vendor, hustling to Fenway Park from
his job with the Department of Correction. His father worked at
Fenway for 45 years. Two sisters, beer servers, have given a total
of 44 years. Minor league and semipro baseball teams honor him on
special nights. He is featured on a NESN promotional tape. Men in
suits beg for his attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I can't even do what I do best in my own park,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   All of which seems, of course, to be absolutely nuts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Brian McGrory's e-mail address is mcgrory(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
