<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTION IN EUROLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   That dull, distant, but unmistakable ``ka-boooom'' that echoed
across the Atlantic this week was not a sonic boom laid down by a
stray Concorde but the sound of the euro cratering.
</P>
<P>
   Only 16 months old, the euro _ a currency introduced with much
backscratching and hand-clapping _ has encountered all of the
ailments associated with the newborn: colic, crankiness, inability
to digest its diet, and the sort of all-round weakness that is the
despair of the immediate, sleep-deprived relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Since inching up to $1.18 against the Almighty Bucko in its
first days as the currency designated to replace the gravel-voiced
German mark, the fractious French franc, the lollygagging Italian
lira, and eight more member nations' money, the euro has slid down
the piano keys to the far lefthand side of the keyboard, dipping
Thursday to a moody and meandering 88.45 cents against the
benchmark buck before burping up again a hair or two.
</P>
<P>
   The euro is still a virtual currency; the actual coins and paper
money won't start circulating till 2002. But the invention intended
to smooth out all the glitches and inefficiences in mainland
Europe's welter of currencies and exchange rates is used now to
settle business debts, contracts, stock trades, and most anything
else that can be done on a computer.
</P>
<P>
   The euro's slide makes the stuff Europe sells to America
cheaper, so in the long run, market share for the Europeans may
inch up in the United States. But when Europeans travel here, their
money is marked down by that 23 percent decline in the euro's worth
since it came into being with much fanfare on New Year's weekend 16
months ago. So all those German, French, and Italian tourists who
traipse over here for commencement season at Harvard, MIT, and BU
may be on shorter rations than usual.
</P>
<P>
   It's not ``sinking,'' claimed one German economist, it's
``floating.'' Of course, the difference between sinking and
floating can be important if you're on an inner tube in Boston's
Outer Harbor. But if you're buying stuff with dollars and only have
euros to pay, you're swallowing a lot of seawater.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-euro argument remains the same as it always was: In the
long run, the elimination of money-changing fees and commissions
and the efficiencies of creating a Europewide trading bloc larger
than the US market will win out. No doubt that will eventually come
to pass. Trends bottom out eventually. There is always solid
ground, even at the bottom of a very high cliff, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``The euro can recover,'' Britain's ambassador to the United
States asserts. And Sir Christopher Meyer was undoubtedly on solid
ground when he maintained in a Globe interview Wednesday that ``we
should not regard this as a terminal condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Britain decided not to join the euro conversion on the
first round, and Britain's pound has waxed as the euro wanes, Meyer
said for his government that ``we genuinely support the euro in
principle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blair government made the decision two years ago to refrain
from jumping into the euro pool till Britain's economic cycle
coincided more decorously with mainland Europe's. The pound has
been rock-steady against the dollar, and Blair, who does not have
to call an election in Britain until May of 2002, has promised his
electorate there will be a referendum before John Bull scraps
sterling.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Blair has never been euro-hostile in anywhere near the
fashion of Britain's Conservative Party, which has been rent badly
by its euroskeptic wing, which denounces any notion of cozying up
to the continent of Bonaparte, the Kaiser, and the Spanish dons.
With his opposition party fractured over the issue and some of the
big British papers controlled by Australian and Canadian
euroskeptics who try to be more British than the British, Blair
tiptoed away from the gaping euro manhole and decided to wait out
the initial birth pangs.
</P>
<P>
   Right now that looks like a shrewd move. Britain's economy is
going gangbusters, just like ours. The economic relationships
between the United States and the United Kingdom, Meyer recounted
accurately, ``are in an absolute golden boom period.''
</P>
<P>
   We are Britain's biggest foreign investor nation, just as they
are ours. ``And the money just keeps coming in from both
directions,'' Meyer said. In Massachusetts alone, ``the UK is
responsible for 30 percent of the foreign money invested.''
</P>
<P>
   In large part it has been economic progress, a big drop in
unemployment, and foreign investment in job-producing ventures that
have improved the prospects for peace in Northern Ireland despite
the current whiff of discord over the IRA's refusal to give up any
of its weapons cache.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unemployment and poverty are the recruiting sergeants of
terrorism,'' Meyer said, but the traditionally high unemployment
rate in Northern Ireland is only 6 percent _ 3 percent less than
that of France. The big European economies are laboring under high
welfare costs, high taxes, and high unemployment rates relative to
the United States and Britain. Interest rate drops decreed by the
European Central Bank have been ``a great inflation stoker,'' said
Meyer.
</P>
<P>
   There are other clouds on the European horizon. Pulling US or
NATO troops out of Bosnia would be a mistake, he counseled, because
in the Balkans ``we are reasonably confident things will revert to
their previously barbarous state.'' But for Britain, as for the
United States, if not for Euroland, this is the economic golden
age.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
