<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-COMMITTED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUGH LIGHTWEIGHT, YOU'LL STICK WITH `COMMITTED' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
COMMITTED 
Written and directed by: Lisa Krueger 
Starring: Heather Graham, Casey Affleck, Luke Wilson, Goran
Visnjic, Alfonso Arau, Patricia Velasquez 
Running time: 92 minutes 
Rated: R (language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lisa Krueger's ``Committed'' proves that Heather Graham can
carry a film, even when it stops pulling its own weight. How
committed is the dishy Graham's high-powered kewpie doll, Joline?
She's so committed to her marriage that she not only wears a ring,
but has one tattooed as well on her ring finger. Joline looks as
innocent as candy, but she's a coper. She doesn't bat an eye as one
thing after another threatens to unravel at the rock club she
manages. She sails through problems, so when her unworthy newspaper
photog husband (Luke Wilson) takes off after 597 days of marriage
in order to, as he so charmlessly puts it, ``find some space to get
out of the fog,'' she hits the road in search of him.
</P>
<P>
   So singleminded is Joline, and so capable, that she drives from
SoHo to El Paso to track him down. Never dreaming that her very
capability is what threatened the jerk and caused him to bolt, she
tempers her effectiveness with a saucer-eyed innocence that disarms
us into overlooking the fact that she's a stalker. When she catches
up with him, she's sensitive enough to hang back, content to be a
protective presence until he comes to his senses. That doesn't seem
likely to happen anytime soon. Still, it's such a sheer pleasure to
watch her cartwheel through various difficulties, including a
larcenous couple who think they can beat her up, that you forgive
the film for thinning out as it does.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Lisa Krueger picks up some of the slack by
parading a string of eccentrics through the stalled action. These
include Alfonso Arau's Mexican medicine man and Patricia Velasquez
as the local woman on whom Joline's husband had been hitting in his
weaselly way. Even here, Joline comes through, bonding with
Velasquez's waitress and clobbering the waitress's jealous
truck-driver boyfriend, who tries to beat Joline's husband to a
pulp. Wilson is funny as the spectacularly unworthy husband. Casey
Affleck not only is funny in his way as Joline's vacant kid
brother, he's likable, too. After ``Drowning Mona,'' and now this
film, he could find himself cornering the market on sweet airhead
roles if he's not careful. Meanwhile, there's no escaping the fact
that ``Committed'' runs dry amid the cactus and sagebrush, but
Graham's cartoony take on angelic unstoppableness makes us not mind
so much.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 1347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
