<HEADER>
A6502 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-BOSSANOVA-BOS &LR;      05-05 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BOSSANOVA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BOSSA NOVA' A BUOYANT TALE OF LOVE IN RIO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
BOSSA NOVA 
Directed by: Bruno Barreto 
Screenplay by: Alexandre Machado, Fernanda Young (novel: Sergio
Sant'Anna) 
Starring: Amy Irving, Antonio Fagundes, Alexandre Borges, Debora
Bloch, Kazuo Matsui, Alberto de Mendoza, Drica Moraes, Sergio
Loroza, Giovanna Antonelli, Pedro Cardoso, Stephen Tobolowsky 
Running time: 95 minutes 
Rated: R (language and some sexual content) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe it's the bossa nova rhythms, maybe it's the buoyant
atmosphere of Rio de Janeiro, maybe it's the screenful of sunny
pilgrims clawing their way out of love limbo. Maybe it's all three.
Either way, ``Bossa Nova'' is one of the most warmly beguiling
romantic comedies the Southern Hemisphere has sent our way in ages.
Brazilian filmmaker Bruno Barreto has clicked before in this genre,
with ``Dona Flor and Her Two Husbands.'' That film was a sexy
fantasy. This film is sexy, too, but it's very much of this world.
The women characters here, most of them anyway, would be happy with
one husband, while the men are, if anything, even more eager to
change their single state.
</P>
<P>
   The film is radical in spotlighting as its main couple a pair of
over-40s. It's awfully easy to root for them. Maturity sits well on
Amy Irving (Barreto's wife) as a widowed teacher of English. Irving
has in the past seemed contained, even a little cold. But here
she's poised and savvy, projecting a becoming generosity and
openness to life as an English-language instructor named Mary Ann.
Her opposite number, Brazilian actor Antonio Fagundes, is a charmer
_ suave, dapper, courtly, in every way disarming, rendered doubly
appealing by being unafraid to project vulnerability. In the film,
he's figuratively licking his wounds after being dumped by his
wife, who has fallen for her much younger tai chi instructor.
</P>
<P>
   There's another reason Fagundes' Pedro Paulo looks pained. He's
slightly guilty about not following in the footsteps of his father,
a master tailor, especially as Pedro had displayed a youthful
talent for tailoring. But that makes it all the more sensual when
at one point he ends his self-exile from the scissors, runs his
hand lovingly across a piece of wine-colored material, and fashions
a garment for the pretty teacher who has caught his eye. He's able
to bring to his pothole-strewn pursuit of Irving a quality all but
unknown in Hollywood comedies _ namely, graciousness. To her
credit, Irving's character, who is interested and a little lonely
but not at all desperate, responds to his delicacy and
gentlemanliness.
</P>
<P>
   These happen to be precisely the qualities lacking in one of her
private pupils, Alexandre Borges' soccer star, who has to learn
English in a hurry because he's been traded to a British team. His
considerable love for himself is shared by Giovanna Antonelli's
pretty lawyer, which means Pedro Paulo's law office may be left a
little disheveled, to say nothing of Pedro Paulo's brother, who has
a crush on her. Adding to the amatory mixups is Drica Moraes as
Mary Ann's pal, a travel agent who has embellished the truth in
fostering an internet romance with a wild SoHo artist. When she
gets an e-mail announcing his imminent arrival in Rio, she goes
ballistic.
</P>
<P>
   With all those romantic strands flailing around, it doesn't seem
likely that they'll all be tied into a neat package by the end, but
most of them do. The sorting out of the various couples never gets
tedious and the bounce and sway of the movie's footwork is upbeat
and enticing. Barreto, Irving, Fagundes and the rest know what
they're doing. Besides, they've got the sun-drenched beachfront
streets of Rio itself, to say nothing of a Jobim soundtrack, on
their side. You've probably fallen in love before with Rio and its
vivaciousness at the movies. ``Bossa Nova'' will smile away your
defenses and make you fall in love with it all over again. It's a
spring vacation for the eyes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
