<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6503 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-COTTON-HN     05-05 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-COTTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AFTER THE RAJ, A BIT OF LOONINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Cotton Mary,'' the scary new Ismail Merchant, movie has a
pristine veneer for a few of its 123 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   An Indian nurse (Madhur Jaffrey) ingratiates herself into the
home of a visiting British family and cares for their newborn. When
mommy can't bring herself to feed her infant, the nanny's
handicapped sister secretly (Neena Gupta) plays wet nurse.
</P>
<P>
   The film has the kind of nonplused mein that Merchant's usual
partners, James Ivory and Ruth Prawer Jhabvala, can pull out of a
top hat while sleepwalking. But when Merchant is not producing
their joint ventures _ as his three solo features testify _ he
thinks beyond Victorian sexual repression and tidy class angst.
</P>
<P>
   Merchant is like the experimental guy in a supergroup who has
that one idea for a record that's just not right for the band.
``Cotton Mary,'' with its grotesquerie and post-colonial
nightmarishness, is a good example.
</P>
<P>
   Adapted by Alexandra Viets' from her play, the film is about a
British family living in India as some kind of poisoned paradise,
indulgent, hypocritical, lusting after that which is not like
itself. Merchant, though, turns the story into a freaky, campy
musing about an Indian nanny wreaking havoc on a household.
</P>
<P>
   The tag lines in the trailer could make this sound juicy: They
thought she looked like the perfect servant to watch their children
while they frolicked and fretted, cheated and idled, slurping up
all the spicy nectar in this scenic utopia. They were wrong. Terror
has a new name this spring. Say hello to ``Cotton Mary.''
</P>
<P>
   If the family in Curtis Hanson's ``The Hand That Rocked the
Cradle'' had half a mind to hire Whoopi Goldberg to help around the
house instead of Rebecca DeMornay, it may have come out something
like this: less sensational, but far more carnivalesque. Set in the
1950s, a few years after India reclaimed its independence from
Britain, the film purports to be a set piece about how tainted
Anglo-Indian relations warped both cultures. But it's really just a
lurid potboiler.
</P>
<P>
   John Mackintosh (James Wilby) is a multitasking aesthete who
transplants his pregnant wife Lily (Greta Scacchi), his daughter,
and loyal butler, Abraham (Prayag Raj), to India where he works as
a journalist and stage actor, flirting with whatever chicky happens
to be starring opposite him. Lily is in no condition to be a
sterling mother to her new daughter, and you're not sure whether
she's dismayed by her jolly husband's benign neglect or the
suspicion that the overly polite Indian midwife cast some kind of
spell on her during labor. She called herself Cotton Mary; she told
the annoyingly passive Lily about her white soldier father whose
picture she carries in a locket, and she kept insisting that this
new baby ``is a child of God, madam.'' Soon, she's in the
Mackintosh home, trying to get Abraham fired so she can hire her
temptress niece (Sakina Jaffrey).
</P>
<P>
   What lends ``Mary'' it's off-kilter sense of the bizarre is
Merchant's two-dimensional staging. The camera peers in on a scene,
then recoils, often clinically, to the other side of a room, as
though filming a play or as if reluctant to get terribly involved
with the proceedings for fear of contamination, either by Mary or
by Viets' very rudimentary story. But Mary's demons are the
province of her collapsing psyche and engorged aspirations of
becoming white, Lily white, no less. Jaffrey plays it like Anna
Magnani in a David Lynch telefilm. Her Mary is the cracked portrait
of deranged post-colonial dementia, hung in the biggest, broadest
frame you put on a wall.
</P>
<P>
   But did Merchant have to make her madness seem so illogically
soapy? It's as though, in documenting cultural queerness afoot, he
skipped the institution and went straight for the loony bin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6507 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-CELIBACY-BOS &LR;      05-05 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CELIBACY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HISTORY OF OUR EXPERIMENTS WITH CELIBACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN CLEGG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
A History of Celibacy 
Elizabeth Abbott 
Scribner, 493 pp., $30 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Celibacy is a long dry season that comes by choice, chance, or
coercion. Laced with spirituality or sorrow, it has had many
adherents through time: Mary, Joan of Arc, Leonardo da Vinci,
Gandhi. It has linked mystics to God, kept women in their place and
allowed them to serve the exalted Oracle of Delphi. In the hands of
Elizabeth Abbott, a Canadian writer and academic dean at the
University of Toronto, it is the basis for a tart romp through
history that lets no one off the hook _ not even Abbott herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout the world and the ages, celibacy has been a key
element of human existence,'' Abbott writes. ``In all its various
forms, it has shaped religious lives, as well as the lives of
laity, and its embrace has included the very young and the very
old. It has haunted widows and prisoners, and conditioned athletes
and shamans. It has pulsated throughout classical poetry and camp
literature, throughout canon and civil law.''
</P>
<P>
   In more than six years of research, Abbott found that if
celibacy is the flip side of lust, it is no less complex. She
abandoned her tongue-in-cheek working title (``The Kama Sutra of
Celibacy'') when she realized the overwhelming scope of her
project. Tossing aside traditional hair-splitting distinctions
between chastity, celibacy, and virginity, she organized her book
around patterns in ``humankind's celibacy experiments.'' From Greek
mythology to modernity, she finds, celibates are defined by what
they aren't; with deft wit and a slew of footnotes, she navigates
this universe of nots.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that the struggle with an elemental human drive
is central to the core of ritual and religion. Although Greek gods
were rapacious by nature, the three main goddesses _ Athena
(wisdom), Artemis (the hunt), and Hestia (the hearth) _ were
virgins. Celibacy was also a requirement for the earthly women who
served the oracle of Apollo's temple at Delphi. Urgent questions
about war and peace were submitted to a priestess, who responded in
verse.
</P>
<P>
   Pagan and Jewish asceticism were precursors to the Christian
institutionalization of celibacy, Abbott notes. It's clear that
she's ripping mad at her own Christian faith and its ``deadly logic
unleavened by the demographic concern that celibate Christians
cannot reproduce themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   She scrupulously documents the role of the celibate in Buddhism,
Jainism, and Hinduism, but returns to settle her own scores with
Christianity in a bitter-sounding epilogue. ``Celibacy's long
history cuts to the core of Christian doctrine, and its pernicious
portrayal of women and its fundamental misogyny caused me great
personal pain.''
</P>
<P>
   But Abbott can employ nuance when she wants to do so.
Historically, she finds, celibacy has provided shelter for people
who didn't want to express outlawed sexuality. Da Vinci, the
Renaissance inventor with the millennial mind, hid much of his
personal life. In 1476, he and three other young men were charged
with sodomizing a male prostitute. After hearings and a long wait,
da Vinci was acquitted. But the gossip tormented him, and Abbott
believes that ``it is quite likely he actually earned his
reputation for perpetual chastity.''
</P>
<P>
   Sir Isaac Newton was probably a lifelong celibate, she writes,
who never consummated his great love affair with his longtime
companion, a male mathematician some 20 years younger. Newton's
thwarted love exerted its own gravitational pull on his scientific
creativity, and he lapsed into a grouchy depression.
</P>
<P>
   Celibacy has a modern face, as well, Abbott finds. Prompted by
personal ethics or frightened by the prospect of sexually
transmitted disease, some teenagers choose chastity. Anorexic girls
achieve chastity and a measure of control by starving off any
tantalizing curves.
</P>
<P>
   In her epilogue, Abbott comes clean. `` `So, are you for it or
against it?' people continually ask me. . . . I find this question
disconcerting.'' But she answers it, honestly and without excess
drama. When she began the book, she was not in a relationship. At
some point, however, circumstance got transmuted into choice. And
that, she concludes, is the point. ``As for so many others, in
history and in the present, the element of choice made all the
difference in how I experienced celibacy. Instead of burdensome and
frustrating, it now felt joyous and liberating.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 1350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6513 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-VIRGIN-BOS &LR;      05-05 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-VIRGIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASTERFUL `VIRGIN SUICIDES' A HAUNTING STUDY OF ADOLESCENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE VIRGIN SUICIDES 
Written and directed by: Sofia Coppola 
Starring: James Woods, Kathleen Turner, Kirsten Dunst, Josh
Hartnett, Hanna Hall, Chelse Swain, A.J. Cook, Leslie Hayman, Danny
DeVito, Michael Pare, Jonathan Tucker, Robert Schwartzman 
Running time: 97 minutes 
Rated: R (strong thematic elements involving teens) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sofia Coppola's ``The Virgin Suicides'' is easily the filmmaking
debut of the year so far. It's an impressive, haunting, layered
work that's several things at once. It uses teen suicides as an
evocation of the acuteness of the outwardly circumscribed but
internally stormy lives of adolescent girls. It's also a metaphor
for the lifelong tug of adolescence well into adulthood, as we're
reminded by Coppola's way of framing the story as the recollection
of one of the boys transfixed by the girls then and now. Although
Coppola nominally tells the story from a male perspective, she
avoids the usual dumbness that goes with this vantage point in this
film that emerges as a triumph of tone. From start to finish
there's a shimmer of discovery about it _ our discovery of it,
Coppola's discovery of how much she can do.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's a feast of superrealist detail, it's anything but
realistic. Rather it's a fabulist reinvention of adolescence, with
everything heightened and much remaining mysterious. The film could
have gone the purely satirical route in examining something that
went terribly wrong in a Detroit suburb in the '70s. Looking back,
a grown male narrator revisits the year when he and his buddies
were fixated by five blond sisters whose parents, played by James
Woods and Kathleen Turner, are rigidly controlling and pitifully
obtuse. Each is an icon of disconnectedness. She's ferociously
protective. Her reaction to her daughters' vulnerability is barely
contained hysteria. He's simply beaten down, in full denial, hiding
behind the non-controversy of the laws of science, asking only to
be left alone as he passively fills his days as the nerdy high
school math teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Turner is at her fire-breathing best, and we've never seen this
side of Woods in what I predict will stand as one of the year's
memorable supporting roles. He's the best castrated father since
Jim Backus' apron-wearing eunuch in ``Rebel Without a Cause.'' The
voyeuristic boys all are inscribed with remarkable rightness,
especially Jonathan Tucker as the one for whom the mythologized
connection to the girls becomes a piece of lifelong detective work,
Josh Hartnett as the high-school's self-aware babe magnet drolly
riding his coolness, and Jonathan Schwartzman as the group's
would-be stud, forever practicing his moves, most hilariously on
Turner's mom.
</P>
<P>
   But of course ``The Virgin Suicides'' must rise or fall on its
girls, and in this case it rises high. To those who haven't been
there, ``The Virgin Suicides'' is like a keenly observed dispatch
from a foreign country. The film wastes no time letting us know
that the 13-year-old (Leslie Hayman) is the first to go. When her
doctor (Danny DeVito) tells her that she isn't old enough to know
how bad life can get, she replies: ``Obviously, doctor, you've
never been a 13-year-old girl.'' She's not being ironic, this
summery little calla lily of a girl with a wiser-than-her-years
look in her eyes. She's serious. Which, of course, is part of the
problem _ and part of the film's rightness: Coppola never minimizes
the sisters' shared angst. Essentially, they're repressed into
excess, especially after their first tentative, exhilarating, yet
painfully self-conscious forays into sex and boys result in their
being yanked out of school and being placed under house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Until mountains are moved and they make it to the prom, with
disastrous results for one of them, the pain and anxiety are mostly
felt by their mother, especially at the thought that she's going to
have to give up some control over them. When their mother reverses
herself and locks the girls in the house after making them get rid
of their record collections, they start devising ways of
communicating with the boys they know are watching them through
binoculars. The story, unfolding with dreamy inevitability, is
sophisticated and compassionate _ a mix of humor, dread, and rage
turned inward. One vignette, when Coppola's camera fixes on the
girls draped passively yet sullenly across the bed of one of them,
is as potent, as loaded with something about to break through its
frozen surface, as any superreal painting of the '70s or '80s. Like
her father, Coppola is an often painterly filmmaker. But she goes
places stylistically and emotionally that none of his films ever
got anywhere near.
</P>
<P>
   Kirsten Dunst is the standout as the one who has most of the
lines and dimension in this exercise that deepens its impact and
its reverberations by avoiding facile explanations. Lux is the name
of her character. She seems partly composed of light _ an airy,
golden apparition, yet heavy with thwartedness until her yearning
and rage and confusion boil over. Coppola loads the screen with
vivid, pungent detail. Black humor explodes from her screenplay
like a string of little land mines, erupting from the film's pall
of unmade connections snuffing out all. When Turner's shattered,
blinkered mom says, ``There was always plenty of love in our
house,'' the line all but impales her as the unerringly assured
Coppola cuts between the self-obliterating girls and the
neighborhood's vanishing elm trees, power-sawed, one by one, into
stumps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6518 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-AFRICA-BOS &LR;      05-05 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-AFRICA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFRICA `DREAMED' TEEMS WITH LIFE, YET FEELS TAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
I DREAMED OF AFRICA 
Directed by: Hugh Hudson 
Screenplay by: Paula Milne and Susan Shilladay (based on Kuki
Gallmann's book) 
Starring: Kim Basinger, Vincent Perez, Eva Marie Saint, Liam Aiken,
Garrett Strommen, Winston Ntshona, Daniel Craig, Lance Reddick 
Running time: 115 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (a scene of nudity/sensuality and some
violent/traumatic episodes) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like ``Out of Africa,'' with which it will inevitably be
compared, ``I Dreamed of Africa'' is based on the true story of a
European woman who learned how to fit into Africa. The story of
Kuki Gallmann could more accurately be called ``Into Africa.'' It
stars Kim Basinger in a visually arresting and at times involvingly
primal education in rewriting the rules of life. One character
after another keeps telling the new arrival from Venice that Africa
moves to its own rhythms and that she had better get used to it.
Something similar can be said of the film. It treats some powerful
experiences in refreshingly unromantic fashion, yet remains
frustratingly tepid.
</P>
<P>
   A number of grandly dramatic things happen to Basinger's
Gallmann, a single mom, after she marries a fellow survivor of a
car crash in the Italian countryside and journeys with him and her
young son to a magnificent but harsh new world in Kenya. Like Karen
Blixen's white lover in ``Out of Africa,'' Gallmann's husband,
played by Vincent Perez, is a decent fellow, but an often absent
one, trapped in macho patterns. This means that she's left to mind
the ranch and cope for weeks at a time with storms, wild animals,
poachers, and other incursions while he's off playing great white
hunter with his pals.
</P>
<P>
   What's good about Basinger's portrayal is her way of showing
hurt feelings and anger with her eyes, then determination with the
set of her jaw as she goes about fixing the generator or chasing an
elephant out of her vegetable garden. The film begins as a
meditation on her life in Africa, ushered in with an overhead shot
of Basinger's Kuki lying in bed, free-associating about the events
of her life. What's too often lacking, though, is the kind of
interior dimension promised by the image of her reflectiveness. ``I
Dreamed of Africa'' depicts its characters, but almost never seems
to really penetrate them.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Kuki's story does not lack for eventfulness as her own
straightforward honesty wins her the respect of the Kenyan locals.
Proving her mettle again and again, she's easily the equal of her
husband in every way that counts and she wins as well the respect
of her mother, an aristocratic museum curator played by Eva Marie
Saint, who convincingly finds ways to allow maternal and
grandmotherly feeling to break through her exterior. Perez isn't
exactly a recessive presence, but he's clearly a secondary one in
this film, which knows enough to avoid seeming myopically
Eurocentric by respectfully portraying the Kenyans, ranging from
Winston Ntshona's old tribal chief to Lance Reddick's major-domo.
</P>
<P>
   There's passion here, and an engaging performance by young Liam
Aiken as the boy who plunges in and embraces his new life.
Basinger's longtime activism on behalf of animals makes for a
committed link to the real Kuki Gallmann's anti-poaching campaigns,
which have saved elephants and rhinos hunted for their ivory
throughout Africa, but no longer in her vicinity. The film about a
white family falling in love with Africa, and the corner of it they
bought and turned into a home, would appear to be out of step with
the times. Still, these lives were lived, and honorably, and this
film depicts them with dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it never becomes the kind of cinematic experience you keep
hoping it will be. It's got magnitude, but little amplitude. One
can overlook the film's slow pace, but not its opacity or
disjointedness. While it's true that life isn't lived as a neatly
strung series of plot points, and while this film unflinchingly
faces some cruel parts of the story it depicts, it seems to
perversely resist all attempts to turn it into a cohesive dramatic
whole with a satisfying cumulative impact. ``I Dreamed of Africa''
plays like a string of journal entries waiting to be assembled into
the fully involving narrative you're convinced it can be, but isn't
here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6524 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-GLADIATOR-BOS &LR;      05-05 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GLADIATOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GLADIATOR' FIRST BIG BLOODLETTING OF BLOCKBUSTER SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
GLADIATOR 
Directed by: Ridley Scott 
Screenplay by: David Franzoni, John Logan, William Nicholson 
Starring: Russell Crowe, Joaquin Phoenix, Connie Nielsen, Oliver
Reed, Derek Jacobi, Djimon Hounsou, Richard Harris, David
Schofield, John Shrapnel 
Running time: 150 minutes 
Rated: R (intense graphic combat) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just as ``Jurassic Park'' dissolved the line between movies and
theme parks, ``Gladiator'' eliminates what may have been any
lingering boundary between movies and the World Wrestling
Federation. It's ``Spartacus'' on steroids. For all its lip service
to the principle of restoring Rome to the people after a twisted
son kills his emperor father and takes over, ``Gladiator'' is about
Russell Crowe and his good guys whacking away at the bad guys in
the Roman death pit known as the Colosseum. It's a joltfest that
showers upon us all the rolling heads, gushing blood and shattered
chariot parts you could hope for. In short, it epitomizes the kind
of high-profile bloodshed we now expect to herald the hazy, lazy,
blockbuster-fixated days of summer.
</P>
<P>
   Words like ``Gladiator,'' ``Battleship'' and ``Dinosaur'' in
their titles probably tell you all you need to know about this
summer's movies, with what to some is their reassuring suggestion
of big, heavy objects dropped on one's head from a great height.
``Gladiator'' plays like a wrestler being dumped in your lap as a
bonus for buying a ringside seat. Obviously, the bread-and-circuses
thing hasn't changed that much in a couple of millennia. Crowe,
director Ridley Scott and their legions throw themselves at the
spectacle thing with gusto and a generous budget, filling the
screen with countless togaed extras screaming their heads off, too
busy tracking the carnage to be bothered with boring details like
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gladiator'' is more pumped up than ``Spartacus,'' but less
earnest. There was idealism in ``Spartacus,'' whereas the only
passion in ``Gladiator'' has to do with registering on the Richter
scale. Which, to give the film its due, it does, despite a
second-half dropoff in its energy level. I suppose it would be too
much to expect one of these sword-and-sandal epics to feel anything
like a human experience. Still, it's going to be huge despite its
old-style Hollywood solemnity between fights. The bouts are
frequent enough and brutal enough to keep kickass-minded audiences
in a thumbs-up mode, right from the start, when Crowe's general and
his army wipes out a Germanic tribe. While Kirk Douglas's Spartacus
starts at the bottom and works his way up, Crowe's general starts
at the top and works his way down.
</P>
<P>
   Crowe's character is named Maximus. (What else would they call
him? Minimus?) His demotion is sudden. He promises the old emperor
_ Richard Harris cannily milking a juicy cameo _ that he'll
re-establish a Roman Republic. But the king's bratty son, Commodus,
who's jealous of Maximus because he knows his father considers
Maxiumus the son he wishes he could have fathered, murders the old
emperor and gets rid of Maximus when the latter refuses to go along
with the coup. ``Gladiator'' also makes a half-hearted effort to
get a little incest going between Joaquin Phoenix's Commodus and
his sister, Connie Nielsen's Lucilla. These scenes _ in fact, all
the non-combat scenes _ are bathed in such gloom that they'd sink
like stones if not for Phoenix's smirk.
</P>
<P>
   One thing he's smirking about is his death by torture of
Maximus's family. Like Spartacus, Maximus would have preferred to
live the life of a simple farmer. As it is, he's motivated by
revenge after being sold into slavery. Crowe isn't asked to do much
beyond staying focused and looking vengeful. This he does as he
efficiently works his way up the food chain to the big time _ Rome.
The late Oliver Reed _ ``Gladiator'' was his swan song _ would have
stolen the movie if his slave dealer and gladiator vendor weren't
so noble. Better he should have been given some comic relief to
play, as Peter Ustinov did in such unctuous fashion in
``Spartacus,'' playing a similar role, greeting his fighters on the
eve of their deadly games by saying, ``Good luck. . . to most of
you.'' As it is, the film must settle for such faint ironies as
casting Derek Jacobi, of ``I, Claudius'' fame, as a potentially
honorable senator.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix comes off relatively unscathed in a role that's all but
self-immolating, requiring him to speak such lines as ``I'm
terribly vexed,'' as he throws a hissy fit. ``Gladiator'' doesn't
so much represent a reinvention of ``Spartacus'' as a revisiting
and italicizing of its tabloid side. Character is scanted or
perfunctory, although Crowe fills the film's big canvas with
commanding presence. Still, there's no getting around the fact that
``Gladiator'' can't drape dignity and righteousness over the
slaughter that's its reason for being. ``Gladiator'' is
red-blooded, but only in a titillating way. Predictably, with its
conspicuous display of pre-fascist trappings. it says more about
our time than about Rome. Its message, insofar as it has one, is
that the only thing bigger than a corrupt ruler is a celebrity
gladiator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
