A6532 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV0     05-05 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV07-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREATING A NEW RUSH CHAIR SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 07, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have a very nice old Windsor chair that was my
grandmother's. I had a new rush seat applied, and while it looks
good, it is very light in color, nothing like the brown the old
rush was. Is there any way to darken it?
</P>
<P>
   ETHEL HANNABURY, Melrose, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Sure. Wait 10 years. The rush will darken naturally over
time. There is no need to finish, but if you want to darken it
instantly, apply two coats of an oil-based polyurethane varnish.
The rush will continue to darken under the varnish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is it OK for a husband and wife to submit questions on the
same day? I understand my wife called you earlier. If it is OK,
here is my question: The houses in my neighborhood occasionally get
water in the basement; mine gets less. A couple bought the big
Victorian next door and they talked of putting on an addition near
a huge maple tree. They were warned that the maple may have to go
if the addition is built as planned. That tree is huge, and must be
taking up a lot of water when it rains. My question is: If the tree
goes, would that raise the water table significantly or at all,
aggravating the flooding?
</P>
<P>
   RALPH HANNABURY, Melrose, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Husbands and wives can ask all the questions they want. The
handyman welcomes all and is impressed by the attention.
</P>
<P>
   And, a short answer to a long question: No, taking the tree down
will not affect the water table much, if at all; the area is too
big to be affected by one tree.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are better reasons to keep the tree: Shade and
generation of oxygen all summer, and good looks all year long. I
suggest you see if you can get the neighbor to consider another
spot for the addition.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I lugged up an old utility sink from my basement. It was
wicked heavy. Does it contain asbestos?
</P>
<P>
   GINA DiROCCO, Reading, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. No. It is probably soapstone (nothing, not even cast iron is
heavier than soapstone). The sink may have some value. Advertise in
your local used-goods flyer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The floor of my deck is made of Trex. I spilled some oil on
the floor. How can I remove it? It has been on the Trex for five
days.
</P>
<P>
   LOUIS D'AMBROSIA, Hampton, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   A. There is no deck that will not stain from oil, except maybe
PVC boards, and they will stain too, but at least it is easier to
remove stains from vinyl, using paint thinner.
</P>
<P>
   Wood is very tender to oil stains. Trex, a combo of ground
plastic bottles and ground wood, also is absorbent, but not as much
as wood. To remove, if the oil has hardened, scrape with a putty
knife. Then apply lots of baking soda, Speedy-Dry or cat litter,
leave it for an hour, then sweep up and throw it away. All these
are absorbents and will suck up the oil, given time. Speedy-Dry,
sold in hardware stores, is normally used to pick up oil (!) in
service stations. If the oil is rather hard, but does not scrape up
easily, apply paint thinner to dissolve it, then apply the
absorbent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My smoke detectors are hard-wired into the electricity. They
have been up for a while, and seem to work OK, but now they make a
snapping sound when any switch is turned on. How can I correct
that?
</P>
<P>
   RICHARD NEWBERG, Carver, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Check with an electrician, or a small appliance repair
person. It sounds as if the detectors have worn from old age and
may need replacing. If you dust them or vacuum them lightly to
clear out dust, that might help.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have 40 vinyl chaise lounges around a resort pool, and
every one is stained with suntan lotion. Regular cleaner does not
remove it. What will?
</P>
<P>
   S.B., Cape Cod, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. There are a lot of things to clean vinyl, so you may have to
try one at a time for suntan lotion stains. Here are some cleaners
for vinyl, in no preferential order:
</P>
<P>
   1. Zap, sold from a catalog called Solutions, 800-987-6564.
</P>
<P>
   2. Soap Scum Remover sold in hardware stores. It took a while to
work, but after it came clean, subsequent treatments were easy and
quick.
</P>
<P>
   3. Simple Green.
</P>
<P>
   4. Armorall, the spray cleaner used to clean vinyl dashboards
and auto tiles.
</P>
<P>
   5. Tackle, a cleaner for vinyl siding that has been on the
market for some years.
</P>
<P>
   6. Rub with a cloth dipped in dry-cleaning fluid.
</P>
<P>
   7. And finally, a mix of one part household bleach and three
parts water. If it works, rinse thoroughly; we don't want all that
tender skin affected by bleach. When working with bleach or any
other cleaner, wear skin and eye protection.
</P>
<P>
   8. Finally, pressure-washing might help, if you can keep from
blowing the chaises all over the Cape.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail
hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
