   And
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-U.N. (Dateline to come)_ On the challenges faced by the
U.N. peacekeeping mission to Congo, including the need to build a
town in one area to support a regional peacekeeping headquarters.
By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LEBANON (Dateline to come) _ Israel said it will not
retaliate against Shiite Muslim guerrillas from the group Hezbollah
who fired more rockets into northern Israel Friday. By Deborah
Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES-HOSTAGES (Manila) _ Developments and background on
the rebels who are holding hostages in the Philippines. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-POLITICS (Tehran) _ The second round of parliamentary
elections was held on Friday as reformers attempt to maintain the
gains made in earlier voting. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   PANAM103-TRIAL (Camp Zeist, the Netherlands) _ Developments in
the third day of the trial of two Libyans who are accused of the
bombing of Pan Am Flight 103. By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TRIPP-TRIAL (Washington) _ A Maryland judge issues a ruling in
the Linda Tripp wiretap case that will determine whether she goes
to trial or the case is dismissed. Ruling expected at 2 p.m. By
Neil A. Lewis. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   OCONNOR (New York) _ Lede-all on funeral preparations for
Cardinal John O'Connor. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT9.
</P>
<P>
   KANSASCITY-SCHOOLS (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Public lives on Benjamin
Demps Jr., Kansas City Schools superintendent, who faces the task
of bringing a district on its knees back up on its feet. By Dirk
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   MISS-FLAG (Atlanta) _ Mississippi Gov. Ronnie Musgrove to
announce a plan of action on the official state flag that wasn't.
By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By
Gustav Niebuhr. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-EDUC (Lansing, Mich.) _ Vice President Al Gore outlines
proposals for improving teacher quality, and uses his speech to
trash his opponent. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-NRA (Washington) _ So was Al Gore ever a member of the NRA
as George W. Bush suggests? By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes on the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The nation's unemployment rate dipped
below 4 percent, to 3.9 percent, for the first time in 30 years in
April, as 340,000 workers found jobs. The payrolls number was
inflated by the hiring of 73,000 workers for the Census and by the
late Easter holiday, which pushed some hiring in retail in April.
Still, the report was much stronger than what economists had
expected. The April report also showed that average hourly wages
rose 6 cents, or 0.4 percent to $13.64. The annual wage increase
was 3.8 percent, the biggest in 10 months. The data will probably
bolster expectations that the Federal Reserve will become
aggressive in raising interest rates. Stocks open lower but quickly
recover to trade sharply higher. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   HEDGE-FUNDS (Undated) _ The days when money managers like George
Soros and Julian H. Robertson Jr. could rattle world markets are
passing as an increasingly volatile economy has made their
investing style fall out of favor. The twilight of the giants has
obscured a recent shift in the industry toward smaller, more nimble
funds that focus on specific sectors or large firms that offer
collections of smaller funds. Even as some prominent investors
suffer, it is evident the hedge fund industry has continued to
flourish. By Danny Hakim.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-RAIL (St. Augustine, Fla.) _ Henry Flagler came to Florida
in 1883 to build grand hotels in what was sparsely populated
coastal scrub. He began cobbling together a railroad, and by 1896
he had built 350 miles of track from Jacksonville to Miami. Now
Florida East Coast Industries, the holding company controlling the
Flagler railroad, is using the right of way to establish itself in
the new economy. A subsidiary has been selling capacity to move
digital information through fiber-optic cables that run alongside
chugging train cars. The experience of Florida East Coast provides
a glimpse into some of the swaps and barters used to create a glass
network for the streams of digital bits and bytes cycling around
the globe. It also suggests how some transportation and power
companies may find prosperity in a cyber age. By Jane Tanner. (1700
words)
</P>
<P>
   UNILEVER-BESTFOODS (Undated) _ Following developments in the
Unilever bid for Bestfoods. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   LOVE-VIRUS (Undated) _ Developments on the ``I love you'' virus.
By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   WPP-YOUNG (London) _ WPP says it has resumed takeover talks with
Young &AMP; Rubicam. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   CISCO-ARROWPOINT (Undated) _ Cisco Systems says it will buy
Internet switch maker ArrowPoint Communications Inc. for about $5.7
billion in stock. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   CASPIAN-OIL (Almaty, Kazakhstan) _ A consortium of nine oil
companies says it is encouraged by drilling in a potentially huge
Caspian Sea oil field. By Steve LeVine.
</P>
<P>
   BMW-ROVER (London) _ BMW raises new doubts about the likelihood
of a deal with a British consortium to rescue its loss-making Rover
Cars operations. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN-DUTCH-TELECOM (London) _ Shares of Telefonica of Spain and
Royal KPN shares fall after the board of Telefonica fails to reach
an agreement on a merger plan. Developing. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks were higher in early trading. At
11:10 a.m., the Dow Jones industrial average was up 1.40 percent,
the S&AMP;P 500 up 1.55 percent and the Nasdaq composite index up 2.01
percent. Treasury prices were slightly lower. European stock
markets were higher: London was up 0.92 percent and Frankfurt up
1.38 percent. Hong Kong closed down 0.30 percent. The Tokyo market
was closed for a national holiday.
</P>
