A6634 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PEPPER-SPRAY-HNS &LR;      05-05 0437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEPPER-SPRAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ANTI-LOGGING PROTESTERS GET ANOTHER TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC BRAZIL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An appellate court has ruled that nine
anti-logging protesters whose eyes were swabbed with pepper spray
by sheriff's deputies in Northern California are entitled to a
second jury trial to attempt to prove that they were subjected to
excessive force.
</P>
<P>
   Reversing a decision by U.S. District Court Judge Vaughn R.
Walker, a three-judge 9th Circuit Court of Appeals panel on
Thursday ruled that a jury might well decide in the demonstrators'
favor.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1997, Walker dismissed the plaintiffs' civil
lawsuit, saying no reasonable jury would find the deputies' actions
improper. The case generated national publicity when network
television showed footage of the Humboldt County deputies applying
pepper spray to the plaintiffs' eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Harry Pregerson, writing for the circuit court panel, said
``a rational person could easily conclude that there was sufficient
evidence for a verdict in favor of the plaintiffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Jurors deadlocked 4-4 in the first trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strong ruling,'' said Brendan Cummings, a Berkeley
lawyer who represents the plaintiffs. ``This is an issue for a
jury, not a judge to decide. It's an issue of community standards.
So much of the world was outraged and horrified by what police did
to these protesters.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit arose from an Oct. 16, 1997, sit-in at the Eureka
office of then-Rep. Frank Riggs, R-Calif., and on Sept. 25 and Oct.
3, 1997, at forest demonstrations by protesters against logging in
the pristine Headwaters Forest.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters in Riggs' office had chained themselves together
using metal sleeves, which made them hard to separate. They refused
to budge, despite warnings from deputies.
</P>
<P>
   Deputies then rubbed cotton swabs dipped in pepper spray on the
protesters' eyelids and sprayed some of them in the face.
</P>
<P>
   Terri Slametz of Oakland, one of the plaintiffs, said she now
feels ``relieved and hopeful that we have a jury that feels as we
do that deputies should not be able to use torture on nonviolent
people.''
</P>
<P>
   In dismissing the lawsuit, Walker found that ``the balance of
hardship'' in the case tipped toward law enforcement. Prohibiting
the practice of direct application to the eyes of nonviolent
demonstrators ``would impair their ability to enforce the law and
impose a significant hardship,'' he said. ``Limiting the officers
options to a cumbersome alternative restricts their ability to
effect arrests.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
