   &UR; IDEAS PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PUTNAM-CIVIC-MALAISE (Undated) _ Five years ago, Robert Putnam's
article, ``Bowling Alone,'' about the decline of civic engagement,
touched a public nerve and became a metaphor for a much larger
national malaise. He suddenly found himself profiled in People
Magazine, appearing on talk shows and getting an invite from
President Clinton to Camp David. Now he's back with a new book and
new evidence for his thesis, and a somewhat more optimistic outlook
for the future. By Louis Uchitelle. (1800 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT2.
</P>
<P>
   BEAUTY-REINTERPRETED (Undated) _ As an ideal, beauty has been
taking quite a beating. It has been viewed as an ideology that is
culture-bound, and it has come to seem irrelevant to art works
preoccupied with race and gender. Yet, there has also been a
movement in the other direction. The philosopher and classicist
Alexander Nehamas has suggested that beauty is once again becoming
an academic obsession, as philosophers and critics resuscitate the
beautiful, recasting old philosophical arguments and forecasting
new variants. By Edward Rothstein. (1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER CULTURE AND ENTERTAINMENT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HOLOCAUST-CANTATA (Washington) _ The balmy spring night belied
the occasion of sad memorial, and, as the cantata played out around
the capital on the radio, listeners paused at the very idea of a
spirited tango composed by some forgotten Buchenwald prisoner, not
to mention the bold humor enduring beyond long gone lyricists at
the Auschwitz death camp. Listening to the Holocaust Cantata, a
choral pastiche of authentic music and song from inmates translated
from the Polish and premiered two years ago by the chorale's
chamber singers. By Francis X. Clines. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   HOLOCAUST-PHILHARMONIC (Berlin) _ The controversy over plans to
have the the Vienna Philharmonic play Beethoven's Ninth Symphony at
the site of the former Nazi concentration camp in Mauthausen,
Austria. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   TV-BALANCHINE-REVIEW (Undated) _ On PBS, ``Balanchine Lives.''
Reviewed by Jennifer Dunning.
</P>
<P>
   TV-JASON-REVIEW (Undated) _ On NBC, ``Jason and the Argonauts,''
a mini-series. Reviewed by Neil Genzlinger.
</P>
