<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6694 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS &LR;      05-05 1596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HEARST EXECUTIVE SAYS FANG CLOUT WAS A FACTOR IN EXAMINER
SALE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SETH ROSENFELD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A Hearst Corp. executive has testified that the
Fang family's offer to wield political clout to help Hearst buy the
San Francisco Chronicle was a consideration in Hearst's decision to
give the Fangs its San Francisco Examiner along with a $66 million
publishing subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   James M. Asher, Hearst's senior vice president, confirmed in
testimony Thursday that the Fangs in December offered to ``use
their extensive political connections.''
</P>
<P>
   Asher said of the Fangs' offer, ``I believe it's fair to say it
was a consideration, but not a very significant one.''
</P>
<P>
   The testimony came in the fourth day of trial, before U.S.
District Judge Vaughn R. Walker, on former political consultant and
1999 mayoral candidate Clint Reilly's antitrust suit to block
Hearst's $660 million purchase of the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   A newspaper broker also testified, saying she believed Hearst
was paying a fair price for the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a Hearst lawyer said he did not tell Hearst
executives that Examiner Publisher Timothy O. White had testified
to the U.S. Department of Justice in December that he offered Mayor
Willie Brown favorable editorial treatment in return for Brown
backing Hearst's purchase of the Chronicle. The Hearst lawyer said
he thought White's testimony was irrelevant to antitrust law.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst indefinitely suspended White on Tuesday, saying it
learned of his comments to Brown only in court testimony Monday,
and was investigating whether he breached journalistic ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's suit contends Hearst's plan to buy the Chronicle and
sell The Examiner will result in Hearst owning the only
metropolitan daily newspaper in town, a situation it claims is an
illegal monopoly. He claims the sale of The Examiner to the Fangs
is a sham and that the paper will fail. Hearst, Chronicle
Publishing Co. and the Fangs have denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's testimony shed light on the intense negotiations
around the Fangs' effort to buy The Examiner and Hearst's effort to
buy the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph M. Alioto, Reilly's lawyer, filed as evidence Thursday a
Dec. 14, 1999, memo on the Fang proposal that Asher wrote and sent
to Jonathan E. Thackeray, Hearst's general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal had been presented by David Balabanian, a lawyer
for the Fangs, who publish the free, three-times-a-week San
Francisco Independent.
</P>
<P>
   The Fangs also are political allies of Brown and other local
politicians who had opposed Hearst's initial plans to buy the
Chronicle and shut The Examiner if it could not sell it. The
politicians said they wanted San Francisco to have at least two
daily papers.
</P>
<P>
   The Fang proposal had four main points, Asher wrote:
</P>
<P>
   Hearst would settle a lawsuit in which the Fangs claimed Hearst
had harmed them by making an illegal, below-cost bid for a city
publishing contract. Hearst later won the suit on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The Fangs would ``take The Examiner off our hands,'' but because
they believed it ``was not viable on its own . . . a cash subsidy
would be required for them to be able to operate the Examiner as a
daily newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fangs ``would want to explore obtaining some assurance from
Hearst that it would not engage in the business of distributing
free circulation newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   And, ``Assuming we reached agreement on all matters, the Fangs
would use their extensive political connections to assist us in
completing our purchase of the Chronicle.''
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning by Alioto, Asher testified that Hearst never
agreed not to publish a free paper that competed with the Fangs.
</P>
<P>
   Asher also said he concluded that the Fangs' request for $35
million a year for five years was exorbitant.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said he determined that, separated from its
profit-sharing agreement with the Chronicle, The Examiner would
lose tens of millions of dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
   And after Hearst could find no paying takers for The Examiner,
Asher said he figured it would be better to sell it for a
``negative purchase price,'' meaning Hearst would pay the buyer.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Hearst had encountered not only local political
opposition, but unexpected scrutiny from the U.S. Department of
Justice's antitrust division.
</P>
<P>
   According to Asher's memo, Balabanian insisted that Ted Fang,
publisher of the Independent, ``would be a preferred buyer of the
Examiner from the DOJ's (Department of Justice's) perspective,''
and could continue to publish the daily ``at the lowest cost'' to
Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Hearst announced it would sell The Examiner to the
Fangs and give them a subsidy of up to $66 million over 32 months
to defray publishing costs.
</P>
<P>
   A copy of The Examiner sale contract, filed in court Thursday,
shows the Fangs paid $100 cash for the paper and the subsidy. They
will get The Examiner's name, office equipment, archives, trucks
and news racks, but no staff and no buildings.
</P>
<P>
   As previously disclosed, the contract says the Fangs may bill
Hearst a maximum of $25 million per year for publishing costs, but
may keep half of each dollar that they don't spend beyond $15
million a year.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Asher confirmed, the Fangs could pocket $5 million
a year that they don't spend on The Examiner. ``There are no
strings attached to it,'' he testified.
</P>
<P>
   ``So is it correct,'' Alioto asked, ``that the less they spend
on the paper, the more they personally make?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not necessarily,'' Asher replied.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Balabanian denied Alioto's contention that the
Fang deal was designed to doom The Examiner. He noted that the
contract allows the Fangs to keep all the paper's advertising and
circulation revenue, saying that's an incentive to invest the
maximum subsidy in it.
</P>
<P>
   Balabanian said Justice Department officials likely considered
Ted Fang a ``preferred buyer'' because he had publishing experience
in San Francisco and the best chance of succeeding with The
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   But Balabanian declined to comment on the Fangs' offer to put
their political power behind Hearst's buying the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted Fang will testify fully about the entire negotiating
process'' next week, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1965, The Examiner and Chronicle have had a joint
operating agreement in which they share printing, circulation and
marketing costs, pay for them from combined revenue for both
papers, and split the remainder evenly. Each paper then pays the
costs of its independent editorial staffs.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto contends Hearst misused its position in the agreement to
ward off other potential buyers for the Chronicle by insisting any
buyer split profits with The Examiner until the agreement expires
in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   He claims that violated the intent of the Newspaper Preservation
Act and antitrust laws, and has argued that if the Chronicle was
put up for bid without that obligation, it would have drawn $1
billion or more.
</P>
<P>
   But the woman who brokered the Chronicle's proposed sale to
Hearst for $660 million last year testified that the Chronicle's
owners are getting a fair price.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Greenthal, a managing director of investment banker
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette's Boston office, said the three
next-best bids for the Chronicle were one of about $500 million
from Gannett Co., owner of USA Today; one in the low-to-mid $400
million range from Knight-Ridder, owner of the San Jose Mercury
News, and one of about $500 million from Times-Mirror, owner of the
Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   Questioned by Chronicle lawyer Greg Lindstrom, Greenthal said
these offers reflected that the buyer would have to pay Hearst its
share of revenue under the joint operating agreement. She estimated
that would come to about $15 million a year from 1999 to 2005, or
about $90 million total.
</P>
<P>
   Because buyers would get only half of the printing presses that
the Chronicle jointly owns with Hearst, they faced having to spend
more money for new presses.
</P>
<P>
   When Hearst offered $660 million, Greenthal testified, ``I
believed that it is the highest price they were going to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenthal also testified that a Hearst attempt to publish The
Examiner as an independent morning paper that economically competed
against the Chronicle would be irrational, and that The Examiner
would lose $160 million and close within three years.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning by Alioto, Greenthal said that in such a
newspaper war, the papers' advertising and subscription rates would
drop 10 to 15 percent. And if the Chronicle were the only daily
paper in San Francisco, she said, advertising rates would increase
by about 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Gary Halling, a San Francisco lawyer for the
Hearst Corp., gave an explanation about why Hearst executives did
not know earlier about Examiner Publisher White's December
deposition that he had offered San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown
support in The Examiner's editorial pages in exchange for his
backing Hearst's bid for the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Halling said Thackeray, Hearst's general counsel, was initially
at the deposition, taken by Justice Department lawyers at Hearst's
New York offices in their review of the company's proposed purchase
of the Chronicle. But Thackeray was not present for White's
testimony, said Halling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was alone in the deposition at the time,'' Halling said. ``I
saw no antitrust significance at all to that comment, and I passed
on to senior management simply that the deposition had gone very
well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 1513EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
