<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6702 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BMW-ROVER-480&AMP;ADD-NYT     05-05 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BMW-ROVER-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BMW RAISES NEW DOUBTS ABOUT DEAL ON ROVER UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Germany's Bayerische Motorenwerke AG raised new doubts
Friday about the likelihood of a deal with a British consortium to
rescue its loss-making Rover Cars operations at one of Britain's
biggest auto plants.
</P>
<P>
   BMW has been talking this week with the so-called Phoenix
Consortium, which is supported by labor unions and the British
government, after earlier negotiations with Alchemy Partners, a
British venture capital firm, collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   The myth-laden names of BMW's successive negotiating partners,
Alchemy and Phoenix, have come to reinforce a sense among analysts
that Rover will need something close to a miracle to survive.
</P>
<P>
   In developments Friday, a BMW spokesman in Munich, Germany, said
the Phoenix bid, led by former Rover chief executive John Towers,
was still under consideration but ``the financial backing is not
yet in place.'' The consortium, which is also supported by Rover
dealers, has given no indication of how it will finance its plans
to maintain Rover as a mass volume car-producer.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Jon Moulton, the head of Alchemy Partners,
told British radio that there was a ``fair chance'' that BMW would
return to a deal with Alchemy, which wants to scrap the Rover brand
and produce niche sports cars under a new MG Car Co.
</P>
<P>
   Moulton said BMW must have concluded ``that mass production of
cars at Longbridge is economic suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   But British government officials who met Friday with
representatives of Phoenix said the consortium's talks with BMW
were continuing. The government officials said Phoenix had not
asked for state aid in purchasing Rover.
</P>
<P>
   Alchemy's plan for Rover foresaw niche production of less than
100,000 cars a year, which would bring far greater lay-offs among
the 9,000 workers at Rover's main Longbridge plant near Birmingham
than the Phoenix proposal.
</P>
<P>
   BMW has said that it is losing over $3 million a day at the
Longbridge plant and that it will close the plant if it does not
find a buyer by the end of this month. The uncertainty has already
extracted a political price: The governing Labor party lost heavily
in the Longbridge area in local elections Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The gloom over the plant's prospects has spread to some labor
unionists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't get our hopes up unnecessarily, but we shouldn't
panic either,'' said Ken Jackson, the head of Britain's largest
manufacturing union. He accused BMW of sending mixed signals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we followed every nuance from Munich, we'd believe about 10
different stories,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   BMW blames its losses at Rover in part on the strength of the
British pound, which makes Rover cars expensive to export. At the
same time, cheap imported vehicles from continental Europe undercut
Britain's domestic market, which the British government says is on
average 10 percent to 12 percent more expensive than continental
European equivalents.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Yet Rover's troubles have produced the very effect that eluded
BMW's six-year, multibillion-dollar investment in the British
company.
</P>
<P>
   According to figures released Friday, Rover's car sales in April
bucked the market trend and almost doubled compared to April 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders said Rover sold
22,665 vehicles in April, just behind top-selling Ford's 24,307 and
ahead of General Motors Corp.'s Vauxhall with 21,908. Overall, new
car sales fell 8.1 percent in April because purchasers rushed in
March to buy cars with new license plates issued every six months
to indicate a vehicle's age. But Rover sales surged because of
discounts of up to $3,200 on the top-of-the-range Rover 75, despite
worries about their resale value if Rover collapses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
