<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KISSINGER-SOCCER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     KISSINGER TALKS SOCCER WITH PELE AND ENRIQUE IGLESIAS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Filed in ``w'' AND ``s'' categories.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger on Friday
engaged yet another matter of great international importance:
soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Kissinger joined Brazilian soccer great Pele and Latin singer _
and soccer fan _ Enrique Iglesias at a news conference held by the
Inter-American Development Bank to promote the world's favorite
sport to North and South America.
</P>
<P>
   Kissinger said he expects the game will become popular in the
United States soon because it is simpler than other American games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need too much equipment, you don't necessarily have
to have 11 players on a team, you don't need as much coaching,'' he
said. ``It has not yet penetrated into the minority groups in the
inner cities. It's still more a middle-class environment, but that
is only a question of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Kissinger said the men's World Cup in 1994 and women's World Cup
in 1999, which took place in the United States, failed to spark
widespread interest in the sport among Americans because of
low-scoring final games.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the Brazil beat Italy on penalty kicks after tying 0-0
through regulation and overtime. In 1999, the U.S. women defeated
China on penalty kicks after another scoreless tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans will never understand a nothing-to-nothing game,''
he said. But he predicted that soccer will enjoy great success once
there is a publicized game in the United States that ends with a
high score.
</P>
<P>
   Kissinger reported that he has not missed attending a World Cup
since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The former diplomat praised the career of Pele, who is generally
regarded as the greatest soccer player in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Pele for the first time in the 1970 World Cup and it was
really a level of football that had never been reached,'' Kissinger
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't compare anyone to Pele,'' he added, comparing Pele's
professional statistics to hitting ``80 homeruns in baseball for 15
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Kissinger explained that his own interest in soccer began at a
young age, though he was a better spectator than a participant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started my career as a goalie, and believe me, those were
not low scoring games,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   He said the professional team in his hometown of Fuerth,
Germany, won several national soccer championships when he was
young.
</P>
<P>
   Kissinger, who immigrated to the United States in 1938, recalled
that ``the spectators were so fanatical that (the team) never lost
a home game because it was dangerous for the referee'' to make
unfavorable calls.
</P>
<P>
   Kissinger said he became infatuated with the game, even lying to
his parents so he could attend matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father, who thought I needed cultural elevation, would give
me tickets to the opera. I'd take the tickets and I'd go to the
football game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kissinger, 76, served as secretary of state in the Nixon and
Ford administrations and now heads the international consulting
company he founded in New York, Kissinger Associates.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
