<HEADER>
A6749 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-RACE-WOMAN-TRAINER-HN     05-05 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-WOMAN-TRAINER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WOMAN TRAINER HOPEFUL FOR DERBY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MATT GRAVES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ A year ago, Jenine Sahadi was considering a
new line of work. Only an unwavering loyalty to her co-workers and
an unflappable passion for the game kept her marching toward a
possible rendezvous with racing history.
</P>
<P>
   No woman trainer ever has won the Kentucky Derby, but in The
Deputy, Sahadi arguably has the best chance ever to bridge the
largest gender gap associated with America's premier horse race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about quitting,'' Sahadi told reporters who swarmed
around her Thursday outside Barn 41 at Churchill Downs. ``I didn't
have anything of any consequence, but I took a look down the
shedrow one day and saw all these guys who have worked for me for
seven or eight years, and realized I'm responsible for them.''
</P>
<P>
   So she pressed on, still perplexed about having to prove herself
to owners despite winning back-to-back Breeders' Cup races in 1996
and '97 with Lit de Justice and Elmhurst.
</P>
<P>
   Racing always has been a men's club, and a couple of
million-dollar winners on racing's championship day couldn't remove
the blinders that have been worn for more than a century. A win in
the Kentucky Derby might.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's more a case of being in the right place at the
right time, because I know too many women that do just as much as I
do,'' said the 37-year-old Sahadi, who is among six trainers
saddling their first Derby horses. ``All it takes is one good horse
to motivate you to get up in the morning and get going.''
</P>
<P>
   She found that motivation when Team Valor's Barry Irwin and
co-owner Gary Barber entrusted her with The Deputy, an Irish-bred
who was unraced on dirt until this year, when Sahadi took over the
training from Englishman John Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't compare him to other horses you've had in the
past,'' said Irwin, whose Captain Bodgit finished a valiant second
in the 1997 Derby. ``You've got to treat each horse like an
individual. A lot of people can't do that. (Sahadi) can. She's very
creative and extremely talented.''
</P>
<P>
   Sahadi will have to be that and more to end this unspoken bias
and historical void in Triple Crown events. That Sahadi even has a
horse in the field is nearly history in itself. Only nine of the
712 trainers who have started horses in the Derby since 1875 were
women. Shelley Riley came closest to winning in 1992, when 29-1
long shot Casual Lies finished second behind Lil E Tee. Three have
tried since, but none had horses that finished in the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people to know there's nothing that precludes a woman
from doing this,'' Sahadi said. ``This is a common-sense thing.
This is taking the best possible care of your horse. Women don't
get the attention they maybe deserve because they don't get the
good horses. Nobody pays attention to bad horses.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, The Deputy has been a very good horse, winning three of
his four starts in this country after a six-horse campaign on grass
in England as a 2-year-old. He won a minor turf stake in January at
Santa Anita, then Sahadi made the move to the dirt. He won the
Santa Catalina over High Yield and Captain Steve, and Sahadi knew
she had a runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had been working well on the dirt, so we decided to give
him a chance,'' she said. ``He has a lot of turf in his breeding,
but he's done pretty well on the dirt.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he has improved his performance each time out of the
gate. He lost by three-quarters of a length to Derby favorite
Fusaichi Pegasus in the San Felipe, then won the Grade I Santa
Anita Derby on April 8.
</P>
<P>
   Sahadi is known as a trainer who is close to all of her horses,
and acknowledges she's a bit unconventional at times. Putting a
quarter-cup of wine in The Deputy's oats every day is a ritual not
many of her contemporaries would subscribe to.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a calming effect on him,'' said Sahadi, whose
individuality has not been lost on the local fans. ``It's been
amazing. Women have brought wine to the barn. One gentleman came by
who is Lebanese, and he had his mother make some homemade Lebanese
food. I've never seen anything like it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Sahadi sounds relaxed, it's because she is. She isn't
allowing the Derby distractions to derail her from the task at
hand, knowing it's an opportunity that might never come again. She
said she believes in her horse, though she certainly hasn't been
above taking advice from colleagues such as D. Wayne Lukas, a
four-time Derby winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sought advice from him because I knew he would offer,'' she
said. ``He was very supportive and very helpful. I was picking his
brain before we left (California).''
</P>
<P>
   Sahadi didn't have quite the same rapport with fellow trainer
Bob Baffert, who asked jockey Chris McCarron who was really
training The Deputy in a news conference before the Santa Anita
Derby. Sahadi stormed off the podium moments later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's over and behind us now,'' Baffert said. ``I was joking
with McCarron. I didn't mean anything by it toward her.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the exchange left a bad taste, reminiscent as it was of
the stereotyping Sahadi had seen before. She had the last word when
The Deputy won by three lengths over Baffert's Captain Steve.
</P>
<P>
   Now the big prize dangles before Sahadi, and a chance to make
previously unreachable inroads for her gender. She prefers to see
it not as a crusade, but as a chance to put another feather in her
professional cap, and a big one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to win the Derby; it would be wonderful, but I don't
spend every waking moment thinking about it,'' she said. ``I know
it's the biggest race in the world. It's sort of like the World
Cup, the World Series and the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   And certainly more exciting than whatever world she might have
entered had she walked away.
</P>
</TEXT>
