<SLUG> BC-RAC-COMMEDIAN-TRAINER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TRAINER OF CAPTAIN STEVE SAYS DON'T PEAK TOO SOON _ BUT PEAK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JIM DENT  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ The $4 million monster known as Fusaichi
Pegasus swaggered down the track, causing trainer/comedian Bob
Baffert to cock his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder how he's going to feel,'' Baffert said, ``when my
little ol' $70,000 horse runs right past him on Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert likes to poke fun at anything and everyone, including
himself. But what he's said lately about Captain Steve, his latest
Kentucky Derby sensation, doesn't qualify as humor.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert might chuckle when he says it. But he's neck deep in
sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Captain Steve just couldn't be any more ready to go,'' he
said. ``I've never had a horse as ready to go in Kentucky as this
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the talk sweeping this town is of Fusaichi Pegasus,
who is fueling hopes of a Triple Crown championship even before
setting hoof in the starting gate at Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   He is the most physically developed 3-year-old to pass in front
of these eyes since Secretariat. He is also the ``crazy horse,''
the one who bucked more than a rodeo bronco a couple of days ago
before a morning workout.
</P>
<P>
   But if Baffert is writing the story line here on Saturday, it
will be Rich Horse-Poor Horse. Baffert began spreading that word
the moment the media army dug in its heels outside of Barn 33 a few
days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golly, I've never had the kind of money to buy a horse like
that,'' Baffert said of Fusaichi Pegasus. ``I sure hope he is worth
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Baffert can put his money where his mouth is. Silver
Charm, his 1997 Kentucky Derby champion, was bought at a sale for
$80,000.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Baffert's Real Quiet won the Derby, the Preakness
and came within a nose of taking the Triple Crown. And he cost the
grand sum of $17,000.
</P>
<P>
   You can barely buy a Honda with that kind of money.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, Baffert's owners love him. Not only has he won
two of the last three Derbys with relatively cheap horses, he came
within a breath of taking the 1996 roses when Cavonnier fell to
Grindstone by a nostril.
</P>
<P>
   The man has a formula, and it's quite simple. Don't peak too
soon. But make sure you peak.
</P>
<P>
   For example, his last two Kentucky Derby winners finished second
in their final tuneup, the Santa Anita Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Almost following suit, Captain Steve finished third at the Santa
Anita Derby four weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Then something quite Baffert-like happened. The horse started to
train better, eat more, cruise without blinkers and, as the trainer
said, ``his feet stopped hurting.''
</P>
<P>
   Voila! It's Baffert magic. His horses simply run their best on
the first Saturday of each May.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the wand he waves, Baffert isn't the most popular guy
on the back side of the track, where trainers don't wear $200
shades, or have flowing silver hair.
</P>
<P>
   They wear hats and boots and spit a stream of Red Man between
broken sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not all of them. But most are blue collar compared to
Baffert's California cool.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing that Baffert has going for him is a warm-hearted
human interest story.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Steve is named for Captain Steve Thompson, commander of
the criminal investigations unit with the Louisville Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   When horse owner Mike Pegram was arrested at the Louisville
Airport for unwittingly packing a .357 in his carry-on bag in 1997,
it was Thompson who convinced airport officials not to file
charges.
</P>
<P>
   As gratitude, Pegram named one of his top 3-year olds after
Captain Steve. And wouldn't you know it? The horse would be good
enough to play in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, Baffert and Pegram have been soaking up the media
spotlight this week, and that is good for business.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of D. Wayne Lukas, there is no one close to Baffert when
it comes to media friendliness.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to Bob Baffert, it seems the rich get richer.
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute. He's the guy with the poor-man's horse, isn't he?
</P>
</TEXT>
