<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  CORRECTED VOTE CHART WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions
regarding this transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100,
ext. 230. NOTE: TWO SENATE VOTES ON THURSDAY WERE UNAVAILABLE FOR
THIS WEEK'S CHART. THEY WILL BE INCLUDED IN NEXT WEEK'S VOTE CHART.
WASHINGTON, May 5 -- The following chart shows how senators and
representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the last
week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: NUKE
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Tuesday failed to reach a two-thirds margin to
override President Clinton's veto of a bill to create a nuclear
waste disposal site in Nevada. Senators voted 64 to 35. The bill
would transfer more than 40,000 tons of highly radioactive waste
now held in nuclear storage facilities around the country to Yucca
Mountain in 2007. Supporters of overriding the veto said a quick
solution is needed to dispose of waste. Opponents of an override
said the location was environmentally unsound. A ``yes'' vote
favors the override.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: VOUCHERS
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Wednesday approved, 98-0, an amendment to limit
the authority of states to distribute federal private school
vouchers. The amendment, attached to an education spending bill,
prohibits 15 states that could choose to receive federal block
grants from using vouchers to pay students' private school tuition.
Supporters said public money should not be used to pay private
school tuitions. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2
</P>
<P>
   --- ---
</P>
<P>
   SANTORUM (R-PA) Y Y
</P>
<P>
   SPECTER (R-PA) Y Y
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: HMONG
</P>
<P>
   The House on Tuesday unanimously approved a bill to allow Hmong
immigrants who assisted the CIA during the Vietnam War to take
United States citizenship exams with translators. The measure
exempts the 45,000 immigrants from rules prohibiting use of
translators during the test. Supporters said the bill is necessary
because the Hmong culture did not have a written language until the
1950s, so many Hmong immigrants fail U.S. citizenship tests.
Tallies are unavailable because the measure passed by a voice vote.
</P>
