<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6808 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CENSUS-CONGRESS06-COX     05-05 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-CONGRESS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE REPUBLICANS ACCUSE CENSUS HEAD OF PLAYING POLITICS
 &HT;    460&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Stoking the issue of privacy rights, House
Republicans on Friday accused the Census Bureau director of playing
politics by criticizing GOP leaders who suggested that Americans
need not fill out their census questionnaires.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla., chairman of the House subcommittee on
the census, said the census long form and its probing questions,
not Republican comments about it, sparked the public controversy
that prompted some Americans to decline to answer some questions or
refuse to return the form altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said Kenneth Prewitt, a career scholar and White House
appointee as census director, was ``attempting to politicize the
census at this crucial period in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush and Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, among others, suggested last month that
Americans should not have to answer questions they believe violate
their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials said Prewitt's recent remarks have been
directed at both congressional leaders and the White House for
failing to join voices in a bipartisan effort to trumpet what
should be regarded as a patriotic duty.
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance Friday before the House subcommittee, Prewitt
challenged Miller to produce evidence that he had ever directly
criticized Republican leaders. ``I don't believe that such a quote
exists,'' Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt repeated his contention, though, that ``national public
voices'' picked an inappropriate time _ with the public's attention
focused on the census through an extensive ad campaign _ to suggest
that the questionnaire, which is mandated by the Constitution, was
optional.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was not a good moment to talk about the census as a
'pick-and-choose' opportunity,'' Prewitt told the subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Miller's criticism of Prewitt, Rep. Carolyn
Maloney, D-N.Y., said Republican leaders were trying to ``pander to
talk shows and right-wing fringe groups'' in an effort to ``trash''
the census for political gain.
</P>
<P>
   Most of America's 120 million households received the short
form, with eight basic questions. One in six received the long
form, with 53 questions, including details about income, lifestyle
and housing.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the climate of public resistance, Census Bureau officials
said there was no evidence thus far to suggest that census takers,
known as enumerators, are being rebuffed at a greater rate as they
go door to door compared to 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The 500,000 census-takers have run into problems, though. Census
Bureau officials have recorded 212 incidents of dog bites, a bad
bee sting and four episodes in Alaska where the enumerators were
met at the door by a homeowner with a gun. None of the gun
incidents resulted in violence.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Census-takers so far have canvassed about 8 percent of the 42
million households that did not return questionnaires, roughly
matching the agency's expectations to date. The door-to-door effort
to reach the remainder of homes continues through mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   Census Bureau officials believe that if the controversy had not
erupted the agency would have come closer to reaching its national
goal of a 70 percent response rate.
</P>
<P>
   With a mail-back response rate nearing 66 percent, the Census
Bureau managed to halt a three-decade slide in the share of
American households that return the form. The slight gain from
1990's 65 percent response rate came largely on a strong response
from Hispanics and African-Americans, who were targeted among other
minority groups by the Census Bureau's promotional campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Participation in the census, as in other civic acts like voting,
has been in decline. In 1980, 75 percent of households returned
their census forms compared with 83 percent in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The rate is an important factor is producing an accurate census
and in reducing the cost of the once-a-decade national count. The
Government Accounting Office estimates a savings of $34 million for
each percentage point above 61 percent, the level used as a
benchmark for planning the census.
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
