<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6809 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-EDUCATION-CONGRESS-$A     05-05 1335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-CONGRESS-$ADV07-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EDUCATION BECOMES AN EXPLOSIVE ISSUE FOR SENATORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, May 7)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For 35 years, Congress and the White House have
joined in bipartisan harmony to dole out federal money for
education. But election year politics have thrust the program into
turbulence this year, and one veteran senator says he has never
seen anything like the political storm swirling around education.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers traditionally have had differences over how to spend
billions of federal education dollars, with Republicans wanting to
cede more control to local governments and Democrats favoring more
spending for federally designated programs.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, however, the senators charged with updating the
five-year Elementary and Secondary Education Act were especially
unyielding over how to spend $14 billion that pays for more than 50
educational programs, most of which are aimed helping disadvantaged
students. The debate resumes this week, with little chance for
quick resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government provides just 7 percent of the money for
public schools, but the policy set by Congress often guides
spending decisions on the state and local levels.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., a leader on education issues,
said he has never seen such partisan ``edge'' over the
reauthorization of the major education legislation. The law was
first signed by President Lyndon B. Johnson in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Elementary and Secondary Education Act has never been a
partisan issue before this year,'' Kennedy said in an interview.
``This is the first time in history.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said he detects ``very little indication of a
willingness'' to compromise on the part of the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said the Republicans, who are pushing block grants that
would give more local control over the federal spending, want ``a
radical departure'' from the current formula. He added he would be
enthusiastic about changing the funding formula when Congress has
more time, but said it won't work now, with 45 days left in the
session.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the partisan rancor is the presidential race, with
Republican George W. Bush and Democrat Al Gore touting education
proposals almost daily.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Democrats are floating volatile gun amendments they
want to add to the education measure that could cause a stalemate
in the Senate and prompt Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., to
remove the bill from consideration.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress fails to reauthorize the five-year education bill,
congressional appropriators would allocate money for the existing
programs year by year. But House Education and Workforce Chairman
Bill Goodling, R-Pa., a former school superintendent, said that
would be a shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll go on appropriating for programs that don't work,''
Goodling said. If that happens, ``you haven't improved anything,
you just hand out a check.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodling said the $130 billion spent on programs for
disadvantaged students since the program began in 1965 has done
little to close the achievement gap because schools have not been
held responsible for getting better results. That federal money has
gone mainly for hiring aides to instruct children on reading and
math, but Goodling said many of them are not well qualified because
of low hiring standards.
</P>
<P>
   Goodling said he feared election-year politics ``unfortunately''
may derail the Senate bill. ``If you don't get things done in the
first year, it's very hard to get them done,'' Goodling said.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, the education bill is split into seven pieces,
which would have to be merged with a Senate bill, if the Senate
passes a bill. So far four of the seven components of the House
legislation have been approved and two are expected to come up in
the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The most contentious issues in the Senate bill are proposals
pushed by Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H. One provision under fire from
Senate Democrats, known as the ``Straight A's'' proposal, would set
up a pilot program to allow 15 states to spend their share of the
federal money as they choose, as long as they get good academic
results.
</P>
<P>
   Another proposal under attack _ known as ``portability'' _ would
allow states to let parents of disadvantaged children to remove
their child from existing programs and spend their child's share of
the money (an average of $500 per year) to enroll in another public
school, in an after-school program or to hire a tutor.
</P>
<P>
   A third GOP proposal would let states allow parents to take any
child out of a failing public school and enroll in a better one if
the school has been designated as failing by the state for two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg said his proposals would let states and school districts
try new approaches to help children learn. ``Local people know what
works best for educating their kids,'' Gregg said.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg said the Republican approach is ``like a cafeteria line''
that allows states to choose.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. John F. Kerry, D-Mass., said the Republican proposals
would strip money away from the schools that are most in need.
``Great schools will get a windfall of money that comes to them at
the expense of schools that need it more,'' Kerry said.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democratic leader Thomas A. Daschle of South Dakota
slammed the Republican approach as equivalent to writing a ``blank
check.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and a large bloc of Democrats have their own
plans for public education.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic proposals would provide $1.3 billion in grants and
loans to fix deteriorating schools; to shrink class sizes by hiring
100,000 teachers; invest $2 billion next year to help states
recruit and train teachers; and provide $1 billion next year to pay
for an after-school program.
</P>
<P>
   But there is even dissension among Democrats. Sen. Joseph I.
Lieberman, D-Conn., chairman of the moderate Democratic leadership
council, and Sen. Evan Bayh, D-Ind., seek to broker a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Their plan would boost funding by $35 billion over five years,
rewarding states that exceed their academic performance goals,
while cutting funds to states that don't meet them.
</P>
<P>
   The moderate Democrats' plan would condense all of the federal
programs into five grants aimed at general goals: closing the
achievement gap between minorities and white students; helping
immigrants with academics; improving teacher quality; providing
more choices among public schools; and testing new teaching ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said the proposal would keep federal spending focused
on broad goals while eliminating many of the programs that have
multiplied over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., said Republicans are listening to the
Democrats who are trying to reach a middle ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are forces out there that are truly looking for another
approach,'' Mack said. ``But the forces of gridlock are always out
there lurking.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the question of how to improve public education
arises almost daily on the presidential campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's Republican campaign is calling for more flexibility for
states and local governments in spending money from Washington and
wants vouchers to pull children out of failing public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Gore echoes many of his fellow Democrats in calling for
universal preschool, teacher testing and programs to repair school
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton last week embarked on a two-day tour of public schools
in Kentucky, Iowa, Minnesota and Ohio to draw attention to his
proposals to hold failing schools more accountable, boost school
construction, open more charter schools and improve teacher
quality. Clinton, who hopes to burnish his legacy as the education
president, has threatened to veto the initiatives contained in the
Republican bill.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address judy(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
