<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6814 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SIERRA-LEONE-U.N.-(TR     05-05 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-U.N.-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBELS IN SIERRA LEONE HOLDING MORE THAN 300 U.N. PERSONNEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ In their most audacious baiting of the U.N.
peacekeeping mission in Sierra Leone so far, rebel fighters
disarmed an entire convoy of Zambian peacekeepers, took the 208
soldiers hostage and appeared to be driving 13 hijacked armored
personnel carriers toward the capital, U.N. officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The convoy, which was dispatched from Lungi, a port town, to
reinforce other peacekeeping troops at Makeni in central Sierra
Leone, lost radio contact on Thursday with the U.N. mission in
Freetown, the capital of the battered West African country. That
prompted concern about their fate.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the chief spokesman of the United Nations, Fred Eckhard,
said the 208 Zambians had been detained, bringing to 318 the number
of U.N. peacekeepers believed to be held by the Revolutionary
United Front, as the insurgents call themselves.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``While there has been no word of fighting in Sierra Leone
today,'' Eckhard said, ``we have received as of yet unconfirmed
information of military movement by the Revolutionary United Front,
possibly involving the use of U.N. armored personnel carriers.''
</P>
<P>
   Another U.N. official said the distinctive troop carriers, which
are white with the bold black identifying letters ``U.N.,'' had
been sighted by helicopter surveillance flights. The armored
personnel carriers, he said, had changed direction and were last
seen heading back toward Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether the rebels were driving the vehicles or
forcing Zambians to do it. It also remained unclear how an armored
convoy could have been overwhelmed without a fight by guerrillas
who normally carry light weapons.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The deterioration of the precarious peace achieved in Sierra
Leone has increased pressure on U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
to achieve a solution to the United Nations' newest crisis in
Africa. Annan expressed concern in Paris on Thursday that the
setbacks could give member countries second thoughts about
contributing troops to a peacekeeping operation being assembled in
Congo.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels on Friday released a four-man Russian helicopter crew
and two passengers who had been detained Tuesday in eastern Sierra
Leone. They were permitted to fly back to Freetown after the
Liberian president, Charles Taylor, who has been sympathetic to the
rebels, called their leader, Foday Sankoh, on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Taylor told the secretary-general yesterday that he
had been tough with Sankoh in the phone conversation he had with
him,'' Eckhard said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Annan has requested help from the leaders of Algeria, Burkina
Faso, Libya, Mali, Nigeria and Togo in interceding with the rebel
leader, who has denied that his fighters are holding any U.N.
peacekeepers hostage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The efforts right now are political in nature,'' Eckhard said,
and attempt to induce leaders with influence over Sankoh to make
him comply with the terms of the peace agreement he accepted last
year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 208 Zambian soldiers, an estimated 110 other
U.N. peacekeepers, military observers and civilian workers are
being held by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Another 100 or so soldiers from a Nigerian unit near Kambia, in
northwestern Sierra Leone, were detained by the rebels and released
without their weapons.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the clashes that erupted early this week, four
Kenyan soldiers are missing and presumed dead, and 12 peacekeepers
are wounded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 1601EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6835 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-DAUGHTERS-ART-NY     05-05 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DAUGHTERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOTLIGHT HAS SPARED THE BUSH GIRLS SO FAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: NYT Photo 4 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FRANK BRUNI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Monday was Decision Day for many high school
seniors choosing colleges, but it came and went without so much as
a peep from the Bush campaign about the destinations of Gov. George
W. Bush's twin 18-year-old daughters, Barbara and Jenna.
</P>
<P>
   How far from home would they be straying? The Texas governor's
aides were silent. What factors had the girls' final selection
hinged on? Mum was the word. Aides acknowledged that the
information would probably trickle out soon enough, through an
unguarded utterance by Bush or an offhand comment by an official at
one of the schools. But for just a bit longer, the family wanted to
try to preserve the girls' privacy.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush family has been remarkably successful at that, so much
so that while Bush could become the next president and while his
extended family is beginning to look an awful lot like a political
dynasty, his two daughters are almost invisible, their faces
unknown to 99.9 percent of voters outside Texas and their public
sightings only slightly more frequent than Bigfoot's.
</P>
<P>
   They have appeared only a few times on the campaign trail, and
they have not shown up in their father's commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the time he was elected governor, we've had a policy that
the girls are not interviewed and not photographed,'' said Karen
Hughes, the communications director for the Bush campaign and a
senior adviser to Bush since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Far from being out of the ordinary, the daughters' anonymity
immediately recalls that of Chelsea Clinton during her father's
first presidential campaign, in 1992, and is shared to a degree by
the three younger Gore children. (The oldest, Karenna Gore Schiff,
26, has a public role as an adviser to her father's presidential
campaign.)
</P>
<P>
   And it proves that even in an age when politicians will use most
facets of their biographies to market themselves and the press
shines a spotlight into many corners of a politician's private
life, there remains at least one largely unexploited, scrutiny-free
zone. The children are spared.
</P>
<P>
   Although President Clinton and his wife, Hillary, have often
been portrayed as indiscriminately ambitious, Tom Rosenstiel,
director of the Project for Excellence in Journalism in Washington,
noted that ``for the most part, the Clintons have not used Chelsea
as a campaign tool.''
</P>
<P>
   In turn, Rosenstiel said, ``for all of the controversy and
invasiveness of the press coverage concerning Bill Clinton, with a
handful of exceptions, the press has respected the Clintons' wish
to leave Chelsea alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has similarly benefited from news organizations' voluntary
restraint. Austin is not so big a place, and there are reporters
whose children _ or whose friends' children _ attend the same
public high school from which Barbara and Jenna Bush will be
graduating this month. But the fruits of that familiarity have not
found their way onto television or into newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Bush trusts reporters on his campaign plane to be
cognizant of, and to respect, his wishes that his daughters remain
journalistically off-limits, and he thus talks somewhat freely
about them on occasion and even mentioned, several times, the kinds
of colleges each daughter was considering.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara, named for her paternal grandmother, actually hopped
aboard the campaign plane on Saturday and used it as her
transportation from Austin to New York City to take a last look at
one of the colleges near the top of her list. But she kept a
careful distance from reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenstiel and several political press secretaries said there
seemed to be an unspoken covenant between politicians and
journalists: If a politician does not press his or her children
into sustained service as political props, journalists have little
rationale for examining in detail the children's lives, at least
when the children are still school-age.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts noted that while most candidates and elected
officials undoubtedly keep their children offstage to protect them,
there may be political benefit as well, in that voters are likely
to take note of, and admire, that course of action.
</P>
<P>
   The personal-biography section of Bush's Web site digresses to
mention, ``Governor and Mrs. Bush have worked hard to protect their
daughters' privacy. They attend public school in Austin but do not
give interviews and only appear at public events if they want to.''
</P>
<P>
   In public, Bush walks a carefully but not always consistently
drawn line. He sporadically delights audiences with a fleeting,
vague riff on the agonies and ecstasies of fatherhood and
repeatedly mentions that Barbara and Jenna go to a public high
school. But he generally furnishes no more specifics about them
than about the family's six-toed cat, Ernie.
</P>
<P>
   There are exceptions to this reticence, the most conspicuous one
being a chapter of his autobiography, ``A Charge to Keep'' (William
Morrow &AMP; Co., 1999), in which Bush discusses his support for the
death penalty. He divulges that one daughter _ he does not say
which _ told him over the dinner table that she disagrees with him.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his wife, Laura, have said repeatedly that they want
Barbara and Jenna, fraternal twins who are the couple's only
children, to be affected by their father's political celebrity as
little as possible.
</P>
<P>
   From what little has been published or broadcast in Texas about
the girls, they have managed to maintain relatively normal lives.
</P>
<P>
   When the family first moved to Austin, the girls attended the
St. Andrews Episcopal School here, but they transferred to Austin
High School in the ninth grade.
</P>
<P>
   And they behaved as teen-agers typically do, bowing to the
latest pop-cultural fashions and sometimes remarking on how
unfashionable their father was. In interviews with Texas
journalists in the past, Bush bemoaned that the girls'
television-watching habits, at least a few years ago, included
``Beverly Hills 90210'' and ``Melrose Place,'' and noted that they
would sometimes stop their father before he walked out the door,
questioning his choice of attire.
</P>
<P>
   Even as a governor's children, they were not constantly escorted
or monitored by guards, but security around the entire family
tightened earlier this year with the arrival of the Secret Service,
much to the girls chagrin, an aide to Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their friends can no longer pull in the back driveway of the
governor's mansion or just drop in and out,'' the aide said.
``That's no fun for teen-age girls, and that's been a big change
for them.
</P>
<P>
   According to the aide and several of Bush's friends, the girls'
low public profile reflects their own desires as much as their
parents' efforts. For example, Barbara and Jenna Bush briefly
considered accompanying their parents to the polls in Texas for the
Republican primary; it was, after all, the first election cycle in
which the girls were old enough to vote.
</P>
<P>
   But when they found out that photographers would be chronicling
their father's movements, they decided not to go. Similarly,
Barbara and Jenna appeared on stage with their father only twice in
the primaries: once in New Hampshire, on the night that he lost to
Sen. John McCain of Arizona, and once in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   One of Bush's advisers said Barbara and Jenna Bush had learned
early on that even the most seemingly harmless exposure could yield
accidental humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   About six years ago, when a television crew shot footage of the
Bushes decorating their Christmas tree, the telephone rang and Bush
joked that it might be a boy who liked Jenna. When the story was
broadcast, it included both that comment and Jenna's mortified
reaction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
