<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6844 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-POET-DOC0506-COX     05-05 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POET-DOC0506-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bard of medicine
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Jacques Hyppolite Guiteau did not hesitate
when he reached the great fork in life's road, the one that leads
cool and logical left brainers to calculus class and dreamy right
brainers to a writer's garret.
</P>
<P>
   He went both ways.
</P>
<P>
   Guiteau began writing poetry at age 12 in his native Haiti and
was buoyed by the warm response from his family, friends and
teachers, but he already had medical school in mind. He managed to
fuse both interests throughout his school years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In college, I majored in French, Greek and Latin,'' he says.
``It made medical school easier. I understood the roots of many
medical terms. They immediately made sense.''
</P>
<P>
   As a student, he carried the works of Jean-Baptiste Rousseau,
Alphonse de Lamartine and other French poets along with his medical
texts. As a doctor, he carries their inspiration along with the
stress of his family practice in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deal with suffering on a daily basis,'' he says. ``If I see
30 patients, that means 30 problems I have to solve. The mind is
always busy. It needs a diversion. That is what poetry does for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Guiteau, 50, has drawn emotional balm from the role of bard
throughout his medical career. In Haiti, he wrote love poems to his
wife, Frantz, while interning at a tuberculosis hospital in
Port-au-Prince. Later, as the only Haitian-born physician in Palm
Beach County, he shouldered a heavy load from West Palm Beach to
Belle Glade.
</P>
<P>
   His community health work won him the honor of Palm Beach County
Doctor of the Year from the state Department of Health and
Rehabilitative Services in 1992. But it challenged his spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was treating AIDS patients for four years, and I got burned
out,'' he says. ``There was very little you could do for people
with AIDS in those days. I had one entire family _ mom, dad and the
kids, all with AIDS. It was devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   Guiteau found comfort by conjuring images of his own wife and
three children and of his childhood in Haiti. He still does.
Between raging fevers and broken arms, between failing hearts and
aching stomachs, Guiteau steals a little time for his own soul. He
retreats to his office, closes the door and picks up a pen.
</P>
<P>
   DREAMING WITH OPEN EYES
</P>
<P>
   Seated in my office watching the
</P>
<P>
   rooftops
</P>
<P>
   Your image appears before me
</P>
<P>
   What can I do
</P>
<P>
   to stop the phantom
</P>
<P>
   which follows me
</P>
<P>
   like a shadow
</P>
<P>
   And does nothing but persist
</P>
<P>
   as time passes?
</P>
<P>
   Day and night blend together
</P>
<P>
   to enfold you in me infinitely
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for his patients, Guiteau is blessed with a
compliant muse. ``I never spend more than 15 minutes on a poem,''
he says. ``It just comes to me.'' So he can be serious about poetry
and medicine without choosing between them.
</P>
<P>
   It's a luxury few others have enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   John Keats was apprenticed to a surgeon as a teenager but quit
medicine after a year of formal study. He barely had time to share
his own daydream about a Grecian urn before he died at age 26 in
1824.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Conan Doyle had a family practice in Scotland but wrote
stories and poems on the side to make ends meet. Doyle's poetry is
not nearly as well-remembered as his tales of a detective named
Sherlock Holmes. He quit medicine at the height of Holmes'
popularity, then returned years later to become an army surgeon. He
died in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   William Carlos Williams is probably the best-known doctor-poet
of the 20th century. Williams, who died in 1963, won acclaim for
evocative images of such unlikely subjects as plums, wheelbarrows
and Paterson, N.J. He kept up his medical practice throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike those predecessors, Guiteau has not had to deal with the
distraction of literary fame. He wouldn't mind trying. He took his
first big step in 1994 when he released a French-language poetry
CD, ``Les Sons Du Coeur, Poemes en Musique.'' It was an ambitious
project: Guiteau hired a narrator and commissioned an original
background score. It cost him $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted something different,'' he says. ``Sometimes, when you
read poetry, it gets tiring. But if you listen, and you have nice
music to go along with it, that may keep you interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Guiteau says he shipped some to France and Canada and sold
others locally. Some were bought by patients _ posters advertising
his CDs are interspersed with awards and framed poems along the
walls of his waiting room _ and others by the Haitian community,
where Guiteau is well known as longtime host of a radio show and
for his community activities, including an annual health fair.
</P>
<P>
   How many copies was that in all? He smiles at the question. ``I
still have a few,'' he says. ``It's something the public is not
used to.''
</P>
<P>
   He has enough faith in the form to keep trying. He released a
``Happy Millennium'' CD to celebrate the New Year.
</P>
<P>
   LOVE, BE THE MOTIVATOR OF THIS NEW YEAR
</P>
<P>
   In order that all become loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   Not to forget as well the unfortunate ones.
</P>
<P>
   They also merit our kindness
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, for Valentine's Day, he released an English-language
version of the first collection, ``Sounds of the Heart.'' Both
English releases are available through Internet vendors.
</P>
<P>
   Guiteau will waste no time watching the Billboard charts, or
waiting for a call from the Pulitzer Prize committee. His
satisfaction comes from within, and from the certainty that at
least some of the people who hear his poetry will be touched by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan to make a new CD every year,'' he says, adding that he
is unlikely to change his theme. ``I tell people: Love makes life
easier for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
