<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MYSTERY-WRITERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK COLUMN: CHAPTER ONE: A MURDER MOST JUICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Bold type should be set in italics.)  
 By CLYDE HABERMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
 &UR; She was standing outside my office, her long blond hair cascading
like Niagara Falls down her shoulder. One look at those legs, and I
knew this one would be trouble.  &LR;  Hang on, hang on, hang on. That
doesn't sound right. Let's start over.
 &UR; Ruby Slade had done an awful lot of living for someone on the near
side of 20. Not much of it was good.  &LR;  No, that doesn't make it,
either. Dang, this business of writing a mystery story is harder
than it looks.
</P>
<P>
   But it took a swing by the Grand Hyatt Hotel the other day to
realize just how difficult making a go of it can be. Really hard.
But doable.
</P>
<P>
   That seemed to be the message of a symposium held at the hotel
for the benefit of hopeful men and women with visions of becoming
the next Grisham or Cornwell. Some had already been published, and
more than once. But they were still in search of the big kahuna,
the book that could bring megadeals and a one-way ticket to La-La
Land.
</P>
<P>
   The conference was organized by the Mystery Writers of America,
and was one of several events leading to the group's presentation
of its annual Edgar Allan Poe Awards Thursday night. What happened
at the awards dinner is itself a mystery to us, though. We never
made it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dress to kill,'' the invitation said. But nothing in the
closet remotely worked. You try living with clothes that can't even
wound, let alone kill. So we stuck with the symposium, which
offered hints from writers, editors and publishers on how to go
about shaping suspense tales to die for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who has a really good mystery could be tomorrow's
millionaire,'' said Walter Wager, who has not done badly for
himself at this craft. One of his books, ``58 Minutes,'' was the
basis for the movie ``Die Hard 2.''
</P>
<P>
   He mentioned that he has a new novel called ``Tunnel''
(Forge/Tom Doherty and Associates), about former East German agents
who, Wager said, ``go for a big heist and hijack the Lincoln
Tunnel.'' Frankly, we thought that had been done, by the Port
Authority of New York and New Jersey. But why not try a variation?
</P>
<P>
   The good news at this symposium was that the mystery novel _ or
``crime fiction,'' as the writer Lawrence Block preferred _ remains
a vibrant form.
</P>
<P>
   Some people have fretted that it may be done in by today's lower
homicide rates. You may recall that similar concerns were expressed
about the suspense thriller soon after the Cold War ended. But
there are always fresh villains in need of a good throttling. If
not the Soviets, then the Iraqis. If not Iraqis, then Serbs. After
the Serbs, who knows? Why not the dot-com geeks?
</P>
<P>
   And all a mystery writer needs, after all, is one good juicy
murder.
</P>
<P>
   That and an agent, cautioned John Baker, editorial director of
Publishers Weekly. Mary Higgins Clark, the best-selling author,
agreed. Without an agent, she said, ``it's almost impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with one, life for a writer today can be an ordeal, said
John Feldcamp, chief executive officer of Xlibris, an online
publishing services company in Philadelphia. The major publishing
houses are taking on fewer new mystery writers, he and others said.
Their focus seems to be more on brand-name authors who will land on
best-seller lists as surely as Leonardo DiCaprio will wind up
bold-faced in gossip columns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're holding a first novel in your hand right now,''
Feldcamp said, ``your chances of being published are one in 400.''
</P>
<P>
   A collective gasp of surprise and dismay arose from some in the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but there are ways to improve the odds, speakers advised.
</P>
<P>
   Like giving your sleuth an interesting specialty. (No reason why
someone who goes antiquing couldn't find himself wrapped in a
mystery, Baker said.) Or like writing in depth about a place. Or
maybe putting a child in danger. ``A missing child is a grabber,''
Clark said. ``I've left kids alone for a while, but if things get
tough, you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   No one argued with Baker when he said that even more than a good
plot, a mystery writer must have a strong voice. OK, we can do
that.
</P>
<P>
   Then he added, ``Editors seem to be looking for a sassy female
voice these days.'' Gulp! Where does that leave us Y chromosome
types?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the answer is to take Clark's advice, maybe with a
ripped-from-the-headlines twist. That's it! Forget the blonde.
 &UR; Elian Gonzalez had done an awful lot of living for someone on the
near side of 7. Not much of it was good.  &LR;  It sings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
