<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6877 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-Y2K-SURVIVAL-NYT &LR;      05-05 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-SURVIVAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A PREPAREDNESS STORE, NO BAD NEWS IS NOT GOOD NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Note spelling of dateline is different from Allegheny
River.) 
 By DAN BARRY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALLEGANY, N.Y. _ The gas masks are gone. The camouflage outfits
and combat knives, the first-aid kits and how-to manuals for
building underground shelters. All gone.
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse, that Y2K disaster thing never happened. So
Dave Boser and Bill Baxter, owners of the Survival Preparedness
Center on Main Street here, had no choice but to shut it down a
couple of weeks ago. Now the dedicated campers and those
lock-and-load militia boys from the surrounding hills of western
New York will have to go elsewhere for their dehydrated fruit mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before Y2K, there were so many people in the store that we
couldn't take care of them,'' Baxter said Saturday, his voice
echoing in the nearly empty store. The ensuing silence spoke to the
dramatic drop in business after New Year's Day _ when a feared
computer problem did not cast the world into darkness and the dawn
of the year 2000 did not bring nuclear winter.
</P>
<P>
   In the corner sat size 10 cans of ``Provident Pantry''
dehydrated food _ elbow macaroni, blueberry muffins, egg whites _
that will keep for a decade. Nearby was half a case of 100-hour
paraffin candles. Still taped to the wall, just above the now-empty
knife case, were the business cards of recruiters for the Navy and
the Marines.
</P>
<P>
   But the preparedness entrepreneurs have not abandoned their
business. They plan to put together a catalog of their merchandise,
and have hopes of selling some of the leftover inventory at cost. A
Mormon church in the area has already expressed interest in their
429 cans of dehydrated food.
</P>
<P>
   And who knows when fear of a looming disaster might drum up some
more interest?
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the two men now have the kind of customer
service experience not to be found at the Wal-Mart store just two
miles down the road. They have loaded up the cars of two women
known as the ``Y2K queens,'' witnessed firsthand the economic
impact of prophecies, and rung up sales for skinheads from Altoona,
Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of smart people out there,'' Boser said, peering
from under his ``Vietnam Veteran &AMP; Proud of It'' hat. ``And a lot
of dumb people.''
</P>
<P>
   Allegany is a small town of 8,500 people along New York's
Southern Tier, about 60 miles south of Buffalo. It is a place where
the Allegheny River beckons and the foothills lend crispness to the
air, a place where students from nearby Saint Bonaventure
University come to live for a while, then leave. But the farmers
and the shop owners, the Dave Bosers and Bill Baxters, stay; it is
their home.
</P>
<P>
   Boser, 49, is a machinist now, but the year he spent soldiering
in Vietnam shaped his worldview; his key chain features the POW/MIA
logo. Baxter, 47, works at the water treatment plant in Olean, a
few miles away. They both smoke, drink beer, stay rail-thin
somehow, and share an interest in the accouterments of survival
preparedness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always saved stuff for whatever happened,'' Boser
explained. ``Storms, tornadoes, my daughter's car breaking down.
And it's not just meals. It's first-aid kits, radios, packs of
water, camping supplies.''
</P>
<P>
   By the fall of 1998, word spread among the campers, hunters and
survivalists in the area that Boser and Baxter were buying supplies
at various outlets, partly in anticipation of the year 2000. The
two men soon found themselves putting in orders for other people.
Then it struck them: they should open their own shop.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, a new presence had established itself among the bars,
restaurants and shops of downtown Allegany.
</P>
<P>
   Baxter spoke with pride of the wares their store once offered.
The camouflage outfits in ``United Nations, European and, of
course, American'' styles were popular with local militia types, as
well as with people who liked to play paintball. The combat knives
sold fairly well, as did the manuals on map reading.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the goods were geared for everyone from casual campers
to those with an abiding distrust of government. The hand-cranked
radios, for example, were big sellers around Christmas. Another big
hit was the dehydrated pudding, in chocolate, vanilla and banana.
</P>
<P>
   For more discerning consumers, specialized items were also
available: your Israeli gas masks, your samurai swords. Baxter said
that a doctor from Jamestown once came in to buy a bulletproof vest
and a helmet; they later learned that he performed abortions.
</P>
<P>
   The store sold no guns or firearms accessories. ``And we never
carried books that were offensive,'' Boser said. ``I mean, we'd get
requests for bomb-making manuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the area churches proved to be regular customers,
particularly those concerned with prophecies of impending doom.
According to Baxter, a man claiming to be a minister from Bradford,
Pa., drove up in a Cadillac one day, popped the car's trunk and
issued the order to ``fill 'er up'' with supplies.
</P>
<P>
   There were other customers claiming to belong to this militia
group or that militia group. Baxter said the largest in the area
hailed from rural McKean County, just over the border in
Pennsylvania. Another militia is based right here in Cattaraugus
County, he said. In fact, the head of the group was nice enough to
drop off his business card one day.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Potok, the spokesman for the Southern Poverty Law Center, a
nonprofit organization in Birmingham, Ala., that monitors hate
groups, said that a group called the Bucktail Militia used to
operate out of McKean County, but that it had not been heard from
since 1995. Still, he said, ``There is heavy movement activity in
western Pennsylvania _ both militias and hate groups.''
</P>
<P>
   And Timothy McVeigh _ the man awaiting execution for the bombing
of a federal building in Oklahoma City in 1995 that killed 168
people _ often used property he owned in Humphrey, just three miles
north of here, as a shooting range. Baxter said that he met McVeigh
once through a friend of a friend. ``We were more or less into the
same thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When pushed further about his own political philosophy, Baxter
said that most of the country's wealth seemed to be in the hands of
a few people, and that ``Mein Kampf'' ``made a lot of sense.'' Then
he added, ``My partner doesn't believe in `Mein Kampf.'''
</P>
<P>
   He was right. When asked later about Baxter's views, Boser gave
an exasperated, there-goes-Bill-again kind of expression. ``Hitler
was a moron,'' he said. ``He was the Antichrist.''
</P>
<P>
   Boser went on to say that while militia types, ``hillbillies''
and people posing as Vietnam veterans _ which personally disgusts
him, he said _ frequented the store, there were plenty of customers
interested in nothing more than having ``just in case'' supplies on
hand.
</P>
<P>
   As for his own philosophy, he said that `` `We the people' has
become `We the government.''' Overall, he said, he believes only
half of what he sees and half of what he hears, and he belongs to
no organization whatsoever _ ``not even the VFW.''
</P>
<P>
   The Survival Preparedness Center did a fairly brisk business in
the days before the year 2000. But by late January, after the
millennial rush, sales had dropped through the linoleum-tiled
floor, and the partners decided that it did not pay to keep the
store open.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Baxter has not given up on the prospect of future
disaster generating future business. ``According to the prophecies,
New York City is going to be hit with a giant tsunami,'' he said, a
vanilla-flavored cigar clenched in his teeth.
</P>
<P>
   But his partner, Boser, seemed to be considering more practical
possibilities, such as moving the store to where most of the
traffic is _ namely, near the Wal-Mart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
