<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6884 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-0506-C     05-05 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-0506-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AMID RUBBLE, FUNERAL FOLLOWING ROCKET ATTACKS, ISRAEL PROMISES
LEBANON WITHDRAWAL
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRYAT SHEMONA, Israel _ While announcements on Israeli
television Friday told residents here it was safe to go outside,
fear and anger from two days of deadly violence threatened Israel's
planned July withdrawal from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting, between Israeli troops, their allies and the
Lebanese Hezbollah guerillas, left smoke billowing on the piney
hillsides of northern Israel after the heaviest Hezbollah rocket
attacks in nearly a year.
</P>
<P>
   Residents on both sides of the border were cleaning up rubble
and weeping over the few dead. Many Lebanese were in the dark after
an Israeli attack on a civilian power station.
</P>
<P>
   The episode displayed both sides of Israel's Lebanon dilemma.
Northern residents were reinforced in fears that a withdrawal will
leave them vulnerable to attacks on the border. Meanwhile, mourners
cried loudly for the latest Israeli soldier killed on that border
in the kind of fighting Israeli leaders hope they can end with a
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak complied with calls from the
United States and the United Nations for both sides to ease the
fighting. But, speaking on Israeli television, he tried to reassure
his public that he was as tough as they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't suggest that anybody test us,'' he said, noting
that many Lebanese now are ``sitting in the dark.''
</P>
<P>
   He hinted that Israel could even hit Syrian targets in Lebanon.
Syria keeps about 35,000 troops in Lebanon and exerts significant
control over the country and Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   A Lebanon withdrawal is a campaign promise that Barak made when
he was elected prime minister in last May. Israel has been fighting
in Lebanon intermittently since 1978, first against Palestinian
terrorists based there and, since 1985, against Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   Barak had hopes that the withdrawal would be part of a three-way
peace agreement between Syria, Lebanon and Israel. But talks with
Syria have broken down. That raises the possibility that Syria may
back attacks against Israel even if Israel withdraws.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, Barak vowed to keep his withdrawal on schedule,
saying Israel's invasion of Lebanon had created Hezbollah and its
withdrawal would help ``solve the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   A cabinet minister reiterated that vow at a funeral Friday for
Shaked Overi, a 24-year-old artillery sergeant killed just inside
Lebanon by a Hezbollah rocket the day before.
</P>
<P>
   ``This government has come to the decision to stop the circle of
blood and bring the boys back from that cursed land,'' Israeli
Internal Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami said at the funeral in El
Yachim, in central Israel. ``This will be of no comfort to this
family, but let us hope that peace will come to the people of this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Northern residents fear that a withdrawal will bring Hezbollah,
or Palestinian terror groups, to their fences.
</P>
<P>
   Many said the rocket attacks Thursday and Friday, hour-long
barrages on both days, show Hezbollah's intention is to kill
Israeli civilians.
</P>
<P>
   They wanted a heavy Israeli response.
</P>
<P>
   One is 37-year-old computer salesman Dubi Friedman, whose house,
along with his mother-in-law's next door, was badly damaged by the
one of the few direct hits in the town Friday.
</P>
<P>
   There were no injuries, as both families had left the suburban
villas the night before.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah's Katyusha rockets are inaccurate and relatively weak,
but this one left a hole in the tile roof of one home while
furniture, toys and computers were scattered in pieces inside both.
The street smelled like burnt gunpowder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ping pong,'' a frustrated Friedman said of the cycle of
Israeli and Hezbollah reprisals. ``We need to kill 200 Arabs. Then
they will be afraid of us.''
</P>
<P>
   This latest round of fighting _ the worst since June, when
Israeli strikes caused severe damage in Lebanon and killed eight
civilians _ escalated early Thursday when the Israeli-paid and
trained militia in Lebanon, the South Lebanon Army, killed two
sleeping Lebanese women with shelling.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah, the force fighting to end Israel's 18-year occupation
in southern Lebanon, responded Thursday afternoon with several
dozen rockets. One killed Overi, who was in a jeep at a post on the
border. Other rockets lightly injured about 20 civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Fitting the pattern of the war, Israel responded with air raids
on a Lebanese power station near Beirut, causing power outages, and
bombed the highway between Beirut and Damascus, Syria. Israel said
it killed three Hezbollah guerillas.
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning, Hezbollah answered with a few dozen more rockets
here in Kiryat Shemona and the western Israeli town of Shlomi.
There were no serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Israel answered with volleys of artillery fire. But, with both
sides under international pressure to cease fire, Israeli leaders
said they would let the fighting stop there.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
