<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Saturday, May 6. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE-U.N. (United Nations) _ In their boldest move yet
against the U.N. peacekeeping mission in Sierra Leone, rebel
fighters have disarmed a convoy of Zambian peacekeepers, taken the
208 soldiers hostage and now appear to be driving 13 hijacked
armored personnel carriers toward the capital, U.N. officials said
Friday. The convoy, which was sent from Lungi, a port town, to
reinforce other beleaguered peacekeeping troops at Makeni, lost
radio contact on Thursday with the U.N. mission in Freetown, the
capital of the battered West African country, prompting concern
about their fate. By Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LEBANON (Jerusalem) _ The Israeli government, facing a
troop withdrawal from southern Lebanon for which it needs
international backing, on Friday declined to continue reprisal
bombings in Lebanon even though another cross-border guerrilla
offensive took place Friday morning. In an effort to interrupt the
volley of retaliatory attacks and defuse the exploding violence,
Prime Minister Ehud Barak and his security Cabinet decided that
they would not respond militarily to a second day of Katyusha
rocket fire on northern Israel. ``Israel has no interest in
escalation,'' a senior Israeli official said. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES-HOSTAGES (Manila) _ They are schoolchildren,
teachers, and a group of mostly European holidaymakers _ true
innocents who have been caught for weeks in a pair of terrifying
kidnappings in the lawless jungles of the southern Philippines.
Their captors, a small army of Islamic separatist bandits, have
herded them up mountains and down riverbeds, to the sound of
gunfire from pursuing Philippine troops. Last weekend, as the
government troops closed in on one group, the kidnappers executed
four Filipino captives, including the priest. With the government
taking a hard line and the kidnappers making wild threats and even
wilder demands, there seems, for the moment, little hope of freedom
for the hungry and frightened hostages. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OCONNOR (New York) _ The scene from St. Patrick's Cathedral, as
the body of Cardinal John Oconnor is moved to the church. By Diana
Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT9.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-GUNS (Undated) _ The fault lines in the presidential
campaign over gun control sharpened Friday as Gov. George W. Bush
suggested that he would support legislation that would block state
and local governments from filing suit against gun manufacturers.
Bush made the suggestion after being pressed by Vice President Al
Gore, who made an explicit pledge on Friday to veto any such
legislation. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The nation's unemployment rate fell
below 4 percent in April for the first time in 30 years, the Labor
Department reported Friday, as employers hired tens of thousands of
census takers, restaurant employees and temporary workers in a
booming economy. The new employment numbers _ 341,000 new jobs and
a 3.9 percent unemployment rate _ offered no evidence that the
nine-year-old expansion _ the longest in America's history _ might
be coming to an end or even weakening in response to the Federal
Reserve's attempt to slow the economy by raising interest rates.
The Fed's great fear is that labor shortages will give workers
enough bargaining power to push up labor costs and employers, in
response, will raise prices to cover the higher costs. But wages,
while rising, are still not going up fast enough to set off an
inflationary spiral, the Labor Department's latest numbers show. By
Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   LOVE-VIRUS (Undated) _ Developments on the ``I love you'' virus.
By John Markoff.
