<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6921 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-HEAT-CARTER-NYT &LR;      05-05 1455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HEAT-CARTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI'S GUARD GOES FROM ASPHALT TO HARDWOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Anthony Carter looks anguished as he stands
in the middle of a brightly lit gym, waiting for the Miami Heat's
evening practice to begin. His sleepy brown eyes move from side to
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll make it short,'' said the 24-year-old point guard. ``I
was a high-school dropout. My freshman year I didn't go back no
more. I was out of school for three years. Went back to school and
got my GED.''
</P>
<P>
   He does not stop, each detail tumbling forward, faster and
faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Went to a junior college in California. Had two great years
there. Went to the University of Hawaii. Had two great years there.
Separated my shoulder before my senior season. That kind of scared
everybody away. Had surgery after my senior year. Went to the CBA
and worked my way back up. That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter left out the part about playing $1,000 winner-take-all
pickup games in Atlanta and how he caught Coach Pat Riley's eye and
eventually borrowed Tim Hardaway's job.
</P>
<P>
   He may have to give it back when the Heat open their Eastern
Conference semifinal series against the New York Knicks here on
Sunday, but Carter will not raise a fuss. He is making a guaranteed
wage to play pro basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Carter started 30 games during the regular season, averaging 6.3
points, 4.8 assists and 2.2 turnovers. In the Heat's first-round,
three-game sweep of Detroit Carter, outplayed Lindsey Hunter, whom
he was buried behind in Pistons training camp last year, and
averaged more than nine points and nine assists.
</P>
<P>
   Carter is not a long-distance threat like Hardaway _ he hit
3-of-23 3-point attempts all season _ but he will break down a
defense, using frontlines as pylons as he maneuvers his
6-foot-2-inch, 185-pound frame with ease through the lane.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, the chances of that happening were remote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing he was on his way to was becoming a playground
legend,'' said Llew Haden, who sponsored Atlanta's first `I Have a
Dream' project and who serves as a surrogate uncle to Carter.
``A.C. making it to the NBA was a pretty big longshot.''
</P>
<P>
   The program, founded in New York, randomly selects classes of
third-grade students and guides them as they grow, providing
tutoring, cultural experiences, contacts with role models and money
for college.
</P>
<P>
   Carter was one of 47 children selected in his class to
participate in the program. By the time he was 15, however, Carter
veered off course, a truant whose grades made him ineligible to
play sports. He dropped out of high school simply because ``I
didn't want to get up in the morning and walk to school.''
</P>
<P>
   Between the ages of 16 and 19, Carter traveled around Atlanta to
hustle games. He and his friends, known as the Boys from Kirkwood,
often divided the $1,000 winners' share after a game. ``It was
physical, and people got upset when they lost, but there were no
fights,'' Carter said. ``After it was over, we just split up the
money. Right there. Everybody paid up. It was a good living.''
</P>
<P>
   The life of a pickup basketball player seized hold of Carter,
and he thought of doing little else with his life. The coach at
Atlanta's Alonzo A. Crim High School still tells Carter he cost him
three state championships.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond his quickness, his stop-and-pop game, Carter also had a
large circle of unending support. He grew with his mother, Brenda,
in his grandmother's home with 13 other siblings. They often
doubled as Carter's uncles and aunts.
</P>
<P>
   One aunt, Deborah Carter, 28, went to college (Georgia) and
became a pro (Utah and Washington of the Women's National
Basketball Association).
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the only girl that could get into the boys' club at the
time,'' she said. ``I'd take him with me to play every day. He used
to get so mad when neighborhood guys would dunk on him. He was just
determined to get back at them. Bottom line, he got a second
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's life took a turn for the better on a summer night in
1994. An opponent recalled how the point guard dunked eight times
in a midnight game. The player, Andre Craig, called his former
coach, Bill Brummel, at Saddleback College _ a two-year junior
college in Mission Viejo, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Craig asked Carter if he could videotape one of his games and
send it to Brummel. Relying only on the grainy footage, Brummel
offered Carter a financial aid package.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a mentor in Haden's ``I Have a Dream'' chapter who
convinced the high-school dropout to give college a try.
</P>
<P>
   Mattie Baker, a project coordinator for ``I Have a Dream,'' was
driving down Memorial Avenue in southeast Atlanta that summer when
she noticed Carter walking down the street. He had been an on and
off participant in the program, and she wanted to know how he was
getting along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just stopped by the YMCA and asked her if she could she help
me fill a form out so I could go back and get my GED, and she
helped me,'' Carter said. He also pulled out a crumpled piece of
paper from his pocket and showed it to her. It was an acceptance
letter to Saddleback.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time she read it, he was supposed to be there two days
already,'' Haden said. ``I called Brummel up and said, `Do you
still want him?' He said, `Damn right! Can you get him here?'''
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Haden used money from the foundation to pay for
the plane ticket to Los Angeles. A friend stuffed $200 in Carter's
pocket, and he was off to college.
</P>
<P>
   Carter led the state in scoring the 1995-96 season, erupting for
44 points in one game. He also earned enough credits to qualify for
a Division I scholarship at the University of Hawaii. By the end of
his junior year, he was considered first-round draft material in
the National Basketball Association, but shoulder surgery before
his senior season scared away scouts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 at the predraft camp in Chicago, where players
scrimmaged at the Moody Bible Institute before hundreds of scouts,
coaches and general managers, Carter re-injured his shoulder three
minutes into the first scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   He went undrafted and spent last season taking long bus rides
with the Yakima Sun Kings of the Continental Basketball
Association. He tried out with the Detroit Pistons, but asked for
his release after two weeks of playing behind Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   Along came Riley, who saw him play for a Mavericks summer league
team and plucked him away from Dallas. The deal: Carter would go to
camp and they would pay his living expenses. If he made the roster
on Nov. 2, the first day of the season, Riley would sign Carter to
one-year, free-agent deal worth $385,000.
</P>
<P>
   After Hardaway jammed his right knee in late November, Carter
started 30 games, including the last four of the regular season.
When Hardaway sprained his left foot in April, Carter started all
three games in the first round of the playoffs against Detroit.
Carter's value has rocketed, and the Heat will compete with other
teams for his services during the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't run into Mattie Baker that day, I wouldn't be here
now,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's game comes straight from asphalt lore. On the court, he
is all about taking risks and hard drives to the hole. But the
package also comes with turnovers, an unreliable jump shot and a
penchant for playing at hyper speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good with him,'' Riley said. ``I feel comfortable with
him. I can deal with his turnovers, because I know they're all
honest. He's trying to make good plays. He's fearless.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley puts special intonation on ``fearless.'' Carter seems cast
from the same mold of fringe players who found a home with a
Riley-coached team, players who all have two things in common: big
hearts and larger limitations. Anthony Mason. Xavier McDaniel. John
Starks. Dan Majerle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved Mase, as many problems as I had with him,'' Riley
said. ``And I cried when X went to Boston,'' Riley said of
McDaniel, the former Knick. ``I couldn't believe he left. Then we
got Starks. Then Dan. Keith Askins. And now A.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are cut out of the same cloth. I develop an
affinity toward these kinds of men. They're great pros. They're
winners.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter distinguished himself further by becoming that rare
rookie Riley entrusted with important minutes. Hardaway's injuries
and Carter's progress forced his hand.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks plan to trap Carter, like any rookie, and exploit his
weaknesses. The player whose income once depended on winning
playground games was asked if he is feeling the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel no pressure out here playing,'' he said. ``I had
a lot of pressure not going to school, when people kept telling me
to go back. This isn't pressure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 1645EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6932 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-PITCHING-MASTERY-     05-05 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-PITCHING-MASTERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON AND MARTINEZ ARE ALIKE IN MASTERY 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The plans and hopes of other teams aside, this baseball year
could end in no better manner than to have the Arizona Diamondbacks
and the Boston Red Sox win their respective league pennants so that
Randy Johnson and Pedro Martinez can pitch against each other in
Games 1, 4 and 7 of the World Series. What more fitting climax
could the season have than to put the premier pitcher in each
league on the mound in the sport's ultimate set of games.
</P>
<P>
   Although that's the only way Johnson and Martinez could pitch in
the same meaningful games, they have been mirroring each other this
season, making four starts on the same day and another start on
consecutive days. In their latest turns in their teams' rotations,
Johnson is scheduled to pitch against San Diego Friday night and
Martinez against Tampa Bay Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the left-hander, will take a 6-0 record and a 0.91
earned run average into the game in Phoenix; Martinez, the
right-hander, will take a 5-0 record and a 1.27 ERA into his game
in Boston. Martinez has made one fewer start than Johnson because
the Red Sox were rained out for four consecutive days last month.
Both pitchers have been no less than terrific. They have clearly
become the most dominating, most intimidating pitchers in their
respective leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The similarities are they are both intimidating,'' Mike
Hargrove, the Baltimore Orioles' manager, said by telephone
Thursday. ``The differences are how they go about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove was asked to compare the two pitchers because as a
long-time American League manager, he has had to deal with both,
during the regular season and in playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy is physically intimidating,'' Hargrove said. ``Here's a
guy 6 foot 12 or whatever he is, 6-10, and when he lets the ball
go, it looks like he lets it go halfway to the plate. That's
intimidating, especially to left-hand hitters. Pedro goes about his
business quietly on the mound, but there's no doubt in your mind
that Pedro feels he owns the entire plate and if you try to take
any of it away from him, he'll come and get you.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Martinez did last Sunday in Cleveland with Einar
Diaz. His brushback pitch led to an exchange of hit batters and a
five-game suspension for Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   If his appeal is unsuccessful, he presumably will fall another
start behind Johnson, though not necessarily in stature and
success.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 36, leads the National League in victories, ERA,
strikeouts (64), strikeouts per nine innings (11.7), batting
average against (.156), complete games (3) and shutouts (2).
Martinez, 28, is tied for the AL lead in victories and leads the
league in ERA, strikeouts (50), strikeouts per nine innings (12.7)
and opponents' batting average (.173).
</P>
<P>
   Neither has lost a regular-season game since last August, though
the Mets beat Johnson in a playoff game last October. Since he lost
last Aug. 31, Johnson has started 11 games and been the winning
pitcher nine times. Martinez has not incurred a loss since last
Aug. 19, winning 11 of 12 starts and adding one victory each as a
starter and a reliever in last year's playoffs. Johnson (17-9,
2.48) and Martinez (23-4, 2.07) were the 1999 Cy Young Award
winners.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Beattie, general manager of the Montreal Expos, knows both
pitchers intimately. He was in the Seattle front office when
Johnson pitched for the Mariners, and he was the Expos' general
manager who traded Martinez to the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both have a lot of confidence,'' Beattie said. ``They
don't let anything bother them. Randy is more emotional out there,
but it doesn't affect how he throws his next pitch. It's the same
with Pedro. They've gotten past those things. That's the mark of a
good pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Beattie, a former pitcher himself, said neither Johnson nor
Martinez was born on the pitching pinnacle; they worked hard to get
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably 1994, '95 when Randy started to step it up and
concentrate,'' Beattie said. ``He worked hard in the off-season. He
started applying himself and got stronger. The same with Pedro. He
worked hard. Conditioning for both these guys is outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   People who don't know the pitchers, Beattie suggested, might
look at both pitchers and think Johnson was just this tall, skinny
guy and Martinez was a small, skinny guy. Both, however, are very
strong, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw the maturing of both into the pitchers they have
become,'' the Expos' executive said. ``Both had questions about
them early in their career, but they developed mental toughness and
concentration. It's something they learned as they got more
experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in his career, after the Los Angeles Dodgers decided he
was too small to become a good major-league pitcher and traded him
to the Expos, Martinez was accused of being a headhunter. He hit
batters with pitches liberally, and the batters went after him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he was a headhunter,'' Beattie said. ``I think
his ball just ran so much that he ended up hitting a lot of guys.
He has refined the way he approaches the game. So has Randy.''
</P>
<P>
   Russ Davis, a San Francisco infielder, played with Johnson in
Seattle and has played against him as a member of the Yankees and
the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gotten so good right now,'' said Davis, who doesn't have
a hit in 11 at-bats against Johnson. ``I don't ever remember him
throwing a sinking fastball, a two-seamer that just runs away from
right-handers now. I thought that was pretty incredible when he
came here and I saw that. Other than that pitch, everything's real
hard, a hard slider _ it's hard to detect if it's a fastball or a
slider. And he pitches. He's not just throwing 95 every time. It's
like he's getting better with age, with time.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove hasn't had to deal with Johnson since he left the
American League during the 1998 season. Sight unseen, though, the
Baltimore manager said Johnson is the best pitcher in the National
League.
</P>
<P>
   But he added: ``Without a doubt I think Pedro's the best in both
leagues. He's kind of a combination of Maddux and Johnson. He has
Johnson's fastball, but Maddux's composure and control.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 1650EDT &QL; 
