<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6935 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-FRAGRANCE-BOUTIQUES-2     05-05 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRAGRANCE-BOUTIQUES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CUSTOM-MADE FRAGRANCE THAT'S ALL `MINE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 7)  
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I started wearing Chanel No. 5 because of Catherine Deneuve. To
my teen-age eyes she was the epitome of French style and classic
beauty, and I figured that if I wore it, too _ bell-bottoms aside _
I would somehow acquire that same je ne sais quoi in Scarsdale,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   I had my dalliances along the way. There was Charlie (Shelly
Hack's appeal was somehow not eternal) and Chloe, even Fracas for a
minute, but in the end it was always Chanel. Those dreaded women at
Bloomingdale's who aim their atomizers and fire get nowhere with
me.
</P>
<P>
   But after 25 years, even I was bored, so when I read that Sarah
Horowitz was taking appointments for her Fragrance Journey, I
called. ``The fragrance equivalent of rebirthing,'' the notice
read, ``Horowitz coaxes forth scent-related memories and then
blends you a scent with emotional meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   Horowitz is based in Malibu, Calif., but she travels regularly
to New York and London; it turns out she has 1,200 clients. Though
it sounded kind of kooky, I found the prospect somehow intriguing _
like having a shrink and a personal shopper rolled into one.
</P>
<P>
   While customization has proved popular recently in everything
from suits to ice cream, it is taking off in the top tiers of the
fragrance industry. Creed, the very upscale European fragrance
house, whose perfumer is the sixth-generation Oliver Creed, offers
custom scents ($20,000 for Creed himself to oversee a process that
takes six months). There are also Creed master blenders at Barneys
New York, Bergdorf Goodman and Neiman Marcus, who can blend five or
six of the existing 100 Creed scents for customers in an hour, for
the more affordable fee of $400 to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   On the West Coast there are a growing number of fragrance
boutiques like Lather in Pasadena, Calif., and Homebody in Los
Angeles that blend custom scents for clients like k.d. lang. As
Mary Lavo, the merchandising manager in charge of cosmetics for
Barneys, says, the custom-scent trend is not sweeping huge numbers
because of the time (and money) the process requires _ like couture
versus ready-to-wear. Historically, fragrance was an exclusive
privilege of royalty and the very rich, until the late 1800s, when
the common folk got in on the act. So, it's not surprising that
with the economy soaring now, the very rich have once again
realized they no longer have to smell like even the moderately
rich.
</P>
<P>
   While the custom-scent trend has not broken through to the
masses, some online sites plan to offer the service to users, via
questionnaire. (Reflect.com was the only one I found promising that
personalized scents ``will be available soon.'') Horowitz and some
other professionals in the fragrance business are skeptical of this
sort of venture, however, since body chemistry plays such an
important part in determining a scent.
</P>
<P>
   She settled down to determine mine in my apartment, breaking her
``no house calls rule,'' because her New York schedule was so
jammed she could see me only on her day off. (She usually sets up
shop in a hotel suite; appointments can be made by calling
310-317-6858.)
</P>
<P>
   The Fragrance Journey costs $255 for a 90-minute session and
includes a quarter-ounce French-cut bottle of the perfume she
creates with you. (Perfect Perfumes, her ready-to-wear line, as she
calls it, is sold in New York at the Bigelow Pharmacy in Greenwich
Village.)
</P>
<P>
   Horowitz travels with a fragrance organ, a large case containing
120 bottles of fragrances and essential oils. As she set up her
apparatus and put some New Age music on the tape player, I learned
that she grew up on Long Island, N.Y., and graduated from Emerson
College in Boston, where she discovered her interest in scent while
working for Essence, a store on Newbury Street, now defunct. She
has apprenticed at Belmay, a perfume house in the Los Angeles area,
and has spent the last 12 years combining her love of scent with
her love of psychology.
</P>
<P>
   ``My passion is to incorporate emotional and physical history
into the blending of fragrance,'' she said. ``I love listening to
people and seeing what we can put together.'' The results have
included everything from separate daytime and nighttime scents to a
custom-made bridal scent that the bridegroom doesn't smell until
the wedding day. ``After that, you only wear it on anniversaries or
special occasions,'' she said. ``It's Pavlovian. You're
impregnating the oil with your memory.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Horowitz started the session by telling me, ``You will have to
name the fragrance you give to yourself,'' which she would then
print up on labels for my future orders. She has a lab assistant
who translates her handwritten formulas into sprays, bath gels and
body lotions.
</P>
<P>
   She gave a brief history of fragrance, noting that the Egyptians
made cones out of beeswax and tallow, laid blossoms on them and
wore them on their heads. As the heat of the sun melted them, the
scented fat ran down their faces. Yum yum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the oldest art forms,'' she said. ``You are
receiving the highest gift you can give yourself, a fragrance based
on your experiences and what you love.''
</P>
<P>
   Then her questions started. What were my favorite foods?
Favorite color? What were my scent memories of my mother? Do I love
citrus? Not especially. How about sweet? Even less.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I do like the ocean, better than the mountains. I like
roses and grass and violets. I especially like the way some people
smell like soap, so clean and straight from the shower.
</P>
<P>
   As I spoke, she pulled bottles from her case and grouped them on
the table, moving them around as if they were chess pieces. She
gave me a Parmesan cheese shaker filled with coffee beans and
instructed me to inhale periodically; it works as a palate cleanser
for the nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perfume is built like music is,'' she said. ``The base note,
middle and top. The base supports the scent, like the percussion,
the middle is the bouquet of fragrance and the top note is the most
pungent and pulls you into the rest. It's like the strings.''
</P>
<P>
   During the first round of inhaling her bottles, she told me what
each scent was and had me tell her whether I loved it, hated it or
wasn't sure. What followed was a series of childhood memories,
instantaneous snapshots of the oddest assortment of people and
places: my Aunt Marcia's bathroom, the soap in my underwear drawer
in junior high school, a hotel room in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet pea smelled like camp. Cassis smelled like Chanel No. 5.
Basil smelled like dinner and did not interest me at all. As a
matter of fact, I disliked most scents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no wrong answer here,'' Horowitz said encouragingly.
``It's all about you, and I know how to balance it.''
</P>
<P>
   During the second round of inhaling she instructed me to keep my
eyes closed. ``When they're open you have a mental association with
what you perceive the scent to be,'' she said. ``With your eyes
closed, you go on your gut. I watch your facial expressions and see
where the emphasis should be when I blend.''
</P>
<P>
   I ended up with six ingredients for her to mix with her long
plastic eyedroppers: Oriental musk, rose, sweet pea, African
violet, gardenia and cassis. ``It has a garden feel, and the cassis
makes it very sophisticated,'' she said, putting it on my arm. I
smelled it and winced. It was way too sweet.
</P>
<P>
   She nodded. ``Your skin brings the rose up,'' she said. ``It
depends on body chemistry. Certain people pull up certain notes
faster.''
</P>
<P>
   She kept adjusting, adding one drop at a time from skinnier
glass eyedroppers to different areas of my arms and hands. She ran
her nose up and down the skin, sniffing, like a puppy. I started to
feel that my choices were wrong, but she kept mixing until suddenly
I smiled. Yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminds me of something,'' I told her. ``Something good.''
</P>
<P>
   She smiled. ``You,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After she had packed up and gone, I showered, dressed and put on
my new perfume, as I did the day after and the day after that. I
tried not to notice, but it was still too sweet. The spray she had
made was better, less concentrated, but still not right. One night
I went back to Chanel No. 5, which surprisingly, smelled thin and
chemical by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   I called Horowitz. ``This happens about 10 percent of the
time,'' she said apologetically. ``My goal is to have you love
this, so I'm going to rework it based on the formula and send you
some samples in the mail.''
</P>
<P>
   She wasn't completely surprised by my reaction, she added. ``My
impressions of you,'' she said, ``were that you are extremely
thorough and very specific. Yet, there is a little contradiction.
You said you didn't like sweet things, but when you smelled them,
you liked them.''
</P>
<P>
   She hesitated. ``If you don't mind my saying so, you do a lot of
thinking in your line of work and I think you don't want to be
perceived as too sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   She was probably right. But she had overcompensated for me a bit
too much.
</P>
<P>
   After I hung up, I realized I still hadn't named my scent. I
could wait, of course, until the revised version came back. But one
night, at the movies, the name came to me. I had caught a whiff of
myself, and it was fragrant, familiar, even comforting. Not to
mention decidedly imperfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
