<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6941 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-EDUC-(TRIMS)-NYT     05-05 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-EDUC-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE OFFERS PLANS TO IMPROVE QUALITY AND PAY OF TEACHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANSING, Mich. _ In a speech here outlining his proposals to
improve the quality of the nation's public school teachers, Vice
President Al Gore offered a spoonful of sugar to help the medicine
go down.
</P>
<P>
   He said that as president he would spend $8 billion over 10
years to recruit 1 million new teachers and another $8 billion over
10 years to increase teacher salaries if the states and teachers'
unions agreed that all new teachers submit to testing and meet
rigorous national standards and if teachers are hired on the basis
of expertise and not seniority.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I am entrusted with the presidency, I will ensure that
there is a fully qualified, well-trained teacher in every single
classroom, everywhere in this nation, before the next four years is
out,'' he declared in a speech here to the Michigan Education
Association.
</P>
<P>
   His proposals are based on the theory that the quality of
teachers is the most significant factor within a school's control
in improving student achievement. And education ranks near the top
of voter concerns, especially in important battleground states like
Michigan, where Gore conducted his fourth ``school day'' Friday,
spending an entire day at the high school in nearby Holt. (He also
conducted his first ``school day'' in Michigan, in McComb County.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's give every teacher a $5,000 raise,'' the vice president
said in Lansing on Friday. ``Let's give $10,000 to master
teachers,'' he said, vowing: ``I will combine greater
accountability with greater investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that by 2004, he would require states to make sure
that teachers are fully qualified to teach the subject they are
teaching. As of now, he said, only 36 percent of teachers consider
themselves to be very well-prepared to meet the standards of their
state or school district. In high-poverty areas, as many as 50
percent of the math teachers have not studied math.
</P>
<P>
   Gore proposes to change that by requiring teachers either to
have majored in their subject area in college or pass a competency
test. And he would reward outstanding teachers and help schools
improve or remove bad teachers quickly, within the academic year as
opposed to the three years that such a process can take now, aides
said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``While we absolutely must respect due process, we have to put
an end to endless delays in removing those few teachers who really
do need to be removed,'' Gore said. He also said principals should
be allowed to hire teachers for reasons other than seniority. ``No
teaching contract should be a lifetime job guarantee,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Teacher testing and seniority hiring are highly controversial
matters among educators and have been strongly resisted by the
teachers' unions, which believe that standardized testing does not
measure the intangibles of good teachers. Others object to
standardized testing of both teachers and students as a step toward
giving up local control of education.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the teachers' unions have heartily endorsed Gore's
presidential candidacy. Against that backdrop, his speech Friday
was intended to be seen as a daring, principled stand, the kind
that his political advisers have been eager for him to take to
demonstrate that, contrary to the popular impression as registered
in public opinion polls, Gore does not just blow with the political
winds and pander to every group he addresses.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It was what Gore aides called a ``Sister Souljah Moment,'' a
reference to Bill Clinton's tough speech during the 1992
presidential campaign when he took on the black singer face to face
for lyrics he said were offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's speech comes after the American Teachers Federation, the
nation's second-largest teachers' union, endorsed the idea last
week of toughening teacher standards.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been trying to demonstrate his commitment to education
in multiple ways, including by spending a full day at a school
somewhere in the country every week or so. He spent Friday at Holt
High School after spending the night with Margot Strong, a computer
teacher, her husband, Jay, who teaches first grade, and their two
children, Nick, 10, and Anna, 6. Gore arrived at their house after
midnight Wednesday night and stayed up late enough to watch four of
the five overtimes in the hockey playoffs on television.
</P>
<P>
   Holt was the first high school Gore has visited during this
campaign, and the older age of the students was evident in some of
their by-play with the vice president. In a morning physics class,
when Gore asked the students what the most interesting thing was
they had learned, Tonia Van Every, 18, called out: ``About Mr.
Pulver's personal life,'' a reference to the teacher, Eric Pulver.
``I'm one of the sarcastic kids,'' she told a reporter later.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the school newspaper, Gore was asked about
abortion. He said he believed it was up to a woman to decide what
to do, but he said he also believed in abstinence.
</P>
<P>
   And he revealed that his glory moment in high school was
shooting _ and sinking _ a long shot at the final buzzer, but only
after the basketball hit the backboard. Asked to list his favorite
sports, he said: ``Football, basketball, track, art.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what his most difficult moment as vice president has been,
he answered without much hesitation: ``The day our soldiers in
Somalia were killed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 1714EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6946 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0506-COX     05-05 2215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0506-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Cinco De Mayo and every day
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Resuming his push for California Hispanics, George W. Bush was
marking today's Mexican holiday of Cinco de Mayo amid fresh polling
evidence that the crucial voter bloc is leaning heavily toward
Democrats. Bush appeared at a U.S.-Mexico Foundation breakfast,
followed by a meeting with Hispanic leaders in San Diego County,
which shares a border with Mexico. Bush has made direct appeals to
Hispanics a staple of his campaign swings to California, where 16
percent of the electorate is Hispanic, compared to 10 percent a
decade ago. Cinco de Mayo marks the May 5, 1862, victory by a
rag-tag group of Mexican soldiers over a sophisticated French army
at Puebla.
</P>
<P>
   POT SHOT MISSES THE MARK
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush raised questions today about Al Gore's
trustworthiness, but also faced questions about his own credibility
after asserting that Gore had once been a member of the National
Rifle Association. Gore aides said that, to their knowledge, he had
never belonged to the NRA. Bush said he was waiting for Gore
himself to definitively answer the question, and said that whether
or not he had been a member, Gore's voting record in Congress
suggested he'd once been a fervent backer of gun rights. ``My
position is that when it was convenient politically he voted one
way, and when it's convenient politically, he's changed his tune,''
Bush said. A day earlier, Bush told reporters: ``I've never been a
member of the NRA. Al Gore's been a member of the NRA, if I'm not
mistaken.''
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL FOCUS ON TEACHERS
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore was presenting his plan today for teacher certification,
testing and, where there's failure, firing, to an audience
traditionally resistant to such mandates: the teachers' unions.
Relying on union support to mobilize voters, Gore, at the Michigan
Education Association convention in Lansing, trod more gingerly on
the question of firing bad teachers than on testing teacher
competence against national standards. He would establish an $8
billion, 10-year fund for salary increases of $5,000 for qualified
teachers, but would make the fund available only to school
districts who, ``in the context of due process protections ...
quickly remove those teachers who really should be removed from the
classroom.'' No guidance, however, on those teachers would be
identified.
</P>
<P>
   READ BARBARA'S LIPS, AFTER THE SHUDDERS
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush attracted the attention of Barbara Walters, and
you can catch the result tonight on ABC's ``20/20.'' Walters says
she sought to ``reveal the man'' behind the presidential candidacy.
``For many people in this country, (his) views are still relatively
unknown on some personal and very controversial subjects,'' Walters
told the Dallas Morning News. ``A great many people think this
election is probably going to be decided on personality and
character. Therefore I asked a lot of questions that I sort of
shuddered about asking, but did anyway.'' A transcript of the
interview shows she asked him about his previous drinking,
allegations of illegal drug use as a young man, gay rights, his
``smirk,'' his smarts, broccoli and whether his father made a
presidential mistake by reneging on his famous statement, ``Read my
lips, no new taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   REFORM PARTY CHIEF QUITS AMID FAMILY ILLNESS
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party chairman Pat Choate resigned today and turned
control over to his vice chairman, citing an illness in his family.
Gerald Moan of Tuscon, Ariz., will head the party until a new
chairman is selected at the summer convention. Choate, 59, the 1996
Reform Party vice presidential nominee, told the Associated Press
that the party is united after months of wrangling, thus his
departure will not be unsettling. Pat Buchanan, recruited to the
party by Choate, is the leading contender for the third-party
nomination. Choate's claim to the party chairmanship was challenged
this year by intra-party rivals, but was upheld in court. His first
order of business was to try to soothe the internal strife.
</P>
<P>
   O'CONNOR FUNERAL PRE-EMPTS BUSH SPEECH
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush canceled his Social Security outline speech in
Pittsburgh on Monday in order to attend the funeral of New York
Cardinal John O'Connor. President Clinton, Al Gore and Senate
candidates Hillary Clinton and Rudy Giuliani also are most likely
to be at St. Patrick's Cathedral. Bush met with O'Connor last fall
while in New York. He also wrote a letter of apology to the
cardinal after being criticized during the primary campaign for
speaking at Bob Jones University, the South Carolina school whose
leader has espoused anti-Catholic views. Bush still will be able to
make an evening fund-raiser in Pittsburgh, though, before his
planned meeting there with John McCain the following day. There was
no immediate word about rescheduling the Social Security speech.
</P>
<P>
   FOLLOW THE SCRIPT, BUT WATCH FOR AD-LIBBING
</P>
<P>
   Nearly scrapped in anger, the long-awaited summit between George
W. Bush and John McCain will produce a show of unity that papers
over their differences, according to aides organizing Tuesday's
session. Top advisers have agreed in advance that McCain will
endorse Bush at a separate event later in the campaign. And while
no formal agreement has been reached, McCain is expected by both
sides to play a prominent role at the convention in Philadelphia.
``We've made a great deal of progress with the Bush campaign on a
lot of issues we've discussed,'' said McCain man Rick Davis.
</P>
<P>
   NEW AD ASSERTS NATIVE RIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Giuliani launched a new TV ad today, squelching speculation
for the time being that he has decided to quit his campaign against
Hillary Clinton because of prostate cancer. Giuliani aides said the
ad will air statewide for about two weeks at a cost that could top
$1 million. He has had campaign spots running off and on for
months. Clinton launched her first statewide TV ad this week, also
for a two-week run. Her's is expected to cost about $400,000.
Neither of the new ads directly attacks the other candidate, though
Giuliani's has thinly veiled barbs. Like this: ``I want to be a
senator because I was born in this state.''
</P>
<P>
   THE SOUND OF MIDCLAP SILENCE
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton finished her tour through each of New York's 62
counties in Plattsburgh with a sharp attack on George W. Bush's tax
cut proposals, leaving her mostly Republican audience in silence.
In outlining her opposition to Bush's call for a $1.3 trillion tax
cut over 10 years, Clinton said his plan would hurt efforts to win
more federal money for New York because such broad-based tax
reductions would deplete the surplus. For 10 months, even
Republicans who have no intention of voting for Clinton have come
to get a glimpse of her. And this time, the audience had been
applauding her speech enthusiastically until she broached the tax
cut subject. At that point, many in the audience stopped
practically in midclap.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH PUSH ON CHINA TRADE
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks before a closely watched vote in Congress on trade
relations with China, George W. Bush and his advisers are making
sure to remind Capitol Hill Republicans of Bush's support for the
bill and have not ruled out his phoning undecided House
Republicans. Aides said Bush is planning a speech the week before
the House vote, expected between May 22 and Memorial Day, to
explain again why he feels so strongly about facilitating trade
between the United States and China. Those remarks probably will be
delivered somewhere on the West Coast, a region that pins many
economic hopes on Asian commerce.
</P>
<P>
   LAUGHTER, BUT WITH LITTLE MIRTH
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay denied being a fund-raising
racketeer extorting money from lobbyists and corporations and
called the allegations contained in a civil lawsuit against him ``a
pretty pathetic'' attempt to disrupt Republican fund-raising
efforts. Speaking with reporters after an appearance at the
National Press Club, the Texan dismissed as ``frivolous'' the
complaint, filed under federal anti-racketeering laws by the
Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee. ``I'm trying to laugh
it off,'' he said with a smile. But even though he shrugged it off,
if the case is allowed to proceed, Democrats would get the chance
to pore over DeLay's fund-raising records and question donors named
in the lawsuit. And that prospect, said the Houston Chronicle, is
beginning to worry some Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   JUST A STRAIGHT TICKET, IF YOU PLEASE
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan ruled out picking a homosexual or gay rights
advocate as a running mate or Cabinet officer, calling such sexual
orientation ``a disorder.'' ``If someone is an out-of-the-closet
homosexual, he's not going to be my running mate, and if someone
advocates the homosexual rights agenda publicly they're not going
to be in my Cabinet,'' Buchanan said during a lunch with reporters.
``I believe that homosexuality is a disorder. It's a wrong
orientation.'' He did add, though, that he had worked in the past
with people he ``thought were gay'' and that they had done a
``great'' job.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS FROM BEHIND THE WHEEL
</P>
<P>
   Republican needling of Al Gore about telling the truth has
struck very close to home. Towering over Gore's campaign
headquarters in Nashville is an enormous highway billboard paid for
by the Republican National Committee. On the side facing oncoming
traffic, this question is posed: ``Why should we believe you will
tell the truth as president if you don't tell the truth as a
candidate?'' The picture alongside the quote isn't flattering,
either. Gore is either winking or wincing at the suggestion he
stretches the facts. The flip side of the billboard shows Gore in a
bearhug with President Clinton, and Gore's own words: ``One of our
greatest presidents.''
</P>
<P>
   FESS UP, WHO'S PAYING?
</P>
<P>
   Interest groups that air TV ads meant to influence elections
would be forced to say who is paying for them under a proposal
advanced in the Federal Election Commission. Groups across the
political spectrum flood the airwaves with ads praising or
criticizing candidates. But the ads stop short of flat-out telling
viewers how to vote, so the law doesn't require them to say how
much they're spending or who's paying. ``Without any information on
these groups, it becomes impossible for the public to make informed
decisions about the real interests of these groups,'' wrote Karl
Sandstrom, a Democrat on the six-member commission. The proposal
will be discussed at an FEC meeting later this month.
</P>
<P>
   NEVER MIND THE ISSUES _ BRING ON THE BARBS
</P>
<P>
   The nominal focus on issues dear to swing voters is being
drowned out by the presidential opponents' volley of barbs.
Speaking with reporters after his announcement at a Mission Viejo,
Calif., elementary school, George W. Bush vented mounting
frustration with Al Gore's attacks on his experience. ``It's
amazing that a person running for president of the United States
would look people in the eye and say I've never submitted a budget
as governor and continue to say so when I did,'' Bush said. Gore,
who has tried to portray Bush as inexperienced, reached
dramatically into his pocket after a Chicago conference of medical
journalists and produced for reporters what he said was Bush's 1995
budget _ 2 1/2 pages folded in fours. ``If you think that's a
budget, maybe I could convince you it's a duck,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   STRUGGLE FOR THE MIDDLE GROUND
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Breaux (D-La.) is a key supporter of Al Gore. But
Breaux and some other moderate Democrats are growing increasingly
concerned about the way Gore has rejected their views on Social
Security reform, Medicare and other major issues, while George W.
Bush has been more supportive. Breaux's concern, says the Boston
Globe, shines a spotlight on a little-noticed but growing rift
between Gore and some members of the moderate Democratic Leadership
Council, a group that Gore helped create. The rift could be crucial
because it centers on what many believe will be the decisive factor
of Campaign 2000: the candidates' ability to attract support from
the vast middle of the electorate that is still undecided.
</P>
<P>
   HARVARD-YALE BRAGGING RIGHTS AT STAKE
</P>
<P>
   It's been 88 years since Yale and Harvard squared off for the
ultimate Ivy League bragging right: president of the United States.
Both lost. That embarrassing outcome is unlikely this year with
contenders George W. Bush and Harvard alum Al Gore. Bush graduated
from Harvard Business School, but Yale claims the pedigree since
Bush got his undergraduate degree there in 1968. His father and
grandfather also were Yale men. Gore graduated from Harvard in 1969
with a degree in government. The last time the two schools faced
off in a presidential election was 1912, when Harvard's Teddy
Roosevelt and Yale's William Howard Taft were running. They were
beaten by Princeton's Woodrow Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
