s l BC-FASHION-COPY-EDITORS-     05-05 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-COPY-EDITORS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW I BECAME THE FAMILY AUTHORITY ON WOMEN'S WEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 7)  
 By ETHAN HAUSER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Here's a rule of fashion: The lower on the totem pole
a model is, the less underwear she gets to wear. Your Kate Mosses,
your Naomi Campbells, your Christy Turlingtons _ supermodels all _
get to sport granny bloomers if they so choose. But those towering,
unnaturally cheekboned 16-year-olds fresh off the boat from Latvia
or the train from Paducah must wear skimpy thongs.
</P>
<P>
   More trivia: there's no period after the K in the clothing label
Daryl K; Dolce is linked to Gabbana with an ampersand; and the
preferred tanning method of the model Maggie Rizer is to go out and
get burned, then peel for the perfect bronze.
</P>
<P>
   How could I possibly have amassed this wealth of knowledge, this
embarrassment of riches? From a fashion-obsessed girlfriend? A
sister in the modeling business? An unhealthy interest in women's
wear?
</P>
<P>
   If only. For three years, I was a copy editor at a fashion
magazine. I don't have any hard figures, but I suspect I am part of
a small minority of people who know what a dangling participle is
and how to spell the name of Gisele Bundchen, the Brazilian cover
girl.
</P>
<P>
   Being a copy editor at a women's fashion magazine _ and a male
to boot _ is a little like being the designated driver: you're
around people having a lot of fun, but you're not allowed to
imbibe. Your job is to make sure the semicolons are right; you
don't get to pick up the phone and trill ``Daaahling'' or air-kiss
the French photographers when they come in with their portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about partaking of the free MAC lipstick and clothing
discounts, and if you try to participate in office chitchat about
Brazilian bikini waxes (J. Sisters is the best _ even Gwyneth
Paltrow goes there), you seem like a pervert. There was the thrill
of occasionally riding the elevator with a model, and my female
friends were always grateful when I passed along freebies the
beauty editors gave me, tokens of thanks for getting their dashes
and commas right. My girlfriend benefited from the pitch-perfect
gift advice the fashion writers dispensed to me come birthday time.
</P>
<P>
   I have since moved on, much to my mother's chagrin. Yes, my
mother. It isn't that she's concerned about my plunge into the
shaky free-lance life. I was prepared for all the questions about
health insurance and how I expected to support myself without the
guarantee of a regular paycheck. I'd even practiced saying, ``Are
you crazy?'' in case she told me to move home.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, she wasn't concerned with such details. She
was worried that she'd lost her entree into the world of high
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   However flimsy my connection was, it was an imprimatur
nonetheless. I'd become the family's fashion authority. When I'd go
home for the holidays, she'd empty her newest purchases onto the
couch and then hold each piece up. ``Yes or no?'' she'd ask, eerily
parroting the same clipped tone I heard leaking from the offices of
the fashion editors at work. I suppose I'm not entirely blameless;
I did manage to wangle her a discount subscription when I was
hired.
</P>
<P>
   This is a mother, keep in mind, who had never picked up a
fashion magazine before her son started working at one, not even in
the supermarket checkout line.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   (If you find this difficult to believe, there is irrefutable
evidence in the back of her closet: pair upon pair of sensible flat
shoes.)
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Now she throws around the names Armani, Prada and Ungaro like a
pro, and she's added some height to her footwear, though she's
careful to clarify, ``I haven't made up my mind about the chunky
heel.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   She recently told me that her Molton Brown shampoo was almost
gone. (To which I was tempted to snap, ever heard of sephora.com?)
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite my hesitation at becoming my mother's wardrobe
consultant, I'm glad I injected some of the sprightly fun of
fashion into her life, however circuitously. If I couldn't benefit
directly from my insider knowledge, why shouldn't she? I could have
avoided it. Months into my copy-editing tenure, my parents were
still confusing Harper's Bazaar with Harper's Magazine, the more
high-brow general-interest magazine. Had I refrained from
correcting them, Mom might never have discovered cargo pants.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   (And my father would have continued to suggest subjects for the
Index, Harper's numerically obsessive trivia column.)
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   From time to time, I worried that I had lured my mother down the
path of frivolousness. Did she really need to start following
runway trends at this point in her life? Wasn't there a
continuing-ed class she could take, rather than tracking down the
best buys of pashmina? Parents don't need a son who knows that Tom
Ford is the genius behind Gucci; they need one who can assure them
that an aching knee is no big deal.
</P>
<P>
   Fear not: my parents' other child, my older brother, is a
physician. There's nothing like medical school to make you Mom and
Dad's golden child, so imagine my delight when I discovered that I
could steer the conversation away from high blood pressure and low
cholesterol with just two words: Calvin Klein.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, my mother's newfound interest in fashion wasn't enough to
keep me ensuring subject-verb agreement in articles about the new
nude shades of eye shadow. I confess I may miss our unexpected
connection. I'm sure she never anticipated it either, after all the
years when she cajoled and dragged me to the department store to
get new clothes for school.
</P>
<P>
   She'll be on her own now, but I suspect she'll still ask me to
look at tops and skirts she's uncertain about. She did have one
final request before I left: ``Could you renew my subscription?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
