<SLUG> BC-SRI-LANKA-CENSOR-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT BEGINS TO IMPOSE RESTRICTIONS ON PRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka _ A day after tightening press censorship in
what it called the interests of national security, the government
said in an official press release Friday that troops had pushed
back Tamil rebels who are trying to capture the northern city of
Jaffna, the cultural capital of the minority Tamils.
</P>
<P>
   But as they issued the press release, government officials also
deleted portions of reports by international news agencies that
described an opposition political rally organized by the United
National Party to protest sweeping new powers that have been given
to the authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider this an issue of national security,'' said Ariya
Rubasinghe, the government's director of information and chief
censor. ``We can't afford to have commotions or civil
disturbances.''
</P>
<P>
   The regulations announced Thursday empower the government to
censor news articles by foreign reporters and to close Sri Lankan
newspapers that defy censorship rules. Before, local journalists
who ignored the censor received written warnings. The government
can also seize private property and prohibit strikes, political
rallies and criticism of President Chandrika Kumaratunga if it
believes doing so is necessary for national security.
</P>
<P>
   But Rubasinghe, the chief censor, said that although the
regulations allow censorship of criticism of the president, ``We
won't enforce it seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Since last month, the government has been in a pitched battle
with the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, a group that has been
fighting for a separate homeland for the Hindu Tamil minority since
1983 and that the U.S. government has included on its list of
terrorist organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Since April 22, the rebels have taken control of two military
bases in the Tamil-dominated north in a push to regain Jaffna,
which the government recaptured five years ago. The majority of
this island nation of 18 million is Sinhalese and Buddhist.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's press release, issued by Rubasinghe, said the
government had strengthened its position since April 22 when it
pulled out of its sprawling military base at Elephant Pass _ now
occupied by the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Continuous attacks by the troops caused the terrorists to flee
southwards with their casualties,'' the release said. ``All troops
in Jaffna peninsula are determined to push back the terrorists. Due
to confrontations on 3rd and 4th of May, terrorists are in a state
of disarray. However, the terrorists continued to fire mortars at
the troops.''
</P>
<P>
   The government said two soldiers were killed Friday and one was
wounded.
</P>
<P>
   And it said that life continued normally in Jaffna, with
government offices and schools functioning. The government said it
was providing ``ample food'' to the people there.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It was not possible to assess the contents of the press release
because no reporters have been allowed to go to the battlefront or
to Jaffna, and telephone communications to the peninsula have been
disrupted.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the opposition United National Party held a rally
Friday in Independence Square in Colombo to protest the new
regulations, including those that censor foreign press accounts,
saying they were an infringement on civil liberties.
</P>
<P>
   News agency reporters based in Colombo said descriptions of the
rally were cut from their stories, as were some other sentences
about the status of the battle in the north that were not part of
the official version.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
