<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6959 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BUFFET-KREME-COX     05-05 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUFFET-KREME-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jimmy Buffett gets Krispy Kreme franchise
 &HT;    By Paul Owers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Come someday, you can thank Jimmy
Buffett for bringing Krispy Kreme doughnut shops to Palm Beach
County.
</P>
<P>
   The Winston-Salem, N.C.-based chain said it has granted the
singer and part-time Palm Beach resident franchise rights to build
outlets in the county.
</P>
<P>
   Krispy Kreme Doughnuts Inc. won't say how many stores will open
here, but one expert predicted the county could support three or
four. The outlets likely won't open until next year.
</P>
<P>
   Financial terms of the deal were not disclosed. Buffett could
not be reached for comment Thursday, and a spokesman did not return
calls.
</P>
<P>
   It is safe to say, however, that Buffett craves Krispy Kremes as
much as he does cheeseburgers in paradise. He mentioned the
doughnuts in his 1999 song I Will Play for Gumbo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really has a passion for our product,'' said Stan Parker, a
senior vice president of marketing for Krispy Kreme. ``He's a great
fan of Krispy Kreme, and Krispy Kreme is a big fan of Jimmy
Buffett.''
</P>
<P>
   Krispy Kreme has been making the pillowy pastries for 63 years.
In the South, they're as popular as country music, but the nearest
local stores are in Broward County.
</P>
<P>
   ``Krispy Kreme sure beats the heck out of Dunkin' Donuts,'' said
Jean Parker, a Jupiter resident and member of Buffett's Island Time
Parrothead Club. Parker is not related to the Krispy Kreme
marketing executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're old-fashioned, sugary, crispy, decadent fat pills that
you always thought doughnuts should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Alleva, who owns the Krispy Kreme shops in Fort Lauderdale
and Tamarac, said he regularly gets customers from southern Palm
Beach County. To satisfy the Krispy Kreme demand here, Alleva
trucks dozens of doughnuts to local gas stations, hotels and other
businesses each day. Sales are excellent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big deal for the area,'' Alleva said. ``People love
hot, glazed doughnuts. That's why the stores are so popular.''
</P>
<P>
   At a typical Krispy Kreme, customers can be found looking on
longingly as doughnut machines make the treats, drop them in hot
oil and bathe them in glaze. The doughnuts then pass along a window
to cooling racks ``like soldiers marching down the conveyor,''
Alleva said.
</P>
<P>
   After each fresh batch, employees light up a red neon sign that
announces ``Hot Doughnuts Now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When that sign is on, you find your car gravitating rapidly
toward the store,'' said Jim Holmes III, vice president of the
Winston-Salem investment firm that helped launch Krispy Kreme's
initial public stock offering last month. ``There's nothing like a
hot doughnut experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Krispy Kreme shares (Nasdaq: KREM) climbed more than 75 percent
during their first day of trading April 5. The IPO was priced at
$21 a share and opened at $32. Shares closed Thursday at $43.69, up
$1.56.
</P>
<P>
   Krispy Kreme has 152 outlets in 27 states. Some stores,
particularly those in college towns, stay open 24 hours a day. The
company makes more than 3 million doughnuts a day and 1.3 billion a
year.
</P>
<P>
   The company traces its origins to a family business that opened
in 1933, when Vernon Rudolph and his uncle bought a doughnut shop
in Paducah, Ky., from a Frenchman named Joe LeBeau. The deal
included the rights to a secret yeast-raised doughnut recipe that
LeBeau had created in New Orleans years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Other members of the Rudolph family soon joined the business as
it expanded in the South. Rudolph left the family venture in 1937
to open his own shop. He had little cash or equipment, but he did
have the secret formula for what would become Krispy Kreme
doughnuts.
</P>
<P>
   The company stayed true to its Southern roots before expanding
into the Northeast and Midwest in the mid-1990s. It is using some
of the $72 million in proceeds from the IPO to break into other
markets.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Riviera Beach talked to Krispy Kreme 18 months ago
about opening a store there, but the two sides could not agree on a
site. The company was interested in land on Blue Heron Boulevard
just off Interstate 95, but the property was not for sale, said
John Green, coordinator of the city's housing and community
development program.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with Buffett is the first time Krispy Kreme has granted
franchise rights to a celebrity, officials said. The venture with
Buffett's Margaritaville Holdings will be called KreMaritta.
</P>
<P>
   Margaritaville Holdings, which leased office space on Worth
Avenue in Palm Beach in 1998, operates four Margaritaville
restaurants in Key West, Orlando, New Orleans and Charleston, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a hoot,'' said Parker, the Buffett fan club
member. ``I'm amused by this. He's totally off the wall, but at
least he does things close to his heart.''
</P>
<P>
   paulowers(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
