<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6960 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-NITEOUT-OSCAR-JOKE-WR     05-05 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-OSCAR-JOKE-WRITER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NIGHT OUT WITH THE ALMOST FAMOUS BRUCE VILANCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 7)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHAEL MUSTO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The packed house at the recent preview of ``Bruce
Vilanch: Almost Famous'' seemed to like everything about this
one-man show playing at the Westbeth Theater Center except the
title. ``Take out the `almost,''' said one audience member, sensing
that Bruce Vilanch, the show's author and star, has already crossed
the threshold from aspirer to being there.
</P>
<P>
   Vilanch, a master of one-liners who has written for Bette Midler
and Robin Williams, most famously provides quips for stars to
deliver at the Oscars. He also writes witty bits for his own
appearances on ``The Hollywood Squares,'' which have allowed
viewers to recognize the impressively hirsute face behind the
zingers, turning Vilanch into something of a modern-day Paul Lynde.
</P>
<P>
   In his stage show, a mixed bag of showbiz stories and shtick,
Vilanch does his own impersonation of Lynde (telling off a mother
with a screaming baby) in between reminiscences of his experiences
writing patter for ``everyone from Abba to Zadora.'' His opening
line sets the tone: ``Good evening, I'm Linda Tripp. The makeover
was not as extensive as you've heard.''
</P>
<P>
   After the performance, Vilanch stepped into a black stretch
limousine and was joined by Craig Austin, his associate producer.
With his Grizzly Adams-style hair and pudgy body squished into an
``I'm a Friend of Kenny'' T-shirt (a gift from Dame Edna Everage,
who claims ``South Park's'' Kenny as her gay son), Vilanch
resembled a Muppet version of Harvey Fierstein crossed with Jerry
Garcia. He's campy and droll, but not mean, especially not to his
newfound fans.
</P>
<P>
   The car stopped at Lot 61, where a young crowd was celebrating
the birthday of Mark Silver, a publicist friend of Vilanch's. But
from the moment Vilanch entered, the party shifted focus, with
admirers descending on him, including one Fran Drescher type who
got close to his face and demanded, ``Are you having fun?'' Vilanch
assured her he was. So were cast members of ``The Donkey Show,''
the 1970s take on ``A Midsummer Night's Dream,'' which is playing
across the street from Lot 61 at El Flamingo. They danced around in
hot pants and body glitter, imploring Vilanch to see their show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about spreading love and glitter,'' cooed one cast
member. Vilanch was soon covered in the stuff and saying he needed
dermabrasion.
</P>
<P>
   A young man cornered Vilanch and gushed: ``You're like a
superstar. You're everywhere!'' Clearly, the fan knew Vilanch only
from his latest efforts, and not from such '70s clunkers as ``The
Brady Bunch Variety Hour,'' which he wrote and now calls the Dead
Sea Scrolls of television, along with the original ``Donny and
Marie Show'' and the movie ``Mahogany,'' in which he played a
fashion designer.
</P>
<P>
   By midnight, Vilanch had made his way to a party in his honor
given by HX magazine, a free gay weekly, at Hannah's Lava Lounge, a
lively bar in Hell's Kitchen featuring silver walls, ``Boys Don't
Cry'' posters and a crowd that seemed out of the later plays of
Tennessee Williams. People again swarmed him. ``Bruce is so
brilliant,'' noted Marc Berkley, a co-publisher of HX. ``It's a
shame some of the gay community rejects him just because he's not
gorgeous.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfazed by the attention, Vilanch broke away to survey the bar's
collection of video games. ``I've never seen a video game with
fruit,'' he said. ``We are in the right neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than play a game though, he headed back to the Excelsior
Hotel, where he was staying, to pare down the unwieldy first act of
``Almost Famous.'' As he was leaving at 12:45, a young man stopped
him to say he'd loved the show, with one reservation. ``At first
the jokes were over my head,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine too,'' Vilanch said. ``You'll grow into them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
