<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6966 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-MOTHER-BRIDE-FASHIONS     05-05 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTHER-BRIDE-FASHIONS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE COMES THE MOTHER OF THE BRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 7)  
(ART ADV: NYT Photo 6 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RUTH LA FERLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fretting over what to wear to her daughter's wedding,
Ilene Beckerman experienced an instant of panic. ``Everybody
remembers Princess Diana's wedding dress, but who remembers what
her mother wore?'' she told herself soothingly. ``Nobody pays
attention to the mother of the bride.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckerman knows better, of course. Taut as a snare drum, smooth
and polished as an apple, the mother of the bride these days is apt
to be as raptly scrutinized and cooed over as the bride herself.
With that in mind, Beckerman, who chronicles her experiences in a
new book, ``Mother of the Bride'' (Algonquin, $17.95), which she
wrote and illustrated, resolved not to fade into the marquetry at
her own daughter's wedding. Bypassing the discreet beige that more
conventional women trot out for such occasions, she chose a
decollete-baring number that riveted all eyes to her chest.
</P>
<P>
   Her dress was not, in a word, standard-issue
mother-of-the-bride, or MOB, garment-speak for a category of dress
that is fast outgrowing the decorous frocks of old. ``The time of
wearing a pale tunic and skirt is way past,'' said Rachel R.
Leonard, the fashion director of Bride magazine, an industry bible.
``It's a much hipper category than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The mentality of the mother of the bride changed,'' said the
designer Carolina Herrera, who is often consulted for weddings by
the gilded set. ``She no longer wants the gray chiffon or the
little lace dress.''
</P>
<P>
   Carole Gabay, 62, is typical of the militantly modern new mother
of the bride. ``Wear a beige dress with sequins?'' snapped Gabay, a
retired beauty industry executive living in Boca Raton, Fla. ``No
way! I jog four miles a day, I'm a size 6, and I wanted to look
like myself.''
</P>
<P>
   For her daughter Madeline's wedding in New York last June, she
wore a pink strapless gown with sheer inserts that showed off her
legs to the hips _ ``tasteful but certainly sexy,'' she said. ``It
could have been construed as a dress you wear to one of those
awards shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Gabay shares with many of her contemporaries a giddy fascination
with such media extravaganzas. Not less than the stars, they crave
their moment in the limelight. ``Women now have a really strong
picture of how they want to look,'' said Nadine Lopez Knudsen, a
New York couturier, who frequently outfits wedding parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the influence is Hollywood. We all want a little
glamour in our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Displaying a competitiveness bred by long years in the
workplace, many women seem to envision their daughter's wedding as
a crowning moment of their own lives _ a time to celebrate personal
triumphs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays, between going to the gym and plastic surgery,
everybody looks younger longer,'' said Frank Composto, a New York
fashion designer.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, mothers are motivated by the desire to take
center stage at the kind of fairy-tale wedding they never had
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of women I dress at least give lip service
that they do not want to overtrump the bride,'' said Vera Wang, the
doyenne of lavish New York weddings, who sells her body-skimming
evening wear to many mothers of the bride. ``In reality, however, I
have done some things so sensual, so sexy, that they could have
gone to the Oscars.''
</P>
<P>
   These days such showstoppers might include a Champagne-tone
number designed by Craig Natiello of Halston, which Joanne de
Guardiola plans to wear to the wedding of her stepdaughter, Jeanne,
in Southhampton on June 17. ``It's gorgeous, very classic and
form-fitting,'' breathed de Guardiola, describing a dress that was
cut to follow her size 6 frame.
</P>
<P>
   The dresses vary in mood from a minimalist black jersey leotard
top and skirt by Wang that was worn in 1996 by Sandy Perlbinder, a
New York filmmmaker, to a pull-out-all-the-stops confection
designed by Composto for Alinda Wyckert, a Texas socialite.
Complete with a black bustier and a cabbage-rose-clotted skirt, it
included a bustle and an elaborate train. ``Sharon Stone saw its
likeness at a White House dinner and loved it,'' Composto boasted.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Finkel, a personal shopper, who dresses many mothers of
the bride, said: ``Mothers all adore their daughters, but sometimes
they forget that the wedding is not their affair. Nine times out of
10, they will tell you, `I want simple, I want sleek, I want
nothing on the dress.''' But then comes the transformation. ``They
end up as embellished as a party gift,'' Finkel said, sighing.
``All those tulle buttoms and bustier tops. All they need is a
veil, and you could push them down the aisle.''
</P>
<P>
   Finkel works hard to prevent such lapses. She was not on hand,
however, at one wedding chosen by the mother of the bride as her
own moment to shine. As her daughter told a bridesmaid, the mother
pressured her to wear a conventional, nondescript frock bought off
the rack for $300. Then she was utterly eclipsed by her mother, a
vibrant bird of paradise in custom-designed raspberry satin, a
coal-size gemstone fastened to her chest. According to the
bridesmaid, the mother had never had a wedding of her own and was
making up for lost time.
</P>
<P>
   But such strenuous efforts to compete are more the exception
than the rule. More typical is Pearlbinder, of the leotard-bodice
Vera Wang. ``All I really wanted was to feel young in what I was
choosing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Beckerman, who subtitled her book ``The Dream, the Reality, the
Search for the Perfect Dress,'' acknowledged that she lacked the
discipline to shed pounds for a contour-skimming siren dress.
Seeking the safety of the traditional, she tried on, and discarded,
a pink and violet chiffon print (``Lady Bird Johnson would have
loved it,'' she writes) and a turquoise crepe (``I looked like a
wall in a hospital'') before settling on something more daring.
</P>
<P>
   The dress she wore plunged precipitously, though it covered the
proverbial multitude of sins. Beckerman said, ``I learned a long
time ago, if you show a little cleavage, nobody ever looks anywhere
else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 1757EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6967 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-NAVY-SPY-$ADV07-HNS &LR;      05-05 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAVY-SPY-$ADV07-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAILOR AWAITING SPY TRIAL BARRED FROM SPEAKING TO LAWYERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, May 7)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A sailor accused of giving the Russians secrets
about the U.S. submarine fleet has encountered a unique obstacle in
his efforts to mount a defense: The Navy won't let him meet
privately with his lawyers out of fear that he might reveal
classified information.
</P>
<P>
   Navy Petty Officer 1st Class Daniel King, an intelligence
analyst being held in the U.S. Marine Corps brig at Quantico, Va.,
faces one count of espionage and two counts of improperly
disclosing classified information for allegedly passing submarine
secrets to Moscow. He could receive the death penalty if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   King, a cryptography or code expert, was working at the National
Security Agency in Fort Meade, Md., in 1994 when he allegedly gave
the Russians a computer disk containing U.S. submarine data.
</P>
<P>
   King, 40, an 18-year Navy veteran and a native of Elyria, Ohio,
was arrested in the Washington, D.C. area by the Naval Criminal
Investigative Service on last Oct. 28 and charged Nov. 5. King
allegedly flunked a routine lie detector test, drawing suspicion
from investigators.
</P>
<P>
   But King has not met with his Navy or civilian defense attorneys
since March 2 when Vice Admiral Joseph S. Mobley, commander of the
U.S. Atlantic Fleet's air unit, barred all contact between the
defendant and his lawyers unless a Navy security officer was
present at the meetings. The Navy said some of King's attorneys
lack high security clearance called ``special access,'' reserved
for some of the nation's most guarded secrets, higher that ``top
secret.''
</P>
<P>
   King's civilian defense counsel, Jonathan Turley, a George
Washington University law professor, said the order also has the
effect of barring e-mails and telephone conversations among the
defense attorneys without a security officer present because all
three of King's lawyers have different levels of security
clearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a gross violation of attorney-client privilege,''
Turley said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   `My client is facing death and this is an untenable idea. What
we are asking is for the right to speak (privately) with our
client.''
</P>
<P>
   The case currently is awaiting the military equivalent of a
grand jury proceeding, known as an Article 32, where King could be
formally indicted. The Article 32 is on hold, however, pending
Turley's appeal to the military's highest court, the U.S. Court of
Appeals for the Armed Forces, to strike the protective order.
</P>
<P>
   The National Institute of Military Justice, a private
organization that monitors military courts, agreed that the
requirement of a security officer ``seemingly shatters the concept
of confidentiality and the attorney-client relationship along with
it. In our corporate experience and research, such an order is
completely without precedent.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the National Association of Criminal Lawyers said
that the protective order ``raises grave and fundamental
constitutional concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How is counsel to prepare for cross-examination, to know what
defense witnesses and evidence is available if they cannot
communicate with the accused with a certainty of privilege,'' the
group asked. The Navy has ``functionally barred the effective
assistance of counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   Both organizations filed amicus briefs in the appeal, which is
expected to be decided within the next month.
</P>
<P>
   Cmdr. Roxie Merritt, a Navy spokeswoman for Mobley in Norfolk,
Va., countered that the service is taking great pains to protect
King's rights while, at the same time, guarding national security.
For example, she said the Navy would appoint the security officer
as a dedicated member of the defense team who wouldn't be called as
a witness to testify against King.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always security officers in classified court
cases,'' she said. ``But this is the first time that we've
appointed a security officer as a member of the defense team.''
</P>
<P>
   While it might be unusual to treat an individual akin to a
secret document, Merritt said the Navy's view is that the
information in King's head must be kept protected. ``We go to great
lengths to protect national security secrets. There are American
lives at stake and the lives of allies,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In defense counsel meetings, the security officer's role would
not be to obstruct the defense, Merritt said. ``If the officer
senses that they are going to talk about things that are
classified, his objective would be to prevent them from going to
that area and warn them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One problem with that arrangement, however, is that it could
easily run afoul of Navy regulations. If King disclosed classified
information in the presence of people who lack proper clearances,
the security officer must report any suspected violations to Navy
officials, Merritt said.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the security officer would be serving two masters, an
arrangement Turley says in unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Merritt said King's attorneys could simply apply for the proper
clearances to end the dispute, allowing the case to move forward to
the Article 32 grand jury then on to a possible trial.
</P>
<P>
   But Turley countered that it could take months for the defense
legal team to obtain special access clearance.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be contacted at 202-298-6920 or via e-mail:
eric(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
