u f BC-CASPIAN-OIL-ART-300&AMP;A     05-05 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASPIAN-OIL-ART-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSORTIUM ENCOURAGED BY SIGNS OF BIG OIL FIELD IN CASPIAN SEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 By STEVE LeVINE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALMATY, Kazakhstan _ A consortium of nine foreign energy
companies has found oil in a huge Caspian Sea field, and resumed
drilling to determine just how much exists, officials close to the
companies say.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes that the find may prove to be huge were raised last week,
when President Nursultan Nazarbayev said at an international forum
here that the field, called Kashagan, looked so promising that he
expected Kazakhstan to export as much oil as Saudi Arabia by 2015 _
8 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   His remarks were premature. The consortium has not yet
determined whether Kashagan contains commercial volumes of oil. But
the officials said Friday that they were encouraged by the data
accumulated so far and that they would accelerate work on the
salt-domed field.
</P>
<P>
   While it will be at least another month before the drilling
establishes whether Kashagan has commercial volumes of oil, the
news that it does contain oil _ and not natural gas or water _ has
prompted much excitement among government and industry officials
both here and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Situated 40 miles off the northeast Kazakhstan coast, Kashagan
is a 2,000-square-mile field shaped roughly like an hour glass.
Early optimism was based on its proximity to and geologic
similarity with the Tengiz field in Kazakhstan, one of the world's
10 largest oil deposits, with recoverable reserves of between 9
billion and 13 billion barrels of oil.
</P>
<P>
   According to seismic tests, the Kashagan structure is two and a
half times the size of Tengiz, making Kashagan potentially one of
the world's five largest oil fields.
</P>
<P>
   Drilling began last year by the consortium partners: Agip of
Italy, BG PLC of Britain, Inpex of Japan, Totalfina of France,
Statoil of Norway, Phillips Petroleum, the Royal Dutch/Shell Group,
BP Amoco and Exxon Mobil.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Much caution has accompanied the exploration because of a
handful of dry holes drilled in the last couple of years across the
Caspian in Azerbaijan. Moreover, the region has turned up a surplus
of natural gas, so that some oil executives have regarded a
possible similar find at Kashagan almost as unfavorably as water.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium penetrated the three-mile-deep salt dome last
month. The drill instantly confronted natural gas, but the gas
dissipated and then all-but disappeared approximately 10 feet
deeper, according to officials close to the companies.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, chips of rock that found their way to the surface in
the drilling process revealed much evidence of hydrocarbons, these
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the consortium planned at this point to shift the
drilling platform to a second test well in a part of Kashagan 25
miles further west. But the initial results convinced the partners
instead to drill further in the current well to try to find its
conclusive ``oil-water contact line'' _ the depth of the oil
floating above the subterranean water also contained within
Kashagan.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium has said it may be able to determine whether
Kashagan contains commercial volumes of oil by June.
</P>
<P>
   If the consortium does declare Kashagan commercial, the
companies may contractually be forced to begin production by 2005 _
thus becoming key to the U.S.-backed oil pipeline to the
Mediterranean port of Ceyhan, Turkey. Washington has sought to have
the pipeline built by 2004.
</P>
</TEXT>
