<HEADER>
A6977 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-RAC-FUSAICHI-PEGASUS-     05-05 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-FUSAICHI-PEGASUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JOCKEY PREPARES TO TAKE HIS `TANK' INTO DERBY COMBAT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MATT GRAVES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ If Kent Desormeaux could navigate a fish to
fame two years ago in the Kentucky Derby, he figures he certainly
can do it again Saturday with an armored personnel carrier.
</P>
<P>
   That's how the California-based jockey compares Real Quiet,
nicknamed ``The Fish'' by trainer Bob Baffert because of his slim
stature, to Fusaichi Pegasus, the favorite to win the 126th running
of the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of talent, I think they're comparable,'' Desormeaux
said shortly after arriving here from a red-eye flight Friday
morning. ``In stature and conformation, there wasn't anything to
the other guy (Real Quiet). My ankles rubbed together when I rode
him. This guy's a tank.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus, a son of the late Mr. Prospector, was a
stunning winner of the Wood Memorial in his last start, and has won
four in a row since losing his debut by a neck. He's as imposing as
Real Quiet was ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be like comparing Shaquille O'Neal to Michael Jordan,
except (Real Quiet) wasn't that crafty on his feet,'' said
Desormeaux, who will be on his ninth Derby mount.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Desormeaux vehicle is trained by freshly minted Hall
of Famer Neil Drysdale. Fusaichi Pegasus will have to conquer a
large field of 18 opponents and a harrowing historical trend that
has buried 20 consecutive post-time betting choices in the 1
1/4-mile classic.
</P>
<P>
   This also will be Drysdale's first Derby starter, but Desormeaux
and Drysdale sound confident, tradition be damned. Desormeaux's
experience on Real Quiet should give him an advantage over many of
the riders _ six of them rookies _ in this cluttered field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think now that I've got a win under my belt, it's a lot
easier to go around there and not be in a panic or concerned about
whether I screwed up my chance to win one,'' Desormeaux said. ``I
can just go out there and ride the horse.''
</P>
<P>
   The major knocks against Fusaichi Pegasus are an unpredictable
temperament and the absence of a 2-year-old foundation. His first
race came less than three weeks before he turned 3. Drysdale said
that timetable was no accident.
</P>
<P>
   As for the colt's tendency to act up when he isn't racing,
Drysdale said, ``It's not been a concern to me. But it sure gave
you guys a lot to write about.''
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale said Fusaichi Pegasus was capable physically of racing
as a 2-year-old, but that he wanted to take his time with the $4
million colt because he was so large and needed time to grow out.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale's other Derby entrant, War Chant, also had only one
race at age 2. And, chronologically, War Chant will not turn 3
until after the Derby (Jan. 1 is the universally assigned birthday
of all thoroughbreds).
</P>
<P>
   ``War Chant was foaled on May 22 and he's slightly more
immature,'' said Drysdale, a soft-spoken Englishman who will be
enshrined in the Racing Hall of Fame in Saratoga Springs on Aug. 7.
``That's why we're putting on the blinkers. Some horses mature very
quickly and are precocious. They're ready to run as 2-year-olds. It
took a while longer than some others for Fusaichi Pegasus to be
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus broke his maiden on Jan. 2 and has been a
runaway freight train since. He won an allowance in February, then
beat The Deputy and 2-year-old champion Anees before romping to a
four-length win in the Wood Memorial at Aqueduct.
</P>
<P>
   But not everybody is convinced that the race should be conceded
to Drysdale's stable star just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's got great credentials coming off a strong Wood,''
said trainer D. Wayne Lukas, a four-time Derby winner who will
saddle High Yield, Commendable and Exchange Rate on Saturday. ``But
I think that was a tough race on everybody. He's coming here and
he's had those good days and bad days. I think this is a race where
you better be pretty focused. It's not a soft enough field where
you can make any mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas knows of what he speaks. He has sent out a record 35 Derby
starters, including last year's long-shot darling, Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   Sheikh Mohammed al Maktoum, who is starting long shots China
Visit and Curule as an entry from Dubai, also is unconvinced that
Fusaichi Pegasus can become the first favorite to win since
Spectacular Bid in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the winner will be an outsider, not the favorite,'' he
said. ``This is such a difficult race.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert, who saddled Real Quiet and Silver Charm to
back-to-back Derby victories, is hoping to upset the favorite with
Hollywood Futurity winner Captain Steve, who remains in search of
his first win as a 3-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked great without blinkers,'' Baffert said. ``The last
couple of times he ran, the riders said he seemed to get edgy and a
little hot going to the gate. He's more relaxed without them.
Basically, what we need now is some luck.''
</P>
<P>
   A little luck also might help Jenine Sahadi become the first
woman trainer to win a Derby. She has an excellent chance with The
Deputy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 1804EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
