<HEADER>
A6979 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-QUANTUM-BOS &LR;      05-05 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-QUANTUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRITE, CLICHED TRY AT AN INTERNET MOVIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is one distinct advantage to downloading a movie and
watching it on your computer. In a word, multitasking. While you
wait for the darn thing to download, you can read your e-mail,
check your stocks, and research your ancestry. While you watch the
darn thing, you can read your e-mail, check your stocks . . .
</P>
<P>
   You get the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quantum Project,'' billed as ``the first premiere event'' to
debut on the Internet, is a multitasking kind of movie, as trite
and cliched as a futuristic, sci-fi romance can get. In fact, it's
hard to decide which is more tedious: the process of downloading
the movie or the movie itself.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the 32-minute film wins the tedium prize. Why? At
least the two-hour downloading process required some investigative
reporting that will come in handy some day.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you don't believe the hype, there is no arguing that the
$3 million film represents the wave of the future. Produced by the
team that made ``What Dreams May Come'' and financed by
SightSound.com, it was made exclusively for distribution on the
Internet. Some day, all films will be distributed online, but the
technology isn't exactly there yet. The high-resolution version
($5.95) took 37 minutes to download Friday using a high-speed
Internet connection. No problem there. But then there was this
little problem when I tried to open the file: I received a message
demanding that I make Internet Explorer my ``default browser,''
instead of Netscape. That should have been easy _ at least that's
what three technical wizards here at the Globe thought. Eventually,
somebody figured out how to change the settings, just around the
time that the folks at SightSound.com answered my frantic e-mail
begging for support.
</P>
<P>
   That was way too much work for what was supposed to be a leisure
experience. After all, this ain't quantum physics.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the movie, which is quantum physics, of a sort.
See, there's this guy named Paul (a blurry Stephen Dorff). He's a
scientist. He smashes atoms. He hallucinates. He multitasks (go,
Paul!). The plot is about as fuzzy as the film quality, which fades
from sepia tones to shadows. There's an accident involving three
Volkswagen Beetles, and somehow, the physicist meets up with his
old flame (a blurry Fay Masterson), who may or may not be restoring
a building that resembles the Sistine Chapel. The lonely physicist
ends up having a tete-a-tete with his father (a blurry John
Cleese), who may or may not be ``the ob-gyn of the Internet.'' All
this amid fiery electrons that seem to communicate messages from
the great beyond, a glass that moves magically across a table, and
an electronic soundtrack that provides appropriate white noise.
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to spoil the ending and tell you whether the
unfeeling physicist wins the artistic beauty back. Actually, I'm
not really sure myself. Maybe the answer is in the credits that are
impossible to see at the end. But, oh well. Maybe the plot doesn't
matter. Consider the movie's great epiphany: ``Reality is what you
choose to make it.'' Such poetry, that.
</P>
<P>
   So here's the reality. If anyone seriously expects folks to go
through the trouble of downloading movies, they have to make movies
that are worth the wait. Granted, ``Quantum Project'' is an
interesting (if expensive and overly hyped) experiment, and it does
point toward the future. But despite what you may have read, the
future isn't now, not yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 1804EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
