<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6989 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-ARTS-HIGHTECH07-COX     05-05 2416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-HIGHTECH07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The (inter)face of arts adn technology
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, May 7.
 &HT;    By Tom Sabulis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a meeting of palette and pixel.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing they need each other to grow, Atlanta's arts
community and its high-tech industry are linking in creative ways,
forming connections that will place fresh troops on nonprofit
boards and reboot the arts' presence among e-world workers and
online.
</P>
<P>
   And if the arts happen to find a little extra cash along the way
_ well, no one's complaining.
</P>
<P>
   This convergence is also helping change the way the arts are
perceived by the business establishment. No longer can the city
powers afford to regard theater, opera, music, dance and the visual
arts merely as tasteful highbrow diversions, an extra for the
elite, something for the wives to do.
</P>
<P>
   Stung by recent criticism of Atlanta's arts commitment, leaders
around town, from both the arts and business spheres, agree that
building a national arts profile is a quality-of-life necessity for
a city competing for wired-world talent against such cultural
capitals as San Francisco, Seattle and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Some steps have been taken to reach that goal.
</P>
<P>
   The inaugural technology task force for the Woodruff Arts
Center's annual corporate campaign recently raised $250,000 from
the high-tech sector. The campaign hopes to attain its overall goal
of $6.6 million next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had two goals,'' says Bert Rayle, regional manager at
Goldman Sachs, who chaired the 19-member task force. ``We wanted to
get active participation, and we wanted to raise a little money.
We've done better on both fronts than we would have anticipated.''
</P>
<P>
   The quarter-million dollars donated by the city's
``up-and-coming wealth'' represents ``virtually all new money'' for
the arts, Rayle says, coming from entrepreneurs such as Alan
Daniels of realestate.com, Jeff Levy of eHatchery and Bob Cramer of
adam.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competing for talent means putting the best face on the
city,'' says co-chairman Steven J. Heyer, president and chief
operating officer of Turner Broadcasting System Inc. ``A critical
component of that is the quality of schools and other institutions
that enrich folks. I put the Woodruff high on that list.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arts &AMP; Business Council of the Metro Atlanta Chamber of
Commerce has, for the first time, recruited its chairman from the
technology sector.
</P>
<P>
   John Bacon is president and CEO of Iterated Systems, a software
company that helps businesses retain control of their brands on the
Web _ ``imagewear for e-commerce,'' he calls it.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon has a much wider target than the Woodruff task force: the
development _ and preservation _ of the culturescape that exists
beyond the mighty arts center.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon, who serves on the board of the Atlanta Singers, a premier
a cappella vocal group, is engaging high-tech firms around the
area, such as iXl and Macquarium, to help explore ways to sustain
the area's niche theaters, pocket-size dance companies and eclectic
music ensembles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to see another Jomandi story,'' he says,
referring to the city's flagship African-American theater, which
cut short its current season due to financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a natural creative affinity between technology workers
and arts enthusiasts, the Georgia Tech grad emphasizes a ground-up
approach that builds audiences, primarily by better communicating
what groups exist and what they're doing.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon, 54, wants to build an ``arts portal,'' which he
alternately describes as a ``really good Web site'' and ``on ramp''
for engaging audiences. Ideally, online visitors will use it to
find event listings, participate in chats, read reviews and learn
about volunteer opportunities with, say, the Metropolitan Atlanta
Arts Fund or the metro chamber's Business Volunteers for the Arts,
a program that trains professionals to be efficient nonprofit
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to have the community-oriented site up and running by
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The portal is a natural way to ``speak'' to the local tech work
force, which, Bacon says, numbers between 160,000 and 190,000
people under age 35.
</P>
<P>
   ``These young folks we're talking about have plenty of money,
and they're happily willing to spend that money on meaningful arts
participation,'' says Bacon, who has 50 employees in his Piedmont
Road office in Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is not an issue. It's just getting them there and
helping them be aware of it. Then their employers will see these
people going to Jomandi or Dad's Garage or wherever, and they'll
see them coming back to work re-energized and happy. They'll see
them staying with the company, which is the biggest issue that
technology folks face today.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon frequently cites Dad's Garage Theatre Company, a
shoestring troupe near Little Five Points specializing in
off-the-wall improvisation, as an example of the cutting-edge
creativity that appeals to the dot-com generation.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that Dad's Garage has one of the more active
arts group Web sites in town. The company gets 20,000 hits per
month at www.dadsgarage.com, according to artistic director Sean
Daniels. He says half the theater's 30,000 tickets sold this season
were purchased online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Web site is our main marketing tool,'' says Daniels, whose
company operates on a $250,000 budget.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from being updated daily, the Web site features an online
improv soap opera, ``Scandal,'' which visitors can participate in
by typing in a message. (A recent entry: ``I think Dr. Weeds is
even more handsome with his gruesome open wound, it draws attention
away from his face.'')
</P>
<P>
   The theater's Web site is sponsored by MindSpring, and Daniels
says the contribution amounts to ``about $2,500 worth of free Web
space and free accounts for our staff.''
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, MindSpring gets free tickets for employees to Dad's
Garage improv shows. ``We let them come here and blow off steam and
shout and yell,'' Daniels says. ``And they go back to work as
happier MindSpring employees.''
</P>
<P>
   In a burst of e-theater ambition, Dad's Garage is planning to
mount Web cams in its steel-roofed theater to broadcast next year's
annual fund-raiser in its entirety _ 25 1/2 hours of nonstop
improvisation _ over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Considering all this interactivity, it's no surprise that
Daniels, 27, has joined Bacon on the Arts &AMP; Business Council.
Daniels loves Bacon's portal idea. ``We (Dad's Garage) have our
own, but as far as everyone else goes, it's really hard to figure
out what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   A sophisticated portal unifying the arts community might also
spark fund-raising. It's important to connect with these tech-world
fans before they're ``zillionaires,'' Bacon says, by inventing new
ways for them to contribute financially, and electronically, to
arts groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these young people have stock options'' _ Iterated
employees do _ ``and some will be worth a lot of money,'' Bacon
says. ``Why shouldn't we invent simple processes that let them
allocate even a tiny portion of their options to some fund that
goes to support the arts?''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone can certify the arts' new clout in the business world,
it's Ellen Meyer, president of the Atlanta College of Art.
</P>
<P>
   With Internet firms looking for designers, ACA students are more
employable than ever. More than half the students major in fields _
video, digital art, computer animation _ relating to technology. If
they're not being hired by local dot-coms, they're moving to
Silicon Alley and Silicon Valley. The animation chief and senior
art director from George Lucas' Industrial Light &AMP; Magic spent a
day on campus last month reviewing student portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cyberspace is a visual world,'' Meyer says, ``and that's
wonderful for our students, because it creates a creative ground
for them. These two worlds are really coming together _ art and
design and business and technology. As they do, art becomes a full
player at the table alongside other business concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Often in the shadow of other Woodruff Arts Center divisions _
the Alliance Theatre, the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra, the High
Museum of Art _ the art college has new celebrity thanks, in part,
to the new technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden we're kind of hot,'' says Sallie Adams Daniel,
chairwoman of the college board and senior vice president at Bank
of America. ``I see us as the way that the Woodruff Arts Center is
going to relate to the high-tech community.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to underline its technological 'tude, the school invited
Marc Adler, the 27-year-old chairman of Buckhead-based Macquarium,
to speak at Saturday's commencement. Adler is also the founder and
chairman of Artisan Network, a global consortium of art-related
companies and the parent company for MisterArt.com, described as
the world's largest online discount art supply store.
</P>
<P>
   Adler agrees that technology's need for artists has legitimized
the arts in the eyes of the old-line business community. The more
technological the world becomes, he says, the more businesses will
need artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question,'' the Emory University graduate says.
``Technology is about pushing the limits and doing something new
and creating something that wasn't there before. Thus, we are all
artists in our own way. And that's what everyone understands and
knows. That's where we all can talk in the same language. And so
when you talk about the culture of the city, these are two groups
that may not, on a strategic sense, seem to be united, but in a
fundamental sense they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon, who has sung bass in the choir at Holy Innocents'
Episcopal Church for 18 years, says, ``It's people like us
musicians who make the best programmers, because a musician has to
deal with all kinds of things going on at once. And a really good
coder has to be able to do that, too. Linear sequential thinkers _
engineers _ typically don't make very good coders. It's just
another example of this arts-technology crossover.''
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that the growth of Atlanta business depends on the
quality of the arts scene?
</P>
<P>
   More than one local high-tech executive says that to attract and
retain creative, highly skilled technology workers, Atlanta needs
to be known as more than a major-league locker room for
professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent interview at his office, Bacon points out to a
cluster of employees. ``The people you'll find here are not the
stereotypical, bare-torsoed, painted-up sports fan,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we love to go to baseball games and whatever. But
these people are looking for more than just sports. Of that, we're
certain. We've got musicians. We've got performers. We have
artists. When they leave work, they're going to go find a great
jazz group or go to the symphony. They'll do all kinds of things
before they choose to go to a hockey fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Joey Burgoom, 31, a program manager at Iterated Systems who has
sung with the Atlanta Symphony Chorus, among other vocal groups,
puts the tech community's interests in a simple light. ``People
like being part of an exciting, international, eclectic
community,'' he says. ``A lot want to do different things, use
other parts of their brains.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta doesn't yet have the reputation of a major arts haven.
Struggling institutions such as Jomandi and the Marietta/Cobb
Museum of Art face uncertain futures. Earlier this year, three
outgoing arts leaders _ Ned Rifkin of the High Museum, Chris
Coleman of Actor's Express and Harriet Sanford of the Fulton County
Arts Council _ publicly questioned the business community's
interest in the arts.
</P>
<P>
   Sour grapes or wake-up call?
</P>
<P>
   Either way, some business people in the technology sector
suggest Atlanta's low profile in the arts dampens their prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've heard (from recruits) is, there's nothing to do
here; it's just a big void,'' says Beverly McDonald, a partner at
Socket PR, a high-tech public relations firm in Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   At an economic forum in March at the metro chamber, McDonald
talked about interviewing people around the country who balked at
coming here due to the perceived arts climate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit home hard,'' she says. ``I feel their pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Socket has formed an in-house group to examine how
company employees might assist arts organizations of their choice.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Levine Hartz, community relations director of iXl
Enterprises, says the Internet service and consulting company has
had no problem luring out-of-town workers, citing the area's usual
strong points _ nice weather, good place to raise a family.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if the arts community erodes further,'' she says, ``that's
one more strike against us. Just as traffic is a strike against
us.''
</P>
<P>
   At the economic forum, Iterated Systems' Bacon described
technology's track record for arts support as ``abysmal.''
</P>
<P>
   The nascent collaboration between arts and technology bodes
well, but tech gurus and art lovers such as Adler and Bacon say the
city has not yet arrived as a cultural destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have kind of a national scene anywhere,'' Adler says.
``We don't have kind of a centralized nucleus where we can gather.
Until we really unite as a city, we're not going to achieve the
greatness that a city like Seattle has, which is also a new city
that's embraced the technology and come up as a cultural mecca.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Bacon: ``Clearly, the money's here. We just need to get
hooked up better. You parachute into San Francisco, Boston, even
Cleveland, and you can't miss the arts. We don't have that quite
yet. We have to help make the arts more physically, tangibly
present, so that when you parachute in, you say, `Wow, this is a
cool place; I want to be here.' We need to work on that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B :
</P>
<P>
   For more on the Metro Atlanta Chamber of Commerce:
www.metroatlantachamber.com
</P>
<P>
   To learn about the Metropolitan Atlanta Arts Fund:
www.metroatlantaartsfund.org
</P>
<P>
   For the Woodruff Arts Center and its divisions, including the
Atlanta College of Art: www.woodruffcenter.org
</P>
<P>
   Join the improvisation at Dad's Garage Theatre Company:
www.dadsgarage.com
</P>
