<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLECTIBLES06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Collectors can indulge habit at show
 &HT;    By Michelle C. Brooks
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are a nation of collectors, and the South is catching on in a
big way.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeast racked up $2 billion in collectible sales for
1998, a growing corner of the market that tallies $10 billion
annually.
</P>
<P>
   So it's no wonder the International Collectible Exposition has
turned its attention to Atlanta. The prestigous show will be making
its Southern debut at the Georgia World Congress Center today and
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is amazing the passion that collectors have,'' says show
producer Claude Chmiel.
</P>
<P>
   In its 26th year, the exposition, sponsored by Krause
Publications, features more than 100 leading manufacturers
including Ashton-Drake Galleries, Barbie Collectibles/Mattel Inc.,
the Bradford Exchange, Cabbage Patch Kids, Harbour Lights, Howard
Miller, Kurt S. Adler and San Francisco Music Box Co. _ plus
hundreds of exhibit booths, seminars and artist signings.
</P>
<P>
   Several artists are scheduled to appear including acclaimed
African-American artist Annie Lee, Priscilla Hillman of Cherished
Teddies fame and Christopher Radko, the blown-glass ornament guru.
</P>
<P>
   Although collectors will not be able to shop at the show, a few
manufacturers _ Fitz &AMP; Floyd, Christopher Radko, Dreamsicles and
Harmony Kingdom _ will be selling pieces made specifically for the
show. Collectors looking to sell or trade their retired pieces will
enjoy the Swap 'n Sell two-day market. Seminars will include topics
such as: ``The Secondary Market: Tracking Your Collectible
Treasures.'' And for those who missed the Christie's auction, one
of Princess Diana's coveted gowns will be on display from
GoCollect.com.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the delicate figurines and the princess' dress
will be an 18-foot semi _ the Precious Moments Care-A-Van, a moving
museum. Recently renovated, this moving tribute to the art of
Samuel Butcher, artist for Enesco's Precious Moments line, will
interest those who adore the tear-drop-eyed figurines known for
their inspirational messages.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 9 a.m.-5 p.m. Saturday and Sunday. One-day
admission is $7; two-day ticket is $10. Georgia World Congress
Center, 285 International Blvd. N.E. 1-877-746-9757,
www.collectibleshow.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
