<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6993 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SOUTHERN-STEW07-COX     05-05 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-STEW07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Exhibit explores cultural side of stew
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, May 7.
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Take 200 pounds of meat, 100 pounds of onions, several gallons
of tomatoes and a heaping helping of tradition and throw it all in
a big iron kettle over an open flame. In a few hours, a good
old-fashioned Southern stew will bubble up _ enough to feed several
hundred at a fair or family reunion.
</P>
<P>
   In Owensboro, Ky., the meat will be mutton and there will be
some lima beans and maybe some okra in the pot. It's called burgoo.
</P>
<P>
   Near the Roanoke River in Virginia, it's known as rockfish
muddle, because striped bass is used. And throughout South
Carolina, it's called hash _ a mixture of onions, potatoes, beef,
pork, chicken and, perhaps, organ meats, all ground and cooked
together and served with rice.
</P>
<P>
   The ingredients vary by location, but the tradition of slowly
simmering large batches of stew for community gatherings is a
shared one captured in a new exhibit at the University of South
Carolina's McKissick Museum in Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exhibit really deals with the history of these stews, the
interaction of the cultures,'' said Jay Williams, McKissick's chief
curator of exhibits. ``So many people have eaten these stews and
don't even question where they came from.''
</P>
<P>
   Stew making is rooted in Colonial times. Europeans brought over
hunter stews or camp stews, which included the wild game of the
day; African slaves accustomed to black pot cooking had their
favorite stews; and Native Americans made vegetable stews. Soon
these traditions were blended and through the centuries have
evolved. Each stew has a story, and the origins of some are a
matter of hot debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like unscrambling an egg,'' Williams said. ``It's
difficult to pin down exact origins because the stews are a product
of very complex cultural interchange.''
</P>
<P>
   Brunswick County, Va., and Brunswick, Ga., have a longstanding
feud over who made the first Brunswick stew. Stewmasters from each
place frequently face off in cooking contests. (The Virginians won
the last one, yet the trophy mysteriously ended up in Georgia.) The
McKissick exhibit weighs in for the Virginians, citing early 1800s
diary entries of plantation owner Creed Haskins.
</P>
<P>
   Williams researched the exhibit with Stan Woodward, who has been
documenting the making of stews for nearly 10 years. Woodward's
videos are the central focus of the exhibit, which has three
viewing stations _ one for Brunswick stew footage (from both
Virginia and Georgia,) one for mutton-based stews (like burgoo in
Kentucky and sheep stew in Virginia), and one for Carolina
traditions of hash and Lowcountry boils. In addition, there are
photographs and artifacts, like heirloom stew paddles, cook pots
and recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said as urbanization takes over many towns and
mom-and-pop restaurants are closing, the stews aren't as available
as they once were. But they are still being made in home kitchens
and at large public events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Southerners tenaciously hold onto their food ways as a part of
their identity,'' Williams said. ``It's one of the taproots of
Southern culture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Southern Stews''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit runs through Oct. 29 at the McKissick Museum, Bull
and Pendleton streets on the campus of the University of South
Carolina. 9 a.m.-4 p.m. Mondays- Fridays, 1-5 p.m. Saturdays and
Sundays. Information: 803-777-5400.
</P>
<P>
   Brunswick Proclamation Stew
</P>
<P>
   Makes 600 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation /cooking time: 7 hours
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the recipes featured in the ``Southern Stews''
exhibit. It certainly is a good indication of the work of a
stewmaster. We didn't test it and wouldn't dare to find out the
nutritional information, but it sure sounds like a crowd pleaser
(though we're told it comes from Virginia, not Georgia.)
</P>
<P>
   210 pounds chicken
</P>
<P>
   12 pounds ground white meat
</P>
<P>
   100 pounds onions
</P>
<P>
   100 pounds potatoes
</P>
<P>
   12 gallons crushed tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   18 gallons butter beans
</P>
<P>
   3 cups salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup red pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup black pepper
</P>
<P>
   12 gallons corn
</P>
<P>
   12 pounds butter
</P>
<P>
   Start cooking chicken and ground white meat in a large pot;
cover with water and boil; add onions and potatoes; add crushed
tomatoes and stir well at all times. Then add butter beans, salt,
red pepper and black pepper. Continue cooking and add corn after
cooking approximately 6 hours. Let corn cook 30 minutes, add
butter, take off heat and continue stirring until served. Makes 75
gallons.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
