<HEADER>
A6995 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HOT-CHEF06-COX     05-05 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOT-CHEF06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For racing-circuit chef, cooking is no drag
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMMERCE, Ga. _ The JEG's drag racing teams pulled into Commerce
this week accompanied by two tractor-trailers, two pro-stock cars,
two pro-stock trucks, a mobile home, motorcycles, golf carts, a
tent, some chairs, grills, an entourage of 20 or so _ and a chef.
</P>
<P>
   While the teams spent Friday morning fine-tuning their engines,
Ian Rough rushed to the grocery and plucked eight fresh avocados,
10 pounds of chicken, cheese, peppers, onions and flour tortillas
to make fajitas for lunch. He also snagged ingredients to make
rigatoni for dinner and other meals throughout the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Rough's job is to keep teams and their families well-fueled
throughout the weekend of racing at the Advance Auto Parts National
Hot Rod Association Southern Nationals.
</P>
<P>
   That would include Jake Coughlin, a race car builder and owner
of JEG's, a high-performance auto parts distributor in Columbus,
Ohio, who leads the group. And his sons, Jake Jr., John, Troy and
Mike, who are race drivers. And wives and kids traveling with them,
and technicians such as clutch and transmission specialists.
</P>
<P>
   The Coughlins are now the envy of the circuit _ the only teams
with their own chef. And Rough's cooking beats the heck out of
midway food, say members of the Coughlin family, who decided to
hire a chef after years of making do with whatever they could grab
from vendors or late-night restaurants. Jake's wife, Sue, tried
feeding the crew, but as the numbers grew, she got fed up with
kitchen duty.
</P>
<P>
   So, relying on a friend's recommendation in Columbus, she hired
Rough, 23, straight out of the Culinary Institute of America, the
nation's top cooking school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It combines two of my favorite things, cooking and cars,''
said Rough, as he mashed avocados into guacamole. ``But no, I never
dreamed when I was in cooking school that I'd end up with a job
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Rough travels with the team to about 24 races between February
and November. Last year, he worked in the mobile home; this year he
has a custom kitchen on one of the tractor-trailers.
</P>
<P>
   His emphasis is on good, healthy food made with fresh local
ingredients, whether it's Seattle or Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly believe we've won a lot of races because of Ian. I've
told him if he ever leaves, he has to give us two years' notice,''
said Jake Sr.
</P>
<P>
   The Coughlins are successful; Jake Jr. currently is the points
leader in the pro-stock car division.
</P>
<P>
   Qualifying races began Thursday and run through today at the
Atlanta Dragway in Commerce. Final rounds will be Sunday, when $1.7
million in prizes will be awarded.
</P>
<P>
   Admission to the drag racing competition on Saturday is $38 for
adults, $10 for children ages 6-12, free for ages 5 and under.
Sunday fees are $42 for adults, with children's prices remaining
the same. Gates open at 7 a.m. both days, with races starting at 8
a.m. Saturday and 9:30 a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : Check out the National Hot Rod Association:
http://216.148.236.25/
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
