<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6997 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-SEASON07-COX     05-05 2139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SEASON07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV season made us feel like a million bucks
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, May 7.
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Switzerland!'' she cried.
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland? My wife is in another room, watching ``Who Wants to
be a Millionaire,'' shouting out the name of that historically
neutral country.
</P>
<P>
   Weird. She's not generally a shouter, and when she is, she's
generally not shouting out European states. But that's her answer
to a question on ``Millionaire,'' and like so many of us this TV
season, which ends May 24, she's talking directly to the TV, as if
a two-way wire somehow ran from our set directly to Regis Philbin's
ear.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not with her. I'm with my son in the living room, where the
TV is off. We're trying, this once, not to let ``Millionaire'' suck
us in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sleeping sickness!'' she cries.
</P>
<P>
   Sleeping sickness? All right, that's it. I'm in. I toss a
catalog on the coffee table, jump off the couch and rush to the
bedroom, where ``Millionaire'' glows on the tube like a votive
candle.
</P>
<P>
   Some guy from somewhere (aren't they all some guy from
somewhere?) has already won $32,000, and Reege's eyes are twinkling
_ partially from that twinkly Irish DNA of his, and partially, I
think, from the reflected sheen of his latest Mafia don wear: dark
suit, darker shirt, shiny dark tie.
</P>
<P>
   My wife's poised for the next question. I am, too. My son
continues to hold out in the living room. When we win our million
tonight, we're cutting him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millionaire'' doesn't usually polarize the family like this.
Just the opposite. When some guy from somewhere won a million
dollars one night (``Cockroach!'' my son shouted incorrectly to the
million-dollar question about which insect shorted an early
computer that led to the term ``computer bug''; it was a moth), the
three of us exploded into a whoop not heard inside the house since
... actually, we had never, ever whooped like that before.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``Millionaire'' became so much a part of our nights
together that when we moved in front of the set following dinner
one Wednesday and found some sitcom on instead of ``Millionaire,''
my son looked at me like that paperboy famously looked at Shoeless
Joe Jackson after learning he threw the 1919 World Series (``Say it
ain't so, Joe'') and asked, ``How come it's not on more often?''
</P>
<P>
   I explained that ``Millionaire'' was already on at least three
nights a week, more than any network show not called ``Dateline.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know,'' he said. ``But how
</P>
<P>
   come it's not on every night?''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Good question. There have been better TV seasons than the one
about to conclude but rarely has there been one more fun, and most
of the credit goes to ``Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   It was as if once a game show was unloosed in prime time to
become the most successful program on TV _ ``Millionaire'' should
be this season's three highest rated regular shows, averaging about
29 million viewers _ everything was up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Couric could show us her colonoscopy on NBC's ``Today''
(during which her doctor declared her ``clean as a whistle!''). CBS
could air ``Fail Safe,'' its first live drama in 39 years (with
more coming next season, can another ``Golden Age'' of live drama
be far behind?). ABC's Peter Jennings could win raves and viewers
(and a Peabody) by anchoring 24 straight hours of globe-trotting
millennium coverage, a rare, joyfully optimistic news event that
``Millionaire'' executive producer Michael Davies called a revival
of the variety show _ the next dead genre he expects the networks
to resuscitate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter Jennings sat there and said, `Let me show you another
thing,' just as Ed Sullivan used to say, `Now watch this,''' said
Davies. ``I know these news guys don't like to hear that. But Peter
did the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   David Letterman's heart got a lube job, and he returned bigger
than Jay Leno. CBS' Bryant Gumble got a new job on a morning show
that virtually no one watched and managed to lure even fewer
viewers (you do that math). John McCain made Americans of every
stripe care about televised presidential politics in February, the
Arizona senator's Straight Talk Express tour bus captivating
nightly news viewers like the enigmatic noodling of Albert Brooks'
trailer home in ``Lost in America.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a TV season that made us talk about TV again _ good, bad,
the worst. We talked about it, even as we were supposedly
e-chatting and
</P>
<P>
   e-shopping and e-trading all night long. After ratings declines
of 3 percent to 10 percent each year since the 1994-95 season, the
major broadcast networks' combined ratings this season are
virtually flat _ chiefly because of ``Millionaire.'' In a media
universe that feels splintered beyond recognition, TV felt warm and
bright enough again to reclaim its place as the national fireplace
_ a spot where we could all gather separately to share, you know,
somebody else's experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom says TV makes you stupid,'' said Stevie (Craig Lamar
Traylor), the four-eyed, asthmatic best friend in a wheelchair on
Fox's ``Malcolm in the Middle,'' the season's only breakout sitcom
(yes, the sitcom is dead).
</P>
<P>
   ``Stupid?'' said a disbelieving Malcolm (Frankie Muniz),the
freshest voice from the American family since Bart Simpson. ``TV
makes you normal!''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Well, normal is stretching it. ``Millionaire'' did have its
collateral damage. Fox's ``Who Wants to Marry a Millionaire?'' was
watched by more people who claimed to hate themselves afterward
than any show in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Rockwell and Darva Conger _ those crazy kids with the
porn-star names _ seemed scissored straight from the pages of
Post-Modern Bride. We saw this one coming a mile away and still we
couldn't not watch. They were like wedding cake figurines placed on
America's altar _ a Las Vegas hotel stage _ then brought suddenly
to life by Fox and sicced, Frankenstein-like, on the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marry'' captured perfectly the conflicted nature of our
televised times: We want to see it all, and we want it on record
how bad we think it is to look. Who wants to marry a millionaire?
Hell, we all do. But like ol' what-was-I-thinking Darva, we woke
the next morning to a world-class hangover, with the lyin' lug
snoring right there beside us.
</P>
<P>
   We promised never to drink like that again: The weeks following
that Fox special, when Rick and Darva made their separate,
pre-annulled rounds with Diane and Larry and whoever else asked,
were this season's ritual atonement, a kind of Stations of the
Cross that reminded us just how bad we'd been, and how sorry we
were, and how we would avoid all temptation in the future _ or at
least until the end of this month, when CBS airs ``Survivor,''
which strands 16 strangers on an island and films their attrition.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Other nights, other
</P>
<P>
   channels. ...
</P>
<P>
   The season's most restorative surprise was NBC's ``The West
Wing,'' a political drama created by Aaron Sorkin. He'd also
created ABC's ``Sports Night,'' the laugh-trackless dramedy that
last year promised to redefine the sitcom _ until both it, and the
sitcom, tanked. (Yes, the sitcom is dead. Remember ``Action''?)
</P>
<P>
   ``West Wing'' toted the season's heaviest baggage _ ask Al Gore
about Clinton fatigue _ then strapped politics to a gurney and
turned it into an executive branch of ``ER.''
</P>
<P>
   As up-to-the-moment and with-it as the show is (Rob Lowe as a
prostitute-dating aide? hel-lo), there's something reassuringly
retro about ``West Wing.'' It's the closest thing we have now to
FDR's old fireside chats. Each week we're let into the White House
to view all the pettiness and meanness and self-interest we can
handle, yet we walk away feeling safely in the committed hands of
engaged, likable folks who deal with those givens and move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``West Wing'' is a smart, savvy, sometimes even savage antidote
to our blaring talk-show cynicism; McCain's primary-season flare
only confirmed our private longing for this stuff. Martin Sheen, as
President Josiah Bartlet, should get more than a few write-in votes
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Less comfy, but no less effective, was ABC's ``Once and Again,''
the latest chronicle from those baby boom Boswells, Ed Zwick and
Marshall Herskovitz (``thirtysomething,'' ``My So-Called Life'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Once and Again'' was a hot boomer soap opera dressed up as
middle-class insight. It's genius was in admitting that they're the
same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Sela Ward (as separated-with-kids Lily Manning) and Billy
Campbell (divorced-with-kids Rick Sammler) were the dimple-chinned
faces all divorced-with-kids fortysomethings wish they had _ or
were with. Slinking last season over to the WB's ``Felicity,'' for
some teasing sex after TV's youthquake briefly wiped them from the
screen, boomers found that Lily and Rick's teenlike gropings let
them throw off Noel and Ben and Julie and feel young again, on
their own terms.
</P>
<P>
   Did I say young? I meant dirty.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Zwick and Herskovitz were annoyingly dead-on;
the guilt, the panic, the exhaustion of divorced parents was
displayed in such keen-eyed, almost poetic detail, that it spoke to
the whole universe of adults whose lives haven't turned out quite
like they'd figured.
</P>
<P>
   Rick: ``I always had a map for my life. And now, it's like I
walked off it entirely. It's weird.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddening as she could be, Ward's character was the season's
most evolved female _ older, divorced, kids, and still attractive
to attractive men. The fact that she really is a knockout was
beside the point _ Lily's glow came less from her gorgeous,
Sprint-spokeswoman hair than a kind of midlife incandescence. Lily
craved both intimacy and sex while lashed to a world of car pools
and visitation exchanges and dying parents.
</P>
<P>
   Ward was one slim rung further along the network evolutionary
ladder than Amy Brenneman, who created a winningly heartfelt role
as a harried juvenile court judge and single mom in CBS' ``Judging
Amy.'' And Ward was two rungs ahead of Kathleen Quinlan, who gave a
harder, more L.A. edge to her lawyering single mom in CBS' ``Family
Law.''
</P>
<P>
   All three were welcome leaps ahead of Sydney Hansen (Melina
Kanakaredes), the prodigal plastic surgeon returned home in
``Providence,'' last year's surprise chick hit on NBC. Dr. Syd was
a start _ she gave the networks permission to build dramas around
adult female leads. Still, the fear before this season was that all
women would be like her: TV smart but not one teaspoon more.
</P>
<P>
   Surprise: The smarts of this season's women weren't dumbed down.
And guess what? We fell for them. Hard.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   In its second season, HBO's ``The Sopranos'' went from cult
favorite to TV's most talked-about show. Much of the talk centered
on whether the second season lived up to the first; office workers
engaged in the kind of cross-cubicle debates not heard since the
last years of ``Seinfeld'' (yes, the sitcom is dead). Now we all
have an Uncle Junior; now we all pay off our debts in ``boxes of
ziti.''
</P>
<P>
   This season's ``Sopranos'' was a frequent stunner, bookended by
the arrival and departure (two gunshots to the chest) of dead-eyed
Richie Aprile (David Proval), who replaced Tony's mother Livia
(Nancy Marchand) as TV's most fearsome character.
</P>
<P>
   In between, ``The Sopranos'' sputtered and soared: the
near-death experience of Tony's nephew Christopher (Michael
Imperioli), during which he arrived at the gates of hell _ an Irish
bar where every day is St. Patrick's Day _ might have been the
series' most profoundly hilarious scene ever.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Sopranos,'' with the unmatchable James Gandolfini as
Tony, the mob boss we all would be, was never less than very good.
The honest artistry of it proved _ despite wailing over the demise
of ``Freaks and Geeks'' and ``Sports Night'' and ABC's two-episode
wonder ``Wonderland,'' each brilliant but fatally flawed _ that
there is no such thing as a show too good for TV. There's only too
much TV.
</P>
<P>
   And that's this season's big lesson. There might have been a lot
of awful game shows this year, but that only meant fewer awful
sitcoms and dramas. ``Millionaire'' and its brethren didn't push
out quality; they just shrunk the networks' sitcom-drama-newsmag
Bermuda Triangle.
</P>
<P>
   The effect, this season, was subtle. For instance, Mike Billok
of Silverdale, Wash., was asked one Sunday night in March, for
$250,000: What did Newton Minow call ``a vast wasteland'' in a
controversial 1961 speech?
</P>
<P>
   The answer: A) public schools, B) Congress, C) suburbia, D)
television.
</P>
<P>
   Billok didn't know. Didn't know! And so he walked away with
$125,000.
</P>
<P>
   That's how much fun this season was. Mike Billok couldn't even
remember that the vast wasteland is... D.
</P>
<P>
   Television.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
