<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7011 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-ART-1S     05-05 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-870&AMP;ADD-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL ATTEMPTS TO DEFUSE NEW VIOLENCE WITH GUERRILLAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for complete writethru to recast and add new reporting and
background; note new byline and addition of dateline and art
note.) 
 (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Israeli government, facing a coming troop
withdrawal from southern Lebanon for which it needs international
backing, decided Friday not to continue reprisal bombings in
Lebanon even though another cross-border guerrilla offensive took
place Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to interrupt the volley of retaliatory attacks and
defuse the exploding violence, Prime Minister Ehud Barak and his
security Cabinet decided they would not respond militarily to a
second day of Katyusha rocket fire on northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel has no interest in escalation,'' a senior Israeli
official said. ``It was the appropriate moment to take a giant step
backward.''
</P>
<P>
   No one was seriously hurt Friday by the barrage from the
Hezbollah, or Party of God, on northern towns. But the rocket
attacks, quickly following an assault on Thursday that killed an
Israeli soldier and wounded civilians, reinforced the residents'
apprehensions that they were entering a volatile period. They fear
that the period leading up to the troop withdrawal, less than two
months away, will be violent and that the aftermath will be
violent, too.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has maintained that Israel's 22-year occupation of
southern Lebanon sustains the struggle, and that once Israel
withdraws, the rationale for guerrilla attacks will fade. With U.N.
troops in southern Lebanon and international monitoring in place,
there is unlikely to be an all-out battle on the border, he says,
even though it would have been safer to pull out as part of peace
agreements with Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Having acted on public sentiment that Israel should end its
involvement in Lebanon, Barak now expresses occasional impatience
with those who are getting cold feet that he is following through
on the most galvanizing campaign promise he made last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame that this sweeping public discussion and internal
dialogue about withdrawing from Lebanon didn't take place before we
went into Lebanon,'' he said in an interview published Friday in
the Yedioth Ahronoth newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Barak did validate the concerns of Israel's northernmost
residents _ if somewhat offhandedly. ``There are no added dangers''
to the north after a troop withdrawal, he said, ``apart from direct
gunfire at the houses that sit right on the border.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is true that those dozens of homes in 17 communities facing
the frontier will be exposed to a higher risk,'' he continued,
``but the entire idea of the withdrawal is to reduce the friction,
because this greatly reduces the legitimization of operations
against us.''
</P>
<P>
   In the latest escalation of violence, Hezbollah said Israel had
started it. Israel and the Israeli-backed South Lebanese Army
caused civilian deaths and injuries on Wednesday and Thursday in
bombing and shooting attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Israeli army officials characterized those attacks as
accidents, compared with the guerrilla response, which they said
was deliberate and murderous.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a difference between mistakes and intended fire into
the center of a populated city,'' said Maj. Gen. Giora Eiland.
</P>
<P>
   After the Hezbollah attacks Friday morning, the Israeli security
Cabinet sequestered itself in a Tel Aviv meeting room for the
second time in less than 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the ministers emerged shortly before midnight to
order a limited bombardment. Israeli warplanes struck two Lebanese
power stations, a suspected guerrilla ammunition depot and the
Beirut-Damascus highway.
</P>
<P>
   Proclaiming their targets to be carefully chosen and their fire
to be efficient, Israeli army generals noted Friday that only one
civilian was injured. They also said that they had not considered
striking Syrian targets, and that they did not think that Syria
encouraged or instructed guerrillas to attack but rather failed to
prevent their fire.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While Barak has said that he is not optimistic that talks with
Syria will resume before the withdrawal, ``the door is always still
open,'' he said. European and Arab diplomats say they still think
it is possible that peace negotiations will resume.
</P>
<P>
   Plans, however, are being made for a unilateral withdrawal from
southern Lebanon, under a 22-year-old U.N. resolution.
</P>
<P>
   In order to carry out the withdrawal, Israel will need the
support of the United Nations on the ground as well as in
maintaining peace once Israeli troops leave. Barak also does not
want to alienate countries with continued bombings, or military
operations outside the zone of conflict, because he hopes to build
up diplomatic support in case the withdrawal goes awry.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the U.S. government urged Israel and Hezbollah to
restrain themselves and expressed disapproval of both sides'
attacks on civilians and civilian targets. ``There is no place for
such attack,'' a State Department official said. ``We are deeply
troubled by the recent escalation of violence, and we deeply regret
the loss of life, injury and damage to infrastructure on both
sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak and his government faced some pressure from the right-wing
opposition to bomb again and more intensely. But the opposition is
not strong.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ariel Sharon, who led Israel's invasion of Lebanon in 1982 and
now heads the opposition Likud Party, said just one air-strike was
insufficient to signal Israel's intention to withdraw and stand up
for itself at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot change the situation with one lone action,'' Sharon
said. ``We must carry out a thorough, systematic and continuous
policy to hit both Syrian and Lebanese interests in Lebanon.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hezbollah rocket attacks Friday on Kiryat Shemona and the
small, poor town of Slomi proved to be less accurate than those on
Thursday, which may indicate that they moved their launchers under
pressure, military experts said. Still, they hit four homes, two
supermarkets, a youth hostel and more than a dozen cars. And since
they fired on the northern and eastern Galilee at the same time,
the hiss of the rockets and the sight and smell of the black smoke
made residents feel that they were in a war.
</P>
<P>
   Many fled south to relatives' homes. Others huddled in bomb
shelters, where they were visited by Barak on Thursday night. He
cautioned them to prepare for a long stay underground.
</P>
<P>
   But by nighttime, with all quiet, military officials told them
they could return to their homes for the Sabbath.
</P>
</TEXT>
