<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7013 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-RELIGION-POLITICS06-C     05-05 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-POLITICS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Both Democrats and Republicans are reaching beyond evangelical
Protestants in hopes of capturing one of the key groups needed to
win elections.
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the pundits were pondering whether religion would play much
of a role in this year's presidential election, most forgot to ask
a pretty fundamental question: Which religion?
</P>
<P>
   Protestant conservatives have played the most vocal role in the
presidential politics of the past 20 years. They have been in the
news this year as well, in the controversy over Gov. George W.
Bush's speech at Bob Jones University and Sen. John McCain's
denunciation of Pat Robertson and the Rev. Jerry Falwell.
</P>
<P>
   As Ronald Reagan and his father had before him, Bush used an
invitation to speak at the fundamentalist Protestant school outside
Greenville, S.C., to appeal to religious conservatives before the
South Carolina primary, which the Texas governor had to win to
restore faith in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But as the controversy over the speech ultimately proved, Roman
Catholic voters are at center stage this year.
</P>
<P>
   Although it had received more attention before the speech, the
university's policy banning interracial dating did not become as
controversial after Bush's speech as the anti-Catholic preachings
on the school's Web site. Bush's success in the South Carolina
primary, where Protestant conservatives swung heavily in his favor,
was contrasted with his loss to McCain a few days later in
Michigan, where McCain's campaign had targeted Catholic voters with
phone calls about the Bob Jones issue.
</P>
<P>
   When McCain upped the ante, attacking Robertson and Falwell by
name in a speech at Virginia Beach, the home of the Christian
Coalition, his appeal fell flat with most Republican voters. But
Bush was sufficiently alarmed to write Cardinal John O'Connor, the
archbishop of New York, who died this week, a letter regretting not
having taken a stronger stand in his speech at Bob Jones
University. It was final confirmation that Catholic voters will not
be ignored this year.
</P>
<P>
   In large part this year's focus on Catholic voters is a matter
of perception catching up with reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the African-American evangelical vote is the base vote of
the Democratic Party and the white evangelical vote is the base
vote of the Republican Party, then Catholic voters are the jump
ball of American politics. They have been the swing vote in every
presidential election since the 1960s,'' said Republican consultant
Ralph Reed.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic voters were at one time a dependable part of the
Democratic majority, but abortion, crime and school busing caused
many to defect to Richard Nixon and later to Ronald Reagan. In the
past decade they have helped elect Bill Clinton _ as well as
several Republican _ and Catholic _ governors, such as John Engler
of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   That point has been brought more sharply to mind this year
because of the importance of Catholic voters in the big
Northeastern and Midwestern states, which are expected to be the
hottest battleground of the presidential election, as well as in
several key Senate races.
</P>
<P>
   Deal Hudson, editor of Crisis, a conservative Catholic magazine,
and an informal adviser to the Bush campaign, said changing
attitudes among American Catholics are also affecting the political
climate. After an era of trying to ``assimilate'' into the larger
American community, he said, Catholics have grown tired of being
ignored and ``want to be recognized as Catholic Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican nervousness over the Bob Jones controversy heightened
when House Speaker Dennis Hastert passed over a committee's
preference for a Catholic priest, the Rev. Timothy O'Brien, to
appoint the Rev. Charles Wright, former senior pastor of the North
Avenue Presbyterian Church in Atlanta, to the post of House
chaplain.
</P>
<P>
   Wright withdrew his name in March and Hastert appointed another
Catholic, the Rev. Daniel Coughlin of Chicago, to be the first of
his religion to hold the honorary post.
</P>
<P>
   Between the two controversies, ``Republicans were in deep danger
of totally blowing the Catholic vote,'' said Clyde Wilcox, a
professor of government at Georgetown University in Washington.
While the damage could be repaired, he said, Bush will need to send
some ``strong positive signals'' to Catholic voters.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the nation's largest religious denomination,
representing a great racial and national diversity, does not vote
in lock step. Polling indicates there is now about an even
Democratic-Republican split, with 40 percent of Catholics in the
swing voter category.
</P>
<P>
   While Al Gore has no competition for liberal Catholic votes,
Bush may also be competing for conservative Catholic votes with a
conservative Catholic, Pat Buchanan, if Buchanan becomes the Reform
Party nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest irony of all was that Bush was the only candidate
with an explicit Catholic strategy,'' Hudson said.
</P>
<P>
   This strategy, he said, was based on an understanding of the
growing role of the Catholic Church in the party.
</P>
<P>
   Eye on running mates
</P>
<P>
   One issue in which sensitivity to the Catholic vote could show
up is the selection of vice presidential nominees. Republican Gov.
Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania and Democratic HUD Secretary Andrew Cuomo
are among Catholics on the parties' short lists of potential
nominees.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee chairman, Jim Nicholson, is
Catholic, and Catholics make up a higher percentage of the party's
governors and members of Congress than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Protestant-Catholic tensions exposed by the Bob Jones
incident, Reed, the former executive director of the Christian
Coalition, argued there's ``probably a greater cooperation and
communication between evangelicals and Catholics than at any time
since they respectively became engaged in civic affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed sees Catholic social teachings that ``the institutions
closest to those in need are best able to help them'' fitting
closely with Bush's ideas about replacing government programs with
private and religious efforts. But Wilcox said Catholics tend to be
more ``communitarian'' in outlook. ``It doesn't have to be
government that helps. But it can be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson, a former Baptist minister who became a Catholic while
living in Atlanta, said that while evangelicals and Catholics often
take the same side on issues, they respond differently to political
appeals.
</P>
<P>
   `Can't get preachy'
</P>
<P>
   ``With evangelicals you can preach the message, and they will
hear and support you,'' the editor said. ``Catholics want calmness
and warmth, an inclusive message and a positive message. You can't
get preachy with them.''
</P>
<P>
   In counterpoint to this political season's focus on Catholic
voters and issues was the recent news that Robertson, who gave up
his ordination as a Southern Baptist minister to run for president
in 1988, has again taken the ministerial vows, this time before an
``ordination council'' of advisers from several denominations.
</P>
<P>
   To some degree the curve of Robertson's career follows that of
the evolution of the religious right. The Christian Coalition is
only a shadow of what it has
</P>
<P>
   been in previous elections, but the influence of the religious
right was clear during the primary season.
</P>
<P>
   There is no longer a need for religious conservatives to charge
the bastions of the Republican Party, Reed said, because they have
largely found their place there.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
