 For Release SATURDAY AMs, May 6, 2000  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta
 &LR; at the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-RAIDS (Tel Aviv) _ Tentative calm returns as Israel's
cabinet decices not to launch a third round of air raids against
Lebanon. But two rounds of Katyusha rocket attacks on Northern
Israel and retaliatory air strikes against power plants, highways
and other facilities in Lebanon have raised tensions to the highest
point in years. By Aliza Marcus. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-FARMS (Johanessburg) _ Invasions of white-owned farms
hits a new peak and violence spirals across Zimbabwe. Thabo Mbkei
travels to Harare to talking things over with embattled President
Robert Mugabe. By Kurt Shillinger. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-LOYALTIES (Washington) _ A House vote on the
Africa-Caribbean trade bill shows how local concerns can trump
global issues. Those loyalties will be tested in what is expected
to be a much closer vote on trade with China. By Susan Milligan.
</P>
<P>
   COASTER-DANGER (Washington) _ US Rep. Edward Markey is planning
to crusade against a generation of huge new roller coasters, coming
to theme parks nationwide, that apparently can damage the brain. By
Anne E. Kornblut. (w and a coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GENES-MISCONDUCT (Undated) _ Allegations of misconduct in gene
therapy experiments reflect unease about this unproven technology.
They also reflect a much broader concern about the oversight of all
research that could pose risks to human subjects. By Richard
Saltus. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-VIRUS (Undated) _ As the Love Bug computer virus morphs
into up to eight other forms, experts say businesses and
law-enforcement officials will have to take strong action to
prevent hackers from using relatively simple code to disable
computers worldwide. By Ross Kerber. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-PLAGIARISM (Undated) _ Connecticut College president
Claire Gaudiani's speech on multi-culturalism was apparently so
good that another college president, in Delaware, delivered big
chunks of the address _ twice. By David Abel. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; MOVIE-QUANTUM (Undated) _ ``Quantum Project,'' billed as ``the
first premiere event'' to debut on the Internet, is as trite and
cliched as a futuristic, sci-fi romance can get. By Patti Hartigan.
600 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CISCO-ARROWPOINT (Undated) _ Cisco Systems makes its second
biggest acquisition, buying Arrowpoint Communications, a
Massachusetts switching-equipment maker. The $5.7 billion stock
deal marks Cisco's 11th acquisition in New England, bringing its
total investment in the region to $9.9 billion since 1994. By
Ronald Rosenberg. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-JETS-PARCELLS (Undated) _ Bill Parcells has decided to stick
around the New York Jets indefinitely, as the director of football
operations. He'll monitor the progress of a record four No. 1 picks
he shopped for in April's draft. By Nick Cafardo. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   RAC-DERBY-COMMENT (Louisville, Ky.) _ It would be nice to bet on
the Kentucky Derby with Confederate money, spreading oodles of
bills every which way and back to cover all the wagering
possibilities, all the while not risking much. By Michael Madden.
1300 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   RAC-DERBY-ADVANCE (Louisville, Ky.) _ How Fusaichi Pegasus will
do in the paddock, or on the way to the gate before the Derby
throng, which numbered 151,051, last year, remains to be seen. By
Ron Indrisano. 950 words.
</P>
