<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7028 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-VIRUS-WORLD-0506-COX     05-05 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRUS-WORLD-0506-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AROUND THE WORLD: COMPANIES, GOVERNMENTS FIGHTING OFF THE 'LOVE
BUG'
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    By ALEC SCHULTZ 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With monikers like ``Joke'' and ``Mother's Day,'' copycat
variants of the ``Love Bug'' virus threatened to infect computers
around the world on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But follow-up reports from governments and corporations from
Hong Kong to Berlin to Rio de Janeiro, working feverishly to clean
up the mess left by Thursday's widespread electronic invasion,
indicated that the new strains lack the virulence of the original.
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, by noon, there were no new reports of chaos caused by
the virus. Multinational corporations in Moscow, complained
primarily of some email difficulties. Spokesmen for a British law
firm and U.S. consumer foods company operating in Russia said their
email systems were down as per instructions from their home
offices, but that business experienced few interruptions.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the bug in Asia was possibly muted by the fact
that markets in four countries _ Japan, South Korea, China and
Thailand were closed for public holidays on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   That followed a day in which the world's fastest-spreading bug,
spawned possibly from two
</P>
<P>
   Philippine e-mail addresses, hit companies in Taiwan and Hong
Kong Thursday afternoon as the other half of the world was
sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong, broker Nomura International's office was hit, as
were the South China Morning Post, Dow Jones Newswires and the
Asian Wall Street Journal. The bug affected only e-mail and did not
prevent Dow Jones Newswires from distributing financial information
to traders. The
</P>
<P>
   Asian Wall Street Journal would have no problems publishing,
officials there said.
</P>
<P>
   About 385,000 computer files were affected by the virus in
Europe, and 19,000 were hit in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The virus forced the British House of Commons shut down its
email network to prevent the spread of the bug. In Copenhagen,
Danish lawmakers were flooded with emails containing the vius.
</P>
<P>
   In France, the ``love bug'' struck several government offices
and banks, with many forced to block access to email servers. In
Italy, officials at the UN Food and Agriculture Organization said
computer systems at the Rome-based group's headquarters were
paralyzed when an employee inadvertently opened a ``LOVE'' email
message.
</P>
<P>
   A banking network in Belgium was suspended and wide disruptions
were also reported in Germany, Austria, Switzerland, England and
Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   In Berlin, several key German government institutions were hit
by the ``Love'' email computer virus and on Friday were forced to
shut down their email systems until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Among those affected were the foreign ministry, the interior
ministry and the finance ministry, German officials said. The virus
was prevented from getting into the German chancellery, law
enforcement agency, and defense ministry because of a computer
security system.
</P>
<P>
   A German government task force will assemble to discuss ways to
prevent a repeat, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates suggested that between 10 percent and 30 percent of
British businesses were hit. Among the firms and organizations
affected in the UK were media companies including News
International _ publishers of the Times of London and the tabloid
Sun _ the BBC, and a number of major companies.
</P>
<P>
   In an announcement to the Commons Thursday, Margaret Beckett,
leader of the House, said the parliamentary email system had
crashed. ``I have to tell you that, sadly, this affectionate
greeting contains a virus which has immobilized the house's
internal communication system,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the UK arm of Reed International, a publisher of trade
magazines, IT engineers alerted staff after the bug had already
crippled their computer system. ``It completely wipes out your
network,'' said Sarah Perkins of PC Pro magazine. ``Ours is down
and we're going to lose a day's business.''
</P>
<P>
   After it was suggested that the virus may have come from
Lithuania, officials in the former Soviet satellite said they would
launch an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   One variant of the virus, called ``Susitikim'' (Lithuanian for
``let's meet'') has a subject line that reads ``Susitikim shi
vakara kavos puodukui.'' In Lithuanian, this means: ``Let's meet
this evening for coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   But Latin America, which appeared to avoid Thursday's havoc,
seemed to escape the variant strains of the virus on Friday as
well.
</P>
<P>
   For example. preliminary estimates put the number of computer
systems affected in the region at about 22,000, a number
significantly less than Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The region escaped largely unscathed due to a smaller amount of
computer infrastructure in many countries. But several of the
region's technologically advanced countries did experience
problems.
</P>
<P>
   In Brazil, the virus transmitted by e-mail affected a gamut of
victims from the Globo.com
</P>
<P>
   portal to the Agencia Nacional de Telecomunicacoes (Anatel).
Computer technicians in the country are working to salvage
information from the affected computers.
</P>
<P>
   In Costa Rica, although the virus appeared in many email
accounts of various businesses, only the Institute for the
Protection of Biodiversity and Microsoft of Costa Rica were
affected. For both companies, the damage to computer systems was
said to be minimal.
</P>
<P>
   That remained a familiar refrain on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, one of the world's hottest high-tech corridors, the
virus reportedly tied up internal email systems at some of the
country's largest hi-tech companies _ including Comverse Network
Systems Ltd., which makes telephone messaging systems, and one of
Israel's cellular telephone companies.
</P>
<P>
   But little, if any, damage was reported overall and there was
scant evidence of Friday's variant strains worming their way into
more systems.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, most news reports focused on the international breadth
of the virus. One newspaper, Yedioth Aharonot, covered the ``I Love
You'' virus under the headline, ``Fatal Love.''
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Newspapers foreign correspondents Julie Chow in Beijing;
Margaret Coker in Moscow; Larry Kaplow in Jerusalem; and Bert
Roughton Jr. in London contributed to this report).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
