<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7033 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-COX-JOURNAL-CHINA-$AD     05-05 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-JOURNAL-CHINA-$ADV07 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOURNAL: IN MORE MODERN CHINA, OLD HABITS DIE HARD
 &HT;    With Photo; photo mug of Chao.
 &HT;    EDs: The surname of Australian scholar Geremie Barme, has an
accent over the ``e.''
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., May 7 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JULIE CHAO 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Returning to China five years after moving away, I was
stunned by the new sights in Beijing: fashionably-dressed young men
and women sipping mochas at Starbucks, and mulling over living room
furniture and bathroom fixtures at Ikea.
</P>
<P>
   New sidewalk billboards had sprung up everywhere, with just
about every one taken up by advertisements for Chinese dot-com
companies. Massive new office buildings, indoor malls and luxury
apartment buildings dominate much of the urban landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing had become a far more international and modern city in
just a few years. Whereas culinary variety used to mean choosing
from Cantonese, Sichuanese or Hunanese, now options for eating out
include Italian, Brazilian, Lebanese and more. When a friend
recently said, ``I don't want Chinese for dinner, I had it for
lunch,'' it didn't sound ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Even government agencies have entered the digital era. The
Public Security Bureau, which issues visas and keeps an eye on
foreign journalists, has fancy new computers, as does every clerk
at the post office. But when a postal worker reached for her abacus
to add up my postage, it hit me _ some very fundamental things
haven't changed at all.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a lot of things: it still takes one month to get a
phone line installed; the English-language China Daily is as boring
as ever; purchasing anything at a department store still involves a
convoluted routine with glue, red rubber stamps and several layers
of carbon paper; and connections are still the key to getting
things done. Just about every aspect of life here _ from getting
into a good school and finding a good job to getting bureaucratic
problems resolved _ will go smoother if you've got good guanxi, or
connections.
</P>
<P>
   I lived in Beijing for three and half years in the early 1990s
and had made only two brief visits back since 1995. After getting
over the shock of the new Beijing my first few days, the hassles of
the old Beijing quickly came to haunt me.
</P>
<P>
   While China may have invented gunpowder and noodles, bureaucracy
may be one of its lesser-appreciated contributions to the world. To
live and work in China and get my shipment through customs required
the following documents:
</P>
<P>
   1. Housing contract in a foreign journalist-approved housing
unit;
</P>
<P>
   2 . Certificate of health, including HIV and syphilis screening,
from a local hospital;
</P>
<P>
   3. Journalist's work card, from the Foreign Ministry;
</P>
<P>
   4. Journalist visa, from the Public Security Bureau;
</P>
<P>
   5. Residence permit, from the Public Security Bureau;
</P>
<P>
   6. News organization permit, from the Foreign Ministry;
</P>
<P>
   7. And customs certificate, from Customs;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these couldn't be obtained in just any order. No,
there was a strict sequence. To get my shipment, I needed numbers
4, 5 and 7. To get numbers 4 and 5, I needed numbers 1, 2 and 3 and
a one-week wait. To get number 7, I needed numbers 3, 5 and 6. To
get number 6, I had to pay more than $100 for a two-line notice in
the Beijing Daily announcing Cox Newspapers' presence. Many of
these documents required photos _ some had to be 1-inch, some
2-inch.
</P>
<P>
   And none of this could've been done without the Cox Newspapers
chop, which thankfully, my predecessors left for me. Like most
chops, ours is nothing more than a simple rubber stamp with our
name, but every organization in China _ governmental or private _
has one, and nothing is official without it.
</P>
<P>
   Worse than the bureaucracy, though, is the almost feudal mindset
of some officials. While the Foreign Ministry is making efforts to
be more accessible to foreign journalists, other government
agencies seem stuck in the Soviet era.
</P>
<P>
   A phone call to a Beijing municipal department with a simple
question is met with: ``It's not my duty to provide that
information.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the Internet is flooding the country with as much
information as its citizens care to access, Customs thinks it can
seal China's borders and keep out dangerous foreign influences.
</P>
<P>
   Because I am a journalist, it insisted on inspecting my shipment
of personal belongings. When I was notified of the upcoming
inspection, a Chinese friend assured me they were looking only for
drugs, pornography and the like, and they wouldn't be so backwards
as to confiscate books and video-tapes as they did in the old days.
</P>
<P>
   But indeed, the Customs official found seven books he decided
could not be allowed in the country. His book choice was _ I hate
to say it _ inscrutable.
</P>
<P>
   Books I would have thought objectionable _ such as those by
Harry Wu, a longtime China critic and former political prisoner,
and Falun Gong, the banned sect _ made it through. The official
also gave a pass to ``The Road to Democracy'' by Lee Teng-hui, the
outgoing president of Taiwan so reviled by China, while objecting
to two innocuous Taiwanese governmental publications about politics
and economy.
</P>
<P>
   Most unfathomable, though, was their choice of four titles that
can be ordered off Amazon.com and shipped to China attracting
little notice from authorities. In fact, ``In the Red: On
Contemporary Chinese Culture'' by Australian scholar Geremie Barme
tops Amazon.com's list of books that are unusually popular in
China. A second book, ``The Search for Modern China'' by Yale
University's Jonathan Spence, one of the most widely-read China
scholars in the world, is No. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Only one selection made sense in the Chinese Communist Party
context: an autographed anthology of essays by Wei Jingsheng,
China's most well-known dissident, forced into exile in 1997. Even
his book, though, is available on Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   No explanation was ever given for the confiscations. I was told
only that the books were not allowed under China's regulations. No
further elucidation was provided for that term, and intervention by
the Foreign Ministry was fruitless. I looked for a logic behind the
book choice, but the word ``logic'' doesn't even exist in the
Chinese language. Instead, a transliteration from the English,
``luo ji,'' is used.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the answer lays in Spence's book, but alas, I shall have
to wait for my Amazon delivery before I can find out.
</P>
<P>
   (Julie Chao's E-mail address is: juliec(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
