<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7036 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SPOT/FEATURE-BUDGET-B     05-05 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT/FEATURE-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 For Release SATURDAY AMs, May 6, 2000  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta
 &LR; at the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-RAIDS (Tel Aviv) _ Tentative calm returns as Israel's
cabinet decices not to launch a third round of air raids against
Lebanon. But two rounds of Katyusha rocket attacks on Northern
Israel and retaliatory air strikes against power plants, highways
and other facilities in Lebanon have raised tensions to the highest
point in years. By Aliza Marcus. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-FARMS (Johanessburg) _ Invasions of white-owned farms
hits a new peak and violence spirals across Zimbabwe. Thabo Mbkei
travels to Harare to talking things over with embattled President
Robert Mugabe. By Kurt Shillinger. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   ISLAMIC-REBELS (Undated) _ Islamic rebellions in southern
Philippines and nearby islands lead to a series of violent hostage
