<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-Q&AMP;A-ART-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH: JOHN MONTGOMERY OF BRIDGWAY ULTRA-SMALL COMPANY
PORTFOLIO 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 7) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CAROLE GOULD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Sunday mornings, John Montgomery plays the flute with a
folk-rock group at St. Andrew's Presbyterian Church in Houston. On
Tuesday evenings, he rehearses for three hours with the group's
vocalists and other musicians. ``We could really use a drummer,''
he complains.
</P>
<P>
   A former research engineer at MIT, Montgomery, who is 44, sees
his music as complementary to the computer-based calculations he
uses to pick stocks for the $42 million Bridgeway Ultra-Small
Company Portfolio. ``Math is the underlying language of music,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ultra-Small fund has turned in some sweet results, returning
23.3 percent a year, annualized, for the three years through April
30, versus 8.2 percent for its peers in the small value category,
according to Morningstar Inc., and 15.2 percent for the Russell
2000 index of small-capitalization stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery came to money management by an unlikely route. In
1985, he joined the Houston transit system as a senior budget
analyst and during his off-hours developed computer models to
manage his investments. He said that in 1990 and 1991, his last
years there, his investment earnings far exceeded his modest
salary. In 1993, he started Bridgeway Capital Management, which now
manages a total of $135 million in four actively managed funds, two
index funds and a dozen private accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery's background in budgeting leads him to run his firm
economically. The firm does not advertise, for example. And because
Montgomery does not allow personal trading by his firm's seven
employees, Bridgeway has no need for a compliance officer to
monitor their investments.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, by negotiating with brokerage firms, he has trimmed
the average commission the fund pays to just a penny a share. The
average such expense is 6 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Managers of successful small-cap stock funds generally face a
problem: their funds are flooded with cash, forcing them to buy
bigger stocks. In Montgomery's view, a small-cap fund is easily
managed as long as its total assets do not exceed the average
market capitalization of the stocks it owns. So he closed the fund
to new investors in June 1998, when assets reached $27.5 million;
he plans to shut it to all new investments, including those by
existing shareholders, when assets hit $55 million, the fund's
current average market capitalization.
</P>
<P>
   That market cap is still far smaller than that of the typical
small-cap fund. Montgomery focuses his search for stocks on the
smallest 10 percent of issues on the New York Stock Exchange, but
also picks from among 2,000 very small stocks in an index created
by the Center for Research in Securities Prices, which tracks the
smallest stocks traded on the Big Board, the American Stock
Exchange and the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing stocks, Montgomery never visits companies or meets
with their management. Instead, he uses five proprietary computer
models, the details of which he is loathe to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   He does say, however, that four of the models review fundamental
data like per-share earnings growth and cash flow; the fifth
analyzes technical factors like trading volume and relative price
appreciation. Each model is used to pick a list of 10 stocks; the
names sometimes overlap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a black box shop,'' he said in a slight Texas drawl.
``We put the data in and the computer cranks it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The portfolio is filled with cheap stocks: its typical
price-to-earnings ratio is in the low to mid-teens, though its
three-year earnings growth rate averages 36 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery runs the technical model monthly. Three of the
fundamental screens highlight value-oriented stocks and are run
weekly. The fourth, which looks for attractive growth stocks, is
run daily.
</P>
<P>
   The fund owns about 160 stocks, giving it a degree of
diversification that dampens the inherent risks of investing in the
smallest stocks, he said. Typically, he sells stocks when they no
longer meet his models' criteria, or when the models produce better
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Among the stocks he likes is Team America, a Worthington, Ohio,
company that provides payroll, retirement plan management and other
human resources services to business. Its per-share earnings, cash
flow and sales have been strong, he said, but the company's share
price is ``dirt cheap,'' in part because of an acquisition-related
charge taken last year.
</P>
<P>
   As the company moves forward, Montgomery said, the share price
could double in the next 12 months. He bought shares in May 1999 at
$4.78; they closed at $4.50 on Friday, 16 times his 2000 earnings
estimate of 28 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Another favorite is the Howell Corp., an integrated oil and gas
company in Houston. ``Oil prices are way up, and its stock price is
dead in the water,'' he said. But because its cash flow was $3 a
share last year, he said, ``you could earn your price back with
cash flow alone in less than three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery, who bought shares last July at $6.50, predicts
three-year earnings growth of 15 percent a year, on average. The
shares closed Friday at $7.1875, or 4.5 times his earnings estimate
of $1.60 a share this year.
</P>
<P>
   He also likes Lifemark, a health maintenance organization in
Phoenix. ``The industry as a whole is cheap,'' he said, ``but this
company is doing great.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the company has doubled its annual per-share
earnings for three consecutive years. Wall Street expects earnings
growth to average 30 percent a year for the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   He bought shares in October 1998 at $4.375; it closed Friday at
$4, or 6 times analysts' consensus earnings of 65 cents a share for
the fiscal year ending in May 2001.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
