<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7042 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-BALANCHINE-REVIEW-     05-05 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BALANCHINE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BALANCHINE LIVES!': LEGACY OF A GREAT CHOREOGRAPHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the thorniest problems facing dance is how to keep the
classics of the past alive yet authentic.
</P>
<P>
   Videotaping and dance notation now augment the age-old handing
down of dances from one performer to another. But what about
differences in individual interpretation or even a choreographer's
different versions? Which should be the interpretation of record?
Those questions are addressed in impressive depth in Michael
Blackwood's ``Balanchine Lives!'' on PBS on Sunday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Balanchine shrugged off the matter of his legacy. He redid
dances and allowed performers to shape them individually. But with
the creation of the George Balanchine Trust, whose work has become
a model for the licensing of dances, Balanchine's work had a head
start on life after his death.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with 14 former New York City Ballet and
Balanchine-trained dancers _ of whom some stage ballets for the
trust and others direct ballet companies throughout the United
States and in Europe _ suggest that the best method may still be
the transmission of choreography through the memories and examples
of those who worked directly with the creator.
</P>
<P>
   The blessedly straightforward ``Balanchine Lives!'' is crammed
with photographs of the choreographer at work, looking much more
poignantly human than the icon he is fast becoming. Balanchine's
biographer Bernard Taper provides historical and social context.
Another part of the rich mosaic are the personalities and
observations of the restagers _ all women, curiously _ who
painstakingly teach Balanchine to the dancers of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Karin von Aroldingen, one of the City Ballet performers to whom
Balanchine left his ballets, is the eloquently poetic dreamer of
the group. Patricia Neary jumps into the fray, a whirlwind on point
in her late 50s. Francia Russell, co-director with Kent Stowell of
Pacific Northwest Ballet, is tellingly pragmatic.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Villella, director of Miami City Ballet, mixes pragmatism
with vivid recall of how it feels to dance Balanchine, and Patricia
Wilde, then director of the Pittsburgh Ballet Theater, speaks
movingly about a personal sense of legacy. Suzanne Farrell offers a
remarkable insight into Balanchine's musicality.
</P>
<P>
   A surprising amount of information is woven into this
thought-provoking and beautifully photographed hourlong
documentary, edited by Julie Sloane and shot by Mark Trottenberg,
Mead Hung and Reinhard Schatzman. Words and images convey not just
the passing down of dance but also subjects ranging from
Balanchine's respect for child performers to the ways that his
ballets help develop dancers and companies.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Christophe Maillot, director of Les Ballets de Monte Carlo,
sums it up. ``For every single choreographer, the day you give your
step to another dancer you accept you're going to be betrayed by
them,'' Maillot says, adding that what is important is what the
dancer can do with that ``betrayal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the choreographer is alive, good, he will give his own
opinion,'' he said. ``If he's not alive, who knows really how `Swan
Lake' should have been danced?''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BALANCHINE LIVES!'
</P>
<P>
   7 p.m. ET Sunday and 1 a.m. ET Tuesday on PBS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 1837EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
