<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAN-ROUTE0506-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AirTran wants clearance to fly to D.C.-National
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ AirTran Airways is seeking special government approval
to fly between Atlanta and Washington's Reagan National Airport,
arguing its presence on the heavily traveled route would bring down
fares.
</P>
<P>
   The discount carrier applied Friday for ``slot exemptions'' to
serve Reagan National that were created in a federal aviation
funding bill passed by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Slots are airline-owned landing and takeoff rights used at
Reagan National and a handful of other congested major airports.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran now flies between Atlanta and Washington's Dulles
International Airport but does not have slots to serve closer-in
Reagan National. Fares to Dulles are often cheaper than to
Reagan-National, which is served nonstop from Atlanta by Delta Air
Lines and US Airways.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most notable airport city-pair that has not benefitted
from the affordable fare competition provided by AirTran's service
in Atlanta is Reagan National Airport,'' AirTran said.
</P>
<P>
   The aviation bill, signed by President Clinton last month,
created 12 slot exemptions for flights within 1,250 miles of Reagan
National. AirTran wants to fly five daily round-trips to Hartsfield
International, which isn't slot controlled.
</P>
<P>
   The slot exemptions are intended in part to foster more service
to small and medium sized airports. While Hartsfield doesn't fit
that description, AirTran argues it could provide one-stop service
via Atlanta to Savannah, Gulfport, Miss., and Fort Walton Beach,
Fla., and connections to a dozen more cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will come down to how the (U.S. Department of
Transportation) secretary interprets the act,'' said Kevin Healy,
vice president of planning at AirTran.
</P>
<P>
   Other carriers also are applying for slots, although no other
applications involve new Atlanta service. Atlantic Southeast
Airlines, a Delta subsidiary, wants to fly nonstop between Reagan
National and Jacksonville, Fla., with regional jets.
</P>
<P>
   The DOT is expected to award the slot exemptions this summer.
</P>
<P>
   A Delta spokeswoman said the airline has no immediate comment on
AirTran's application but added the carrier will file arguments
with the DOT.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 1849EDT &QL; 
