<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Saturday, May 6 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   DEUTCH-CIA (Washington) _ Developments in the case of John
Deutch, the former director of central intelligence accused of
mishandling classified information. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   AUTISM-SCHOOLS (West Windsor, N.J.) _ One family came from
India, others from Greece and Italy and Israel. Compared to those
migrations, Rob and Anne Mandel had it pretty easy, giving up his
medical practice and a life they loved in Indiana to get their son,
Sam, the help he needed in New Jersey. Sam is autistic, and his
parents' move here made the Mandels part of the phenomenon of
families that, desperate for the most sophisticated special
education services for their disabled children, move from other
states and even other nations in search of care. But, increasingly,
the needs of parents with autistic children are clashing with the
bottom lines of school districts that have to pay for enormously
expensive services. Iver Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, nyt25, sent on 4-27.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The nation's unemployment rate fell
below 4 percent in April for the first time in 30 years, the Labor
Department reported Friday, as employers hired tens of thousands of
census takers, restaurant employees and temporary workers in a
booming economy. The new employment numbers _ 341,000 new jobs and
a 3.9 percent unemployment rate _ offered no evidence that the
nine-year-old expansion _ the longest in America's history _ might
be coming to an end or even weakening in response to the Federal
Reserve's attempt to slow the economy by raising interest rates.
The Fed's great fear is that labor shortages will give workers
enough bargaining power to push up labor costs and employers, in
response, will raise prices to cover the higher costs. But wages,
while rising, are still not going up fast enough to set off an
inflationary spiral, the Labor Department's latest numbers show. By
Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-EDUC (Lansing, Mich.) _ Vice President Al Gore today
promised to spend $8 billion over 10 years to recruit one million
new teachers and another $8 billion over 10 years to increase
teacher salaries, but only if the states and teacher unions agreed
that all new teachers submit to testing and meet rigorous national
standards and if teachers are hired on the basis of expertise and
not seniority alone. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE-U.N. (United Nations) _ In their boldest move yet
against the U.N. peacekeeping mission in Sierra Leone, rebel
fighters have disarmed a convoy of Zambian peacekeepers, taken the
208 soldiers hostage and now appear to be driving 13 hijacked
armored personnel carriers toward the capital, U.N. officials said
Friday. The convoy, which was sent from Lungi, a port town, to
reinforce other beleaguered peacekeeping troops at Makeni, lost
radio contact on Thursday with the U.N. mission in Freetown, the
capital of the battered West African country, prompting concern
about their fate. By Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   OCONNOR (New York) _ The scene from St. Patrick's Cathedral, as
the body of Cardinal John O'connor is moved to the church. By Diana
Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT9.
</P>
<P>
   SALMON-DAMS (Lower Granite Dam, Wash.) _ The fate of the huge
hydroelectric dams on the Snake River, and of the endangered salmon
there, may hinge on the effectiveness of a program to bring
millions of the fish on barges around dams. Its success or failure
is the likely key to a momentous decision that will ultimately come
before the U.S. Congress: whether to take down the Snake River dams
altogether. That once-unthinkable idea has emerged in several
federal studies as the single action with the best chance of
restoring healthy salmon runs. But many people in the area bitterly
oppose that plan as an assault on the area's agricultural economy,
and the proposal has already emerged as a hot-button issue in the
state in this year's presidential race. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, nyt14,15,16,17, sent 5-4; and map.
</P>
<P>
   LOVE-VIRUS (Undated) _ Developments on the ``I love you'' virus.
By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   NY-NEEDLES (Albany, N.Y) _ The New York state legislature has
passed a measure that permits the sale and possession of hypodermic
needles without a prescription, a move intended to slow the spread
of the AIDS virus among addicts who inject drugs. The legislation
would overturn the state's longstanding prohibitions against needle
sales, making New York the 43rd state in the nation to allow
individuals to make such purchases from pharmacists without a
prescription. By Raymond Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   TRIPP-TRIAL (Washington) _ A Maryland judge rules that the state
can go ahead with its prosecution of Linda Tripp on charges that
she broke the law when she secretly tape-recorded conversations
with Monica Lewinsky about Lewinsky's relationship with President
Clinton. But the judge, Diane Leasure of Howard County Circuit
Court, also dealt a severe blow to the case by suppressing the
testimony of Lewinsky and another witness that may be crucial in
obtaining a conviction. By Neil A. Lewis. (800 words)
</P>
