</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADIDAS-BREVARD-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 ADIDAS NAMES NEW RUNNING SHOES AFTER A TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARRISON METZGER   
 Times-News, Hendersonville, N.C.  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BREVARD, N.C. _ This western North Carolina town now has a
running shoe named after it in honor of Brevard College's history
of national champion running teams and its acclaimed summer camp
for runners.
</P>
<P>
   Adidas is marketing the Brevard running shoe for women, said
Norm Witek, professor of exercise science and director and
co-founder of the Brevard College Distance Running Camp.
</P>
<P>
   The German-based shoe company named the lightweight running shoe
for the college and town after top Adidas executives visited
Brevard College two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``About a year ago there were rumors they were going to pull
this off _ I just never thought it would be reality,'' Witek said.
``It's just such a neat idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Witek describes the Brevard shoe as a ``high-end support shoe''
designed to help runners with unstable foot plants. The shoe
retails for $89, weighs 10.4 ounces and comes in an ``aluminum
blue-white'' color.
</P>
<P>
   Witek, 55, coached four national junior college champion
cross-country teams at the college in the early 1980s, along with a
champion marathon team. Dave Rinker, who followed him as coach in
1985, coached two national champion teams.
</P>
<P>
   Witek and Rinker founded the Distance Running Camp in 1990 to
train young runners. The camp now attracts about 1,000 runners from
eighth grade through high school each summer to Brevard, which is
about 40 miles south of Asheville.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, under Witek's coaching, Mike Peveto of Lake Charles,
La., won the national junior college marathon, Brevard College's
first national title. Peveto went on to become a top running-shoe
executive at Nike and later Adidas, where he worked until recently
as senior product manager for running shoes.
</P>
<P>
   About five years ago, Witek accepted an invitation by Peveto to
have Adidas sponsor the camp. In 1998, Peveto and his senior staff
from Germany came to the college for a corporate retreat.
</P>
<P>
   The executives brought more than 100 pairs of shoes with them
and asked camp participants for critiques. They offered advice that
the company used in improving its shoes, Witek said.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Kimzey, director of Brevard College's news bureau, said the
college was proud of the honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our distance running programs have always been the highest
caliber, and we have always competed against the best of the best
in running programs across the country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Harrison Metzger writes for the Times-News in Hendersonville,
N.C., which is part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
