<HEADER>
A7065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v BC-NYT-WORLD-WKND-BUDGET     05-05 1626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYT-WORLD-WKND-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors at publications outside the United States may find the
following stories from the New York Times News Service that are
scheduled for release on  &UR; SUNDAY, MAY 7, &LR;  of particular interest.
We plan to move these stories by 2 p.m. EST on Saturday, May 6.
</P>
<P>
   Please note that some of these stories are tentative and may be
held for space or other reasons. For updates please consult these
weekend budgets: SUNDAY-UPDATE-BUDGET, STYLE-BUDGET, SUNBIZ-BUDGET
and REVIEW-BUDGET.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONEY AND BUSINESS &LR;  (Will move in `f' category)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PRIVACY (Undated) _ There has been no shortage of
discussion about how the Internet is stripping consumers of what
thin veil of privacy they have left in this world of credit bureaus
and supermarket scanners. But lost in this debate is just how
ineffective most of these data-gathering systems have been. So far,
no one has been able to make a big business out of being Big
Brother. By Saul Hansell. (With graphic)
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-GOLD (Undated) _ A leading historian of the American West
finds the roots of the dot.com investing boom, and bust, in other
get-rich-quick rushes to find gold and oil. By Patricia Nelson
Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   CONTRARY-VIEW-GLOBAL (Undated) _ On the Contrary Column:
Protesters decry globalization, the process whereby dastardly
capitalists provide paying jobs to starving Third Worlders who were
previously without hope. But their choice of targets is puzzling:
they vent spleen at the World Bank and the IMF while letting
another crucial agency of globalization _ the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service _ off scot-free. By Daniel Akst.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEK IN REVIEW &LR;  (Will move in `a' or `i' categories, as noted)
</P>
<P>
   MOTHERHOOD-POLITICS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Never underestimate the
political potency of motherhood. The leaders of the Million Mom
March for ``sensible gun control'' next Sunday, Mother's Day in the
United States, have an appealing web site, a shrewd media effort
and an aggressive grass-roots organizing campaign. But above all,
they are invoking a very old tradition in politics: Trying to break
through ideology and partisanship and make an appeal based on the
moral authority of women as mothers. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-SECURITY-REVIEW (Undated) _ If Eisenhower were alive
today, he might be amused or puzzled by the Clinton
administration's linkage of national security to issues like trade
privileges for China, AIDS in Africa and global warming. But it is
possible that after a decade of unchallenged power and prosperity,
Americans are ready to think about their national security in
broader terms. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   CELLPHONES-CRIME-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at the use of
cellular phones as crime-fighting devices. Since the early 1990s,
cell phones have increasingly become the all-purpose, cure-all
solution for individual safety. The issue, however, is whether
people are really safe, or merely think they are. By Jason Blair.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   E-BOOKS-REVIEW (Undated) _ For more than a year, I've been
experimenting with electronic books. The various e-book devices
felt like solid hardcovers in hand, but the first generation seemed
stiff to me, somehow nerdy and bulky. Reading books on a PC felt
too much as if I was working, chained upright to a desk. I was
drawn to the devices that offered one of the basic elements of
pocketbook design: portability. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-OBSTACLES-REVIEW (Washington) _ The debacle of the Sierra
Leone peacekeeping mission and the awkward U.S. response
demonstrate again that Africa takes more than good intentions. Even
as the U.S. House of Representatives approved a trade bill granting
new trading privileges to Africa, there are some doubts whether
many African countries have the economic capacity to take advantage
of it. The fact remains that sub-Saharan Africa is so poor that
McDonald's cannot find enough of a customer base to open one outlet
in even one nation. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
