<P>
   HAMLET-FILM (Undated) _ Given the story's familiarity, it seemed
altogether natural to locate a new ``Hamlet'' in the immediate
present, to translate the Danish kingdom into a multimedia
corporation, and to watch the story unfold in penthouse hotel
rooms, sky-level office corridors, a coffee shop, an airplane, the
Guggenheim Museum. Director Michael Almereyda discusses his
decision to bring Hamlet into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   (This story has moved)
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY-REUNION-THEATER (London) _ T.S. Eliot's ``Family
Reunion'' has risen greatly in critical esteem since it flopped in
the West End 60-odd years ago. Many now regard the poet's story of
the English lord impelled by updated Furies to atone for his wife's
dark death as the nearest to a theatrical masterpiece Eliot ever
wrote. New Yorkers will make up their own minds when the Royal
Shakespeare Company's revival opens on Wednesday. By Benedict
Nightingale.
</P>
<P>
   (This story has moved)
</P>
<P>
   ORESTEIA-THEATER (Undated) _ Murder. Adultery. Courtroom drama.
A fugitive's hair-raising flight from implacable justice. With
super-heated elements like these to work with, it's no wonder
modern playwrights keep rewriting Aeschylus' ``Oresteia,'' the
fifth-century B.C. dramatic trilogy about a family ensnared in
guilt and violence. By Celia Wren.
</P>
<P>
   (This story has moved)
</P>
<P>
   BEETHOVEN-MUSIC (Undated) _ When in the course of human events,
musicians feel impelled to declare to the world and to themselves
the highest ideals of which the individual and humanity are
capable, the composer to whom they are most apt to turn is
Beethoven. By Matthew Gurewitsch.
</P>
<P>
   (This story has moved)
</P>
<P>
   ABT-DANCE (New York) _ With the turn of the millennium, American
Ballet Theater moved into overdrive on its new production of ``Swan
Lake.'' The production will have its New York premiere at the
Metropolitan Opera House on May 19 and is expected to be the
blockbuster of the company's 60th-anniversary season, which opens
with a gala performance May 8 and runs through July 1. By Iris
Fanger.
</P>
<P>
   (This story has moved)
</P>
<P>
   SCHWARTZ-PHOTOGRAPHY (New York) _ When he saw a camera obscura
on the roof of a private museum in Kyoto in 1991, Charles Schwartz
knew he had to have one. So now, poking through the roof of his
staid apartment building on the Upper East Side, is a jaunty,
medieval-looking turret that holds the telescopic lens and mirror
of what surely is the only camera obscura of its size in Manhattan,
and one of the very few private devices of its kind in the world.
By Grace Glueck.
</P>
<P>
   (This story has moved)
</P>
<P>
   PARIS-COMMUNE-ART (Paris) _ The Paris Commune of 1871 is one of
those smoldering ruins in French history. As the first news event
in French history covered by photographers, the Commune and its
aftermath also left a unique visual record, as a compelling new
exhibition at the Musee d'Orsay, on view until June 11, makes
clear. By Richard C. Woodward.
</P>
