<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-FARMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARM SEIZURES, VIOLENCE CONTINUE TO ESCALATE IN ZIMBABWE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ Monday: 18 farms seized. Tuesday: 18 farms.
Wednesday: 32 farms. Thursday: 15 farms, maybe more. Friday, Farm
representatives were still reckoning the latest seizures at day's
end.
</P>
<P>
   As Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe this week brushed off the
growing international pressure to halt a 10-week campaign against
white-owned commercial farms, his supporters picked up the pace of
their murderous land grab, seizing new tracts at an increasing
rate.
</P>
<P>
   At least 18 people have been killed and thousands of farm
workers have been badly beaten, often repeatedly, since veterans of
Zimbabwe's war of liberation and other Mugabe supporters began
raiding white farms 10 weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned by the rising violence, white farm representatives
petitioned the High Court Friday to postpone sentencing the leader
of the liberation war veterans, the group behind the farm
invasions, on contempt charges. Blocked by the violence from
working their fields, farmers are losing the window to plant winter
wheat, and they feared the sentencing would only stoke the crisis
at a critical moment in the crop cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking the conciliatory tone farmers have tried to maintain
since the attacks began two months ago, the deputy director of the
Commercial Farmers' Union publicly accused Chenjerai Hunzi, the
veterans leader charged two weeks ago with failing to comply with
court orders to end the land grab, of breaking promises to contain
his followers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any agreements that we strike with Mr. Hunzvi . . . are
absolutely meaningless,'' Jerry Grant told a group of businessmen
in Harare Friday, describing the situation on the farms as ``total
anarchy.''
</P>
<P>
   Though nominally about land, the attacks have become
increasingly political. The self-styled veterans have accused
Mugabe's political opponents, including white farmers and the
fledgling Movement for Democratic Change, of obstructing land
reform by defeating a draft constitution that would have allowed
the government to seize land without compensating owners. Voters
rejected the document in a nationwide referendum in February.
</P>
<P>
   Land remains the most volatile issue in Zimbabwe. In the 1970s,
blacks fought a bush war against white-ruled Rhodesia, as the
country was called then, to recover land stolen from their
ancestors by British colonialists a century ago. Two decades after
independence, most of the prime agricultural land remains in the
hands of a small community of white farmers, while most rural
blacks subsist on marginal plots owned by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe, facing the first serious challenge to his 20-year rule
as the new opposition taps frustration over economic decline and
high joblessness, has encouraged the war veterans to seize land
from whites. He has vowed to take half of the 31 million acres of
white commercial farmland and has given financial backing to the
war veterans' attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Farm representatives say pro-government mobs have invaded nearly
1,200 farms in two months and have occupied 760. Despite earlier
assurances to the contrary, Hunzvi emerged from the courthouse
Friday vowing to continue the invasions. The court now plans to
sentence him on May 19.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis poses a serious dilemma for regional leaders, some of
whom face similar land imbalances in their own countries and whose
economies have been shaken by the unrest in Zimbabwe. Appearing
with Mugabe in the southern Zimbabwean town of Bulawayo Friday,
South African President Thabo Mbeki publicly urged his counterpart
to seek a ``cooperative and non-confrontational'' solution on the
land issue.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki, who two weeks ago offered Mugabe a Western-backed
economic bailout if he ended the farm attacks and organized the
upcoming elections, broke weeks of public silence on Zimbabwe after
drawing indirect public criticism from his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   After an hour-long meeting in London on Wednesday with Nelson
Mandela of South Africa, British Prime Minister Tony Blair said the
former South African president backed Britain's strong condemnation
of the violence and that ``Mbeki had a key role to play in contact
with Harare.''
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's economy has felt sharp economic tremors in recent
weeks, with its banking sector warning of ``Zimbabwean contagion''
as the crisis undermined investor confidence and helped sink the
rand to record lows against the US dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Making his first nationwide address since taking office last
June, Mbeki blamed the media for failing to report accurately the
diplomatic efforts he has made to help stabilize Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our government,'' he said, ``will work persistently and
without making the noise of empty drums to help the sister people
of Zimbabwe to find a just and lasting solution to the real and
pressing land question in their country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
