<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7067 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-DERBY-ADVANCE-COX     05-05 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DERBY-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fusaichi Pegasus odds on favorite
 &HT;    By John Crittenden
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Early odds of 9-5 say Fusaichi Pegasus will
prove that you get what you pay for at the horse sales. Undefeated
this year in four races, the colt that brought $4 million at
auction is favored to win the 126th Kentucky Derby today against 18
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Pegram is not convinced you can buy a Derby winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't a science,'' said Pegram. ``A plus B does not always
equal C.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years before he won the 1998 Derby for Pegram, Real Quiet
was sold for $17,000. At the same stage in his career, 1997 winner
Silver Charm went for $16,500. Less than four months before he won
the 1999 Derby, Charismatic could have been taken with a claiming
slip for $62,500.
</P>
<P>
   At the race track, this is called The Cinderella Factor. For
three straight years, bargain horses have been the stars of The
Kentucky Derby Ball, an embarassment to their peers with far more
expensive price tags.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is this conduct considered more unorthodox than in
Kentucky, where thoroughbred auction sales are based on the idea
that breeding is everything. Good papas and good mamas and good
looks keep the market price rising. When a faster horse from the
wrong side of the track comes along, that is an argument against
bids that go over $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   If Fusaichi Pegasus fails today to uphold the theory that top
auction prices produce top records, perhaps High Yield will
represent the blockbluster price tags in the winner's circle. He
cost $1,050,000 before he was turned over to Wayne Lukas for
training. In his last two races, High Yield has been a strong
finisher, second in the Florida Derby and first in the Blue Grass
Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you pay high prices for a horse, you get a lot of pedigree,
and I think pedigree is important,'' said Lukas. ``But even if you
pay more than $1 million for a horse, like we did for High Yield,
once you get to running and being tested, you have to go on what
you see in front of you.
</P>
<P>
   ``That price tag is not going to help you a bit when you are a
quarter-mile from the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of Derby entries with a bargain sales history
ready to extend The Cinderella Streak.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost among these is The Deputy, purchased in Ireland by
Barry Irwin, president of Team Valor. Irwin won't say how much the
Santa Anita Derby winner cost, but surely it was far less than
$100,000. The colt is likely to be the second betting choice today,
with High Yield third.
</P>
<P>
   The Deputy's family tree is without promise. His father needed
five races to win for the first time and finished first just twice,
both in short races. His mother did not win in seven races. But in
four races in the United States, Irwin's horse lost just once, by
less than a length to Fusaich Pegasus.
</P>
<P>
   The Deputy has earned new support because of his Churchill Downs
practices and so has Captain Steve, the prospect purchased by
Pegram two years ago to be sent to Bob Baffert, who trained Real
Quiet. The cost was $70,000.
</P>
<P>
   While Baffert has plenty of high-priced stock, he claims to feel
more comfortable among the inexpensive Derby challengers. Baffrt
saw Fusaichi Pegasus at the auction sales. ``I said that he looked
great. I said he would go for a lot of money. Then I said for them
to take me to look at the $70,000 horses.''
</P>
<P>
   History will be made at the first Derby of the new century and
more history can be made.
</P>
<P>
   On Curule, at 50-1 odds, Marlon St. Julien, who rides in
Louisiana, Texas and the Midwest, will become the first black
jockey to ride in the Derby since 1921.
</P>
<P>
   With The Deputy, Jenine Sahadi can become the first woman
trainer ever to win the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   And if Fusaichi Pegasus ends The Cinderalla Streak, he will be
the first favorite to win the race since 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
