<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7068 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-BONDS-ART-$ADV     05-05 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-BONDS-ART-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW SHEEN OF MUNICIPAL BONDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 7) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every so often, most strikingly when Congress gets agitated
about the nation's tax structure, the market for municipal bonds
sags, driving yields to lip-smacking levels. Challenges to the
bonds' tax-exempt status typically loom much larger in investors'
eyes than a possible benefit from the scarcity that would be
created by action in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, returns on municipals have been elevated by
economic fundamentals _ mainly the necessity of competing with the
stock market and the near certainty that interest rates _ already
raised five times by the Federal Reserve since mid-1999 _ will
climb even further.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government's budget surplus, meanwhile, is shrinking
the supply of Treasury bonds even as growing numbers of refugees
from stock-market gyrations are seeking a haven; both forces are
driving down returns on Treasury debt.
</P>
<P>
   A result is the unusual situation of long-term municipal bonds
that pay tax-free interest yielding just as much, or even a bit
more, than taxable Treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long-term munis and long Treasuries are basically yielding the
same thing,'' said William Hornbarger, fixed-income strategist at
A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis. For many investors, he added,
``that's a no-brainer'' situation.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, no municipality or other tax-exempt issuer matches
the United States Treasury for credit quality, but the difference
is less than many investors imagine. In fact, roughly half of
municipals carry insurance, making credit comparisons of little
practical consequence.
</P>
<P>
   Until about a year ago, according to Alexandra Lebenthal,
president of a family-owned New York firm that specializes in
municipal bonds, municipals were considered attractive when
long-term yields as measured by the Bond Buyer's Index reached 85
percent of those on Treasury bonds. Now, with the ratio above 90
percent for the highest-quality debt and approaching 100 percent
for lesser but still investment-quality bonds, ``it's a fantastic
time for the individual'' buyer to scoop up tax-exempts, she said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a recently marketed New York State Dormitory
Authority issue rated Baa-1 and BBB+ yields about 6 percent in a
maturity as short as 10 years. That return is equivalent to a
taxable investment generating 9.34 percent for a New York resident
earning $150,000 and filing a joint return. Ten-year triple-A bonds
yield 5.25 percent, equal to a taxable 8.17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Most people, though, don't bother with fancy calculations even
when sophisticated, state-specific translation tables are
available, like the one at the Bond Market Association's Web site,
investinginbonds.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``The individual investor looks at absolute yield,'' said Dan
Keating, a senior managing director at Bear, Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   A 6 percent coupon is ``magic,'' Lebenthal added.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, quality ``has probably never been better,'' according
to a study by Merrill Lynch, whose analysts found that upgrades by
rating agencies have far exceeded downgrades for the last four
years as city, state and authority budgets improved, with the best
performance in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Although mutual funds that invest in municipal bonds had
substantial outflows in the second half of last year _ aggravated
by redemptions to establish losses for tax savings, of all things _
specialists say the appeal of municipal bonds is broadening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just 70-year-old people'' any longer, said Jane
Trust, who runs four tax-exempt funds for Legg Mason Trust in
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Hornbarger concurred, pointing to stock-market and
entrepreneurial profits being redirected to the tax-free market.
``We're seeing more and more younger people in their 30s and 40s,''
he said. ``It's part of their asset allocation strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   And municipals have become easier to buy, with many state and
local issuers insisting on a special retail order period to give
individuals first crack at bonds. Moreover, increasing competition
has sharply cut insurance premiums, reducing the cost to 10 or 15
basis points (or $1 to $1.50 per $1,000), from 40 or 50 a decade
ago. The savings have mostly been passed on to investors in the
form of higher yields.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another attraction of munis is their ability to provide
portfolio ballast when stocks are in turmoil. ``Their volatility is
significantly lower _ that is the real edge to municipals,'' said
Michael Shamosh, chief fixed-income strategist for Tucker Anthony
Inc. Throughout financial history, he said, munis swing only
one-fourth as widely as stocks and half as widely as Treasury
bonds, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But what is' the smart strategy, given that most analysts expect
the Federal Reserve to keep tightening the monetary screws at least
through midyear, a trend that overwhelms the downward pressure on
rates from a shrinking supply of new bonds?
</P>
<P>
   Most experts suggest deferring purchases of longer-term bonds
and buying only those that come due fairly soon, say within a year
or two but perhaps in as little as a few weeks or months. The idea
is to preserve the chance to reinvest at progressively higher rates
rather than being locked into current levels.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take much to persuade most investors of the wisdom of
that approach, since the municipal yield curve _ the progression of
rates through the maturity spectrum _ provides relatively little
extra payment for lengthening one's commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the short term if you have to put money to work,''
Keating said. ``I'd stay within one to five years' maturity.''
</P>
<P>
   But Shamosh takes a different view. ``You want to get out of the
Fed's reach,'' he said. This suggests buying maturities that are
affected relatively little by the Fed's rate increases, those due,
say, between 6 and 20 years, in the conviction that the central
bank will eventually succeed in slowing down the economy. This, in
turn, would reassure the market that inflation _ the worry of
long-term investors _ will be kept in check.
</P>
<P>
   Investors should always have some short-term investments for
liquidity, Shamosh said, but longer-term munis are what should be
added to a sensible person's portfolio. ``The Fed,'' he said,
``doesn't have any control over the long rates, which could come
down,'' enhancing the value of such bonds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 1903EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
