u s BC-RAC-DERBY-ADVANCE-BOS     05-05 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-ADVANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL EYES ON PEGASUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Neil Drysdale, who was born in Great Britain,
schooled at the University of Barcelona, and once taught English,
is unfailingly polite. Unfortunately, the Kentucky Derby favorite
he trains is not.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus is 9-5 in the morning line for the 126th Run
for the Roses at Churchill Downs. Many are impressed with the
handsome son of Mr. Prospector. However, he is temperamental, given
to refusing to move or bucking like a bronco during workouts and
gallops. How he'll do in the paddock, or on the way to the gate
before the Derby throng, which numbered 151,051 last year, remains
to be seen. If he runs his race before the starting gate opens, the
chalk players are in serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fusaichi Pegasus has been very, very good on race day,'' said
Drysdale, 52, who was named to the Hall of Fame Tuesday. ``I expect
him to be good, even with 150,000 people there.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 26, Fusaichi Pegasus caused a stir at Churchill by
tossing his exercise rider, then falling over on his hip. As it
turned out, there were no injuries but it was a heart-stopping
moment. ``The exercise riders know not to interfere with him,''
said Drysdale. ``If he wants to play, we let him. We'll live with
that. I've warned them that he might flare up. Because a lot of
focus is on him, I think there might be hyperbole. I realize the
press has to focus on something. But he's never done anything
unprofessional in a race.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a mean horse. I've had mean horses, like Labeeb (a
former star on turf). One time, I told the jockey for a race in
California not to hit him. The rider hit him in the stretch, and
Labeeb threw him to New York. Fusaichi Pegasus is not going to be a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   A trainer who uses the word ``hyperbole'' is unusual enough, but
the fact that Drysdale has remained so calm while training a heavy
Derby favorite is even more remarkable. It also appears Drysdale is
unconcerned that, at $4 million, Fusaichi Pegasus was the sale
topper at the 1998 Keeneland July yearling sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which horse is the favorite is not important to me,'' said
Drysdale. ``It is relative to people who gamble, and I don't bet. I
was at the sale when Fusaichi Pegasus was sold and, as with
everybody else, I was very impressed with him. But the sales price
doesn't enter into the equation at the level that I work. I do the
best I can. I don't wake up in the morning and say: `Oh, no! I
train a $4 million horse.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus has the speed and the looks. He lost his only
race at age 2, by a neck at Hollywood Park. This year, he is 4 for
4 _ a maiden win, an allowance win, a win in the San Felipe Stakes,
all at Santa Anita, then the big score in the Wood Memorial at
Aqueduct April 15, the race that brought him to prominence.
</P>
<P>
   But before Fusaichi Pegasus caught the eye of the racing world,
he first caught the eye of Fusao Sekiguchi, his owner. Sekiguchi, a
venture capitalist, has owned horses for 20 years in Japan. When he
saw Fusaichi Pegasus, Sekiguchi refused to be outbid. ``I would
have gone to $5 million,'' he said. ``This was the only horse we
were interested in. My first impression when I saw him was an
inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   Sekiguchi often gives his horses the first name of ``Fusaichi,''
which combines part of his first name with ``ichi,'' which means
``the best'' in Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale has trained five champions (Princess Rooney, Tasso,
A.P. Indy, Hollywood Wildcat, and Fiji), but he has never saddled a
Derby starter. In 1992, A.P. Indy, who had won the Santa Anita
Derby, suffered a quartercrack (a tear in the wall of the hoof)
that was discovered the day before the Derby. He was scratched the
day of the Derby, went on to win the Belmont Stakes and Breeders'
Cup Classic, and became Horse of the Year. The last trainer to win
a Derby without having saddled a previous starter was Carl Nafzger,
who conditioned Unbridled in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a black and white decision to scratch A.P. Indy,'' said
Drysdale. ``He had a blind (hidden) quartercrack and we couldn't
locate it. It took three or four days to find it. He went off on
Friday afternoon. When he came out for his afternoon walk, he was
not happy, and the foot was carrying heat. There was just no other
decision to make. My thoughts were on how to get to the Belmont. We
want to look forward. When he won the Belmont, I was glad that his
form had been confirmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale has two chances to win Derby 2000. Although he is
deeply hidden in the shadow of Fusaichi Pegasus, War Chant, owned
by Irving and Marjorie Cowan of Florida, is a very nice colt. The
son of Danzig has won three of four starts, losing only when he
finished second to The Deputy in the Santa Anita Derby April 8. War
Chant is 6-1 in the morning line, will race for the first time with
blinders, and is a serious contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is not to fantasize about winning,'' said Drysdale.
``My job is to get the bloody horse over to the gate. Fusaichi
Pegasus could get in a trap, or he could be bumped around. Lord
knows that things can happen. But Fusaichi Pegasus can turn it on
and off in a race, he did so in the Wood. He's tractable.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Fusaichi Pegasus and War Chant must answer the distance
question _ but so must the other 17 entrants. And the fact that
both are so lightly raced could pose a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come here with two talented horses,'' said Drysdale. ``I
feel that if I have a choice between experience and talent, I
prefer to have talent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
