<SLUG> BC-CAR-SHORTAGES-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A SEARCH FOR HOT WHEELS, BUYERS HIT A DEAD END 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 7) 
 By MICHELINE MAYNARD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Robert Forester watched his dealer pull up in a black
Chrysler PT Cruiser to take him for a test drive, he decided on the
spot that the retro-looking small van would join his family's
fleet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got in that PT Cruiser and fell in love,'' said Forester,
who works for a printing and stationery business in Henderson,
Texas, 150 miles east of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   But two months after he ordered a red one with automatic
transmission and tinted moonroof for his mother, Jean, it still has
not arrived. In fact, it has not even been built, and Chrysler
representatives could not tell him when it would be.
</P>
<P>
   With auto sales booming along with the economy, consumers who
want the hottest vehicles are struggling to find the unfindable,
which this spring includes eye-catchers like the PT Cruiser and the
Toyota MR2 Spyder sports car, the highly rated Honda Odyssey
minivan, and luxury vehicles like the BMW X5 sport utility and
Mercedes S-Class sedans. Orders like Forester's go on waiting lists
and languish for months.
</P>
<P>
   In some areas, it can be impossible even to find a vehicle to
inspect in the showroom, because dealers are selling every one that
comes in. Honda dealers on Long Island are telling customers who
want to test-drive an Odyssey that they must first order one, put
down a deposit, and then wait for it to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   In response, many consumers find that they must alter their
tactics, searching by phone over wide areas for dealerships that
have a car on the lot. A growing number of people are turning to
the Internet, combing dealer sites, omnibus shopping sites like
Autobytel and Microsoft's Carpoint, and even auction sites like
eBay for leads.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking down a hot car is one thing; taking title is another.
Joel Manby, a former executive with Saab and Saturn who is now
president of Greenlight.com, a car-buying site, estimated that half
of all buyers use the Internet to research or find vehicles, but
that only one in 20 concludes a deal online.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet also tends to lengthen the lines at the dealers who
have hot cars on hand. Corky Jones, Internet sales manager for
Covington Pike Chrysler in Memphis, said his dealership had 103
orders for PT Cruisers from people as far away as Ohio, Illinois
and Texas. In one hour on Wednesday, six people came into the
showroom to see the vehicle, with its vaguely 1930s front end; they
were told that new orders would be filled in December.
</P>
<P>
   Jones likened the demand to the frenzy last year over
Volkswagen's New Beetle, which remains in short supply in some
parts of the country. But he is enjoying the clamor. ``Just once in
your life, you want to sell something that is so popular you have
people lining up for it,'' he said. ``It's fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   On the wall in Covington Pike's showroom is an ever-lengthening
list of buyers who have put down $500 deposits. James Alexander, a
mechanic from Mason, Tenn., who went on the list in February, just
got his PT. ``It's a joy to drive,'' Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite having no bargaining leverage on such a hot vehicle,
Alexander got his for the sticker price, about $20,000 with
options, because Covington Pike has decided not to charge a
premium. ``That wouldn't be fair to the customer,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   But other dealers feel differently. Last week, anyone willing to
pay $24,999 _ $5,000 above list _ could drive home that day in the
dark blue PT Cruiser on the showroom floor at Village Chrysler-Jeep
in Royal Oak, Mich. Village's new-car sales manager, Jeff Radke,
said it had been bought used with a few hundred miles on the
odometer; his waiting list for new ones numbers 60.
</P>
<P>
   And the dealership is not guaranteeing what the final price will
be on those, he said, leaving open the possibility that it will
tack on a premium if demand stays strong. And if customers balk?
``If they don't want it, they can cancel,'' he said. ``It's up to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Some dealers are looking to maximize profits on scarce vehicles
by auctioning them online. Blouin Truck Center of Augusta, Me.,
posted a dark red PT Cruiser on eBay last week, seeking an opening
bid of $19,990, or $2,400 above list. ``It's a variation on what
the market will bear,'' said Mike Linkenbach, the dealership's
manager. ``This is a unique vehicle. This isn't like a Dodge Neon
that they build every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Rossi, vice president for global communications at
DaimlerChrysler, said such markups were isolated. ``You've heard a
handful of stories,'' he said. ``What you haven't heard are the
10,000 positive experiences, people who went through the process,
placed an order and got their vehicles.'' Chrysler dealers
delivered 8,325 PT Cruisers in April, he said, and have about
79,000 more on order.
</P>
<P>
   In introducing the X5, its first sport utility, in December, BMW
found itself in the catbird seat. Jack Pitney, a spokesman, said,
``We're in an enviable position where demand far outweighs
supply.''
</P>
<P>
   Too far, in fact. The first year's production is sold out, and
dealers are not yet allowed to take orders for 2001 models. For
now, the only way to get one is to buy it used; an X5 with 4,700
miles was on eBay last week at a minimum bid of $49,100, just $800
below its base price when new.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, with Toyota's new MR2, a two-seat sports car whose
production was limited to generate buzz with consumers: all 7,425
available this year are spoken for, the company said. And at Betten
Imports in Grand Rapids, Mich., the back-order time for the latest
Mercedes S-Class cars, which start at around $80,000, is up to a
year.
</P>
<P>
   The Odyssey has no such cachet; its attractions are Honda's
reputation for quality and raves in the consumer press. Joseph
Phillippi, automotive analyst at PaineWebber, observed, ``It's a
Honda _ enough said.''
</P>
<P>
   Introduced more than a year ago, the Odyssey is still scarce,
even though Honda is making as many as it can. ``Most dealers only
have one or two,'' said Michael Luckey, an automotive consultant
who shopped for an Odyssey in Pompton Plains, N.J. Manby of
Greenlight.com, which matches potential buyers with 1,000
participating dealers, said it ``is tough to find anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the toughest of all, for now, is BMW's Z8 sports car,
featured in ``The World Is Not Enough,'' last year's James Bond
thriller. The car went on sale only last Monday, but all 400 to be
sold in the United States have already been allotted to buyers who
ordered them up to a year ago, when the Z8 began appearing in
European car magazines. An Internet search last week found none on
auction sites.
</P>
<P>
   In such cases, ``the advice I can give any customer is
basically, `Get to your dealer early,''' said Steven Sturm, vice
president for marketing at Toyota.
</P>
<P>
   What will be the next hot car? Analysts mention the Audi TT
Roadster and the new Thunderbird that Ford is planning for next
spring. Jeff Leckta, Internet Services Manager at Betten Imports,
cites the convertible New Beetle. Though Volkswagen told dealers
not to expect the car until the fall of 2001, he said, ``I already
have orders.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
