<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DERBY WAGERING REQUIRES IMAGINATION, COURAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ It would be nice to bet on the Kentucky Derby
with Confederate money, enough to cover the wagering possibilities
without risking much.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Confederate money has not been worth much here since Union
generals Ulysses S. Grant and William Tecumseh Sherman met at the
Galt House hotel in downtown Louisville in 1864 to discuss the
strategy of how Sherman could best light up Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   So, only real money is accepted at the endless number of
``windows'' at Churchill Downs that seldom are closed on the
weekend of the Kentucky Derby. Change is given at these windows,
but not information.
</P>
<P>
   With no desire to waste real money and with a real desire to
impart information, here are some ways to approach wagering on this
most-competitive 126th Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   1. Betting on The Prettiest Horse: It is possible, especially
here in horse-crazy Kentucky, for the mere sight of a horse to take
one's breath away. If a beauty contest were held, the two top
contenders would be War Chant and Fusaichi Pegasus, two animals
that are absolutely gorgeous.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus is such a perfect specimen that you're wowed by
a mere glance at the colt. If you like to bet on the prettiest
horse, go with Fusaichi Pegasus.
</P>
<P>
   2. Betting on a horse's name: Many, many contenders here. Only
one guess, for example, where Impeachment last raced before coming
to Louisville (the Arkansas Derby). For you football fans, you
elderly football fans, that is, Trippi is named after Charlie
Trippi, the legendary running back from the University of Georgia
in the 1940s and later with the Chicago Cardinals. Trippi (the
horse) was sired by End Sweep to carry on the football analogy, but
it is unsure whether Trippi (the horse) can run any further than
Trippi (the elderly football player). &UR;  &LR; Today.
</P>
<P>
   The most touching name, especially for policemen, is Captain
Steve, trained by fun-loving Bob Baffert and owned by even more
fun-loving Mike Pegram. It seems that when the Baffert-trained
Silver Charm won the 1997 Derby, paying $10, Baffert and Pegram had
bet oodles and oodles and won boodles and boodles of money.
</P>
<P>
   Pegram packed the boodles of money into his bag, which also
contained a .357 Magnum. Pegram was stopped at the airport gate and
was arrested when authorities put two and two together _ namely
boodles of money with a .357 Magnum equals one drug dealer.Only the
intervention of Louisville Police Capt. Steve Thompson, a friend of
the fun-loving Baffert crowd, saved good ole boy Pegram from many a
long night in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Even more touching is Hal's Hope, named by 88-year-old trainer
Harold Rose after himself. Rose has never had a Kentucky Derby
winner, but the mere prospects of training Hal's Hope enabled Rose
to leap out of a hospital bed after bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   For the intellectuals, there is Curule, a Latin word for a seat
or throne reserved for the highest dignitaries. The occult-obsessed
can claim Deputy Warlock, whose connections have named their horses
from the deepest corners of the Twilight Zone, such as Obeah, Go
for Wand, and Witching Hour. Bet on your favorite name.
</P>
<P>
   3. Betting on the politically correct: A sure thing _ The
Deputy, who is trained by Jenine Sahadi. No horse trained by a
woman has ever won the Derby, but Sahadi has an excellent chance.
Even more of a sure thing for the yuppie crowd, Sahadi is the only
trainer to spike her horse's feed with wine. Second choice: Curule,
whose jockey is African-American Marlon St. Julien. No black jockey
has won the Derby in 98 years.
</P>
<P>
   4. Betting on the jockey: Only five of the 19 jockeys have ever
won a Derby (Jerry Bailey, Chris McCarron, Pat Day, Craig Perret,
and Kent Desormeaux) and, of those five, only Bailey has won as
many as two. So, many a jockey is going to make many a wrong move
as they wilt under the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   But a favorite, especially of the car-wash set, is Roger Velez,
the jockey on Hal's Hope, who likes to relieve the pressure of big
races by going to a car wash and helping to towel down a few cars
before heading to the track. So bet on your favorite jockey.
</P>
<P>
   5: Betting out of spite: Americans have long been suckers for
the Sky-is-Falling and the End-is-Near crowd, usually of a
religious variety. But lately the doomsayers have been
environmentalists (global warming), and last year it was the
computer crowd (the Y2K bug). Few doomsayers have made as much
money off so many gullible Americans as Satanish Sanan, whose Y2K
software raked in untold millions as Jan. 1, 2000, came and went
with barely a blip.
</P>
<P>
   Sanan, though, had not made so much money doomsaying that he was
willing to bid a penny more than $4 million for a Mr. Prospector
yearling that eventually was bought by a Japanese businesman. That
colt, of course, was Fusaichi Pegasus. So the wager for all those
who despise doomsayers is Fusaichi Pegasus.
</P>
<P>
   6. Betting on horses chosen after 64 straight hours of
handicapping: Some believe this is the more
intellectually-responsible way to analyze a horse race than merely
picking a winner by name, color, or jockey's silks. Alas, the
percentage of winners chosen in this responsible manner often does
not top the percentage of those merely choosing by name.
Nevertheless . . .
</P>
<P>
   One secret to handicapping is to eliminate horses with no
chance. In early betting at Churchill Downs Friday, the four-horse
entry of Trippi, Commendable, Impeachment, and High Yield was made
the 3-to-1 favorite. Not one of those horses has a chance to make
the board, especially High Yield, a speed ball starting from post
position 17.
</P>
<P>
   Another secret to handicapping is deciding what to do with the
favorite. When the horses are put into the starting gate, Fusaichi
Pegasus will be the strong favorite at 8-to-5 or so, and a decision
must be made about this extremely good horse.
</P>
<P>
   Here is where Chaos Theory enters, as many unexpected events are
going to happen when 19 horses mount their calvary charge for two
minutes. It is possible, if not likely, that Chaos will envelop the
favorite and his jockey, Desormeaux, who is not the most dependable
under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Which leaves us with the winner, Irish-bred The Deputy. There is
tremendous early speed in this race from four or five horses and a
closer will win it. Sahadi is a master in having her horses primed
for big races, and The Deputy looks very ready to make a winning
closing kick under his dependable jockey, McCarron.
</P>
<P>
   It seems probable that Fusaichi Pegasus has to finish second or
third. But if he runs into traffic trouble, which is sure to hinder
some horses, look for one of the horses in the mutuel field, either
Wheelaway or Deputy Warlock, to make the board. Captain Steve and
More Than Ready also can finish second or third.
</P>
<P>
   The Final Play: The Deputy to win, with Wheelaway or Fusiachi
Pegasus second in your perfecta (betting horses to finish first and
second in order), and those two horses with Captain Steve and
Deputy Warlock third in your trifecta combinations (picking the top
3 in order).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 1908EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
