<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7073 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BEAUTY-REINTERPRETED-     05-05 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAUTY-REINTERPRETED-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO FACES OF BEAUTY: TIMELESS AND TIMELY 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was once a time, says the cultural historian Sander
Gilman, when Irishmen had their noses surgically altered to look
more like Englishmen so they could seem more American. Later many
Jews had their noses surgically altered to look more like Irishmen
so they could seem more American. Such are the knotty ways in which
different cultures pursue visions of beauty, proclaiming timeless
ideals while succumbing to the tastes of their time and place.
</P>
<P>
   In even more knotty ways, contemporary culture is doing the same
thing. As an ideal, beauty has been taking quite a beating. It has
been viewed as an ideology that is as culture bound as the taste
and distaste for Irish noses. It has come to seem irrelevant to
artworks preoccupied with race and gender. And claims for its
superiority and moral stature have been beaten down by the memories
of artistic mastery cohabiting with evil in regimes like the
Nazis'. So beauty is often treated as merely a matter of taste.
</P>
<P>
   Yet during the last 10 years or so, there has also been a
movement in the other direction. The philosopher and classicist
Alexander Nehamas has suggested that beauty is once again becoming
an academic obsession as philosophers and critics resuscitate the
beautiful as an ideal, recasting old philosophical arguments and
forecasting new variants.
</P>
<P>
   These two opposing perspectives have led to a tense mixture of
politics and aesthetics, reflected in recent books reinterpreting
beauty. Four of their authors gathered under the auspices of the
Vera List Center at the New School for Social Research on Wednesday
night to discuss their views. They included Gilman, a professor at
the University of Chicago; Nehamas, a professor of philosophy and
comparative literature at Princeton; Elaine Scarry, a professor of
aesthetics at Harvard and Jed Perl, the art critic for the New
Republic. (Full disclosure: this writer moderated the discussion).
</P>
<P>
   In Gilman's view, much evil has been caused in the name of
beauty. His book, ``Making the Body Beautiful: A Cultural History
of Aesthetic Surgery,'' (Princeton, 1999) portrays the quest for
physical beauty as an ugly human epic. He tells how flesh and fat
and lids and lobes have been cut from bodies and faces to modify
ethnic and racial characteristics and create new identities. While
cosmetic surgery allows each person to be sculptured into a version
of an ideal, that ideal is itself politically constructed and is
meant to exclude as much as refine. Surgery can seem to confer
power, he said on the panel, adding, ``I can be anyone I want to be
because I can control who I am.'' But it also creates servitude to
notions of beauty that are no more than ``a reflex of the culture
in which we live.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``On Beauty and Being Just'' (Princeton, 1999), Scarry also
attends to the political aspects of beauty but invokes them in
beauty's defense. One of the reasons beauty has been eclipsed in
recent decades, she argues, is that it has been considered
politically harmful. Beauty is criticized for being a distraction,
opium for the elites as well as the masses. What's more it has been
perceived as inherently oppressive, most evidently in what has been
called the ``male gaze'' that treats women as objects.
</P>
<P>
   But this argument, she says, is all wrong. The beautiful is life
restoring, not imprisoning. It serves as a muse of sorts, inspiring
the viewer to give birth to other beautiful objects created in
homage: paintings, poems, sculptures. And far from distracting from
justice, beauty does just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   It teaches a kind of fairness _ the fairness of balance and
symmetry. This sense of fairness, Scarry suggests, is precisely the
quality that defines justice. She invokes the philosopher John
Rawls, whose vision of justice is of a ``symmetry of everyone's
relations to each other.'' So while in Gilman's view beauty can
deform justice, in Scarry's, beauty leads to it. Beauty is
politically beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   Nehamas is more reluctant to generalize. In ``The Art of
Living'' (California, 1998), he argued that the philosophical quest
for a worthwhile life does not involve the application of universal
principles; each life is given shape in a particular and
idiosyncratic manner. On the panel Nehamas gave a glimpse of some
of the similar arguments he is developing into a book on beauty,
suggesting that beauty, like philosophical investigation, is also
personal, not universal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't want anyone or everyone to accept my judgment of
beauty,'' he said. Instead beauty inspires communities of shared
taste in which notions of moral or political virtue are secondary.
But within these communities, Nehamas argued, beauty provides an
education in character; beauty aids in ``the art of living.'' Like
Scarry, Nehamas sees beauty as socially therapeutic and
enlightening; like Gilman, he sees it as a conglomeration of
contrasting visions, each defining a distinct community.
</P>
<P>
   As a practicing critic, Perl has a different perspective. He is
less interested in beauty's political benefits or betrayals
(although like Nehamas, he is reluctant to seek universals),
attending instead to the ways the eye perceives each artwork.
</P>
<P>
   In his latest collection of essays, ``Eyewitness: Reports From
an Art World in Crisis'' (Basic Books, 2000), Perl proposes that
art is endangered precisely because it is treated as subservient to
political or social ideals. He writes about the ``internal logic of
a work of art'' and defends art's ``freestanding value.'' He
attacks the manners and machinery of dealers, curators and the
media, who he suggests distort the dynamic and mysterious powers of
the beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   But Perl does not seem to be alluding to beauty as some
universal property. It is, for him, inseparable from the work of
art. In fact, there are few contemporary thinkers anywhere who
would try to define beauty in the abstract; such claims would have
to be sweepingly large. Yet until recently this was one of the
principal ways in which beauty was discussed. Objects were
beautiful because they possessed beauty.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In his 1790 ``Critique of Judgment,'' for example, Kant outlines
the principles that characterize judgments of beauty. He argued
that any judgment of beauty is removed from any considerations of
an object's usefulness, political or otherwise. The beautiful
object may inspire a desire to possess it or understand it, but the
judgment of its beauty is untainted by such considerations of
interest.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Kant argued, when we are gazing at an object, we do
not consider its beauty a mere assertion of taste; we do not
emphasize the relative aspects of our experience _ the cultural
moment or our mood. Instead, beauty is felt to be universal, beyond
the reach of time and fashion or individual whim. We may not
declare that everyone will agree with our proclamation of beauty,
but beauty inspires a feeling that everyone should agree. The
judgment of beauty carries an assertion of authority: something
universal has been found.
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, such authority is gone. A contemporary judgment
of beauty incorporates a belief that not everyone will agree or
should agree. Beauty is almost never felt to be universal; it is
almost always a product of experience. The judgment of beauty is
not free of interest; it is laden with interest. Beauty, far from
being independent of usefulness, may even be assessed by its
usefulness.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the contemporary revival of beauty completely undoes
this inversion of the Kantian idea. Beauty may create injustice, as
in Gilman's argument, inspire justice, as in Scarry's, cultivate
character, as in Nehamas', and serve an artwork as in Perl's, but
it does not exist apart from this place and this time. That may be
this era's taste in beauty, our version of the surgically altered
nose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
