<HEADLINE>
DATABASE DISPUTE SETTLED WITH BIG SWISS BANKS IN HOLOCAUST
RESTITUTION PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Representatives of Swiss commercial banks and Holocaust
survivors are expected to present the final details of a $1.25
billion restitution settlement to a federal judge next week after
two of the largest banks agreed to give the survivors' lawyers
access to databases containing information on 2.1 million Nazi-era
accounts, the lead lawyer for the survivors said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Burt Neuborne, said the agreement, which was reached
at a 2 1/2 hour meeting on Thursday with Judge Edward R. Korman of
U.S. District Court in Brooklyn, could greatly speed up the last
bit of haggling about the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hope is to give the judge a completed set of negotiations
late next week so he can finalize the agreement,'' Neuborne said.
``I call it inching toward Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Swiss banks and the Holocaust survivors reached the
precedent-setting accord in August 1998 to create a billion-dollar
fund intended to settle the claims of tens of thousands of people
whose families lost assets in World War II, the negotiations have
been hamstrung for months over the question of checking Swiss
records to find additional claimants.
</P>
<P>
   Neuborne and Paul Volcker, the chairman of an independent panel
that conducted much of the investigative work in the case, wanted
to create a centralized database that would have contained 4.1
million Swiss accounts set up from 1933 to 1945. The two banks,
Credit Suisse and UBS, agreed to grant access to their own 2.1
million accounts, but scores of smaller banks, which control about
another 2 million accounts, have so far declined to allow the
lawyers to search their files.
</P>
<P>
   In December the Independent Committee of Eminent Persons, the
panel led by Volcker, the former chairman of the Federal Reserve,
said a centralized database was needed ``to reach a speedy
conclusion to the claims resolution process.'' Neuborne added
Friday that the power to sift through all accounts opened in
wartime Switzerland was needed in order to ensure that no claimant
was left unfound.
</P>
<P>
   In letter to Volcker in February, Korman supported the idea of a
wide-ranging database, writing, ``I agree that the success of this
effort depends on the willingness of the Swiss authorities to adopt
your recommendation that a central archive of data on all 4.1
million accounts be established.''
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss originally balked at the proposal and, in March,
authorized the creation of a much smaller database that included
only 46,000 accounts. In a report issued in December, Volcker's
panel had named those 46,000 accounts as the most likely to have
been owned by Holocaust victims.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Credit Suisse nor UBS could be reached Friday for
comment. Roger M. Witten, a Washington-based lawyer, who represents
the banks, refused to discuss details of the agreement but said,
``Everybody wants to get to the point where the settlement is
approved and the money is flowing to class members.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
