<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-PARCELLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARCELLS TO DIRECT JETS EFFORT INDEFINITELY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As it turned out, Bill Parcells didn't want to shop for the
groceries and then head off into the sunset. Instead, he has
decided to remain with the New York Jets indefinitely as the
director of football operations and monitor the four No. 1 picks he
had in this year's draft.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells will also continue to be in full view of the Patriots,
not in the ``Monday Night Football'' booth, or an ESPN studio, or
diagramming X's and O's with the Fox crew. Parcells rejected all TV
overtures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I indicated some time ago that I would not abandon this
franchise,'' said Parcells. ``I look forward to working with
(owner) Woody Johnson and Al Groh in a collective effort to try to
bring a championship to New York. I view my job very simply: to try
and get good players for the coach.''
</P>
<P>
   That coach is Al Groh, named on Jan. 24. He's a longtime ally of
Parcells, but not his first choice. That was Bill Belichick, who
took the job then quit the next day, citing the instability of the
ownership as it passed from the late Leon Hess to Johnson, of
Johnson &AMP; Johnson fame.
</P>
<P>
   There had been reports that Parcells was going to guide the Jets
and help Groh for a while, but then leave by the summer. But
Parcells may be on the verge of building a stellar defense; he
traded Pro Bowl wide receiver to Tampa Bay for two first-round
picks, which gave New York an unprecedented four of the first 30.
</P>
<P>
   With those picks, the Jets selected defensive end Shaun Ellis,
outside linebacker John Abraham, quarterback Chad Pennington, and
tight end Anthony Becht.
</P>
<P>
   The offense may miss Johnson, one of the premier players in the
game, but on the other side of the ball, Ellis and Abraham are
highly regarded and Pro Bowl linebacker Mo Lewis had earlier signed
a one-year tender offer.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has had to deal with defections on his staff. Besides
Belichick, Parcells's son-in-law, Scott Pioli, the team's former
director of pro scouting, left the organization to join the
Patriots. Over the past few days, Belichick and Pioli have tried to
interview scout Lionel Vital for the job of national scout,
replacing the fired Dave Uyrus. Parcells rejected a request by the
Patriots to allow Vital to interview because Parcells viewed it as
a lateral move. The Patriots may now offer a title under Vital's
name so he can be free to interview for the job.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets should be a competitive team with quarterback Vinny
Testaverde returning from a ruptured Achilles' heel that he
suffered in the season opener vs. the Patriots last season. The
Jets have not adequately replaced Johnson, but have been discussing
the possibility of Cincinnati's Carl Pickens, who has been
disgruntled for the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole idea and thought process is to improve this team each
year,'' Parcells said. ``The only reason you should be in this
business is to win championships.''
</P>
<P>
   Groh, the former Patriots' defensive coordinator, said ``Bill's
decision to remain in his current position means we kept a Hall of
Fame performer on our team. What could be better than that?''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells turned the 1-15 Jets of 1996 into a 9-7 team in 1997,
then went to 12-4 and won the AFC East in '98. Considering the
disaster of losing Testaverde in the first game, the Jets rebounded
to go 8-8, same as the Patriots. Parcells will now attempt to bring
the Jets back to where they were two years ago. No small task.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am obviously delighted that Bill Parcells has decided to
stay with the New York Jets,'' Johnson said. ``Our sole objective
since the purchase of the team has been to create a winning
organization, attitude and team. Having Bill around to help us
through this period is an enormous advantage to the franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   It may also be an advantage for the Jets in the Patriots-Jets
rivalry. Now, twice a year, it'll be Belichick vs. Groh _ Who's the
better coach? Belichick and Groh have worked hand-in-hand on
defenses for the Giants, Patriots, and Jets. And now Parcells will
be looking down on Belichick, the coach who scorned him. Belichick
has sometimes been referred to as the ``genius'' behind Parcells.
Belichick is not competing against Parcells on the field, but now
he'll be competing against him in the personnel office.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former Patriots tight end Ben Coates has been talking to the
Detroit Lions about a job . . . . . . The Patriots are considering
unrestricted free agent defensive tackle Gilbert Brown of the
Packers, who lost 25 pounds at a Duke University weight loss clinic
this offseason and is reportedly down to 320.
</P>
</TEXT>
