<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STONE-WEBSTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSS OF N-PLANT CLEANUP WORK THREAT TO STONE, WEBSTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The owners of the Maine Yankee nuclear power plant have
canceled a $250 million cleanup contract with Stone &AMP; Webster Inc.,
which could push the engineering firm closer to a bankruptcy
filing.
</P>
<P>
   Maine Yankee's owners, including Central Maine Power Co., Bangor
Hydro, and National Grid, voted Thursday to suspend payments to
Stone &AMP; Webster. Earlier in the week, a key Stone &AMP; Webster
subcontractor ceased work on a power plant project in Tiverton,
R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Other projects could also slip as the gravity of Stone &AMP;
Webster's financial position begins to sink in with customers
around the world. Last Sunday, Stone &AMP; Webster disclosed that its
problems had forced it to take a $27.5 million charge and begin
talks to sell most if its assets.
</P>
<P>
   If the talks fail, Stone &AMP; Webster may be forced into default
with creditors, it said. The company expects to receive credit
extensions in such an event.
</P>
<P>
   Many worry that Stone &AMP; Webster might not be able to continue
operating, though.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the Massachusetts Water Resources Authority said it
would reduce payments to Stone &AMP; Webster if it seeks bankruptcy
protection and shift contracts so that subcontractors are still
paid to work on the MetroWest water-supply tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Stone &AMP; Webster is construction manager for the $680 million
tunnel. It has 30 employees dedicated to the job and has received
$19 million of the $38 million it is due under an eight-year
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Maine Yankee was closed in 1997 amid safety problems and rising
costs, and Stone &AMP; Webster was hired in 1998 to ``decommission''
the plant by removing or storing radioactive material. Stone &AMP;
Webster employs 480 people at Maine Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are in talks to try to return the employees to
work on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   WHEN Central Maine's board ended the contract, Stone &AMP; Webster
had already received about $60 million under a contract due to end
in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Michael Frietag would not discuss the company's
financial outlook beyond its previous disclosures. But he said that
``while we dispute Maine Yankee's right to terminate our current
arrangement, we're encouraged by its willingness to explore
alternatives that would allow S&AMP;W to continue its involvement in
this important project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to quickly identify a solution that allows us to
continue our work and ensure that the project is completed safely
and within the time frame originally estabilished.''
</P>
<P>
   Maine Yankee spokesman Eric Howes said the vote to suspend the
contract was not unanimous but declined to say which owners don't
support the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Stone &AMP; Webster shares rose 18.75 cents to close at $3.1875 in
New York Stock Exchange trading.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
