<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7083 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MONTREAL-BOOM-ART-2TA     05-05 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTREAL-BOOM-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER A LONG DECLINE, MONTREAL REINVENTS ITSELF IN A VARIETY OF
WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Canada Journal) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT 14 and 15 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ St. Catherine's Street, this city's fabled
entertainment and shopping artery, once boasted the highest rents
in Canada. But 25 years ago, after separatist governments mandated
French supremacy in commercial signs, English-speakers sourly noted
that the most common sign on the street was ``A louer'' _ ``For
Rent.''
</P>
<P>
   But now Rue Ste. Catherine has a new face. Vacant storefronts
have been filled with high-fashion boutiques, restaurants and
``exotic dancing'' clubs that are attracting crowds that spill off
sidewalks into the street. At one end, the old hockey rink is being
transformed into a multimedia entertainment center with 5,000 movie
theater seats. At another end, the old Loews Theater is to reopen
next year as entertainment salad of circus stages, restaurants and
night clubs, the second ``Club Med World'' after Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal is coming back after years of fray and decay. Once the
eastern shipping hub of the country, Montreal has reinvented itself
as a center for biotech, telecommunications and information
technology companies. Rents are rising along with construction
cranes, tourists are packing hotels, and this city of 3.3 million
people has become the third most popular site in North American for
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Toronto is still No. 1, the pendulum is swinging back to
Montreal,'' Gillian Cosgrove, a business writer, lamented recently
in The National Post, a newspaper edited in a city stuck with such
labels as ``Toronto the Good'' and ``Toronto the Clean.'' The
rivalry between Montreal, the fun center, and Toronto, the
financial center, compares with the rivalries between Rome and
Milan, or between Rio and Sao Paulo.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time anyone can remember, Montreal's unemployment
rate has dipped below Toronto's, hitting 6.5 percent in January,
the lowest level in a quarter century.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Quebec province registered 4 percent economic growth last year,
higher than the rest of Canada for the first time in more than a
decade. While poverty still blights many communities, Quebec's
welfare rolls have dropped by about a quarter in the last five
years.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Where once construction cranes were an endangered species, more
than a billion dollars worth of construction is under way. The
convention center is being doubled, and the downtown airport is
expanding. Near the river, workers are finishing Cite Multimedia, a
huge incubator for high-tech start-up companies. Later this summer,
work is to begin downtown on a new $150 million baseball stadium
for the city's Expos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are shooting to get the shovels in by June,'' Stephen
Bronfman, the 36-year-old co-chairman of the Expos who is member of
the wealthy Bronfman clan, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Montreal hotels enjoyed their best occupancy rates
since Expo 67, the world's fair 33 years ago that marked the city's
last economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it `Paris without jet lag,''' said Marie-Josee
Allaire, spokeswoman for the Ritz Carlton Montreal, one of several
Montreal hotels that have spent a total of $150 million for
renovations.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The floods of New Englanders and New Yorkers booking rooms in
Montreal this summer follows a 20 percent jump in foreign tourism
that Canada has enjoyed for two years. As airlines add new flights
this year between the United States and Montreal, the tourist boom
is partly built on bargains to be had with the weak Canadian
currency, which trades at almost 1.50 for one American dollar.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Montreal has also reinvented itself as a major center for higher
education. The city now edges out Boston for the highest number of
college students per capita in North America's largest cities,
4.38.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal to is to have 25 percent of our students coming from
outside of Canada,'' said Bernard J. Shapiro, principal of McGill
University, which is the largest predominantly English-language
school in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage French-speaking bonds, a student from Senegal,
where France was the colonial power, often pays less state tuition
to study in Montreal than a student from neighboring,
English-speaking Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   This concentration of brain power has helped to move Montreal
away from its old industrial base into a mix of biopharmaceutical
companies and other technology-based concerns. In Montreal's
suburbs, the shift can be most visible at ``pill hill,'' where 40
percent of Canada's pharmaceutical companies are based. Bombardier,
a Montreal company that many Americans associate with snowmobiles,
has become the world's third largest aircraft manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new economy is multimedia, we are No. 1 in research and
development,'' said Montreal's mayor, Pierre Bourque, in an
interview. Reflecting the economic dynamism here, the Quebec
government and the Nasdaq Stock Market announced plans a week ago
to open Nasdaq Canada this fall, a new electronic exchange based
here. That would return company stock trading to the city since the
Montreal Stock Exchange closed last year.
</P>
<P>
   Spending by American filmmakers has also been a source of
economic growth, jumping four-fold in the last five years to $200
million a year. American directors have discovered that this
gracefully aging city with its stately churches and quaint public
squares offers discount locations that can pass for European or
American.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Attracting American startup companies is the fact that
electricity, office rents and industrial construction costs are
about half those of New York and Boston. The downside is that
Quebec has North America's highest income tax rates; combined
federal and provincial rates top out at 51.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rents are extremely cheap relative to the horror stories
I've heard about Manhattan,'' said David E. Pawsey, a 24-year-old
digital editor. Referring to the American equivalent of $550, he
added, ``You can get a three bedroom place downtown for $800, and
that's considered expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   With free trade, Quebec is increasingly oriented south,
expanding the part of its economy devoted to trade with the United
States to 25 percent today, from 10 percent a decade ago. If Quebec
were a nation, it would now be the United States' fifth largest
trading partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Montreal is losing Canada as its hinterland and focusing on
the U.S.,'' said Raphael Fischler, a Belgian immigrant who teaches
urban planning at McGill. ``The francophones have reconquered
Montreal. Now, the great tension in Quebec is between linguistic
nationalism and economic globalization.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although red and white maple leaf flags generally fly only over
federally owned buildings here, separatist passions and linguistic
tensions seem increasingly relaxed. In the last vote on Quebec
separation from Canada, in 1995, the separatists narrowly lost.
</P>
<P>
   After the French-supremacy language laws were imposed, about 40
percent of Montreal's English-speaking population decamped for
Ontario and points west. Those remaining are more culturally and
linguistically supple. The Gazette, the city's English-language
newspaper, recently published a series on ``the new Anglos,''
noting that in one generation, the percentage of bilingual
English-speaking residents had doubled, to about two-thirds today.
While ethnic politicians often demonize the other group, bicultural
marriages now outnumber marriages between two English-speakers.
</P>
<P>
   While English-speakers in Montreal may sometimes feel as
beleaguered as English-speakers in Miami, there is no sign that the
English presence is going to disappear here. Indeed, in one of the
biggest investments in the Canadian newspaper world this year, The
Gazette plans to inaugurate a $50 million, full color printing
press in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely an endorsement of the city and, frankly, of
the English-reading audience,'' Alan E. Allnut, editor of the
222-year-old newspaper, said over lunch in a French restaurant in
the gradually gentrifying Vieux Port neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden, Montreal, with its improving economy, European
style and cheap real estate, is looking more and more attractive.
Bronfman, the co-chairman of the Expos, said of friends who left,
``There are a lot of people who are in Toronto who are dying to
come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Toronto Life magazine committed a very public hara-kiri for a
boosterish city monthly. The cover of an issue last fall was
devoted to a photograph of a smoked meat sandwich, with the title:
``Where to find Montreal in Toronto: the food, the fashion, the
booze, the fun _ a guide to all things Montrealish.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
