<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISLAMIC-REBELS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILIPPINE TERRORISM ROOTED IN MEDIEVAL STRUGGLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Muslim insurrection that has launched a wave of terrorism
and kidnapping in the remote southernmost corner of the Philippines
is a 21st-century incarnation of political and religious struggles
that stretch back 500 years to Europe and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   The upheaval also has roots in the emergence of the United
States as a superpower in the middle of the last century, and in
the ebbs and flows of Philippine politics in recent decades.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle ``is really the jihad vs. the crusade, still being
fought out in the Philippines,'' said David Steinberg, president of
Long Island University. Steinberg is widely acknowledged as the
leading American specialist on the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   The story begins in the 15th century, when a resurgent Spanish
crown began dispatching ships westward with the dual mission of
finding a route to the Spice Islands and converting native peoples
to Roman Catholicism. In the Philippines, they encountered the
advancing edge of Islam, which had spread east and south from
Mecca, through Pakistan and India, down the Malay peninsula, and
across what is now Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Spanish were able to push the Muslims out of most of the
Philippines, but were not strong enough to push them out of the
south,'' Steinberg says. ``For centuries, there was an uneasy peace
between local sultans and the distant Spanish culture'' based in
Manila, which ``claimed Mindanao, but didn't really control it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mindanao Island, the Muslim heartland, encompasses 35 percent of
the land area of the Philippines, but over the centuries it
remained outside the country's mainstream. When American forces
defeated Spain and made the Philippines into a US colony 100 years
ago, they saw in Mindanao's open fields and pastures an echo of the
American West and an outlet for the intensifying political unrest
among the masses of landless, destitute peasants crowding Luzon,
the main island.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans set out to move people to relatively unpopulated
Mindanao, oblivious to the possibility that the Asian Muslims and
the ardently Catholic peasants from Luzon might not prove a
compatible mix. But limitations of technology and transportation in
the early 20th century were barriers to massive change. The area
remained predominantly Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   All this changed after World War II. The United States and the
new republican government of its former colony were under pressure
from communist movements. They feared such movements would prosper
in the squalid poverty of Luzon, and President Ramon Magsaysay,
actively assisted by the US Central Intelligence Agency, began
again to resettle poor people from Luzon to Mindanao. In short
order, Muslims were a minority in their ancestral homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Today, in central and northern sections of Mindanao, Christians
outnumber Muslims about 9 to 1. In southern sections and the
smaller out-islands, where many of the kidnappings and armed
clashes are occurring, Muslims outnumber Christians by similar
lopsided proportions.
</P>
<P>
   The influx of Christians did not spark immediate rebellion,
probably because Washington and Manila did not press the aggressive
advocacy of Catholicism that had been integral to the Spanish
empire.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 1970s, anger about exploitative mining and farming
concessions that President Ferdinand Marcos, who was notoriously
corrupt, granted his cronies coincided with a global trend of
Muslim societies seeking to throw off foreign influences. The long
period of uneasy truce in Mindanao and the out-islands gave way to
an armed Muslim insurgency, with the rebels gaining support from
Libya, Iran, and Iraq, and, closer to home, from Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   This conflict wound down but did not end decisively. Marcos
eventually fell to a political revolution. Efforts by his
successors, Corazon Aquino and Fidel Ramos, to reduce corruption
and reconcile with the Muslims made headway; and the general
situation was eased by improving economic conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But since 1998, those gains have been squandered under the
corrupt and unsophisticated administration of Philippine President
Joseph Estrada, Steinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a loss of cohesion throughout the country and a sense
that the center cannot hold,'' Steinberg said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
