A7086 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PANAM103-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      05-05 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAM103-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATORS WHO SEARCHED THROUGH DEBRIS OF PAN AM 103 TESTIFY 
</HEADLINE>
   By By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands _ The police officers who searched the
scenes of the crash of Pan Am 103 in 1988 began taking the stand
Friday in the trial of two Libyans accused of blowing up the plane.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony was drier than that of the first two days, when
air traffic controllers described the flight winking off their
radar screens, and neighbors described the hailstorm of fire, metal
and bodies that fell on their roofs and gardens in Lockerbie,
Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   If the day's testimony was more about the grim minutiae of
police work in the confusion of a crime scene covering 850 square
miles, it was also testimony that let the defense tip its hand a
bit more.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers tried to get witnesses to say that both CIA and
FBI agents were tramping the moors, with opportunities aplenty to
plant or steal evidence.
</P>
<P>
   They did get testimony that the Scottish police believed for
more than a year that Palestinians had bombed the London-to-New
York flight, which fell out of the skies on the small town of
Lockerbie. The 259 people on the plane and 11 on the ground died.
</P>
<P>
   The day ended with a reading of the names of the victims, by
families when applicable, with their addresses and the ages of all
those under 21. Audience members wept quietly as a speaker buzzed
faintly with the noise of the list being repeated in Arabic by a
translator. Two older women sobbed when the prosecutor reached the
Owens family, killed with their daughters, and a young woman
employed by the Scottish government slipped down the aisle with a
box of tissues, patting their arms. Others reached across the seats
to comfort each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the relatives have become close friends,'' Jim Swire,
a Briton who lost a daughter on the flight, said afterward. ``And
all I can say is that that's one of the few good things that have
come out of this.''
</P>
<P>
   The testimony elicited by the prosecution from seven officers
who directed the searches of various sectors, seemed intended to
leave the image of a vast but precise operation. Pictures were
displayed of long rows of searchers combing fields while
helicopters flew grid patterns overhead. The first sweeps were for
bodies, they said, and then it was done over again, sometimes in
driving rain, for debris. Items as small as watches were logged. At
one point, said former Chief Inspector Alexander McLean, tarpaulins
had to be brought in because the cargo included a million sewing
machine needles, and two officers had been pricked.
</P>
<P>
   The defense cross-examined six of the seven officers, mostly
probing for details about Americans on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   There are almost as many published theories about Pan Am 103 as
about the Kennedy assassinations.
</P>
<P>
   One published in Britain held that it was a U.S. Drug
Enforcement Administration sting that went wrong when someone
swapped a bomb for a heroin package.
</P>
<P>
   Because two people who worked for the CIA were believed to have
died in the crash, agency personnel were on the scene, officers
testified Friday. Scenarios blaming the CIA have been bruited.
</P>
<P>
   More widely believed was the theory that U.S. and Scottish
investigators worked with until 1991: that the plane was bombed by
Syrian-backed Palestinians working for Iran, which was seeking
revenge for the downing of an Iranian passenger jet by a U.S.
warship in July, 1988.
</P>
<P>
   That had plausibility because in October 1988, two months before
the plane went down, West German federal police arrested a dozen
Palestinians with Syrian passports, a Toshiba boombox, detonators,
barometric fuses, a bazooka, a grenade-launcher and other arms.
</P>
<P>
   But most of them, including a known bomb maker named Marwan
Khreesat, were released by a German judge and disappeared. In a
later search, the Germans found three more bombs packed in
Toshibas, one of which killed the man dismantling it.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian groups have repeatedly denied blowing up Pan Am
103.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators changed their minds about them after finding bits
of a timer embedded in a charred shirt in the debris. The timer was
traced to a Swiss firm that is said to have identified its customer
as the Libyan government, although it later said it also sold to
others and lost some in a burglary.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the defense announced its intention, as required
by Scottish law, that it would blame another party, namely, the
Palestinians. As the defense, they need not prove that to win; they
must only raise doubts in the judges' minds about the prosecution's
case.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, they plan to suggest that the Libyan-connected timer
was planted by U.S. investigators.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony for the prosecution, former Deputy Chief
Inspector Andrew D. Jackson described his sector search. Then the
defense asked him about six months he spent in Washington in 1989
as a liaison officer with the FBI. He acknowledged that the bureau
then believed the Palestinians were guilty and that he purchased
and brought home two Toshiba boom boxes for Scottish investigators.
</P>
<P>
   McLean, on cross-examination, expressed surprise that foreign
investigators suggested which items of debris might be interesting,
but he appeared confused about differences between the FBI and the
CIA, which he twice called the ``Criminal Intelligence Agency.''
</P>
<P>
   And in his prosecution testimony, former Chief Inspector Norman
Brown described how he tagged and recorded tons of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   On cross-examination, he was pressed to admit that rows of large
plastic evidence bags stood open and unguarded on a park lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Then the defense lawyer, William Taylor, asked: ``This debris
was collected by police officers?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes sir.``
</P>
<P>
   ``Fire personnel?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes sir.''
</P>
<P>
   ``RAF volunteers?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes sir.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Army personnel?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   ``American personnel?''
</P>
<P>
   There was a long pause.
</P>
<P>
   Finally Brown said, ``I don't remember any American personnel in
Sector B, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   The day's hero was Constable Michael Stryjewski of Lockerbie,
who saw the crash from his house, fetched a first aid kit and ran
up a flaming street and into burning houses to rescue residents. He
then drove to another neighborhood, did it again, and finally got
aboard a military helicopter to spend the rest of the night looking
for bodies.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked to describe how, days later, he spotted a crumpled
luggage container, labeled AVE 4041. A defense lawyer asked if he
had been sent to find that particular number. ``No,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you certain?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely _ no.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 1922EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
