<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7088 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-RAIDS-BOS &LR;      05-05 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-RAIDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSIONS MOUNT AS ISRAEL, HEZBOLLAH CALL CEASEFIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV _ Israel and Hezbollah guerrillas called a halt to
their attacks Friday after dozens of Katyusha rockets slammed into
northern Israel and Israeli fighter jets struck at targets across
Lebanon in a sharp escalation of violence just two months before
Israel's planned withdrawal from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis in northern border towns cautiously emerged after
spending most of the previous 24 hours in small concrete bunkers
during the attacks and counterattacks that left large parts of
Lebanon without electricity and scorched the northern Israeli town
of Kiryat Shmona.
</P>
<P>
   But both Hezbollah and Israel made it clear that they would
resume fighting if provoked.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's security Cabinet, meeting for the second time in 24
hours, ordered a halt in retaliatory strikes for the time being,
and officials said the bombings were a warning of the damage Israel
could inflict on Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in no hurry to escalate the level, but we say very
clearly that if there is a need, we will go up one step,'' Deputy
Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh told Israel's Channel One.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah, which is backed by Syria and Iran and says it is
fighting to oust Israeli forces from south Lebanon, warned that it,
too, would not hesitate to attack again if Israel kept up its air
raids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We warn the Zionist enemy against continuing in the rape of
Lebanon, because we are going to respond and confront it,''
Hezbollah said in a statement. ``If it wants to spare its northern
settlements the danger of the Katyusha rockets then it has to
restrain its army from any aggression and also has to restrain its
agent militia,'' a reference to the Israeli-financed South Lebanon
Army.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's decision to suspend strikes on suspected Hezbollah
targets and Lebanon, which Israel holds responsible for attacks by
Hezbollah, came as the United States and France appealed for an end
to the fighting. The Arab League scheduled an emergency meeting for
Saturday in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   But opposition Likud politicians immediately criticized Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak for halting the Israeli strikes that
began early Friday and resumed at midday after Hezbollah again
rocketed northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``What, are they going to wait until civilians are dead?'' asked
Gideon Ezra, former deputy director of Israel's internal security
agency Shin Bet. ``Every so often we must remind the Lebanese army
that we have the stronger army, and that the best thing for Lebanon
will be to stop Hezbollah because otherwise they will get hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Fires still smoldered late Friday along the northern border
where Katyusha rockets had fallen short of their targets, and large
areas of Lebanon were without electricity after Israeli F-15 and
F-16 fighters bombed two power stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will plunge their world into darkness,'' warned Israeli
President Ezer Weizman during a visit to the hard-hit town of
Kiryat Shmona, which was littered with shattered glass and the
burned wreckage of cars.
</P>
<P>
   One Israeli soldier was killed and about 30 Israelis lightly
wounded in the barrage of missiles that hit Thursday night and
again Friday morning, just as people emerged from shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's counterattack destroyed a Hezbollah arms depot and left
a crater that halted traffic on the main highway linking the
capitals of Syria and Lebanon. Israeli gunboats off the coast
joined in the pounding of suspected Hezbollah targets. One Lebanese
civilian and an off-duty soldier were injured in the Israeli
reprisals.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes and counterstrikes underscored the problems Israel
may face once it ends its 20-year occupation of a strip of south
Lebanon along the northern border, and pointed to the difficulties
Israel faces despite the so-called security zone.
</P>
<P>
   The tens of thousands of Israelis living along the border are
worried that without a peace agreement with Syria and Lebanon, the
Israeli withdrawal will only leave border towns more vulnerable to
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 40 Katyusha rockets slammed into Kiryat Shmona alone in
this round of fighting, damaging some 16 buildings and leading to
calls for more and tougher attacks on Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are afraid and they are angry and they want the army to
hit back so Hezbollah will think twice before it attacks again,''
said Mayor Haim Barbivay.
</P>
<P>
   This round of violence, the biggest in nearly a year, was
apparently sparked by attacks on Wednesday that killed two Lebanese
women and wounded six other civilians.
</P>
<P>
   In the first incident, Israel's proxy militia in south Lebanon
opened fire when it saw movement in an abandoned village, killing
an 82-year-old woman and her 40-year-old daughter. In the second,
the Israeli army said one of its planes flying over Lebanon had
accidentally released a bomb over a civilian village, wounding six
people.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli soldiers in the 10-mile deep security zone killed at
least two guerrillas readying to lay land mines.
</P>
<P>
   The scale of Hezbollah's counterattack was seen by some in
Israel as a last-ditch attempt to stop the unilateral Israeli
withdrawal _ or a warning of what it will be like after Israel does
withdraw. Syria, which has 35,000 troops in Lebanon, wants the
Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon to occur as part of a peace
agreement that will secure the return of the Golan Heights, which
Israel captured from Syria in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Israel also preferred to withdraw as part of a peace deal, but
when talks with Syria broke down earlier this year Barak decided to
stick to his campaign promise to get Israeli soldiers out of
Lebanon by July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
