<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7092 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CISCO-ARROWPOINT-450&AMP;     05-05 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISCO-ARROWPOINT-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CISCO SYSTEMS AGREES TO BUY ARROWPOINT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Cisco Systems said Friday that it had agreed to
buy ArrowPoint Communications in a stock swap valued at $5.7
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ArrowPoint, based in Acton, Mass., makes switches _ specialized
computers that optimize the delivery of content over the Internet.
Acquiring ArrowPoint gives Cisco, the leading maker of network
equipment, the technology it needs to compete against companies
like Alteon Web Systems in the fast-growing portion of the market
devoted to what is known as content switching, or load balancing.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street rewarded Cisco with a boost to its valuation that
eclipsed the cost of the deal. Cisco shares rose $3.9375, or 6
percent, to close at $67.5625 in Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in ArrowPoint, which went public in March, had gained 27
percent on Thursday after a report by Greg Geiling, an analyst with
J.P. Morgan, forecast that the company's sales would quintuple in
the next 12 months. Its shares closed Friday at $139.875, up
$5.0625.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco dominates the market for routers, computers that manage
data traffic on a network using the Internet Protocol, known as IP.
More than 80 percent of the routers connected to the Internet are
Cisco machines, which move traffic around the Internet based on the
IP address assigned each packet of data.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last year, a market has developed for switches that
can rapidly identify the type of data in the packet, and give
preferential routing to voice, for example, over plain text.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very big market opportunity, and ArrowPoint had
come in with the most intelligent switch,'' Geiling of J.P. Morgan
said. ``It was just a great opportunity for Cisco to seize once
again the No. 1 product in an emerging market. I think it's a good
transaction for all involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement, Cisco will exchange 2.1218
shares of its common stock for every outstanding share and stock
option of ArrowPoint Communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Content distribution is increasingly important for our
customers,'' Ammar Hanafi, Cisco's vice president for business
development, said in a telephone interview. ArrowPoint ``has taken
a very innovative software-based approach and is a real leader. We
think over time content networking is going to be as important a
technology as IP,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Volpe, ArrowPoint's president and chief operating officer,
said that a merger with one large company or another at some time
seemed likely, but that Cisco was the most compelling candidate.
``When the most highly regarded technology company comes calling,
they're probably only going to come once,'' he said. The deal
``ensures our technology will be the dominant technology in this
space.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As corporations move to an Internet-hosted computing model,
where not only software applications but telecommunications and
transaction-processing occurs over the Web, ArrowPoint's
load-balancing software is just one of several technologies they
will need, said Paul Johnson, a Robertson Stephens analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco already dominates routing, and is now buying a leading
player in load balancing, but still lacks strong positions in other
areas like gigabit ethernet, for fast transmission of data, and
cache technology, which smooths and speeds Web traffic by storing
frequently used data closer to the user, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you believe in this, it's highly likely Cisco will have to
do more acquisitions to fill in their product line,'' Johnson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
