<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7094 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV07-     05-05 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURB A DOG; HELP A TREE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For Sunday, May 7) By ANNE RAVER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I know I'm supposed to curb my dog, but occasionally
she goes when I'm not paying attention, and it seems cruel to yank
her away. Well, I'm not going to feel sorry for her anymore. You
shouldn't feel sorry for your dog. Because that urine kills trees
and other plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The acid eats right through the bark and cambial zone to the
wood zone, destroying the tree's defense system,'' said Eric T.
Fleisher, the director of horticulture at the Battery Park City
Parks Conservancy, which oversees the public park at the lower tip
of Manhattan. Even a small opening in the bark is a gateway for
micro-organisms that can spread disease through the tree.
</P>
<P>
   One gorgeous morning last week, Fleisher, who is known as T,
bent over the devastated base of a 15-foot linden tree on a corner
of Rector Place, where it ends at the walkway along the Hudson
River. The bark was completely eaten away, exposing the living
tissue, through which nutrients and water flow. A knobby ridge of
calluses showed where the tree had tried to wall off the damage, to
no avail.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you do a proper pruning cut, the tree can
compartmentalize that damage,'' Fleisher said. ``But it can't
localize something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The base of the tree was stained dark gray, and its bark was
deeply fissured, from dog-leg-level to the ground. The soil was as
hard as concrete, from all those dog feet, so the roots were
suffocating. (Urine also contains a lot of salt, which deprives the
plants of water and burns their roots.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to correct this is for people to alter the way
they train their animal,'' Fleisher said. ``Even an older dog can
be trained. Years ago, when my family moved to the Upper East Side,
we taught our old dog Franny to go in the street.'' This is
especially important for a dog that has been kept inside for hours.
``He'll still try to mark the plants, but he won't be emptying his
bladder on one tree,'' Fleisher said. Picture dozens of dogs doing
that to the same tree.
</P>
<P>
   Such frank talk might disturb readers expecting to learn about
tree peonies and such, but this is consciousness-raising time. Take
a look at street trees and shrubs along well-used park paths. The
damage is unmistakable. And even if you don't have a dog, you might
say something to the next offender _ politely, of course. Many
people don't realize that their adorable pets kill trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the 24 trees we replaced this year, six were due to
urine,'' Fleisher said. And trees at park entrances, like this
linden, are usually the first to go.
</P>
<P>
   Battery Park gardeners never wrap a newly planted tree with
burlap, because it holds urine next to the bark. To try to
counteract ground compaction, they add gypsum to lighten the soil
and neutralize the salt, and lime to offset the acidity. Aerating
is also important, to open up compacted soil and let plant roots
breathe. Mulching with organic matter also helps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do very little fertilizing,'' Fleisher said. ``We just keep
incorporating leaf mold and compost. A small percentage of aged
horse or cow manure is helpful, in terms of grubs and other
insects, protozoa and nematodes, which all make up a healthy,
living soil.'' Such additions also help roots absorb magnesium and
other elements in the soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I view fertilizer as junk food,'' Fleisher said. ``If the pH
is right, and you have good organisms in your soil, the plants will
get what they need.'' As we walked along the allee of lindens, he
pointed out mugho pines, azaleas and yew all under stress from
dogs. The leaves were limp and flaccid, and the soil was compacted.
The yew's needles were yellowed; the muhgo pines had scale. When a
plant is stressed, it's more likely to be attacked by insects.
</P>
<P>
   Fleisher also emphasized the importance of planting a tree at
the right depth to give it a healthy start and a leg up, so to
speak, on dogs. ``They used to say plant at the same depth as it
was planted in the nursery, but there's often too much soil on top
of the root ball,'' he said. If you plant too deep, the roots
aren't able to get enough oxygen, so they grow upward, seeking air.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tend to grow back towards the trunk and girdle the
tree,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If you look carefully at a tree, you will see how the trunk
flares out near the bottom. The bottom of this flare should be
flush with the ground, Fleisher said. ``The periderm is much
tougher in this area, so it won't deteriorate as fast from dog
urine,'' he said. Bark higher up is less resistant.
</P>
<P>
   But such measures just delay a tree's demise if it is constantly
watered by dogs. So keep them in the street to do that.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds ``unnatural,'' cities are unnatural places.
Remember how awful the streets were before owners were required to
clean up after their pets?
</P>
<P>
   Fleisher's garden crew is also experimenting with a minty spray
that is supposed to repel dogs from plants. In their own version of
a controlled experiment, they are spraying some trees with the mint
mixture and others just with water. The sprayers aren't supposed to
know which is which, but the minty smell is unmistakable. It's
quite attractive. If I were a dog I'd go toward those trees.
Fleisher's crew isn't waiting with bated breath, but they'll try
anything once.
</P>
<P>
   You get the picture. You can love Fido and a linden, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
