<HEADER>
A7097 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV07-B     05-05 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV07-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING WITH ROBIN HOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 07, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the only column I am truly embarrassed to have written.
(That I can remember, that is; it is always possible that I have
repressed the memory of others.) Last winter the pioneering Harvard
Pilgrim Health Care health maintainence organization was in crisis.
A couple hundred thousand dollars were required to tide it over
until higher fees kicked in. Who besides the state of Massachusetts
could provide the financing?
</P>
<P>
   Why not Harvard? I wrote. Why not the institution whose name was
on the door, which 30 years had blown life into the noble
experiment? Just a sliver of its $14 billion endowment could back a
credit guarantee that would prevent irreperable harm to the
venerable plan.
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion wasn't as farfetched as it sounded, I argued
privately to friends. The impulse at Harvard to do good was
powerful. And sure enough, the next day, the Globe on its front
page headlined, ``Harvard may end millions to aid HMO. Proposed
investment would keep university's namesake nonprofit.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a couple of days, however, cooler heads at Harvard's
headquarters in Massachusetts Hall prevailed. Whatever offer had
been broached had been rescinded, leaving a testy and confused
Massachusetts Attorney General Thomas Reilly with no alternative
but to ``cram down'' the health plan's debt, subordinating its debt
and sticking it mildly to its bondholders. The plan survived.
</P>
<P>
   So what was wrong with what I wrote? Just this: There are many
reasons for the size of Harvard's enormous war chest. Most of them
have to do with the competition among universities for the best
students; a large endowment makes possible bigger student
subsidies, which attracts better students. Explaining odd markets
like this one is a big part of my job.
</P>
<P>
   And the fact is that when you've got $14 billion in the bank,
it's a mighty slippery slope if you start responding to public
pleas, demands, threats and all other sorts of requests for help.
Cave in and pretty soon every two-bit Robin Hood in the neigborhood
will have a sword at your ribs.
</P>
<P>
   That was the point last week, when a band of ruffians with a lot
more clout than me attempted to stick up Harvard and came away, if
not empty handed, then with something other than they had sought.
</P>
<P>
   My colleague Alex Beam calls Cambridge the Sixteenth Republic.
The first fifteen belonged to the former Soviet Union, he says.
``The FSU is no longer, but the Sixteenth Republic lives.''
</P>
<P>
   In fairness Cambridge has had some notable successes in recent
years. After it was forced to junk its rent control ordinance, it
set a national standard in building affordable housing, mainly
through the mechanism of inclusionary zoning. But Beam is right.
Despite its strong city manager form of government, the city's
system of proportional voting insures that tightly organized
interst groups can play a larger-than-usual role in politics, and
in Cambridge that means Lefties.
</P>
<P>
   Boom times have made the city council loopier than ever. Though
it sits astride several major highway arteries, the city has
attempted to ban truck traffic after dark. After four years and
four architects, the councillors have been unable to site a new
public library. A recent campaign against mutual savings bank
conversions spawned charges of of ``attempted nationalization.''
</P>
<P>
   Last fall's election brought three new councillors to the
nine-memmber board. Two in particular, Jim Braude and Marjorie
Decker, have taken on a new high-profile foe: Harvard University.
Decker is a newcomer to elective politics, but Braude, 50, has had
a long career as union organizer and community activist. As
director of the Tax Equity Alliance for Massachusetts for many
years he unsuccessfully sought passage of a state-wide progressive
income tax. In 1986 his wife Kristine Rondeau led a successul
campaign to unionize Harvard's clerical workers.
</P>
<P>
   Braude and Decker immediately put their weight behind a campaign
to force Harvard to pay a ``living wage'' _ a $10 minimum wage
(already paid to its workers by the city of Cambridge),
substantially above the federally-mandated minimum wage $6 an hour,
which is slated to rise to $6.75 next year. Their tactic has been
to deny the university building permits. ``If Harvard wants to
build a new building and comes to the city council, all nine of us
will say, `Implement a living wage and we'll talk,''' he said
recently, according the the Harvard Crimson. ``Many of us would
feel it hard to approve some beautiful new building when somebody
working in it is making $8 or $9 an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus plans for development are at a standstill: for a new art
museum that Harvard wants to build on the banks of the Charles
River; for a a new center for government and international studies
on the opposite edge of the campus.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Harvard made its response: a blue-ribbon committee
recommended an extensive effort to better the lot of workers at the
law end of the university's pay scale _ especially the 372 persons,
three percent of the workplace, who make less than $10 an hour _
but not through a big boost in the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the committee recommended, Harvard should broaden its
education and training programs (especially its language and
literacy coaching); extend subsidized health care benefits to every
employee working more than 16 hours a week; and insist that outside
contractors to the university do the the same. (A couple of deans
argued that the contractor provision would cost the university too
much.)
</P>
<P>
   Harvard clearly intended the plan to be a national model for
improving the lives of low-wage workers. Equally clearly, it
intended to demonstrate that it wouldn't be held hostage by
shakedown-minded politicians. In rolling out its proposal, it
signalled its intention to fight Cambridge City Hall in a highly
public manner.
</P>
<P>
   The ``living wage'' isn't a foolish idea, especially when
applied to governmenmt organizations. The situation of the working
poor should be a subject of far greater national concern than it
is. But when wages controls are extended to non-profit institions
and firms operating in open markets, they begin to have serious
perverse effects. Harvard is right to refuse to deal, even though
it easily can afford to pay. In fact, the benefits recommended by
the committee almost certainly will cost far more than knuckling
under to the wage demand would have.
</P>
<P>
   The ``living wage'' plan won't go away. Indeed, a rally is
scheduled for Harvard's big arts festival Saturday, led by city
councilors Braude and Decker and Cambridge homeboys Ben Affleck and
Matt Damon, the movie actors. But the students who throng to the
the bullhorns must have something else in mind as well; they should
claim victory, be proud of themselves and go study for finals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
