<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY FACES WIZARDS IN SHOWDOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The Western Division is now Major League
Soccer's group of death for one reason: the Kansas City Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   K.C. is tops in most everything best record (6-0-1, 19 points),
most goals (17) and fewest goals allowed (4).
</P>
<P>
   Tonight the Wizards can really stamp themselves as contenders
when they visit the Rose Bowl to face the Los Angeles Galaxy
(5-0-2, 17 points), MLS' only other unbeaten team.
</P>
<P>
   The Wizards, 8-24 a year ago, made two key acquisitions in
Danish striker Miklos Molnar and defender Peter Vermes. The rebirth
of goalkeeper Tony Meola has bumped them up another level.
Suddenly, K.C. sounds as dangerous as D.C.
</P>
<P>
   There are other factors. Preki (36) and Mo Johnston (37) are
playing with renewed energy, and coach Bob Gansler, the 1990 U.S.
National team coach who took our troops to the World Cup in Italy,
has everyone believing the best is yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're happy about what has transpired so far,''
said Gansler. ``We feel that we are for real. I think the
combination of veterans and good young players are going about
their business in good fashion. How real are we? Only time will
tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Vermes, acquired from Colorado, said Kansas City is only showing
glimpses of what it's capable of.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of room to grow,'' he said. ``No doubt this game
will be a huge challenge, but the amazing thing for our team is
that we've come together as quickly as we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is glowing at the Wizards' amazing turnaround,
especially Galaxy defender Danny Pena.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people may be surprised with K.C.'s start, but I'm
not,'' said Pena. ``They have always been a good team on paper, but
now they've got a coach they believe in, a system they believe in
and they're believing in each other. When all of that happens it
makes for a great formula for success.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy defender Greg Vanney said he always believed the Wizards
had the players to contend.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a team that was always good but maybe lacked
leadership,'' said Vanney. ``Something was always missing from that
organization but now they have it. Tony is having a great season,
Vermes in solid in the back, Molnar has provided a lift and the
workrate of Johnston and other guys has turned their franchise
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this has done is change the outlook of our division. This
isn't only a battle of undefeated teams, it's a battle to stay on
top of your division.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy leads the overall series with K.C. 9-7, but each
match is usually a struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure why they give us trouble,'' said Galaxy defender
Robin Fraser. ``It's something about the individual match-ups that
we have. They've always been a very tough team to play against;
maybe it's the styles. It's going to be even more difficult now,
based on the players they have brought in.''
</P>
<P>
   Molnar was the biggest acquisition. He was named the MLS player
of the month for April after registering 11 points. Molnar missed
K.C.'s last match, a 5-0 victory over Colorado, because of an ankle
strain.
</P>
<P>
   He is questionable again tonight, but Schmid said K.C. will be
tough with or without him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Molnar doesn't play, they've got (Alex) Bunbury and (Gary)
Glasgow, two others guys with speed,'' said Schmid. ``It doesn't
change how they play because they have replaceable items.''
</P>
</TEXT>
