<HEADLINE>
STUDY CITES BRAIN DAMAGE FROM ROLLER COASTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amid an explosion this year of gargantuan roller
coasters, including several that set records for speed and
gravitational force, a growing number of passengers are being
diagnosed with severe brain injuries after being whipped through
the most adventurous rides.
</P>
<P>
   At least 18 incidents of closed-head injury have occurred since
1995, according to one pathologist monitoring the trend. And a
study released this week by Representative Edward J. Markey
(D-Mass.) found that of more than a dozen cases documented in the
past decade, almost all patients suffered brain injury from the
sheer force of the ride, not from being hit in the head by a loose
object.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are of particular concern to doctors this season,
as more than 100 million Americans are expected to visit amusement
parks now featuring a new generation of extreme rides. At Six Flags
New England, which opened in Agawam, Mass. Friday, one ``thrill
ride'' boasts speeds of up to 80 miles per hour _ the
fourth-fastest in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the country, new roller coasters have gravitational
forces, or G-forces, greater than what an astronaut experiences
during liftoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Newton's laws of physics,'' said Dr. Pete Speth, a
forensic pathologist in Wenonah, N.J., who is studying the
neurological impact of roller-coaster rides. ``If the head is
suddenly stopped, the brain will keep moving ... And as they
increase the rates of acceleration on the rides, they are reaching
the limit of (people's) endurance.''
</P>
<P>
   What is most troubling to consumer advocates is the absence of
any federal or state oversight. No rules govern the G-force of a
roller coaster; in 14 states, including Massachusetts, amusement
parks are not subject to any federal or state inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials insist they sufficiently regulate themselves.
In most cases, amusement parks and roller coasters are inspected by
insurance companies, who have a serious financial stake in making
sure all rides and activities are safe. Additionally, officials
say, better technology has made rides far safer than they were in
1981, when Congress approved a Reagan initiative to abolish the
federal role in amusement park safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress looked at this issue 20 years ago and decided there
was nothing they could do to improve on the outstanding record of
this industry,'' said John Graff, president of the International
Association of Amusement Parks and Attractions, a trade group of
some 450 theme parks. ``The truth is that modern technology has
made our rides much safer than they were years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, about 9,200 theme park accidents last year landed
park-goers in the emergency room, according to the Consumer Product
Safety Commission.
</P>
<P>
   That does not include passengers who stepped off roller coasters
with a headache, only to discover weeks later they had suffered
brain damage during the ride.
</P>
<P>
   Medical experts are not sure how many such head trauma cases
exist, in part because they have been treated in isolation for so
long. In the study he released this week, Markey, who is pushing
for federal regulation of amusement parks, sought to compile more
than a dozen medical journal articles about roller coaster-induced
brain damage in order to demonstrate what he believes is a
``growing epidemic.''
</P>
<P>
   The study, completed by the National Institutes of Health, found
that the number of detected brain injury cases surged in the 1990s.
While there was only one incident in 1979, and one in 1991, there
have been a total of 13 documented incidents in the years since _
during the same years that amusement parks began ``constructing
roller coasters that move at supersonic speeds,'' Markey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question, the frequency of these reported brain
injuries is accelerating,'' said Markey, a Malden Democrat.
``They're going 90 miles an hour now. The G-forces are above five,
which is greater than what an astronaut is subjected to on takeoff
of a shuttle mission.''
</P>
<P>
   In one case, a 31-year-old dance teacher suffered a severe
headache and vomiting after riding ``Space Mountain'' at the
Disneyland park outside Paris. She was diagnosed as suffering from
``dissection,'' in which arteries in her brain were split. In
another case, a 64-year-old man was diagnosed with a subdural
hematoma, or a clot inside the layers of the lining of the brain,
after riding on a roller coaster with six upside-down loops.
</P>
<P>
   Taken against the hundreds of millions of visitors to amusement
parks each year, some industry officials said the several dozen or
so head injuries should be taken seriously but not blown out of
proportion.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Nauser, an official at Six Flags, said: ``Sixteen cases,
I don't really think that's in the realm of what we do every season
at our parks ... Our coasters travel the equivalent of 75 orbits
around the Earth each season. And they are all safe rides.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
