u s BC-FBN-HEARST-SURGERY050     05-05 0315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HEARST-SURGERY0506-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Key surgery for Hearst today
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ San Francisco 49ers running back Garrison Hearst will
have surgery today on his left leg, a procedure doctors hope will
save the former Georgia star's NFL career.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst, from Lincolnton, missed all of last season after
breaking his left ankle in an NFC playoff game against the Falcons
in the Georgia Dome on Jan. 9, 1999. His left leg suffers poor
blood flow, which makes the bones in his foot susceptible to
necrosis. The same type of bone deterioration developed in running
back Bo Jackson's hip after an injury and forced him to retire from
football.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst, Georgia's second all-time leading rusher, will be
operated on in Seattle. Orthopedic specialist Pierce Scranton and
Michael Dillingham, the 49ers' team physican, will perform the
procedure. Doctors will drill holes in Hearst's lower leg and plug
the holes with cartilage from his knee. The procedure is designed
to generate blood flow and aid healing in the affected area.
</P>
<P>
   Dillingham said last month that Hearst had a ``70-percent
chance'' of returning this season if he underwent the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm assuming that's still holding true,'' said Pat Dye Jr.,
Hearst's Atlanta-based agent.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst, 5 feet 11 and 215 pounds, set a San Francisco team
record with a career-high 1,570 rushing yards in 1998. He was
selected to the Pro Bowl for the first time in his career but
didn't play after he was injured in the playoffs. A former
first-round draft pick of the Arizona Cardinals in 1993, Hearst
suffered a season-ending knee injury as a rookie and missed half of
the 1994 season. He was named the NFL's Comeback Player of the Year
in 1995, when he rushed 1,070 yards for the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
