<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGGIE LEWIS JURY SEEKS INSTRUCTIONS FROM JUDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After a third full day of deliberations -- and a round
of feverish late-day negotiations among lawyers for both sides --
the jury in the Reggie Lewis medical malpractice retrial failed to
reach a verdict Friday and will return Monday for further
instructions from Judge Thayer Fremont-Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 jurors, looking weary and frustrated, filed into the
courtroom at about 5 p.m., nearly 90 minutes after they had sent a
note to the judge, who did not disclose its contents.
</P>
<P>
   While the note was not read publicly, the lawyers were shown it,
prompting intense and at times animated group discussions in the
courthouse corridor among lawyers for Donna Harris-Lewis and Dr.
Gilbert H. Mudge Jr., as well as representatives from Risk
Management Foundation, which insures Mudge and all
Harvard-affiliated doctors and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis, Lewis's widow, has accused Mudge, Lewis's chief
cardiologist, of failing to diagnose her late husband with the
heart condition that caused the Celtics star's July 1993 death.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge heads the cardiac transplantation unit at Brigham and
Women's Hospital, a Harvard-affiliated institution.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, a crush of news photographers crowded the hallway
to film the huddled attorneys, who were gathered in a small circle
at the far end of the corridor. The gathering spurred heated
speculation that settlement talks may be in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, two months after an earlier jury deadlocked over
whether Mudge's treatment of Lewis was negligent, a source close to
the case told the Globe that Harris-Lewis's lawyers had offered to
settle the case for no more than $5 million -- the ceiling on
Mudge's malpractice insurance coverage -- but that the offer had
been rejected. Mudge's coverage is known as a ``wasting'' policy,
meaning that it is being steadily depleted to pay for the lawyers
defending him.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the source said that a major sticking point was
Risk Management's refusal to settle.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, after lawyers for both sides met privately with
Fremont-Smith in his chambers, the jury was brought into the
courtroom and told by Fremont-Smith to return Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The jury, which began deliberating Tuesday after hearing more
than four weeks of testimony, has now spent more than 20 hours
discussing the case. The panel includes ten women, six men.
</P>
<P>
   As the deliberations grind on, there have been indications of
disagreement among the jurors. On Thursday, after deliberating for
two full days, jurors sent a note to Fremont-Smith saying that,
``The jury is at a point where nothing more productive will occur
today. It might be good to cool off overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   To reach a verdict, 13 of 16 jurors must be in agreement. They
must consider eight separate questions, including whether Mudge was
negligent in his care of Lewis, and, if so, whether that negligence
substantially contributed to his death. If Mudge's negligence is
found to have contributed to Lewis's death, jurors must determine
how much his family should be compensated.
</P>
<P>
   In the first trial last year, 15 jurors deliberated for six days
before announcing that they were hopelessly deadlocked, resulting
in a hung jury. After a mistrial was declared, one of the jurors
later told the Globe that nine of the 15 jurors had concluded on a
fourth and final ballot that Mudge was not negligent in his care of
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   If the jurors in the retrial were to announce that they had
reached an impasse, Fremont-Smith is obligated to deliver
additional instructions, the so-called dynamite charge, aimed at
helping them reach a verdict.
</P>
<P>
   It is also possible for the jury to agree on some questions but
deadlock on others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 1939EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
