<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7108 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-COURTING-BOUTIQUES-$A     05-05 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURTING-BOUTIQUES-$ADV07-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOWER MAN GOES A COURTIN' CHARITY BALL CHAIRMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, May 7) 
 By MONIQUE P. YAZIGI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An unsuspecting woman received a bouquet of flowers
recently at her Fifth Avenue home. Set in a silver-plated urn, the
$350 arrangement was lush with romantic pink roses, Italian
poppies, deep-purple sweet peas, calla lilies and a card that read,
``We'd be a good match.''
</P>
<P>
   Her secret admirer? A floral designer named David Beahm, whose
intentions were not particularly romantic. The object of his
attentions is a member of the organizing committee for a fall
fund-raising gala for the Metropolitan Opera, with the unofficial
position of flower chairwoman: she picks the florist who picks the
flowers.
</P>
<P>
   The unsolicited arrangement was ``a courting bouquet,'' Beahm
explained. He sent it in hopes of winning the account to provide
flowers for a party that annually attracts some of New York's
richest and swellest, names like Kissinger, Kravis and Bass. (He
did not want to reveal the woman's name, out of fear that his
competitors would court her as well.)
</P>
<P>
   Beahm sends up to five courting bouquets a week this time of
year, with a retail value of $250 to $400 each, to women all over
the city who are immersed in the charity social circuit and are
selecting the decor for fall benefits. Doing flowers for the
$1,000-a-plate dinners can make the career of an ambitious florist.
Centerpieces that provoke oohs and ahhs among the guests can lead
to contracts to provide arrangements at extravagant society
weddings and Park Avenue dinner parties, and to fill the floral
needs of hostesses like Carroll Petrie, who spends up to $20,000 a
week in the summer filling her Southampton house with Casablanca
lilies and white mixed blooms.
</P>
<P>
   The ``flower chairs'' and those who advise them are the keys to
this lucrative business, and they are courted in ways that go well
beyond sending a free bouquet. Four florists discussed how, to win
these women's favor, they provide flowers at discounts of 50 to 75
percent for the private needs of some of the city's wealthiest and
most socially active hostesses. The largesse includes fresh flowers
sent weekly to the women's homes, bouquets that they send to
friends as thank-yous for dinner invitations and reductions of tens
of thousands of dollars from the going price for their daughters'
weddings.
</P>
<P>
   The deep discounts are little known outside the world of the
ultrasocial. ``It's simply the way most of my friends keep fresh
flowers in their houses year round,'' said Arlene Dahl, an actress
who can be seen at many a Park Avenue dinner party. ``It's like
buying wholesale.''
</P>
<P>
   Dahl, who chooses the decor for the Oscar party for New York
members of the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences and for
annual galas by the Pearl S. Buck Foundation and the New York
Cancer Society, said that at this time of year, her apartment is
abloom with courting bouquets. She considers it an innocuous form
of petty bribery, she said, adding, ``It's in the course of
business.''
</P>
<P>
   She has not chosen florists for public events as a result of
price breaks for her personal flowers, she said, but she knows
others who do. In general, women who receive personal discounts say
they see nothing unethical in choosing a florist for a public
fund-raiser and receiving discounts for one's personal use.
</P>
<P>
   The practice is related to the quiet but widespread convention
that allows some of New York's best-dressed, most socially visible
women, who are often most able to pay full price, to receive
clothes free from designers, or have their homes furnished at a
deep discount. ``Doing an apartment for free or at `a special
price' is the only way for some newcomers to get the caliber of
clients on their roster,'' said Mario Buatta, the interior
decorator. ``These women kind of sponsor you.''
</P>
<P>
   Polly Onet, a party planner with wide experience among the beau
monde, agreed. ``That's New York,'' she said. ``Look at the girls
we know who get all these cut-rate designer clothes, and they are
loaded and they don't pay a dime, for clothes or jewelry. We see
them every night, and they don't even dry-clean the clothes before
they bring them back to the designer, and the designer doesn't care
_ he is just happy that they are wearing the clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharyn Mann, another object of Beahm's attention, is a
well-connected social figure with homes in Manhattan and Quogue,
which she likes to keep well appointed with fresh blooms. ``Flowers
are your calling card,'' she said. ``They represent you and your
taste. Flowers are like angels blessing the room.''
</P>
<P>
   One day recently, Mann was showing Beahm pictures of a 28-acre
island she and her husband, Stephen, an investment banker, had
bought in Vero Beach, Fla. Sitting on the down-filled damask couch
in the family room of her Fifth Avenue duplex, Mann said, ``David
is going to see the property before my husband.'' (Mann had
approved the purchase sight unseen.) She turned to Beahm to say,
``We must go to Vero Beach soon.'' Beahm agreed. With a blush on
his cheeks and glee in his voice, he said, ``I already have ideas
of what we're going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Beahm had that week filled Mann's living room overlooking
Central Park with more than $600 worth of Kwanzan cherry blossoms
and lilacs, at no cost. Mann, who was chairwoman of the Food
Allergy Ball at the Plaza in December, hired him to do the flowers
for the 70 tables at the event, which raised more than $2.2 million
for charity. Mann introduced him to Robert F. Kennedy Jr., Valerie
Zilkha, Fe Fendi, Iris Love and CeCe Kieselstein-Cord.
</P>
<P>
   ``My head was spinning with all the contacts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you make the right people happy and then meet the right
people, that hopefully is going to make the discount worthwhile,''
he added. By the same logic, he said, he did the gala flowers for
$20,000, with the cost covered by an anonymous sponsor, though the
job was really worth more than $80,000.
</P>
<P>
   Mann said it is natural for an up-and-coming florist to offer a
discounted fee for a high-profile assignment like her gala. ``He
was just starting, unknown in New York, so it was understood if he
was good to me, I in turn would be good to him by introducing him
to everyone I know,'' she said. ``I purposefully looked for someone
just starting. Other people who are established and well known
don't try that hard.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the flowers he provides for little or nothing for her
apartment, she denied using her position with the gala for personal
gain. ``I have never asked for anything personally,'' she said.
``Whatever David charges, we pay the bill.'' Even if that bill is
sometimes nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Another charity woman, who receives about $300 worth of peonies
and roses for her home each week, paying only about $100, also
defended the practice. ``Look, what's wrong with receiving
discounted flowers at home?'' she said, sipping a cocktail during a
``tailgate party'' at the New York Auto Show to benefit the East
Side Settlement House last month. This woman is not a flower
chairwoman, but she has many prominent friends. ``We are giving
these boys a big opportunity,'' she said, ``and you know, important
people come to my home and see what they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Many florists say they refuse to court socialites, either with
the occasional sample arrangement or with more valuable long-term
discounts. ``I know it goes on,'' said Helena Lehane, a floral
designer who places arrangements every week in the homes of several
Upper East Side billionaires. ``I think integrity has something to
do with it. I have preferred over my career not to court.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Those who do court justify it as good business sense. Gaige
Clark, a co-owner of Spruce, whose clients include the model Amber
Valletta and the actress Julianne Moore, said, ``I do give special
discounts to special clients.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing business with them has helped our name get out there,
considering who they are sending their flowers to: people in
fashion, people in the film industry,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Some florists never have to weigh the ethical or economic
issues, because they are already so busy they don't have to offer
discounts. Two designers, Robert Isabell and Philip Baloun, have
long had a near duopoly on society parties and benefits, and both
deny courting clients with personal discounts. In fact, hostesses
sometimes grumble about their high prices. Donna Harvey, a senior
account manager at George Trescher Associates, which organizes
charity fund-raisers, said it was hard to stay within a budget when
planning a party with one of the top-tier florists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very talented, but many times we have to look
elsewhere for someone who is eager for the business,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren Veronis, another socialite involved in the charity world,
is heavily courted by up-and-coming florists. ``If you get a nod
from Lauren Veronis, you're in for the long haul,'' one florist
said.
</P>
<P>
   Veronis, who was chairwoman this spring of a gala celebrating
the 30th anniversary of Zubin Mehta's directorship of the Israel
Philharmonic and a buffet dinner at the Four Seasons for the
Irvington Institute for Immunological Research, is flattered by the
sentiment. For both events, Veronis broke with the florist she has
long favored, Isabell. ``We used Robert for years, and he was
wonderful,'' she said. ``But it was time to move on and give the
up-and-coming a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   For both events she chose David Tutera, a party planner in
Mamaroneck who, she said, has not given her any discounts for
personal flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The understanding always is when they do a big charity that
there is no budget for the party,'' she said. ``We want all of our
proceeds to go to the basic research, so we're delighted to provide
the audience for their work to give them big exposure. But in
return they have to work below cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Tutera, whose clients include Clarissa Bronfman, several Tisch
family members and Iris Cantor, said: ``I don't exactly give them
financial discounts. I give them more attention and hand-holding.
Personally, I'm totally with them every step of the way, and I make
sure they get the best flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know in the long run what I will receive if I give them a
lot of attention. I know who is on their guest list. The secret to
being successful in the society world in New York is all word of
mouth, and I know what they can do for me if I give them a better
product for a little less.''
</P>
<P>
   Another up-and-coming florist who does give Veronis a price
break is Lisa Marie McWilliams, who said she provides flowers for
the Veronis homes in New York and Southampton more than 40 times a
year, for 40 percent less than the going rate. McWilliams said she
is so grateful for the exposure her work receives because she is
Veronis' florist that she would not think of charging more.
Moreover, it is her way of repaying Veronis for encouraging her to
leave a previous employer and go into business on her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I owe so much to her,'' said McWilliams, who has not handled
any of the charity accounts Veronis oversees, but hopes to in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Veronis said she had never asked McWilliams for a discount, and
seemed unaware she was receiving one. ``Whenever I use anyone
personally, I have never received a reduction or asked for one,''
she said. ``It would be inappropriate to expect something like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The hand-holding that florists provide is no small thing on the
social circuit. Like fashion designers, interior designers and even
some hairstylists, florists have gone from being members of a
service class to escorts and dinner-party guests in some of the
swankest company. At a gala for the Horticultural Society of New
York on Tuesday, where the city's new and old society converged
around 40 tables set with flowers by 48 designers, Suzette de
Marigny Smith, a chairwoman of the event, described ``the very
special relationship'' some people have with florists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to be little geniuses,'' she said. ``They have to
know more about you than your dressmaker and your interior
decorator and your caterer.''
</P>
<P>
   De Marigny Smith, who was wearing a Sander Witlin gold lame
dress with hand-painted irises and waving a gold wand, said,
referring to some of the florists, ``They are very amusing and
attractive people, and they are good conversationalists, and
they're just fun to have at parties _ like flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   Another coveted assignment for floral designers is the society
wedding. Some admit that they are willing to offer huge discounts
on jobs worth tens of thousands of dollars to have their work seen
at its most extravagant by the right crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Joanne de Guardiola, an interior designer who takes an important
part in prominent charities like the Society of Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center and the New York Botanical Garden
(she is fashion chairwoman of the garden's June gala), could have
hired a name-brand florist for the wedding of her stepdaughter,
Jeanne de Guardiola, next month. Instead, she is using McWilliams.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be very big for me,'' McWilliams said. ``There will
be a lot of important people there who could very well recommend me
for the next step, the charity parties.'' She said she will charge
the family $50,000 to $75,000, less than half what a comparable job
for another wedding would cost.
</P>
<P>
   McWilliams, who speaks to Joanne de Guardiola every week, is
planning a white and cobalt theme with lots of peonies for the
wedding, which will be in Southampton and will be attended by 400.
</P>
<P>
   Like many florists in her position, she must weigh how long she
can continue in business without making a profit on some of her
biggest jobs.
</P>
<P>
   For Beahm, who said he lives hand to mouth despite consorting
with the rich and powerful, the flower business is a dicey one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, they'll spend as little as they can get away
with,'' he said, referring to the women who ask him to send
bouquets to friends as thank-yous for a dinner party or to mark a
birthday. ``The minimum I'll let someone get away with paying is
$50, and yet they'll get a $250 bouquet. It's killing me. I have to
remind these ladies all the time that I'm not the charity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
