<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7112 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HEDGE-FUNDS-NYT &LR;      05-05 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEDGE-FUNDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEDGE FUND INDUSTRY GROWS, BUT BIG IS NO LONGER GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   By DANNY HAKIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Money managers George Soros and Julian H. Robertson Jr., who
once rattled world financial markets with mere hints of their
actions, have lost much of their punch. But hedge funds, the
investment vehicles for the wealthy that these prominent investors
epitomized, are by no means on the ropes.
</P>
<P>
   Though comprehensive figures are unavailable, the unregulated
hedge fund industry continues to grow. Domestic and offshore hedge
fund assets grew 23 percent to $362 billion in 1999, according to
TASS Research, a Rye., N.Y., firm that advises hedge fund clients.
Figures provided by the Hennessee Group, a New York firm that
tracks hedge funds and consults with their clients, indicate that
the industry grew by 47 percent last year to $324 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the portion of the hedge fund industry known as
``macro'' funds has seen its role greatly diminished. These are
funds like Long-Term Capital, which was rescued by a group of big
financial firms in 1998, and those run by Soros and Robertson,
which have used complex financial strategies to make large,
leveraged bets on the direction of global currency, bond and equity
markets.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of 1996, macro funds accounted for roughly 30 percent
of all hedge fund assets, making them by far the largest single
category, according to a Hennessee Group report. By the end of last
year, they had dwindled to about 7.2 percent of hedge fund assets.
Because of the recent demise of Robertson's Tiger Management and
the turmoil of the Soros family of funds, the portion in macro
funds will probably be smaller still at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   The macro funds have been eclipsed by a core of smaller, more
nimble funds that focus on specific sectors, or larger firms that
offer collections of smaller funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the next wave,'' said Philip W. Treick, who managed
two mutual funds for the insurer Transamerica to top performances
in 1998 before departing to co-found his own hedge fund group last
year. ``It is becoming absolutely apparent that big is not good in
hedge funds.''
</P>
<P>
   The new managers are more likely to be stock pickers than the
superstars of the past. ``There is a change in the industry,'' said
Andrew J. Kessler, who co-founded the $500 million Silicon Valley
hedge fund Velocity Partners in 1996. ``We don't do macro bets. I
don't even know how to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pequot Capital, a secretive investment management firm based in
Westport, Conn., that oversees $10 billion to $12 billion in more
than 18 funds, avoids macro strategies and is widely considered the
largest hedge fund manager after Soros' group, which has shrunk
considerably.
</P>
<P>
   In a London press conference this week, Soros said he thought
investors might withdraw as much as $3 billion from his $14.2
billion hedge fund empire. After incurring significant losses this
year, Soros' top two lieutenants announced a week earlier that they
were departing Soros Fund Management. Their exit came just three
weeks after the industry's other most prominent investor,
Robertson, said he was dismantling his Tiger Management investment
company.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Soros and Robertson each presided over hedge fund
empires with assets of more than $20 billion, and their sway over
markets was amplified by their use of leverage and their
reputations. Soros was nicknamed `'the man who broke the pound''
after making a $10 billion bet against the British pound in 1992
that brought him a profit of at least $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Despite impressive long-term records, Soros and Robertson could
not keep up the pace the last two years. Besides failed bets on the
direction of currency prices like the euro, both firms were burned
by technology stocks and their transforming effects on the markets,
though in different ways. Robertson missed out largely because he
avoided technology stocks. Stanley F. Druckenmiller, who managed
Soros' flagship $8.2 billion Quantum Fund, made a significant move
into technology stocks in the middle of last year. But his
technology exposure during April's market woes led to a 22 percent
decline in the fund's performance this year, he said last week.
</P>
<P>
   The losses prompted Soros, in a letter to his shareholders, to
say that ``a large hedge fund like Quantum Fund is no longer the
best way to manage money.'' He plans to remodel Quantum as a more
conservative fund called Quantum Endowment.
</P>
<P>
   Hedge fund clients now prefer funds that use less leverage, or
borrowed money, than Soros was known for, according to B. Scott
Reid, who oversees four hedge funds for the Auda Group, a New York
firm that manages $1.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want risk controls, reduced leverage and more
transparency,'' Reid says. ``They don't simply want to know if
they're making money or losing it; they want to know how it's
made.''
</P>
<P>
   The valuation models at the big firms are also being questioned.
Increasing volatility in the markets, and the wide-eyed enthusiasm
for the next new thing, has made traditional methods of valuation
less profitable of late. As the kick-the-tires investor Warren E.
Buffett notably quipped after a disappointing 1998, he would have
done better if he had gone to the movies instead of the office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fundamental analysis says value stocks should be bought and
tech stocks sold, but that's not what was happening,'' says Charles
J. Gradante, chief investment strategist at the Hennessee Group.
Gradante believes certain macro strategies continue to succeed, but
that the rules of the game have changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who were reading the tape _ in terms of currency
trends, bond market trends and stock market trends _ were making
money,'' he said. ``The people that were reading balance sheets and
income statements were losing money.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson does not expect fundamental analysis to be forever out
of fashion. ``The market goes through these periods of
irrationality, where the worst stocks do best,'' he said last week.
``We've been in a period of irrationality for such a long time that
it hurts a rational strategy. You have a group of irrational
investors carrying the market.''
</P>
<P>
   As Soros was describing his difficulties last week, Robertson
was preparing to take his family snorkeling at the Great Barrier
Reef in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of great young people coming along,'' he said.
``It's their time to be in the sun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
