<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A CROWDED FIELD, FUSAICHI PEGASUS STANDS OUT
</HEADLINE>
  By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ America's oldest racing traditions surrounded
19 of the world's best 3-year-old thoroughbreds Friday on the eve
of the 126th Kentucky Derby with its deep cast primed to answer the
question: Is Fusaichi Pegasus a wonder horse, or will he be
thwarted by the dense traffic in the race and the 150,000 clamorous
fans watching it?
</P>
<P>
   One answer was ventured Friday by D. Wayne Lukas, who has
entered three horses in the Derby and has won with four others,
including Charismatic last year. He considered the twists of Derby
fortunes, and said, ``It's just a matter of letting the race
unfold.''
</P>
<P>
   He meant the uncertainties of racing 1 1/4 miles with a field of
19 colts struggling to gain favorable position for the long drive
down the homestretch, which measures 1,234{ feet from the final
turn to the finish line at Churchill Downs. And most of the field
will be trying to catch Fusaichi Pegasus, the son of Mr. Prospector
who was bought for $4 million as a yearling and comes into the
Derby as either a superhorse or a potential victim of
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think,'' Lukas added, sounding like a basketball coach,
``too many times we get all caught up in strategy, and these
Hollywood scripts don't play out. Sometimes when you've got good
players, it is better not to coach them.''
</P>
<P>
   The weather was mild, almost summery, and the track was fast as
Derby Day neared. Most racing analysts seemed to agree that this
was the most tightly matched bunch of horses in years: it includes
champions from the United States, Britain and the Middle East. But
the favorite was still Fusaichi Pegasus, owned by the Japanese
venture capitalist Fusao Sekiguchi, who arrived at his horse's Barn
41 Friday morning while his trainer, Neil Drysdale, was sending the
colt through a trot of 1 1/4 miles followed by a gallop of 1 1/4
miles.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale, an Englishman who was elected to racing's Hall of Fame
this week, continued to protect his star against the growing furor
at Churchill Downs as well as the warming weather. Aside from the
fact that no favorite has won since Spectacular Bid in 1979,
Drysdale's chief problem seemed to be the balky temperament of
Fusaichi Pegasus, who might be inflamed by both the weather and the
clamor. In fact, Drysdale said his last-minute training plans for
introducing his horses to the outdoor paddock would be influenced
by the heat of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to depend on the weather,'' he said. ``It was
pretty sticky yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   At Barn 42 next door, Todd Pletcher sent his fleet of four Derby
horses through their final dress rehearsals of about 1 1/4 miles,
then said, ``They're all doing great.'' Pletcher, 36, a former
assistant to Lukas, was asked whether his speed horse More Than
Ready could last 10 furlongs one month after he ran nine in the
Blue Grass Stakes and lost to High Yield by a head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was questioned about his ability to go a mile-and-an-eighth
before the Blue Grass,'' he replied. ``And now, of course, his
ability to go 10 furlongs is in question. Then the Belmont is 12
furlongs, and that will be a question, too. But anyone who says
they know their horse can go that far is kidding themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Each horse in the race will move one stall to the inside because
of the withdrawal of Globalize, who was first in the Turfway Park
Spiral and second in Keeneland's Lexington. The horse was scratched
after he was kicked by his stable pony while leaving the track
Thursday after exercising. He had held the No. 1 post position,
which now goes to last year's juvenile champion, Anees.
</P>
<P>
   The Deputy, winner of the Santa Anita Derby, will move from his
No. 11 slot to No. 10, but will still be loaded in the gate first
with Anees. Under the double-loading system, Nos. 1 and 10 are
loaded at the same time, then No. 2 (Aptitude) and No. 11 (China
Visit).
</P>
<P>
   The Deputy was galloped 1 1/4 miles Friday morning for his final
exercise, and will not go to the track the day of the race,
according to his trainer, Jenine Sahadi. She is the 10th woman to
saddle a Derby starter and probably has the best chance so far of
becoming the first to win. Shelly Riley finished second with Casual
Lies in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The international flavor of the Derby will be upheld by China
Visit and Curule, both owned by Sheik Mohammed al-Maktoum of Dubai,
who watched his colts cantering Friday morning. He was asked about
the fact that China Visit had only two races on his record, and
Curule four. But he repeated his abiding interest in winning the
Kentucky Derby, and said: ``We can win from Dubai, and we will do
it. They will not have any prep races here. From my home, which is
2 kilometers from the training center, I can see my horses. I can't
do that if they are over here.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert, who won the Derby in 1997 with Silver Charm and in
1998 with Real Quiet, was conceded a good shot this year with
Captain Steve. The colt, who has shined in his workouts at
Churchill Downs, galloped 1 3/8 miles Saturday. Bobby Frankel, who
trains Aptitude, third in the Wood Memorial, was asked if he had
scouted any of his rivals who looked sharp, and he replied, ``The
favorite and Captain Steve.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
