<P>
   MATERIAL WORLD
</P>
<P>
   PALAEOLITHIC-TEXTILES-NEW-SCIENTIST
</P>
<P>
   Ice Age women may not have been just the subservient preparers
of food and bearers of children. A recent discovery that women wore
woven clothes looks set to challenge conventional wisdom about the
status of Stone Age women.
</P>
<P>
   THE WINTER PALACE
</P>
<P>
   ICE-PALACE-HOTEL-NEW-SCIENTIST
</P>
<P>
   Ice palaces built for Empresses are the stuff of legend. The
modern day ice hotels are just as dazzling. But how do you build a
hotel out of snow and ice and what does it feel like when your
painstaking efforts melt away just five months later?
</P>
<P>
   ATOMIC LOGIC
</P>
<P>
   DEMISE-OF-SILICON-CHIP
</P>
<P>
   The next generation of computer processors could be grown in
vats of chemicals and be millions of times faster. A growing number
of scientists believe there are ways to shrink computer components
a million fold using the smallest building blocks around-molecules.
</P>
<P>
   ORDINARY MIRACLES
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS-AND-MORTALS-NEW-SCIENTIST
</P>
<P>
   How do the complexities of the living world arise from its
simplest parts? It seems that for any kind of intelligent behaviour
to emerge, all is needed is a scattering of ``angels.''
</P>
