<HEADER>
A7126 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-CAR-CYCLES-MLADIN-NYT     05-05 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-CYCLES-MLADIN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAT MLADIN: MOTORCYCLE RACING'S JEFF GORDON 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LOWELL COHN   
 Santa Rosa, Calif., Press Democrat   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mat Mladin was casually explaining how he broke
his back.
</P>
<P>
   He was eating a piece of sourdough bread at a restaurant before
heading north to Sonoma County to race this weekend at Sears Point
in the AMA Superbike Challenge. As he munched, his mind happened to
wander back over the years to 1994, to the day he and his
motorcycle parted company for the briefest, most frightening
moment.
</P>
<P>
   It was in Perth, Australia. Not that Mladin's from Perth. He
grew up outside Sydney, and still has a place there, although he
spends most of his time in Las Vegas these days. He was speeding
down a hill in practice, doing something like 130 or 140 mph, and
wouldn't you just know, he got himself into false neutral.
</P>
<P>
   ``False neutral'' was Mladin's phrase, and he said it as
matter-of-factly as someone might say ``Pass the mustard.'' So he
was in false neutral and found he had no chance to get his bike
back in gear, not with that wall gaining on him at warp speed. So
he jumped off the bike and landed in a sand trap. And he didn't
think anything about the accident after that, except for being out
of breath all the time, and not being able to suck in a good
lungful of air.
</P>
<P>
   He smiled at that detail about not being able to breathe. He ate
a bit of Caesar Salad. He's 28 and in remarkably good health, and
because he won this race last year at Sears Point and because he
was last year's AMA Chevy Trucks US Superbike champ, any time he
``throws it away'' (motorcycle slang for crashing), it's big news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I raced the following day,'' he announced to the people eating
at his table. ``Do you believe me?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   No one was about to question his veracity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I did,'' he said. ``I had gone to the hospital for
X-rays, but they didn't pick up any problem. I thought I just took
a good hard bang. I spent all night in the Jacuzzi. They kept a guy
with me to make sure I didn't drown. The next day it was raining. I
finished sixth in the first race and first in the second race. I
couldn't bend at all. I looked funny.'' Mladin smiled at the memory
of how funny he looked. Broken backs will do that to you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two weeks later, I hadn't improved,'' he said. ``I told my mom
something was wrong. So they gave me some more tests and they
picked up that I had five fractured vertebrae and three
compressions.''
</P>
<P>
   People at the table praised Mladin on his high pain threshold,
but he brushed them aside. ``It's just something you do,'' he said.
``You've got to race. It's a championship. You don't always get the
day off from work because you've got a cold or the flu, do you?''
</P>
<P>
   Mladin started racing motorcycles at age 4, which means he was a
child prodigy, which means he's something like the Jeff Gordon of
superbikers. He went through the 10th grade in school, but only
because he had to. ``I would have left earlier if I could have,''
he said. ``I wasn't allowed. I really didn't care for school. I
loved bikes. School just got in the way of practicing.'' School
always gets in the way of something.
</P>
<P>
   He is one of those racers who loves Sears Point. He's a
road-course guy. Some aren't. Some want to ride around in circles
with no surprises _ maybe they approach life that way, too. And
although Mladin can't gun his Suzuki past 155 at Sears Point (he
pushes 190 at other tracks), he likes to say, ``Sears Point is one
of the most technical race tracks.'' By ``technical'' he means
hardly any straightaways and a certain number of blind turns. These
kinds of things turn him on.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some tracks,'' he said, ``you take two riders and give them
the same bike, they'll finish very close together at the end. Sears
Point is different. It rewards how well you set up your bike, how
well you think. It rewards you if you're an aggressive rider who
hangs it out all race.'' In other words, Mladin is a thinking
person's superbike racer. He likes solving problems.
</P>
<P>
   He's cleverly solved the problem of how to get from track to
track. You probably know that Winston Cup drivers fly from race to
race like royalty. On race day at Sears Point you can see some of
them being coptered in so they don't get caught in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   That copter business isn't for Mladin. He doesn't stay at a
fancy hotel even though top superbike racers can earn upwards of
$1.5 million a season. He bought himself a motor home in which he
and his wife Janine tool around the country. They park that baby at
the track and set up house right there on top of the grease and the
old engine oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the beauty of it,'' Mladin said, not that everyone
would find a motor home beautiful. ``I can eat what I want and I
won't get food poisoning because Janine does all the cooking. I've
got a microwave, washer and dryer, satellite TV and a DVD player.
When you get more money you can afford motor homes. More and more
of the racers are doing that.'' And you can just picture it, the
cream of the crop of superbikers hanging out in the dark night at
the track, roasting weenies, swapping yarns and avoiding food
poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live for my racing,'' Mladin said.
</P>
<P>
   We believe you, Mat.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
