u a BC-DETROIT-SCHOOLS-(TRIM     05-05 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DETROIT-SCHOOLS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETROIT SCHOOL DISTRICT'S NEW CEO HAS HIS WORK CUT OUT FOR HIM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Mich.)   By NICHOLD M. CHRISTIAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Detroit's troubled school district has selected as its
new chief executive Dr. Kenneth Burnley, a Colorado Springs
superintendent known for making tough decisions and increasing
parental involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Burnley, a 58-year-old Detroit native, will take over the
172,000-student district, the state's largest, at a time of immense
turmoil. It will be his job to shepherd a $1.4 billion bond
construction project for 69 new schools, raise, test scores, which
for years have trailed state and national averages, and repair a
payroll system that routinely issues late checks.
</P>
<P>
   He will also be responsible for a $1.9 billion budget, 10 times
the budget of Colorado Springs District No. 11, where he worked for
13 years. That district, which has struggled financially, has 263
schools and 33,500 students.
</P>
<P>
   ``This won't be an easy job,'' said Burnley, who was
superintendent of schools in Fairbanks, Alaska, before moving to
Colorado. ``There is a lot of heavy lifting that needs to be done
to focus on our young people.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would commute between Detroit and Colorado Springs
through the end of June. The job here, which could pay him up to
$250,000 a year, is unusual because, as the school CEO, he has the
authority to approve budgets and contracts without input from a
school board. The CEO post was created last year when the state
took over the troubled district and removed its superintendent and
elected school board
</P>
<P>
   Choosing Burnley took the Detroit board 11 months, a job that
proved challenging in part because at least a dozen other cities
are looking for school superintendents and the jobs have become
increasingly difficult to fill.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the difficulty was a complicated state school reform
law that allows Michigan's governor, John Engler, to appoint one of
the district's seven board members and grant that person sole veto
power in the selection of a new CEO. Mayor Dennis Archer appoints
the other six members of the board.
</P>
<P>
   In January the board's first choice, John Thomson, former
superintendent of schools in Tulsa, Okla., was vetoed by the
governor's appointee, Mark Murray, the state treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But after a three-hour interview late Thursday night, the board
took just five minutes to unanimously select Burnley.
</P>
<P>
   ``His leadership, his vision were all well stated ,'' said
Freeman Hendrix, the board's chairman. ``He did more than just talk
philosophically about what needs to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Burnley is a graduate of the district and was
reared in a pro-union family in this heavily unionized citywere
bonuses, Hendrix said.
</P>
<P>
   Murray said he did not regret delaying Detroit's search. ``This
is a very powerful position,'' he said. ``You take as much time as
you need to make a good choice.''
</P>
<P>
   People familiar with Burnley's work in Colorado Springs say he
is quite capable of wrestling with Detroit's problems. Critics and
supporters in Colorado Springs cheer him for creating an outreach
program that has recruited more than 7,000 parents as volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the American Association of School Administrators named
Burnley superintendent of the year. He also That same year, he
raised eyebrows by making the district the first in the nation to
allow major companies to advertise in the schools. Through contract
with more than 50 companies, including Coke, the district had been
able to draw $100,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Burnley was criticized for recommending that the
district close five schools to save money after a school millage
failed. The board sided with the community, deciding to keep the
schools open for at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes he doesn't listen as well he should,'' said Kathy
Glasmann, president of the Colorado Springs Education Association.
``But he's very pro-teacher and willing to try new things. It's a
real loss.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
