<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7130 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-DERBY-BISHER0506-COX     05-05 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DERBY-BISHER0506-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Amid all Derby stories, expect `Pegasus' to fall
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, KY _ Outside Barn 42, where Dogwood Stable's hopes
for the 126th Kentucky Derby are in residence, there was much
jollifying. Cot Campbell, master of Dogwood, was accommodating
photographers with his series of grotesque masks. Trippi, the colt
bearing the name of the old football character from Georgia, was
wearing a thin, white cloak as he nibbled in the grass while being
admired. (Most women have never seen the thoroughbred they don't
admire.) Lila Campbell was fondling the harmonica on which she had
learned to play ``Old Kentucky Home.''
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment was in his stall, bobbing and weaving, as if begging
attention. All week, Trippi has been the attraction, not just
because he is unbeaten, but the name. The name, though it has been
half a century since the heyday of old Charlie himself.
Impeachment, a $260,000 purchase, has a name that draws snickers,
out of a filly named Misconduct, whose daddy was named Criminal
Type. You draw your own conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Inside a little alcove of an office sat the topic of note. Todd
Pletcher is a 32-year-old by a former trainer named Jake, as bright
as he is young, but serious in his work, especially this week. He
has worked the Derby before as an assistant to D. Wayne Lukas. Now
he has four _ count 'em, four _ horses in his first Kentucky Derby
on his own, the two Dogwood horses, More Than Ready and Graeme
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   He sat at his desk in the office, wearing a baseball-type cap,
poring over papers, but with time to be affable. ``You try to be
fair to them all,'' he said. ``Having four is really not much more
trouble than one, just get out early and do the same thing four
times.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider him more an executive director than trainer. The new
variety of trainer that has sprung up is far removed from the old
hardboots who came with the farm or were seasoned in the bluegrass.
Pletcher is a college graduate, degree in animal science at
Arizona, now lives in New York and has made quite a dent in racing
on the East Coast. Call it his first Derby, if you choose, but he
was trainer-behind-the-scene of Thunder Gulch, winner in 1996, but
unsung in his own stable.
</P>
<P>
   Trainers now come to the Derby in all shapes, sizes and
heritage, all for one reason _ to win the most cherished prize in
horse racing. There are, and have been, trainers here from
Yugoslavia, England, the United Arab Emirates, Mexico, Brooklyn,
Canada, France and none more avid in the pursuit than the Godolphin
Stable of Sheikh Mohammed al Maktoum. The sheikh has been in form
this week, visiting around, shaking hands with the great and
near-great, handing out blue shirts, caps and windbreakers with the
Godolphin insignia at his barn. And talking more of Dubai
Millennium, who won the rich Dubai Stakes, than his two Derby
visitors, China Visit and Curule.
</P>
<P>
   The sheikh's trainer is one of his own, Saeed bin Suroor, who
speaks passionately of winning the Derby. Winning a Derby, however,
says D. Wayne Lukas, ``is no guarantee of prolonged success. David
Cross (Sunny's Halo, 1983) is running a kitchen in California. Cam
Gamboloti (Spend a Buck, 1985) now has a small stable, and Jack van
Berg has had some hard times since Alysheba.''
</P>
<P>
   The same might be said of jockeys. Pat Valenzuela won with
Sunday Silence, fell into the drug pit and is now down and out in
California. Chris Antley, the comeback kid of '99, hasn't been able
to keep his weight down, and he won't be defending his title.
</P>
<P>
   There's even a female trainer on the grounds this week, Jenine
Sahadi, who is Lebanese and known to spike her horses' oats with
wine. The name comes up here, for Jenine (Mrs. Ben Cecil at the
courthouse) has the horse your traveling seer expects to win the
roses Saturday. The Deputy is Irish-bred and has staying power, and
if you take stock in such things, has the lowest Dosage Index in
the field. That's a gauge that has lost some of its influence in
recent years, but when you've got it on your side, use it. He is
not your typical closer, rather hangs nearer the lead than, say,
Impeachment, who comes out of the next county.
</P>
<P>
   Chris McCarron has been The Deputy's only rider since coming
over here, knows where the finish line is at Churchill Downs, was a
winner on Alysheba and Go for Gin, and the rider-horse relationship
is advantageous. War Chant, More Than Ready and Impeachment come in
that order. Sorry, Fusaichi Pegasus, there's no next year in the
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
