<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7132 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-JASON-REVIEW-1STLD     05-05 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JASON-REVIEW-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JASON AND THE ARGONAUTS': COVETS FLEECE! SLAYS HARPIES! YESSSS! 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to correct spelling to ``Halami'' sted ``Halmi'' twice in 4th
graf.) 
(Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By NEIL GENZLINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NBC miniseries ``Jason and the Argonauts,'' like any good
epic, has profound questions at its heart. What drives men to
pursue the seemingly unattainable? Are there limits to love and
friendship? And what is that thing on Dennis Hopper's head?
</P>
<P>
   Hopper, sporting a curly coiffure and a creepily understated
malevolence, is one of the high points of this often entertaining
account of Jason, the hero of Greek legend, and his quest for the
Golden Fleece. So odd is Hopper's get-up _ he plays Pelias, the
king with a penchant for stabbing his relatives _ that when he
first appears in Sunday's opening installment that it is difficult
to recognize him. But then comes that voice.
</P>
<P>
   Pelias covets the fleece far more than any animal hide ought to
be coveted, and he sends Jason (Jason London), his nephew, to find
it. Jason is given a ship, the Argo, and the underqualified crew he
recruits becomes known as the Argonauts. Adventures ensue, watched
over and sometimes manipulated by Zeus (Angus MacFadyen) and Hera
(Olivia Williams), the deities of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   The miniseries, another lavish offering by the producing team of
Robert Halmi Sr. and Robert Halmi Jr., doesn't quite capture the
suicide-mission camaraderie that ought to prevail on Jason's ship.
Half of the Argonauts are drowned or otherwise disposed of before
they have made much of an impression on the screen. Of those who
aren't, only Kieran O'Brien as a weaselly thief, Brian Thompson as
Hercules and Olga Sosnovska as Jason's longtime
friend-who-wishes-she-were-more-than-that are particularly
memorable.
</P>
<P>
   But calamities, not character studies, are the main attraction
here, and several of the ones the Argonauts blunder into are
skillfully served. Poseidon, the sea god, is a huge, scaly fright.
The Clashing Rocks, which come together to squash passing ships,
are as believable as Clashing Rocks get. And once the voyagers
reach Colchis, the island where the fleece hangs from a tree, they
encounter the worst horror of them all: Frank Langella, playing the
island's king, who appears to have the same hairdresser as Hopper.
</P>
<P>
   Those who think about this ``Jason'' too hard will readily find
flaws. Why do some characters have British accents and others not?
What law of physics allows the Argo to zip smartly along when its
oars are barely reaching the water? When Jason, moments after being
flame-broiled by the fire-breathing Minoan Bull, stirs himself back
to consciousness, would his buddies back there in B.C. Greece
really have shouted a Marv Albert-like ``Yessss!''?
</P>
<P>
   But there is no need for anyone to nitpick when watching this
``Jason.'' It's more fun to trace the antecedents of the various
effects _ beasties that could have been plucked from ``Jurassic
Park'' or the ``Terminator'' movies; a talking statue that is a
cinematic descendant of Babe, the sheep-herding pig; a
color-changing moment from ``Pleasantville.'' There's even a
bow-and-arrow torch-lighting borrowed from that Olympic ceremony a
few years back.
</P>
<P>
   It's also amusing, for anyone whose mythology classes have
merged into one big blob since graduation, to try to guess what's
coming for the Argonauts. Is this the part where they meet the
Cyclopes? (Well, no, that was ....) Wait, it's the Sirens, right?
(No, you're thinking of ....) Wait, I've got it; it's the Harpies,
isn't it? (Yessss!)
</P>
<P>
   And finally, viewers can spend some of their idle time simply
marveling at the restraint of the cast and crew, especially at one
particular moment near the end. Jason has made it back home with
the fleece, which turns out to be a mangy rag still attached to the
skull of its original four-legged owner. Pelias' son, Acastus (Tom
Harper), has snatched the fleece to try to impress Dad. Pelias and
Acastus come face to face, Pelias in his goofy curls, Acastus
wearing the ratty-looking fleece on his noggin.
</P>
<P>
   And no one bursts out laughing. But there's a sense that there
was a lot of laughing on the inside. When this ``Jason'' works,
that is why: It's drama wrapped around a sense of fun.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `JASON AND THE ARGONAUTS'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Sunday and Monday on NBC
</P>
<P>
   Nick Willing, director; Dyson Lovell, producer; Chris Thompson,
line producer; Matthew Faulk and Mark Skeet, writers; Sergei
Kozlov, director of photography. Music by Simon Boswell. A Hallmark
Entertainment production. Robert Halmi Sr. and Robert Halmi Jr.,
executive producers.
</P>
<P>
   With: Jason London (Jason), Frank Langella (Aertes), Dennis
Hopper (Pelias), Derek Jacobi (Phineas), Natasha Henstridge
(Hypsipyle), Angus MacFadyen (Zeus), Jolene Blalock (Medea), Olivia
Williams (Hera), Brian Thompson (Hercules), Adrian Lester
(Orpheus), Mark Lewis Jones (Mopsus), David Calder (Argos), Diana
Kent (Polymele), James Callis (Aspyrtes), Hugh Quarshie (Chiron),
Olga Sosnovska (Atalanta), Kieran O'Brien (Actor), Tom Harper
(Acastus) and Ciaran Hinds (Aeson).
</P>
</TEXT>
