<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7133 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-TV-VIKINGS-SPI &LR;      05-05 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-VIKINGS-SPI </SLUG>
  
 PBS EXPLORATION OF vIKINGS WOULD MAKE EVEN THE STONY LEIF SMILE  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At Shilshole Marina, on the edge of Seattle's wellspring of
Scandinavian identity, the 12-foot-high statue of Leif Ericson
offers stony testimony that the Vikings weren't exactly the
effervescent type. Leif's dour likeness could be the poster boy for
irritability, though you'd probably be annoyed, too, with seabirds
using your head as a restroom.
</P>
<P>
   If ever there was occasion for Leif to crack a smile, though, it
would be now. All of a sudden, Vikings are everywhere. Hotter than
the Dixie Chicks, they grace the covers of Time and National
Geographic, they're starring in a new Smithsonian road show and a
just-published companion book (``Vikings: The North Atlantic
Saga''), and _ here's a shock! _ they're on TV.
</P>
<P>
   It's all because the scholars say Ericson (a k a Erickson,
Ericsson and Eriksson) discovered North America 1,000 years ago.
Nothing like a good, round-numbered anniversary to get our
inquisitive, revisionist juices going. And nothing like PBS to stir
the brew _ twice in eight days _ when there's enlightenment to be
had.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, a special episode of ``NOVA'' gets things started
with ``The Vikings,'' an enjoyable treatment in the
scholarship-is-painless ``NOVA'' style. The two-hour exploration of
Viking lore suggests the Norse invaders of the late eighth century
probably weren't much worse than any other group of aggressive,
peripatetic, materialistic expansionists who believed the best
defense is a good offense. It's just that they got bad press from
the people they were conquering. (Doesn't help that the early
Vikings themselves were storytellers, not writers.)
</P>
<P>
   So the Vikings, who swept into other parts of Europe from
Norway, Sweden and Denmark, went down in history as a marauding
bunch of blood-spilling plunderers who held sway for 2{ centuries,
then faded from the scene in a remarkable bit of social blending.
</P>
<P>
   Ten centuries later, the accumulated historical and
archaeological evidence doesn't refute the unsavory record. Rather,
it balances the saga of savagery with solid proof that the Vikings
were skilled artists and artisans, sophisticated traders, astute
politicians, fearless explorers and absolute geniuses when it came
to nautical engineering. They traveled farther and wider than the
Greeks and Romans, affecting social and economic developments in
much of what is now modern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   And, while Leif Ericson's forays from Greenland to North America
never established the sort of foothold the Vikings established in
England, Ireland, France, Russia and Iceland, they at least serve
to remind us that unrecorded achievement isn't any less important
than the written record, just harder to prove.
</P>
<P>
   As with most episodes of ``NOVA,'' the best part of ``The
Vikings'' is the application of science to imagine the Viking
experience. Bit by bit, from the use of ground-penetrating radar to
microscopic analysis of charcoal fragments to good old mucking
around in ancient privies and garbage dumps, forensic scientists
have pieced together a Viking mosaic shimmering with the allure of
new discovery. Faithful replicas of sailing ships and
computer-generated re-creations of villages complete the
transformation of the Vikings from figures of legend to
flesh-and-bone people.
</P>
<P>
   It is generally accepted that the Viking Age ended in 1066 when
William the Conqueror invaded England and defeated King Harold at
the Battle of Hastings. But William himself was descended from
Vikings who had wrested Normandy from the Romans 155 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   So, what makes one a Viking?
</P>
<P>
   The ``NOVA'' piece would suggest that a successful weaving into
the tapestry of the places they occupied is perhaps the greatest
Viking legacy, a contribution that includes democratic government,
a fabulous spirit of adventure and a trading network that reached
across the Mediterranean Sea and as far east and south as Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   This record of survival makes all the more strange the
disappearance of a settlement from Greenland in the middle of the
14th century. On May 16, ``The Lost Vikings of Greenland'' on PBS
takes a look at this colony, which thrived on Greenland's eastern
coast for about five centuries before vanishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lost Vikings'' is the second in a four-part ``Secrets of the
Dead'' series airing next Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday (may 15, 16
and 17) on PBS. (Other segments examine the origin of the Dark
Ages, the disappearance of the Anasazi in what is now New Mexico,
and a theory on what really caused the Hindenburg to explode.)
</P>
<P>
   Set up as a kind of cheesy detective story, ``Lost Vikings''
isn't as much fun as Tuesday's ``NOVA'' profile, but its subject
matter is fascinating and the detective work, right down to the
examination of fossilized blowflies, is a riveting example of how
scientists can create a believable construct when it seems they
have nothing to work with but a pile of centuries-old rubble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lost Vikings'' loses points for promising to tell us the truth
about the colony, when its conclusion is really a best-guess
scenario that posits a mini-ice age. That, combined with the
settlers' apparent depletion of natural resources and their
inability or unwillingness to mix with the native Inuit population,
spelled certain doom.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the theory is eminently plausible, and it suggests
somewhat ironically that the colonists' demise may have been
abetted by the very religion that was anathema to their pagan
ancestors 500 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Iceland, where the Greenland settlers were from, had adopted
Christianity around the time Leif Ericson was exploring the western
reaches of Viking territory. There is no question of significant
church presence in the Icelanders' settlements on Greenland. What
isn't known, but assumed by some historians, is that xenophobic
churchmen may have forbidden contact with the Inuit, thus
establishing a social barrier that effectively prevented the
Vikings' descendants from learning how to adapt to a changing
environment.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, ``Lost Vikings'' underscores the clarion lesson
of ``The Vikings'' that, despite the seeming incongruity of the
premise, the enrichment of national or ethnic ``identity,'' at
least in terms of social contribution and achievement, ultimately
lies in assimilation, not isolation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
