<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7134 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-BARS-ANTICELEBRITY-NY     05-05 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARS-ANTICELEBRITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUZZ OFF: SECRET BARS THAT SPURN HYPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, May 7) By JULIA CHAPLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At 1:30 a.m. on a recent Saturday, Milk &AMP; Honey, a
tiny bar on the Lower East Side of Manhattan, was jammed for one of
the few times since it opened in January. But instead of feeling
elated, the 27-year-old owner, who had barely been able to make the
rent until a few weeks ago, scooped up the discarded martini
glasses and cast a disapproving eye on the cheery crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're breaking the rules,'' he said, raising his brows in
concern. ``Men are talking to women all over the place without
permission.''
</P>
<P>
   It was amazing that anyone was in the bar at all, considering
the effort made to hide it among the grated storefronts and
overflowing garbage cans on an unassuming block near Delancey
Street. Not only is there no sign, but the place is as disguised
as, in the words of the owner, ``an old Jewish tailor shop.'' The
word Alterations, in fact, was freshly painted in an antiquated
style on the store window. Behind it was a dusty mannequin dressed
in a ratty three-piece suit.
</P>
<P>
   To gain admission, would-be patrons must phone at least 20
minutes ahead, have their references approved, then traverse a
pitch-black hallway. Anyone caught knocking or talking while
waiting to be admitted is blacklisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The service I'm offering is an idiot-free environment safe
from celebrity sycophants and frat boys who read the listings in
Time Out,'' said the owner, who agreed to be interviewed only if
his bar's exact location was not revealed and he was identified by
his first name only, Sasha. ``Unfortunately, hiding my bar was the
only way I could think of to do it these days.''
</P>
<P>
   These may seem like extreme measures, but Sasha is the most
extreme example of a small contingent of night life entrepreneurs
less dedicated to cultivating heat and hype than avoiding it. They
have had enough of clubs and bars used as promotional venues, that
act as hosts of parties sponsored by liquor companies and where
paparazzi are planted at every velvet rope.
</P>
<P>
   New clubs striving for the cachet of bold-faced names shell out
small fortunes for publicists to broker premiere parties and other
promotional events. The scenes are all but interchangeable:
clipboard-wielding list-keepers in headsets part the sea of
beautiful but not famous guests to make way for limousines with
celebrities. The next day, the spectacle is chronicled in the
tabloids, and legions of readers form the impression of a hot new
destination they must go to as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The prepackaged hoopla has created something of a backlash. A
wave of secretive bars have lately cropped up, from the simple SoHo
establishment on the corner of Spring and Sullivan Streets with no
sign, no name and blacked out windows, to bars modeled after old
Mafia social clubs, to the underground Milk &AMP; Honey.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is to stay hype-free, catering to a small but loyal
crowd, and make enough money to remain in business. It's not so
easy, as Ian Stell and Michael Drury learned. As owners of the
popular downtown scenes Orchard Bar and Double Happiness, they
opened the secretive Wyanoka last year, hoping to provide a
laid-back environment for the art world. Located upstairs from
Double Happiness on Mott Street in Little Italy, Wyanoka was an
apartment-like single room with decor inspired by the mobster
gambling parlor that formerly occupied the space. The only clue to
its existence was a tiny logo of a Wyanoka Indian on a plain metal
door. The initiated would slide a special membership card through
an ATM-like slot. But exclusivity couldn't pay the bills, and the
two partners closed down after eight months. They are now
converting it to a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way a bar like this could work is if the owner was
extremely dedicated,'' Stell said. Sasha turns out to be that
owner. He sees himself as a kind of Holden Caulfield of night life,
scorning ``phonies'' and crusading against lapsed values. In
addition to his strict entrance policy, he has eight house rules
posted in the bathrooms and strictly enforced. Rule No. 1 is ``No
name dropping.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who thinks that celebrities are the new aristocrats
will not be tolerated,'' Sasha said. ``They are the most tedious
people in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The bar is for people who feel responsibility, not
entitlement,'' he added, volleying the incoming requests for entry
on a rotary phone and whipping up elaborate cocktails with egg
whites and hand-squeezed citrus. ``If Puffy showed up here in a
limo, he could come in as long as he had a reservation and could
obey my rules,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other rules include: ``Don't tell anyone about this place unless
you would leave that person alone in your apartment,'' and
``Gentlemen will not introduce themselves to ladies. You may not
speak to a woman to whom you have not been introduced. Wait for her
to speak to you, or ask the bartender for an introduction.'' That
is the rule most often broken.
</P>
<P>
   Sasha maintains a Rolodex with all of his customers' names in
it, cross-referenced with the initials of the person who
recommended them. If either party breaks the rules, the card is
torn up and both are banished. Sasha said he heard that this
screening method was practiced by a secret Yale University club or
an illegal after-hours gambling parlor. He also plans to install a
video surveillance system on the front door to screen the guests,
as soon as he can raise $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   He opened the club with money that he, his sister and three
friends he met while at Stuyvesant High School borrowed against
their credit cards, between $10,000 and $15,000 each. The debts are
still outstanding; all of the revenues from the bar are put back in
the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, I haven't had to physically kick anyone out,'' he
said. ``I find the best way to make people leave is to make them
think it is their idea. I just speak to them like I'm scolding a
child in a stern disapproving voice. They usually apologize and
then never come back.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Milk &AMP; Honey is like a Prohibition-era speakeasy.
Sasha wears only old-fashioned clothes: suspenders, high-waisted
pleated trousers and a fedora. He plays jazz and soul from the
1920s and 1950s. The bar is made of solid oak, the banquettes are
leather and the walls are plaster, not sheet rock. Hat hooks are
provided. The bathroom is stocked with meticulously rolled cloth
towels. No Bounty here.
</P>
<P>
   Only top-shelf liquor is served, though Sasha refuses to serve
drinks he deems fratlike. These include woo woos, kamikazes and
shots of any kind. If you sit at a table long enough, a silver tray
will arrive with long-stemmed strawberries drizzled with honey, or
freshly shucked oysters.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Milk &AMP; Honey isn't for everyone. Many one-time patrons
who have been chastised for sitting on the tables, whistling loudly
or trying to pick up women refer to it as ``that rule place'' and
have complained that the atmosphere is a ``buzz kill.'' But most of
the regulars are extremely loyal and protective. When Sasha gets
too busy (he is the only employee other than one part-timer), they
help out by answering the phone, opening the door and escorting
``ladies'' to taxis.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are enough good people out there to fill up a
500-square-foot bar,'' Sasha said. ``But I doubt there are enough
to fill up 1,000 square feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Felix Salmon, 28, an English journalist, who was leaning against
a polished brick wall last Saturday night, said: ``If I broke one
of the rules, I'd feel dreadful. It would be like talking during
the opera.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
