<HEADLINE>
RANCOROUS HOWDY DOODY CUSTODY TRIAL NEARS DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ With a ghost of a smile occasionally playing
across his face, a federal judge is prepared to play Solomon
Saturday in a struggle over the puppet that is commonly known as
the Original Howdy.
</P>
<P>
   That is, not Ugly Doody, an early model that was abandoned as
not sufficiently appealing for television, and not Double Doody, a
duplicate built especially for public appearances. Not Photo Doody,
which had no strings and was sold last year to a Palm Beach, Fla.
woman for about $113,000, or the two Canadian Doodies, but Doody
himself, the Doody who matters, and who is locked in a Rhode Island
safe deposit box while a preeminent puppet museum and a Connecticut
puppeteering dynasty battle over who owns him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That seems to be the universe of Doodies,'' said U.S. District
Court judge Christopher F. Droney, who heard both sides argue for a
summary judgement Friday in their first face-to-face court
appearance. Droney's decision could be many months in coming.
</P>
<P>
   The battle over the freckle-faced '50s icon _ which one
collector said could easily fetch half-a-million dollars at auction
_ was precipitated by the death in 1998 of his human sidekick and
voicebox, ``Buffalo Bob'' Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Howdy Doody appeared from 1947 to 1960, on a show that began
with Smith's ritual question to the Peanut Gallery, ``Say, kids,
what time is it?'' They would scream, ``It's Howdy Doody time!''
</P>
<P>
   A decade after the show went off the air, eager to cash in on
Howdy Doody's nostalgia value, Smith had borrowed it from the man
who pulled his strings, Rufus Rose, who kept the puppet after the
show ended. Rose died in 1975. Shortly before Smiths' death, Rose's
son Christopher, 53, flew down to North Carolina and took
possession of the puppet, which Smith and the Roses had planned to
sell at auction.
</P>
<P>
   But the Detroit Institute of Arts said Rufus Rose had long ago
promised to add the puppet to their 850-puppet collection upon his
death. And the lawsuit that followed, filed last year, has teams of
lawyers debating removable hands, puppet abandonment, and the
mysterious handwriting inside Howdy Doody's head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a forensic puppet examiner, but what I saw was when
they took the skull cap off the back of the head, there was some
notation in there,'' said Stuart Rosen of Bingham Dana LLP, who is
representing the museum. The notation named a Scott Brinker as the
designer, opening up a new set of disagreements between the many
factions that have taken an interest in Howdy.
</P>
<P>
   The clash over Howdy Doody comes just as the market for 1950s
collectibles is at its demographic peak, said Gary Busk, a
Carrollton, Texas man who is one of the nation's foremost
collectors of marionettes. Baby boomers in their 40s and 50s have
the disposable income to invest in the icons that defined their
childhood, and then about age 60, they start ``pulling in their
horns,'' he said. With that in mind, Busk estimated that the puppet
could draw a price of $500,000 _ probably from a foreigner, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely very big, it really is,'' Busk said. ``There's
a lot of people that are sitting out there who would like to get a
shot at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not if the team from Detroit can help it, though. Arguing for
summary judgement Friday, Rosen said Rufus Rose had custody of the
puppet, rather than ownership, and that his promise to the museum
amounted to a contract. He cited a letter ``Buffalo Bob'' Smith
wrote in 1995 after the museum had refused his request to sell the
puppet to relieve his financial woes: ``In complying to you
request, when I no longer wish to keep the HOWDY DOODY PUPPET for
my personal use and enjoyment, I shall contact the museum director
to have him arrange for the transfer according to the wishes of
Rufus Rose, who, incidentally, did not create the puppet or the
character.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Rose family maintains there was never a real contract,
and Christopher, the only of Rufus Rose's three sons to attend the
hearing, said he is shocked at how aggressively the museum
approached the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Within the clannish puppet world, that family has won a lot of
loyalty, said Steven Abrams, president of the Puppeteers of
America, an organization Rufus Rose once led. Although Howdy Doody
hardly represented Rufus and Margaret Rose's range and
craftsmanship _ Rufus Rose's favorite was a far less successful
production based on the story of Pinnocchio called ``The Blue
Flower'' _ observers from the trade have sympathy for the Roses'
attempt to capture ``the only opportunity to realize this kind of
windfall,'' Abrams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's real fascinating that Detroit has the moxie to do
this,'' Busk said. ``For an organization to file suit against the
Rose family _ look, if they win, they lose, as far as the puppetry
community is concerned, because look what they put the Roses
through. And if they lose, look what they put the Roses through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
