u a BC-KANSASCITY-SCHOOLS-47     05-05 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KANSASCITY-SCHOOLS-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING A CITY'S INTRACTABLE SCHOOL PROBLEMS, AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla.)   By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ On top of everything else, the coffee was not
ready for Benjamin Demps Jr., the superintendent of the beleaguered
Kansas City School District, as he arrived in his office early
Friday, charged with fixing educational woes here that have endured
for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a good sign for the day,'' said Demps, 65, whose schools
have essentially been judged a failure by a state review board,
which stripped them of its seal of accreditation on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Demps has been on the job just 10 months. He is a former air
traffic controller who rose to become a high-ranking federal
aviation official before turning his attention to the school
problems in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I'm asking for is patience,'' said the chief of the Kansas
City schools, which have been under a court desegregation order
stemming from a lawsuit filed in 1977. ``I don't mind the criticism
_ that comes with the job. I've got confidence in what I'm doing.
When you've been an air traffic controller, and you need to bring
down the plane safely, you have to trust your own judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of a laborer, Demps grew up in New York and joined the
Air Force after graduating from high school in 1951. He later went
to work as an air traffic controller, rising into management ranks.
Going back to school as a married man with two daughters, Demps
earned a college diploma at age 32 and a law degree at 48.
</P>
<P>
   He has also served as Oklahoma's secretary of health and human
services.
</P>
<P>
   The state Education Board removed the accreditation from the
Kansas City District after its schools failed each of 11
performance standards, including test scores and attendance.
</P>
<P>
   The move means that the district has two years to show
significant improvement, or face the prospect of being abolished by
the state Legislature and broken into smaller districts. It also
means that students in the district are eligible to attend suburban
districts, and that the Kansas City District must pay tuition and
transportation costs for them.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging the problems in the Kansas City system _ similar
to those, he noted, that endure in most urban centers _ Demps
nonetheless bristles about the timing of the state board's action.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make it official in May _ three weeks before the school
year ends,'' he said. ``I'm incensed for our graduating seniors.
They've gone to school all these years, and just before their
graduation, this happens.'' Demps said state education officials
insisted that the loss of accreditation would not harm the college
prospects of Kansas City graduates, who can expect admission based
on test results.
</P>
<P>
   But the superintendent is not so sanguine. ``When colleges have
50 students for 25 spots,'' he said, ``they've got to look at
something, and maybe this will be one of those things.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the national debate on ways to remedy problems in urban
schools, the Kansas City district has long been an object of
scrutiny. Despite spending some $2 billion over the last two
decades to better the schools and draw more white students from the
suburbs, the Kansas City schools continue to struggle, and
three-quarters of the students are still members of racial minority
groups.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to satisfy federal court demands to draw more white
students, and to narrow the performance gaps between whites and
blacks, the district has spent lavishly on new buildings and
created special magnet schools like one focusing on Greek studies.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri lawmakers outside Kansas City have long complained
about the city schools drawing a disproportionate share of
education spending. Meanwhile, many residents of Kansas City,
especially blacks, have complained that the spending focused too
much on attracting white students, and not enough on improving
basic education for all.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping into the firestorm, Demps, who earns $156,000 a year,
has grown accustomed to fierce criticism. For example, Clinton
Adams, a black lawyer and leader of a group of dissatisfied
parents, has labeled the Demps administration ``feebleminded.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are skeptical because I'm not from Kansas City,
I'm not a Missourian _ `Who is this guy?''' said Demps, who was a
high-ranking federal civil aviation official in Belgium between
1985 and 1991. His wife, Patricia Demps, is a lawyer for Kerr
McGee. He has one daughter in Norman, Okla., and another in
Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that some people believe that a superintendent
should have had experience as a teacher or a principal, Demps said
his role was that of a leader of the education forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does the general necessarily know how to drive the tank?'' he
asked. ``Maybe not. But he knows how to lead the troops.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides coping with the loss of accreditation, Demps is working
to build ties with civic and academic leaders, who he believes can
help city schools with their resources and suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   To improve attendance, his administration now works with the
police on truancy sweeps during school hours to find young people
who are playing hooky. He said he had also sent a message to
teachers and administrators that academic standards could not be
compromised.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a recent increase in attendance, he said he was hoping
that other improvements would follow swiftly. Results of important
standardized tests, which students have just completed, will be
known in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``So there's a lot of anxiety around here,'' he said. ``How did
we do? We just don't know yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems in the Kansas City schools are not much different
from those confronting other big city districts, he said, and the
solutions are just as difficult to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not doing well in Kansas City,'' he said. ``The
difference here is that we're attacking it openly. You've got to
say: `We've got a problem here, gang. Let's get this train going in
the right direction.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 2001EDT &QL; 
