<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV07-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CAREER COST OF CARING FOR ELDERLY PARENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)  (For Release Sunday, March 7) 
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By SUSAN J. WELLS  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is growing evidence that caring for the elderly is taking
a big financial toll on employees and their careers.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study suggests that two-thirds of workers who care for
elderly relatives have lost out at work by forgoing promotions, pay
raises and training opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The study focused on 55 people age 45 or older who spent more
than eight hours a week providing unpaid care. Although it involved
relatively few participants, it is the first to detail financial
losses for providers, the researchers said. It was conducted last
year for the MetLife Mature Market Institute in New York by the
National Center for Women and Aging at Brandeis University in
Waltham, Mass., and the National Alliance for Caregiving in
Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
   How expensive can elder care be? For workers in the study who
were able to quantify the impact, the care has cost an average of
$659,000 over their lifetimes in lost wages, Social Security and
pension contributions, because they have taken time off, passed up
promotions or ``plum'' assignments, quit their jobs or retired
early.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it the caregivers' glass ceiling,'' said Sandra
Timmermann, a gerontologist and director of the MetLife Mature
Market Institute. ``It's an issue that will become even more
critical within the next 5 to 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the reason is clear: As the nation's population
continues to age, the number of people providing their care will
grow in tandem. That will intensify the impact on businesses and
workers.
</P>
<P>
   According to projections from the Census Bureau, 82 million
Americans will be 65 or over by 2050, more than double the 34.6
million in that age group in 1999. The projections, released in
January, show an especially rapid surge in the elderly population
as baby boomers begin reaching 65 in 2011.
</P>
<P>
   Women apparently bear a larger share of the responsibility for
elder care, according to a recent survey commissioned by Senior
Care Action Network, a health plan for seniors in Long Beach,
Calif. Of nearly 1,500 seniors over 65, some 29 percent said they
relied on a daughter or daughter-in-law for care, while 12 percent
said they relied on a son. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Until it hits home, it tends to be viewed as someone else's
issue,'' said Joyce Ruddock, vice president of MetLife's Long-Term
Care Group. ``But demographics will change that and put elder care
on a lot more employer radar screens. It's not only an emotional
issue, but a financial one, too. Elder care will be to the 21st
century what child care was to the last few decades.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
