Real Quiet, nicknamed ``The Fish'' by trainer Bob Baffert because
of his slim stature, to Fusaichi Pegasus, the favorite to win the
126th running of the Kentucky Derby. By MATT GRAVES. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   RAC-KENTUCKY-DERBY (Louisville, Ky.) _ On the one side, you have
the supposed ``Super Horse.'' On the other side, you have a host of
intriguing subplots involving the main characters in Saturday's
126th running of the Kentucky Derby. By FRED M. FAOUR.
</P>
<P>
   With: RAC-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   FOR SUNDAY:
</P>
<P>
   NAVY-SPY (Washington) _ A sailor accused of giving the Russians
secrets about the U.S. submarine fleet has encountered a unique
obstacle in his efforts to mount a defense: The Navy won't let him
meet privately with his lawyers out of fear that he might reveal
classified information. Navy Petty Officer 1st Class Daniel King,
an intelligence analyst being held in the U.S. Marine Corps brig at
Quantico, Va., is facing one count of espionage for passing
submarine secrets to Moscow and one count of disclosing classified
information improperly. He could face the death penalty if
convicted. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Filed Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-CONGRESS (Washington) _ For 35 years, Congress and the
White House have joined in bipartisan harmony to dole out federal
money for education. But election year politics have thrust the
program into turbulence this year. One veteran senator says he's
never seen anything like the political storm swirling around
education. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Filed Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   DEFENDING-TAIWAN (Washington) _ China's efforts to squash
Taiwan's talk of independence with fresh saber rattling spotlights
one of the best-kept secrets in Washington: The United States would
be hard-pressed to defend Taiwan against a Chinese invasion of the
craggy, remote island. U.S. forces would face huge handicaps in any
likely combat scenario adopted by China to terrorize, dominate or
occupy Taiwan _ from a naval blockade or missile attack to seizing
Taiwan's airspace or launching an invasion. By STEWART M. POWELL
And ERIC ROSENBERG. (1STLD-WRITETHRU filed Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-ELECTIONS (Washington) _ Beneath the hoopla of the
presidential race is another important national electoral conflict:
Control of the House of Representatives. Having battled back from
their 1994 debacle, House Democrats are six seats away from taking
back control. Republicans say they can hold the line, and if Texas
Gov. George W. Bush wins, it will be 1952 all over again _ the last
time Republicans controlled Capitol Hill and the White House. By
DAN FREEDMAN. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Those who abhor isolationism and
fear the consequences of protectionism can draw some solace from
the foreign policy declarations of Al Gore and George W. Bush. The
Democratic and Republican presidential hopefuls have stated quite
firmly their intentions of adhering to the centrist and
internationalist foreign policy principles that have guided every
president since World War II. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Filed
Thursday.)
</P>
