<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-DIOXIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGACY OF AGENT ORANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty-five years after the end of the Vietnam War, the
devastation that the United States wreaked on large parts of South
Vietnam by spraying millions of gallons of herbicides is still an
open wound. The most common herbicide was Agent Orange, named for
the orange band around its containers. Sprayed on forests and
fields to deny cover to enemy troops and supply lines, it included
trace amounts of dioxin, a toxic substance that has been linked to
several diseases.
</P>
<P>
   While there has been considerable research in the United States
on the effects of Agent Orange on US personnel, much less has been
done on its impact on the Vietnamese. It is high time that US
scientists join with their Vietnamese counterparts to do such
studies, and in March US Defense Secretary William S. Cohen gave
Clinton administration support to bilateral research projects.
</P>
<P>
   So far, studies done in the West have pointed to statistical
links between dioxin and diabetes, heart disease, and some cancers.
While the Vietnamese contend that dioxin is to blame for a range of
birth defects among children born in high-dioxin areas, US
scientists dispute their evidence.
</P>
<P>
   What is indisputable is that the world needs to know more about
dioxin, and Vietnam is _ sadly _ one of the best places to study
it. As Dr. Arnold Schecter, a professor of environmental science at
the University of Texas School of Public Health in Dallas, has
noted, everyone living in the industrialized world has dioxin in
his or her body.
</P>
<P>
   Dioxin hot spots show up in many parts of the globe; Baltic Sea
fish have been shown to have high levels, for instance. New studies
in Vietnam, combined with previous ones in the West, could provide
scientists with a better idea of what dioxin does to the human body
and what levels are unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States should do more than just cooperate with
Vietnam on dioxin research. We should be prepared to assist in
cleaning up areas of highest contamination, such as river
sediments, and in helping Vietnam deal generally with defoliation's
grim environmental and public health legacy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
