<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-VIRUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNLOVABLE BUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The streets have their usual version of calm, but there's chaos
in cyberspace. Massive _ and expensive _ damage has been caused by
a raging computer virus, the Love Bug. It's a high-tech plague born
from a very human _ and twisted _ heart.
</P>
<P>
   The virus may have come from the Philippines, possibly making it
an Internet Asian flu. It has infected millions of computers across
the globe at point-and-click speed.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail's subject says ``ILOVEYOU.'' Open it and there's an
attachment. Open the attachment, and the virus explodes. It
slithers into e-mail address books and resends itself to those
listed.
</P>
<P>
   The result is an infestation. E-mails have flooded and shut down
e-mail networks and destroyed data. Victims include the Pentagon,
the British House of Commons, the Danish Parliament, and companies
all over the world. Early guesses are that damages will cost
billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI has opened an investigation, but it will not be easy to
round up the usual suspects. Hackers can be almost anyone,
anywhere. Still, the usual human motivations stand out _ even in
the world of servers, drives, and bytes.
</P>
<P>
   The Love Bug seems like the work of some Superman comic book
villain who wants to take over the world: a vast, diabolical
project used to disguise a sad cry of ``Pay attention to me!'' It
is the manipulative gambit that recipients will find a message
saying ``I love you'' irresistible. It is that the three little
words may have sent a warm, electric rush through those who had
been waiting for a declaration of previously unspoken affection. It
is the chance that, for even a micro-second, someone believed an
e-mail could contain an epiphany.
</P>
<P>
   All the infected e-mails contain is a warning: The Internet is
vulnerable. What will protect us? There should be stronger
partnerships between governments and businesses to better unite law
enforcement and industry innovators.
</P>
<P>
   Shielding e-mail networks is a priority, because the system has
become a common but essential tool. And because, occasionally, we
do have profound things to say to each other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
