<SLUG> BC-WEB-MOVE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON`T EXPECT TOO MUCH FROM FIRST `FEATURE FILM' ON THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WINDA BENEDETTI  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the story of a quantum physicist in search of lost love, a
computer scientist who lost his way and a talking electron with a
few words to say.
</P>
<P>
   It's a film with big stars and a big budget and it's coming to a
home computer near you. Right now. Whenever you happen to have some
time to download it.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is called ``Quantum Project,'' a sci-fi tale about
technology and humanity and a young physicist caught in between. It
was released by SightSound.com late Thursday night and can be
downloaded to a computer _ if you happen to have a credit card
handy and somewhere between 15 minutes and four hours to transfer
it to your hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   SightSound.com is a Pennsylvania company that specializes in
downloadable movies and music. It's generated a fair bit of buzz by
billing ``Quantum Project'' as the first ``feature film'' to be
made for and distributed exclusively on the Web. Go to their site
and they'll tell how to get it.
</P>
<P>
   While the term feature film sounds pretty exciting, don't get
your hopes up too high.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the movie was produced by a major studio _ Metafilmics,
which made ``What Dreams May Come''.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there are some biggish-named stars in it _ Stephen Dorff
(``Blade''), Fay Masterson (``Eyes Wide Shut'') and John Cleese
(shouldn't have to tell you who he is).
</P>
<P>
   And sure, they spent lots of money making it _ $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this made-for-the-Web movie comes off on par with your
average made-for-TV movie: semi-cheesy special effects, weak
character development, mediocre plot (so maybe it's actually good
that it's a lot shorter, too).
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, although the distributors say the movie will cost
you only $3.95, you actually end up paying $5.95. Yes, that's
nearly $6 for a movie that lasts a mere half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   And although SightSound's technology is quite advanced, watching
a movie on your computer still leaves you with the feeling that you
might need glasses. The images are a bit blurry and they move a wee
bit haltingly.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's own AtomFilms.com offers far more clever movies made
for far less money.
</P>
<P>
   Their short films are ``streamed'' rather than downloaded, so
the visual quality isn't as high as SightSound's. But they also
don't charge any money to watch them _ which is the way it should
be until the visual experience is good enough to make
Net-distributed movies worth paying for.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: It's still way cooler to watch a movie on your TV,
and especially on a big screen.
</P>
<P>
   As far as Internet-delivered entertainment goes, ``Quantum
Project'' isn't a quantum leap, but it is an interesting _ if small
_ step in what is guaranteed to be the future of entertainment
delivery.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is already a major source of entertainment for a
growing portion of the world's population. Downloadable music is
flourishing. Would-be filmmakers are flocking to put their
low-budget films on the Net. And thousands of movie fans are
already downloading bootleg versions of their favorite movies _
``The Blair Witch Project'' and ``The Matrix,'' to name a couple.
</P>
<P>
   Movies are and will continue to be delivered via the WWW. And as
technology improves, they will become quicker to access and more
enjoyable to watch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
