A7145 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-SUPERMARKET-ST     05-05 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-SUPERMARKET-STOCKS-ART-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERMARKET STOCKS, IN THE BARGAIN AISLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, May 7) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHELLE LEDER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suddenly, the long-suffering supermarket sector seems an
attractive place for investors to shop. Those seeking safety in a
turbulent market have already begun to pile into what analysts
perceive as the highest-quality supermarket stock, Safeway. Despite
the pounding of retail stocks last week, its shares are up 20.3
percent so far this year; other grocery stocks have also shown
gains of late.
</P>
<P>
   Money managers and analysts say some of these companies _
including Safeway _ may still be good bets, particularly for
investors willing to take a longer-term approach.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Standard &AMP; Poor's retail food chain stores index
of five supermarket stocks fell 26 percent, versus a 20 percent
gain in the S&AMP;P 500, as investors fled value stocks in general and
low-margin retailers in particular. This year has been a different
story: the S&AMP;P retail food chain index is up 5.3 percent, compared
with a loss of 2.5 percent for the S&AMP;P 500. But Lisa Cartwright, an
analyst at Salomon Smith Barney, estimates that the group is still
trading at a 40 percent discount to the S&AMP;P 500, based on current
price-to-earnings multiples.
</P>
<P>
   The chains themselves have joined the buying spree. Last month,
the nation's two largest grocery chains, Kroger and Albertson's,
announced plans to buy back $750 million and $500 million of their
shares, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The attraction in a time of tumult is obvious. In the past,
grocery stocks have held up well during market downturns and
recessions, so the stocks are seen as good defensive plays. The
industry is likely to continue consolidating, many analysts say,
creating greater economies of scale and fattening what have long
been razor-thin net margins of 3 percent or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sector has good earnings growth and it's trading at close
to its 20-year lows in terms of valuation,'' said Mark Husson, an
analyst at Merrill Lynch. ``Food retailing stocks are stable and
solid. They have good earnings potential and the valuations are
very cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are risks. If the stocks are to stay
attractive, analysts say, earnings per share need to grow in the
range of 16 to 18 percent _ a level last achieved in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   While many analysts expect some of the companies to reach that
rate in 2000, they disagree on which ones will do so. Last year
earnings per share for the five stocks grew just 14 percent, on
average.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the threat posed by Wal-Mart Stores, which has
been rapidly pushing into the grocery business with its Supercenter
outlets. Wal-Mart Supercenters combine a large grocery store with
the traditional Wal-Mart discounted general merchandise in vast
stores of between 100,000 and 200,000 square feet. The company is
introducing the Supercenters at a rapid pace: there were 739 as of
March 31, compared with 582 a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Among the large chains, Kroger, of Cincinnati, faces the biggest
risk from Wal-Mart because of geographical overlap: Wal-Mart
operates Supercenters in about half of Kroger's 15 largest markets.
So far, Kroger is holding its own, according to analysts. Indeed,
Joseph Pichler, the chief executive, told analysts in a conference
call two months ago that Kroger had increased its market share in
five of the seven markets where it competes head-to-head with
Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're finding is that Wal-Mart is consolidating the
business, but that Kroger is still able to compete effectively,''
said George Thompson, an analyst at Prudential Securities. Thompson
said Kroger should have no problem achieving earnings-per-share
growth in the 16 to 18 percent range going forward.
</P>
<P>
   He has a strong buy on the stock and a 52-week price target of
$32; the shares now trade at $19.5625, or 14.5 times analysts' 2000
earnings estimate of $1.35 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Basu Mullick, co-manager of the Neuberger Berman Partners fund,
says Kroger presents an interesting risk-reward story because of
its $13.5 billion acquisition last May of Fred Meyer, a supermarket
chain based in Portland, Ore., that nearly doubled Kroger's size.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a combination of a terrific opportunity and a terrific
challenge,'' said Mullick, who had about 2.5 percent of the fund
invested in Kroger on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Others say the merger has made it more difficult for Kroger to
focus on its Internet strategy. Though Internet grocers are
struggling to turn profits, some analysts worry that traditional
brick-and-mortar chains will eventually feel some impact.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last month, Safeway has invested in Groceryworks.com,
an online grocer in Dallas, while Royal Ahold, the
Netherlands-based operator of Stop &AMP; Shop and Giant Food Stores,
has invested in another, Peapod of Skokie, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is clearly going to be a channel, even if the
model has not yet been figured out,'' Cartwright said. ``But it's
important to have a strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the run-up in Safeway's stock, it remains the favorite
of some analysts, largely because the company has avoided the big
acquisitions that Kroger and Albertson's have made.
</P>
<P>
   Safeway, which is based in Pleasanton, Calif., and operates more
than 1,600 stores, is often cited as having a strong management
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have have the integration risk that Kroger has'' as
a result of its merger, said Deborah Weinswig, an analyst at Bear
Stearns. Her 52-week price target for the stock is $65; the shares
closed on Friday at $43, or 19 times analysts' earnings estimates
of $2.23 a share for this year.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Albertson's, based in Boise, Idaho, is not
encountering major problems in its merger with American Stores,
completed last June, but analysts said it still has to prove that
it can handle increased competition from Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright has a hold on the stock and a 12-month price target
of $35. It now trades at $32.1875, or 12 times analysts' 2000
earnings estimates of $2.68 a share.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 2007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
