<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7149 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CISCO-ARROWPOINT-BOS &LR;      05-05 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISCO-ARROWPOINT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CISCO SWAPS $6 BILLION IN STOCK FOR ARROWPOINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Technology giant Cisco Systems Inc. announced its second biggest
acquisition ever Friday, snapping up ArrowPoint Communications Inc.
in a stock swap valued at $6.08 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ArrowPoint, a switching equipment maker that had its initial
public stock offering barely five weeks ago, is the largest
Massachusetts high-tech company to be acquired so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   The deal marks Cisco's 11th acquisition in New England since
1994, bringing its total investment in the region to nearly $10.3
billion. Ten of the companies it has bought are in Massachusetts,
and one is in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   New England, in fact, has become Cisco's largest base of
operations outside its home state of California. The San Jose-based
company is purchasing 580 acres along Interstate 495 in
Massachusetts to consolidate its holdings and expand further.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng Wu, founder and chief executive of ArrowPoint, said the
Acton, Mass. company would be a good fit with Cisco, an
infrastructure company that has prospered making the nuts and bolts
of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never expected all this to happen so quickly, but we always
felt that the technology we were developing would be very
signficant,'' Wu said.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco officials said they pursued ArrowPoint earlier this year
but held off making an offer once the small firm began preparing
for its public stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   ArrowPoint's value rose quickly as its shares climbed from an
IPO offering price of $34 a share to $118.48 in the first day of
trading. Friday, it closed at $140.1875 a share, up $5.375. Cisco,
meanwhile, closed at $67.75 a share Friday, up $4.125.
</P>
<P>
   Under the purchase agreement, Cisco will exchange 2.1218 shares
of its stock for each share and option of ArrowPoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cisco saw that ArrowPoint had products and capabilities it
needed,'' said William R. Becklean, managing director of technology
research at SunTrust Equitable Securities in Boston. ``And since
money is no object and (Cisco has) a philosophy of getting to
market before anyone else, it bought the company.''
</P>
<P>
   ArrowPoint is the largest of a group of companies developing
specialized switching products in the emerging field of Web traffic
management. Its software routes online transactions, or content,
from the browsers of individual users to computers best able to
handle search requests immediately. This quick flow of data is
known as content switching.
</P>
<P>
   Wu said he first identified the need for this kind of equipment
as Internet use exploded more than three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But only in the past 90 to 120 days, said ArrowPoint and Cisco
officials, did the market for content switching take off as large
companies such as MCI WorldCom, Excite At Home Corp. and Lycos
became ArrowPoint's customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (Cisco) did not want ArrowPoint to each their lunch,''
Becklean said.
</P>
<P>
   For Cisco, the leading supplier of Internet servers, switches
and routers, ArrowPoint's products filled a void in its product
line. And with a push from Cisco's massive sales force, the market
for content switching products is projected to increase to $2
billion by 2003 from $500 million this year, said Greg Geiling, an
analyst for J.P. Morgan Securities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw how fast the content networking arena was shaping up
and that we had to be in it,'' said Ammar Hanafi, Cisco's vice
president of business development. ``So it made sense to talk to
ArrowPoint again. Our discussions took a strategic turn after they
went public. We never made an offer before then.''
</P>
<P>
   ArrowPoint agreed to the acquistion, in part, because it could
grow more quickly under Cisco, said Lewis Volpe, ArrowPoint's
president and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   During the first three months of this year, ArrowPoint added 80
customers for its switching equipment. The price of the gear ranges
from $14,000 to $100,000 and more. ArrowPoint also hired more than
185 sales and support employees in the first quarter, boosting its
sales and marketing force to 337 at the end of March.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always felt that, if we were going to be acquired, we
preferred Cisco,'' said Wu, who with Volpe will continue to run
ArrowPoint under the umbrella of Cisco. Wu said they plan to expand
ArrowPoint employment to about 400 by year-end.
</P>
<P>
   Wu previously co-founded Arris Communications, which was
acquired by Cascade Communications Corp. of Westford, Mass. in
1996. He owns 2.58 million ArrowPoint shares, now worth $371
million in Cisco stock.
</P>
<P>
   ArrowPoint's largest shareholder is Matrix Partners, the
Waltham, Mass. venture capital company that helped Wu start
ArrowPoint. Matrix will receive Cisco stock valued at $1.1 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
