<SLUG> BC-MISS-FLAG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSISSIPPI PROMISES DIVERSE VIEWS ON NEW-FLAG COMMITTEE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., S.C., Ga.)   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A day after Mississippi learned that its bitterly
contested state flag had not been an official symbol for 94 years,
Gov. Ronnie Musgrove formed an advisory commission Friday to design
a new flag, guaranteeing a year of debate about whether the flag
should bear a Confederate symbol.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Mississippi Supreme Court ruled that because of
a legal technicality, the state had not had an official flag since
1906, when the Legislature forgot to include the flag in a
codification of state laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Confederate cross in the flag's left corner has been
criticized by many black residents over the years, but the court
said the flag had no legal status unless the government chose to
make it or another design the official symbol.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Jackson, Musgrove, a Democrat, said he
wanted the commission to ``take positive action,'' but he voiced no
opinion on whether the new flag should carry a Confederate symbol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Symbols mean a lot,'' he said, standing in front of a pole
bearing the current flag. ``They mean a lot to all of us. We want a
good, open, honest discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   He promised that the 17-member commission would be a diverse
group, containing members of both parties and black and white
residents. The commission will include three members of the State
Senate, three members of the House and 11 members appointed by the
governor from a variety of fields.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is to recommend a design by May 4 of next year,
according to the governor's executive order, which also mandates
that the current flag be kept in use until the Legislature acts.
The Legislature, however, is not required to approve the
commission's recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Several white members of the Legislature have already made it
clear that they want the current flag to be made official and that
they are not interested in a new design. But many black
legislators, who had already vowed to make the flag a major issue,
have welcomed the opportunity for a new design.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to the official use of Confederate symbols has been
growing in the South this year, spurred by the movement to lower
the Confederate battle flag from atop the South Carolina
Statehouse. That issue may be settled next week when the South
Carolina House votes on a plan to remove the flag and place a
smaller version in front of the Capitol, but five other states,
most notably Georgia and Mississippi, incorporate Confederate
designs into their state flags.
</P>
<P>
   Several Georgia legislators have promised to begin a movement to
change the state's flag later this year, and civil rights groups
have threatened an economic boycott of the state if it is not
changed. Up to now, opponents to the flag in Mississippi faced a
big challenge in getting it changed, but the court's ruling has now
created an opportunity to change the flag.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
