<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7153 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CONGO-U.N.-ART-NYT &LR;      05-05 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-U.N.-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. DELEGATION SEES DESPERATION IN CONGO UP CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain, Netherlands)  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANANGA, Congo _ They ran to the side of the road, scores of
people waving wildflowers or palm fronds or anything they could
pluck from trees lining the route.
</P>
<P>
   ``La Paix!'' they shouted. ``Peace! Peace!''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are saying, `The U.N. is coming and the war will end,'''
a Congolese doctor working for UNICEF said as a delegation from the
U.N. Security Council rode into Kananga, a town in south central
Congo that seems to be sliding downhill from collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Kananga has been designated one of four outposts of a U.N.
mission bound for Congo sometime this year, and three Security
Council members broke away from meetings in Kinshasa Friday to fly
here over a vast, deep green tropical jungle and take a look at
what was in store for the peacekeepers.)
</P>
<P>
   It was a voyage into the heart of sadness.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Jeremy Greenstock, the British ambassador, who had pressed
for this visit away from the politics of Kinshasa, was moved by the
passion of the crowd in a city that has no electricity, water for
only an hour a week, and the rusting remains of a great rail hub,
once the pride of a line that went all the way to Cape Town.
Thousands of emaciated refugees who have come to escape endless war
are as close as 50 or 60 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``You only have to see their faces,'' Greenstock said. ``You
have only to see the faces we saw on the streets of Kananga to see
how very deeply they want the U.N. to come here and bring peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter van Walsum, the Dutch ambassador, and Martin Andjaba, the
ambassador of Namibia to the United Nations, shared his bittersweet
reaction to the place whose fate may lie in their hands if the U.N.
Security Council decides the situation in Congo is safe enough to
send 5,500 peacekeeping troops. It was good, they said, to get away
from the diplomacy of capitals to see the reality. But the reality
was sobering.
</P>
<P>
   It was soon clear, traversing the rutted streets of Kananga and
catching glimpses of the buildings the U.N. mission in Congo may
have to inhabit, that this will be a mission with a challenge. And
a price tag. The startup costs in the first year alone may be $600
million. And that's just the projection.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be the most expensive peacekeeping operation
ever, per head of peacekeeper,'' Greenstock said. And putting it _
and the future of the Congo _ together, he said, is like walking
``on stepping stones in a river in the mist, where you can't see
where the next step is.''
</P>
<P>
   For the United Nations and its members, who will have to pay the
bill and send the troops, a policy of ``slowly, slowly'' prevails.
</P>
<P>
   For Andre Qabwe, a restaurant cook who was standing outside the
gate of the provincial governor's palace when the Security Council
delegation and the predictable swarm of ministers and outriders
arrived, that won't do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want them here this very night,'' he said, pointing
emphatically to the ground between his feet. ``We have suffered too
much, and now we need peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Kananga has a history of hardship. It was a town _ now swollen
to a city of 700,000 _ that opposed Mobutu Sese Seko, the dictator
who was driven from power in 1997 by Congo's current president,
Laurent Kabila. The provincial governor's father was killed by
Mobutu's thugs. But the victory of Kabila has not brought them
peace or a better life, a number of people in the crowds who
gathered Friday said. As in many places in the Third World, there
is hope that the United Nations will bring not only peace but also
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   It is a tall order for an organization that is not even sure the
peacekeeping operation in Congo will ever be deployed, given the
fragility of repeated cease-fires _ illustrated bizarrely Friday by
an outburst of fierce fighting between Ugandan and Rwandan troops
who are supposed to be united against Kabila's government, which
they once supported. Security Council diplomats, as they prepare to
meet the presidents of Rwanda and Uganda in the next few days,
wonder whether this points to another rearrangement of alliances.
</P>
<P>
   For two reporters who left the motorcade to visit the village of
Katora, several miles beyond Kananga, the human cost of war was
quite evident. Although Kananga and its immediate outlying areas
have been free of fighting, they have become places of refuge for
people from other towns with terrible stories to tell.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph is 9 years old but the size of a child half his age in
the richer world. He has never owned shoes. But last year he was
thrown out of a hamlet under attack 120 miles away and separated
from his family, so he decided to follow a soldier here to Katora _
on foot. Once here, a Belgian priest, Ivo Vanvolsem, took him in
and added him to his collection of desperate people who have lost
the wherewithal to survive in a country watered profusely by
rivers, replete with fertile land and studded with diamonds and
gold. Here, even the adult men are skeletally thin, wasting away
from a lack of nourishment.
</P>
<P>
   Lalula, a woman of about 30 from a distant village trashed by
war, saw her husband die. She found her way to Vanvolsem with three
of her children. One died on arrival, drained by malaria. She has
the passivity of the truly hopeless.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Mogwanja, a Kenyan who is the UNICEF representative in
Congo, said that women caught in the ebb and flow of war are more
than just victims of family tragedy these days; they are also among
the fastest-growing AIDS-infected population. Often, the cause is
rape. In Eastern Congo, he said, women have been raped repeatedly
as armies advanced, retreated, then advanced and retreated again.
These women carry immense burdens.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all these wars,'' Mogwanja said, ``the women are always the
losers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0308 </DOCNO>
