<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-PRIVACY-$ADV07-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO FAR, BIG BROTHER ISN'T BIG BUSINESS  
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 7) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SAUL HANSELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steven Kane thought he had concocted the perfect advertising
medium.
</P>
<P>
   First, in 1996, he created an Internet site called
Gamesville.com that let visitors distract themselves with bingo,
card games and quizzes _ typically for cash prizes.
</P>
<P>
   The contestants would willingly enter their names and addresses,
because otherwise how could Gamesville mail them their prize
checks? The advertising on the site, in turn, would be customized
to each user, based on all sorts of facts that Gamesville could
gather with that address from credit bureaus and mailing-list
houses.
</P>
<P>
   And all of this could hardly offend, Kane figured, because he
told users what he was doing. ``Our privacy policy was simple,'' he
said. ``Abandon all privacy ye who enter here.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan worked. Gamesville has attracted more than four million
visitors who entered their addresses _ information that turned out
to be the key to all sorts of other data, not just the usual lists
of magazine subscriptions and auto registrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can find out whether you are a person who lives on the edge
of your credit limit or pays your bills,'' he said, ``whether you
are a mountain guy or a beach guy.''
</P>
<P>
   There was only one problem: advertisers didn't much care. Most
just wanted to reach as large an audience as possible. Some used
the most basic pieces of data that Kane collected, aiming their
messages, say, at women or college students or people in the
regions where the advertisers have stores. But Kane's effort to
find debt-laden beach bums or Volvo owners who read Guns and Ammo
was to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   And that is the unspoken but enlightening secret about corporate
America's attempt to get even more personal with its customers. For
all the discussion about how the Internet is stripping consumers of
whatever thin veil of privacy they have left in this world of
credit bureaus and supermarket scanners, analysts have failed to
recognize just how ineffective most of these data-gathering systems
have been. Sure, many companies are trying to peer back through the
glowing screens at Internet users, but so far no one has been able
to make a big business out of being Big Brother.
</P>
<P>
   Many ad-driven Web sites, from Gamesville to giants like Yahoo,
have hoped that their clients will be willing to pay a premium for
the ability to aim ads at specific groups of users who, presumably,
will be more likely to buy their products. And database systems
have been promoted even more heavily by advertising networks, like
DoubleClick and Engage, that increasingly act as middlemen between
sites and advertisers, inserting ads into Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   The few advertisers that have tried these systems have not yet
given up on them. But most say the response to their ads does not
go up enough to be worth the extra cost and bother. It seems easier
for them to buy cheap shotguns, in effect, than expensive
laser-guided rifles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been overwhelmed by how underwhelmed I have been on
people's ability to deliver on the promise of targeting,'' said Dan
Springer, director of marketing of NextCard, a credit card company
that is one of the Web's biggest advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Some data marketing systems have already been abandoned _ though
that doesn't mean that privacy-rights advocates should be retiring
to count their successes. Many proponents of database marketing say
they are building new systems to overcome their temporary setbacks,
with more ways to collect and link data about users.
</P>
<P>
   ``Data is the holy grail,'' said Anil Singh, the senior vice
president for sales at Yahoo, which has based much of its business
strategy around database marketing. Yahoo's problem is that while
it can command high prices for advertising on some parts of its
site, like its stock quotation page and computer shopping area,
advertisers are willing only to pay much lower rates for others,
like e-mail and weather pages.
</P>
<P>
   So Yahoo's goal is to be able to track users so that advertisers
can find the ones they are looking for, whatever page they are on.
If it can identify those users who frequent the stock-quotation
pages, for example, Yahoo hopes to charge brokerage firms high
rates to reach them, even while they are checking the weather.
</P>
<P>
   Singh says such data-based targeting is essential.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't use data, you wind up with a bunch of excess
inventory,'' Singh said.
</P>
<P>
   But many advertisers, and even some operators of big Internet
sites, find that they do not need to look in keyholes to figure out
their best prospects. That is because the sites that people go to _
and the searches they conduct _ tend to reflect their interests
better than even the most elaborate mailing lists developed in the
pre-Internet era.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need to track people,'' said Robert Pittman,
president of America Online, which has disavowed the database
marketing techniques that are being offered to advertisers by other
big Internet sites. ``If you want to sell cars, you talk to people
when they are in the car area.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The failure, to date, of Web-based data-gathering systems is not
for lack of trying by Web sites and ad networks, which have worked
to gather and correlate information about computer users from a
wide range of sources.
</P>
<P>
   Sites can glean a few facts about users from the Internet itself
_ mainly, what type of computer and browser a user has and through
what network it is connected to the Internet. That lets advertisers
aim at corporate users in certain industries, say, or sometimes at
home users in certain cities.
</P>
<P>
   They can also follow surfing habits, keeping track of Web pages
that a user visits in order to infer his interests. Some also try
to use this information to predict users' demographic
characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   A site may gather personal information online by asking users to
register and fill out surveys, as is required by The New York Times
on the Web.Or a site may accumulate such data slowly, grabbing a
ZIP code, for example, when a user checks the weather, or a
birthday when he checks his horoscope. Many sites offer sweepstakes
to get users to enter their addresses and other information.
</P>
<P>
   Personal information is also obtained off line. Once a site
collects a user's name and address, it can buy other information
about him or her from mailing-list companies or, if it already has
a database, it can examine its own customer files.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this data-gathering relies on a technology that places
small files, known as cookies, on the hard drive of an Internet
user; these generally contain an identifying number. Cookies allow
sites to record each page a user sees and to show each user
different advertisements based on information in their files.
</P>
<P>
   With all these techniques, it would seem that Web sites could
collect vast dossiers on users. In fact, much of the available
information is crude, fragmentary and filled with errors.
</P>
<P>
   For example, though the network address can often pinpoint a
user's location, the 20 million users of America Online all show up
as living in Dulles, Va., where the company has its headquarters.
Moreover, most systems cannot figure out all the sites visited by a
user. Yahoo knows where users go on its own site but knows nothing
about where they go on other sites. Working with such a fragmentary
file is something like having only 50 pieces of a 500-piece jigsaw
puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   An ad network gets a broader view by inserting ads into Web
pages on a wide range of sites and by using a cookie to record
which sites are visited. But this method, too, provides information
on only a portion of the pages viewed by a user.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick, in fact, decided that its information on users'
surfing habits was so meaningless, at least for now, that it does
not even offer it to advertisers. (The company has become the
lightning rod for concerns over privacy issues, but the criticism
relates to its future plans to use data about people's mail-order
purchases, not its current practices.)
</P>
<P>
   MatchLogic, an ad network now owned by Excite(at)Home, has
collected personal information on 20 million users through a
multiplicity of techniques. Using banner ads on various sites,
MatchLogic runs contests to lure users into identifying themselves.
It also gains access to information when people register at and use
the Excite Web portal, and from other sites that agree to share
user identities.
</P>
<P>
   For these Web users, the company can customize advertising based
on their answers to questions. Moreover, it tries to use this hard
data to draw better inferences about 52 million other users on
whose computers it has placed cookies, examining their surfing
habits to reach conclusions about their interests and demographic
characteristics, even though it does not know their names.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking for signals and patterns in the data to figure
out whether you are male or female rich or poor, married or
single,'' said Mitchell Bennett, MatchLogic's vice president for
sales. But, he acknowledged, ``It's an art, not a science.''
</P>
<P>
   Matchlogic officials say that for now, use of its targeting
systems is small _ but that it is growing as advertisers learn how
to use them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get more mind-share from clients than spending,'' said
Martin Smith, MatchLogic's director of enterprise solutions. ``The
clients say we have to prove we are faster, better and cheaper for
them to use us. We will. This is like television in 1950.''
</P>
<P>
   Engage, an ad network that is partly owned by CMGI, is also
trying to deduce information about users by tracking where they
surf. It hopes to get a comprehensive picture of users' interests
by getting a big network of sites to feed the topics of all the
pages a user visits into a central database. In return for
providing the information, the sites have access to profiles of
individual users' interests; that, in turn, can be used to help
determine which ads to show.
</P>
<P>
   To get sites and users to cooperate, Engage promises that it
will not collect personally identifiable information like names or
addresses. The interest profile is simply associated with a cookie
on a computer's hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   The company has 52 million profiles, with information from 3,000
sites. Nonetheless, it has had trouble attracting either
advertisers or many of the most visited sites _ so much so, in
fact, that it has changed its strategy to also offer other, more
general advertising services.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the company says its data system will eventually prove
successful. ``We think the original premise is absolutely 100
percent on the money,'' said Paul Schaut, Engage's chief executive.
``Your past online behavior is the best predictor of your future
online behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Web sites and ad networks say advertisers have just been too
harried to learn how to use the database tools. But many
advertisers that have tried them find the results modest at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this stuff is the tail wagging the dog,'' said Al
Noyes, executive vice president for sales and marketing at
SmarterKids.com, an online seller of educational toys that has
tried various ad networks that promise to search out mothers of
young children. ``Maybe you can increase your returns by 10 or 15
percent, but it's not worth it for such a small increase to the
bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Web sites and ad networks see targeted ads as their premium
product, so they charge advertisers the full rate-card price _
typically $20 to $80 per thousand times an ad is shown.
</P>
<P>
   But because of the glut of available Web pages, site owners
often sell general advertising at heavy discounts, with prices well
under $5 a thousand available to advertisers who bargain well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found it much more effective to buy cheap media than to pay
more money to buy targeted ads,'' said Springer of NextCard.
</P>
<P>
   Some Web sites are themselves beginning to question whether they
come out ahead by charging a higher price for a smaller number of
ads. Many are concluding that they can make more money selling a
lot of broader ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a media company, you want to sell your entire base,'' said
Charles Ardai, chief executive of Juno Online Services, an e-mail
and Internet service company that initially hoped to sell focused
advertising based on responses of its users to a questionnaire.
``You don't want to sell an infinitely large number of infinitely
small segments. It's not a good use of our sales force.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
