<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-VIRUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNICIANS STRUGGLE TO STAY AHEAD OF MORPHING LOVE BUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Love Bug computer e-mail virus morphed into varients like
the Mothers Day Bug and the Joke Bug Friday, raising new hurdles
for technicians trying to corral the runaway code.
</P>
<P>
   The new bugs didn't appear more advanced than the original
virus, which has already disabled tens of millions of computers
worldwide including at least two classified U.S. military systems.
But their appearance meant more work for technicians and slowed
efforts to restore e-mail services at many companies who shut down
their systems Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, authorities were preparing to arrest a man in
Manila suspected of creating the virus, though the FBI and Justice
Department declined to confirm those reports.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, computer-security experts said the virus,
and the quick appearance of the copycats, show the Internet is more
fragile than many of its users assume.
</P>
<P>
   It may be years before businesses and Internet service providers
can make the medium as reliable as the telephone network, said Pete
Tasker, director of security of systems at Mitre Corp., a research
contractor in Bedford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   `It's the wild, wild West out there, and in many ways the Web
still is not a robust place to do business,'' Tasker said. ``Nobody
wants this to happen on a regular basis, but it's going to continue
at least for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   The Love Bug first appeared Thursday morning, presenting itself
as an attachment to e-mails with the words ``I Love You'' in the
subject field. If activated the attachment can delete audio and
graphic files as well as forward itself to other computers.
</P>
<P>
   The virus uses relatively simple computer code, but it is seen
as the most destructive example of its kind to date, with damages
estimated at $1 billion or more. Companies like Fidelity
Investments and Ford Motor Co. were forced to shut down their
e-mail systems or lose data.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most active virus we've encountered,'' said Jennifer
Latchford, deputy chief information officer for the City of Boston.
``The replication was unbelievably fast.'' The city's internal
e-mail service was only restored at noon to 5,000 users, 26 hours
after it was pulled off-line.
</P>
<P>
   At least 100 city computers were rendered useless and require
more servicing, said Latchford, who added Massachusetts and Maine
state agency mail servers would probably be down until next week.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Smith, a computer-security expert, said clues in the
virus' code suggested it originated in the Phillipines. In
Washington, FBI and Justice Department officials wouldn't discuss
their investigation except to repeat vows to track down the
creators of all types of the virus, just as they arrested the
author of the ``Melissa'' virus a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   That virus was designed to swamp e-mail systems, and the creator
pleaded guilty to causing $80 million in damages. But the Love Bug
is more dangerous because it seeks out and destroys certain audio
and graphics files.
</P>
<P>
   Also, at least five new versions of the Bug appeared that seemed
to be copycats, created by users who had made subtle changes to the
Love Bug's roughly 45 lines of code.
</P>
<P>
   The new strains bore titles like ``Very Funny'' and ``Mothers
Day Order Confirmation.''
</P>
<P>
   In the latter version, the body of the email includes a message
that the recipient has been charged $392.92 for a ``diamond
special'' and invites users to open an attached invoice file _
which activated the bug.
</P>
<P>
   Software companies said it wasn't clear just how extensive was
the damage from the copycats. But software to combat them quickly
became available, and for many techicians was a time of clean-up
rather than crisis.
</P>
<P>
   At Fidelity Investments, where almost all 30,000 computers have
e-mail accounts, employees were able to trade messages but remained
cut off from outside communication as of Friday afternoon, said a
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   At Cabletron Systems in Rochester, N.H., service was still slow
after its computers received 100,000 e-mail copies of the bug.
Technicians worked through the night, however, and employees
retained access to the Internet, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Carnegie-Mellon University's Software Engineering
Institute, said new reports of the Love Bug had trailed off Friday
afternoon, though they repeated warnings of the new version and
cautioned users not to open unfamiliar attachments.
</P>
<P>
   Some avoided the problem altogether. Wendy Wolfson, a
public-relations specialist, said she received three copies of the
Love Bug from clients on Thursday morning but deleted them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I instantly knew it was a virus, because nobody sends me love
letters,'' Wolfson said. ``The companies I deal with, they're just
not that effusive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
