<HEADER>
A7159 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-STOWAWAY-BODIES-SPI &LR;      05-05 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOWAWAY-BODIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WIDOW'S WISH FRUSTRATED BY POVERTY, TWO NATIONS' BUREAUCRACIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE and HSIAO-CHING CHOU  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Chen Shaolin has a simple wish: She wants to see her
husband.
</P>
<P>
   An ocean stands between the Chinese woman and Jiang Dainbiao,
dead since January. But the Pacific is nothing compared to the
seeming indifference of two governments, and the poverty in which
Chen and her two children are mired.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang and two other illegal immigrants were dead when the cargo
ship they were hiding in arrived in Seattle. Since then, the three
men's remains have been stored at the King County Medical
Examiner's Office, where officials wait for families to decide what
should be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to see my husband one more time, then I'll come
home,'' Chen said in a tearful telephone interview from her
in-laws' home in Fujian province. ``No matter how difficult it is
to go to America, I will go.''
</P>
<P>
   People from Fujian are used to hardships, especially where
America is concerned. Thousands have come to the United States,
arriving for supposed vacations, then disappearing. Hundreds have
braved ocean crossings in rusty fishing boats.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang and dozens of other illegal immigrants tried a different
tactic earlier this year _ cramming themselves into 40-foot cargo
containers, then crossing the Pacific in the black dankness of the
hold of a ship.
</P>
<P>
   In a little more than a week in January, four such containers
arrived in Seattle on ships from Hong Kong. Immigration agents
opened them to find 63 men who endured squalor and sea sickness
only to fail.
</P>
<P>
   The worst moment came Jan. 10 at Harbor Island. Acting on a tip,
immigration agents waited for a container from the NYC Cape May at
Terminal 18. Three of the 18 men inside were dead. Thirst and
starvation brought on by unending sea sickness took their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang Hui, a few days short of his 26th birthday, died first on
New Year's Day. He left a father and brother in China.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang, 35, died Jan. 7. Besides Chen, he left a daughter, Nana,
8, and a son, Jiazhi, 3, in Fujian.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu Benqing, 30, died two days later. He had a wife, Jiang
Saimci, and a 2-year-old daughter, Shiyao.
</P>
<P>
   Entombed in the hold of the ship, fellow stowaways pounded on
the sides of the container for help as the men died, said Alan Lai,
a counselor with the Chinese Information and Service Center in
Seattle. No help came.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't want to see people die,'' said Lai, who has talked
to the families of the dead men to try to offer help.
</P>
<P>
   One more container filled with stowaways arrived in Seattle
after the Cape May, then the human smuggling to the Northwest ended
_ temporarily, immigration officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service has detained the 60
stowaways who arrived in January. The U.S. Attorney's Office in
Seattle has been investigating the deaths.
</P>
<P>
   There is mostly waiting at the Medical Examiner's Office and in
China.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tangled, bureaucratic political situation,'' said Jerry
Webster, chief investigator at the Medical Examiner's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Until he hears from the families, the bodies will remain where
they are. ``If this goes on another year, those folks still will be
with me,'' Webster said.
</P>
<P>
   In China, three families want to come to Seattle to see their
loved ones. They fear that if the bodies are shipped home, the
Chinese government will dispose of them, allowing relatives neither
the opportunity to see them nor to perform final rites.
</P>
<P>
   Lai's social service organization has offered to help, as has
U.S. Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   But the State Department hasn't been encouraging about issuing
tourist visas to the relatives of illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``While their applications will receive every consideration
consistent with U.S. visa law and regulations, they should realize
their situation arises because of their relatives' attempt to enter
illegally the United States,'' Edward McKeon, U.S. counsul general
in Guangzhou, in Canton province, wrote in a telegram to Murray.
``This indicates the deceased did not believe themselves eligible
for United States visas.''
</P>
<P>
   The visas, Lai said, are the key. After that, money probably can
be raised in the Chinese community in Seattle to bring family
members here.
</P>
<P>
   Chen has been trying to arrange a visa interview in Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday I called five or six times, but they wouldn't help
me. They put the phone down and wouldn't even listen to me,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please help. I called five or six times, and they wouldn't
talk to me. I beg you to please help.''
</P>
<P>
   Life was never easy for Chen and Jiang. The government forced
him to have a vasectomy after the couple violated China's one-child
policy, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple scraped together $1,000 as a downpayment to the
snakeheads, as smugglers are called, to get to America and earned
needed money for his family. He left Fujian as 1999 ended.
</P>
<P>
   Now Chen said she lives ``one day at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Poverty has forced her and her children to move in with in-laws.
``There is no work,'' she said. ``I want to work, but there is
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   As she waits, Chen must face her son and daughter. For now, she
has kept the truth from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They call, `Daddy! Daddy!' But I had to lie to them. I told
them their Dad left for a faraway place to make money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 2026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0314 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7161 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INTERNET-PRIVACY-$ADV     05-05 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-PRIVACY-$ADV07-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: sales force.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   These disappointments do not come as a surprise to veterans of
the mail-order world, who have long used customer data and found
that database marketing has hardly been the panacea that was
predicted 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some pieces of data _ particularly information about
a customer's behavior _ have been enormously useful to certain
industries. Credit card companies, for example, found that people
who borrow a lot of money but pay it back are their best customers.
And direct-order merchants found that the best predictor of whether
someone would buy from a given catalog was whether he had recently
bought something _ anything _ by mail.
</P>
<P>
   But there are hundreds of other variables that are seemingly
just as logical but do not work as well, like ZIP codes or magazine
subscriptions.
</P>
<P>
   The effects of even the most advanced data analysis techniques
are not huge. In the direct-mail area, such techniques have allowed
the most sophisticated users of data to increase their response
rates by only tenths of a percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, such gains can be important; a company that spends $2
or $3 to mail a catalog has a lot of incentive to send it only to
people who are likely to respond. But because Internet marketing is
neither as expensive nor as precise, such fine-tuning has less
impact.
</P>
<P>
   More fundamentally, the often-quoted idea that that technology
lets companies market their products with a different message for
each consumer turns out to be hardly more practical than sending a
sales representative to every person's home.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of technology people with no direct marketing
backgrounds assumed that since the Internet allows you literally to
have one-to-one marketing, then that must be the holy grail,'' said
George Garrick, the former chief executive of Information
Resources, a big marketing data company, who later started and then
sold Flycast, an Internet advertising company. ``But they just
don't understand the law of diminishing returns. The more and more
finely you segment an audience, the less the increase in your
return on investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, efforts to develop even more elaborate database
marketing systems are continuing. Some ad networks have started to
link their cookie files to those of their clients, so that a
company's existing customers see different ads as they surf the Web
than new sales prospects do.
</P>
<P>
   For example, another advertising network, 24/7 Media, is
creating an ad for an online stock brokerage firm that will show
the brokerage's customers up-to-the-minute quotations on the three
largest holdings in their portfolios. The idea, naturally, is to
prompt them to trade. Others will see a promotion encouraging them
to open an account.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest effort by the ad networks is to move beyond data
about where people surf to customizing ads on the basis of what
people buy.
</P>
<P>
   That is the theory behind DoubleClick's recent acquisition of
Abacus Direct, which runs a consortium through which catalog
companies share information about the purchasing habits of their
customers.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick wants to learn the names and addresses of as many
Internet users as possible, by running contests and by having the
information referred from other sites that learn the identities of
users. This data, in turn, will let the company look up purchase
habits in the Abacus database and in a new consortium of online
merchants that DoubleClick is putting together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Transactions are the best predictor,'' said Kevin O'Connor,
chief executive of DoubleClick. ``If you buy a computer, you are
more likely to buy other computer products.'' (Doubleclick's plan
is on hold, however, until it works through the privacy concerns.)
</P>
<P>
   Others argue that the problem with database marketing on the Web
is not the data but rather the ineffectiveness of advertising on
Internet pages, especially with narrow banner ads. Indeed, many
advertisers are finding surprisingly good results by using
companies that have assembled lists of people who have agreed to
receive advertising by e-mail. Most ad networks have started or
have bought e-mail programs.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies say the real value of data will be realized after
a customer goes to the site of an online store or advertiser.
Amazon.Com, for example, has long used its records of customers'
past purchases to recommend other items that they may like.
Similarly, Fingerhut, a subsidiary of Federated Department Stores
that has opened an online retail operation, is trying to identify
all the Web surfers who have bought from its many catalogs; the
information will help it customize its home page to feature items
that they are most likely to buy.
</P>
<P>
   Angara E-Commerce Services, a software vendor, is using many of
the techniques of the ad networks to gather data about Web users.
But it will feed that information to Web sites so that they can be
personalized, even for people who visit them for the first time.
Its first client, Greatcoffee.com, features one of four different
coffees, depending on where the user lives.
</P>
<P>
   In a variation on banner ads, some companies have found ways to
get users to accept superimposed ads on the pages they are viewing.
Companies that offer free Internet service have such ads, as does a
company called Dash, which offers shopping discounts. The
technology allows them to record all the sites that their users
visit; Dash even plans to read all the pages to record what its
users are buying.
</P>
<P>
   Though advertisers have not been very interested in such data so
far, the ability to float an ad for one company directly over the
site of a competitor has been very popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``What better place for BMW to advertise than when someone is on
Mercedes' site?'' said Daniel Kaufman, the chief executive of Dash.
</P>
<P>
   The devotees of database marketing remain insistently loyal to
their work in progress. Kane, for one, figures that eventually
someone will get it right.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of interest by advertisers in its more
sophisticated targeting systems, Gamesville was one of the few
Internet companies to make a profit; it was sold to Lycos for $232
million in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gamesville.com barely crawled out of the primordial ooze onto
the beach,'' Kane said last month, shortly before leaving the
company. ``And our clients still have one fin and two cells. But we
will evolve.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
