A7163 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BAD-AIR0506-COX     05-05 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAD-AIR0506-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia's air quality problems call for more stringent standards
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Even as Atlanta struggles to resolve its ozone
problem, environmental officials are just beginning to tackle what
may be an even more dangerous pollutant _ ultrafine specks of soot,
dust, metals and other material that can penetrate deeply into the
lungs.
</P>
<P>
   It's called particulate matter, the solid component of smog and
the cause of the area's thick summertime haze. Ozone and
particulate matter mix together to form smog. While ozone is a
colorless gas, the particulates are visible in the form of the haze
over Atlanta on high-pollution days. And it may be a killer some
research indicates the tiny particles may be responsible for
hundreds of deaths in the metro area each year.
</P>
<P>
   New data released this week by Georgia Tech researchers shows
just how pervasive the problem may be. An analysis of monitoring
for ultrafine particulate matter nationwide in 1999 shows that
Atlanta's dirty air now rivals that of Los Angeles, long regarded
as having the nation's most polluted air.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, however, has been focusing its efforts almost
exclusively on reducing levels of ozone, the lung-scarring gas
responsible for metro Atlanta being on the federal government's hit
list of cities that violate clean air standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, Georgia is going to have to deal with particulate matter,
and that may be just as hard to resolve as ozone,'' says C.S.
Kiang, a professor in Georgia Tech's School of Earth and
Atmospheric Sciences. ``We are going to have to look at our air
quality problems wholistically, and not just focus on one pollutant
at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiang said new monitoring data shows that the entire state will
be out of compliance with new, more stringent standards for
particulate matter proposed by the Environmental Protection Agency.
Those standards are being challenged in a case being considered for
review by the U.S. Supreme Court. Trucking industry groups and
others charged that the standards were based on flawed data.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, EPA spokesman Dave Ryan said Friday the agency is
confident it will prevail in court. He said the agency is
proceeding with steps to put the new standards in place. The
monitoring data reported this week is part of that effort.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA's case was bolstered last month, when researchers
meeting in Atlanta said that even low levels of very fine
particulate matter raise the risk of death and serious illness. The
study examined the link between dirty air and human health in 90 of
the largest U.S. cities.
</P>
<P>
   It found that for every increase of 10 units of particulates in
the air, the risk of death rose by an average of 0.4 percent
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the meeting also affirmed two other studies which
the EPA cited in setting stricter limits on particulates in the
air.
</P>
<P>
   Research shows that the microscopic specks _ especially the
tiniest ones, 30 times smaller than a human hair _ may be sickening
thousands of Atlantans and hospitalizing many of them each year. A
1996 study by the Natural Resources Defense Council, a
Washington-based environmental science group, estimates that the
ulfrafine matter contributes to the deaths of up to 950 metro
Atlantans annually from acute respiratory illnesses and heart and
lung diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conclusions of the report are sound,'' Dr. Howard Frumkin,
chairman of Emory University's Department of Environmental and
Occupational Health, said this week.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Emory are in the midst of an 18-month study of
emergency room visits and hospital admissions to get a clearer idea
of the health effects of particulate matter.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
