<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH EYES ON ELECTIONS, LAWMAKERS DEBATE EDUCATION POLICY  
</HEADLINE>
 
  &HT;    (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from
the Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers)  By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN  
NYT Regional Newspapers  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Setting the stage for a November showdown, lawmakers are
sparring over education with Democrats and Republicans both making
the claim that they care more about America's classrooms and
children.
</P>
<P>
   But the two parties differ in their approach, and those
distinctions surfaced in the Senate where members debated a bill to
reauthorize the sweeping 1965 Elementary and Secondary Education
Act, which commits roughly $14 billion a year to more than 50
federal programs.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Republicans favor granting states and local school
districts more leeway in how they spend education money, and they
want to dismantle some of those programs. They also want to
introduce more accountability into the system.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Connie Mack of Florida, for example, wants to allow states
to use some money to establish merit pay programs for teachers
``without any additional Washington mandates.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats prefer to spend the money on specific programs or
initiatives, such as school construction or hiring more teachers.
They're leery of giving a blank check to states, fearing that poor
and disadvantaged children would lose.
</P>
<P>
   For all the partisan jabs, Democrats and Republicans have found
common ground in recent years. Consider that Republicans no longer
talk about dismantling the U. S. Department of Education as they
once did, and they have supported substantial increases in federal
spending on schools.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some moderate Democrats have also embraced the idea
that accountability ought to be an important part of any federal
initiative. In the Senate, Florida's Bob Graham, and Louisiana's
John Breaux and Mary Landrieu, are pushing a plan that calls for
pegging funding to academic performance standards that states would
have to set and meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time we challenge conventional thinking to improve the
way we educate our children,'' Breaux said.
</P>
<P>
   DOWN BY THE SCHOOLYARD
</P>
<P>
   Bringing the nation's schools up to snuff won't come cheap,
according to a new study from the National Education Association
that looks at costs from a bricks-and-mortar perspective.
</P>
<P>
   In what it described as the first-ever tally of the costs of
repairing and modernizing schools, the NEA put the expense at $322
billion nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Southern states were not exempt from the costs, but the push in
the region to make room for the unbroken flow of new students left
it in better shape than other parts of the nation, particularly the
Northeast and Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Still there is work to be done, the NEA report said, estimating
the bill for modernization at $2.3 billion in Alabama; $5.5 billion
in Florida; $8.5 billion in Georgia; $3.9 billion in Louisiana;
$1.6 billion in Mississippi; $7.5 billion in North Carolina; $3.3
billion in South Carolina; and $3.2 billion in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   BITTER SWEETS
</P>
<P>
   It's being cast by some as a David vs. Goliath battle, but a
fight over sugar imports really involves two giants.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. sugar lobbyists are upset with a Michigan refiner that they
say is bypassing quotas on foreign sugar imports by buying
so-called ``stuffed molasses'' from Canada. The company, Heartland
By-Products of Michigan, then distills the sugar from the syrup and
sells it.
</P>
<P>
   Heartland By-Products insists it's a victim of industry greed.
In ads, the company portrays itself as being crushed by ``Big
Sugar.'' In fact, Heartland is itself part of E D &AMP; F Man Inc., an
international corporation based in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hardly refer to this sophisticated multi-national
conglomerate as a beleaguered little David,'' said James Johnson,
president of the United States Beet Sugar Association.
</P>
<P>
   Siding with U.S. sugar interests, Sen. John Breaux, D-La., is
pushing for a bill that would raise tariffs on the sugar syrup, but
he recently lost an effort to attach the measure to another trade
bill.
</P>
<P>
   TUNED OUT
</P>
<P>
   The presidential candidates like to seem hip, but a recent study
of four media markets found that they're old at heart when it comes
to spending their campaign money.
</P>
<P>
   The study by Third Millennium, an advocacy group for Generation
X, found that the presidential contenders spent far more money on
political television ads that aired during shows aimed at older
viewers, who are more likely to vote. In other words, shows like
``60 Minutes'' trump ``Friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The group studied four markets: New York City, Los Angeles,
Manchester, N.H., and Greenville-Spartanburg, S.C., a key primary
battleground this past February.
</P>
<P>
   Brent McGoldrick, project director for Third Millennium, said
the results weren't surprising but underscore the generational
divide between young Americans and politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The candidates' spending priorities have shifted to Americans
50 and older,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin are in the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 2029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0318 </DOCNO>
