<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7167 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PHILIPPINES-HOSTAGES-     05-05 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILIPPINES-HOSTAGES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INNOCENTS IN WEB OF PHILIPPINE TERROR
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines _ They are schoolchildren, teachers and a
group of mostly European holiday makers _ true innocents who have
been caught for weeks in a pair of terrifying kidnappings in the
lawless jungles of the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Their captors, a small army of Islamic separatist bandits, have
herded them up mountains and down riverbeds, to the sound of
gunfire from pursuing Philippine troops. Last weekend, as
government troops closed in on one group, the kidnappers executed
four Filipino captives, including a Roman Catholic priest.
</P>
<P>
   With the government taking a hard line and the kidnappers making
wild threats and even wilder demands, there seems, for the moment,
little hope of freedom for the hungry and frightened hostages.
</P>
<P>
   The longest held of the groups includes a dozen children and
teachers, the last of about 50 people kidnapped from two
schoolhouses on March 20. When 15 children and teachers were
rescued last weekend, they described beatings, torture and abuse.
</P>
<P>
   There are 21 people in the second group, kidnapped from a nearby
Malaysian resort island on Easter Sunday. In addition to local
workers, they include two South Africans, a Lebanese, three
Germans, two Finns and two French travelers. Although the
kidnappers recently said two of those hostages had died, emissaries
who visited Friday said all were alive.
</P>
<P>
   On a videotape made by a local journalist one week ago,
foreigners in the second group said that they were not being
treated badly but that they were sick and hungry. In tears, they
pleaded for their freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The hostage taking is as complex as it is seemingly senseless,
the full expression of a lawless world of pirates, smugglers and
warlords, where kidnapping for ransom is a business and religious
wars are fought by throwing bombs into markets and churches.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 30 years, various Islamic separatist groups have
battled the government on the island of Mindanao, some 500 miles
south of Manila. The conflict has taken as many as 120,000 lives
and has helped to keep the island of 17 million people one of the
poorest areas in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   In this largely Roman Catholic nation of 74 million people, the
Muslims of Mindanao have never been assimilated and have lived _
for four centuries _ in continuing conflict with the island's
Christians.
</P>
<P>
   The kidnappings are the work of a fundamentalist splinter group
called Abu Sayyaf, or ``Bearer of the Sword'' in Arabic, a group of
as few as 200 fighters whose founder was trained in Libya and
fought in Afghanistan. It is a group whose trademark is bloodshed
rather than policy _ it is known for kidnappings, church bombings
and the massacre of 53 people in 1995 _ and it counts other Islamic
groups, as well as Christians, among its enemies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Abu Sayyaf are bandits masquerading as religious
fundamentalists, giving Muslims a bad name,'' said Col. Hilario
Atendido, a military spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The current standoff began when the children and teachers were
seized six weeks ago, along with the priest, from two schools on
the small island of Basilan, in the Sulu Sea, where pirates and
bandits have held sway for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   At first the kidnappers seemed to be demanding certain fishing
rights and a large sum of money. Then they insisted that a popular
action-movie actor, Robin Padilla, act as a negotiator. He posed
for photographs with them and won the release of two hostages.
Then, in what seemed to be an attempt to gain support from Islamic
militants abroad, they demanded that the United States release
Ramzi Yousef, who is serving a 240-year sentence for the bombing of
the World Trade Center in New York in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   When the president of the Philippines, Joseph Estrada, brusquely
rejected that demand, they announced that they had beheaded two
hostages, a claim that is widely doubted here. They have since
threatened to behead some of their foreign hostages if the
government does not withdraw its troops.
</P>
<P>
   On April 22, the army launched a major ground and air assault on
the Abu Sayyaf camp deep in the jungles of Basilan. One day later,
six men with AK-47 assault rifles landed in a motor launch on the
tiny Malaysian island of Sipadan, an exclusive diving resort with a
coral reef that the explorer Jacques Cousteau once called ``one of
the 10 wonders of the underwater world.''
</P>
<P>
   The kidnappers arrived at dinner time, bursting into a dining
hall and shouting, in English and Malay, ``Be quiet or we will
shoot you all!''
</P>
<P>
   An American couple escaped but the other tourists, along with a
dozen local workers, were herded onto the boat and taken one hour
across the sea to the island of Jolo, some 50 miles from Basilan
island.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the age-old bloodletting of Mindanao was an
international affair. Foreign governments began to press the
Philippines to tread gently, but the government has taken a hard
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military will never retreat,'' said Defense Secretary
Orlando Mercado. ``If the military withdraws, the Abu Sayyaf will
be in control.''
</P>
<P>
   So the foreigners _ along with the local schoolchildren and
their teachers _ find themselves pawns in a nightmare of ancient
hatreds and rivalries, strange foreign creatures who cannot begin
to comprehend this brutal, insular world.
</P>
<P>
   The hostages are accustomed to a European life with European
comforts, said Marie Michel Moarbes, a Lebanese hostage, on the
videotape. Now, ``it's getting very, very hard,'' she said. ``We
don't have enough food. We don't have anything to drink. We don't
have anything.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``I will never go to another Asian place, starting
from now.''
</P>
<P>
   The local hatreds and rivalries have produced a bizarre
counterkidnapping in which a group of anti-rebel vigilantes seized
nearly a dozen members of the family of the Abu Sayyaf leader,
Khaddafi Janjalani, last month.
</P>
<P>
   When Abu Sayyaf freed 18 of the hostages from the school, the
vigilantes freed Janjalani's mother, pregnant wife and 1-year-old
daughter. But they still hold nine other relatives.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   All of this may be little more than a violent sideshow to the
main Muslim insurgency in Mindanao, carried out by the Moro Islamic
Liberation Front. That group of about 15,000 fighters was formed 22
years ago as a splinter from what was then the mainstream Moro
National Liberation Front.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 the latter group reached an accommodation with Manila.
The group's leader, Nur Misuari, is now a government go-between
with the Abu Sayyaf group.
</P>
<P>
   Peace talks with the Moro Islamic Liberation Front broke down in
mid-March, and, coinciding with the Abu Sayyaf kidnappings, that
group has begun a new campaign of violence that has included a
series of bombings and the brief kidnapping of 100 people on a
pineapple plantation.
</P>
<P>
   According to the government, that separate surge of violence has
taken more than 300 lives and has forced more than 100,000 people
to flee their homes to escape the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   As the different local groups circle one another and the
military mounts its separate counterinsurgency campaigns, the
hostages are marched from one hideout to another, their feet
bruised and bleeding, as they comfort one another and capture
rainwater to drink, according to some of the rescued victims.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, just one step behind them, the military seized a
bamboo hut where the foreign hostages had been held. They found
some medicine that had been brought by a doctor, evidence of a
hasty departure. And they found three room keys from the Malaysian
diving resort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
