<HEADER>
A7172 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CYBERSEX06-COX     05-05 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSEX06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Siren song of cybersex strengthens
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   They just can't pull the plug.
</P>
<P>
   Cybersex has gone beyond a flirtatious romp online for many
Internet users, with more than 2 million users now considered
serious addicts _ people who chat or visit pornography sites so
often it interferes with their off-line lives.
</P>
<P>
   And with more than 60 million Internet users tapped in at work
stations, on laptops and, soon, through their microwaves, that
number is expected to explode, experts said during a daylong
symposium in Atlanta, part of the National Council on Sexual
Addiction and Compulsivity annual conference.
</P>
<P>
   Women and gay men appear to be more susceptible to the
cyber-siren's song because the Internet gives them the ability to
experiment and explore their sexuality with less fear of disease,
abuse or discovery, panelists said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is a great equalizer,'' said Al Cooper, clinical
director of the San Jose Marital and Sexuality Centre and author of
one of the most comprehensive studies of cybersex. ``The Internet
provides a way that women can experiment and be free to explore,
but it's also getting a lot of them in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Children are also vulnerable, still too young to understand and
fear the deep waters they're trolling. For example, Vermont
counselor Robert Freeman-Longo discussed how he ventured into
sexual chat rooms under various identities to test the
participants' response. When he identified himself as a 15-year-old
boy in search for adult women, he was chastised and told to get
out. But when he identified himself as a 14-year-old girl, one man
_ in a different state _ said he would arrange to meet
Freeman-Longo (posing as the girl) at her school.
</P>
<P>
   And the ones who are hooked are wrecking careers, marriages and
family lives. A primary cause: an increasing lack of, as experts
say, face-to-face time.
</P>
<P>
   And society is still grappling with what exactly is a violation
of marital trust. Initially, husbands and wives tend to play down
their spouses' interactions on the Internet, thinking it's
harmless. But then they discover a cache of e-mail or pornographic
material, it leaves them devastated.
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Young, director for the Center for On-Line Addiction,
said she had one client, married 38 years, who discovered six
months after her husband's death explicit e-mail he had written to
27 women.
</P>
<P>
   And many partners believe their fight doesn't involve real
people but fantasies created within their own home. ``I felt like
he was choosing between me and it,'' one woman wrote in a survey
about cybersex. ``And it usually won.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you're doing something that you and your spouse
can't talk about, you've got a problem,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment for such addicts needs to model treatment for food
addiction, experts say. And often that means users need to move the
computer back into a public place _ such as the den or living room
_ dismantle bookmarks and subscriptions, install software or use a
server that will filter out porn sites, and strictly monitor time
spent on the computer with an alarm clock if they need to use it
for work or other tasks.
</P>
<P>
   Snapshot of cybersex
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Of those who participated in cybersex activities, 91.7 percent
reported they spent less than 11 hours a week in online sexual
pursuits. Of those, half spent less than an hour a week.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  70 percent of e-porn activity occurred between 9 a.m. and 5
p.m. workdays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  49.9 percent of the men who engage in cybersex activities look
at visual erotica; 23 percent of women did the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  48.6 percent of women preferred sexually explicit chat rooms;
22.8 percent of men did.
</P>
<P>
   Source: ``Sexuality on the Internet: From Sexual Exploration to
the Pathological Expression.'' (For the full study, go to
www.sex-centre.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
