<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7173 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-885&AMP;A     05-05 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-885&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. JOBLESS RATE DROPS BELOW 4 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The United States' unemployment rate fell below 4 percent in
April for the first time in 30 years, the Labor Department
announced Friday, as employers hired, among others, tens of
thousands of census takers, restaurant employees and temporary
workers in a boom that showed no signs of letting up.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there was little evidence in the employment numbers _ a
total of 340,000 new jobs last month and a jobless rate of 3.9
percent _ that the 9-year-old expansion, the longest period of
uninterrupted growth in U.S. history, might be weakening in
response to the Federal Reserve Board's attempt to slow the economy
by raising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere you look, you see the supply of people available
for work continuing to shrink pretty rapidly,'' said John
Youngdahl, a senior economist at Goldman, Sachs. ``Although there
is not much pressure yet on companies to raise prices, the
inflation rate has begun to creep up and the Fed must think about
where we will be a year from now.''
</P>
<P>
   The economy may be in its best shape since the 1960s, but the
Fed's great fear, often expressed by its chairman, Alan Greenspan,
is that job shortages will eventually give workers enough
bargaining power to push up labor costs ahead of productivity
gains.
</P>
<P>
   While wage gains remained relatively modest and many of the
latest jobs _ including those created by the Census Bureau _ are
temporary, employers may still raise prices because of the higher
costs resulting from the tight labor market _ or simply because the
strong economy allows them to.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street reacted as if the Fed would be successful in
containing any inflationary threat, even if that meant it would
have to be more aggressive in raising interest rates. Stock prices
shot up, instead of tanking, as they often do in reaction to a
strong employment report. The Dow Jones industrial average gained
more than 165 points to close above 10,577, the Nasdaq rose 2.6
percent and bond yields edged up only modestly.
</P>
<P>
   Just a week ago, the consensus among analysts and brokers was
that the Fed's policy-makers would probably raise the short-term
interest rates that it controls by one-quarter of a percentage
point to 6.25 at their May 16 meeting. That would be the sixth such
increase since last June.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts now expect a half-percentage-point increase in
rates in May, with more increases likely to follow later. Wall
Street's exuberance, however, seemed to reflect a view that half a
percentage point in midmonth should be enough to finally make a
dent in the robust economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``God only knows why the markets are doing what they are
doing,'' said David Wyss, chief economist at Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI.
``All I can figure is that they figure the Fed is going to do a
half-point and that will be it. Get the tightening over, and they
can go back to business as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wyss and other economists noted that a booming stock
market complicates the Fed's task by encouraging the all-out
consumer spending that has kept the economy booming. ``The stock
market certainly did not help the Fed out,'' Youngdahl said,
referring to Friday's jump.
</P>
<P>
   April's employment report was striking for the evidence it
offered that the nation's pool of people still available for hire
is drying up fast. That pool shrank by 426,000 to under 9.9 million
last month, the lowest level since the Labor Department began to
track it in 1994. Greenspan pays particular attention to this
statistic because with fewer people available, existing workers _
in theory at least _ are in a better position to demand and receive
strong wage increases.
</P>
<P>
   With the unemployment rate falling from 4.1 percent to 3.9
percent _ the lowest since January 1970 _ the pool now consists of
5.5 million people labeled as officially unemployed because they
are actively looking for jobs, and 4.4 million others who tell
Labor Department surveyors that they want to work but are not
currently looking.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is clearly some evidence of accelerating wages and
prices,'' said Jared Bernstein, a labor economist at the Economic
Policy Institute, noting that labor costs, by several measures, are
growing at an annual rate of at least 3.6 percent, and the consumer
price index is rising at a similar pace.
</P>
<P>
   But he wondered whether wages were pushing prices, or the other
way around. ``If you track this month to month,'' he said, ``it
looks more like tight labor markets are allowing workers to press
for wage gains to keep up with prices that reflect the rising cost
of oil.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the cause and effect, the average hourly wage of
production workers rose 6 cents last month, to $13.64, up 3.6
percent over the past 12 months. That is roughly in line with the
gains recorded month after month for more than a year. But broader
measures, covering benefits as well as wages, show a recent jump in
what companies pay for health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the Clinton administration's concern that an overly
aggressive Fed could damage the economy in an election year, Alexis
Herman, the secretary of labor, argued that labor productivity is
rising quickly enough to offset rising wages. ``In the midst of
this debate over interest rates,'' she said, ``we must keep the
focus on the nation's strong productivity to absorb any pressure on
wages.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   President Clinton, pointing to the social benefits of a strong
economy, called attention to ``the lowest unemployment rate for
blacks and Hispanics ever recorded.'' For Hispanics, unemployment
dropped to 5.4 percent from 6.3 percent in March, and for blacks
the rate edged down to 7.2 percent from 7.3 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
   While spread broadly across business and government, job
creation was particularly strong at the Census Bureau, which added
73,000 part-time census takers last month on top of the 115,000
added in March. But that hiring will taper off quickly. To count
the population, the bureau has hired 500,000 workers this year and
now is up to full strength, a spokesman for the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the employment gains of 340,000, while strong, were
down from an even stronger 458,000 advance in March. But job
creation in the private sector remains robust, averaging 222,000 a
month since January, up from 198,000 a month last year. Total
employment rose to 131.1 million in April.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants made the the biggest contribution, adding 80,000
jobs, while temporary-help agencies added 46,000 jobs. ``Companies
cannot find people, so they turn to the temp agencies, which are
luring the elderly back into the work force, kids into part-time
work and housewives into work,'' Wyss said.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of the population now holding jobs edged up last
month to a record 64.9 percent, from 64.7 percent in March. Only
one industry lost ground: Employment in construction fell by 55,000
after having risen by 90,000 the month before.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers also increased their rolls, but by only 11,000
jobs, although the work week in manufacturing rose by nearly half
an hour, and overtime pay also rose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
