<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, MAY 6
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-PUERTORICO-BASE-NYT (moved on Wednesday, May 3)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, May 3,
about demonstrations against United States military operations on
the island of Vieques referred incorrectly to the earlier prison
release of one protester, Lolita Lebron. Convicted in the attack by
Puerto Rican nationalists on Congress in 1954, she was granted
clemency by President Carter in 1979. She was not pardoned by
President Clinton last fall.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-GENE-THERAPY-NYT (moved on Wednesday, May 3)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, May 3,
about the death of a patient in a gene therapy experiment at St.
Elizabeth's Medical Center in Boston misidentified the authority to
which the hospital failed to report the death. It is the
institutional review board of St. Elizabeth's, not the Food and
Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   BC-BOSTON-REPORTER-NYT (moved on Thursday, May 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, May 4,
about the Boston Herald's suspension of a consumer affairs
columnist, Robin Washington, misstated his account of the cause.
Washington has said publicly that he believes he was originally
demoted after a bank, the FleetBoston Financial Corp., complained
about his columns on its fee structure. He said he was then
suspended after asserting publicly that the bank influenced
coverage. He did not say he believed he was suspended because of
pressure from the bank.
</P>
