   &UR; AUTOS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAR-SMART (Undated) _ Ford's car-truck-SUV combo may seem like
the biggest compromise since the bicameral legislature, but for
buyers who can't be pigeon-holed into a particular lifestyle, the
vehicle may come as a pleasant surprise. By Dan Lienert.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT-CARS (Undated) _ Since ``sport utility vehicle'' entered
the common lexicon, the taxonomists of the auto business have been
pulling out their wiry hair trying to keep up with the diversity of
the four-wheeled kingdom. Should one, for instance, accept BMW's
classification of its X5 as a ``sport activity vehicle''? Is that
different from an ``all activity vehicle,'' which is what Mercedes
calls its M-Class? Whatever term should come of age, it had better
grow up quick, since five- and six-passenger pickups with four
sedan-style doors and shortened cargo beds are barging into the
market like an enraged SWAT team. By Dan Neil.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-SHORTAGES (Undated) _ With auto sales booming along with the
economy, consumers who want a hot-selling vehicle are struggling to
find the unfindable, which this spring includes eye-catching models
like Chrysler's PT and the Toyota MR2 Spyder sports car, the
eminently practical Honda Odyssey minivan and luxury vehicles like
BMW's X5 sport utility and Mercedes' flagship S-Class lineup.
Orders go on waiting lists and languish unfilled for months. By
Micheline Maynard.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
nn
