<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service has moved the following articles
for release Sunday, May 7:
</P>
<P>
   All articles from Arts/Entertainment, Business and Style have
moved. Articles from the Week in Review section will move Saturday
morning:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARTS/ENTERTAINMENT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Moved in `e' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COVER STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MOGUL-IMAGE-FILMS (Hollywood) _ When Budd Schulberg dreamed up
Sammy Glick _ the ultimate Hollywood wheeler-dealer, back in the
1930s, he meant his novel, ``What Makes Sammy Run?,'' to be seen in
part as a cautionary tale. Back then, Sammy Glick was the villain
of the piece, the awful example of what might happen if you let
individualism and free-enterprise run away with you. But Not until
the 1970s did Schulberg notice the beginnings of a ``180-degree
turn in our national attitude toward Sammy.'' By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   INDEPENDENT-TV (Los Angeles) _ For more than two decades, Robert
Greenwald, a prolific television producer, has owned the films he
made, which gave him the leverage to do such Emmy Award-winning
shows as ``The Burning Bed'' and ``A Woman of Independent Means.''
But now Greenwald and virtually every other producer of films and
series is under powerful pressure to yield to the networks and
allow them to own the shows. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HAMLET-FILM (Undated) _ Given the story's familiarity, it seemed
altogether natural to locate a new ``Hamlet'' in the immediate
present, to translate the Danish kingdom into a multimedia
corporation, and to watch the story unfold in penthouse hotel
rooms, sky-level office corridors, a coffee shop, an airplane, the
Guggenheim Museum. Director Michael Almereyda discusses his
decision to bring Hamlet into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   HEART-FILM (Undated) _ The first-time writer-directors Anthony
Stark and Sean Smith, best friends since high school, are in a
difficult position when they talk about their new movie, ``Into My
Heart,'' a dark story about two men, best friends since childhood,
whose relationship takes a tragic turn after they grow up and get
married. Stark and Smith's reluctance to admit that their art may
imitate life could be more than the usual insistence by writers
that their creation is a work of fiction. By Dana Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   LANCASTER-FILM (Undated) _ In many ways, Burt Lancaster is the
antithesis of the modern leading man. Today's young actors build
themselves the bodies of athletes. He was an athlete who built
himself into an actor. Lancaster was both of his time _ a
golden-age Movie Star _ and way ahead of it. As an independent
producer, he helped sabotage the studio system that made him, at
one time, the highest-paid actor in the world. By Rick Marin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY-REUNION-THEATER (London) _ T.S. Eliot's ``Family
Reunion'' has risen greatly in critical esteem since it flopped in
the West End 60-odd years ago. Many now regard the poet's story of
the English lord impelled by updated Furies to atone for his wife's
dark death as the nearest to a theatrical masterpiece Eliot ever
wrote. New Yorkers will make up their own minds when the Royal
Shakespeare Company's revival opens at the Brooklyn Academy of
Music on Wednesday. By Benedict Nightingale.
</P>
<P>
   ORESTEIA-THEATER (Undated) _ Murder. Adultery. Courtroom drama.
A fugitive's hair-raising flight from implacable justice. With
super-heated elements like these to work with, it's no wonder
modern playwrights keep rewriting Aeschylus' ``Oresteia,'' the
fifth-century B.C. dramatic trilogy about a family ensnared in
guilt and violence. By Celia Wren.
</P>
<P>
   GUARE-THEATER (New York) _ John Guare's play ``Gardenia'' begins
in 1875 with Joshua Hickman reading from Walt Whitman's poem ``On
the Beach at Night Alone'': ``A vast similitude interlocks all.''
That quotation about the interconnectedness of humanity is the
central theme of the 1982 play and of the cycle of plays of which
``Gardenia'' is a part. Whitman's line was also at the heart of
``Six Degrees of Separation,'' Guare's 1990 play about the idea
that ``everybody on this planet is separated by only six other
people.'' In the world of Guare, a vast similitude interlocks all.
After years of revising that earlier cycle, he has reordered it
into two plays under the collective title ``Lydie Breeze.'' By Mel
Gussow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-COMEDY-TV (Undated) _ The proportion of viewers
admitting that they get their politics from television comedy may
not be overwhelming. But considering that the 1996 presidential
election was decided by a mere eight percentage points, what each
and every consumer of comedy on television takes away from the
experience can be highly significant. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JOPLIN-MUSIC (Undated) _ When the directors of Opera Theater of
St. Louis began planning its 25th anniversary season, the idea of
presenting Scott Joplin's ``Treemonisha'' as its opening production
seemed a natural. It was in St. Louis that Joplin conceived and
largely composed ``Treemonisha,'' a tender story of a Negro
community on a plantation abandoned to its former slaves in
Reconstruction-era Arkansas. And yet, the directors of the Opera
Theater hesitated for some time about presenting ``Treemonisha''
out of concern for the Joplin's text, which is riddled with what
audiences today might consider demeaning Negro stereotypes and
dated dialogue. By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   BEETHOVEN-MUSIC (Undated) _ When in the course of human events,
musicians feel impelled to declare to the world and to themselves
the highest ideals of which the individual and humanity are
capable, the composer to whom they are most apt to turn is
Beethoven. By Matthew Gurewitsch.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRO-ACOUSTIC-MUSIC (Undated) _ Electro-acoustic
improvisation is a growing phenomenon in the music world. By Ben
Ratliff.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ABT-DANCE (New York) _ With the turn of the millennium, American
Ballet Theater moved into overdrive on its new production of ``Swan
Lake.'' The production will have its New York premiere at the
Metropolitan Opera House on May 19 and is expected to be the
blockbuster of the company's 60th-anniversary season, which opens
with a gala performance May 8 and runs through July 1. By Iris
Fanger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART/ARCHITECTURE/PHOTOGRAPHY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCHWARTZ-PHOTOGRAPHY (New York) _ When he saw a camera obscura
on the roof of a private museum in Kyoto in 1991, Charles Schwartz
knew he had to have one. So now, poking through the roof of his
staid apartment building on the Upper East Side, is a jaunty,
medieval-looking turret that holds the telescopic lens and mirror
of what surely is the only camera obscura of its size in Manhattan,
and one of the very few private devices of its kind in the world.
By Grace Glueck.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-CHINA-ART (Santa Ana, Calif) _ The opulence of China's
last imperial rulers is an ever-present thread in the largest-ever
exhibition of national treasures from China's Imperial Palace,
installed in February at the Bowers Museum of Cultural Art, a
Spanish-style hacienda near downtown Santa Ana, Calif. By Andrea
Adelson.
</P>
<P>
   PARIS-COMMUNE-ART (Paris) _ The Paris Commune of 1871 is one of
those smoldering ruins in French history. As the first news event
in French history covered by photographers, the Commune and its
aftermath also left a unique visual record, as a compelling new
exhibition at the Musee d'Orsay, on view until June 11, makes
clear. By Richard C. Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Moved in 'T' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-VENEZUELA (Caracas) _ Venezuelan tourism hit hard by
floods. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-PA-INTRUDERS (Undated) _ The lovely farmland enshrined in
memory is changing _ fast. First-person essay by Jan Benzel.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Lead item: Chicago views the largest
Tyrannosaurus Rex ever found.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Travel questions and answers: Motorcycle
tours in Europe; Traveling to Lourdes; Listening to on travel. This
week: Nepal treks; From Italy to Dubrovnik; Glasgow city tours. By
Paul Freireich.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ The Internet's sea of travel
medicine. By Betsy Wade.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BARGAINS (Undated) _ Deals and discounts: B&AMP;B the French
way; sailing the Mediterranean; El Al companion fares; Tour of
Thailand. By Janet Piorko.
