<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7182 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-VIRUS0506-COX     05-05 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRUS0506-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New strains of Love Bug virus surfaceBy Heather Cocks
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ At least seven variations of the devastating
``Love Bug'' virus floated through cyberspace Friday, one
masquerading as a virus warning and another pretending to be an
electronic receipt for a diamond Mother's Day present.
</P>
<P>
   But as they scrambled to track the new bugs, anti-virus
researchers braced themselves for a fresh bout with the old one.
This weekend, experts say they expect to see a smaller-scale flurry
of Love Bug attacks caused by people who didn't check their e-mail
during the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of home computer users wait to read messages until the
weekend, so we speculate that there will be a spike in virus
reports,'' said Eddy Hsia of McAfee.com Corp., part of anti-virus
software maker Network Associates Inc. ``Corporate reports have
tapered, but who knows what will happen (Saturday).''
</P>
<P>
   The new strains have different names, but the damage reportedly
remains the same as Love Bug which ravaged e-mail servers Thursday
by clogging them with ILOVEYOU messages that carried a lethal
love-letter attachment. It also ruined sound and video files.
</P>
<P>
   The common thread among virus variations is a ``.vbs'' at the
end of the document name, an almost surefire sign that it's a
troublesome attachment. The key to avoiding the fast-morphing virus
strains is to ignore any ``.vbs'' files.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 45 million people received the infected ILOVEYOU
e-mail Thursday, according to California-based research company
Computer Economics. The CERT Coordination Center at Carnegie-Mellon
University in Pittsburgh, Pa. estimated as many as 600 million
computers worldwide had been affected by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Organizations from government agencies to small businesses to
universities spent the day assessing the damage. Taking into
account the number of ruined files and the time wasted by shutting
off e-mail servers, Computer Economics pegged the damages at $2.6
billion _ but said that total could skyrocket to $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, total damages from all virus attacks in 1999 was
estimated at $12.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators continued scouring the Love Bug code,
having found clues that hint at a 23-year-old from The Philippines,
code-named Spyder, who included that name and little notes like ``I
hate go to school'' in the text of the virus program.
</P>
<P>
   The question, then, is whether investigators can trust what they
read.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty hokey and obvious, but it is also pretty common
for virus writers to leave their name in the code for notoriety,
even though it's like signing their own arrest warrant,'' said Matt
Yarbrough, a Dallas attorney who once worked on the Justice
Department's CyberCrimes Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``It either is this 23-year-old kid or someone sophisticated who
wanted everyone to think it's a kid. It has to be either one _
nothing in between.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday afternoon, a new message circulated claiming to be a
virus warning and asking readers to click on
``viruswarning.jpg.vbs'' to somehow view the bug. That file is
infected just like Love Bug and its less-than-loving letter.
</P>
<P>
   Another, Mother's Day Order Confirmation, tells recipients that
their credit card has been charged $326.92 for a diamond gift to
their mother. A fake invoice is attached, and if puzzled readers
download it, they too will catch the bug. Other variations include
JOKE and a sentence written in Lithuanian that translates as an
invitation to go out for coffee.
</P>
<P>
   The point of changing the message title, or the name of the
attached document, is to evade special filters set up to detect the
ILOVEYOU messages and block them from arriving in mailboxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We normally see a surge of variations, but it usually drops
back down again,'' Leibrock said. ``It's like a flu attack.''
</P>
<P>
   So as the bug keeps crawling, Leibrock said he's trying to
dispel myths he's heard from people who think they're invulnerable
simply because the Love Bug didn't bite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard some remarkably stupid comments, like, 'It only
affected one type of e-mail server,' `` Leibrock said. ``That's
like saying that if a car has a collision, then only that make and
model of car will ever have collisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's immune _ that's what we should learn from this.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
