people think of when they hear the name Dow Corning: breast
implants, and nothing else. And if Anderson, Dow Corning's chief
executive, were an irritable kind of fellow, that would irk him
mightily. But irritability is not Mr. Anderson's style. A product
that never accounted for more than 1 percent of its sales blackened
the name of Dow Corning in the public mind like few others in
recent memory, and drove it into bankruptcy. So why haven't its
co-owners, Dow Chemical and Corning, dumped it, or even changed its
name? By Claudia H. Deutsch.
