<P>
   COURTING-BOUQUETS (New York) _ An unsuspecting woman received a
bouquet of flowers recently at her Fifth Avenue home. Set in a
silver-plated urn, the $350 arrangement was lush with romantic pink
roses, Italian poppies, deep-purple sweet peas, calla lillies and a
card that read, ``We'd be a good match.'' Her secret admirer? A
floral designer named David Beahm, whose intentions were not
particularly romantic. The object of his attentions is a member of
the organizing committee for a fall fund-raising gala for the
Metropolitan Opera, with the unofficial position of flower
chairwoman: she picks the florist who picks the flowers. The
unsolicited arrangement was ``a courting bouquet.''By Monique P.
Yazigi.
</P>
<P>
   MOTHER-BRIDE-FASHIONS (Undated) _ Fretting over what to wear to
her daughter's wedding, Ilene Beckerman experienced an instant of
panic. ``Everybody remembers Princess Diana's wedding dress,'' she
told herself soothingly, ``but who remembers what her mother wore?
Nobody pays attention to the mother of the bride.'' Mrs. Beckerman
knows better, of course. Taut as a snare drum, smooth and polished
as an apple, these days the mother of the bride is apt to be as
raptly scrutinized and cooed over as the bride herself. By Ruth
LaFarla.
</P>
<P>
   FRAGRANCE-BOUTIQUES (Undated) _ While customization has proved
popular recently in everything from suits to ice cream, it is
taking off in the top tiers of the fragrance industry. Creed, the
very upscale European fragrance house, whose perfumer is the
sixth-generation Oliver Creed, offers custom scents. There are also
Creed master blenders at Barneys New York, Bergdorf Goodman and
Neiman Marcus, who can blend five or six of the existing 100 Creed
scents for customers in an hour, for the more affordable fee of
$400 to $1,000. On the West Coast there are a growing number of
fragrance boutiques like Lather in Pasadena and Homebody in Los
Angeles that blend custom scents for clients like K.D. Lang. By
Alex Witchel.
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-OSCAR-JOKE-WRITER (New York) _ The packed house at last
Wednesday night's preview of ``Bruce Vilanch: Almost Famous''
seemed to like everything about the one-man show playing at the
Westbeth Theatre Center except the title. ``Take out the Almost,''
said one audience member, sensing that Bruce Vilanch, the show's
author and star, has already crossed the threshold from wannabe to
being there. Vilanch, the New Jersey-born quipmeister who has
written for Bette Midler and Robin Williams, currently pens
one-liners for stars to deliver at the Oscars. He also writes witty
bits for celebrity appearances, including his own, on ``The
Hollywood Squares.'' By Michael Musto.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Anne Raver: I know I'm supposed to
curb my dog, but occasionally she squats when I'm not paying
attention, and it seems cruel to yank her away in midstream. Well,
I'm not going to feel sorry for her anymore. And you shouldn't feel
sorry for your dog. Because that urine kills plants and trees.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-COPY-EDITORS (New York) _ Being a copy editor at a
women's fashion magazine _ and a male to boot _ is a little like
being the designated driver: you're around people having a lot of
fun, but you're not allowed to imbibe. Your job is to make sure the
semicolons are right; you don't get to pick up the phone and trill
``Daaahling'' or air-kiss the French photographers when they come
in with their portfolios. By Ethan Hauser.
</P>
