<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-EAST0506-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weary Pacers face ailing 76ers
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ From a visual standpoint, the
Indiana-Philadelphia second-round playoff series promises to be an
eyesore. But the competitive nature of the battle ought to make up
for any unsightly play.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers, coming off a difficult and emotional five-game
series with Milwaukee, play host to the 76ers in Game 1 tonight at
Conseco Fieldhouse. And the No. 1-ranked team in the Eastern
Conference might have an edge in health but maybe not in energy.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana outlasted the Bucks and had just one day to shake the
effects before facing the 76ers, who are battered but determined.
It is a test that beaten Milwaukee coach George Karl said the
Pacers can pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're declining,'' Karl said. ``Have they
plateaued? Is Toronto catching them a little bit? Have we caught
them a little bit? Has Philly caught them a little bit? I would
view anybody that puts 55 wins up as having not declined.'' Indiana
actually won 56 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they walk out there, they're a team and they don't want
to lose, and I really respect that,'' Karl said. ``The character of
that team, to me, is as scary as their talent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sixers' most talented player, all-star guard Allen Iverson,
continues to be hampered with injuries. ``I've never had this many
injuries in one year in my life,'' Iverson said. ``I guess I'm not
drinking enough milk.''
</P>
<P>
   Iverson has a chip fracture in his right ankle that can be
stablized with heavy taping. He has a toe injury and problems with
his right rotator cuff.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, starting point guard Eric Snow, who missed the last
two games of the first round against Charlotte with a bad ankle,
said he is optimistic that he will be able to play tonight. The
76ers advanced to the second round on the strength of their tough
defense and valuable play from their bench. In particular, Aaron
McKie, a defensive specialist, was important on offense in the
decisive game.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers' bench has been less productive, although former
Georgia Tech star Travis Best did hit the game-winning and
series-clinching shot against Milwaukee on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been up and down,'' coach Larry Bird said about his
reserves. ``Just like our starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's a new series now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
