<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LONG-GAME-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARATHON ON ICE AS TIRED TEAMS SKATE INTO THE WEE HOURS
</HEADLINE>
  By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ In the two dressing rooms, during the many
intermissions, the players consumed what was to have been their
post-game pizza. They munched on nutritional energy bars, washing
it all down with water and other healthy beverages. They stretched
to ward off muscle cramps. They talked among themselves about who
would get the winning goal that would allow everyone to finally go
home.
</P>
<P>
   In the stands, less than half full at the end but
standing-room-only many hours before, a few fans slept while
waiting for the third, fourth and fifth overtime periods of Game 4
of the second-round playoff series between the Pittsburgh Penguins
and the Philadelphia Flyers. Other fans visited refreshment stands
that were still open but out of everything but nachos and peanuts.
``Let's Go Pens!'' some chanted, rooting for the home-town
Penguins. ``Let's Go Home!'' one fan shouted in retort.
</P>
<P>
   This was early Friday morning in the Mellon Arena, site of the
third-longest game in the history of the NHL. It began at 7:39 p.m.
on Thursday night and ended at 2:35 a.m. the next morning on a goal
by Keith Primeau of Philadelphia. Primeau said he suffered leg
cramps before the start of the final period and that he lost track
of periods and the time of night. ``If I thought of what period it
was or what time it was it would throw me off,'' Primeau said.
</P>
<P>
   His goal, ending a game that lasted 152 minutes and 1 second on
the scoreboard clock, gave the Flyers a 2-1 victory that tied the
best-of-7 Eastern Conference semifinal at two games apiece. Game 5
will be on Sunday in Philadelphia. It begins around noon, so it
should be over before dark.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL said the 6-hour, 56-minute length in real time was the
longest game in its history. In that same time span, the fastest
runners could complete the Boston, New York and Olympic Marathons
and still have time for sprints; horses could run 210 Kentucky
Derbys.
</P>
<P>
   For four-plus overtime periods, in a sudden death situation in
which the next goal would clinch the game, players strived in vain
to muster a winning shot. Toward the end, with no strength or
speed, they looked like the middle-aged men who sometimes pool
their money to rent rinks in the middle of the night for what are
sometimes called beer leagues. Ron Tugnutt, the Pittsburgh goalie,
said ``everything seemed to be in slow-motion. This is the wildest
thing I've ever been through. The mind kind of shuts down on you. I
was just in a daze.''
</P>
<P>
   He had his reasons. In a normal three-period game, a goalie
might face 25 to 35 shots; Tugnutt faced 72, stopping 70 of them,
and his teammates blocked another 42. Seven of those were blocked
by Darius Kasparaitis, the Pittsburgh defenseman who at the end was
victimized by Primeau's smooth move that created shooting space in
the right-wing faceoff circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each overtime you go on it's getting ridiculous,'' Kasparaitis
said. ``Some guys are not even hitting anybody, just falling apart.
It was tough, but it was a good experience. Sometimes, it was
funny. John LeClair was falling all over the place. Both benches
were laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaromir Jagr, the Pittsburgh captain who was last season's Most
Valuable Player and is this season's scoring champion, said when a
game goes this long, ``You don't even play hockey. It's just
skating. I was so tired I didn't feel anything.'' Jagr led his team
in minutes played with 59:08, twice what he might play in a
regulation game.
</P>
<P>
   LeClair, Philadelphia's star left wing, caused the overtime by
scoring the tying goal early in the third period. Nobody was
certain, but video review suggested the puck might have entered the
net after bouncing off a Pittsburgh stick and then LeClair's
helmet. ``Something dinged my head,'' LeClair said. ``I didn't
touch it with my stick.''
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh's Alexei Kovalev had scored on the first Pittsburgh
shot of the game, before sunset, at 2:22 of the first period, then
the Penguins didn't score again the rest of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not even thinking about what you're doing,'' Kovalev
said of the overtime. ``Your body is playing for you. When you go
that long, it's all about luck. You start making moves on
defensemen and you can see they're not even reacting. What else can
you do?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Kasparaitis reacted to Primeau's move and Primeau wristed a
rising shot over the glove of Tugnutt to end the longest game since
March 24, 1936. That was when Mud Bruneteau of the Detroit Red
Wings scored after 176:30 to beat the Montreal Maroons by 1-0. In
second place is Toronto's 1-0 victory over Boston on April 3, 1933.
That one lasted 164:46.
</P>
<P>
   After his teammates mobbed him and left the ice, Primeau
stripped off his uniform and stood in the corner of the locker room
wearing a weary smile and gray underclothing, soaked in
perspiration. In his hand he held a half-filled bottle of water.
``I definitely feel dehydrated,'' Primeau said. ``It was a lot of
fun to play in that game. I was surprised that it was only the
third-longest game. It felt like an eternity.''
</P>
<P>
   Because there are no timeouts for television commercials after
regulation time, the pace of the game seemed brisk even as the
skating of the players slowed down. One whole overtime, the second,
was free of icing, a play in which a defending team relieves
pressure by clearing the puck down to the other end, resulting in a
faceoff back up ice in its own zone. It seemed as if neither team
had the will or energy to skate that far to retrieve the puck.
</P>
<P>
   Although he put nine shots on goal and created several scoring
chances with passes in overtime, Jagr said he could put no power
into his shots. ``I know it's tough for the goalies to stand
there,'' Jagr said, ``but it's easier.''
</P>
<P>
   The goalie he tried to beat, Boucher of the Flyers, said players
were joking that if they won they would get Friday off from
practice. He said his body was cramping and that his skates held so
much perspiration that he could ``feel it squashing around in
there.''
</P>
<P>
   When Primeau beat Tugnutt at the other end, Boucher said he
heard the ``ping'' of the puck hitting the metal part in the back
of the net but could barely see the little, red light bulb behind
the cage that signaled the goal. Then came the sound of near
silence. ``You could hear that the crowd was so disgusted,'' he
said. And the crowd could hear the shouts of happy Flyers gathering
around Primeau, and their tired hands pounding him on his broad
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going down in hockey history,'' Primeau said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 2105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
