<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7200 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TRIPP-TRIAL-1STLD-WRI     05-05 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIPP-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE APPROVES PROSECUTION OF TRIPP, BUT RESTRICTS LEWINSKY
TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for additional details, clarification and rewriting
throughout; story grows by 550 words)  
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Maryland judge ruled Friday that the state could
proceed with its prosecution of Linda Tripp on charges that she
broke the law when she secretly tape-recorded conversations with
Monica Lewinsky about Lewinsky's relationship with President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge, Diane O. Leasure of Howard County Circuit Court,
also dealt a severe blow to the case by suppressing the testimony
of Lewinsky and another witness that may be crucial in obtaining a
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Leasure ruled that the testimony of Lewinsky on one critical
point was not credible. The judge dismissed as implausible
Lewinsky's statements to the court in December about why she was
certain that a specific conversation secretly tape-recorded by
Tripp had occurred on Dec. 22, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The date of the conversation is pivotal because the Maryland law
under which Tripp is charged specifies that a person is guilty only
if it can be shown that she knew at the time of the taping that it
was illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Although Tripp recorded more than 20 hours of her telephone
conversations with Lewinsky, the one that occurred Dec. 22 was the
only one that took place after prosecutors believe Tripp was
definitively informed by her lawyer that it was illegal to tape
phone conversations in Maryland without the consent of the other
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Ms. Lewinsky has admitted that she lied under
oath in a federal proceeding and has stated that lying has been a
part of her life does not enhance her credibility as a witness,''
Judge Leasure wrote in her 41-page opinion.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Leasure ruled that prosecutors could not use the
testimony of another witness, Mary Catherine Friedrich, the only
other person who might have been able to identify the time period
in which Tripp secretly tape-recorded her conversations with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The chief state prosecutor in the case, Stephen F. Montanarelli,
acknowledged in an interview that while the ruling allowed him to
go forward, ``We now have a very serious problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Montanarelli said he would review the ruling and make a decision
whether to pursue the prosecution without the testimony that
Leasure barred in her ruling Friday. He said he would decide before
the scheduled trial date of July 10.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tripp said Friday that she believed a decision by Montanarelli
to go forward after Friday's ruling would be especially vindictive
and malicious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision to indict me was politically motivated and
wrong,'' she said in a statement. ``This case is being prosecuted
solely because I blew the whistle on President Clinton's attempt to
fix a court case.''
</P>
<P>
   She was referring to Paula Jones' sexual misconduct lawsuit in
which Clinton and Lewinsky both denied having had a sexual
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The issue decided Friday involved whether the Maryland
prosecutors could demonstrate that their evidence against Tripp was
developed independently of and did not rely on the work of Kenneth
W. Starr, the federal prosecutor who investigated Clinton on
Whitewater and other matters.
</P>
<P>
   That is because when Tripp became an informer for Starr, telling
him of the president's relationship with Lewinsky, she was given a
grant of immunity. Although Leasure sharply limited the scope of
the immunity agreement earlier, prosecutors still had to
demonstrate that their witnesses and evidence were not derived from
or tainted by knowledge of Starr's findings.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dec. 22 conversation, Tripp and Lewinsky discussed the
subpoenas they had just received in the Jones lawsuit. Lewinsky
talked about whether she could lie for Clinton, and they discussed
gifts he has given her.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky testified that she did not rely on her association with
Starr's investigators to identify the tape recording as having
occurred on Dec. 22, 1997, as the investigators had concluded. She
said she recognized the conversation as having occurred a few days
before Christmas of that year because it coincided with other
memorable events.
</P>
<P>
   But Leasure said there was no question that Lewinsky had been
exposed greatly to Starr's investigation, even seeing testimony as
to the date of the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense argues that Ms. Lewinsky is `bathed in
impermissible taint,''' Leasure wrote. ``The court agrees.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Murtha, Tripp's lawyer, said that while he had hoped
Judge Leasure would have dismissed the case, he believed her ruling
``significantly hobbled the state's ability to prosecute.''
</P>
<P>
   Leasure ruled that prosecutors could not use Friedrich's
testimony because they only learned of her through the Starr
investigation. Friedrich said Tripp played some of the tapes for
her and she knew that one occurred around Christmastime because it
had Tripp yelling at her daughter for knocking down the Christmas
tree.
</P>
<P>
   If Montanarelli decides to go forward, Leasure ruled, Lewinsky's
testimony will be limited to her assertions that she never gave
consent to have her conversations with Tripp recorded.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling appears to leave the prosecutors with only the
testimony of some of Tripp's partners in a weekly bridge game and a
neighbor, all of whom seemed aware that she was secretly taping
conversations with a woman named ``Monica'' who was having an
intimate relationship with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The women testified that Tripp sometimes boasted of secretly
taping the other woman and even invited Lewinsky to a Christmas
party at her Columbia, Md., home so the others could gaze upon the
woman she had told them about.
</P>
<P>
   Leasure ruled Friday that the testimony of those women could be
used by the prosecution. But none of them seemed able to recollect
exactly when they learned of the taping and none are able to
identify the date of the crucial Dec. 22, 1997, conversation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 2120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7201 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-VIRUSES0506-COX     05-05 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRUSES0506-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No computer vaccine in sight
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Experts warned Friday that only dramatic improvements
in defenses will keep computers safe from costly, annoying
assaults, even as the worst of this week's computer attack was
fading.
</P>
<P>
   In other words: Learn to live with it.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, yet another clever mischief-maker will pump a
new virus or worm into the Internet, infecting millions of users
just like the computer ``worm'' that Thursday slithered into
millions of machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say there will be another one in six months,'' said Chris
Rouland, director of the X-Force, research arm of Internet Security
Systems in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Known as Love Letter, I Love You or the Love Bug, the computer
worm that popped up Thursday was generally regarded as the worst
cyber-assault ever, choking e-mail systems, rewriting software,
erasing photos and music and stealing passwords.
</P>
<P>
   The attack caused no bloodshed, toppled no governments and
darkened no cities, but it almost certainly cost hundreds of
millions of dollars in lost opportunities and wasted resources.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, weaker copycat versions were circulating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is just a speed bump,'' said Roger Thompson, director of
malicious code research at Virginia-based ICSA.net. ``There will be
other speed bumps. It's a cost of doing business.''
</P>
<P>
   Cyber-attacks are so frequent that most go unreported in the
national media. Among those doing enough damage to receive public
notice was last year's Melissa virus, which temporarily clogged
e-mail systems. Then, a few months ago, someone harnessed thousands
of computers across the Internet and programmed them to pour data
at major Web sites _ freezing them.
</P>
<P>
   Love Letter was an escalation _ Melissa on steroids.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the attack was a worm, a self-replicating bit of
software that also tried to rewrite some files and purloin
passwords. Using the come-on of romance in the subject line, Love
Letter invited recipients to open an attachment. If they did, it
grabbed e-mail addresses stored on Microsoft Outlook, cloned itself
and sent copies to each address.
</P>
<P>
   Spared were computers using Linux or Apple Computer systems _
and not necessarily out of respect.
</P>
<P>
   As any Justice Department attorney will tell you, most of the
world's computers run Microsoft Windows. So that's the best way for
hackers to get maximum damage _ or publicity. Most bugs target
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   As Love Letter swept across the Net, fixes were rushed onto
various anti-virus Web sites, some so jammed with traffic that they
could not be reached. Users were told to distrust all e-mails with
attachments, even those they thought came from friends.
</P>
<P>
   In a kind of arms race, Internet security companies have dueled
for years with the mostly faceless hackers and ``script kitties,''
who copy viruses and ship them out into the Net. One side produces
a bug, the other responds quickly with a fix _ because much
anti-virus software cannot stop a brand new bug. The result is that
the Internet remains less reliable than the phone or power system
even as the world relies on it more.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, as the Net's technology gets stronger, so do the
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   As new functions are added, more gaps for mischief are created,
said Thompson. ``The better the functionality, the worse the
security. We have a world that demands power. That gives the bad
guys one more thing they can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the ocean of computer viruses is constantly swelling.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred are cascading around the Net and are potentially
dangerous _ right now. Plus there are about 50,000 known computer
viruses drifting through cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Why do they persist? For one thing, the pool of people who enjoy
fiddling with them is continually restocked with the young and
restless, many of whom have the time it takes to concoct an attack.
They tend to be male, young and isolated. Unlike hackers
intercepting messages or manipulating data, they're not doing it
for money, but for fun or the pursuit of notoriety.
</P>
<P>
   Internet bugs _ like cockroaches in the real world _ are awfully
tenacious. Like the chain letters and uncountable bad jokes
circulating the Net, viruses seem to survive even determined
efforts to squash them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is a big place,'' Thompson said. ``There's always a
copy on a floppy disk in somebody's briefcase somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a physical virus, a computer bug must be passed somehow
from one individual to the next. Before the Internet's surge, that
happened only with floppy disks being moved from one machine to
another _ and it could take years to cross the world.
</P>
<P>
   Love Letter moved in hours across five continents _ thanks to
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In general, a bug that doesn't get off to a quick start never
becomes a global threat. And even with the Net, not every bug
bursts into prominence. Experts this week said the fast-moving worm
was lucky: In its early hours, Love Letter may have snagged a huge
network _ perhaps a multinational bank or the U.S. military. It was
the cyber-equivalent of a flu-sufferer walking through rush hour at
Grand Central Station shaking hands and sneezing.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking a computer bug may be easier than finding the original
sneeze. On the Net, there are footprints and fingerprints,
remaining for months or even years, something that pranksters often
forget.
</P>
<P>
   While the Net may seem anonymous, it's not _ at least not to
determined hackers, researchers with resources or law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Netizens bent on mischief in many ways mimic the deceptions of
criminals in the physical world. They pose behind many different
identities. They cover their tracks, use false addresses and steal
the addresses of the law-abiding.
</P>
<P>
   And most get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   Of 419 cases of alleged computer fraud referred to federal
prosecutors in 1998, just 83 were prosecuted, according to the
Electronic Privacy Information Center. Most cases were dismissed
for lack of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Of those the 83 cases that went to trial in 1998, 47 people were
convicted of federal computer crimes, 20 went to prison and 10 were
found innocent of the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Security companies and law enforcement often reserve their
resources for big cases, and they are definitely not helpless.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, ICSA.net has a team of faux-hackers who don
cyber-disguises and infiltrate the world's hacker communities.
Information is shared with the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson is confident that the Love Letter perpetrator will be
caught. A look at Love Letter's path and source code and the Web
sites used as part of the program quickly led investigators to the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   How long can the game go on?
</P>
<P>
   Until computers have ``immune systems'' like animals do, they
will be vulnerable, said Steve White, manager of anti-virus
research at IBM's Watson Research Center. ``It just takes too long
for companies to come up with the fix and the virus moves too
fast.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM and Symantec Corp. have written software aimed at
recognizing anything virus-like, putting it into ``quarantine'' and
transmitting a copy via the Net to a central computer for analysis.
If the suspect is dangerous, it can be wiped out _ perhaps without
the user even knowing there was a problem, White said.
</P>
<P>
   Even immune-like systems will not put an end to cyber-crime or
cyber-sickness, but they can mount defenses strong enough to keep
attacks from endangering the Net, White said. ``We still need
doctors and we still need medicine. But without our immune system,
we would never have survived as a race.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
