<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0349 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7206 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-GORE-GUNS-710&AMP;AD     05-05 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GORE-GUNS-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BUSH CLASH FURTHER ON FIREARMS 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The lines that divide the presidential candidates on
the issue of gun control came into sharper focus Friday, as Vice
President Al Gore vowed to veto any measure prohibiting cities from
suing gun manufacturers, and Gov. George W. Bush suggested that he
might support such a bill.
</P>
<P>
   Gun manufacturers have been lobbying federal lawmakers for such
legislation; Gore, in an interview Friday, pledged to block that
effort and questioned whether Bush would do likewise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I challenge Governor Bush to make the same pledge,'' Gore said
in an interview with Political Points, the Web-cast of The New York
Times and ABC News. ``Will he veto any bill that lets gun
manufacturers off the hook? Will he fight for the gun industry or
for America's families?''
</P>
<P>
   When Bush was asked about that at a subsequent news conference
here, he said, ``It depends on what's in the legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   But, the Texas governor added, ``You can get a feel for my
position by looking at what I've done in office, and what I did in
office was sign a bill that made it very difficult for local
municipalities to sue manufacturers of a legal product.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was referring to a 1999 law that required lawsuits on
behalf of Texas cities or counties against gun makers to be filed
by the state attorney general, who might or might not support that
course of action. The measure was similar to ones supported by
other Republican governors and reflected their general push to curb
civil litigation in many areas.
</P>
<P>
   The divergent statements of Gore and Bush continued an often
tense back-and-forth over gun control that has lasted several days
and signaled the potential potency of the issue in the 2000
elections. Each candidate has been trying to cast doubt on his
opponent's commitment to gun control, and each has been trying to
tar the other by linking him to the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference, Bush said that Gore had a voting history
in Congress of support for the NRA's positions and had a good deal
of explaining to do.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush's aides circulated a brief document titled ``Al Gore &AMP;
Guns,'' which cited examples from the 1980s of Gore's agreements
with the gun lobby, the governor used a news conference here Friday
to cast the vice president as a candidate whose current advocacy of
more stringent restrictions on firearms was simply the latest
fashion, not a matter of steadfast principle.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it was convenient politically, he voted one way,'' Bush
said, ``and when it's convenient politically, he's changed his
tune.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also refused to back off his suggestion on Thursday that
Gore was once a member of the NRA and, when challenged Friday to
say how he knew that, offered no proof.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he reminded reporters that he ended his statement about
Gore and the NRA with the phrase ``if I'm not mistaken'' and told
them it was their job to verify the assertion and Gore's
responsibility to show that he was not a member of the group.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed about where he had gotten the idea in the first place,
the governor responded, ``A little birdie.''
</P>
<P>
   William Powers, a spokesman for the gun organization, said he
had found no evidence that Gore had been a member. But he said that
when Gore was a congressman from Tennessee, ``he certainly received
very high ratings from the NRA.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Hattaway, a spokesman for the Gore campaign, said that
it could not find any record of Gore's ever being a member of the
NRA and that the vice president ``doesn't have any recollection of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's an irrelevant issue, anyway,'' Hattaway added. ``Al
Gore is standing up to the NRA's leadership and its increasingly
extreme agenda, while Bush is doing their bidding.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchanges between the Bush and Gore campaigns were touched
off in part by a gun-control group's distribution this week of a
television commercial featuring footage of an NRA official saying
that if Bush became president, the organization would be working
out of the White House. Bush said that was not true.
</P>
<P>
   His efforts on Friday to turn the tables on Gore seemed to
reflect not only the ascendancy of gun control as a political issue
but also Bush's desire to court swing voters, many of whom favor
greater regulation of firearms.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And Bush took his swipes at Gore during his third day of
campaigning in California, a state full of such voters. In fact,
Bush's campaign schedule here this week represented an especially
aggressive attempt to portray himself as a progressive, open-minded
Republican by emphasizing his sensitivity to religious and ethnic
diversity.
</P>
<P>
   In recognition of Cinco de Mayo, a Mexican-American holiday,
Bush delivered a long address here Friday morning on the shared
values of Latinos and other Americans. In it Bush used more Spanish
phrases and sentences than he had previously used on the campaign
trail this year.
</P>
<P>
   And he made a plea for greater acceptance of new immigrants,
recalling his introduction, during a walk through Santa Ana on
Thursday, to a grocery-store owner who had come to California from
Mexico with very little except a ``sueno,'' or dream.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's remarks, delivered to hundreds of people at a ``breakfast
fiesta'' sponsored by a private group called the U.S.-Mexico
Foundation, followed a series of events, encounters and photo
opportunities _ many of them filmed by the candidate's advertising
team _ that put Bush together with Latino and Catholic voters.
</P>
<P>
   The first group is crucial to Bush's hopes of winning
California. The second is key to his success nationwide, and Bush
has been working especially hard to appeal to Catholics since his
controversial appearance in February at Bob Jones University in
South Carolina, a school with a history of anti-Catholic bias.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign also said Friday that Bush would postpone a
speech about Social Security, scheduled for Monday, so that he
could attend the funeral Mass for Cardinal John O'Connor in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Bush campaign document about Gore's record on
gun control in Congress, Gore supported a measure to remove a ban
on interstate sales of rifles, shotguns and handguns; opposed a
14-day waiting period for handgun purchases; and cast votes between
1985 and 1990, as a senator from Tennessee, that were in line with
the wishes of the NRA three-quarters of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Hattaway did not dispute that, saying that Gore's positions had
evolved with the growing prevalence of gun-related violence in the
country. He also said that the NRA is more extreme now than it was
in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Hattaway noted that Gore now advocates a much wider array of
restrictions on firearms than Bush, who signed legislation in Texas
that permitted people to carry concealed handguns and seemed in
other ways to agree with the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, though, Bush chastised an official with the
organization for making inflammatory statements about President
Clinton. He also signaled a slightly greater receptiveness to some
gun-control proposals. And he has tried to link Gore to the NRA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
