<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7208 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-COMPUTER-VIRUS-HNS &LR;      05-05 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-VIRUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW VERSIONS OF COMPUTER VIRUS WREAK HAVOC &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JENNIFER MONTGOMERY 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   (Undated) New strains of the Love Letter e-mail virus attacked
computers around the world Friday, some disguised as jokes or
Mother's Day gift orders.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's uproar over the most far-reaching and destructive
virus yet inspired copycat vandals to spend the night playing with
the destructive code in their own e-mail files or at hacker sites
on the Internet. The code is simple to copy, change slightly, mask
with a new subject line and deliver worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, 45 million people have probably received original
or copycat versions of the virus, according to Computer Economics,
a research firm in Carlsbad, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take a genius to replicate this kind of virus,''
says Samir Bhavnani, a research analyst with Computer Economics.
``You or I could spend a day researching it and replicate it
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping up with each variation isn't as simple, however.
Software security firms are scrambling to develop antidotes for at
least eight versions of the ``VBS.LoveLetter.A'' virus, which was
distributed in e-mail attachments with the subject line
``ILOVEYOU.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the new versions enticed e-mail recipients to open
attachments by suggesting that they confirm a Mother's Day order
for diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   Another variation appeared to be a forwarded joke with the
subject line ``very funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Others purported to contain programs to kill the Love Letter
virus, and one contained a message in Lithuanian.
</P>
<P>
   Even though most of the variations involve only cosmetic
changes, such as the subject line, there are small changes in the
coding that require antivirus software makers to keep coming up
with new fixes, says Laura Garcia Manrique of the Symantec
Antivirus Research Center.
</P>
<P>
   The impact on commerce could be severe. Computer Economics
estimates that $2.6 billion in damage has been done, and the bill
could reach $10 billion by the middle of next week. That would make
it even more destructive than the infamous Melissa virus that
spread in a similar fashion early last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Melissa was verging on economic terrorism,'' says Bhavnani.
``This is beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the original virus, the copycat versions begin wreaking
havoc when an e-mail recipient using Microsoft's Windows operating
system opens an attachment to his e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   They overwrite system, image and music files and download a
program from the Internet that allows them to steal passwords. Then
they replicate themselves by e-mailing copies to everyone in the
computer's Microsoft Outlook address book.
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing flood of e-mail messages has clogged up computer
networks and forced many businesses to shut down their e-mail
operations while making repairs and installing security measures.
</P>
<P>
   The virus, thought to have originated in the Philippines, first
appeared Thursday morning in Asia, then spread rapidly across
Europe and into the United States. It has infected corporations
from Ford to Kmart and government agencies from the Chicago Public
School System to the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Even though antivirus software makers continued to post new
fixes at their Web sites Friday, some companies are going so far as
to temporarily block all e-mail attachments, says Sharon Ruckman at
Symantech, which makes the Norton Antivirus. It was a strategy that
some companies adopted the first week of 2000 because of fears
about Y2K vandalism, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Security experts expect trickier variations of the virus to
appear as vandals find time to play with it over the weekend.
Ruckman expects the viruses to mutate for about a week before
enough computer users get the security in place to lock them out.
</P>
<P>
   Most makers of popular antivirus software will post fixes at
their Web sites daily until the threat has abated.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, e-mail recipients should delete _ without opening the
attachment _ any messages from unknown senders as well as e-mail
from known senders if the subject line is suspicious, like a love
note or a Mother's Day message from a co-worker. PC users also
should empty their computers' recycle bins.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
