<SLUG> BC-OLY-FOXHALL0506-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Black happy just to be riding
 &HT;    By Carrie Teegardin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dressed in top hat and tails and riding a bold bay
horse named Hyde Park Corner, Julie Black of Newnan finished the
first phase of competition Friday at the Foxhall Cup and let loose
with a big smile.
</P>
<P>
   Her dressage test, the first element of the equine triathlon in
which horses demonstrate grace and discipline, had gone well. Black
stood in 12th place with Hyde Park Corner and in 21st on
Bartolomeo.
</P>
<P>
   But the bigger victory for Black was that she was in the ring at
all.
</P>
<P>
   Black is one of the equestrian world's rising stars, and
everything appeared to be on track for her to make a strong bid for
the U.S. equestrian team headed for the 2000 Games in Sydney,
Australia. But two weeks ago, while preparing for an Olympic trial
in Kentucky, Black took a nasty fall. Doctors told her she had
suffered a major back injury. The pain was so bad, if it persisted,
there could be no riding, no competing, and no chance at the
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   More tests, however, showed Black's injury wasn't that bad,
after all. And maybe, just maybe, the doctors told her, she could
ride in the Foxhall Cup, another Olympic selection trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real blessing that we're here,'' said Black, 29.
``Without this event my chances of going to the Olympics, or even
letting these horses compete in something we've been working for
all spring, were just going to be nothing.'' The Foxhall Cup is
what is knows as an ``eventing'' competition, one of three Olympic
equestrian sports. The triathlon's first phase is dressage, in
which horses demonstrate grace and discipline, not unlike the
compulsories that figure skaters used to perform. The heart of the
event is today's test _ the cross-country run in which horses and
riders must navigate a grueling course of gigantic, immovable jumps
positioned over the fields and waterways of Foxhall Farm. The final
stage is the stadium jumping, where horses must show the
athleticism and endurance to jump the day after the cross-country
marathon.
</P>
<P>
   After the first phase, Tiffani Loudon of South Carolina and
Makabi are in the lead. One of Australia's top riders, Phillip
Dutton, is in second place, followed by David O'Connor, a U.S.
rider who was a silver medalist in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   While the dressage results are significant, anything can happen
on the cross-country course. ``The course is beautiful and my
horses are really fit and prepared,'' Black said. ``It should be a
fun day.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
