<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELAY-LAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
SUIT AGAINST DeLAY SIMILAR TO ONE AGAINST CLINTON 
 
By STEVE LASH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Democrats who sued House Majority Whip Tom
DeLay this week for alleged campaign-finance improprieties used
legal arguments similar to those in a lawsuit that an anti-Clinton
group filed against them.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee's racketeering
claim against the Texas Republican reads like allegations of
fund-raising irregularities the conservative group Judicial Watch
has pending against the DCCC, President Clinton, his staff and
party contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Judicial Watch chairman Larry Klayman, an outspoken critic of
Democratic campaign tactics, said Friday that the similarities
between the lawsuits are too strong to be merely coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently they thought highly of our lawsuit,'' Klayman said
of the DCCC's attorneys. ``Imitation is the sincerest form of
flattery.''
</P>
<P>
   But the DCCC's chief lawyer and its spokesman said Judicial
Watch's lawsuit in no way inspired the claim against DeLay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't generally tend to imitate Larry Klayman,'' attorney
Robert Bauer said of his courtroom nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   Added DCCC spokesman Erik Smith: ``Our suit's completely
unrelated to that suit.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether by accident or design, the commonalities between the
lawsuits are rooted in the deep partisan differences between
Democrats and Republicans, said political science professor George
Edwards III of Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   Both cases allege violations of the Racketeer Influenced and
Corrupt Organizations Act, a law generally aimed at combating
organized crime and corporate fraud.
</P>
<P>
   That the statute, widely known as RICO, has been used in a
fund-raising context is unusual. That it has been used in two such
cases appears to be more than happenstance, Klayman said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bauer dismissed Klayman's copycat view of the origin of the
case against DeLay.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer said racketeering was the appropriate claim to make
against DeLay's alleged use of three organizations, set up by close
advisers to the Houston area Republican, to evade fund-raising
disclosure laws and to strong-arm contributors. The DCCC claims
that DeLay solicited campaign contributions by promising corporate
donors that their largess would be rewarded with favorable
legislation from the GOP-led Congress.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, who said he intends to fight the lawsuit, called the
allegation ``frivolous'' and a ``pretty pathetic ... act of
desperation'' by the Democrats to disrupt legitimate GOP
fund-raising efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Judicial Watch, in its similar lawsuit filed in November 1998,
claims that Clinton and the DCCC violated RICO in securing more
than $1 million in contributions from Loral Space and
Communications Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   Klayman, representing Loral shareholders in the lawsuit, says
the DCCC, Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and White House staff
violated the law by soliciting $1.46 million in contributions from
the company. In return for the donations, Clinton issued a
presidential waiver to Loral that allowed the high-tech company to
launch a communications satellite from China, Klayman alleges.
</P>
<P>
   The DCCC and the other defendants counter that they operated
within the law.
</P>
<P>
   In another similarity, both lawsuits have drawn heavy fire from
Democrats and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Each party has accused the other of being more interested in
scoring political points with their claims than in trying to stop
illegal campaign fund-raising. The parties argue that the aim of
the lawsuits is not to win but to enable each side to subpoena
campaign staff and documents in an effort to upset each other's
fund-raising operations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the two groups bringing the lawsuits have a history
of trying to embarrass the defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Klayman and Judicial Watch have been a constant thorn in the
president's side, as they have sued, subpoenaed and deposed White
House staff regarding genuine and alleged Clinton scandals. The
group has questioned staff and sought documents related to
Clinton's tryst with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky and
about alleged campaign finance irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the DCCC has been aggressive in going after DeLay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
