<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-DIARY-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TEMPTATION OF THE MARKET TIMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, May 7) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   So the volatility of technology stocks is on the rise. But what
_ if anything _ can investors do about it?
</P>
<P>
   In an April 30 research report, Edward Kerschner, chief
investment strategist at PaineWebber, offers this advice: Grin and
bear it.
</P>
<P>
   According to Kerschner, the average daily price change of the
technology sector, as tracked by Standard &AMP; Poor's, was 1.07
percent from 1993 through 1999, though it rose steadily over that
period. This year through April, it was 2.29 percent, or more than
twice that figure.
</P>
<P>
   As volatility increases, creating more peaks and valleys in
stock prices, so does the temptation for investors to time the
market. To see the potential, consider the path of the technology
sector. From 1993 through April of this year, its compound annual
growth rate was 38.6 percent, more than double the 17.8 percent of
the S&AMP;P 500-stock index. But say an investor was a perfect market
timer over that period _ putting all of his or her portfolio into
technology stocks, but switching to the broader market every month
the technology stocks underperformed. Bingo! That growth rate rises
to 59.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, of course, is when to jump and when to sit tight.
Despite all the investor talk of ``January effects'' and ``summer
doldrums,'' Kerschner says that there appears to be no seasonality
in the technology stocks' outperformance of the broader market.
</P>
<P>
   Without a methodology to help decide when to trade out of
technology stocks, market-timing is even more difficult. As
technology stocks' volatility has risen, so has the implied cost of
a wrong market-timing decision.
</P>
<P>
   Say a market-timing technology investor switched into the S&AMP;P
500 for just one month in a given year, but that month happened to
be the one in which technology stocks performed best. Back in 1993,
such a mistake would have shaved 5.1 percentage points of the
market-timers' returns for the year. In 1996, 9.6 percentage points
would have been sacrificed. In 1999, the error would have cost a
fat 20.1 percentage points in potential gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the information age,'' Kerschner wrote in his
report. ``Tech stocks define that age. And just as they offer
unprecedented growth opportunities, they also offer unprecedented
volatility.'' In other words, caveat trader. ``How to play?'' he
asked. ``Don't try to time it.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ RICHARD TEITELBAUM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS WATCH: THE PAYOFF FROM AT&AMP;T'S FALL
</P>
<P>
   Last Nov. 23, shares of AT&AMP;T hit $53, and Donald L. Luskin,
manager of the $35 million OpenFund, was engulfed in doubt. A month
and a half earlier, he had sold the stock short at $46.50, betting
that it would fall.
</P>
<P>
   But it was heading up. Moreover, Luskin lives in a glass house,
by mutual fund standards: OpenFund, which started last year, posts
all its investment decisions on its Web site daily, lets the public
post opinions of its performance and even has a Webcam on its
trading floor.
</P>
<P>
   Now the public was talking back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to eat crow and cover the short,'' one visitor
wrote. ``I'm thinking about it, I'm thinking about it!'' Luskin
wrote back.
</P>
<P>
   He has added to and covered part of the short position at
various times over recent months. On March 29, when AT&AMP;T hit $61,
another visitor accused Luskin of being ``obsessed'' with AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Luskin was vindicated.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T announced that its earnings and revenue growth for the
remainder of the year would fall short of analysts' expectations.
The stock fell 18 percent for the week, closing on Friday at
$38.4375, and Luskin, who had last added to his short position when
the stock hit $58.50 on March 29, had a tidy $98,983 profit as of
Friday, not including trading costs.
</P>
<P>
   He is maintaining a short position on the stock. ``The company
is sitting on a huge legacy of network architecture,'' Luskin said
in an interview. ``Everything about the way it connects people is
three or four generations old. It's America's most unnecessary
company.''
</P>
<P>
   _ DANNY HAKIM
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
