<HEADLINE>
FRAM'S LUNCH SPECIAL: AIR-FILTER MARINARA 
</HEADLINE>
  (For Release Sunday, March 7) 
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PATRICK J. LYONS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's about as unlikely a promotional gimmick as you can find. To
publicize the advantages of the Triad fibers used in its automotive
air filters, the Fram unit of Honeywell is handing out packages of
deep red ``A Taste of Triad'' pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Labeled in Fram's signature orange-and-black style, the ``100
percent edible'' noodles are ``a fun way to see what a difference
shape can make,'' according to the package. The pasta's unusual
cross-section _ a bit like a Star Wars TIE fighter with an extra
wing _ is said to hold a lot more sauce than plain old spaghetti.
Demonstrating the principle in the kitchen is meant to help
retailers and sales representatives remember the company's
assertion that similarly shaped and colored fibers in the new air
filter hold 48 percent more dirt than ordinary fibers.
</P>
<P>
   According to Heather Gillette, a spokeswoman for Fram, a
packaging designer at the company first suggested the metaphoric
macaroni. Marketing executives turned up an artisan pasta maker in
Rhode Island who could manufacture it in the unusual shape; the
correct red food coloring had to be imported from Italy. All the
effort paid off in the attention the new Fram filter garnered at
the latest Automotive Aftermarket Industry Week trade show. ``The
pasta was a big hit,'' Gillette said.
</P>
</TEXT>
