<SLUG> BC-BBN-PHILS-SCHILLING0506-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Schilling shoulders Phillies' aspirations
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An hour before Friday's game, Philadelphia pitcher
Curt Schilling stretched carefully in front of the Phillies'
dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Forty feet away, Braves first baseman Andres Galarraga was
approached by Hal McRae, Philadelphia's hitting instructor.
</P>
<P>
   ``How's the swing going?'' McRae asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too good,'' Galarraga replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' McRae said with a grin, ``you better get it (Friday)
because you won't (today).''
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies coach was referring to Schilling, who has nearly
fully recovered from a shoulder injury that caused the former
All-Star to miss part of the 1999 season and the first 23 games
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling (0-1, 6.00 ERA) will make his second start of the
season when he faces the Braves at 7:10 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've leaned on (Schilling) more than what has been fair the
last couple of years,'' Philadelphia manager Terry Francona said.
``Now that we have him back in the rotation, it's nice. We've
really got a chance to have a pretty respectable rotation.''
</P>
<P>
   Schilling returned to the mound last week against the St. Louis
Cardinals, striking out eight batters over the first five innings,
including Mark McGwire twice. However, McGwire launched a two-run
homer for a 4-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to be back out there again, but we lost,''
Schilling said. He had the velocity on his fastballs, but the
off-speed pitches weren't as sharp. Most important, the pitcher
said his shoulder felt fine after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came back with good velocity. He's not rehabbing any more;
he is pitching and that is good,'' Francona said.
</P>
<P>
   Braves manager Bobby Cox is aware of Schilling's capabilities,
selecting the right-hander for the All-Star Game in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I can tell you about Curt Schilling is that he
had been one of the horses in the National League for a long time
now,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   I wish he wasn't pitching against us, but I am glad his arm is
back. He can really pitch, he's outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
