<SLUG> BC-DEUTSCH-CIA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-835(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI AND JUSTICE DEPARTMENT INVESTIGATE EX-CIA DIRECTOR
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: 3 new graphs, tones down ``complete reversal'' in 2nd graf;
picks up ``She decided...'') 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department and the FBI have begun a
criminal investigation to determine whether former CIA Director
John M. Deutch mishandled classified material by placing it on
unsecure computers in his home, government officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation, which amounts to a change of course by the
Justice Department, is the result of an internal review of the case
ordered in February by Attorney General Janet Reno, following
criticism of the CIA's handling of the case and of her initial
decision not to prosecute Deutch for the security lapses.
</P>
<P>
   Reno ordered the new inquiry to determine whether her initial
decision not to prosecute him was in error and whether he should
now face criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   She decided against prosecution last year, officials said,
without ordering any investigation by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation is the result of an internal review of the
case ordered earlier this year by Reno.
</P>
<P>
   For the new criminal investigation, officials said, the Justice
Department has assigned a prosecutor to work directly with FBI
agents. They are pursuing an inquiry that focuses on whether Deutch
should face criminal charges for having retained highly classified
information on his unsecured home computers while he was leading
the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, officials said, a special White House intelligence
panel presented President Clinton with a toughly worded report that
is critical of current and former CIA officials for failing to
follow through adequately on the evidence against Deutch.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the President's Foreign Intelligence Advisory
Board was presented to Clinton personally earlier this week by the
board's chairman, former Sen. Warren Rudman.
</P>
<P>
   The report's findings, they said, were similar to those of the
CIA's inspector general, who also found that senior CIA officials
failed to aggressively investigate Deutch when the computer lapses
were discovered.
</P>
<P>
   While the presidential board's findings remain classified,
officials described its report as sharply critical of the roles
played by several of the agency's most senior officials, including
some who had worked closely with Deutch.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to Deutch's lawyer were not immediately returned Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that the board's report was particularly critical
of the roles played in the investigation by the former CIA
executive director, Nora Slatkin, and the former CIA general
counsel, Michael O'Neil.
</P>
<P>
   Slatkin comes in for the heaviest criticism, officials said,
because she was effectively in charge of the CIA's botched initial
investigation. Both Slatkin and O'Neil had been brought to the CIA
by Deutch and had close relationships with him.
</P>
<P>
   Others cited in the report include former CIA Inspector General
Frederick Hitz and Richard Calder, now the CIA's deputy director
for administration. Hitz began the inspector general's
investigation of the Deutch matter but it was completed last year
by his successor, L. Britt Snider. The presidential board also
criticized CIA Director George Tenet for allowing Slatkin to take
charge of the Deutch investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential board began its review of the way the CIA
handled the Deutch matter at the request of Air Force Gen. John A.
Gordon, deputy director of the CIA, who was dissatisfied with the
CIA's own efforts to review the matter, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has received a copy of the presidential board's report
and will now try to determine whether any further disciplinary
action is required at the CIA against those involved in the Deutch
case.
</P>
<P>
   The handling of the Deutch case has been highly controversial
from the start.
</P>
<P>
   The case began just as Deutch was leaving office in December
1996, when an agency computer security specialist discovered that
Deutch had placed large volumes of classified material on unsecure
computers in his home, including information about some of the
government's most sensitive covert operations.
</P>
<P>
   The material included detailed personal journals about Deutch's
activities at the CIA and memos prepared for Clinton. Placing
classified material on these unsecure computers represented
potential violations of both agency rules and federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after the classified material was detected, Deutch
deleted more than 1,000 files from his personal computers,
according to the inspector general's report.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA's security staff began a probe of the matter, but before
long it bogged down, and some CIA security officials became
convinced that senior CIA officials were attempting to protect
Deutch from a thorough investigation. The security staff wrote a
report on its investigation in 1997 without ever questioning
Deutch.
</P>
<P>
   No action was taken against Deutch for more than a year, when
the CIA's inspector general was told by an agency employee that the
earlier investigation had not been handled properly. Until the CIA
inspector general launched his own investigation in early 1998,
Tenet had not taken any action to reprimand Deutch or discipline
any other current or former CIA officials.
</P>
<P>
   Tenet had said there was never any attempt by anyone at the CIA
to constrain the internal inquiry into the Deutch matter.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The CIA's inspector general notified the Justice Department of
the Deutch matter in 1998. The delay in notifying the Justice
Department about the case allowed a one-year time limit on
appointing an independent counsel to lapse, according to the
inspector general's report. The independent counsel act was still
in effect at the time. ``Application of the Independent Counsel
statute was not adequately considered'' by CIA officials handling
the case, the report says. ``Given their failure to report to the
Department of Justice on a timely basis, this in effect avoided the
potential application of the Independent Counsel statute.''
</P>
<P>
   But in April 1999, Reno decided not to prosecute Deutch.
</P>
<P>
   Officials now say that the Justice Department decided not to
prosecute without any FBI investigation of the matter. The decision
to decline prosecution was also made before the CIA's inspector
general had issued its report on the case.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1999, after the inspector general finally issued his
classified report on Deutch's actions, Tenet, the CIA director,
suspended Deutch's CIA security clearances. At the time, Deutch
issued a statement apologizing for his actions.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general's report recommended that a special CIA
accountability review planel be created to examine whether Tenet
and other top CIA officials properly handled the agency's internal
investigation. That accountability review panel issued a classified
report earlier, and presented it to Gordon for use in determining
disciplinary action. But officials said Gordon was not pleased with
the accountability review panel's report, apparently because it was
too soft on agency officials involved in the Deutch case.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Gordon asked the presidential board to conduct an
independent review. The presidential board interviewed Deutch
during its review of the matter, officials said. The White House
has rejected a request from the Senate Select Committee on
Intelligence for a copy of the presidential board's report, but
Rudman has briefed the committee on his findings, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the government's handling of the Deutch case have
tried to draw a comparison between the gentleness of it and the
harsher treatment of Wen Ho Lee, the Los Alamos scientist who has
been indicted on charges of downloading and copying files
containing nuclear secrets with the intention of aiding a foreign
country and damaging national security.
</P>
<P>
   Tenet has dismissed the comparison, telling a Senate panel that
while Mr. Deutch was ''sloppy'' in his handling of classified
documents, there was no evidence that he had intended to aid a
foreign country by handing over American secrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually think there is a great difference in the two
cases,'' Tenet said. ''In both cases there was a referral made to
the Department of Justice. In one case, the Department of Justice
declined any action, in the case of the director. In the case of
Wen Ho Lee, there is an indictment pending.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 2207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0375 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7242 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-QUALIFYING0506-CO     05-05 0423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-QUALIFYING0506-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Bodine, return to racing is a victory in itself
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. _ Geoffrey Bodine won't be on the pole for
tonight's Pontiac Excitement 400. No bulletin there: That spot went
to Rusty Wallace in the No. 2 Ford with a top lap of 124.740 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the bigger news: Bodine will be starting.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that he qualified fourth (124.161 mph) makes his
comeback from the fiery truck crash at Daytona three months ago all
the more remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   Bodine returns to Winston Cup racing tonight for the first time
since February when his truck flipped end over end, nearly
disintegrating in a ball of fire. He broke a wrist, injured his
back and missed the first 10 races of the season while three
drivers substituted in the No. 60 Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   It was the worst accident of Bodine's 538-race Cup career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in some accidents where I thought I would kill
myself,'' Bodine said. ``There was a time at Watkins Glen at the
end of the back straightaway when my brake rotor blew up. I thought
I was going to hit a tree. I thought I was going to kill myself
that day. I had some time to think about it so it was real scary.
</P>
<P>
   ``This accident happened quickly and I thought it was going to
be a normal accident. I had no idea it was going to be as dramatic
as it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodine, 51, said he has no fear returning to the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no apprehension whatsoever,'' he said. ``It might be
normal to have some apprehension, but racers aren't normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodine tested here a couple of weeks ago with Ken Schrader and
Ward Burton. ``We ran faster than both of them,'' he said. ``It was
a little uncomfortable getting in the car with my back brace on,
but once I fandangled my way into the car, I was 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll wear the back brace in the car tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The comeback adds another chapter to Bodine's story of the
successful underdog. He came into the sport as an outsider from New
York, was the 1982 Winston Cup Rookie of the Year, bailed out of a
brief try as an owner-driver and was fortunate to hook up with Joe
Bessey.
</P>
<P>
   He's won 18 races in his career, none in four years and 106
starts. Now his story is one of courage and faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite a remarkable story that I'm here, and I'm very
fortunate and thankful for that,'' Bodine said. ``It certainly
wasn't luck that I survived. It was the grace of God that saved me.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 2208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
