<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0376 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7247 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-R-OCONNOR-ART-490&AMP;ADD     05-05 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-OCONNOR-ART-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL'S BODY AT CATHEDRAL FOR FINAL SERVICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Repeating to add three more photo numbers.)  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT9,11,12,18 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Free of the illness that sapped his energy and
ultimately his life, Cardinal John Joseph O'Connor's body was
returned to St. Patrick's Cathedral on Friday, beginning a final
farewell to the eloquent, unswerving archbishop of New York from
the millions of Roman Catholics he led.
</P>
<P>
   The cathedral's great double doors were thrown open for the
arrival at 4 p.m., as a solemn procession of seminarians, priests,
nuns and auxiliary bishops, led by altar boys bearing the
archbishopric cross, marched toward the mahogany coffin that held
the cardinal's body.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet incense floated over the coffin and rose toward the
heavens, as the faithful believe that the cardinal's soul now does.
In a greeting, Bishop Patrick J. Sheridan, the cardinal's vicar
general, who had been his right-hand man, sprinkled holy water over
the bier of his friend of many years and then covered it with a
white funeral pall _ both acts reminiscent of baptism.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing death was near, the cardinal had said his formal
goodbyes several times since he underwent surgery for a brain tumor
last August: in a note to his fellow bishops last fall, when he
visited the pope in February, and in a letter to the 875 or so
priests of his archdiocese in the same month.
</P>
<P>
   But those messages seemed powerless to counter the quiet grief
as the cardinal's coffin glided past the pews for the last time,
carried on the shoulders of sad-eyed men wearing dark gray gloves.
</P>
<P>
   The mourners in the pews sang a processional hymn as they
watched the cardinal's coffin move past them. ``He who is throned
in heaven, takes up his dwelling place,'' they sang. ``No sound is
heard of weeping, for pain and sorrow cease. And sin shall reign no
longer, but love and joy and peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Edith McGowan, 80, prayed the rosary as she waited in the pews,
and said she felt the sadness welling inside her throughout the
half-hour ceremony. ``He was such a beautiful man,'' said McGowan,
who met the cardinal last year. ``So gentle speaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Agnes Ohuche, 28, from Harlem, was sitting in one of the last
pews, a black lace scarf falling over her face. She prayed for
mercy for O'Connor as his soul reached judgment. ``I'm grateful to
God for all the things the cardinal has done for us,'' she said.
``He was a strong defender of the Holy Father.''
</P>
<P>
   In his homily, Sheridan spoke of O'Connor not only as his bishop
but as ``my brother and my friend.'' He said that next door to the
cardinal's spare bedroom in his Madison Avenue residence was a
small private chapel. And on the other side of the chapel was
Sheridan's room. He said the two men often joked that ``The only
one who ever came between us was Jesus Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   Wherever O'Connor's far-flung travels took him, Sheridan added,
the cardinal always made sure he was home by Saturday night, so he
could celebrate the 10:15 Mass at St. Patrick's the following
morning. ``His work is done, and now he is home,'' Sheridan said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As pallbearers removed the top of the cardinal's coffin to begin
the public viewing, those in the pews sang ``Morning Has Broken,''
a hymn to earth's capacity for renewal and rebirth, made famous by
Cat Stevens. The cardinal had specifically requested that the song
be sung at the moment New Yorkers would view his body for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the music had ended, the cardinal could be seen
dressed as he would be if he were about to celebrate Mass.
</P>
<P>
   He wore the scarlet cassock of the cardinal, covered by a white
flowing gown, or alb. Over his alb was the cardinal's chasuble, and
flowing in a line down the front and back of the chasuble was his
white woolen pallium, the symbol of his archbishop's office. Around
his neck the cardinal wore a stole, the symbol of the priesthood,
and the pectoral archbishopric cross, with its double crossbeams.
In his hands he clasped a rosary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
