<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7262 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CATHOLIC-CARDINALS-AR     05-05 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLIC-CARDINALS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS RECALL O'CONNOR'S FRIENDSHIP AND INSIGHT ON DIOCESE
MANAGEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT17 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ For Cardinal Bernard Law, the archbishop of Boston,
Cardinal John O'Connor was a friend to whom he spoke nearly every
day by telephone, a rare colleague with whom he could share the
distinctive and unusual concerns that come with being one of the
most public figures in the Roman Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could share honestly what we were facing,'' said Cardinal
Law, in an interview at a downtown hotel here this evening, three
days before he was to give the homily at O'Connor's funeral Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Law said he had flown to New York to be with O'Connor as the
cardinal lay dying Wednesday, and spent the day at his bedside,
praying with a small group of his friends and relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Law came to Chicago on Friday to participate in a long-planned
gathering of American cardinals, an occasion made poignant by the
death of a man so well known to each of the church leaders here.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was the annual American Cardinals Dinner, an event
held to benefit student scholarships to the Catholic University of
America in Washington. In the brief interval since O'Connor's
death, the university's president, the Rev. David M. O'Connell,
dedicated the event to the cardinal's memory.
</P>
<P>
   Eight cardinals have come to the event, six of them Americans,
and one of them Irish. The eighth is Cardinal Pio Laghi, a man
deeply familiar with the United States and its hierarchy through
his service as the Vatican's apostolic delegate to the American
church in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In individual interviews, several cardinals said O'Connor had
helped them with suggestions or ideas about their roles as public
figures and managers of archdioceses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I became archbishop of Chicago,'' said Cardinal Francis
George, who was appointed to that position by Pope John Paul II in
1997, ``he gave me some very good advice, just sharing it, as an
older brother would.'' Although he did not specify what precisely
O'Connor told him, George said, ``I looked to him to give me some
clues as to how you handle the public role.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal Roger Mahony of Los Angeles had been head of the
diocese in Fresno, Calif., for several years before O'Connor was
appointed to his first diocesan position. Mahony became Los
Angeles' archbishop a year after O'Connor became archbishop of New
York. Outside of their work on issues at the National Conference of
Catholic Bishops, the two found common ground in sharing their
concerns as administrators of vast, urban jurisdictions. They would
sometimes discuss how to raise money to keep their inner-city
Catholic schools open and available to the children of poorer
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the insights he gave me,'' Mahony said, ``which I never
thought of, was to utilize the corporate community'' in finding
supporters for inner-city Catholic schools. Corporations tended to
donate to colleges, but, said Mahony, ``you can't get anybody into
college unless they finish high school.''
</P>
<P>
   The two cardinals also talked about books. ``We would try to
remain as current as we could'' with theological publications,
Mahony said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the cardinals who came here said they had known Cardinal
O'Connor for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met him 20 years ago,'' said Cardinal Anthony Bevilacqua,
archbishop of Philadelphia, recalling a time before he and O'Connor
were appointed to their respective archdioceses. Back then, said
Bevilacqua, a Brooklyn native, O'Connor used to take him to dinner
at an Italian restaurant in Manhattan that both of them enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   The two of them were attending a bishops' meeting in 1983,
Bevilacqua said, when O'Connor came over and announced, with some
surprise, it seemed, that Laghi had just informed him that the
Vatican had picked him to be the next bishop of Scranton, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, congratulations,'' Bevilacqua said. (Scranton turned
out to be but a brief stop for O'Connor, as the pope appointed him
archbishop of New York the next year.)
</P>
<P>
   As for Law, he said he came to New York to visit O'Connor just
after O'Connor had undergone his surgery late last summer for
removal of a brain tumor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him how he felt,'' Law said, ``how he was dealing with
it, because it was obvious what the course of that was going to
be.'' He said that O'Connor replied that he felt a ``great peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I spoke with him was the Friday before he
died,'' Law said. ``We had a great youth event, and I asked him for
his prayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Law said he received a call from O'Connor's staff on Wednesday
morning, telling him that the cardinal's health was deteriorating.
``I cleared off my schedule and flew to New York and spent the day
with him,'' Law said. ``I led the prayers for the dying. We went
through them twice. We finished with them just as he died.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
