u s BC-RAC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     05-05 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CHARACTERS IN THE ANNUAL DERBY DRAMA
</HEADLINE>
  By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ If you love horses, the smells, the sights and
the sounds never get old; if you love the Kentucky Derby, the
pre-race excitement never loses its electricity. At 6 a.m. Friday,
the darkness at Churchill Downs was defined by shadows, with
grooms, trainers and riders moving in a haphazard choreography of
chores in the refreshing chill of spring air. Through the muddy
maze of walkways and stables, Wayne Kotcamp led the way.
</P>
<P>
   He was taking part in a Derby ritual, the first hours of the
Kentucky Oaks Day races, the elaborate prelude to the Kentucky
Derby. As such, Kotcamp was one of hundreds of thousands of
characters in the Derby drama.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning, he and his wife, Eileen, will meet with
friends by 10 and have brunch by 10:30. Then they'll proceed to
Churchill Downs and watch the first Kentucky Derby of the
millennium. Kotcamp is an orthopedic surgeon by training, the owner
of a horse by choice. But not a high-stakes owner. On the drive
over to the track Friday, he talked about the high cost of
maintaining a horse and wisely advised: ``You can't own racehorses
and have children.''
</P>
<P>
   I reminded him that he raised four children. ``I was an
orthopedic surgeon,'' he said, by way of explaining how he defied
his own advice. ``A hard-working orthopedic surgeon.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two main attractions in Louisville _ the Ohio River
and the horses. For Kotcamp, who was born in Greenup, Ky., in 1928,
the track has been an emotional outlet much more than a succession
of financial windfalls. As such, the pursuit of the ultimate horse
is really background music for relationships forged over the years.
</P>
<P>
   The first person to greet Kotcamp Friday was Robbie O'Connor,
who trains Kotcamp's horse, Divet. O'Connor's primary client is Jim
Bohanon, but his relationship with Kotcamp has deep roots. Kotcamp
owned horses with O'Connor's father, a psychiatrist, and has known
the son since he was a teen-ager. O'Connor said that the track was
his second home growing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the track a lot with my dad,'' he said. ``That was
our quality time. They had an old place, an old track that raced at
night. We'd go out there in the evening and watch races. So I got
kind of smitten by the bug.''
</P>
<P>
   After two years of college, O'Connor dropped out of school to
make the track his life. He made up his mind to leave after a trip
to New Orleans. He emptied his bank account, put $400 aside for
expenses and bet $1,600 on a horse that his mentor, the trainer
Billy Ashenbrener, felt had potential. ``I got back $16,000,''
O'Connor said. ``I didn't want to be a doctor anymore; I thought
I'd be a horse trainer.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor said that once he left school and became an assistant
to Ashenbrener, his parents put him out of the house. O'Connor's
father owned horses but wouldn't give any to his son to train.
Kotcamp came to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called his dad, asked if it was OK to give him one of my
horses,'' Kotcamp said. ``He said it was OK, and that's how we
started.'' O'Connor smiled. ``When I started doing well, picking up
clients, my dad gave me horses,'' he said. ``The rest of it's
history.''
</P>
<P>
   A few yards away, Kotcamp spotted Angel Montano and went over to
greet him. Montano is a trainer who arrived at Churchill Downs by
way of Mexico in 1956, when he was still a jockey. The track helped
put five children through college and provided Montano and his
family with a comfortable life. He celebrates each Derby with a
Saturday feast on the backside of the track. This year, he has
prepared 250 chickens, crawfish from New Orleans and barbecue ribs
from Evansville.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to have to haul me off the racetrack,'' he said.
``I won't retire.''
</P>
<P>
   At 11 a.m., Kotcamp and I left the insular world of Derby racing
and headed for Memorial Park, about 10 minutes south of Churchill
Downs. The Rev. Al Sharpton, Dick Gregory and Martin Luther King
III had scheduled an Oaks Day rally to highlight accusations by
local African-American groups that Louisville police and other
local government bodies have racist hiring policies. They
intentionally chose Derby week for the protest. Gregory stood in
the hot sun, his face covered with a costume horse mask. ``I had to
take a walk this morning, someone suggested I'd be safe wearing
this,'' Gregory said. ``The police won't shoot a horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Kotcamp, asked if he thought Louisville was being treated too
harshly, said of the protesters: ``Maybe they need to be harsh.''
</P>
<P>
   After the rally broke up, Kotcamp drove back through the bubbly
Derby crowd.
</P>
<P>
   In Louisville, there's the track, but there's also the race of a
different color.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
