u w BC-DEUTCH-CIA-2NDLD-WRIT     05-05 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEUTCH-CIA-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI AND JUSTICE DEPARTMENT INVESTIGATE EX-CIA DIRECTOR
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: ADDS 12th graph, beginning ``In the past...,'' moving up
concept from the bottom of 1STLD; ADDS 16th graph including
previous denials of Slatkin and O'Neil; SUBSTANCE changes in 6th
graph of 2nd take; ELIMINATES everything starting with the next
graph, beginning ``In February...''; ADDS new last graph. Also,
minor word changes throughout. 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department and the FBI have begun a
criminal investigation to determine whether John M. Deutch, a
former director of the CIA, mishandled classified material by
placing it on unsecured computers in his home, government officials
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation, which amounts to a change of course by the
Justice Department, is the result of an internal review of the case
ordered in February by Attorney General Janet Reno after criticism
of the CIA's handling of the case and of her initial decision not
to prosecute Deutch for the security lapses.
</P>
<P>
   Reno ordered the new inquiry to determine whether her initial
decision not to prosecute him was in error and whether he should
now face criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   She decided against prosecution last year, officials said,
without ordering any investigation by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation is the result of an internal review of the
case ordered earlier this year by Reno.
</P>
<P>
   For the new, criminal investigation, officials said, the Justice
Department has assigned a prosecutor to work directly with FBI
agents. They are pursuing an inquiry that focuses on whether Deutch
should face criminal charges for having retained highly classified
information on his unsecured home computers while he was leading
the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, officials said, a special White House intelligence
panel presented President Clinton with a toughly worded report that
is critical of current and former CIA officials for failing to
follow through adequately on the evidence against Deutch.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the President's Foreign Intelligence Advisory
Board was presented to Clinton personally this week by the board's
chairman, former Sen. Warren B. Rudman.
</P>
<P>
   The report's findings, they said, were similar to those of the
CIA's inspector general, who also found that senior CIA officials
had failed to aggressively investigate Deutch when the computer
lapses were discovered.
</P>
<P>
   While the presidential board's findings remain classified,
officials described its report as sharply critical of the roles
played by several of the agency's most senior officials, including
some who had worked closely with Deutch.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to Deutch's lawyer were not immediately returned Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Deutch has apologized for the security lapses.
Critics of the Justice Department have questioned what they
describe as the lenient treatment of Deutch in light of its highly
publicized prosecution of Wen Ho Lee, a former Los Alamos National
Laboratory scientist who has been charged with transferring and
copying secret nuclear data from the laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that the board's report was particularly critical
of the roles in the investigation played by the agency's former
executive director, Nora Slatkin, and the former general counsel,
Michael O'Neil.
</P>
<P>
   Slatkin receives the heaviest criticism, officials said, because
she was effectively in charge of the agency's botched initial
investigation. Slatkin and O'Neil had been brought to the CIA by
Deutch, and had close relationships with him.
</P>
<P>
   Others cited in the report included Frederick Hitz, the agency's
former inspector general, and Richard Calder, currently the deputy
director for administration. Hitz began the inspector general's
investigation of the Deutch matter but it was completed last year
by his successor, L. Britt Snider. The presidential board also
criticized the agency's current director, George Tenet, for
allowing Slatkin to take charge of the Deutch investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Slatkin, O'Neil and others criticized in the new report have
previously denied that they took any actions to impede the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential board began its review of how the CIA handled
the Deutch matter at the request of Gen. John A. Gordon, the
agency's deputy director, who was dissatisfied with the internal
efforts to review the matter, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has received a copy of the presidential board's report
and will try to determine whether the agency should take any
further disciplinary action against those involved in the Deutch
case.
</P>
<P>
   The handling of the Deutch case has been highly controversial
from the start.
</P>
<P>
   The case began as Deutch was leaving office in December 1996,
when an agency security specialist discovered that Deutch had
placed large volumes of classified material on unsecured computers
in his home, including information about some of the government's
most sensitive covert operations.
</P>
<P>
   The material included detailed personal journals about Deutch's
activities at the CIA, and memos prepared for President Clinton.
Placing classified material on these unsecured computers
represented potential violations of both agency rules and federal
law.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after the classified material was detected, Deutch
deleted more than 1,000 files from his personal computers, the
inspector general's report said.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA security staff began an investigation, but before long
it bogged down, and some security officials became convinced that
senior agency officials were trying to protect Deutch from a
thorough inquiry. The security staff wrote a report on its
investigation in 1997 without ever questioning Deutch.
</P>
<P>
   No action was taken against Deutch for more than a year, when
the agency's inspector general was told by an employee that the
earlier investigation had not been handled properly. Until the
inspector general started his own investigation in early 1998,
Tenet had taken no action to reprimand Deutch or discipline any
other current or former agency officials.
</P>
<P>
   Tenet has said there was never any attempt by anyone at the CIA
to constrain the internal inquiry intentionally.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general notified the Justice Department of the
Deutch matter in 1998. The delay in notifying the Justice
Department about the case allowed a one-year time limit on
appointing an independent counsel to run out, the inspector
general's report said. The independent counsel act was still in
effect at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Application of the Independent Counsel statute was not
adequately considered'' by agency officials handling the case, the
report says. ``Given their failure to report to the Department of
Justice on a timely basis, this in effect avoided the potential
application of the independent counsel statute.''
</P>
<P>
   But in April 1999, Reno decided not to prosecute Deutch.
Officials now say that decision was reached without any FBI
investigation and before the agency's inspector general had issued
its report on the case.
</P>
<P>
   After the inspector general issued his classified report on
Deutch's actions last August, Tenet suspended Deutch's CIA security
clearances. At the time, Deutch issued an apology.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general's report recommended that a special CIA
accountability review panel be created to examine whether Tenet and
other top officials properly handled the internal investigation.
That review panel issued a classified report earlier this year, and
presented it to Gordon for use in determining disciplinary action.
But officials said he was not pleased with the report and in
February, Gordon asked the presidential board to conduct an
independent review. The presidential board interviewed Deutch
during its review of the matter, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has rejected a request from the Senate Select
Committee on Intelligence for a copy of the presidential board's
report, but Rudman has briefed the committee on his findings,
officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
