r s BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     05-05 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DEPUTY IS A SMART PICK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ The Kentucky Derby is to the typical big-money
horse race what a presidential campaign is to an Assembly election
or a Picasso is to a paint-by-numbers. Different not merely in
degree but in kind.
</P>
<P>
   Everything about the Derby is out of proportion and skewed: It's
run too early in the season for its 3-year-old contestants to be
counted on for their best. It crowds the largest field of the
American racing season into a sharp clubhouse turn. It's run at a
distance none has attempted.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the people who know how to get horses ready for the
Derby seem to operate by different rules. There's a reason the past
five Derby winners were trained by either D. Wayne Lukas (Thunder
Gulch, Grindstone, Charismatic) or Bob Baffert (Silver Charm, Real
Quiet) and two of the four before that were trained by Nick Zito
(Strike the Gold, Go for Gin).
</P>
<P>
   Of course they're given talented horses to train. But they also
know exactly what to do with them with the Derby in mind.
</P>
<P>
   They begin testing and seasoning their prospects as 2-year-olds.
They run them hard and work them hard and fast as the Derby season
builds. If their horses make it to Churchill Downs healthy, they
are as ready for a 1-mile battle as their pedigrees will allow.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus, the heavy favorite for today's 126th running
of America's greatest horse race, has come to the first Saturday in
May in a decidedly different way under Neil Drysdale. We'll find
out this afternoon if the Derby gods respect the kinder, gentler
approach.
</P>
<P>
   It says here they'll take that mouthful of a name -
Foo-saw-ee-chee - and spit it out.
</P>
<P>
   It would be absurd for a writer to second-guess the methods of a
Drysdale, a Belmont Stakes winner, a five-time Breeders' Cup winner
and a newly elected Racing Hall of Famer - if history didn't back
up the skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus is bucking several Derby traditions: Horses who
start their careers late (Dec.11, in his case) and don't have a lot
of experience (five races, in his case) don't win.
</P>
<P>
   A stat from Andy Beyer of the Washington Post: In the past 30
years, 63 horses who began their careers after Nov.1 ran in the
Derby - all of them lost.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale's training of Fusaichi Pegasus and War Chant at
Churchill Downs was described by a local analyst as the ``trot to
the Derby'' approach.
</P>
<P>
   Add the possibility that the rambunctious Fusaichi Pegasus will
spend his energy in the post parade and you have the very picture
of a vulnerable favorite.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard enough to take 9-5 - Fusaichi Pegasus' morning line -
on any horse in a race where the post-time favorite hasn't won in
20 runnings. To take 9-5 on a horse with demonstrable shortcomings
is insane.
</P>
<P>
   So I'm looking elsewhere for my Derby horse and have settled,
not far from home, on the Santa Anita Derby winner, The Deputy.
</P>
<P>
   If Fusaichi Pegasus is UCLA, then The Deputy is Princeton,
likely to outsmart him with fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
   The Deputy won't pitch a fit on the way to the starting gate.
The Deputy won't be wishing in midstretch that he'd had one more
fast workout. The Deputy won't be intimidated by the large field -
he ran against 20 other horses last September on English turf in
his fifth and last start before coming to Jenine Sahadi in
California.
</P>
<P>
   The Deputy won't be unable to recover if traffic takes him out
of his game - he has proven his tractability by winning races wire
to wire and from off the pace (the only horse in this Derby to have
done both in races of 1 mile or more). Chris McCarron can position
The Deputy wherever is comfortable as the jockey seeks his third
Derby victory.
</P>
<P>
   Sahadi has had exactly as many horses as Drysdale in past
Kentucky Derbies: zero. But the issue isn't the trainer's Derby
experience. It's a matter of learning from history.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a bettor trying to beat Fusaichi Pegasus, you have a
lot of rational ways to go. I've marked six other horses in my
program.
</P>
<P>
   Give me $100 to bet on the Derby, and I'll spend it this way:
</P>
<P>
   --$50 to win on The Deputy.
</P>
<P>
   --$1 trifectas linking The Deputy (on top) with Aptitude, High
Yield and More Than Ready (in second) and those three plus Hal's
Hope, Captain Steve, China Visit and Fusaichi Pegasus (in third) -
a total of $18.
</P>
<P>
   --$1 trifectas connecting Aptitude, High Yield and More Than
Ready (on top) with The Deputy (in second) and the top three plus
Hal's Hope, Captain Steve, China Visit and Fusaichi Pegasus (in
third) - also $18.
</P>
<P>
   --$14 to buy the biography of Fusaichi Pegasus if he wins. He'd
have to be one for the books.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 2258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
