<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7381 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-PHILIPS0506-COX     05-05 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PHILIPS0506-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Davies and Turner have eyes on the prize
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Laura Davies took off most of April so she could
spend time hanging out in her hometown of West Byfleet, England. In
her four-week respite from the LPGA Tour, she never picked up a
club, preferring to play soccer, roughhouse with her two dogs and
shop.
</P>
<P>
   She admitted to mostly shopping, with her most expensive
purchase being a black, two-seater Mercedes. She traded in her
Ferrari to get the Benz.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the fun of having any money if you can't spend it?''
said Davies, whose career winnings of $4.87 million rank 10th all
time.
</P>
<P>
   Given that shopping mind-set, Davies definitely has eyes set on
the top prize of $127,500 that comes with winning the Philips
Invitational Honoring Harvey Penick.
</P>
<P>
   Davies, the longest hitter on tour, shot a 3-under-par 67 Friday
afternoon for a two-day total of 135, 5 under par at Onion Creek
Club. Coming into today's third round, Davies and first-round
co-leader Sherri Turner top a congested leader board, with six
golfers one stroke back in third place and another four golfers
within three shots of Davies and Turner.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Akiko Fukushima shot a 67 Friday to put
herself in that crowded group one back of Turner and Davies.
Meanwhile, Sherri Steinhauer, the first-round co-leader with
Turner, suffered through a miserable afternoon, shooting a 76.
Steinhauer, a former University of Texas All-American,
double-bogeyed her second hole Friday and never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Steinhauer made the cut along with 76 others. The cut was at
4-over 144.
</P>
<P>
   The most noticeable players who were trimmed from the field were
Becky Iverson, Maria Hjorth and Leta Lindley. Iverson is 17th on
this year's money list, Hjorth 19th and Lindley 21st.
</P>
<P>
   Former Longhorns Kelli Kuehne, Heather Bowie and Nancy
Ramsbottom also did not make today's field.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions were much tougher Friday, with a swirling south wind
gusting in excess of 20 mph. The pin placements weren't as
difficult as Thursday, but the greens still were slow and mushy
from this week's rain.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the low scores came in the afternoon, although Jean
Bartholomew had the best performance of the day with a 6-under 64,
which she finished just after noon.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian Dawn Coe-Jones and Alicia Dibos of Peru created the
most buzz in the gallery late in the day when they each carded a
hole in one within 20 minutes at No. 8, a 156-yard par 3.
</P>
<P>
   The holes in one vaulted both players into contention at 4-under
136.
</P>
<P>
   Coe-Jones, who played collegiately at Lamar University in
Beaumont, didn't realize she had a hole in one until she saw the
reaction from the people around the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it hit, and it rolled the rest of the way,'' she said.
``Everyone was saying `Come on, come on.'''
</P>
<P>
   Coe-Jones used an 8-iron from the tee. The ball carried about
140 yards, hit the green, then slowly climbed uphill another 45
feet until it softly landed in the cup.
</P>
<P>
   Dibos used a 7-iron. Her shot hit about 10 feet closer to the
hole than Coe-Jones. And like the Canadian's shot, it then slowly
climbed the slope before finding the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Davies finished just after Coe-Jones. If not for a three-putt
bogey performance on her final hole, Davies would have been the
outright leader. She has already won once this year (the Los
Angeles Women's Open) to break a two-year championship drought.
She'll be looking for career LPGA victory No. 19.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in her storied career, the affable Davies has
opted to practice before tournaments, although she refuses to play
an actual pre-tournament round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing a practice round ... you might as well have your
fingernails slowly pulled out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   However, she took several baskets of balls to the driving range
and practice green at Onion Creek this week, hitting for two to
three hours.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Turner, a 43-year-old veteran, is trying desperately
to regain her winning form that made her the LPGA player of the
year and leading money winner in 1988. This is the first time in 11
years she has led a tournament after two days. On Friday, she shot
an uneventful 70.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said she hoped someone else would come behind her on
Friday with a lower overall score so she wouldn't feel so much
gnawing pressure when she tees off this morning. She got at least
part of her wish hours later when Davies finished her round.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long, long time since I've led a tournament,''
Turner said. ``The main thing, what I'll probably do (Friday night)
is to try and not talk about golf. But I've got some friends coming
in from Corpus Christi, and that's all they'll want to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the most recent tournament (where she was in
contention) was last year at the (U.S.) Open. I was a little
nervous before Saturday's round. I couldn't sleep. I was tossing
and turning. I finally fell asleep. Hopefully that won't happen
(Friday) night. ... This isn't like it's a bra
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
