<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-PEREZ0506-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves lose Perez for season
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Braves' fears were confirmed Friday. Or as Eddie
Perez put it, ``No mas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm gone,'' said the backup catcher, who will miss the rest of
the season after an MRI test revealed a torn rotator cuff in his
right shoulder. Perez and shortstop Walt Weiss (strained left
hamstring) were placed on the 15-day disabled list, retroactive to
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   While Weiss is expected back promptly, Perez will be operated on
Monday by team orthopedists Marvin Royster and Xavier Duralde, who
repaired Perez's left shoulder and right knee during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say four, five months (rehabilitation). But the pain, I
can't take it any more,'' said Perez, who aggravated a
spring-training injury Wednesday night in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   For now, this leaves 19-year-old rookie Rafael Furcal as the
starting shortstop and the Braves seeking an experienced backup
catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making a lot of calls,'' said manager Bobby Cox.
``Lunar's the guy for now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves bought the contracts of catcher Fernando Lunar from
AA Greenville and infielder John DeRosa from AAA Richmond. Both
joined the team Friday when the Braves opened a weekend series with
Philadelphia at Turner Field. For Lunar, who was hitting .213 at
Greenville with four RBIs in 23 games, this is his first time on
the major-league roster. His stay might be brief.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have to take care of Javy,'' Cox said of Lopez, the
starting catcher who missed almost half of last season after July
26 knee surgery. ``We're using him too much as it is.'' Yet, Lunar
hardly seems a long-term replacement for Perez, Greg Maddux's
regular catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, Eddie's a No. 1 catcher backing up,'' Cox said.Perez
was the MVP of last season's NLCS when he hit .500. ``He's been
important to us for a long time. We lost a lot there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very disappointing, especially with this team we have
right now,'' said Perez, who was hitting .182 in seven games this
season. ``Everybody wants to be a part of this team. It's
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux said of Perez:``It's too bad. Eddie's been a big part of
our success,'' Maddux said. ``He brings a lot of things to the
club, and you can't replace his leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
