<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WPP-YOUNG-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS RESUME BETWEEN WPP GROUP, YOUNG AND RUBICAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to rewrite 7th and 8th grafs with different emphasis.)  
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The on-again, off-again merger talks between WPP Group
of Britain and Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. are on again. A week after
negotiations between the two advertising companies broke down, WPP
said Friday that it had returned to the bargaining table in hopes
of reviving a takeover of Y&AMP;R, which is based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Young &AMP; Rubicam continues to be courted by
Publicis SA, the French advertising company. According to
executives close to the talks, the chief executive of Y&AMP;R, Thomas
D. Bell Jr., is negotiating with both companies again, seeking to
take advantage of each company's ambition to add Y&AMP;R to its
holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Bell has two suitors for Y&AMP;R, he may be able to
instigate a bidding war between them.
</P>
<P>
   A deal between WPP and Y&AMP;R, which has already been derailed
twice, would create the world's largest advertising company in
billings and revenue and would be the richest agency-company
takeover in history. WPP, which owns Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide, J.
Walter Thompson and the public relations agency Hill &AMP; Knowlton, is
keen to take control of Y&AMP;R to add even more mass and scale to its
ever-growing operations as the industry continues to consolidate.
</P>
<P>
   Y&AMP;R is one of the last few big independent agency companies,
which makes it particularly attractive to Sir Martin Sorrell, the
acquisitive, ambitious chief executive at WPP.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the talks ended, both sides wagged their fingers
at the other in a public scuffle with conflicting versions of who
was at fault. Executives from WPP accused Y&AMP;R executives of
changing the terms of the deal at the 11th hour, contending that
the lawyer representing Y&AMP;R wrote new details into the merger
document by hand. Y&AMP;R executives, for their part, asserted that WPP
made oral and written assurances that were then not included in the
document.
</P>
<P>
   The debate centered on to what extent WPP could make changes to
Y&AMP;R operations in the first year after the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Controversy also arose over Sorrell's plan to discourage Y&AMP;R's
top executives from leaving the combined agency company by
instituting a noncompete provision that would have effectively kept
departing employees from working in the industry for a year. Y&AMP;R
managers considered the provision too harsh. Other disagreements
occurred over severance packages and contractual matters.
</P>
<P>
   But on the most important issue, price, both sides had different
stories.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at WPP said they believed Y&AMP;R had agreed that its
British suitor would pay about $5 billion. Executives at Y&AMP;R said
no deal had been struck on the price of the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear what changed to bring WPP back to the bargaining
table, but executives close to the talks said both agency companies
might be willing to make more concessions. Sorrell, the executives
say, wants desperately to agree to a friendly deal with Y&AMP;R, though
they portrayed him as not averse to a hostile bid. Indeed, it was
through a hostile takeover of Ogilvy &AMP; Mather that Sorrell turned
WPP into what is now the world's third-largest agency company.
</P>
<P>
   Bell's interest in a deal with WPP has also been reignited,
though executives close to the talks said Bell and Sorrell still
had disdain for each other.
</P>
<P>
   A tie-up between WPP and Y&AMP;R is more compelling than a deal with
Publicis, an executive close to Y&AMP;R said, because both WPP and Y&AMP;R
serve some of the same clients _ like Ford, Kraft, Mattel and Sears
_ and do not have major client conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Y&AMP;R and Publicis could have a major client
conflict because Y&AMP;R works for Ford Motor and Publicis works for
General Motors (through an American agency, Publicis &AMP; Hal Riney in
San Francisco) and for Renault.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, shares of Young &AMP; Rubicam rose
$4.50, or 9 percent, to $54.125. American depository receipts of
WPP _ with each ADR representing five shares of the British company
_ fell $5.50, or 6.8 percent, to $75.50. Publicis shares fell 18
euros, or 3.3 percent, to 534 euros on the Paris bourse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
