<HEADLINE>
MERCKER TO GET FIRST START OF SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ This is the start Kent Mercker never thought he would
get.
</P>
<P>
   Mercker will get his first start of the season today against the
Mariners because Jason Dickson is out with a strained left hip
flexor. Mercker was so disappointed he didn't win a spot in the
rotation at the end of spring training he said he didn't expect to
get another chance.
</P>
<P>
   But that was unrealistic, considering the chance for injury or
lack of production from one or more of the pitchers. So now he has
his chance, but he says he isn't looking at it as more than just
one game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about five days from now, 10 days from now,''
he said. ''I'm not making the decisions, I'm a player. If I throw a
shutout or give up eight runs, it's not going to change their long-
or short-term plans for me one way or another.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker is 0-1 with a 6.61 ERA in 10 relief appearances, but has
made it clear he prefers starting.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I do?'' he said. ``There's no sense in wondering why.
I've pretty much blocked it out. ... I was honestly disappointed
coming out of spring, but I'm not one to pout or create waves.
There's a political side to this game, there are politics
everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Mike Scioscia, however, simply wants to put his best
pitchers out there. He chose Scott Schoeneweis over Mercker and
Schoeneweis is 4-0 with a 3.43 ERA. As for today, Scioscia would
like to see Mercker pitch deep into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fortunate some of Kent's outings have stretched him out
some,'' Scioscia said. ``He's thrown some three-innings-plus stints
and his pitch counts have been high enough to think six innings is
not unrealistic.''
</P>
<P>
   DISARCINA ENCOURAGED: Shortstop Gary DiSarcina worked out
Friday, fielding ground balls and making throws to test his sore
right shoulder. He said it went well, but Scioscia implied it will
probably be a few more days before DiSarcina is back in the
starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a great day today as far as getting his confidence
back,'' Scioscia said. ``We're much more encouraged that this will
be short-term rather than long term.''
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina said he's not going to rush himself back.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I feel it tighten up again I'll stop,'' DiSarcina said.
''It's too early in the season.''
</P>
<P>
   BELCHER THROWS: Pitcher Tim Belcher played catch Friday, but the
next course of action in his recovery from elbow surgery has not
been determined. Belcher is probably still at least a week away
from making another rehab start.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
