<SLUG> BC-OCONNOR-FUNERAL-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'CONNOR FUNERAL PREPARATIONS: LITURGY TO LOGISTICS, HUNDREDS OF
DETAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SHAILA K. DEWAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are very few differences, ritually speaking,
between a funeral for a cardinal and one for any other Catholic.
One is that a cardinal, like other priests, lies in state in his
church before burial. In this case, of course, the cardinal is John
O'Connor, who died at 80 on Wednesday night, and the church is St.
Patrick's Cathedral, the largest Roman Catholic cathedral in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   As mourners pay their respects to O'Connor this weekend, they
will see him dressed in the same vestments he would use when
celebrating a Mass on Easter or Christmas, with the white bishop's
miter that is reserved for the holiest days. . On his wedding
finger, there is a ring that symbolizes devotion to his flock.
</P>
<P>
   Before he is placed in the crypt underneath the high altar, a
final commendation will be spoken, most likely by one of the three
cardinals who will preside over the funeral Mass. After another
rite, the Prayer of Entombment, the cardinal's family and the
clergymen will file out of the crypt, and the cardinal will be
entombed in private, said the Rev. Eric Raaser, dean of students at
the St. John Neumann Seminary Residence. There the cardinal will
rest, unless there is a motion to canonize him and his coffin is
disinterred to check whether, by chance or miracle, his body has
remained ``incorruptible.''
</P>
<P>
   As the funeral weekend progresses, there are hundreds of details
to be taken care of. But the liturgical ones are almost rote,
compared with the logistical ones.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some matters were far from the spiritual. And many of them were
attended to by Joseph Zwilling, the press spokesman who had played
straight man to the quip-loving cardinal for 16 years. No, he did
not remember saying NY1 could set up a camera stand on the steps of
the cathedral, Zwilling almost sighed into a walkie-talkie after a
news briefing Friday, a few hours before the cardinal's body was
due to arrive there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want this to be as dignified as possible,'' he said
patiently. ``If it's what I'm picturing in my mind, I probably
wouldn't have agreed to it.'' Then, almost in the same breath, he
agreed to the camera stand if someone at the cathedral said it
looked acceptable. A television journalist rushed in, late, and
asked him how he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``About to fall over,'' Zwilling said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For the funeral Mass, more than 3,500 tickets will be issued for
a cathedral that seats 2,300. President and Clinton will attend,
Secret Service in tow. Vice President Al Gore, Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas, Gov. George E. Pataki and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani plan to
come, as well. During the Mass at 2 p.m. Monday, the streets around
St. Patrick's will be closed to traffic.
</P>
<P>
   In preparation, the Catholic Center on First Avenue has
suspended all its normal operations. An ad hoc office was created
to help with hospitality arrangements. A command center was set up
to handle calls. The director of human resources, Deacon Randy
Velez, spent Friday manning one of six urgently ringing phones,
talking to everyone from a new convert in Denver who wanted to
express his condolences, to the archbishop of Northern Ireland
calling about his trip.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Archdiocese faxed forms to every bishop asking
for their RSVPs and travel requirements. All eight U.S. cardinals
will be at the funeral, along with the Vatican's secretary of
state, Cardinal Angelo Sodano, who will preside over the Mass.
``Every bishop I can think of will be attending,'' Velez said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Mass, the priests will gather at the Palace Hotel,
across the street from the cathedral buildings, to put on their
robes for the procession of concelebrants, or clergy. The bishops
will dress downstairs at the cathedral, and exit through the side
door to join the procession, which will be arranged by rank.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no altar boys; instead the altar will be manned,
as it is every third Sunday, by seminarians from St. Joseph's
Seminary of Dunwoodie, N.Y. The Rev. Tom Lynch, the seminary's
master of ceremonies, said that all 40 seminarians would be on hand
to help the concelebrants, but only eight would serve at the altar.
There was not much debate over which eight would have the honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I just look at who's better at pushing priests
around, and doing it nicely,'' Lynch said.
</P>
<P>
   While Sodano will preside over the Mass, two men who were at the
cardinal's deathbed will, according to his request, take part.
Cardinal Bernard Law, archbishop of Boston, will deliver the
homily, and Cardinal William Wakefield Baum, a Vatican official,
will give an address.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual for such requests to be made, even when they
break with the tradition of bishops preaching at bishops' funerals.
At the funeral for Cardinal Joseph Bernardin, archbishop of
Chicago, in 1996, a monsignor who had long been his secretary gave
the homily. At St. Patrick's, multiple Masses will be held all
weekend for groups of special concern to Cardinal O'Connor,
including children and the disabled. Those Masses are all open to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``What was really our overriding concern was that as many people
be given an opportunity to pay their respects,'' Zwilling said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
