<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: BLAIR VOWS COOPERATION
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair promised to work with Ken Livingstone,
the left-wing maverick he tried to keep off the ballot but who won
the race for London's first elected mayor with 58 percent of the
final vote. Blair also acknowledged that Conservative success in
winning back some 600 of the 3,300 local council seats across
England represented ``some bad results.'' But Conservatives
suffered a shock loss of a parliamentary seat in the one
by-election, in Romsey, southeast England, where the winner was a
Liberal Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: $3 MILLION LEGAL BILL
</P>
<P>
   The historian David Irving, who lost a libel case against
Penguin Books and the American academic Deborah Lipstadt last
month, was ordered to begin paying their legal costs, estimated at
more than $3 million. Justice Charles Gray, who ruled that Irving,
62, was a racist and a Holocaust denier, gave him until June 16 to
pay a first installment of $231,000. If Irving cannot pay, he will
be forced to declare bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: READY FOR CHECHEN ATTACKS
</P>
<P>
   Russian forces in Chechnya are preparing for attacks by Islamic
guerrillas timed to coincide with the May 9 holiday marking
Russia's World War II defeat of Germany, the Interior Ministry
said. Security has been increased after intelligence reports that
the rebels may try sabotage. Russia says about 3,500 guerrillas
remain in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: 10 HELD IN McDONALD'S BLASTS
</P>
<P>
   Investigating two McDonald's restaurant bombings in Brittany
that left one person dead, the police have detained some 10 people
for questioning. Those detained include Basques and suspected
Breton separatists. Small groups of Breton separatists are seeking
autonomy. Two Breton groups have denied responsibility for a blast
April 19 that killed a 27-year-old McDonald's employee.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL: EX-FIRST LADY SENTENCED
</P>
<P>
   A court has sentenced the former first lady Rosane Collor de
Mello to an 11-year prison term on charges of taking kickbacks and
diverting money from the relief agency she ran during her husband's
presidency. Fernando Collor de Mello was impeached in 1992 after
his brother accused him of taking millions of dollars from
companies bidding for government contracts. Lawyers for Collor, who
has been in exile in Miami with her husband, said she would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL: FISCAL LAW SIGNED
</P>
<P>
   In a major advance for the government's effort to bring budget
deficits under control as promised in a 1998 accord with the
International Monetary Fund, President Fernando Henrique Cardoso
has signed a ``fiscal responsibility law'' that puts strict limits
on spending by states. The law caps government salaries, sets fines
for officeholders who violate those ceilings and prohibits state
governors from increasing budget outlays unless there is a rise in
tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: CAMPAIGNING IN U.S.
</P>
<P>
   The two leading opposition presidential candidates headed to the
United States to campaign for the allegiances of Mexicans north of
the border, hoping that millions of expatriates might influence the
votes of their relatives living in Mexico. Vicente Fox, a centrist
who was governor of Guanajuato, was to campaign in Chicago and Los
Angeles. Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, a leftist former Mexico City mayor,
was to tour Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: NATIONAL STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   Dissident union members began a nationwide strike in opposition
to labor reform legislation proposed by President Fernando de la
Rua. The strike, led by the head of the truckers' union, Hugo
Moyano, was limited in impact, but buses in major urban centers and
the nation's flagship airline cut back on services.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANISTAN: SPYING FOR U.S.
</P>
<P>
   An Arab arrested in Afghanistan confessed on videotape that the
United States recruited him to find Osama bin Laden, who is accused
of terrorism. The Associated Press has reviewed the tape, made by a
camera crew working for United Arab Emirates Television. The
television reporters said the prisoner also told them he provided
information that led to the Taliban's arrest of an American spy.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: SRI LANKA TIES
</P>
<P>
   Israel and Sri Lanka will resume diplomatic ties, and officials
from Colombo are expected to visit next week and deliver a plea for
immediate military aid. The Sri Lankans, who cut off official
relations with Israel in 1990 but renewed a military procurement
relationship in 1995, are requesting Kfir fighter jets and small
sea craft to arm the country in its defensive battle against Tamil
rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
