<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OAKS-BLIGHT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARBORISTS TRY TO TRACE DEADLY OAK MALADY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY ANDERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A mysterious blight that has decimated oak trees
from Mendocino to Monterey may have claimed its first casualties in
Los Angeles, four oak trees in Topanga Canyon, officials said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists and arborists said the cause of what they call
``sudden death'' is unknown, but the disease moves with such
stunning speed that it can kill a tree in a matter of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Northern California, they are calling it an epidemic,''
said Los Angeles County Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky, whose district
includes Topanga and the Santa Monica Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   In areas where the disease has been identified in Northern
California, it has afflicted 30 percent to 48 percent of oak trees,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Because so little is known about the blight, the Board of
Supervisors is expected to vote Tuesday on Yaroslavsky's motion to
ask for an urgent investigation of the Topanga tree deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously our oak woodlands are very precious and we cannot
afford to lose them,'' Yaroslavsky said. ``We need to do everything
we can to save them. Some of these oaks are hundreds and hundreds
of years old. Before this becomes an epidemic here, if there is
anything we can do to prevent this, I want our experts to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosi Dagit, a certified arborist and senior conservation
biologist for the state Resource Conservation District of the Santa
Monica Mountains, said the death of the Topanga trees is unusual
and scary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quick death is uncommon and a very frightening thing,''
Dagit said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went from full, green, healthy trees to absolutely brown
in a month or less,'' she said. ``I didn't believe it initially.
That is very uncharacteristic of oaks. But several homeowners had
photos that were dated.''
</P>
<P>
   Dagit called a plant pathologist at the University of
California, Davis, who is studying the disease that first appeared
in Marin County in the mid-1990s and has since spread to Mendocino,
Sonoma, Marin, Santa Clara, Santa Cruz and Monterey counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we found were infestations of bark beetles,'' she said.
``But what came first - the dead trees or the beetles? Did the
beetles kill the tree, or did something kill the tree and the
beetles came in? We were not able to conclusively answer that
question.''
</P>
<P>
   Since finding the trees, Dagit has not received any more reports
of oak deaths in the Topanga area. The four dead trees were removed
and burned, with twig samples sent to UC Davis for study.
</P>
<P>
   In Northern California, the disease has not discriminated,
killing tan oak, coast live oak, black oak and canyon wild oak
trees, said Rick Standiford, associate dean of the College of
Natural Resources at the University of California, Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   The possible causes include beetles, fungi and weather.
</P>
<P>
   Experts have differences in opinion about whether the deaths are
the result of a single pathogen or oaks weakened by drought or
other environmental factors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trees have a weepy, black sap, which is usually the first
symptom,'' Standiford said. ``Then they get attacked by a couple of
different species of beetles. They get a secondary pathogen. And
then they go from green to suddenly brown. That's how the name
`sudden death' was attributed to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Standiford said scientists are considering using pesticides on
the trees near homes to kill the beetles, but it would be
impractical to use on hundreds of thousands of oak trees throughout
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Their work is important not only because oak trees provide food
and shelter for wildlife, but because oak trees are a treasured
resource in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people think about the California landscape, they think
about spreading oaks and golden hills. I think oaks have a certain
tie with our cultural psyche.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before this disease, oak trees have been endangered and
subject to tough restrictions. Homeowners and developers must seek
permission to cut them down or even prune live branches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oak trees are fairly limited in Los Angeles County. Out of
152,000 acres in the Santa Monica Mountains National Recreation
Area, fewer than 16,600 acres remains of oak woodlands,'' Dagit
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you consider that when the Spanish came through here in
the 1700s, they described coming over the pass and seeing
magnificent trees stretching all the way to the ocean. We have
changed things fairly dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
