<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-FUSAICHI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUSAICHI PEGASUS: MYTH OR MASTER?
</HEADLINE>
 PEGASUS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Racehorses _ fast racehorses, fortunate
racehorses _ win the Kentucky Derby. The winner isn't always the
best racehorse _ he's sometimes the luckiest _ but there's no doubt
about it. He, and occasionally she, is a racehorse.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus (pronounced Foo-saw-EE-chee) might be the
favorite once the horses are loaded into the starting gate for the
126th Kentucky Derby at about 4:25 p.m. Saturday. But he doesn't
always act like a racehorse.
</P>
<P>
   Since arriving at Churchill Downs more than two weeks ago, he
has sometimes looked more like the rank animal that comes out of
chute No. 3 in the saddle-bronc contest at Will Rogers Memorial
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   After one of his less-eventful mornings at Churchill, when he
bucked only a few times, trainer Neil Drysdale smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was full of beans this morning,'' Drysdale said. ``He's
throwing in a few bucks, playing out there, feeling good about
himself. We let him do it because he's such a big horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm very happy with the way he's training. He's had strong
gallops. He's been on the bit and maintained good pull. There's no
maliciousness in him at all. I'd be worried if he'd go out there
and be placid.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his bucking, rearing and kicking, Fusaichi Pegasus puts
on a game face when the starting gates open. He has lost only one
race, his career debut five races ago, when he lost a slim lead
late in the stretch. Since then, he has won four in a row, by an
average margin of 2 1/2 lengths.
</P>
<P>
   That includes a winning effort in the Wood Memorial Stakes for
his final Derby prep. He balked going to the starting gate before
the race and reared away from his escort pony going back to the
winner's circle. In between, he drilled the field, winning by 4 1/2
lengths.
</P>
<P>
   But his victory didn't make believers of everyone. A favorite
hasn't won the Derby in 20 years, since Spectacular Bid in 1979. D.
Wayne Lukas has trained four Derby winners, and he says the media
creates false favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys put so much importance on that last prep race,'' he
said. ``But what the horse does in the three weeks between that
last prep race and the Derby is the most important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas points to Arazi in 1992. Arazi went off as an odds-on
favorite in the Derby largely because he was a runaway winner in
the Breeders' Cup Juvenile the year before at Churchill. A a
3-year-old, he had one prep race in France before shipping to
Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``He comes walking by here every day on his way to the track,
looking less than perfect,'' Lukas said at his barn. ``He dumps
(jockey) Pat Valenzuela off one morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they finally get him to the track, he bolts to the
outside. Yet, nobody thinks anything of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas won't pinpoint Fusaichi Pegasus as this year's Arazi, who
finished eighth. He said he'll only make specific comments about
his own horses.
</P>
<P>
   Others say Fusaichi Pegasus is the real deal. Chris McCarron
rides The Deputy, who's second on the morning line behind Fusaichi
Pegasus. Both horses raced in the San Felipe Stakes in March at
Santa Anita, and Fusaichi Pegasus edged away to win by nearly a
length despite jockey Kent Desormeaux not touching him with the
whip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pulled up alongside him that day, and it was clear Kent
wasn't even trying to get to the bottom of his horse,'' McCarron
said. ``That was scary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I watched him race in the Wood on TV. I see Kent take him
back behind horses on that wet track and hope to see that horse's
head fly up in the air because he doesn't like the dirt in his
face. But he handled it beautifully. My horse can win. But I think
Kent's on a really good horse.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
