<SLUG> BC-TIMEWARNER-CABLE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME WARNER OFFERING REFUNDS FOR ABC FLAP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Time Warner Cable subscribers will get a free
month of a company-owned premium channel and credit for two days'
worth of basic service because of this week's 36-hour ABC blackout,
officials announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   And KABC (Channel 7) said it has given away thousands of
vouchers for free satellite television systems - an anti-cable
retaliation strategy that it will continue through the weekend,
further escalating the battle of the entertainment titans.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Brown, Time Warner Cable's division vice president, said
the two-day rebate amounts to roughly one dollar each for 150,000
Time Warner households in the San Fernando, Santa Clarita and San
Gabriel valleys.
</P>
<P>
   The refund, which varies slightly among areas of service and
even between neighbors (an apartment complex may have a group rate
and therefore a lower refund for each tenant than the house next
door), will be posted automatically on customers' bills. Similar
offers were made to customers in New York City, Houston and other
affected markets.
</P>
<P>
   Southern California customers will also receive one free month
of HBO Family, a premium channel showing G-rated movies, Brown
said. Customers will be advised by ads and mailers of the start
date and other details about HBO Family, valued at about $10 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   It comes as no surprise that Time Warner chose a direct
competitor of The Disney Channel, one of the services at the heart
of the adversarial contract talks between The Walt Disney Co. and
Time Warner that led to Monday's ABC blackout.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at KABC reported brisk demand for its rebates for
purchase and installation of DirecTV satellite dishes. Station
spokesman Bill Burton said the company gave away all 1,000 of its
$198 rebates for DirecTV within 25 minutes of the launch Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Thursday) we upped it to 2,000 and that sold out in about two
hours, and today we're just about to sell out,'' Burton said midday
Friday. KABC will continue offering 2,000 rebate certificates per
day at least through Monday and will consider extending the plan if
demand warrants it.
</P>
<P>
   The two media giants had been negotiating for several months
over the fees Time Warner Cable must pay Disney - parent company of
ABC, ESPN, The Disney Channel and other TV networks - for the right
to carry its cable channels. Their latest extension expired April
30 at midnight, and while Disney wanted to keep ABC running until
the end of the current ratings sweeps, Time Warner pulled the ABC
signal for 3.5 million households nationwide. Some 350,000 in the
Los Angeles area were affected.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner reinstated the signal Tuesday afternoon under a
temporary extension that lasts until July 15. Executives from both
sides have been comparing their schedules and may resume talks as
soon as next week.
</P>
<P>
   The blackout threw a spotlight on the acrimonious negotiations,
which started late last year. Time Warner contends that Disney is
trying to overcharge the cable company for its channels, which
would drive up customer rates.
</P>
<P>
   Disney has accused Time Warner of acting like a monopoly and
throwing its weight around in anticipation of its merger with
America Online, which will make it the world's largest
entertainment corporation.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown of Time Warner said the apparent success of the
satellite rebate program indicates otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it sort of refutes some of the statements about us
being a monopoly,'' he said. ``People do have choices as to where
they get their nonbroadcast channels.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 2330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0401 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7410 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-BARTALI-NYT &LR;      05-05 0272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BARTALI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GINO BARTALI, 85, A HERO IN ITALY FOR HIS CYCLING CHAMPIONSHIPS
</HEADLINE>
  By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Gino Bartali, an Italian cycling champion whose victory
in the 1948 Tour de France helped unite his politically torn
country, died Friday at his home in Florence, his son Andrea
Bartali said. He was 85. Bartali, who also won the Tour de France
in 1938 and the Giro D'Italia in 1936, 1937 and 1946, was nicknamed
the Iron Man of Tuscany for his endurance. Bartali, who was
Catholic, was also known as Gino the Pious, especially after he
surged ahead of the pack on the stage to the pilgrimage city of
Lourdes in the 1948 Tour de France, a lead he maintained all the
way to Paris.
</P>
<P>
   For older Italians, Bartali's victory was memorable for its
soothing effect on one of the most politically edgy moments in
post-war Italian history. Bartali's 1948 triumph occurred on the
same day that the Communist leader Palmiro Togliatti was shot and
wounded, an assassination attempt that brought Italian communists
to the brink of insurrection.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say that civil war was averted by a Tour de France victory
is surely excessive,'' said the former prime minister Giulio
Andreotti, 81, who at the time was a young Christian Democrat
politician. ``But it is undeniable that on that 14th of July of
1948, day of the attack on Togliatti, Bartali contributed to ease
the tensions.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartali, who fought with the partisans during the last year of
World War II, competed in 988 races between 1931 and 1954, winning
184.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Adriana, two sons and a daughter.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
