<HEADLINE>
DERBY HAS CINDERELLA STORY AMID STACKS OF CASH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ There are many stories of horses who were
bought for relatively bargain prices winning the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet, the Derby winner two years ago, cost about $17,000
when he was a yearling. Seattle Slew, the Triple Crown winner of
1977, cost about the same. Last year's winner, Charismatic, was
running in a claiming race for $62,500 just a few months before he
improved enough to hit the Derby trail.
</P>
<P>
   But it's money, serious money, that is homing in on the 126th
running of the Kentucky Derby contested Saturday at Churchill
Downs. Derby favorite Fusaichi Pegasus took $4 million from the
account of Japanese businessman Fusao Sekiguchi when the colt was
purchased at a yearling auction two years ago. And The Deputy, the
second choice on the morning line, was brought from Great Britain
late last year and syndicated for $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   It sometimes costs that much to satisfy Derby Fever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in this business for a long time, and I really never
was that interested in the Derby,'' said Barry Irwin, the managing
partner of the Team Valor syndicate that owns The Deputy. ``But our
clients \Rin Team Valor\S are diseased with Derby fever. They want
to do this, so we supply them with the stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's a Cinderella story, go to the barn of Harold Rose.
He's 88 years old and has been training for more than 40 years. His
wife is writing a book about his experiences. His jockey, Roger
Velez, is a recovering alcoholic, and Rose underwent quadruple
bypass heart surgery last year.
</P>
<P>
   He has Hal's Hope in the race, a horse he bred, raised and
trains. He has been at the barn every morning, but the busy
schedule finally got to him late in the week. He had to take a seat
in a chair rather than stand up as he had been doing while talking
with the media outside his barn.
</P>
<P>
   ``My legs are getting just a little bit tired, what with keeping
up with this horse and all you guys,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those old legs could handle another walk, right over to the
winner's circle.
HORSE RACING/KENTUCKY DERBY CAPSULES
