r s BC-RAC-DERBY-JOCKEY-TEX     05-05 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-JOCKEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFRICAN-AMERICAN JOCKEY GLAD FOR DERBY SHOT, EVEN A LONG ONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Marlon St. Julien is accustomed to making
history. He was the winning jockey for the first race at Lone Star
Park at Grand Prairie in 1997, and he was the leading rider at the
track the first two years.
</P>
<P>
   And when St. Julien rides Curule on Saturday in the Kentucky
Derby, he'll be the first African-American to be in the race in 79
years. The last time it happened was 1921, when Henry King rode
Planet to a 10th-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   Curule might not do any better. Along with stablemate China
Visit, Curule is listed as 50-1 in the morning line. Owned by the
Godolphin Stable of Sheik Mohammed bin Rashid al Maktoum of Dubai,
Curule (it's pronounced Koo-RULE) has never raced in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he's a way, way long shot,'' St. Julien said. ``But I'm
going to just ride this race with confidence. You gotta be in it to
win it.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Julien, 28, said he wasn't surprised when the news got out
that it had been almost 80 years since an African-American has
ridden in the Derby. He said he has been studying the history of
the Derby and the heritage of black riders since he moved from Lone
Star to ride in New Orleans and on the lucrative Kentucky circuit
last year.
</P>
<P>
   In the first running of the Kentucky Derby in 1875, 13 of the 15
jockeys were African-American. And 15 of the first 28 runnings of
the Derby were won by African-American jockeys.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly the most-famous African-American jockey was Isaac
Murphy, who was the first jockey _ no matter the skin color _ to
win the Derby three times and also in consecutive years. His three
Derby winners ranks in a tie for fourth behind Eddie Arcaro, Bill
Hartack and Bill Shoemaker.
</P>
<P>
   St. Julien, a native of Lafayette, La., is hoping his appearance
in the race will help him get another ride in future years. He also
rode Zoftig to a fifth-place finish in Friday's Kentucky Oaks,
which is considered the Kentucky Derby for fillies.
</P>
<P>
   ``My business (as a jockey) is good,'' said St. Julien, who also
appears in various print ads with other jockeys promoting cellular
phones in the Louisville area. ``But maybe people will pay more
attention to me. And maybe it will bring in some other
African-American riders who have been struggling to make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad that things have been this way, no African-American
rider in the Derby for this long. Anyone who works hard deserves a
shot.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 2337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
