<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7420 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-INJURIES-     05-05 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-INJURIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURIES GIVE RANGERS A BIT MORE PAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Texas Rangers' bewildering injury news
got worse Friday.
</P>
<P>
   David Segui was out of the lineup with a strained hip flexor and
Justin Thompson couldn't throw in the bullpen as scheduled because
of continued soreness in his left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder:
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates looked at the sky around 6 p.m. and said,
``Come on rain!''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Doug Melvin, fighting a nasty cough said, ``I
need to go on the disabled list but there's no room for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Esteban Loaiza sat on the bench before the game, shook
his head and said, ``I've never seen this many injuries before.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the day-to-day troubles, Thompson is the biggest
concern. Thompson said he felt good enough to throw Friday, but
reported some soreness while going through some range-of-motion
tests with Dr. John Conway.
</P>
<P>
   Conway then decided Thompson should hold off a couple more days
before his next bullpen session. Thompson will play catch Saturday
and be re-examined by Conway on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's come this far without any major setbacks; we didn't want
to push it,'' trainer Danny Wheat said. ``So we decided to give him
an extra couple days.''
</P>
<P>
   Segui is listed as day-to-day but is still ``pretty sore'' and
is questionable for Saturday night's game. He injured himself
running to first base while hitting into the crucial ninth-inning
double play in Thursday's 8-7 loss to the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Palmeiro is struggling with a strained hamstring muscle
but did start at designated hitter. He, like Oates, was hoping for
rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team could definitely use an extra day,'' Palmeiro said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Sheldon started at first base Friday night, an ironic
twist considering the great debate in spring training and the start
of the season over how much Segui and Palmeiro would split time
there.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also had Luis Alicea in the lineup despite his calf
muscle injury. But Segui's problems kept the Rangers from calling
up outfielder Scarborough Green from the minor leagues. Instead the
Rangers went with the extra infielder and three outfielders for the
third consecutive game.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers would like to get Rusty Greer back, but, while he
has recovered from his ankle surgery, he is bothered by a pulled
hamstring. The Rangers thought the ankle would take longer.
</P>
<P>
   Greer said he's not sure when he'll be ready to play, but the
Rangers are hoping to send him on a medical rehabilitation
assignment next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard when you a watch a game and see teammates getting
injured, and you can't do anything about it,'' Greer said. ``The
thing you focus on is trying to get well and get off the disabled
list.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been easy for Greer ... or anybody else. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
