<HEADLINE>
ON THE DOCKET: HOWDY DOODY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., R.I., Mich.)  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ As Howdy Doody cooled his heels in a secret
Rhode Island bank vault, two lawyers tried Friday to persuade a
U.S. District Court judge here to grant their clients custody of
the famous puppet.
</P>
<P>
   On one side of the Howdy lawsuit is the family of his former
master, the puppeteer Rufus Rose; they believe that the marionette
belongs to them. On the other side is the Detroit Institute of
Arts, which claims that Rose, who died in 1975, had agreed to hand
over Howdy when he retired.
</P>
<P>
   Howdy was the star of ``The Howdy Doody Show,'' a television
program for children which ran from 1947 to 1960.Friday, lawyers
for the Rose family and the museum filed motions for summary
judgment, a way of asking Judge Christopher Droney to decide who
owns Howdy without calling in a jury.
</P>
<P>
   Droney allowed each side two more weeks to submit supporting
documents. After that, he will issue a decision, a process that
could take weeks or even months, lawyers said.
</P>
</TEXT>
