<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-CHANGES-655&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI CALMER AMID TURBULENCE IN HIS PRIVATE LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It has been one of the most turbulent weeks in Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani's 55 years. He met with more doctors to determine
his treatment for prostate cancer, acknowledged at a news briefing
that he has a ``very good'' female friend, fended off questions
about his wife's postponement of her starring role in ``The Vagina
Monologues,'' and stepped outside the gates of Gracie Mansion
shortly before midnight on Wednesday to talk of his sadness at the
loss of a friend, Cardinal John O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   And, not least, he made two trips upstate in his campaign for
U.S. Senate against the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Next week promises more. Giuliani's advisers say the mayor's
campaign schedule and four big California fund-raisers in mid-May
give him until late next week to announce his plans for treatment
and indicate which way he is leaning about staying in the race.
Most of his advisers say his concerns about his health have made
the Senate race and the news about his female friend of the last
year, Judith Nathan, less important for now.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said as much on Friday during his weekly radio call-in
show. In response to a question from ``Keith from Washington
Heights,'' Giuliani recounted how he had been asked during a
campaign stop last week in Saratoga Springs whether he saw his
cancer as an opportunity to get out of the Senate race and run for
governor in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how profoundly off base all that is,''
Giuliani said. ``If you understand anything about someone that is
trying to focus on cancer, what it means, how to deal with it, how
to deal with it effectively, you would know that that becomes the
thing that you focus on as intelligently and as focused a way as
you possibly can. And that's what I'm doing. And it puts everything
almost in a sense of perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, City Hall advisers describe the self-contained
and often short-tempered mayor as unusually warm, solicitous and
even affectionate. ``He comes in in the morning and he'll throw his
arm around one of the deputy mayors and give him a hug,'' said one
mayoral adviser who requested anonymity because he did not want to
be identified as passing on City Hall secrets, even ones flattering
to the mayor. ``He says hello to everyone and shakes everyone's
hands. He seems happier. It's weird.''
</P>
<P>
   Advisers say that since Giuliani's announcement of his
diagnosis, he is listening more to them at staff meetings, thanking
them for their contributions and asking about their welfare. And
while no one is predicting that Giuliani's mood will last, he
himself addressed the change after his diagnosis in one of his
increasingly reflective, and friendly, comments to reporters last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it has changed me in any way,'' he said at a
campaign stop last weekend in Buffalo. ``I think when you face news
like this, and you absorb it, it changes you. I think it changes
you in a good way.''
</P>
<P>
   But his advisers, who last week said the mayor's battle with
cancer could give him the kick and focus he needed for the race,
are now saying they have no idea what he will do. Giuliani, they
said, does not yet know himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the advantages that I have, and it gets you through all
kinds of difficulties and problems and maybe it's the only way to
get through them, is to just be honest,'' Giuliani said in a long,
introspective answer to ``Keith from Washington Heights'' on his
radio show. ``You know, like, be honest with yourself, say what you
think, and then you can reflect on it that way personally, and you
don't end up dividing yourself into two or three different
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said that he had spent most of Thursday ``going though
evaluations'' for his treatment, that he ``would very much like''
to run, and that he expected to raise as much as $32 million for
the race _ he already has $20 million. He added, ``I am not
thinking about any other office.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Giuliani said he was a ``very, very strong supporter'' of Gov.
George Pataki, who ``in this difficulty'' had been ``very kind and
generous to me, above and beyond everything else.'' He added: ``If
you know me at all, you know that personal loyalty is the single
most important thing. Nothing is more important than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Advisers and associates of the mayor say Giuliani, in
acknowledging his relationship with Nathan earlier this week,
evidently wanted it to become known, because he was taking her to
such highly public events as town hall meetings and the annual
Inner Circle dinner, which is attended by reporters, politicians
and hundreds of others.
</P>
<P>
   Some advisers say that the acknowledgment was timed to get the
matter out in the open a full six months before the election, and
that it came at a time when Giuliani's battle with cancer had
generated much sympathy, even among his longtime enemies. Giuliani,
they said, could not be charged with political hypocrisy, because
he has not made ``family values'' a part of his campaign, and has
made no secret of his estrangement from his wife, Donna Hanover.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Minarik, the Monroe County Republican chairman, said
Friday in Rochester that Giuliani's relationship with Nathan was
getting no coverage in Rochester and that it would not matter to
voters. ``People don't care about the personal stuff,'' Minarik
said. ``I don't know what the mayor's relationship is with his
wife. I've never asked him. It's none of my business.''
</P>
<P>
   But one political consultant to Democrats and Republicans in New
York City said Friday that the mayor's relationship with Nathan
could harm him with women and Catholics upstate. ``I think there's
a tendency for women to look askance upstate in heavily Catholic
areas,'' the consultant said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
