<HEADLINE>
DIRT-TRACK MOTORCYCLE RACING STRIVING TO REGAIN RECOGNITION
</HEADLINE>
 TRACKS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEN HAYWARD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Dirt-track motorcycle racing has a history
that predates the debut of the Indianapolis 500 in 1911.
</P>
<P>
   There is even some dirt track, or flat track, history in North
Texas, where motorcycle fans speak about Ross Downs with reverence.
Formerly located in Colleyville, Ross Downs was the training ground
for dirt-track motorcycle national champions Mike Kidd and Bubba
Shobert and the center of the sport in the Southwest through the
1970s. The quarter-mile track closed in the 1980s, and the land has
become one of the many subdivisions in ever-expanding Colleyville.
</P>
<P>
   This year finds dirt-track motorcycle racing at a crossroads.
Places such as Ross Downs are memories, and a form of motorcycle
racing that has a rich tradition and history is not experiencing
the type of growth as other forms of motorsports.
</P>
<P>
   When people think of motorcycle racing today they think of
Jeremy McGrath leaping on his Yamaha over a high jump at a
Supercross event, not Chris Carr sliding through a turn in excess
of 120 mph on his 750cc Harley-Davidson at a dirt-track race.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an opportunity here to take a sport that is in need
of some repair and build it to what we have done with Supercross,''
said Kidd, a Fort Worth resident who is vice president of PACE
Motorsports. ``We need to have (dirt track motorcycle racing) in
the big venues, the nice venues in the major markets. In the long
run that will rebuild the grass roots of dirt racing and rekindle
places like Ross Downs.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd is hoping that the Formula USA-sanctioned Wrenchead.com
National Dirt Track Series will be the tool that helps start the
repair work on dirt-track motorcycle racing.
</P>
<P>
   The inaugural season for the series starts Saturday at the Texas
Motor Speedway Dirt Track with ``Motorcycle Mania.'' Saturday
night's event, which will feature motorcycle racing in the National
Championship and Pro Singles divisions, will be the first in an
11-race schedule that will run through October.
</P>
<P>
   Formula USA is part of PACE Motorsports, which has helped move
Supercross into the national spotlight by running at venues such as
Texas Stadium and the Silverdome in Pontiac, Mich. A crowd in
excess of 40,000 saw the Supercross event at Texas Stadium in early
April.
</P>
<P>
   That level of attendance in dirt-track motorcycle racing is
rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``PACE is a company that has a proven track record promoting
motorcycle races,'' said Carr, the 1999 American Motorcyclist
Association Grand National Dirt Track Series champion. ``There is
going to be some growing pains, but the racers understand that.
PACE is going to get it right and can take it to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Up until this year, dirt-track races in the United States were
exclusively sanctioned by the long-established AMA. But many in the
dirt-track community feel the AMA has not been aggressive enough in
promoting the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Others have complained the prize money has not increased.
</P>
<P>
   That can't be said for the Wrenchead.com Series. Saturday's race
on the four-tenths mile dirt track features a purse in excess of
$40,000, with $7,500 going to the winner. In addition, the series'
points champion will earn $50,000 from a $150,000 fund.
</P>
<P>
   On 1-mile dirt tracks, riders will race for $50,000 in total
prize money. The winner will take home $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had been talking about this for the last year, and about
five months ago they said they were going to have their first race
(in May),'' said Carr, of Fleetwood, Pa. ``The purse money has
almost doubled in the five months since PACE got involved. But you
cannot blame the AMA for the lack of growth. It was a combination
of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd said the Wrenchead.com Series was not formed to compete
directly against the AMA's established Grand National Series, as
only two race weekends conflict with the AMA schedule. Kidd said he
wants to show people other than motorcycle fans that dirt-track
motorcycle racing is exciting and give the sport its proper
recognition, starting with Saturday's event here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The AMA is loyal to the historic dirt tracks and there are
some markets that I feel there is not growth potential,'' Kidd
said. ``This is a key event for us and we would like to be able to
show the motorcycle fans, the stock car fans (and) the football
fans that motorcycle racing is exciting.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
