<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS OWNER GETS HIS PHIL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Before the Los Angeles Lakers and Sacramento Kings
could settle their differences on the court Friday, there was one
more volley in the battle of words. A day after Lakers coach Phil
Jackson called Sacramento fans ``semi-civilized'' and ``rednecks,''
Kings owner Joe Maloof took a few shots at the coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil Jackson is so damn arrogant,'' Maloof told Bloomberg
News. ``Wouldn't it be fun to see him at the podium explaining why
he lost? Would he ever say that he got outcoached? Would he say
that? I doubt it.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Kings went down 0-2 in the series, Maloof took great
joy in seeing his team stun the Lakers - and Jackson - with two
straight wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil was just so cool the first two games, just having a ball
over there, standing up and doing that little whistle of his,''
Maloof said. ``When we beat him the first game, he was cowering in
the corner. When we beat him the second time, you should've just
seen his face.''
</P>
<P>
   In a final shot at Jackson - who coached Michael Jordan and the
Chicago Bulls to six championships - Maloof said, ``I'd like to see
Phil coach Vancouver. He's always had the greatest players in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson grinned slightly when asked to respond before Game 5 on
Friday. His thoughts? ``None,'' he said. ``I don't know the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this guy a gambler? Is that where he makes his money?''
Jackson said of Maloof, whose family owns a Las Vegas casino.
``He's a character builder.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the source of such venom from a team owner, Jackson said,
``I'm curious about that, too. Right now it doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Suns sit: The Phoenix Suns are a big beneficiary of the Kings'
comeback in this series. They finished off the San Antonio Spurs on
Tuesday, then awaited the winner of the Lakers-Kings series. The
second round begins Sunday, giving the Suns' opponent precious
little time to recuperate and prepare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was concerned about a long week with a layoff (of six days,
had the Lakers swept the series), and here I am playing right up
until Friday,'' Jackson said before tipoff. ``I think it's better
off to do it this way this time of year sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   A benefit for the Suns? ``Yeah, it is for them,'' Jackson said,
``but they don't know are we home or are we away?''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns, of course, wouldn't say who they wanted to face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope people aren't fooled by the regular-season records,''
said Phoenix coach Scott Skiles. ``We were 0-4 against the Lakers
and 4-0 against the (Kings), but those things don't mean a thing
this time of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Clutch appearance: A smiling Lakers executive Jerry West made a
quick trip through the locker room before the game, shaking hands
with Shaquille O'Neal, Glen Rice and Robert Horry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
