<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL EYES ON FUSAICHI PEGASUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ When Fusaichi Pegasus, the would-be
superhorse, arrives at the starting gate for today's Kentucky
Derby, he will find it filling up with worthy foils - and some of
the meatiest subplots in years.
</P>
<P>
   Or should that say, if Fusaichi Pegasus arrives at the starting
gate?
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese-owned colt is known as much for his temperament
(unpredictable) as for his astounding yearling-auction price ($4
million) and his 3-year-old campaign (spotless, so far).
</P>
<P>
   He bucks playfully during morning gallops - he dumped a rider
and toppled over harmlessly last week - and can be a handful before
and after races. Jockey Kent Desormeaux had trouble getting him to
the starting point before the smashing Wood Memorial victory in New
York that stamped Fusaichi Pegasus as a solid Kentucky Derby
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus trainer Neil Drysdale accuses the press of
``hyperbole'' in describing the risk the horse's behavior will
hinder his chances or those of the other 18 Derby horses. But rival
trainers are thinking about it, especially as they picture 140,000
fans making noise in the Churchill Downs stands and infield on a
hot, sticky afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might be the first time in history that we have to van
one to the gate,'' joked D. Wayne Lukas, the four-time
Derby-winning trainer who has High Yield, Exchange Rate and
Commendable in the 1-mile race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want that horse to go over there (to the gate)
trouble-free,'' Lukas added. ``A, it's good for the game if he
runs. B, I'll have two of them (horses) back there waiting to
load.''
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, Fusaichi Pegasus could be ordered scratched by
the stewards if he threatened to hold up the start of the race. But
now we are guilty of hyperbole. That's highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale, elected to the Racing Hall of Fame earlier this week,
insists he doesn't envision a problem. He said Fusaichi Pegasus is
an intelligent horse who ``just likes to look at things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got only 2 furlongs (one-quarter mile) between where he
gets on the track and the gate, and he's got 12 minutes to get
there,'' the trainer said. ``I think we can manage that.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus will start from post 15. Drysdale selected an
outside post so the colt wouldn't have to stand in the gate for too
long. Other horses' handlers tried to avoid the slots next to him.
</P>
<P>
   Derby horses enter the gate in pairs - post 1 and 11, then 2 and
12, and so forth - so he'll load in the middle of a process that
can take a couple of minutes. He'll have to stay calm until the
starter lets the doors spring open.
</P>
<P>
   Then that subplot will end and the rest will take their shots -
Jenine Sahadi (The Deputy), trying to be the first female trainer
to win the Derby; Marlon St. Julien (Curule), the first
African-American jockey in the Derby since 1921; 88-year-old
trainer Harold Rose (Hal's Hope); the Dubai-based mystery horses
(China Visit and Curule); Lukas protege Todd Pletcher's foursome
(More Than Ready, Trippi, Graeme Hall, Impeachment); and Drysdale's
other horse (War Chant).
</P>
<P>
   This Derby would be intriguing enough without subplots. Fusaichi
Pegasus, 9-5 on the morning line, figures as the most popular
favorite since Arazi started at 9-10 and finished eighth in 1992.
``This is the first time in a long time that people are talking
about a Triple Crown ahead of time,'' said Tom Meeker, Churchill
Downs' CEO.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a freak,'' said Alex Hassinger, trainer of Anees.
``Look how easy he's won.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus would be the first winning favorite in the
Derby since Spectacular Bid in 1979. He also would be the first
horse without a win at age 2 to win the Derby since Proud Clarion
in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Should he win, his reputation will be bolstered by the quality
of his opponents. If Fusaichi Pegasus doesn't fire - because of his
relative inexperience or because he's distracted - major prep
winners The Deputy (Santa Anita Derby), High Yield (Blue Grass
Stakes) head the list of logical beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Front-running Trippi, Hal's Hope, High Yield and Graeme Hall
figure to force a fast pace, stretching out the field and
preventing the kind of first-turn traffic jam that jumbled the 1999
Derby won by Charismatic. Fusaichi Pegasus and The Deputy figure to
be among those tracking the leaders. Aptitude, Anees, Deputy
Warlock and Impeachment will try to make late impacts.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus' balkiness on the way to the starting gate is
matched by his antics on the way to the winner's circle. But
significantly, he has visited that circle four times in five
starts, meaning he's acting just fine during his races. Drysdale
has sounded optimistic as he prepares to run his first Derby
horses, having had to scratch a sore-footed A.P. Indy on the
morning of the race in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be good to be back,'' Drysdale said, ``when they're both
in the gate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-05-00 2346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000505.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-05 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7430 &Cx1f; kan-z
r v BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN &LR;      05-05 0382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Saturday,
Aug. ??. If you have any questions, please call Bruce Janssen on
the Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   GENOME _ Dr. Francis Collins, director of the National Human
Genome Research Institute at NIH, announced Friday in Kansas City
that researchers with the project have completed the gene sequence
for the chromosome involved in Down Sydrome, Lou Gehrig's disease,
Alzheimer's disease and some forms of epilepsy. Genes on this
chromosome have been the target of medical researchers for more
than a decade. Researchers already are seeking new treatments for
ALS and Alzheimer's. But this latest accomplishment will help lead
the way to treatments that could improve the learning abilities of
children with Down Syndrome. By Alan Bavley. Story will move in the
``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   WIGAND _ Jeffrey Wigand, president and founder of Smoke Free
Kids, appears before an auditorium full of students at Truman High
School. He also speaks at a luncheon of the Kansas City-area World
No Tobacco Day committee. Wigand inspired the motion picture ``The
Insider'' and was the guy who blew the whistle against Big Tobacco.
By Donald Bradley. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEARWASTE _ Sen. John Ashcroft and Gov. Mel Carnahan,
Ashcroft's challenger in this year's Senate race, have something
new to snipe over _ transportation of radioactive waste through
Missouri on its way to Yucca Mountain in Nevada. By Kevin Murphy.
Story will move in the ``p'' category.
BUSINESS OFFERINGS
</P>
<P>
   GM-FAIRFAX _ General Motors has some specifics on changes to its
product line at the Fairfax plant in Kansas City, Kan. By Randy
Heaster. Story will move in the ``f'' category.
</P>
<P>
   NASD -- Jack Rosenfield, head of the Kansas City office of the
NASD, is retiring after a long career as a securities' regulator.
By Mark Davis. Story will move in the ``f'' category.
</P>
<P>
   HEASTER-COLUMN -- Business column by Jerry Heaster. Story will
move in the ``f'' category.
SPORTS OFFERINGS
</P>
<P>
   ROYALS -- White Sox at Royals, 7 p.m. CDT start. By Dick Kaegel.
Story will move in the ``s'' category.
</P>
