<HEADLINE>
POLLARD STEPS UP FOR BURN DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BLANE BACHELOR 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dallas Burn defender Brandon Pollard admits his excitement last
week about his first significant playing time of the season might
have been a bit overzealous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was running around like a chicken with my head cut off,''
Pollard said.
</P>
<P>
   Pollard's window of playing opportunity opened for the same
reason he had been on the bench this season: an injury. When Eric
Dade went down with a strained back in the 20th minute Saturday
against Columbus, Pollard got his chance and saw his first
significant playing time since breaking his right leg during last
season's playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Pollard eventually settled down and helped stifle the Crew in
the Burn's 2-1 victory. And he has had plenty of time to prepare
for his role as a starter in Saturday's game at Tampa Bay. Four of
the Burn's defensive players will likely be out with injuries,
leaving Pollard and Ricardo Iribarren as the only two healthy
defenders available.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Farrer's strained back kept him out of training all
week, and Dade isn't likely to be available. The Burn is also
missing two defensive midfielders, Sergi Daniv (fractured rib) and
Mark Santel (strained quadriceps). Santel could be out two more
weeks, Burn coach Dave Dir said. Defender Jorge Rodriguez is with
the El Salvador national team.
</P>
<P>
   The patchwork back line, which might also tap the services of
midfielders Chad Deering or Ted Eck, hasn't played a full game
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``You certainly can't expect there to be much rhythm in a lineup
that hasn't been together much before,'' Pollard said. ``But in
situations like these, you have to concentrate on being very
disciplined and not taking too many chances. Certainly
communication is the key.''
</P>
<P>
   Dir noted improved chemistry in the defense Saturday,
specifically good communication from Rodriguez, who filled in at
sweeper for Farrer.
</P>
<P>
   Deering might fill that role today because he has some
experience playing defense. He trained at sweeper this week and
seemed to be a good fit, Pollard said.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important for the Burn will be the overall ability of
the rest of the team to play with a focus on defense. The Mutiny
(4-4) has outscored opponents 14-3 in four games at Raymond James
Stadium and boasts a midfield that includes dangerous playmakers
Carlos Valderrama and Steve Ralston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take all 10 guys defending smartly, and helping
one another out,'' said Eck, who might have to mark Valderrama.
``If one side doesn't get closed off, they'll go down the other
side, and attack out of the back as well. It's going to be a key
that all 10 of us defend.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
