<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MUSSELMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL MUSSELMAN, 59, INTENSE BASKETBALL COACH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Ore., Minn., Ala.)   By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Musselman, who in the last 35 years held 13 head coaching
jobs in college and professional basketball and left an imprint
everywhere as a volatile, intense taskmaster, died Friday at the
Mayo Clinic's St. Marys Hospital in Rochester, Minn. He was 59.
</P>
<P>
   A Mayo Clinic spokesman said the cause of death was heart and
kidney failure related to liver disease. Musselman suffered a
stroke last October. Last month he received a diagnosis of multiple
myeloma, cancer of the bone marrow. His doctors said he also had
amyloidosis, which causes the liver to produce an abnormal protein
that attacks body organs.
</P>
<P>
   For the last three seasons, he was an assistant coach of the
Portland Trail Blazers of the NBA. When the Trail Blazers played
the Minnesota Timberwolves in the first round of this year's
playoffs, he wanted to sit behind the Trail Blazers' bench, but his
doctors would not let him leave the hospital. On Tuesday night,
when the Trail Blazers won the series, their players and coaches
signed the game ball as a gift to him.
</P>
<P>
   His biography, by Bill Heller, was aptly titled ``Obsessed.'' He
slept three to five hours a night because he would not spare more
time from work. For four years he kept a VCR at the foot of his bed
so he could watch game film until he drifted off to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   At 25, Musselman became the head coach at Ashland University in
Ohio, where his team set an NCAA record by allowing an average of
only 33.9 points a game over a season. In six seasons at Ashland
(1965-71), four at Minnesota (1971-75) and two at South Alabama
(1995-97), his teams won 233 games and lost 84.
</P>
<P>
   He brought Minnesota its first Big Ten title in 53 years,
sold-out arenas, 127 NCAA violations and a 1972 brawl that sent
three Ohio State players to a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   In the NBA, he coached the Cleveland Cavaliers for two seasons
(1980-82) and became the first coach of the expansion Minnesota
Timberwolves (1989-91). His NBA record was 78-180. He also coached
professionals in the American Basketball Association, the Western
Basketball Association and the Continental Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   William Clifford Musselman was born Aug. 13, 1940, in Wooster,
Ohio. He was a decent high school athlete whose basketball team
fared well against a neighboring team led by Bobby Knight.
</P>
<P>
   At Wittenberg University, Musselman, 5 feet 10 inches and 175
pounds, lettered in basketball, football and baseball. He received
a bachelor's degree from Wittenberg and a master's in education
from Kent State.
</P>
<P>
   One regret, he said, was not spending more time with his family.
He is survived by his wife, Julie; their son, Max; and a son, Eric,
and a daughter, Nicole, from a previous marriage. Eric is an
assistant coach for the Orlando Magic of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of Musselman's players enjoyed him. Sidney Lowe, an
assistant coach of the Timberwolves who played on three of
Musselman's CBA champion teams, said he liked the coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be a Bill Musselman player to play for him,'' Lowe
once said. ``He wants guys he can put together like a chain,
linked.''
</P>
<P>
   Musselman once explained his intensity this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``I love competition. I don't know why. A lot of people don't
like competition. They'd rather go set up a business down the block
where there's no competition. I want my business where there's
three other guys doing the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the intense man could laugh at himself, too. Once, he was
asked the most irrational thing he had ever done. The answer came
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach basketball,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
