u p BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      05-05 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS WEIGHING BUDGET PROPOSALS; LEADING THE RACE FOR NO. 2;
A QUESTION OF INFLUENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS WEIGHING BUDGET PROPOSALS
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas began a news conference in San
Diego on Friday with some heavy lifting: He waved two thick books
that represented budget proposals he had sent to the Texas
Legislature in 1997 and 1999, and he lit into Vice President Al
Gore anew for suggesting that he did not produce such extensive
spending blueprints.
</P>
<P>
   The props in his hand, Bush said, proved otherwise, and featured
``a lot of line items _ there's a lot of pages, there's a lot of
numbers.'' Only the day before, Gore had pulled from his pocket a
three-page document that he said was a copy of Bush's 1995 budget,
telling a reporter that ``if you think that's a budget, then maybe
I can convince you it's a duck.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush turned to examples from later years and said that he was
wishing fervently for a campaign ``not full of hyperbole and
distortion.''
</P>
<P>
   LEADING THE RACE FOR NO. 2
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush and Vice President Al Gore remain
tight-lipped about running mates, but an NBC News-Wall Street
Journal poll has found that most voters have already made up their
minds.
</P>
<P>
   Among Republicans and independents, 40 percent want Bush to pick
Colin Powell, the retired chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, 20
percent favor Sen. John McCain of Arizona and 15 percent favor
Elizabeth Dole, the former president of the Red Cross. (Both Powell
and McCain insist that they are not interested.)
</P>
<P>
   Among Democrats and independents, 33 percent want Gore to pick
former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey and 18 percent favor Sen.
Dianne Feinstein of California. The poll surveyed 1,003 registered
voters from April 29 to May 1. It has a margin of sampling error of
plus or minus three percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   A QUESTION OF INFLUENCE
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly this year, interest groups as prominent as the
National Rifle Association and as obscure as Republicans for Clean
Air are running television commercials intended to influence
elections.
</P>
<P>
   This week Karl J. Sandstrom, a Democratic member of the Federal
Election Commission, proposed that these groups be required to say
whom they represented and where the money came from to pay for the
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal will provide grist for a commission discussion
later this month. But do not count on the matter going anywhere.
Experts on election law say the commission probably has no
authority to order the interest groups to report on their affairs.
And if the commission tried to exercise the authority, Congress
would probably block the move.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: The Kentucky Derby
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Washington
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
